Oprah-You-Get-A.name: Oprah-You-Get-A

text_options.description: This bottom text box is typically used for the punchline of the meme, completing the setup from the top text. It often contains the phrase "EVERYBODY GETS A [NOUN]!" to mirror Oprah's enthusiastic giveaway announcement, applying it to a new, often humorous or absurd context.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It usually follows the pattern "You get a [noun]! And you get a [noun]!" to build anticipation and mimic Oprah's original speech, establishing what is being generously 'given' away.

Oprah-You-Get-A.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of Oprah Winfrey from a 2004 episode of The Oprah Winfrey Show, where she famously gave away a car to every member of her studio audience. In the image, she is wearing a red suit, holding a microphone, and has her arms outstretched in a gesture of magnanimous giving, looking ecstatic. The meme, known as "Oprah's You Get A Car" or "Everybody Gets A Car," is used to humorously or sarcastically announce the widespread distribution of something, whether it's a desirable item, a punishment, or an abstract concept.

Distracted-Boyfriend.name: Distracted-Boyfriend

text_options.description: This label is placed on the girlfriend, who represents the current, sensible, or obligatory option that is being neglected. Her disapproving expression reinforces that this is what the subject 'should' be focused on.

This label is placed on the boyfriend, representing the subject or protagonist of the meme. This is the person, group, or entity that is being tempted or making a poor decision by shifting their focus.

This label is placed on the woman in the red dress, who symbolizes the new, attractive, or distracting alternative. She represents the temptation or the shiny new thing that is drawing the subject's attention away from their responsibilities.

Distracted-Boyfriend.image_description: This is the "Distracted Boyfriend" meme, a popular object-labeling format from a stock photo. It depicts a man in a plaid shirt looking admiringly at a woman in a red dress walking by, while his own girlfriend in a light blue top looks on in shock and disgust. The meme is used to represent situations where someone foolishly or humorously chooses a new, tempting option over a current, more responsible one.

Bernie-I-Am-Once-Again-Asking-For-Your-S.name: Bernie-I-Am-Once-Again-Asking-For-Your-Support

text_options.description: This text box is the punchline of the meme, completing the sentence "I am once again asking for...". Users insert their specific, often humorous or mundane, request here, contrasting with the serious tone of the original video.

This area is typically used to label the person or entity making the request. It sets the context for the plea, for example, "Me:", "My cat:", or "My last two brain cells:", framing who is "once again asking" for the thing mentioned in the bottom text.

Bernie-I-Am-Once-Again-Asking-For-Your-S.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of US Senator Bernie Sanders from a 2019 campaign fundraising video. In the image, Sanders is outdoors in a winter coat, earnestly addressing the viewer with the caption "I am once again asking." The meme format is used to humorously make a repeated or desperate request for something, often trivial or relatable, by completing the phrase with a custom punchline.
Bernie-I-Am-Once-Again-Asking-For-Your-S.display_name: Bernie I Am Once Again Asking For Your Support

Grus-Plan.name: Grus-Plan

text_options.description: This is the fourth and final panel. The text is an exact repetition of the text in the third panel (index 1), reinforcing the disastrous outcome. Gru's dejected look away from the board emphasizes the failure and disappointment.

This is the third panel and the punchline of the meme. The text describes an unexpected, negative, or absurd consequence that ruins the plan. Gru's expression shifts to one of dawning horror as he realizes the flaw.
This is the second step of the plan. The text here builds upon the first step, continuing the logical progression of what seems like a good idea. Gru remains confident in this panel.
This is the first step of the plan. The text here introduces the initial goal or action, which is usually something desirable or logical. Gru is shown confidently presenting this step.

Grus-Plan.image_description: This meme, known as "Gru's Plan," features the character Gru from the movie "Despicable Me" presenting a plan on a board across four panels. He confidently outlines the first two steps, but then realizes a critical, unforeseen negative consequence in the third step. The final panel shows him looking back at the board in dismay, repeating the negative consequence to emphasize the plan's failure.

Marked-Safe-From.name: Marked-Safe-From

text_options.description: This area contains the icon, typically a flag, associated with the 'Marked Safe' status. In many variations of this meme, this icon is replaced with a custom image that is thematically related to the 'danger' being avoided, adding another layer to the joke.

This is the main customizable text area where the user writes the humorous 'threat' they are safe from. The comedy comes from juxtaposing the serious tone of a safety alert with a trivial or relatable annoyance, such as 'spoilers,' 'unnecessary meetings,' or 'making bad decisions'.

Marked-Safe-From.image_description: This meme format is a parody of Facebook's "Safety Check" feature, which allows users to mark themselves as safe during disasters. The template, reading "Marked Safe From... Today," is used humorously to declare oneself safe from trivial, annoying, or absurd situations. Users customize the meme by adding text or images to express relief at avoiding a particular, often mundane, 'danger.'

Anakin-Padme-4-Panel.name: Anakin-Padme-4-Panel

text_options.description: Placed over Padmé's now-concerned face, this text is typically a repetition of her first line, but rephrased as a worried question (e.g., '...right?'). It emphasizes her dawning horror or confusion after hearing Anakin's response.

This text, placed over a smiling Padmé, represents a positive or naive statement that sets up the joke. It's the first line of the dialogue, establishing an optimistic premise that will soon be subverted.
This text is Anakin's deadpan response, which serves as the punchline. It's a dark, unsettling, or absurd clarification that directly contradicts or twists Padmé's initial statement.

Anakin-Padme-4-Panel.image_description: This meme, known as "For the Better, Right?", features Anakin Skywalker and Padmé Amidala from the Star Wars prequel trilogy. The four-panel format depicts a conversation where Padmé makes a positive or naive statement, and Anakin responds with a dark or unsettling clarification, causing her smile to vanish. This format is used to create humor through dramatic irony, where an innocent statement is met with a grim or unexpected reality, highlighted by Padmé's concerned reaction.

Bike-Fall.name: Bike-Fall

text_options.description: Located in the final panel next to the fallen cyclist. This text represents the external person, group, or concept that the cyclist is blaming for his crash, serving as the scapegoat for his self-inflicted problem.

Positioned in the middle panel, pointing to the stick the cyclist is inserting into his own bike's spokes. This text describes the act of self-sabotage or the poor decision that directly causes the negative outcome.
Situated in the first panel, next to the cyclist who is riding along happily. This text typically identifies the person, company, or entity that is about to commit the act of self-sabotage.

Bike-Fall.image_description: A three-panel comic strip meme known as 'Bike Fall' or 'Bicycle Fall.' It depicts a man who, while riding his bike, intentionally shoves a stick into the front wheel, causing himself to crash. In the final panel, he lies on the ground in pain, blaming an external factor for his self-inflicted misfortune. The meme is used to satirize situations where individuals, groups, or entities sabotage their own efforts and then refuse to take responsibility, instead blaming others for the negative outcome.

Yall-Got-Any-More-Of-That.name: Yall-Got-Any-More-Of-That

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, specifying the object of the intense craving. It's what the character is desperately asking for, which can range from anything like 'weekend,' 'motivation,' to a specific video game or TV show.

The top text box typically contains the setup phrase of the meme, which is most famously "Y'all got any more of that". This text establishes the desperate question, setting the stage for the punchline below.

Yall-Got-Any-More-Of-That.image_description: A still image from "Chappelle's Show" featuring comedian Dave Chappelle as his character Tyrone Biggums, a crack addict. Biggums, wearing a red beanie and jacket, is shown scratching his neck with a desperate and fiending expression on his face. This meme, known as "Y'all Got Any More of That," is used to humorously express an intense craving or addiction to something, often something mundane or popular.
Yall-Got-Any-More-Of-That.display_name: Yall Got Any More Of That

Success-Kid.name: Success-Kid

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, revealing the successful or positive outcome of the situation described in the top text. This text justifies the baby's triumphant expression, completing the narrative of a small victory.
The top text sets up a scenario or describes an action, often one where a negative or mediocre result is expected. This creates the context for the success that will be revealed in the bottom text.

Success-Kid.image_description: This meme, known as "Success Kid," features a toddler with a determined expression clenching his fist in a celebratory gesture. The image is set against a blue and purple radial background, a common feature of the "advice animal" meme format. It is used to express satisfaction over small, personal victories or unexpectedly positive outcomes in everyday situations.

Megamind-peeking.name: Megamind-peeking

text_options.description: This text box, positioned at the bottom of the image, contains the punchline of the question. In the original meme, this is where "Bitches?" is written. It represents the specific thing that the subject is being humorously accused of lacking.

Located at the top over Megamind's large forehead, this text box contains the setup for the punchline. It typically contains the word "No", initiating the question that will be completed by the text at the bottom.

Megamind-peeking.image_description: This meme features a close-up of the character Megamind from the 2010 animated film of the same name, looking down with a forlorn and questioning expression. The image is famously associated with the question "No Bitches?", used humorously to mock or question someone's lack of romantic partners. The format is highly adaptable, replacing the object of the question to humorously point out a perceived absence of anything (e.g., "No sleep?", "No money?").

Drake-Hotline-Bling.name: Drake-Hotline-Bling

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to Drake's approving gesture. It contains the text for the desirable, popular, or preferred option.
This text box is placed next to Drake's rejecting gesture. It contains the text for the undesirable, unpopular, or rejected option.

Drake-Hotline-Bling.image_description: This meme, known as 'Drakeposting' or 'Drake Hotline Bling,' features two stills of the rapper Drake from his 'Hotline Bling' music video. In the top panel, he shows disapproval with a rejecting gesture, while in the bottom panel, he smiles and points in approval. The format is used to express a strong preference for one thing (bottom) over a less desirable alternative (top), making it a versatile template for showing likes and dislikes.

Two-Buttons.name: Two-Buttons

text_options.description: This area, placed over the sweating man, typically identifies the person or entity facing the difficult decision. It provides context for who is struggling with the choice presented by the two buttons.
The text label for the first button. This space is used to describe one of the two conflicting options, desires, or outcomes that the person must choose between.
The text label for the second button. This space describes the other choice, which is typically in direct opposition or conflict with the first option, creating the dilemma.

Two-Buttons.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as "Daily Struggle" or "Two Buttons," depicts a man agonizing over a difficult choice. The top panel shows a hand hovering between two labeled red buttons, representing conflicting options. The bottom panel reveals the man sweating profusely, visually representing his intense anxiety and indecision. The meme is widely used to humorously illustrate a dilemma or internal conflict between two desirable or undesirable choices.

Left-Exit-12-Off-Ramp.name: Left-Exit-12-Off-Ramp

text_options.description: This label is on the swerving car. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity making the sudden and dramatic choice.
This label is on the right side of the highway sign, corresponding to the arrow pointing straight ahead. Text here represents the sensible, logical, or easy option that is being rejected.

This label is on the left side of the highway sign, indicating the exit ramp. Text here represents the tempting, impulsive, or more desirable (but often less rational) choice that the subject is making.

Left-Exit-12-Off-Ramp.image_description: This meme, known as 'Left Exit 12 Off-Ramp' or 'Car Swerving Off Highway,' is a two-panel image format. The top panel displays a highway sign presenting two choices: continuing straight or taking a sharp left exit. The bottom panel depicts a car recklessly swerving across lanes to make the exit at the last second. This format is used to humorously represent someone making a sudden, impulsive, or difficult decision over a more sensible, straightforward, or expected one.

Running-Away-Balloon.name: Running-Away-Balloon

text_options.description: This text label is placed on the yellow balloon in the second panel. It contains the same text as the balloon in the first panel (index 3), representing the desired goal or object that is now unattainable because the character is being held back.

This label is on the main character in the second panel, who is now sweating and distressed. The text here is identical to the character in the first panel (index 4), typically 'Me' or a specific person/group, showing their reaction to being thwarted.

This label is on the large pink character who is holding the main character back. This text represents the obstacle, responsibility, or problem that prevents the protagonist from achieving their goal, serving as the punchline of the meme.
This text label is placed on the yellow balloon in the first panel. It represents a goal, desire, or something positive that the protagonist is happily pursuing.

This label is on the main character in the first panel. The text here typically identifies the protagonist, often labeled as 'Me' or a specific demographic, who is joyfully pursuing the goal represented by the balloon.

Running-Away-Balloon.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Running Away Balloon' or 'Guy Chasing a Balloon', illustrates a relatable struggle. In the top panel, a simple comic character joyfully reaches for a yellow balloon, representing a goal or desire. In the bottom panel, the character is held back by a larger, pink, blob-like figure, watching in distress as the balloon floats away. The meme is used to express frustration when a desired outcome is prevented by an unavoidable responsibility, obstacle, or unfortunate reality.

UNO-Draw-25-Cards.name: UNO-Draw-25-Cards

text_options.description: This text box, positioned above the man holding the cards, typically labels the person or group who is refusing to do the action on the card. It provides the subject of the meme, such as "Me," "My friends," or any group that would find the choice difficult.

Located on the blank space of the Uno card, this text describes the undesirable action or statement. The humor comes from this action being something the subject (labeled in box 0) finds so abhorrent they would rather accept the punishment of drawing 25 cards.

UNO-Draw-25-Cards.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Draw 25," presents a difficult choice. The left panel shows a custom Uno card with the ultimatum "[do something] OR draw 25," while the right panel shows a man with a pained expression holding a massive hand of cards. The meme is used to express a strong aversion to a particular action, implying that one would rather accept a severe penalty (drawing 25 cards) than perform the undesirable task.

Disaster-Girl.name: Disaster-Girl

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or entity (the 'Disaster Girl') who is implied to be pleased with or responsible for the negative event.
This label describes the disaster, problem, or unfortunate situation that the 'Disaster Girl' is seemingly enjoying.

Disaster-Girl.image_description: This meme, known as 'Disaster Girl,' features a young girl with a sly, knowing smile looking at the camera while a house burns in the background. The juxtaposition implies she is responsible for or takes pleasure in the disaster. It's used to humorously represent someone finding satisfaction in a chaotic or unfortunate situation they may have caused.

Epic-Handshake.name: Epic-Handshake

text_options.description: This label is placed on the bicep of the character Dutch (Arnold Schwarzenegger). It typically represents the first of two distinct or opposing groups, individuals, or concepts.
This label is placed on the bicep of the character Dillon (Carl Weathers). It represents the second group, individual, or concept, which is usually contrasted with the first one.

Positioned over the clasped hands, this central label contains the punchline. It describes the common ground, shared belief, or quality that unites the two seemingly different entities shown on the arms.

Epic-Handshake.image_description: This meme, known as the "Epic Handshake" or "Predator Handshake," originates from a scene in the 1987 film Predator featuring Arnold Schwarzenegger and Carl Weathers. The image depicts a close-up of their two muscular arms clasping hands, symbolizing an intense agreement or greeting. Culturally, this meme is used to show an unexpected point of agreement or a shared quality between two otherwise different or opposing groups, ideas, or individuals.

Sad-Pablo-Escobar.name: Sad-Pablo-Escobar

text_options.description: This text box is in the first panel, showing Pablo Escobar standing alone by an empty pool. Text here typically introduces the initial scenario or the beginning of a long, boring wait.

Located in the second panel where Escobar sits alone at a table, this text box continues the narrative of waiting. The text here often shows the progression of time or the deepening of thought from the first panel.

This text box is in the final panel, showing Escobar on a swing. Text here usually delivers the punchline or the conclusion of the long wait or contemplation, often highlighting a mundane or anticlimactic outcome.

Sad-Pablo-Escobar.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as 'Sad Pablo Escobar' or 'Pablo Escobar Waiting,' features actor Wagner Moura as the character from the TV series 'Narcos.' The images depict him looking pensive and lonely in different settings, such as by an empty pool, at a table, and on a swing. This format is used to humorously express feelings of boredom, loneliness, or deep contemplation while waiting for something to happen.

Waiting-Skeleton.name: Waiting-Skeleton

text_options.description: This text box is located at the bottom of the image, often serving as the punchline or specifying what is being waited for. It provides the specific context for the skeleton's long wait, for example, 'Me waiting for the next season of my favorite show.'

The text box at the top of the image typically contains the setup or a general statement about the act of waiting. It establishes the premise of the meme, which is then often specified by a caption at the bottom.

Waiting-Skeleton.image_description: The 'Waiting Skeleton' meme features a skeleton sitting patiently on a wooden park bench. This image is used to humorously express an extremely long, seemingly endless wait for something to happen. The implication is that the person has been waiting so long they have died and decomposed, highlighting feelings of impatience and the slow passage of time.

Change-My-Mind.name: Change-My-Mind

text_options.description: This small area on the ground is not a primary text location in this meme format. It is often left blank or used for a watermark or a very subtle, secondary punchline that adds a layer to the main joke on the sign.

This is the main editable area of the meme, located on the large white sign. Users place a controversial, absurd, or strongly held personal opinion here. This statement is the setup for the punchline, which is the challenge implied by the fixed text "CHANGE MY MIND" printed below it.

Change-My-Mind.image_description: This meme, known as "Steven Crowder's Change My Mind Campus Sign," features conservative podcaster Steven Crowder sitting at a table outdoors with a smug expression, holding a mug. The table has a large sign on the front that reads "CHANGE MY MIND." The format is used to state a controversial, unpopular, or humorous opinion on the sign, challenging others to debate the point, mirroring the original context of Crowder's campus segments.

Always-Has-Been.name: Always-Has-Been

text_options.description: This text box is for the punchline, which is almost always "Always has been." This phrase is delivered by the astronaut with the gun, confirming the shocking revelation posed by the other astronaut and sealing their fate.

This text box, positioned over Earth, contains the first astronaut's question or moment of realization. It typically follows the format "Wait, it's all [X]?" or "It's all [X]?", where 'X' is the surprising or absurd concept that the world is secretly based on (e.g., "Ohio").

Always-Has-Been.image_description: This meme, known as "Always Has Been" or the "Ohio Astronauts" meme, depicts two astronauts in space. One astronaut points a gun at the back of the other's head, who is looking at Earth. The gun-wielding astronaut has an Ohio state flag patch, a key detail in the original version. The meme humorously portrays the revelation of a shocking or absurd conspiracy theory, with the armed astronaut silencing the one who has just discovered the "truth."

Batman-Slapping-Robin.name: Batman-Slapping-Robin

text_options.description: This speech bubble, originating from Batman, contains the punchline of the meme. It's the harsh correction, the blunt truth, or the exasperated response to what Robin has said. The text here is the 'slap' itself, delivering the final, decisive statement.

This speech bubble, belonging to Robin, sets up the joke. The text here is typically a naive question, an incorrect statement, or an annoying comment that provokes Batman's violent reaction. It represents the initial, often foolish, assertion that is about to be shut down.

Batman-Slapping-Robin.image_description: This meme, known as "Batman Slapping Robin" or "My Parents Are Dead," originates from a 1965 comic book panel. It depicts the superhero Batman delivering a powerful slap to his sidekick, Robin. The format is typically used to express a strong, often humorous, rebuttal or correction to a statement perceived as naive, incorrect, or annoying. Batman represents the voice of reason or frustration, while Robin represents the person making the initial, provoking comment.

Woman-Yelling-At-Cat.name: Woman-Yelling-At-Cat

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the cat, Smudge, who looks confused and unbothered. The text here represents the cat's calm, witty, or literal-minded response to the accusation from the woman. This is the punchline of the meme, creating humor through its stark contrast with the emotional outburst in the other panel.

This text box is positioned over the yelling woman, Taylor Armstrong. The text here represents an emotional, often irrational or hysterical, accusation, complaint, or statement. It serves as the setup for the joke, establishing a high-stakes emotional conflict that the cat will then deflate with its response.

Woman-Yelling-At-Cat.image_description: This is the "Woman Yelling at a Cat" meme, a two-panel image macro that contrasts an emotional accusation with a calm, confused response. The left panel features a distraught Taylor Armstrong from "The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills" yelling and pointing, while the right panel shows Smudge the Cat sitting at a dinner table with a bewildered expression. The meme is used to humorously depict a conflict where one party is overly emotional or irrational, and the other party is nonchalant, witty, or completely misunderstands the situation, leading to a comedic punchline.

X-X-Everywhere.name: X-X-Everywhere

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region completes the meme's catchphrase, 'X, X Everywhere'. It repeats the subject from the top text and adds 'Everywhere' to emphasize the overwhelming nature of the trend, aligning with Buzz's expansive gesture.

The text in this top region introduces the subject of the meme, which is perceived as being overly abundant. It's the first part of the two-part punchline, setting up the 'X' in the 'X, X Everywhere' format.

X-X-Everywhere.image_description: This meme features Buzz Lightyear and Woody from the movie 'Toy Story'. Buzz is enthusiastically gesturing while Woody looks on with a concerned expression. Known as 'X, X Everywhere', this format is used to humorously point out the sudden and overwhelming proliferation of a particular trend, topic, or item. Buzz represents the ubiquitous subject, while Woody represents the observer's reaction to it.

Mocking-Spongebob.name: Mocking-Spongebob

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the mocked version of the original statement. It's written in alternating caps (e.g., "iT's wRiTtEn iN aLtErNaTiNg cApS") to mimic a childish, mocking tone, directly attributing the mockery to the foolish-looking SpongeBob.
The top text box is where the original, serious statement or opinion that is about to be mocked is placed. This text sets up the premise for SpongeBob's derisive repetition.

Mocking-Spongebob.image_description: The "Mocking SpongeBob" or "Spongemock" meme features a still image of SpongeBob SquarePants from the episode "Little Yellow Book." In the image, SpongeBob is hunched over with a distorted, goofy expression, seemingly imitating a chicken. This meme is used to ridicule or mock a statement by repeating it in a sarcastic tone, visually represented by alternating upper and lower case letters.

Trade-Offer.name: Trade-Offer

text_options.description: This is an optional space at the bottom of the image, often left blank. When used, it typically contains a caption, a punchline, or an additional comment that adds context or humor to the trade offer presented above.

Located under the heading "you receive:", this box contains the part of the deal offered to the viewer. This is usually the punchline of the meme, describing something undesirable, comically minimal, or disproportionately worse than what the proposer gets.

Positioned under the heading "i receive:", this box describes what the person making the offer gets out of the deal. The text here sets up the trade by stating the proposer's desire, which is then contrasted with the other side of the offer for comedic effect.

Trade-Offer.image_description: The "Trade Offer" meme features TikToker Bradeazy dressed in a suit, presenting a proposition directly to the viewer with a serious expression. The format is designed to mimic a formal business deal, with text fields for what the proposer receives versus what the viewer receives. This meme is used to highlight humorous, absurd, or unfair exchanges common in social situations, video games, or everyday life, with the comedy stemming from the lopsided nature of the deal.

Buff-Doge-vs-Cheems.name: Buff-Doge-vs-Cheems

text_options.description: This text box is placed beneath Cheems, the weaker character. It typically contains a description or quote representing the inferior, present-day subject of the comparison, highlighting its perceived weakness or pathetic nature.

Positioned under Swole Doge, the stronger character, this text box describes the superior, past version of the subject. It often contains a boastful statement or an impressive fact that contrasts with the text under Cheems.
Located above Cheems, this text serves as a label for the weaker or present-day entity in the comparison. It directly identifies the subject associated with the sad dog character.
This text box is placed above Swole Doge and acts as a label for the stronger, idealized, or past version of the subject. It identifies the entity being represented by the muscular dog.

Buff-Doge-vs-Cheems.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Swole Doge vs. Cheems,' presents a humorous comparison between two eras or concepts. On the left, a muscular and powerful Shiba Inu, 'Swole Doge,' represents a glorified or superior past. On the right, a small and sad Shiba Inu, 'Cheems,' represents a weaker, disappointing present, creating a 'then vs. now' contrast.

Expanding-Brain.name: Expanding-Brain

text_options.description: This is the final and bottom-most panel, corresponding to the most radiant, god-like brain. The text here represents the punchline: the most absurd, illogical, or ironically profound "galaxy brain" idea in the sequence, presented as the highest level of enlightenment.

This is the third panel from the top, paired with a brain that is significantly more illuminated. The text here typically presents a more unconventional or complex idea, escalating the absurdity from the previous panels and setting up the final punchline.

This is the second panel from the top, showing a brain with some glowing spots indicating increased activity. The text in this box usually represents a slightly more clever, nuanced, or alternative idea compared to the one in the first panel.

This is the top-most panel, corresponding to the least active, x-ray style brain. The text here establishes the baseline for the meme, typically representing a simple, normal, or common-sense idea or action.

Expanding-Brain.image_description: This is the "Expanding Brain" or "Galaxy Brain" meme format, which uses a series of four images to satirically compare different ideas or levels of understanding. The panels progress downwards, showing a brain that becomes increasingly illuminated and cosmically powerful. This format is used to present a hierarchy of thoughts, starting with a simple or conventional idea and escalating to increasingly absurd, nonsensical, or ironically profound concepts, with the final panel representing the ultimate "enlightened" or ridiculous take.

Tuxedo-Winnie-The-Pooh.name: Tuxedo-Winnie-The-Pooh

text_options.description: This text box, placed next to the sophisticated Pooh in a tuxedo, presents a more complex, verbose, or 'superior' version of the concept from the top panel. This text is the punchline, creating humor through its exaggerated refinement.
This text box, placed next to the standard Winnie the Pooh, describes a simple, common, or basic concept. It serves as the baseline or 'inferior' item in the comparison.

Tuxedo-Winnie-The-Pooh.image_description: This meme, known as 'Tuxedo Winnie the Pooh,' presents a two-panel comparison to show levels of sophistication. The top panel features Winnie the Pooh in his normal red shirt, looking unimpressed, representing a simple or common concept. The bottom panel shows a more refined Pooh in a tuxedo, looking smug and sophisticated, representing an elevated, fancier, or more verbose version of the same concept. The format humorously contrasts the ordinary with the pretentious or superior.

Bernie-Sanders-Once-Again-Asking.name: Bernie-Sanders-Once-Again-Asking

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It reveals the object of the request, which is often a humorous substitute for the original 'your financial support.' This text completes the joke by contrasting the serious setup with a typically mundane or silly demand.

The top text box typically contains the setup phrase, 'I am once again asking for'. This text establishes the context of the meme, mimicking Bernie Sanders's earnest plea from his campaign video. It sets a serious tone that is then subverted by the punchline in the bottom text box.

Bernie-Sanders-Once-Again-Asking.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of US Senator Bernie Sanders from a 2019 presidential campaign video where he earnestly says, 'I am once again asking for your financial support.' The meme format adapts this phrase to humorously request something, often trivial or personal. The contrast between Sanders's serious expression and the typically mundane or absurd request creates the humor.

0-days-without-Lenny-Simpsons.name: 0-days-without-Lenny-Simpsons

text_options.description: This label is placed on the character Lenny. It typically identifies the person, group, or entity responsible for the action described on the sign, effectively 'resetting the counter' to zero.
This text is placed on the blank part of the sign following 'DAYS WITHOUT'. It describes a specific, often undesirable, event or action that happens frequently, forming the core of the joke.

0-days-without-Lenny-Simpsons.image_description: This meme originates from an episode of "The Simpsons" and features the character Lenny Leonard in front of a sign that reads "DAYS WITHOUT [something]". The counter on the sign is set to zero, indicating a recent failure or incident. This format is used to humorously highlight a recurring mistake, bad habit, or frequent event by labeling the culprit (Lenny) and the specific failure (on the sign), emphasizing that they can't even go one day without it happening.

I-Bet-Hes-Thinking-About-Other-Women.name: I-Bet-Hes-Thinking-About-Other-Women

text_options.description: This area represents the man's internal monologue. The text placed here is the punchline of the meme, revealing a silly, mundane, or deeply nerdy thought that contrasts with the serious emotional atmosphere set by the woman's suspicion.

This area represents the woman's internal monologue and sets up the joke. The text is almost always a variation of "He's probably thinking about other women," establishing her suspicion and creating an expectation that the man is thinking about something serious related to their relationship.

I-Bet-Hes-Thinking-About-Other-Women.image_description: This meme, often called "I Bet He's Thinking About Other Women" or "Man Thinking in Bed," features a stock photo of a couple in bed, turned away from each other. The woman looks upset and suspicious, while the man appears to be deep in thought. The humor arises from the contrast between the woman's presumed serious concern (usually about infidelity) and the man's actual, completely unrelated and often trivial or absurd internal monologue, which serves as the punchline.
I-Bet-Hes-Thinking-About-Other-Women.display_name: I Bet Hes Thinking About Other Women

Theyre-The-Same-Picture.name: Theyre-The-Same-Picture

text_options.description: This box is placed over the character Pam Beesly. This area can be labeled to represent the person, group, or entity that believes the two subjects in the top panel are identical. The original dialogue, "They're the same picture," serves as the punchline, confirming the perceived similarity.
This box is over the first of two pictures being compared. Users place text or an image here to represent the first concept or item in the comparison.
This box is over the second of two pictures being compared. Users place text or an image here to represent the second concept or item, which is being equated to the first one.

Theyre-The-Same-Picture.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the American sitcom *The Office*. In the top panel, someone holds up two pictures for comparison with the caption "Corporate needs you to find the differences between this picture and this picture." In the bottom panel, the character Pam Beesly (played by Jenna Fischer) looks directly at the camera and states, "They're the same picture." The meme is used to humorously or critically assert that two seemingly different things are, in fact, identical or functionally equivalent.

One-Does-Not-Simply.name: One-Does-Not-Simply

text_options.description: The bottom text line, which serves as the punchline of the meme. This text describes the action or task that is presented as being deceptively difficult, completing the phrase started in the top line.
The top text line, which sets up the meme's premise. This text almost invariably starts with the phrase 'One does not simply...' to introduce the subject of the meme.

One-Does-Not-Simply.image_description: This meme features a still of the character Boromir, played by Sean Bean, from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring.' The image captures him during the Council of Elrond explaining the difficulty of entering the enemy territory of Mordor. This format, widely known as 'One Does Not Simply,' is used to humorously point out that a task is far more complex or difficult than it might seem at first glance, substituting 'walk into Mordor' with another challenging activity.

Monkey-Puppet.name: Monkey-Puppet

text_options.description: This text box, positioned below the first image of the puppet, typically represents the person or entity (often labeled as "Me") who is experiencing the awkward situation. It sets the perspective for the reaction shown in the images.

This text box, located at the top of the meme, describes the awkward, incriminating, or uncomfortable situation, statement, or question that causes the puppet's reaction. It provides the context for the nervous side-glance.

Monkey-Puppet.image_description: This meme, known as "Monkey Puppet" or "Awkward Look Monkey Puppet," features a puppet character from a Japanese children's show. The two-panel format shows the puppet first looking forward, then nervously darting its eyes to the side. It's used to humorously depict a person's guilty, anxious, or awkward reaction when confronted with an uncomfortable situation or question, trying to avoid attention.

Is-This-A-Pigeon.name: Is-This-A-Pigeon

text_options.description: This area labels the person or entity who is confused or making the incorrect assumption. It represents the naive subject of the meme.
This area labels the object, person, or concept that is being misunderstood or misidentified by the subject.
This space is reserved for the punchline, which is the incorrect label or question posed by the subject about the object. It typically follows the format 'Is this a [incorrect thing]?'.

Is-This-A-Pigeon.image_description: This meme, known as 'Is this a pigeon?', originates from a scene in the 1990s anime series 'The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird'. It features an android character, Yutaro Katori, who is unfamiliar with Earth and mistakenly identifies a butterfly as a pigeon. The meme is widely used to humorously portray a person or group naively or ignorantly misinterpreting or mislabeling something.

Mother-Ignoring-Kid-Drowning-In-A-Pool.name: Mother-Ignoring-Kid-Drowning-In-A-Pool

text_options.description: This label is on the skeleton at the bottom of the pool. The text here represents something that has been neglected for a very long time, a forgotten project, a long-dead hobby, or a past version of the 'drowning child' that was never saved. It signifies the ultimate consequence of long-term neglect.

This label is on the mother figure. The text here typically represents the person or entity responsible for the neglect, such as a company, a government, or an individual. They are the ones misplacing their priorities.

This label is on the happy child being held up by the mother. The text here represents the thing that is receiving all the attention and focus, often something new, trivial, or less important than the thing being neglected.

This label is on the struggling child in the foreground. The text here represents the urgent responsibility, problem, or task that is currently being ignored in favor of the thing labeled on the favored child.

Mother-Ignoring-Kid-Drowning-In-A-Pool.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format known as "Skeleton at the Bottom of the Pool" or "Mom Ignoring Drowning Child." The top panel shows a mother in a pool happily holding one child aloft, while another child in the foreground appears to be struggling or drowning. The bottom panel shows a skeleton sitting in a chair at the bottom of a body of water. The meme is used to humorously depict situations of neglect and misplaced priorities, where one thing is given attention while another, often more important, thing is ignored to the point of its demise.
Mother-Ignoring-Kid-Drowning-In-A-Pool.display_name: Mother Ignoring Kid Drowning In A Pool

Ancient-Aliens.name: Ancient-Aliens

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline of the meme. It almost invariably contains the word "Aliens" to provide a humorous, pseudo-scientific, and conspiratorial explanation for the statement or question posed in the top text.

The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically presents a question, a statement, or an observation about a mundane or unexplained event, often phrased in a way that implies a deeper mystery, such as "I'm not saying it was aliens..."

Ancient-Aliens.image_description: This meme features Giorgio A. Tsoukalos from the TV show "Ancient Aliens," known for his distinctive hairstyle and enthusiastic theories about extraterrestrial influence on human history. He is depicted with his hands raised as if explaining a conspiracy, wearing a knowing and slightly smug expression. The meme is used to offer a comically absurd or far-fetched explanation for a simple phenomenon, often attributing the cause to aliens.

This-Is-Where-Id-Put-My-Trophy-If-I-Had-.name: This-Is-Where-Id-Put-My-Trophy-If-I-Had-One

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the angry Mr. Turner in the bottom panel. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically the phrase "IF I HAD ONE!" or a variation of it, expressing the frustration of not having the thing mentioned in the top panel.
This text box is in the top panel where Mr. Turner is smiling. The text here describes a hypothetical object, achievement, or situation that the user desires but lacks, setting up the joke.

This-Is-Where-Id-Put-My-Trophy-If-I-Had-.image_description: This two-panel meme features Mr. Turner from the cartoon 'The Fairly OddParents,' in a scene from the episode "Father Time!". In the top panel, he proudly gestures towards an empty trophy stand, and in the bottom panel, he yells in frustration. The meme, known as "This Is Where I'd Put My Trophy... If I Had One!", is used to express bitter disappointment or longing for something one does not possess.
This-Is-Where-Id-Put-My-Trophy-If-I-Had-.display_name: This Is Where Id Put My Trophy If I Had One

Hide-the-Pain-Harold.name: Hide-the-Pain-Harold

text_options.description: This is the punchline panel. The text here reveals the painful, awkward, or disappointing outcome or reality of the situation set up in the top panel. Harold's direct, pained smile at the viewer represents the subject's internal suffering.

This is the setup panel. The text here typically describes an action, a statement, or a seemingly normal or hopeful situation. Harold looking at his computer screen suggests he is discovering or reading something that leads to the painful realization in the panel below.

Hide-the-Pain-Harold.image_description: A two-panel meme featuring the stock photo model known as "Hide the Pain Harold." In the top panel, Harold looks at his laptop with a pained smile while holding a mug. In the bottom panel, he looks directly at the camera with the same forced, uncomfortable grin. This meme is used to express internal suffering, awkwardness, or disappointment while trying to maintain a facade of being okay, often contrasting an expectation with a painful reality.

This-Is-Fine.name: This-Is-Fine

text_options.description: This label is placed on the dog's body. Text here typically identifies the person, group, or entity that is in a state of denial or calmly accepting a disastrous situation. It represents the subject who is ignoring the surrounding chaos.

This label is placed on the burning house in the first panel. Text here describes the catastrophic problem, overwhelming situation, or disaster that is being ignored. It provides the context for the dog's denial.

This-Is-Fine.image_description: This meme, from KC Green's webcomic "On Fire," features an anthropomorphic dog in a bowler hat sitting calmly in a burning room and saying, "This is fine." Known as the "This is Fine" dog, the character represents a state of denial or extreme calm in the face of chaos. The meme is widely used to humorously comment on situations where one is pretending everything is okay despite overwhelming evidence to the contrary, often in political, social, or personal contexts.

Clown-Applying-Makeup.name: Clown-Applying-Makeup

text_options.description: This bottom panel corresponds to the final image of the fully made-up clown. The text here represents the ultimate, most foolish, or self-owning statement in the sequence, completing the person's transformation into a "clown."

This panel aligns with the man getting his colorful clown wig. The text here is a significantly more foolish or illogical statement, representing a major step in the argument that makes the person's flawed reasoning apparent.

This panel is next to the image of the man with more detailed makeup (eyeshadow, lipstick). The text here represents the second step in the foolish progression, a statement that is more questionable or demonstrates poorer judgment than the first.

This top panel is placed next to the first step of the transformation, where the man applies white base makeup. The text here is typically the initial, often seemingly innocuous or reasonable, statement or belief that begins the descent into foolishness.

Clown-Applying-Makeup.image_description: This meme, known as "Putting on Clown Makeup," is a four-panel exploitable format showing a man progressively applying clown makeup and a wig. It is used to satirize someone's process of making themselves look foolish through a series of increasingly absurd statements, beliefs, or actions. Each panel represents a step in this descent into foolishness, with the final panel symbolizing the complete transformation into a "clown," a common internet insult for a fool.

Boardroom-Meeting-Suggestion.name: Boardroom-Meeting-Suggestion

text_options.description: This speech bubble belongs to the third, relaxed employee. The text here is the punchline of the meme, presenting a simple, obvious, or comically unhelpful solution that directly leads to his defenestration.
This speech bubble is for the second employee. The text here provides another safe, conventional, or sycophantic suggestion, reinforcing the corporate groupthink environment.
This speech bubble belongs to the first employee offering a suggestion. The text is typically a serious and predictable idea, setting a conventional tone that contrasts with the final suggestion.
This is the speech bubble for the boss character in the first panel. The text here sets up the entire premise of the meme, usually by stating a problem, a goal, or a question for the team to address.

Boardroom-Meeting-Suggestion.image_description: This three-panel comic, known as the "Boardroom Suggestion" meme, depicts a business meeting that ends with an employee being thrown out of a window. The first panel shows a boss presenting a problem, the second shows two employees offering earnest suggestions while a third offers a simple or undesirable one. The final panel shows the boss's violent reaction to the third employee's suggestion, humorously satirizing corporate culture and the rejection of unwelcome ideas.

Doakes.name: Doakes

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image typically presents the initial statement, question, or scenario that elicits the confused or disappointed reaction. This is the setup or the 'cause' of the meme, presenting the information that the driver (and the viewer) is reacting to.

The text at the top of the image usually represents the internal monologue or the direct reaction to the text below. It can be a question expressing disbelief (e.g., 'The what?'), a description of the action (*stares in confusion*), or left blank to let the facial expression carry the punchline. This text clarifies the specific nature of the driver's silent judgment or confusion.

Doakes.image_description: This meme, known as 'Disappointed Black Guy' or 'Confused Black Guy,' features a still of actor Lennie James as the character Lincoln from the movie 'Snatch'. The image captures his intense, slightly bewildered expression while driving, which has become a popular reaction image. It is typically used to convey confusion, disbelief, or silent judgment in response to a preceding statement, action, or situation that is perceived as foolish or nonsensical.

Blank-Nut-Button.name: Blank-Nut-Button

text_options.description: Text placed on the blue button represents the impulsive action, tempting choice, or irresistible urge that the person is about to act upon. This is the punchline of the meme, representing the decision made without hesitation.
Text in this top area sets up the context or scenario. It describes a situation that prompts the impulsive reaction, making the action on the button a humorous and relatable response.

Blank-Nut-Button.image_description: The "Nut Button" meme features a blurry, motion-filled image of a hand about to slam down on a large blue button. This visual represents an immediate, impulsive, and often enthusiastic decision or reaction. The meme is used to humorously illustrate a person's strong and irresistible urge to do something in response to a given situation.

Squidward-window.name: Squidward-window

text_options.description: This label is placed over SpongeBob and Patrick, who are having fun outside. The text here typically describes the enjoyable activity or the group of people that the main subject is excluded from, such as "My friends hanging out without me" or "People enjoying their weekend."

This label is placed over Squidward, who is inside looking out. The text here represents the person feeling left out or resentful. It is almost always labeled "Me" or describes the subject's unfortunate situation, like "Me having to work."

Squidward-window.image_description: This meme, known as "Squidward Looking Through Blinds," features the character Squidward from SpongeBob SquarePants peering sadly through his window at SpongeBob and Patrick playing happily outside. The image is used to represent feelings of FOMO (fear of missing out), loneliness, or envy. It contrasts a person in an undesirable situation (Squidward) with others who are enjoying themselves.

Roll-Safe-Think-About-It.name: Roll-Safe-Think-About-It

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region provides the punchline – a comically simple, illogical, or counterproductive piece of advice that supposedly solves the problem mentioned above. This text aligns with the character's gesture of "thinking," creating the meme's humor. For example, it might follow a statement like "You can't be broke..." with "...if you don't check your bank account."
The text in this top region typically describes a problem, a negative situation, or a goal someone wants to achieve. It sets the stage for the flawed "solution" that follows in the bottom text box.

Roll-Safe-Think-About-It.image_description: This meme, known as "Roll Safe" or "Think About It," features actor Kayode Ewumi as the character Reece Simpson from the web series "Hood Documentary." He is shown tapping his temple with a confident, knowing smile, as if sharing a profound piece of wisdom. The format is used to present comically poor advice, flawed logic, or a simple-minded solution to a problem, contrasting the character's smug expression with the absurdity of the text.

Laughing-Leo.name: Laughing-Leo

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over DiCaprio's torso, delivers the punchline. This text reveals a cynical or unexpected truth that makes the statement in the top text seem naive or foolish, serving as the reason for his mocking laughter.
The top text, placed above DiCaprio's head, sets up the scenario. It usually presents a naive question, an innocent belief, or a plan made by someone else, which is then mocked by the punchline.

Laughing-Leo.image_description: This meme features a still of Leonardo DiCaprio as the character Calvin Candie from the film "Django Unchained." In the scene, he is laughing condescendingly while holding a drink. The meme, often called "Laughing Leo" or "Django Laughing," is used to express patronizing amusement or schadenfreude in response to a naive statement or situation. It typically follows a two-part format where a setup is presented, followed by a punchline that reveals a harsh or cynical truth, making the initial statement seem foolish.

Flex-Tape.name: Flex-Tape

text_options.description: Text placed over Phil Swift represents the person or entity responsible for applying the simplistic solution to the problem.
Text over the hand slapping the tape describes the quick, often inadequate, or superficial fix being applied. This represents the 'Flex Tape' in the meme's logic and serves as the punchline.
Text placed over the leaking water tank describes a large, severe, or complex problem that needs to be addressed.

Flex-Tape.image_description: This two-panel meme features Phil Swift from the Flex Tape infomercial. In the top panel, he stands next to a heavily leaking water tank, representing a significant problem. The bottom panel shows him slapping a piece of Flex Tape over the leak, symbolizing a quick, simplistic, or comically inadequate solution to that problem. The meme is widely used to illustrate attempts to patch up complex issues with simple, often ineffective, fixes.

Bell-Curve.name: Bell-Curve

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the high-IQ character on the right. It contains a simple, often profound or correct statement that mirrors the opinion of the low-IQ character. This placement is crucial for the punchline, showing that true wisdom can be simple and straightforward.

Located at the peak of the bell curve above the distressed, average-IQ character (the "Midwit"). This area is for a complex, jargon-filled, or mainstream but aggressively defended opinion. The text here represents the flawed, over-intellectualized perspective that the meme is mocking.

This text box is positioned over the low-IQ character on the far left. It typically contains a very simple, blunt, or seemingly naive take on a subject. This sets up the meme's central joke, as this simple opinion is ultimately shown to be the same as the enlightened, high-IQ perspective.

Bell-Curve.image_description: This meme, known as the "IQ Bell Curve" or "Midwit" meme, uses Wojak characters to satirize intellectual pretension. It depicts a bell curve of IQ scores with three figures: a low-IQ "Brainlet" on the left, an average-IQ, crying "Midwit" in the center, and a high-IQ, enlightened figure on the right. The meme's format suggests that both the simplest and the most intelligent minds often arrive at the same simple, correct conclusion, while the person of average intelligence holds an overly complicated and flawed opinion.

Squid-Game.name: Squid-Game

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the image of the character looking serious and disillusioned. It typically contains the punchline, describing the harsh reality, the negative consequence, or the disappointing outcome that contrasts with the initial hope expressed in the top panel.

This text box is placed over the image of the character smiling happily. It is used to describe a hopeful, naive, or positive situation or expectation. This text serves as the setup for the meme's joke, establishing the 'before' state or the ideal scenario.

Squid-Game.image_description: This meme features two contrasting images of Seong Gi-hun, the protagonist from the Netflix series "Squid Game." The top panel shows him smiling happily, representing a positive expectation or a naive beginning. The bottom panel shows the same character looking grim and weary, symbolizing a harsh or disappointing reality. The format is used to create a humorous or relatable contrast between an idealized situation and its actual, often negative, outcome.

Spider-Man-Triple.name: Spider-Man-Triple

text_options.description: This label is placed on the Spider-Man on the right. The text here identifies one of the groups, individuals, or concepts being compared or put in conflict, which is functionally identical to the others.
This label is on the central Spider-Man. The text here represents the second of three identical or hypocritical entities, contributing to the circular nature of the accusation or comparison.

This label is on the Spider-Man on the left. The text here identifies the third party in the standoff, completing the trio of identical or mutually accusing subjects that defines the meme's punchline.

Spider-Man-Triple.image_description: This meme, known as "Spider-Man Pointing at Spider-Man," originates from the 1967 Spider-Man animated series and depicts three identical Spider-Men pointing at each other. It's used to humorously illustrate situations where multiple parties are hypocritically accusing each other of the same thing, are unexpectedly identical, or are engaged in a circular conflict. The image perfectly captures the irony of such a standoff.

Sleeping-Shaq.name: Sleeping-Shaq

text_options.description: This text box, placed next to the 'woke' Shaq with glowing eyes, contains the punchline. It describes the contrasting concept that is exciting, superior, or captures the user's intense interest, representing the 'real shit' that warrants their full attention.

This text box, positioned next to the sleeping Shaq, is used to describe a concept, idea, or situation that is considered boring, conventional, or undesirable. It represents the thing that the user is ignoring or 'sleeping on'.

Sleeping-Shaq.image_description: This two-panel reaction meme, known as "Shaq Sleeping" or "I Sleep / Real Shit?", features basketball player Shaquille O'Neal. The top panel shows him sleeping to represent indifference towards a certain topic, while the bottom panel shows a distorted, deep-fried image of him with glowing eyes, signifying sudden, intense interest in a preferable alternative. The meme is used to contrast something mundane or undesirable with something exciting or highly appealing.

Pawn-Stars-Best-I-Can-Do.name: Pawn-Stars-Best-I-Can-Do

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the punchline, representing Rick Harrison's lowball counter-offer. It's a disappointing or comically underwhelming response to the initial request, often starting with his catchphrase, "Best I can do is...".
The text at the top of the image sets up the joke by stating a high expectation, a valuable item, or a desirable request. This represents what a person wants or is offering.

Pawn-Stars-Best-I-Can-Do.image_description: This meme features Rick Harrison and his son Corey Harrison from the reality TV show "Pawn Stars." In the show, Rick is known for his shrewd negotiating and often gives very low offers for items brought into his shop. The meme format plays on this by contrasting a high-value request or expectation with Rick's comically lowball counter-offer, representing a disappointing or underwhelming outcome.
Pawn-Stars-Best-I-Can-Do.display_name: Pawn Stars Best I Can Do

Leonardo-Dicaprio-Cheers.name: Leonardo-Dicaprio-Cheers

text_options.description: The bottom text typically identifies the person, group, or concept being toasted. It acts as the punchline or the direct object of the toast, completing the sentiment of 'Here's to...' or 'Cheers to...' initiated by the image and the top text.

The top text usually sets up the context or makes a statement that prompts the toast. It provides the reason for the celebration or acknowledgment, leading the viewer to understand why Gatsby is raising his glass.

Leonardo-Dicaprio-Cheers.image_description: This meme features a still of actor Leonardo DiCaprio as Jay Gatsby from the 2013 film 'The Great Gatsby'. He is dressed in a tuxedo, smiling with a self-assured expression while raising a champagne coupe in a toast. The meme, often called 'Great Gatsby Toast' or 'Leonardo DiCaprio Toasting', is used to express a celebratory salute, agreement, or appreciation towards a person, group, or idea, sometimes with a hint of smugness or sarcasm.

They-dont-know.name: They-dont-know

text_options.description: This area depicts the lively party scene with people dancing and having fun. It typically does not contain text. This group represents the oblivious 'they' in the meme's catchphrase, serving as a visual contrast to the isolated main character and their internal thoughts.

This space, positioned like a thought bubble next to the Wojak character, contains the meme's punchline. The text almost always begins with "They don't know..." followed by a statement revealing a niche hobby, obscure knowledge, or a personal secret that sets the character apart from the others at the party.

They-dont-know.image_description: This meme, known as "They Don't Know" or "I Wish I Was at Home," features a Wojak character (also called Doomer) standing alone in the corner at a party, looking sad despite wearing a party hat. In the foreground, other crudely drawn figures are happily dancing and socializing, creating a stark contrast. The meme is used to express feelings of social anxiety, introversion, or possessing a niche interest or secret that makes one feel isolated from the crowd.

Whisper-and-Goosebumps.name: Whisper-and-Goosebumps

text_options.description: This area, showing an arm with goosebumps, represents the physical reaction of intense pleasure or excitement. It typically does not contain text, as the image itself serves as the punchline, visually representing the feeling evoked by the words in the top panel.

This text box is placed over the whispering action. The text here represents the whispered words, which are meant to be something incredibly appealing, satisfying, or exciting to the listener, causing the reaction shown below.

Whisper-and-Goosebumps.image_description: This two-panel meme format, often called 'Whispering into Ear' or 'Goosebumps Meme,' illustrates a powerful, positive reaction. The top panel shows a person whispering something into another's ear, while the bottom panel shows a close-up of an arm with goosebumps. The meme is used to humorously convey intense satisfaction, excitement, or pleasure in response to a specific phrase or idea, which is placed over the top panel.

AJ-Styles--Undertaker.name: AJ-Styles--Undertaker

text_options.description: This text box is placed over The Undertaker. It represents the impending doom, threat, or negative consequence that the other subject is unaware of.
This text box is placed over the laughing AJ Styles. It represents the person or entity who is blissfully unaware or overconfident, about to be blindsided by the threat represented by The Undertaker.

AJ-Styles--Undertaker.image_description: This meme, known as 'Undertaker Standing Behind AJ Styles,' originates from a WWE WrestleMania match. It depicts wrestler The Undertaker looming menacingly behind a laughing and oblivious AJ Styles. The format is used to illustrate a situation where someone is enjoying themselves, completely unaware of an impending doom, problem, or negative consequence that is about to strike.

Soldier-protecting-sleeping-child.name: Soldier-protecting-sleeping-child

text_options.description: A label placed on the sleeping person, representing an individual, group, or concept that is oblivious to or benefiting from the sacrifice being made on their behalf.
A label placed on the soldier, identifying the person, entity, or concept that is making a sacrifice or enduring hardship to protect the sleeping person.
A label placed over the incoming projectiles, describing the various threats, problems, or negative influences that the soldier is shielding the sleeping person from.

Soldier-protecting-sleeping-child.image_description: This meme, known as "Soldier Protecting Sleeping Man" or "Sacrificing Soldier," shows a soldier in camouflage kneeling and shielding a peacefully sleeping person from a barrage of weapons like knives, grenades, and bullets. The soldier, who is on fire and bleeding, represents a person or entity making a significant, often unappreciated, sacrifice. The sleeping person represents an oblivious beneficiary, and the incoming projectiles represent the various dangers or problems being averted, creating a template to highlight thankless efforts or unseen struggles.

Megamind-no-bitches.name: Megamind-no-bitches

text_options.description: This bottom text area is where the punchline question is typically placed. The text is famously formatted as "No bitches?" but is often customized to "No [something desirable]?". This text directly asks about the thing that the subject of the meme is sadly lacking.

This top text area on Megamind's large forehead is often used for a caption that provides context or labels the person or group being addressed. It sets up the scenario for the punchline question below, identifying who is being mocked for their lack of something.

Megamind-no-bitches.image_description: This meme features a close-up, distorted image of the character Megamind from the film of the same name, looking down with a sad and disappointed expression. Known as the "No Bitches?" or "Megamind Peeking" meme, this image serves as the punchline, confirming a lack of something desirable. It's used as a reaction image to humorously convey disappointment, failure, or the absence of a particular item or quality that was questioned.

Who-Killed-Hannibal.name: Who-Killed-Hannibal

text_options.description: This text is placed over Eric Andre as he looks at the camera in feigned shock. It typically contains a question that shifts blame for the problem he just created, such as "Why would [someone else] do this?" or "I can't believe you've done this."

This text is placed over Hannibal Buress, who is slumped over in the chair as the victim. It represents the problem, the negative outcome, or the entity that has been harmed by the perpetrator's actions.
This text is placed over Eric Andre in the act of shooting. It identifies the perpetrator or the cause of the problem—the person or group responsible for harming the entity labeled in box 1.

Who-Killed-Hannibal.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Who Killed Hannibal?" or "Why Would X Do This?", originates from a skit on "The Eric Andre Show." In the top panel, host Eric Andre shoots his co-host Hannibal Buress. The bottom panel shows Eric Andre turning to the camera with a shocked expression. The meme is used to satirize someone causing a problem and then hypocritically blaming others or feigning ignorance about its cause.

Futurama-Fry.name: Futurama-Fry

text_options.description: The bottom text area contains the punchline, presenting the two conflicting options of the dilemma. It typically follows the format 'X, or just Y', where X is one possibility and Y is the alternative, often more mundane or cynical, explanation for the situation described in the top text.
The top text area sets up the scenario or question that causes the confusion. It almost always starts with the phrase 'Not sure if...' to introduce the dilemma that Fry is contemplating.

Futurama-Fry.image_description: This meme, known as 'Futurama Fry' or 'Not Sure If...', features a close-up of the character Philip J. Fry from the animated show 'Futurama'. Fry is depicted with a suspicious and uncertain expression, squinting his eyes as if deep in thought. The meme is used to express an internal monologue of confusion or suspicion, humorously weighing two conflicting possibilities for a given situation.

Surprised-Pikachu.name: Surprised-Pikachu

text_options.description: This text box, located directly above the Pikachu image, typically contains a label like 'Me:' or 'My face when:'. It serves to attribute the surprised reaction depicted by Pikachu to the person or entity who initiated the actions described in the text boxes above.

This middle text box describes the predictable, and usually negative, consequence that results from the action mentioned in the top box. It represents the 'effect' in the cause-and-effect setup of the meme.

The topmost text box sets up the scenario by describing an action or statement with a very obvious potential outcome. This is the 'cause' that leads to the predictable result and the feigned surprise.

Surprised-Pikachu.image_description: This meme features a still image of the Pokémon character Pikachu with a wide-eyed, open-mouthed expression of shock. Known as 'Surprised Pikachu' or 'Shocked Pikachu,' it originates from the Pokémon anime. The image is used as a reaction to an obvious or predictable outcome, sarcastically feigning surprise at a consequence that was clearly foreseeable.

Two-guys-on-a-bus.name: Two-guys-on-a-bus

text_options.description: This area, positioned over the happy passenger and the sunny landscape, is used to label the positive, optimistic, or fortunate perspective in a comparison. The text here represents the 'good' side of the duality being presented.

This area, placed over the sad passenger and the bleak cliffside, is used to label the negative, pessimistic, or unfortunate perspective. The text here directly contrasts with the text at index 0, representing the 'bad' side of the comparison.

Two-guys-on-a-bus.image_description: This meme, known as 'Two Guys on a Bus' or 'Two People on a Bus', features a cartoon of two men sitting on opposite sides of a bus. One man on the right looks happily out the window at a bright, sunny landscape, while the man on the left looks sadly at a bleak, rocky cliff face. The image is used to represent duality and contrasting perspectives, highlighting how people can experience the same situation differently or to compare two opposing outcomes, often representing optimism versus pessimism.

Grant-Gustin-over-grave.name: Grant-Gustin-over-grave

text_options.description: Text placed on the grave mound typically identifies the person, idea, or object that has been defeated, eliminated, or replaced. This represents the "victim" in the meme's narrative, whose demise is being celebrated by the cheerful character.

The text on the tombstone serves to label the "deceased" entity, reinforcing the finality of its end. This is where the name of the person, company, or concept that has been metaphorically killed or made obsolete is written, similar to a real epitaph.

Grant-Gustin-over-grave.image_description: This meme, known as "Grant Gustin Next to Oliver Queen's Grave," originates from a behind-the-scenes photo of the TV show "Arrow." It features actor Grant Gustin, who plays The Flash, cheerfully posing with a peace sign next to a freshly dug grave and tombstone while other actors look on somberly. The stark contrast between his happy demeanor and the funeral setting creates a humorous image. The meme is used to represent someone celebrating or being responsible for the downfall, failure, or metaphorical "death" of another person, concept, or thing.

Types-of-Headaches-meme.name: Types-of-Headaches-meme

text_options.description: This area is intentionally left blank in the meme template. It is located under the fourth head diagram, where a description might normally go, but its emptiness emphasizes that the source of the overwhelming headache is the concept described in the label above (box 1).

This is the punchline of the meme. Text placed here describes a specific, often trivial or mundane, situation that is comically presented as the cause of an extreme, all-encompassing headache, far worse than the medical examples shown.

Types-of-Headaches-meme.image_description: The "Types of Headaches" meme is a four-panel exploitable format that contrasts three medically illustrated headaches (Migraine, Hypertension, Stress) with a fourth, comically exaggerated one. This final panel depicts the entire head glowing red, signifying an overwhelming, all-encompassing source of annoyance or frustration. The humor comes from equating a mundane or specific irritant to an extreme level of pain, making it a popular way to complain about frustrating situations.

A-train-hitting-a-school-bus.name: A-train-hitting-a-school-bus

text_options.description: The text here, placed on the train, represents the overwhelming, unstoppable force or inevitable event. This label identifies the person, concept, or reality that is about to completely destroy the subject represented by the bus.

The text on the school bus identifies the vulnerable subject, plan, or idea that is about to be destroyed. This label represents the victim of the situation, something that is powerless against the oncoming force of the train.

A-train-hitting-a-school-bus.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Train Hitting a Bus,' shows a train about to collide with a school bus on the tracks, and then the moment of impact. The train is used to represent an unstoppable, overwhelming force, while the bus symbolizes a vulnerable person, plan, or idea. The meme humorously illustrates a situation where one thing is completely and brutally overpowered by another, highlighting the futility of the bus's position.
A-train-hitting-a-school-bus.display_name: A train hitting a school bus

George-Bush-911.name: George-Bush-911

text_options.description: Text placed over George W. Bush, who is receiving the news. This label typically represents the person, group, or entity reacting to the information, often standing in for the meme's creator or audience. His serious expression is recontextualized as a reaction to the punchline.

Text placed over Andrew Card, who is delivering the news. This text contains the punchline of the meme—a piece of information that is usually absurd, mundane, or comically out of place, which causes Bush's shocked reaction.

George-Bush-911.image_description: This meme, known as "George Bush 9/11 News" or "A Second Plane Has Hit the Towers," features a historical photo of U.S. President George W. Bush being informed by his Chief of Staff, Andrew Card, about the September 11th attacks. The meme subverts the serious nature of the original event for comedic effect. Card is shown whispering some absurd, trivial, or shocking news, and Bush's stunned expression is framed as the reaction, representing anyone receiving unexpected information.

Inhaling-Seagull.name: Inhaling-Seagull

text_options.description: This is the final and most impactful panel, where the seagull is screaming. The text placed here is the punchline of the meme – a loud, obvious, or frequently repeated phrase associated with the person or group introduced in the first panel. The visual effects in this panel emphasize the volume and intensity of the statement.

The third panel shows the seagull taking a deep breath, head tilted back. This is the peak of the inhalation before the scream. This box is almost always left empty to visually represent the act of inhaling deeply before shouting.

In the second panel, the seagull begins to inhale. This panel, along with the next, builds visual tension and anticipation for the coming outburst. It often remains blank, but if text is present, it continues the setup from the first panel.

This is the first panel, showing a calm seagull. The text here introduces the subject or sets the scene, often describing a person or group in a specific situation, just before they are about to speak.

Inhaling-Seagull.image_description: This meme, known as 'Inhaling Seagull,' is a four-panel comic strip showing a seagull taking a deep breath before letting out a loud squawk. The first three panels build anticipation as the seagull inhales, while the final panel, often with a red tint and lens flare, shows the loud exclamation. The meme is used to humorously represent someone preparing to say something obvious, repetitive, or annoying with great fervor.

Evil-Kermit.name: Evil-Kermit

text_options.description: This text is associated with the 'Evil Kermit' figure. It represents the user's intrusive, impulsive, or malevolent thought, often starting with 'Me to me:'. This text serves as the punchline, suggesting a selfish or irresponsible action that contradicts the good intention expressed by the other Kermit.

This text is associated with the regular Kermit the Frog. It typically represents a person's initial, responsible, or moral thought (e.g., 'I should study for my exam'). This sets up the internal dialogue and conflict that the meme portrays.

Evil-Kermit.image_description: A meme featuring two versions of Kermit the Frog, based on a scene from 'Muppets Most Wanted'. On the left is the regular Kermit, and on the right is a sinister-looking Kermit in a dark hood, resembling a Sith Lord from Star Wars. This 'Evil Kermit' or 'Me to Me' meme format illustrates an internal conflict between one's conscience (regular Kermit) and their darker, impulsive thoughts (Evil Kermit). It's used to humorously depict giving in to temptation or making a bad decision.

where-monkey.name: where-monkey

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the orangutan on the right who is asking the question. The text here represents a simple, direct, and often comically out-of-place question or desire, which is the punchline of the meme. For example, 'Where banana?'.

This text box is located in the upper part of the image, often serving as a caption to establish the context. This text typically describes a complex, serious, or abstract situation that the orangutans are supposedly discussing, creating a humorous contrast with the simple question asked by the orangutan at index 0.

where-monkey.image_description: This meme, known as 'Where Banana?' or 'Monke,' features three orangutans digitally edited into a BBC Breakfast news studio set. The orangutan on the right turns to the one in the middle, creating a dynamic of questioning. The meme is used to humorously express a very simple, direct, or primal thought or question in a situation that would normally call for more complex discussion, often captioned with the phrase 'Where [something simple]?'

Trump-Bill-Signing.name: Trump-Bill-Signing
