text_options.description: This is the right-hand page of the document Trump is holding. It is a blank space where users typically add the second half of a drawing or a punchline that complements the content on the left page.

This is the left-hand page of the document. It serves as a blank canvas for user-generated content, often the first part of a simple drawing or a setup for a joke that is completed on the right-hand page.

Trump-Bill-Signing.image_description: This meme features former U.S. President Donald Trump holding up an open folder with two blank pages, as if proudly displaying a signed executive order. The blank pages serve as a canvas for users to photoshop humorous drawings, text, or images, creating the illusion that Trump is presenting something childish, absurd, or nonsensical. The humor comes from the contrast between the serious official setting and the trivial content added to the documents.

Three-headed-Dragon.name: Three-headed-Dragon

text_options.description: This text label is placed on the body of the goofy-looking dragon head. It represents the outlier, the incompetent, or silly member of the group, which serves as the punchline of the meme.

This label is on the body of the central, menacing dragon head. The text here represents one of the two serious, competent, or formidable elements in the trio, setting up the contrast with the outlier.

This label is on the body of the left, menacing dragon head. Like the central head, this text represents the second serious and competent element, reinforcing the norm before the punchline is revealed.
Positioned at the top of the image, this text box typically contains a title or label for the group being compared. It provides the overall context for the three elements described below.

Three-headed-Dragon.image_description: This meme, known as "Three-Headed Dragon" or "Goofy Ghidorah," features a fan art depiction of King Ghidorah from the Godzilla franchise. Two of the dragon's heads are portrayed as menacing and serious, while the third head on the right is drawn in a comically goofy and derpy style. The meme is used to contrast two competent or serious entities with a third, comically inept or foolish outlier within the same group. The humor arises from the stark visual difference that highlights the odd one out.

Anime-Girl-Hiding-from-Terminator.name: Anime-Girl-Hiding-from-Terminator

text_options.description: The text here labels the crying anime girl. This position represents a person, group, or concept that is vulnerable, overwhelmed, and trying to hide from a perceived threat or responsibility.
This label is placed on the T-800 Terminator. The text here identifies the powerful, relentless, and unavoidable force, problem, or obligation that is pursuing the entity labeled on the girl.

Anime-Girl-Hiding-from-Terminator.image_description: This meme, often called "Terminator Hiding From Girl," features a crying anime girl hiding under a desk while a T-800 Terminator from the Terminator franchise stands menacingly behind her. The stark contrast between the cute, vulnerable girl and the relentless, powerful robot creates a humorous depiction of a one-sided conflict. It's typically used to represent someone trying to avoid an overwhelming or unavoidable problem, task, or entity.

cmon-do-something.name: cmon-do-something

text_options.description: This text box labels the object, person, or concept being poked by the stick figure. It represents the target of the user's impatience or mockery, the thing that is expected to 'do something'.

This text box typically contains the phrase 'C'mon, do something' or a label for the person doing the poking (e.g., 'Me'). It explicitly states the sentiment of impatience and anticipation that drives the meme.

cmon-do-something.image_description: This meme features a simple, crudely drawn character poking something with a stick. Known as the 'C'mon, Do Something' or 'Stickman Poking' meme, it's used to express impatience or to taunt something that is inactive, unresponsive, or not performing as expected. The user is metaphorically nudging a person, company, or situation, urging it to act.

Friendship-ended.name: Friendship-ended

text_options.description: This text box highlights the name of the new best friend, "SALMAN." In the meme template, this slot is used to name the person, object, or concept that is replacing the old one. Its central placement between the two main figures signifies the new alliance.

This text box contains the name of the former friend, "MUDASIR." This is the subject being rejected or renounced. In the meme format, this is where users place the name of the thing they are abandoning.

Friendship-ended.image_description: This is the original "Friendship Ended with Mudasir" meme, a viral image created by Pakistani man Asif Raza Rana to publicly declare the end of his friendship with Mudasir and the beginning of a new one with Salman. The image features Asif shaking hands with his new best friend, Salman, while photos of the ex-friend, Mudasir, are crossed out. The meme's earnest tone and distinctive graphic design made it famous, and its format is now widely used to humorously announce a shift in allegiance from one person, brand, or idea to another.

Disappointed-Black-Guy.name: Disappointed-Black-Guy

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the man's disappointed face. It contains the punchline of the meme, revealing the disappointing reality, negative outcome, or unexpected twist that contradicts the initial positive statement from the top panel.

This text box is positioned next to the man's smiling face. It describes an initial positive situation, a hopeful expectation, or an optimistic assumption. This text sets up the joke by establishing a scenario that seems favorable.

Disappointed-Black-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Disappointed Black Guy," uses a two-panel format to show a man's reaction shifting from happiness to disappointment. The top panel sets up a positive expectation or scenario, corresponding with his smiling face. The bottom panel reveals a negative or unexpected outcome, causing his expression to change to one of shock and dismay, making it a popular format for expressing relatable letdowns.

All-My-Homies-Hate.name: All-My-Homies-Hate

text_options.description: The bottom text area, which typically contains the punchline or the main action of the scenario. In the popular 'In Da Club' variant, this space is used for the iconic lyrics 'you can find me in the club, bottle full of bub,' completing the setup from the top text. For other 'Me and the Boys' formats, it describes the specific, often mundane or silly, activity the group is about to do.

The top text area, which serves as the setup or introduction for the meme. It often contains the first part of a song lyric, like 'Go shawty, it's your birthday,' which sets up the punchline at the bottom. Alternatively, it can introduce the group with phrases like 'Me and the boys' before the bottom text reveals their humorous mission.

All-My-Homies-Hate.image_description: A sepia-toned photo of a group of young Black men in winter coats posing inside a store, known as the 'Me and the Boys' or 'In Da Club' meme. The image depicts a group of friends or a 'squad' with a tough demeanor, often humorously contrasted with the text added by meme creators. This format is typically used to represent a group getting ready for an activity, often quoting rap lyrics or describing mundane tasks in a comically serious way.

Panik-Kalm-Panik.name: Panik-Kalm-Panik

text_options.description: This text box, corresponding to the bottom panel with a motion-blurred, panicked Meme Man, contains the punchline. It describes a new, often worse, problem or a negative realization that invalidates the temporary relief from the middle panel, escalating the initial panic.

This text box corresponds to the middle "Kalm" panel. It typically describes a solution, a positive development, or a moment of relief that seemingly resolves the initial problem stated in the top panel, creating a false sense of security.

This text box, located at the top next to the first "Panik" image, introduces the initial problem or stressful situation. It sets the scene for the narrative and gives the reason for Meme Man's initial panic.

Panik-Kalm-Panik.image_description: This is the "Panik, Kalm, Panik" meme, which features the surreal 3D character Meme Man in a three-panel format. The meme illustrates a short narrative of escalating anxiety: a stressful situation occurs (Panik), followed by a moment of relief or a solution (Kalm), and then a realization that makes the situation even worse (Panik). The intentionally misspelled words are a hallmark of memes featuring this character.

Third-World-Skeptical-Kid.name: Third-World-Skeptical-Kid

text_options.description: The bottom text area contains the punchline, which is the boy's skeptical reaction to the statement above. It's often phrased as a question beginning with 'So you're telling me...', rephrasing the initial statement to highlight its absurdity from his point of view.

The top text area typically contains a statement representing a 'first-world problem' or a naive belief. This text serves as the setup for the meme's punchline, presenting an idea that will be questioned by the boy's skeptical perspective.

Third-World-Skeptical-Kid.image_description: This meme, known as 'Skeptical Third World Kid,' features a young African boy looking sideways with a dubious and unimpressed expression at a woman next to him. The format is used to satirize 'first-world problems' or statements of privilege by contrasting them with the assumed hardships of life in a developing nation. The boy's skeptical gaze serves as a punchline, questioning the validity or importance of the initial statement.

Green-Background-or-whatever.name: Green-Background-or-whatever

text_options.description: The bottom text box, which typically contains the punchline, reaction, or outcome of the situation described in the top text. Its meaning is directly complemented by the video or image content that replaces the green screen.
The top text box, which serves as the setup for the meme. It usually describes a scenario, a person's action, or a general statement to establish context for the visual element and the bottom text.

Green-Background-or-whatever.image_description: This is a generic green screen meme template, widely used for creating video memes on platforms like TikTok, Instagram Reels, and YouTube Shorts. The format consists of a top and bottom caption overlaying a green background, which is meant to be replaced with a video or static image. This template is highly versatile and is used to frame a wide variety of humorous or relatable situations, where the text provides context for the visual content.

Grandma-Finds-The-Internet.name: Grandma-Finds-The-Internet

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the laptop, delivers the punchline. It represents the shocking, confusing, or unexpected search result or content that causes the grandma's reaction.
The top text acts as the setup for the meme. It usually contains a seemingly innocent question, a search query, or a statement that leads to the surprising discovery shown in the bottom text.

Grandma-Finds-The-Internet.image_description: This meme, known as 'Grandma Finds the Internet' or 'Confused Grandma,' features an elderly woman squinting at a laptop screen with a look of shock and confusion. The image humorously captures the reaction of someone, typically older or less familiar with the internet, encountering strange or unexpected online content. It's widely used to express bewilderment or a double-take reaction to surprising information found online.

No---Yes.name: No---Yes

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the approving Drake. It contains the text for the preferred, superior, or more desirable option in the comparison. This is the punchline of the meme, representing the thing that is being endorsed.

This text box is positioned next to the disapproving Drake. It is meant to contain text describing an idea, object, or action that is considered undesirable, unpopular, or the wrong choice. This sets up the contrast for the preferred option below.

No---Yes.image_description: This meme, known as "Drakeposting" or "Drake Hotline Bling," features two stills of the rapper Drake from his music video for "Hotline Bling." The top panel shows Drake with a look of disgust, rejecting something, while the bottom panel shows him smiling and pointing in approval. This format is widely used to express a preference for one thing over another, contrasting an undesirable option with a desirable one.

The-Rock-Driving.name: The-Rock-Driving

text_options.description: This text box represents the dialogue of the girl in the back seat. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically a simple question or statement that unexpectedly refutes or complicates what The Rock said in the first panel, causing his shocked reaction.

This text box corresponds to Dwayne Johnson's dialogue. It typically contains a confident, assertive, or declarative statement that sets up the premise of the joke, which is then immediately challenged by the text in the panel below.

The-Rock-Driving.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "The Rock Driving" or "Race to Witch Mountain," features actor Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson and actress AnnaSophia Robb in a car. In the first panel, The Rock makes a confident statement. In the second, the girl says something that unexpectedly contradicts or questions him. The final panel shows The Rock looking back in shock, making the format ideal for jokes where an assertion is hilariously undermined by a simple, unexpected counterpoint.

Star-Wars-Yoda.name: Star-Wars-Yoda

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline, often a variation of Yoda's quote, "There is another." This text provides an unexpected alternative or solution to the problem or statement presented in the top text box, completing the joke.

The top text box establishes the premise of the meme. It typically contains a statement describing a situation where there seems to be only one option or something is believed to be the last of its kind.

Star-Wars-Yoda.image_description: This meme features the character Yoda, a wise Jedi Master from the Star Wars franchise. The image is used in a two-panel format to represent the famous quote, "There is another." The meme sets up a scenario where something is believed to be the only or last of its kind, and the punchline reveals a surprising or hidden alternative, mimicking Yoda's role as a wise mentor revealing a hidden truth.

say-the-line-bart-simpsons.name: say-the-line-bart-simpsons

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the celebrating classroom in the bottom panel. It typically labels the group that benefits from the situation, often at the expense of the individual in the middle panel. The text here represents the collective joy and positive outcome for the majority.

Located in the middle panel over a sad-looking Bart Simpson, this text box identifies the individual or entity that is negatively affected by the initial statement. This character represents the 'loser' or victim in the scenario, whose disappointment is central to the meme's conflict.

This text box in the top panel contains the initial statement, announcement, or action that triggers the events of the meme. It is usually presented by an authority figure (the teacher) and sets up the contrasting reactions in the panels below.

say-the-line-bart-simpsons.image_description: This three-panel meme from "The Simpsons" illustrates a situation with contrasting outcomes. The top panel shows teacher Edna Krabappel making an announcement to her class. The middle panel shows a close-up of Bart Simpson looking dejected and disappointed. The final panel depicts the entire class, including Bart, erupting in wild celebration. The format is used to represent a scenario where an action or decision is detrimental to one person (Bart) but overwhelmingly beneficial or joyous for a larger group (the class).

The-Scroll-Of-Truth.name: The-Scroll-Of-Truth

text_options.description: This area, located in the water in the bottom-right panel, is typically part of the background art and does not contain editable text. The focus of this panel is the character's action of angrily discarding the scroll, symbolizing the rejection of the truth.

This is the central part of the meme, where the "truth" is written on the scroll. Text placed here is the punchline, usually an unpopular opinion, a harsh reality, or a statement that people don't want to accept, which causes the character's angry reaction.

The-Scroll-Of-Truth.image_description: The "Scroll of Truth" meme is a four-panel comic featuring a green adventurer who, after a long quest, finds a magical scroll. In the third panel, he unrolls it to read a profound truth, but in the final panel, he angrily throws the scroll away. This format is used to present an inconvenient, unpopular, or hard-to-swallow truth, with the character's rejection representing the audience's own denial or frustration with that reality.

is-this-butterfly.name: is-this-butterfly

text_options.description: The text here labels the main character, representing the person or group who is making an incorrect assumption or misidentifying something.
This area labels the butterfly, which represents the actual object or concept being observed and misunderstood by the character.

This text represents the incorrect conclusion or question asked by the character. In the original scene, the subtitle reads 'Is this a pigeon?', but in memes, it's replaced with a different, humorous misidentification of the object labeled at index 1.

is-this-butterfly.image_description: This meme, known as 'Is this a pigeon?', originates from a scene in the anime 'The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird'. It features an android character, Yutaro Katori, looking at a butterfly with a curious and naive expression. The format is used to humorously depict someone misinterpreting or mislabeling something, often due to ignorance or a flawed perspective.

Look-At-Me.name: Look-At-Me

text_options.description: This bottom text is the punchline, representing the new authority figure. It's a variation of the iconic line 'I'm the captain now,' directly stating who or what has taken control of the situation.
This top text establishes the context by identifying the original, established authority figure or the 'old captain' who is being overthrown or replaced.

Look-At-Me.image_description: A still image from the 2013 film 'Captain Phillips' featuring actor Barkhad Abdi as the Somali pirate Muse. In the scene, he asserts his dominance by saying, 'Look at me. I'm the captain now.' This meme is used to humorously illustrate a sudden and unexpected shift in power, where a new person or entity takes control from the established authority.

Spongebob-Ight-Imma-Head-Out.name: Spongebob-Ight-Imma-Head-Out

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, which reads "IGHT IMMA HEAD OUT." This colloquial phrase, meaning "Alright, I'm going to leave now," directly states the reaction to the situation described in the top text, solidifying the meme's purpose as a declaration of departure.
This top caption area is used to describe a scenario or situation. The text placed here provides the context that prompts SpongeBob's reaction to leave, setting up the punchline in the image below.

Spongebob-Ight-Imma-Head-Out.image_description: This meme, known as "Ight Imma Head Out," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants getting up from his armchair with a tired or smug expression. The image is taken from the SpongeBob episode "The Smoking Peanut." It is widely used to humorously express a desire to leave an awkward, uncomfortable, or undesirable situation, with SpongeBob's action of getting up perfectly representing the decision to exit.

spiderman-pointing-at-spiderman.name: spiderman-pointing-at-spiderman

text_options.description: This text label is placed over the Spider-Man on the right. It typically identifies one of the two parties in a situation of hypocrisy, self-contradiction, or uncanny similarity.
This text label is placed over the Spider-Man on the left. It identifies the second party, which is identical or shares the same characteristic as the first, creating the core joke of the meme.

spiderman-pointing-at-spiderman.image_description: This meme, known as 'Spider-Man Pointing at Spider-Man,' originates from the 1967 Spider-Man animated series. It depicts two identical Spider-Man characters pointing at each other in a standoff. The image is widely used to humorously illustrate situations where two people, groups, or concepts are identical, hypocritical, or ironically accusing each other of the same thing.

Two-Paths.name: Two-Paths

text_options.description: The text here labels the person or entity who is facing the decision. This is the central character of the meme's narrative, contemplating the two available options.

This label describes the 'bad' or difficult choice. The path leads to a dark, spooky castle, visually representing a negative or challenging option, which is often ironically presented as the more desirable or exciting one.

This label describes the 'good' or easy choice. The path leads to a bright, welcoming castle, visually representing a positive or straightforward option, which often serves as the boring or less appealing alternative in the meme's context.

Two-Paths.image_description: This meme, known as "Two Paths" or "Two Choices," depicts a person at a crossroads facing a decision between two distinct options. One path leads to a bright, sunny castle, symbolizing a conventional, easy, or morally good choice. The other path leads to a dark, stormy castle, representing a difficult, unconventional, or seemingly negative choice that is often framed as the more appealing or interesting one in a satirical way.

the-lion.name: the-lion

text_options.description: This bottom text box is for the attribution of the quote. It often serves as the punchline, crediting the quote to a comically inappropriate or unexpected source, such as a historical figure for a modern-day observation, or simply "Me."

This top text box contains the main body of the quote. The text is crafted to sound wise, profound, or motivational, but is usually satirical, nonsensical, or a mundane observation presented as deep wisdom.

the-lion.image_description: This meme format features a stoic, black-and-white image of a lion, often used to parody inspirational or "alpha male" quotes. The majestic and serious nature of the lion is juxtaposed with text that is typically humorous, absurd, or nonsensical, creating a comedic effect. The meme plays on the trend of using powerful imagery for profound-sounding but often shallow motivational content.

American-Chopper-Argument.name: American-Chopper-Argument

text_options.description: This is the final panel where Paul Sr. gets the last word. The text here is his concluding, often stubborn or definitive statement that ends the argument, delivered as he points angrily.

This panel captures the climax of the physical confrontation where Paul Jr. throws a chair in frustration. This box is often left blank or contains an action description like "*throws chair*" to represent the point where the argument becomes non-verbal and explosive.
In this panel, Paul Sr. is shouting back at his son. The text here is an angry, escalated rebuttal to the point made by Paul Jr. in the previous panel, showing the argument intensifying.
This panel shows Paul Jr. leaning in and yelling his counter-argument. The text here is the core of his position, presented more forcefully than his father's initial point, escalating the conflict.
This is the first panel, where Paul Sr. initiates the argument. The text here is the opening statement or a controversial opinion that sets up the entire debate.

American-Chopper-Argument.image_description: The "American Chopper Argument" meme features Paul Teutul Sr. and his son, Paul Jr., in a heated exchange from the reality show of the same name. This five-panel comic strip format depicts an escalating argument, culminating in a thrown chair and a final, emphatic point. The meme is widely used to humorously dramatize debates on any topic, with the text representing two conflicting viewpoints that grow increasingly passionate.

Domino-Effect.name: Domino-Effect

text_options.description: This area, covering the smallest dominoes and the man's hand, represents the initial, small action or catalyst. The text placed here is typically a seemingly minor or innocuous event that starts the chain reaction.

This area over the largest domino represents the final, massive outcome or consequence. The text here describes the dramatic, often unexpected or disastrous result that stems from the initial small action.

Domino-Effect.image_description: This meme, known as the "Domino Effect," originates from a physics demonstration video showing a chain reaction of progressively larger dominoes. A man is about to push a tiny domino, which will ultimately topple a massive one. The meme is used to illustrate how a small, seemingly insignificant initial event can lead to a much larger, often disproportionate and unforeseen consequence.

Absolute-Cinema.name: Absolute-Cinema

text_options.description: This text box, located at the bottom of the image, is used to label the subject that is considered inferior, mainstream, or less sophisticated in the comparison. It represents the thing that Scorsese (and the meme creator) is implicitly dismissing or looking down upon.

Positioned at the top of the image, this text box labels the subject that is considered superior, artistic, or the epitome of quality—often referred to as 'cinema.' This text represents the preferred option that Scorsese is championing with his authoritative gesture.

Absolute-Cinema.image_description: This meme features a black and white photograph of acclaimed film director Martin Scorsese sitting with his hands raised. He looks directly at the camera with a discerning expression, as if making a definitive statement. The meme is used to contrast two subjects, with Scorsese representing a preference for a more sophisticated, artistic, or 'high-culture' option over a more mainstream or populist one. His gesture and expression convey a sense of finality and authority, often humorously applied to debates about art, film, and media.

Scooby-doo-mask-reveal.name: Scooby-doo-mask-reveal

text_options.description: This label is placed on Fred in the bottom panel after the reveal. The text here identifies the person or entity who has uncovered the truth, and it typically mirrors the text in box 2.
This label is on the unmasked villain. The text here is the punchline, revealing the true, often surprising or mundane, cause of the problem that was initially blamed on the 'ghost'.
This label is on Fred in the top panel before the reveal. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity investigating a problem.
This label is on the disguised villain (the ghost). The text here represents the apparent problem, the scapegoat, or the surface-level issue that is being investigated.

Scooby-doo-mask-reveal.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Fred Unmasks Villain" or "Scooby-Doo Unmasking," originates from the cartoon "Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!". It shows Fred Jones unmasking a ghost to reveal a regular man underneath. The format is used to humorously reveal the true or underlying cause of a problem, where the ghost represents the perceived issue and the unmasked man is the actual, often unexpected, culprit.

whe-im-in-a-competition-and-my-opponent-.name: whe-im-in-a-competition-and-my-opponent-is

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme, revealing the identity of the opponent. The humor is derived from this opponent being an expert or the epitome of the skill described in the competition, which justifies Squidward's terrified reaction.
This text box is for defining the type of competition. Users insert a skill, trait, or activity here to set up the scenario, for example, 'a procrastination competition'.

whe-im-in-a-competition-and-my-opponent-.image_description: This meme, known as 'When I'm in a Competition and My Opponent Is,' features a low-resolution, shocked-looking Squidward Tentacles from SpongeBob SquarePants. The format sets up a hypothetical contest, and the humor comes from revealing an opponent who is an unbeatable expert or the very embodiment of the competition's theme. Squidward's horrified expression represents the user's realization that they have no chance of winning, creating a relatable and humorous scenario of being outmatched.
whe-im-in-a-competition-and-my-opponent-.display_name: whe im in a competition and my opponent is

Gus-Fring-we-are-not-the-same.name: Gus-Fring-we-are-not-the-same

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, which almost always reads, "We are not the same." It's placed at the bottom to deliver the final, conclusive statement of superiority after the comparison has been made.

This text block describes the meme creator's supposedly superior or more complex action or motivation. It directly contrasts with the statement in the top text block, establishing the core of the joke. For example, 'I [do the same action] for a much more elaborate/sinister reason.'

The top text block describes a common, simple, or relatable action or motivation attributed to the reader or a general audience. It sets up the comparison that follows. For example, 'You [do an action] because [simple reason].'

Gus-Fring-we-are-not-the-same.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor Giancarlo Esposito as his character Gus Fring from the TV series 'Breaking Bad' and 'Better Call Saul'. Fring, a calm and calculating villain, is shown adjusting his tie with an intense, serious expression, conveying a sense of superiority and meticulousness. This image is the template for the "We Are Not the Same" meme, which humorously contrasts two different motivations or actions to assert that one is more sophisticated, complex, or superior to the other.
Gus-Fring-we-are-not-the-same.display_name: Gus Fring we are not the same

Grim-Reaper-Knocking-Door.name: Grim-Reaper-Knocking-Door

text_options.description: The text on the closed door represents the final, unsuspecting victim or the punchline of the meme. This is the person, company, or concept that is next in line to be 'killed' or rendered obsolete by the force the Grim Reaper represents.

The text on this open, bloody door represents the second victim in the sequence. It builds upon the pattern established by the first victim (door 2) and reinforces the Reaper's unstoppable progress towards the final target.

The text on the furthest open door represents the first victim in the chronological sequence. It sets up the premise of the meme, establishing the pattern of destruction or obsolescence that the Grim Reaper is carrying out.

Grim-Reaper-Knocking-Door.image_description: This meme, known as 'Grim Reaper Knocking on Doors', depicts the personification of death with a scythe sequentially visiting three doors. Having already left two doors open with bloody trails leading from them, the Reaper is now knocking on the third, closed door. This format is used to humorously illustrate a powerful force or trend (the Reaper) systematically eliminating or making a series of related things obsolete (the doors), with the final one being the unsuspecting punchline.

Drake-Blank.name: Drake-Blank

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Drake looking pleased and pointing. It contains the text for the preferred or superior option, which is being approved of in contrast to the rejected option in the panel above.
This text box is placed next to the image of Drake looking displeased. It typically contains a word or phrase representing an idea, object, or action that is being rejected or considered inferior.

Drake-Blank.image_description: This meme, known as 'Drakeposting' or 'Drake Hotline Bling,' features two stills of the rapper Drake from his 'Hotline Bling' music video. The top panel shows Drake with a look of disgust, gesturing to reject something. In contrast, the bottom panel shows him smiling and pointing in approval. This popular two-panel format is used to express a clear preference for one thing (bottom) over another (top).

Finding-Neverland.name: Finding-Neverland

text_options.description: This text is placed on the bottom panel, showing the man hugging the boy. It represents the outcome or resolution, often showing the boy accepting the flawed comfort or the bittersweet result of the conversation, concluding the meme's narrative.

This text is placed on the middle panel next to the man (J.M. Barrie). It represents the man's comforting words, advice, or proposed solution to the boy's problem. This text is often the setup for the punchline, presenting a simplistic or humorous perspective.

This text is placed on the top panel next to the sad-looking boy (Peter). It typically describes the problem, disappointment, or sad realization that the boy is experiencing, setting up the premise of the meme.

Finding-Neverland.image_description: This three-panel meme format originates from the 2004 film "Finding Neverland," featuring J.M. Barrie (Johnny Depp) and Peter Llewelyn Davies (Freddie Highmore). The meme depicts a sad child being comforted by an adult. It is typically used to illustrate a scenario where someone expresses a problem or disappointment, and another person offers a simplistic, flawed, or comically inadequate solution, which is then accepted.

Charlie-Conspiracy-Always-Sunny-in-Phili.name: Charlie-Conspiracy-Always-Sunny-in-Philidelphia

text_options.description: This lower section of the image typically represents the person or entity being subjected to the wild explanation. The text here often labels the listener, who is usually confused or skeptical about the theory being presented.

This upper section, focusing on Charlie and his conspiracy board, represents the person frantically explaining their theory. The text here usually identifies the speaker (e.g., "Me") and the absurdly complex topic they are trying to connect, setting up the premise of the joke.

Charlie-Conspiracy-Always-Sunny-in-Phili.image_description: This meme, known as the "Pepe Silvia" or "Charlie Day Conspiracy" meme, originates from the TV show "It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia." It features the character Charlie Kelly looking disheveled and manic while gesturing wildly in front of a corkboard covered in papers and connected by red string. The meme is used to humorously represent someone frantically trying to explain a complex, convoluted, or nonsensical theory, symbolizing obsessive over-analysis and connecting unrelated dots.
Charlie-Conspiracy-Always-Sunny-in-Phili.display_name: Charlie Conspiracy Always Sunny in Philidelphia

Im-The-Captain-Now.name: Im-The-Captain-Now

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a variation of the character's famous quote. It typically reads, "Look at me. I'm the [new role] now," signifying the user's takeover of a situation established in the top text.

The top text box sets up the scenario, describing a situation where someone else is initially in charge or has authority. This provides the context for the power shift that the meme's punchline delivers.

Im-The-Captain-Now.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the character Abduwali Muse, played by Barkhad Abdi, from the movie "Captain Phillips" (2013). In the scene, he confronts Captain Phillips and declares, "Look at me. I'm the captain now." The meme is used to humorously assert dominance or take over a role in a given situation, often replacing "captain" with another title relevant to the context.

The-Most-Interesting-Man-In-The-World.name: The-Most-Interesting-Man-In-The-World

text_options.description: This is the bottom text and the punchline of the meme. It completes the phrase started in the top text, typically reading, "...but when I do, I [do something exceptional or humorous]." This line creates a humorous contrast with the setup, highlighting an exaggerated or superlative action.

This is the top text, which serves as the setup for the joke. It almost always follows the format, "I don't always [do a certain activity]..." This line establishes the premise that the speaker rarely engages in a particular, often mundane, behavior.

The-Most-Interesting-Man-In-The-World.image_description: This meme, known as "The Most Interesting Man in the World," features actor Jonathan Goldsmith from a Dos Equis beer ad campaign. The image depicts a suave, distinguished older man with a grey beard sitting confidently at a table with a beer. The meme is used to make hyperbolic or humorous claims following a specific two-part phrasal template, contrasting an infrequent action with an extraordinary outcome.
The-Most-Interesting-Man-In-The-World.display_name: The Most Interesting Man In The World

Bugs-bunny-communist.name: Bugs-bunny-communist

text_options.description: This bottom text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically contains a statement from a person claiming individual ownership of something, for example, "My girlfriend" or "My grades."

This top text box contains the punchline, representing Bugs Bunny's corrective statement. It humorously refutes the claim of individual ownership from the bottom text by rephrasing it as collective property, such as "*Our* girlfriend" or "*Our* grades."

Bugs-bunny-communist.image_description: This meme, known as "Communist Bugs Bunny" or "Our Meme," features the Looney Tunes character Bugs Bunny with a smug expression against the backdrop of the communist hammer and sickle symbol. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the beloved cartoon character with communist ideology. It is typically used to reframe a statement about personal possession ("my thing") into one of collective ownership ("our thing"), parodying the concept of communal property.

Jarvis-Template.name: Jarvis-Template

text_options.description: Located over Tony Stark's mouth, this is the punchline of the meme. The text here represents his witty, sarcastic, or often nonsensical reply, leveraging his character's smug and confident persona. In the popular 'I'm stuff' variant, this area contains that exact phrase as an absurdist response.
This top panel serves as the setup for the punchline. It typically contains a question, a statement from another character, or a description of a situation that prompts a response from Tony Stark.

Jarvis-Template.image_description: This meme features a close-up shot of Robert Downey Jr. as the character Tony Stark (Iron Man) with a smug expression. The format is a two-panel reaction meme where a statement or question is presented at the top, and Tony Stark provides a witty, sarcastic, or absurd response at the bottom. This template is famously used for the 'I'm Stuff' meme, a form of surrealist, ironic humor.

What-Gives-People-Feelings-of-Power.name: What-Gives-People-Feelings-of-Power

text_options.description: This is the primary punchline area of the meme. Users insert text describing a simple, everyday action or small victory that gives them an immense feeling of power, contrasting it with the lesser bars for 'Money' and 'Status'.

This area, located between the title and the bar chart, is intentionally left blank in the meme template. It serves as empty space to visually separate the setup from the chart itself, focusing all attention on the customizable punchline next to the largest bar.

What-Gives-People-Feelings-of-Power.image_description: The 'What Gives People Feelings of Power' meme is a hand-drawn bar chart format from a webcomic. It humorously compares conventional sources of power, like 'Money' and 'Status', with a third, user-defined category. This third category, represented by a disproportionately large bar, is used to highlight a mundane or relatable action that provides an exaggerated sense of satisfaction and control.
What-Gives-People-Feelings-of-Power.display_name: What Gives People Feelings of Power

Goose-Chase.name: Goose-Chase

text_options.description: This label is on the person running away. The text here typically represents the user, a relatable group, or anyone who is intimidated, overwhelmed, or wants to avoid the consequences of the statement made by the goose in the top panel.

This label is on the goose in the top panel. This text represents a powerful, often out-of-context or absurdly threatening statement made by an individual or entity. The goose's calm yet assertive expression sets up the punchline of the person fleeing in the panel below.

Goose-Chase.image_description: This is a two-panel comic meme format known as "I Am The Senate" or the goose chase meme. The top panel shows a close-up of a goose, and the bottom panel shows a person in a winter jacket running away from the same goose. The meme is used to depict a situation where one entity makes a powerful, absurd, or intimidating statement, causing another entity (the person) to flee in fear or exasperation.

patrick-to-do-list-actually-blank.name: patrick-to-do-list-actually-blank

text_options.description: This is the third item on the list. It often serves as the punchline, presenting a task that is either absurdly simple, completely off-topic, or highlights the character's simple-minded approach to their goals.
This is the second item on the list. It typically adds another task that builds on the first, often with a humorous or ironic twist, continuing the narrative of the list.
This is the first item on the to-do list. The text here usually establishes the main goal or the setup for the joke, representing the primary task at hand.

patrick-to-do-list-actually-blank.image_description: This meme, known as "Patrick's To-Do List," originates from the cartoon 'SpongeBob SquarePants.' It features Patrick Star's hand writing on a to-do list and is used to humorously represent tasks, priorities, or goals. The humor often stems from the simplicity, absurdity, or relatable procrastination depicted in the list items.
patrick-to-do-list-actually-blank.display_name: patrick to do list actually blank

Kombucha-Girl.name: Kombucha-Girl

text_options.description: Text placed here, above the woman's contemplative face, represents the preferred, more acceptable, or surprisingly good alternative. It contrasts with the text in the other panel, showing a shift in opinion from negative to positive or neutral.

Text placed in this box, above the woman's disgusted face, describes something undesirable, unpleasant, or an initial negative thought. This sets up the punchline or comparison presented in the second panel.

Kombucha-Girl.image_description: This two-panel meme features Brittany Broski, famously known as "Kombucha Girl," from a viral TikTok video where she tastes kombucha for the first time. The first panel shows her with a disgusted expression, representing an initial negative reaction or a disliked option. The second panel shows her with a contemplative, slightly intrigued look, signifying a change of heart, reluctant acceptance, or a better alternative. The meme is used to contrast two ideas, showing a progression from dislike to consideration.

the-office-congratulations.name: the-office-congratulations

text_options.description: This label is placed on Michael Scott, who represents the naive, enthusiastic, or less powerful party in an agreement. The text here identifies the person or group that is being taken advantage of or is entering a situation with misguided optimism.

This label is placed on Ed Truck, who represents the more powerful, experienced, or dominant party in the interaction. The text here identifies the entity that holds the upper hand or is benefiting from the naive agreement made by the other party.

the-office-congratulations.image_description: This meme features a flashback scene from the TV show "The Office," where a younger Michael Scott with a mullet awkwardly shakes hands with his former boss, Ed Truck. The format is typically used to represent an unequal agreement or interaction. Michael Scott represents a naive, enthusiastic, or foolish party, while Ed Truck represents a more powerful, knowing, or even exploitative entity that benefits from the exchange.

spongebob-rainbow.name: spongebob-rainbow

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image typically presents a problem, a question, or a challenging situation. This serves as the setup for the meme's punchline.

The text at the top, placed over the rainbow, represents the simplistic, naive, or magical solution to the problem stated below. Its placement along the rainbow emphasizes its fantastical and often impractical nature, delivering the sarcastic punchline.

spongebob-rainbow.image_description: This meme, known as "Imagination SpongeBob," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series creating a rainbow with his hands. Originating from the episode "Idiot Box," the image captures a moment where SpongeBob demonstrates the power of imagination. The meme is typically used sarcastically to mock overly simplistic, naive, or unrealistic solutions to complex problems, contrasting a difficult situation with a magical, effortless fix.

Dont-make-me-tap-the-sign.name: Dont-make-me-tap-the-sign

text_options.description: This area, representing the bus driver or the person tapping the sign, is often labeled to identify the individual, group, or entity that is frustrated and pointing out the obvious rule on the sign.

This large, blank sign is the focal point of the meme. Text placed here represents an obvious rule, a hard truth, or a frequently ignored piece of advice that the person 'tapping the sign' is exasperatedly pointing out.

Dont-make-me-tap-the-sign.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the animated TV show The Simpsons. The top panel shows the bus driver, Otto Mann, looking annoyed with the caption "DON'T MAKE ME TAP THE SIGN." The bottom panel shows a yellow cartoon hand pointing at a blank sign. The meme is used to express frustration when having to point out an obvious rule, fact, or piece of information that others are ignoring.
Dont-make-me-tap-the-sign.display_name: Dont make me tap the sign

obama-medal.name: obama-medal

text_options.description: This label is placed on the smiling Obama who is receiving the medal. The text here typically represents the person or entity being praised, often labeled simply as 'Me' after completing a task or achieving something.

This label is placed on the Obama who is awarding the medal. The text here represents the source of the praise, which is the same person or entity as the recipient. This is also frequently labeled 'Me,' completing the visual gag of self-congratulation.

obama-medal.image_description: This meme, known as "Obama Awards Obama a Medal," is a photoshopped image depicting former U.S. President Barack Obama awarding the Presidential Medal of Freedom to himself. The Obama receiving the award is smiling broadly, while the one presenting it looks on with a proud, serious expression. The meme is widely used to humorously illustrate situations of self-congratulation, self-praise, or giving oneself credit for an accomplishment, essentially 'patting yourself on the back'.

Who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire.name: Who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire

text_options.description: This is the second multiple-choice answer, labeled 'B'. It presents one of four potential, often humorous or equally undesirable, options in response to the question posed above.
This is the fourth and final multiple-choice answer, labeled 'D'. It completes the set of choices, solidifying the difficult or absurd dilemma the contestant is facing.
This is the third multiple-choice answer, labeled 'C'. It continues the list of options, contributing to the overall stressful or comical situation.
This is the first multiple-choice answer, labeled 'A'. It's the first of four options presented to the contestant, setting the tone for the difficult choice ahead.
This is the main question area. The text here poses a difficult, absurd, or stressful question that causes the man's panicked expression, setting up the entire premise of the meme.

Who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire.image_description: This meme features a photoshopped image of a man, often mistaken for Steve Harvey or Keegan-Michael Key, looking panicked and wide-eyed as a contestant on the game show 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'. The format is used to express extreme stress, confusion, or being faced with an impossible or absurd multiple-choice question. The humor comes from the relatable feeling of panic when confronted with a high-stakes, difficult decision, framed within the familiar game show context.
Who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire.display_name: Who wants to be a millionaire

undertaker.name: undertaker

text_options.description: This text box is placed over wrestler AJ Styles, who looks upward, unaware of the figure behind him. The text here typically represents a person, company, or concept that is enjoying a moment of success or is simply oblivious to an impending problem or downfall.

This text box is placed over the menacing face of wrestler The Undertaker. The text here represents the looming threat, the unexpected challenge, or the superior force that is about to surprise and overwhelm the subject labeled in box 0.

undertaker.image_description: This meme, known as "Undertaker Standing Behind AJ Styles," features professional wrestler The Undertaker looming menacingly behind a blissfully unaware AJ Styles. The image captures a moment of dramatic irony, where one character is oblivious to an immediate and significant threat. It is widely used to represent situations where a person, group, or idea is about to be blindsided by a superior force, an unexpected problem, or a negative consequence they haven't seen coming.

Wolverine-Remember.name: Wolverine-Remember

text_options.description: This area inside the picture frame is the focal point of the meme. Users insert an image or text representing the person, object, or concept that is being longed for or missed. This is the punchline and the subject of Wolverine's (and the creator's) nostalgia.

Text placed on the headboard of the bed typically serves as a label to identify who or what Wolverine represents in the context of the meme. For example, it might say 'Me,' 'Gamers,' or 'My Dad,' providing context for who is feeling the sense of longing.

Wolverine-Remember.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Wolverine Crush,' features the X-Men character Wolverine lying in bed and looking wistfully at a framed picture. The top panel shows Wolverine's melancholic expression, while the bottom panel is a close-up of him holding the frame. This format is used to express longing, nostalgia, or sadness for something or someone that is missed or unattainable, with the object of affection placed inside the frame.

i-receive-you-receive.name: i-receive-you-receive

text_options.description: This text box, positioned under "you receive:", describes what the viewer or the second party in the transaction will get. The humor of the meme relies on this item being something of very little value, undesirable, or completely insignificant compared to what the proposer receives.

This text box, located under "i receive:", is where the meme creator lists what they will get out of the proposed trade. This is typically something highly valuable or desirable, creating a stark, humorous contrast with the meager offering in the "you receive" box.

i-receive-you-receive.image_description: This meme, known as "Trade Offer," features TikTok creator @bradeazy dressed as a businessman making a proposition. He looks directly at the viewer with a serious expression, presenting a deal under a red "TRADE OFFER" banner. The format is used to humorously highlight lopsided or unfair exchanges, where the proposer offers something of little value in return for something significant. The meme's versatility allows it to comment on a wide range of scenarios, from gaming to social dynamics.

Moe-throws-Barney.name: Moe-throws-Barney

text_options.description: This text label is placed on Barney in the final panel as he reappears. It typically repeats the text from index 2, representing the problem or idea that has stubbornly and immediately returned despite efforts to remove it.
This label is placed on Moe in the middle panel. The text here identifies the person or entity who believes they have successfully solved a problem or gotten rid of something undesirable.

This text label is placed on Barney in the top panel as he is being thrown out. It represents the initial problem, unwelcome idea, or person that the subject (Moe) is trying to forcefully reject or remove.

Moe-throws-Barney.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Moe Throws Barney Out," originates from the animated series The Simpsons. It depicts bartender Moe Szyslak forcefully ejecting his patron Barney Gumble from the bar. After Moe dusts off his hands in satisfaction, he turns to find Barney has instantly and inexplicably reappeared behind him. The format is used to represent getting rid of a problem, idea, or person, only for it to immediately return, much to the subject's annoyance.

You-know-Im-something-of-a-scientist-mys.name: You-know-Im-something-of-a-scientist-myself

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always the character's famous quote: "You know, I'm something of a scientist myself." This text represents the speaker's exaggerated or ironic claim to expertise.

This top section provides the setup or context for the meme. It typically describes a simple, mundane, or slightly clever action performed by the user, which then humorously justifies the exaggerated claim of expertise made in the bottom text.

You-know-Im-something-of-a-scientist-mys.image_description: This meme features a still of actor Willem Dafoe as Norman Osborn from the 2002 film "Spider-Man," smiling with a self-satisfied expression. The image is famously associated with the quote, "You know, I'm something of a scientist myself." It is used to humorously and often ironically claim expertise in a particular field after performing a very basic or trivial task related to it.
You-know-Im-something-of-a-scientist-mys.display_name: You know Im something of a scientist myself

Sure-grandma-lets-get-you-to-bed.name: Sure-grandma-lets-get-you-to-bed

text_options.description: This label is placed on the young woman. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is providing support or 'carrying' the other entity. This is the strong, capable, or modern element in the meme's comparison.

This label is placed on the elderly woman using a walker. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is struggling, outdated, or being supported by the other. This represents the weaker element that requires assistance.

Sure-grandma-lets-get-you-to-bed.image_description: This meme, often called "Woman Helping Elderly Woman," features a stock photo of a young woman assisting an elderly woman with a walker. The format is used to humorously depict a situation where one entity is supporting or "carrying" another, often weaker or less competent entity. The young woman represents the capable party, while the elderly woman represents the one being supported, commonly applied to scenarios in gaming, group projects, or technology.
Sure-grandma-lets-get-you-to-bed.display_name: Sure grandma lets get you to bed

Both-Buttons-Pressed.name: Both-Buttons-Pressed

text_options.description: This label is placed on the man in the bottom panel and identifies the person or entity facing the dilemma. This is the subject who makes the difficult or often contradictory choice and feels smug about it.
This text box labels the button on the right, representing the first of two conflicting choices, desires, or ideas. It sets up one side of the dilemma.

This text box labels the button on the left, representing the second conflicting choice, which is often at odds with the first option. Together with the other button, it establishes the central conflict of the meme.

Both-Buttons-Pressed.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as 'Two Buttons' or 'Daily Struggle,' depicts a character making a difficult choice. In the first panel, a hand presses two separate red buttons simultaneously, representing two conflicting options. In the second panel, a smug-looking man with a prominent chin gives a thumbs-up, signifying his satisfaction with choosing both options, a third alternative, or simply embracing the conflict. The meme is used to humorously illustrate internal conflicts, dilemmas, or hypocritical decisions.

Yo-Dawg-Heard-You.name: Yo-Dawg-Heard-You

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which serves as the punchline of the meme. It completes the recursive phrase started in the top text, typically following the format '...so I put an X in your Y so you can [verb] while you [verb].'
This is the top text, which sets up the premise of the joke. It almost always starts with the phrase 'Yo dawg, I herd you like X...' where 'X' is the object or concept that will be humorously nested.

Yo-Dawg-Heard-You.image_description: This meme features a smiling picture of the rapper Xzibit, who hosted the MTV show "Pimp My Ride." Known as the "Yo Dawg" or "Xzibit meme," it's used to create jokes about recursion or putting one thing inside another similar thing. The humor comes from the nested, and often absurd, logic presented in the text, mimicking the show's style of adding extravagant features to cars.

The-future-world-if.name: The-future-world-if

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom contains the punchline of the meme. It describes the specific, often trivial or mundane, condition that, if met, would supposedly lead to the utopian society shown. For example, '...people didn't leave their shopping carts in the middle of the parking lot.'
This text box at the top serves as the setup for the meme. It typically contains a phrase like "Society if..." or "The world if..." which introduces the image as a representation of an ideal future.

The-future-world-if.image_description: This meme, often captioned "Society If..." or "The World If...", depicts a technologically advanced, utopian future with flying cars, sleek architecture, and a clean environment. It is used to humorously suggest that if a specific, often minor, problem or annoyance were solved, humanity would have already achieved this perfect world. The meme's humor comes from the dramatic contrast between the grand, idealized future and the mundane, everyday issue presented in the text.

damn-got-hands.name: damn-got-hands

text_options.description: This text box identifies the opponent or challenge that has just defeated the subject. It follows the word "damn" and precedes "got hands," completing the punchline that the underestimated foe was surprisingly skilled. The text here is typically the same as in the top panel.

This text box is used to name the opponent or challenge that the subject is about to confront. It follows the phrase "ok ima fight," establishing the setup for the meme by showing the subject's initial, often misplaced, confidence.

damn-got-hands.image_description: This is a two-panel meme featuring a 3D-rendered boxer, used to express underestimating a challenge and being swiftly defeated. In the top panel, the boxer stands confidently in a fighting stance with the text "ok ima fight [opponent]". The bottom panel shows the same boxer looking dejected and beaten, sitting down and drinking water, with the text "damn [opponent] got hands." The meme humorously portrays a situation where someone's initial confidence is shattered after they realize their opponent or task is much more difficult than anticipated.

Bad-Luck-Brian.name: Bad-Luck-Brian

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image, which serves as the punchline. It describes the unfortunate, embarrassing, or disastrous outcome of the situation established in the top text, highlighting the character's signature bad luck.
The top text of the image, which sets up a scenario. This text usually describes a seemingly normal, hopeful, or mundane action or event that the character is involved in.

Bad-Luck-Brian.image_description: This is the "Bad Luck Brian" meme, an image macro series featuring a yearbook photo of a young man with braces and a plaid sweater vest. The character represents someone with chronic misfortune and social awkwardness. The meme is used to describe a variety of embarrassing, tragic, or unlucky situations, creating humor from schadenfreude. The format typically presents a setup on the top line and an unfortunate punchline on the bottom.

Black-guy-hiding-behind-tree.name: Black-guy-hiding-behind-tree

text_options.description: This label is placed next to the tree, which acts as a visual barrier or hiding spot. The text here typically represents the target of the main character's anticipation or the situation they are about to take advantage of.
This label is placed over the man's face. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is eagerly and greedily anticipating something good happening to them.

Black-guy-hiding-behind-tree.image_description: This meme, known as "Anthony Adams Rubbing Hands" or "Yellow Suit Guy," features a man in a bright yellow jacket peeking from behind a tree. He is rubbing his hands together with a greedy, anticipatory expression, licking his lips. The meme is used to represent someone eagerly awaiting a favorable outcome, often in a mischievous or self-serving way, as if they are about to get exactly what they want.

Mr-McMahon-reaction.name: Mr-McMahon-reaction

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to the final, most intense reaction. The text here represents the ultimate, most desirable, or mind-blowing option in the series, eliciting the peak level of excitement.

Paired with McMahon's overtly shocked and excited expression, this text box contains a significantly better or more impressive option than the previous ones, representing a major step up in desirability.
This text box is placed next to McMahon's expression of growing interest. The text here describes an option that is superior to the first one, showing an increase in approval or excitement.

This text box, located at the top next to McMahon's most subdued expression, introduces the first and most basic or least impressive item in the comparison. It serves as the baseline for the escalating reactions.

Mr-McMahon-reaction.image_description: This meme, known as 'Vince McMahon Reaction', features a four-panel comic strip of former WWE CEO Vince McMahon reacting with escalating excitement. The format is used to rank or compare a list of related concepts or items, with each subsequent panel representing a more desirable, impressive, or appealing option. The final panel, showing McMahon with a red tint and glowing eyes, signifies the ultimate or most mind-blowing choice in the hierarchy.

Man-Holding-Cardboard-Sign.name: Man-Holding-Cardboard-Sign

text_options.description: This area is the blank cardboard sign, which serves as the main canvas for the meme's text. The user adds a short, punchy statement here that represents a humorous or relatable complaint, social commentary, or a mundane 'protest,' forming the core punchline of the meme.

Man-Holding-Cardboard-Sign.image_description: This meme, known as 'Dude with Sign,' features a man holding a blank cardboard sign aloft in a crowd, mimicking a protest. The format is used to voice humorous, relatable, or mundane complaints and observations about everyday life by adding text to the sign. The humor arises from the contrast between the serious protest format and the often trivial nature of the 'cause'.

elmo-cocaine.name: elmo-cocaine

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the white powder where Elmo has collapsed. It typically represents the overwhelming task, addiction, or source of burnout that has led to the subject's downfall or exhaustion.

This text box is placed over the fruit in the bottom panel. It represents the healthy, responsible, or planned activities that were neglected or ignored in favor of the vice, remaining untouched after the crash.
This text box labels Elmo in his upright, energetic state in the top panel. It represents the subject (e.g., 'Me') at the beginning, full of ambition and ready to engage with something.

This text box is placed over the pile of white powder in the top panel. It represents a tempting but ultimately destructive or exhausting vice, task, or interest that the subject is about to indulge in.
This text box is placed over the fruit (an apple and banana) in the top panel. It represents the responsible, healthy, or productive choice that the subject should be making but is about to ignore.

elmo-cocaine.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Elmo Rise" or "Cocaine Elmo," features the Sesame Street character Elmo. In the top panel, Elmo sits enthusiastically before a pile of white powder and some fruit. In the bottom panel, he has collapsed face-first into the powder. The meme humorously contrasts initial energy and ambition with subsequent burnout and exhaustion, often by labeling the fruit as a responsible choice and the powder as a tempting but draining vice.

Here-it-comes.name: Here-it-comes

text_options.description: Text in this area, often placed directly over the man, identifies the person, group, or entity that is panicking, overwhelmed, or foolishly confronting a superior force. This label establishes the protagonist or the subject of the meme's joke.

Text placed over the tornado represents the overwhelming problem, unstoppable force, or abstract concept that is causing the man's distress. This label acts as the antagonist or the source of the conflict, highlighting the absurdity of the man's reaction or situation.

Here-it-comes.image_description: This meme, known as "Tornado Selfie" or "Man Screaming at Tornado," features a man with a distressed, screaming expression taking a selfie in front of a large tornado in a desert. The man represents an individual or group foolishly confronting or being overwhelmed by a much larger, more powerful force. The meme is used to humorously depict lopsided conflicts, poor decision-making, or someone being completely outmatched by a situation or problem, which is represented by the tornado.

Live-reaction.name: Live-reaction

text_options.description: This small box in the bottom-right corner is part of the main placeholder area. In the context of the meme, this specific location is not typically used for user-added text and the number '0' appears to be part of the template image itself, rather than a space for customization.

This central area within the red banner, located between 'LIVE' and 'REACTION', is a customizable space. Users typically insert a name, pronoun, or noun here to specify who or what is reacting (e.g., 'My Honest Reaction,' 'The Internet's Reaction'). This text provides crucial context, identifying the subject of the reaction shown in the image below.

Live-reaction.image_description: This is a 'Live Reaction' meme template, designed to look like a news broadcast graphic. It features a red banner at the top with the text 'LIVE REACTION' and a large black placeholder box below. Users insert an image or video into the black box to represent a reaction to a preceding statement, image, or situation, often for humorous or satirical effect.

I-dont-want-to-play-with-you-anymore.name: I-dont-want-to-play-with-you-anymore

text_options.description: This label is placed on the toy, Woody, who is being dropped. Text here represents the old, outdated, or abandoned item, idea, or person that is being rejected.
This label is placed on Andy, the boy dropping the toy. Text here represents the person, group, or entity that is doing the abandoning in favor of something new.

I-dont-want-to-play-with-you-anymore.image_description: This meme originates from the movie Toy Story 2, showing the character Andy dropping his once-beloved toy, Woody, with the caption "I don't want to play with you anymore." The scene captures a moment of abandonment and moving on. Culturally, this meme format is used to humorously depict someone discarding an old interest, hobby, technology, or person in favor of a newer, more exciting alternative.
I-dont-want-to-play-with-you-anymore.display_name: I dont want to play with you anymore

Skinner-Out-Of-Touch.name: Skinner-Out-Of-Touch

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the bottom panel where Skinner has a look of shocked realization. The text here is the punchline, representing the character's flawed conclusion. The classic line is "No, it's the children who are wrong," which ironically confirms that the person is, in fact, out of touch and unwilling to accept it.

This text box is placed on the top panel where Principal Skinner looks pensive. The text here represents a moment of self-reflection or questioning, typically phrased as a question like "Am I so out of touch?". It sets up the premise of someone doubting their own perspective or relevance in a given situation.

Skinner-Out-Of-Touch.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Am I So Out of Touch?" or "Skinner's Pathetic," features Principal Skinner from The Simpsons. In the top panel, Skinner thoughtfully questions his own relevance or understanding of a situation. The bottom panel shows his sudden, incorrect realization, where he blames others instead of himself. The meme is used to humorously depict someone who is completely out of touch with reality but refuses to admit it, instead concluding that everyone else is the problem.

That-Would-Be-Great.name: That-Would-Be-Great

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always the character's catchphrase, "That would be great." This phrase delivers the sarcastic and passive-aggressive tone of the request, making the meme's point.

The top text box sets up the scenario by describing an inconvenient or unreasonable request. It's phrased as a polite suggestion, often starting with "If you could just..." to mimic the character's condescending way of speaking.

That-Would-Be-Great.image_description: This meme features Bill Lumbergh, the condescending boss from the 1999 film "Office Space." In the image, he stands in an office cubicle farm, holding a mug with a smug expression. The meme, known as "That Would Be Great," is used to make sarcastic or passive-aggressive requests, mimicking Lumbergh's annoying and micromanaging demeanor when asking employees to do something unreasonable or inconvenient.

Oh-yeah-Oh-no.name: Oh-yeah-Oh-no

text_options.description: The text in the bottom panel, next to the disappointed expression, describes the negative outcome or the disappointing reality. This serves as the punchline, subverting the expectation set in the top panel.
The text in the top panel, corresponding with the smiling face, sets up a positive scenario or a hopeful expectation. This is the premise of the joke.

Oh-yeah-Oh-no.image_description: This meme, known as "Disappointed Black Guy", features actor Kayode Ewumi in two vertically stacked panels with contrasting expressions. The top panel shows him smiling confidently, representing a positive expectation or a favorable situation. The bottom panel shows a sudden shift to a look of shock and disappointment, representing the negative or unexpected reality. This format is used to humorously contrast expectations with a harsh or disappointing outcome.

Blank-White-Template.name: Blank-White-Template

text_options.description: The bottom panel of a two-panel meme. This area typically contains the punchline, the reaction, or the outcome of the situation presented in the top panel. It's the core of the joke, often presenting an unexpected, funny, or relatable response.

The top panel of a two-panel meme. This section is used to set up the premise of the joke or comparison. The text here introduces a situation, a statement, or a question that the bottom panel will then react to or resolve.

Blank-White-Template.image_description: This is a generic two-panel vertical meme template, one of the most fundamental formats for creating memes. It is used for comparisons, showing a cause-and-effect relationship, or presenting a setup followed by a punchline. The simplicity of the format allows for endless variations, where the top image or text sets a premise and the bottom one provides a reaction or a contrasting outcome.

family-guy-louis-pills.name: family-guy-louis-pills

text_options.description: Text placed over Lois Griffin describes a person, group, or situation that is problematic, stressful, or annoying. This element sets up the problem that the 'pills' are meant to solve or provide a coping mechanism for.

Text on the label of the oversized pill bottle describes the 'solution' or 'cure' for the problem represented by Lois. This is often a harsh truth, an extreme action, or a coping mechanism, serving as the punchline of the meme.

family-guy-louis-pills.image_description: This meme, known as 'Lois's Pills,' originates from the animated show 'Family Guy.' It depicts the character Lois Griffin looking stressed or weary while sitting at a table next to a giant prescription pill bottle. The format is used to illustrate a difficult situation (represented by Lois) and the extreme or necessary 'solution' or 'hard pill to swallow' (labeled on the bottle) required to deal with it.

kermit-window.name: kermit-window

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned near Kermit, typically contains the punchline or the sad realization. This text expresses the specific feeling of disappointment or melancholy that aligns with Kermit's somber mood, completing the thought set up by the top text.
The top text serves as the setup for the meme. It usually describes a situation, a thought, or an expectation that leads to a feeling of sadness or disappointment.

kermit-window.image_description: This meme features a plush toy of Kermit the Frog from The Muppets, looking forlornly out a window covered in raindrops. The image conveys a strong sense of sadness, disappointment, and introspection. It's typically used to express a sad realization or a relatable, melancholic thought, often contrasting an initial expectation with a disappointing reality.

Imagination-Spongebob.name: Imagination-Spongebob

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, located below SpongeBob's hands. This area typically contains the original statement, idea, or quote that is being mocked or dismissed as naive.

The top text, positioned over the rainbow. This is the punchline, which sarcastically rephrases the bottom text to highlight its perceived foolishness. It often uses alternating upper and lower case letters (known as 'mocking SpongeBob text') to emphasize the condescending tone.

Imagination-Spongebob.image_description: This meme, known as 'Imagination SpongeBob' or 'SpongeBob Rainbow,' features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the eponymous TV show, cheerfully making a rainbow with his hands. The image is used to sarcastically mock or condescend to an idea, statement, or another person's opinion. The rainbow symbolizes the naive or childish 'imagination' being used, implying the original point is foolish or simplistic.

Never-ask-a-woman-her-age.name: Never-ask-a-woman-her-age

text_options.description: This is the punchline area. Text here describes the specific, often humorous or niche, question or topic that should never be brought up to the group or person mentioned in the line above (index 1). It completes the "rule of three" setup by the first two panels.
This area is for the subject of the third taboo. Text here typically names a person, a group, or a character archetype to whom the forbidden question in the line below (index 0) should not be asked.

Never-ask-a-woman-her-age.image_description: This is a three-panel exploitable meme format known as "Never Ask A Woman Her Age." The first two panels establish a pattern by stating common social taboos: asking a woman her age and a man his salary, each accompanied by a generic cartoon character. The third panel is left blank for the user to add their own humorous or niche taboo, often an inside joke or a sensitive topic within a specific community or fandom, creating the punchline.
Never-ask-a-woman-her-age.display_name: Never ask a woman her age

Community-Fire-Pizza-Meme.name: Community-Fire-Pizza-Meme

text_options.description: This label is placed on a character in the background, observing the chaos. Text here typically represents a secondary problem, a bystander, or a contributing factor that is being ignored amidst the larger disaster.
This label is on two people on the floor. Text here often represents the victims of the situation, a specific failure, or a direct consequence of the main problem.
This label highlights the fire on the floor, the most obvious sign of disaster. Text in this area usually represents the central problem, the core of the chaos, or the main issue causing the turmoil.

This label is on a character actively participating in the chaos. Text here often represents the person or entity causing the problem, or someone trying to deal with it in a destructive or ineffective way.

This label is on the character Troy in the top panel, before he sees the chaos. Text here represents the user or an optimistic entity who is blissfully unaware of the disastrous situation they are about to encounter.

Community-Fire-Pizza-Meme.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the TV show "Community" and is often called "Troy Enters with Pizza" or "The Darkest Timeline." The top panel shows the character Troy Barnes arriving with pizzas, looking happy and hopeful. The bottom panel reveals the chaotic, fiery scene he is walking into, capturing his look of shock. This meme is used to represent someone innocently entering a disastrous or overwhelming situation, contrasting blissful ignorance with a harsh, chaotic reality.

triggerpaul.name: triggerpaul

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the statement being mocked. It is almost always written in alternating upper and lower case letters (e.g., "iT iS aLmOsT aLwAyS wRiTtEn LiKe ThIs") to mimic a sarcastic, childish, or mocking tone of voice, which directly corresponds to SpongeBob's derisive posture.

The top text area typically provides the context or the original, un-mocked statement that the meme is responding to. This could be a quote, a screenshot of a comment, or a simple declarative sentence that the user finds foolish or worthy of ridicule. It sets up the punchline that follows below.

triggerpaul.image_description: This meme, known as "Mocking SpongeBob" or "SpongeBob Chicken," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the eponymous animated series.
