He is depicted with a distorted, wild-eyed expression and a contorted body, as if clucking like a chicken. The image is used to sarcastically mock or ridicule a statement or opinion by repeating it in a condescending tone. The alternating case text often used with this meme visually represents this mocking voice.

Spongebob-Burning-Paper.name: Spongebob-Burning-Paper

text_options.description: This text is placed over the final panel where SpongeBob is warming his hands. It typically describes the feeling of relief, satisfaction, or blissful ignorance after having 'destroyed' the responsibility from the first panel, serving as the punchline.

This text is placed over the second panel where SpongeBob is scrutinizing the paper. It usually represents the user or a character contemplating the task or information written on the paper, often with a serious or annoyed expression before deciding to discard it.

This text is placed on the blank piece of paper SpongeBob is holding up in the first panel. It represents a task, responsibility, piece of advice, or any unwanted information that the subject of the meme is supposed to address but will ultimately ignore.

Spongebob-Burning-Paper.image_description: A four-panel meme from SpongeBob SquarePants, often called 'SpongeBob Burning Paper'. In the sequence, SpongeBob holds up a piece of paper, looks at it with a critical expression, then cheerfully throws it into a fire and warms his hands. The meme is used to humorously depict someone acknowledging a responsibility, task, or piece of advice, only to deliberately and happily ignore or destroy it.

Soyboy-Vs-Yes-Chad.name: Soyboy-Vs-Yes-Chad

text_options.description: This text box is placed under the 'Chad' character. It typically contains a short, simple, and confident statement representing the superior or desirable opinion in the comparison.

This text box is located under the crying 'Soyjak' character. It usually features a long, rambling, emotional, or nonsensical argument that represents the inferior or contemptible viewpoint being mocked.

Soyboy-Vs-Yes-Chad.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Soyjak vs. Chad' or 'Virgin vs. Chad,' contrasts two opposing viewpoints or individuals using Wojak characters. On the left, the emotional and distraught 'Soyjak' represents a perceived weaker, inferior, or contemptible stance. On the right, the stoic and masculine 'Nordic/Yes Chad' embodies the superior, correct, or desirable alternative, creating a clear dichotomy of good versus bad.

Mugatu-So-Hot-Right-Now.name: Mugatu-So-Hot-Right-Now

text_options.description: This area, covering the flamboyant Mugatu and his stern assistant Katinka, represents the person or entity holding a very enthusiastic and often unpopular or niche opinion.
This area, covering the unimpressed audience in the background, represents the general public, the mainstream, or anyone who does not share the intense passion of the person in the foreground.

Mugatu-So-Hot-Right-Now.image_description: A scene from the movie Zoolander (2001) featuring the villainous fashion designer Mugatu (Will Ferrell) shouting enthusiastically in the foreground, while the audience behind him looks on with unimpressed or neutral expressions. This meme format, often associated with the line "He's so hot right now," is used to contrast someone's passionate, often niche, interest with the indifference of the general public.

Borat-2-Tonight-Queen.name: Borat-2-Tonight-Queen

text_options.description: This text box is for a name or subject in the most recent message, 'tonite 👀'. It repeats the initial message, emphasizing the sender's persistent and unsuccessful efforts, which is the core of the meme's humor.

This text box is for a name or subject in the middle message, 'tonight queen??'. This represents a variation in the sender's approach, using a term of endearment ('queen') that can be interpreted as overly familiar or cringey, escalating the perceived desperation.

This text box is for a name or subject in the first message sent, 'tonite 👀'. It establishes the initial, unanswered attempt to make plans, setting the stage for the subsequent messages that highlight the sender's persistence.

Borat-2-Tonight-Queen.image_description: This meme, known as 'tonite' or 'tonight queen', is a screenshot of a one-sided iMessage conversation showing three attempts to make plans over several days. The sender's messages, which go unanswered, convey a sense of desperation or being overly eager. The meme is used to humorously depict relentless and unreciprocated attempts to get someone's attention, often with a romantic or social connotation.

Math-ladyConfused-lady.name: Math-ladyConfused-lady

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region typically presents the initial confusing statement, question, or scenario. This is the setup that causes the "Math Lady's" perplexed reaction, prompting her to try and reconcile the information.

The text in this top region usually presents a second, often contradictory or equally confusing piece of information. It works with the bottom text to create a scenario that requires complex mental gymnastics to understand, amplifying the humor of the woman's confused expression.

Math-ladyConfused-lady.image_description: This meme, known as "Math Lady" or "Confused Lady," features actress Renata Sorrah from the Brazilian telenovela "Senhora do Destino" looking perplexed. The image is a four-panel collage of her face with mathematical equations overlaid, visually representing intense mental calculation or confusion. It is widely used to humorously depict someone trying to understand a complex, contradictory, or nonsensical situation.

Brain-Before-Sleep.name: Brain-Before-Sleep

text_options.description: This speech bubble is in the first panel, coming from the person trying to sleep. It typically contains text establishing the context, such as "Me trying to sleep," setting up the initial state of calm before the brain's interruption.

Located in the third panel, this is the speech bubble for the brain and contains the meme's punchline. This text represents the intrusive, embarrassing, or silly thought that prevents the person from sleeping, such as a cringey memory or a pointless question.

This speech bubble, also from the brain in the third panel, acts as a setup for the punchline. It usually contains a simple phrase like "Hey" or "Psst" to get the sleeper's attention before delivering the disruptive thought in the bubble below it.

Brain-Before-Sleep.image_description: The "Brain Awake" or "Brain, Let Me Sleep" meme is a four-panel comic illustrating the frustrating experience of being kept awake by one's own thoughts. The first two panels depict a person trying to sleep peacefully. The third panel introduces their personified brain, wide-eyed and ready to interrupt, leading to the final panel where the person is now wide awake and distressed by the intrusive thought, making it a relatable format for sharing anxieties or embarrassing memories.

Afraid-To-Ask-Andy.name: Afraid-To-Ask-Andy

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme: '...and at this point I'm too afraid to ask.' This completes the thought started in the top text, expressing the user's social anxiety about revealing their ignorance.

The top text box typically starts the phrase, 'I don't know what [subject] is...'. The user inserts a specific topic, trend, or concept they are unfamiliar with into this section, setting up the premise of the meme.

Afraid-To-Ask-Andy.image_description: This meme features a still of Andy Dwyer, played by Chris Pratt, from the TV show 'Parks and Recreation'. Andy has a concerned and confused expression, looking slightly off-camera. The meme, known as 'Afraid to Ask Andy', is used to humorously express ignorance about a popular topic, trend, or piece of common knowledge that one feels they should already know. The format conveys the social awkwardness of being too embarrassed to admit a lack of understanding after a certain point.

I-Should-Buy-A-Boat-Cat.name: I-Should-Buy-A-Boat-Cat

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the image, this text represents the cat's sudden, out-of-context realization or thought. The classic line is 'I should buy a boat,' but it can be replaced with any non-sequitur or aspirational phrase that humorously contrasts with the cat's serious demeanor. This is the punchline of the meme.

Positioned at the top, this text box often provides the setup or context that triggers the cat's thought. It might describe a situation, a headline the cat is reading, or a preceding event. This text sets the stage for the punchline that appears in the bottom caption (box 0).

I-Should-Buy-A-Boat-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as the 'I Should Buy a Boat' Cat or 'Sophisticated Cat,' features a cat in a suit sitting at a table with a newspaper, looking thoughtfully into the distance. The image captures a moment of sudden, often random or profound, realization. It's typically used to express an unexpected urge or decision that comes to mind while engaged in a mundane activity, highlighting the humorous contrast between the sophisticated setting and the arbitrary thought.
I-Should-Buy-A-Boat-Cat.display_name: I Should Buy A Boat Cat

Uncle-Sam.name: Uncle-Sam

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, typically used for the punchline or the specific action the viewer is being commanded to take. It completes the phrase started in the top text, and its position below Uncle Sam's pointing finger reinforces that the demand is directed at the reader.

This is the top text area, which usually contains the setup or the beginning of the phrase, often starting with "I WANT YOU" or a variation. It establishes the direct address and authoritative tone of the meme.

Uncle-Sam.image_description: This meme features the iconic image of Uncle Sam from a US Army recruitment poster, where he points directly at the viewer with a stern and commanding expression. Originally captioned "I WANT YOU FOR U.S. ARMY," the image is a popular macro format used to make a direct demand, request, or call to action. The meme's humor or message comes from replacing the original text with a new, often mundane or absurd, command, leveraging the poster's authoritative tone.

Oprah-You-Get-A-Car-Everybody-Gets-A-Car.name: Oprah-You-Get-A-Car-Everybody-Gets-A-Car

text_options.description: This is the punchline panel, where Oprah has her arms wide open in a gesture of grand giving. The text here reveals what everyone is getting, often with the phrase "Everybody gets a [item]!" or a similar all-encompassing statement, completing the joke.

Placed over a shot of Oprah pointing directly at the audience, this text box often identifies a third recipient or acts as a bridge with text like "And YOU get a...". It builds anticipation for the final punchline.
This box is over another audience member. The text here identifies a second person or group, continuing the pattern of Oprah giving things away individually before the grand finale.
This text box is placed over an audience member Oprah is pointing to. It typically labels the first person or group to receive the "gift," setting up the repetitive and generous nature of the meme.

Oprah-You-Get-A-Car-Everybody-Gets-A-Car.image_description: This meme, known as "Oprah's 'You Get a Car'", features four panels of Oprah Winfrey from a famous 2004 episode of her show where she gave cars to her entire audience. The format is used to humorously or generously "give" something (an object, a label, a feeling) to various groups or individuals. The escalating excitement in the panels builds up to a final, grand reveal where everyone receives the item in question.
Oprah-You-Get-A-Car-Everybody-Gets-A-Car.display_name: Oprah You Get A Car Everybody Gets A Car

Steve-Buscemi-Fellow-Kids.name: Steve-Buscemi-Fellow-Kids

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline, which is often the direct quote "How do you do, fellow kids?" or a similarly out-of-touch phrase. This text represents the cringeworthy and failed attempt by the subject to connect with the group they are trying to fit in with.

The top text box is used to set up the context of the meme. It usually identifies the person, group, or company that is making the awkward attempt to seem cool or relatable, framing them as the Steve Buscemi character in the scenario.

Steve-Buscemi-Fellow-Kids.image_description: This meme, known as "How Do You Do, Fellow Kids," features actor Steve Buscemi from a scene in the TV show *30 Rock*. In the scene, he is comically disguised as a high school student, complete with a backward cap and skateboard. The image is used to mock people, brands, or institutions that are transparently and awkwardly trying to appeal to a younger demographic or a subculture they don't understand.

Grumpy-Cat.name: Grumpy-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, located in area 0, delivers the punchline from the cat's grumpy perspective. It's a cynical or negative response that subverts the positive setup from the top text, creating the meme's signature pessimistic humor.

The top text, placed in area 1, sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes a situation, event, or statement that is generally considered happy, fun, or positive, which will then be contradicted by the punchline.

Grumpy-Cat.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Tardar Sauce, the cat famously known as 'Grumpy Cat.' Her permanently frowning expression, a result of feline dwarfism, became an internet sensation. The meme is used to express cynicism, annoyance, or a negative perspective on a subject that is usually considered positive or enjoyable, creating humor through its pessimistic punchlines.

Empty-Stonks.name: Empty-Stonks

text_options.description: This box is where the punchline of the meme, the word 'Stonks,' is typically placed. 'Stonks' is a deliberate and iconic misspelling of 'stocks,' which encapsulates the meme's humor by representing a flawed or silly understanding of financial markets. Its position over the upward-trending arrow ironically celebrates the questionable financial decision described at the top.

The top portion of the image is used to describe a scenario or action, setting up the punchline. This text usually details a poor, illogical, or comically simple financial decision. For example, 'When you sell a stock for a $1 profit' or 'When you buy a game on sale that you'll never play.'

Empty-Stonks.image_description: This meme, known as 'Stonks,' features the surreal 3D character Meme Man in a business suit, standing confidently with his arms crossed before a rising stock chart. The meme is used to humorously or ironically comment on financial decisions, particularly those that are questionable, absurd, or nonsensical yet somehow result in a perceived gain. The overall tone is satirical, mocking financial speculation and amateur investors.

Drake-NoYes.name: Drake-NoYes

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Drake smiling and pointing in approval. The text here represents the preferred, superior, or desired option in the comparison.
This text box is placed next to the image of Drake holding up his hand in rejection. The text here represents the disliked, inferior, or rejected option.

Drake-NoYes.image_description: This is the "Drakeposting" or "Drake Hotline Bling" meme format, which originates from stills of the rapper Drake in his 2015 music video for "Hotline Bling." The two-panel image shows Drake looking displeased and rejecting something in the top frame, while looking pleased and approvingly pointing at something in the bottom frame. This popular format is used to express a strong preference for one thing (the approved item in the bottom panel) over another (the rejected item in the top panel).

Brace-Yourselves-X-is-Coming.name: Brace-Yourselves-X-is-Coming

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It describes the action or task that 'one does not simply' do, completing the phrase from the top text. For example, 'walk into Mordor'.
The top text of the meme, which typically contains the setup phrase 'One does not simply...'. This establishes the well-known phrasal template of the meme.

Brace-Yourselves-X-is-Coming.image_description: This meme features the character Ned Stark, played by Sean Bean, from the TV series 'Game of Thrones'. The image is used for the 'One Does Not Simply' meme format, which humorously points out the difficulty or complexity of a certain action. The character's serious and foreboding expression is juxtaposed with a statement about a task that is presented as surprisingly challenging.

hello-human-resources.name: hello-human-resources

text_options.description: This speech bubble is for the man in the 'INAPPROPRIATE' panel. The text here is typically identical to the text in the top panel (box 1) to create the punchline. It represents an action or statement that is perceived negatively, highlighting the double standard at the core of the meme.

This speech bubble is for the handsome man in the 'APPROPRIATE' panel. The text placed here is a statement or action that is received positively by his female colleague. This sets up the 'successful' or 'acceptable' version of the event.

hello-human-resources.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as 'Know The Work Rules' or 'Appropriate vs. Inappropriate,' illustrates a social double standard based on physical attractiveness. The top panel, labeled 'APPROPRIATE,' shows a handsome man in a suit saying something to a female colleague, who reacts positively. The bottom panel, 'INAPPROPRIATE,' depicts a less conventionally attractive man saying the exact same thing, which causes the colleague to call Human Resources in alarm. The meme is used to satirize situations where an action is judged not on its own merit, but on the appearance of the person performing it.

5-black-guys-and-blonde.name: 5-black-guys-and-blonde

text_options.description: This label is placed on the woman, Piper Perri. Text here identifies the singular, often vulnerable or outmatched subject of the meme's scenario. This is the entity that is about to be confronted or overwhelmed by the larger group.

This label is placed over the five men standing behind the couch. Text here represents the overwhelming, numerous, or powerful force that is about to act upon the single subject. This group embodies the challenge, problem, or impending doom in the meme's setup.

5-black-guys-and-blonde.image_description: This meme, known as "Piper Perri Surrounded" or "5 Black Guys 1 White Girl," originates from an adult film. It features a petite blonde woman, Piper Perri, sitting on a white couch while five tall, muscular Black men stand behind her. The stark visual contrast in size and number is used to humorously represent a situation where a single, often outmatched entity is about to be overwhelmed by multiple, more powerful forces. The meme is versatile, applied to scenarios ranging from personal struggles to global events.

First-World-Problems.name: First-World-Problems

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which often serves as a punchline or a continuation of the trivial problem. It can also be a simple hashtag like "#FirstWorldProblems" to explicitly label the complaint, reinforcing the meme's theme.

The top text, which describes a minor, trivial inconvenience or complaint that would only be considered a problem in a wealthy, developed nation. This text sets up the joke by presenting a non-issue as a source of great distress, contrasting with the woman's pained expression.

First-World-Problems.image_description: This meme, known as "First World Problems" or "Crying Woman," features a stock photo of a woman crying with her hand on her forehead in a pose of distress. The meme is used to satirize trivial complaints and frustrations experienced by people in privileged, developed countries. The humor arises from the dramatic, overly emotional reaction depicted in the image being paired with a minor, insignificant problem, highlighting the absurdity of the complaint.

Hold-fart.name: Hold-fart

text_options.description: The text here identifies the person or group who is experiencing the intense struggle. This label acts as the subject of the meme, setting up who is trying to hold something back.

The text in this area, typically placed on the whiteboard, describes the urge, opinion, or action that the subject (labeled in box 0) is desperately trying to suppress. This provides the context for the internal conflict and is the punchline of the meme.

Hold-fart.image_description: This meme, known as "Straining Guy" or "Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl," features a male student in a classroom looking extremely strained, with veins bulging on his forehead and neck. The image humorously depicts an intense internal struggle to suppress an overwhelming urge, thought, or comment. It's widely used to represent the immense effort required to refrain from doing or saying something, often in a social context where it would be inappropriate.

Cant-prove-it.name: Cant-prove-it

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, representing the sudden and unexpected person or event that shatters the false sense of security. It often contains the character's famous catchphrase, "Surprise, motherfucker," or a variation of it, symbolizing the abrupt confrontation.

This top text box sets up a scenario of false security or ignorance. It typically describes a person or entity that believes they are safe, hidden, or have successfully gotten away with something, creating the context for the surprise.

Cant-prove-it.image_description: This meme features Sergeant James Doakes from the TV series Dexter, staring intently while sitting at a bar. Known as the "Surprise, Motherfucker" meme, it's used to represent a sudden, shocking, and often unwelcome appearance or realization. The format typically sets up a scenario where someone feels safe or oblivious, only to be confronted by an unexpected reality represented by Doakes.

death-knocking-at-the-door.name: death-knocking-at-the-door

text_options.description: This door is labeled with the next target or victim in the sequence. As the Grim Reaper is actively knocking on it, this text serves as the punchline, representing what is currently under threat or about to be metaphorically "killed" or ended by the trend.

This door represents the most recent victim in the sequence, the one just before the current target. It's the last step in the pattern before the punchline, showing the immediate predecessor to the subject on door 0.

This door is labeled with an earlier victim in the chronological sequence. It helps to establish the pattern of destruction or elimination that the Grim Reaper represents, showing that the event at door 1 was not an isolated incident.

This door, being the furthest down the bloody hall, represents the first victim or the starting point of the destructive trend. The text here sets up the historical context and the beginning of the pattern that the meme is illustrating.

death-knocking-at-the-door.image_description: This meme, known as "Grim Reaper Knocking on Doors," depicts the personification of Death having just "killed" the occupants of three rooms, evidenced by a trail of blood. The Grim Reaper is now knocking on a fourth door, ready to claim his next victim. The meme is used to illustrate a destructive force, trend, or entity sequentially eliminating or ending a series of related people, concepts, or things.

Surprised-Koala.name: Surprised-Koala

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the punchline or the shocking piece of information. This text is what causes the 'surprised' reaction depicted by the koala, creating a humorous contrast with the setup text at the top.

The top text of the meme, which sets up a scenario or presents a statement. This text is typically mundane or seemingly innocent, designed to lead into the unexpected or shocking punchline at the bottom.

Surprised-Koala.image_description: The 'Surprised Koala' meme features a close-up photo of a koala with wide, shocked eyes, seemingly caught off guard while eating a eucalyptus leaf. This image is a popular reaction macro used to convey feelings of shock, disbelief, or being utterly flabbergasted by a preceding statement or revelation. The format typically involves a top and bottom text, where the koala's expression serves as the punchline to an unexpected or outrageous claim.

If-those-kids-could-read-theyd-be-very-u.name: If-those-kids-could-read-theyd-be-very-upset

text_options.description: This area labels the group of people being targeted by the meme. They are represented by the students in the classroom who, according to the punchline, cannot read and are therefore oblivious to the insult directed at them.

This blank sign is where the meme creator places a controversial statement, a harsh truth, or an insult. The content written here is what the group labeled in box 0 would supposedly be upset about if they had the intelligence or awareness to understand it.

If-those-kids-could-read-theyd-be-very-u.image_description: This two-panel meme from the animated show "King of the Hill" features Bobby Hill pointing at a sign, followed by Principal Moss saying, "If those kids could read they'd be very upset." The format is used to present a controversial or insulting statement on the sign, which is directed at a specific group labeled over the students. The punchline implies that the targeted group is too ignorant or uneducated to understand the criticism, thus saving them from being offended.
If-those-kids-could-read-theyd-be-very-u.display_name: If those kids could read theyd be very upset

See-Nobody-Cares.name: See-Nobody-Cares

text_options.description: This area in the bottom panel contains the punchline of the meme. The text here is almost always "See? Nobody cares," which expresses the anticlimactic result of the announcement made in the top panel, highlighting the complete lack of interest from others.

This text box is placed over the top panel where Dennis Nedry is shouting. It represents the topic or person that someone is trying to expose or excitedly bring attention to, setting up the expectation that it's a big deal.

See-Nobody-Cares.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "See? Nobody Cares" or "We've Got Dodgson Here," originates from the 1993 film Jurassic Park. It features the character Dennis Nedry (in the floral shirt) loudly pointing at and calling out Lewis Dodgson at an outdoor cafe. The format contrasts Nedry's loud, attention-seeking announcement in the top panel with the subsequent lack of any reaction, encapsulated by the punchline in the bottom panel. It's used to humorously depict a situation where someone's attempt to expose, shame, or draw attention to something is met with complete indifference.

Car-Salesman-Slaps-Roof-Of-Car.name: Car-Salesman-Slaps-Roof-Of-Car

text_options.description: This text box is positioned next to the salesman's mouth and represents his sales pitch. It typically contains the main punchline of the meme, following the structure "this bad boy can fit so much [X] in it," where [X] is an absurd or relatable concept.

This text box, placed above the scene, often serves as the setup or action text for the meme. It usually contains the phrase "*slaps roof of car*," which describes the salesman's action and precedes the punchline.

Car-Salesman-Slaps-Roof-Of-Car.image_description: The "Slaps Roof of Car" meme features an illustration of a car salesman enthusiastically pitching a vehicle to a customer by patting its roof. The format is used to make humorous and often absurd claims about the capacity or function of the car, or any object that replaces it. The classic punchline follows the template, "*slaps roof of car* this bad boy can fit so much [X] in it," where [X] is the funny element.
Car-Salesman-Slaps-Roof-Of-Car.display_name: Car Salesman Slaps Roof Of Car

Doge.name: Doge

text_options.description: This area at the bottom right typically features a key phrase of the dog's internal monologue. The text here often expresses a core reaction or observation in the characteristic broken English, such as 'much confuse' or 'very scare'.

Positioned at the bottom left, this text box is another common spot for a primary phrase in the Doge meme. It helps create the scattered text effect and often contains a reaction word like 'wow' or a descriptive phrase like 'so majestic'.

Located centrally on the dog's cheek, text in this position often directly relates to the dog's expression or the central theme of the meme. It's a focal point for a key part of the internal monologue, like 'such concern'.

This text box in the upper right corner is typically used for a secondary or supporting phrase. Its placement contributes to the meme's signature chaotic and multi-faceted internal monologue, adding another layer to the dog's thoughts.

Placed on the dog's forehead, this area is a prominent spot for a short, impactful exclamation. It often contains one of the classic Doge prefixes like 'wow,' 'so,' or 'many,' setting the tone for the rest of the meme's text.

Doge.image_description: This is the iconic "Doge" meme, featuring a Shiba Inu named Kabosu with a quizzical, side-eye expression. The meme is characterized by scattered, colorful Comic Sans text representing the dog's internal monologue in broken English. Phrases typically start with modifiers like "so," "such," "many," and "wow" to convey a sense of awe, confusion, or excitement, making it a versatile reaction image.

A-second-plane-has-just-hit.name: A-second-plane-has-just-hit

text_options.description: This text box is placed over George W. Bush, who is receiving the news. This label identifies the person or entity who is about to be unpleasantly surprised or affected by the information, often representing the user ('me') reacting to some revelation.
This text box is placed over Andrew Card, the person delivering the news. This label represents the messenger or the source of the shocking or absurd information that is being whispered.

A-second-plane-has-just-hit.image_description: This meme features a famous photograph of White House Chief of Staff Andrew Card whispering into President George W. Bush's ear, informing him of the September 11th attacks. Bush's somber and serious reaction is central to the format. The meme is used to humorously depict the delivery of shocking, absurd, or mundane news in a dramatic fashion, contrasting the gravity of the original moment with trivial content.
A-second-plane-has-just-hit.display_name: A second plane has just hit

Second-Breakfast.name: Second-Breakfast

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains two labels, one for each character, to create the punchline. The text on the left aligns with Merry's serious expression, representing the concerned or expert party, while the text on the right aligns with Pippin's happy expression, representing the naive or beginner party.

The top text box sets up the context or scenario that both characters are reacting to. This text describes the situation that highlights the humorous contrast between Merry's concern and Pippin's blissful ignorance.

Second-Breakfast.image_description: This meme features the hobbits Merry and Pippin from "The Lord of the Rings" with contrasting expressions. Merry (left) looks concerned and serious, while Pippin (right) has a cheerful, oblivious smile. The format is used to contrast two different perspectives on the same situation, typically representing a knowledgeable or experienced person's worry versus a naive or ignorant person's blissful optimism.

Horse-Drawing.name: Horse-Drawing

text_options.description: This text box covers the poorly drawn front half of the horse. Text placed here represents the final, disappointing, or low-effort outcome of a process. It serves as the punchline, contrasting sharply with the initial high quality established by the other half of the image.

This text box is placed over the realistically drawn back half of the horse. Text here typically describes the beginning of a project, the first part of a series, or any initial state that is high-quality, well-made, or promising. It sets up the expectation of quality that will be subverted by the other half of the meme.

Horse-Drawing.image_description: This meme, often called the "Two-Part Horse Drawing" or "Horse Drawing Meme," depicts a horse that is drawn in two drastically different styles. The back half of the horse is a detailed, realistic, and well-executed artistic rendering, while the front half is a simplistic, childlike stick-figure drawing with a smiley face. The meme is used to humorously illustrate a significant decline in quality, effort, or complexity over time. It represents projects, series, or situations that start strong and promising but end poorly or with a noticeable lack of care.

Pepperidge-Farm-Remembers.name: Pepperidge-Farm-Remembers

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the punchline, representing the simpler, old-fashioned solution or perspective. It typically starts with a phrase like "Back in my day..." or "We just..." to contrast with the modern problem described above, delivered from the perspective of the nostalgic character.

The top text box is used to set up the joke by describing a complex, annoying, or absurd modern-day problem, trend, or situation. This text establishes the context that the character is reacting to with exasperation.

Pepperidge-Farm-Remembers.image_description: This meme features Carter Pewterschmidt from the animated show "Family Guy" dressed in old-fashioned attire, driving a horse-drawn buggy with a weary expression. The image is used to create a contrast between a modern, often frustrating situation and a simpler, idealized past. This format, often called "Back In My Day," humorously critiques contemporary issues by presenting an old-fashioned, straightforward alternative.

Guy-recording-a-fight.name: Guy-recording-a-fight

text_options.description: This label is placed on the person being pinned to the ground. It represents the victim, the losing side of an argument, or an entity that is suffering or being negatively affected by the actions of entity '1'.
This label is on the person in the dominant position in the fight. It represents the aggressor, the cause of a problem, or the force that is overpowering or harming the entity labeled '0'.

This label is on the person in the background filming the fight. It represents an indifferent bystander, a third party that benefits from the conflict, or an unhelpful entity that simply watches a problem unfold without taking action.

Guy-recording-a-fight.image_description: This meme, often called 'Girl Fight' or 'Bystander Filming Fight,' shows one person (1) physically dominating another (0) on a grassy area. In the background, a third person (2) lies on the grass and calmly records the altercation on their phone instead of intervening. The format is an object-labeling meme used to illustrate a conflict where one entity is harming another, while a third party remains indifferent, complicit, or even benefits from the situation.

dave-chappelle.name: dave-chappelle

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, specifying the object of the intense craving. It replaces the original line's subject ('crack rocks') with whatever the meme creator desires, humorously equating their want to an addict's need.

The top text box sets up the context for the meme, often starting with the phrase "Y'all got any more of that..." or describing a situation that has led to the intense desire. This text serves as the lead-in to the punchline placed in the bottom box.

dave-chappelle.image_description: This meme, known as "Y'all Got Any More of That" or "Dave Chappelle Crackhead," features comedian Dave Chappelle as his character Tyrone Biggums from 'Chappelle's Show.' The image shows the character, an addict, scratching his neck with a desperate, fiending expression. The meme is used to humorously express an intense craving or addiction to something, replacing the original subject of drugs with more mundane or relatable things like TV shows, food, or video games.

Doof-If-I-had-a-Nickel.name: Doof-If-I-had-a-Nickel

text_options.description: This is the customizable part of the meme. The user inserts a description of a very specific and unusual event that has happened to them or that they have observed exactly twice.

This area contains the image of Dr. Doofenshmirtz, which provides the visual context and reaction for the quote below. No text is typically added here; the image itself serves as the setup for the punchline in the text.

Doof-If-I-had-a-Nickel.image_description: A screenshot from the animated show 'Phineas and Ferb' featuring the character Dr. Doofenshmirtz. He looks surprised while explaining a strange coincidence, a scene which has become a popular meme format. The meme is used to express surprise that a very specific and unlikely event has happened twice, using the quote 'If I had a nickel for every time [X], I'd have two nickels. Which isn't a lot but it's weird that it happened twice.'
Doof-If-I-had-a-Nickel.display_name: Doof If I had a Nickel

Unsettled-Tom.name: Unsettled-Tom

text_options.description: This bottom text box delivers the punchline or the unsettling detail. This text reveals a piece of information that makes the initial situation described above deeply disturbing or confusing, directly causing Tom's concerned reaction.
This top text box sets up an ordinary or innocent situation. It's the first part of a two-part narrative that establishes a sense of normalcy before the twist is revealed below.

Unsettled-Tom.image_description: This meme, known as "Unsettled Tom" or "Concerned Tom," features a close-up of Tom the cat from the cartoon "Tom and Jerry." His wide-eyed, furrowed-brow expression conveys a sense of dawning horror, suspicion, or deep concern. The meme is typically used to react to a situation that seems normal at first but becomes disturbing or questionable upon realizing a specific, unsettling detail.

the-office-handshake.name: the-office-handshake

text_options.description: Text over Michael Scott represents the person, group, or entity that is naively entering into a bad deal or being exploited. This character is often portrayed as enthusiastic but clueless about the negative consequences of the agreement they are making.

Text over Ed Truck represents the person, company, or concept that is benefiting from the unfair agreement. This character is the exploiter, knowingly taking advantage of the other party's ignorance or desperation.

the-office-handshake.image_description: This meme, known as "Michael Scott's Handshake," originates from the TV show "The Office." It features a young, awkward-looking Michael Scott (right) with a mullet and fanny pack shaking hands with his former boss, Ed Truck (left). The meme is used to represent a lopsided agreement where one party (Michael) is naively being taken advantage of by a more powerful or cunning party (Ed), symbolizing an unfair deal or exchange.

High-five-drown.name: High-five-drown

text_options.description: This label is placed on the high-fiving hands in the third panel. The text here represents the unhelpful, superficial, or counterproductive action that is given instead of real help. It's the punchline of the meme, highlighting the absurdity of the gesture.
This label is on the hand reaching down from above. This hand represents the person, group, or entity offering the useless "help" or superficial support. It is the source of the misguided action.
This label is on the hand of the drowning person. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is in distress and in need of genuine help. This sets up the initial problem or crisis.

High-five-drown.image_description: This four-panel comic, known as the "Drowning High Five" meme, illustrates a person struggling to stay afloat in water. Another person's hand appears, not to save them, but to give them a high five, after which the drowning person sinks. The meme is used to criticize situations where someone in need of help receives a superficial, unhelpful, or even detrimental response instead of genuine assistance. It satirizes performative gestures, bad advice, or actions that worsen a problem.

You-know-Im-something-of-a--myself.name: You-know-Im-something-of-a--myself

text_options.description: This text box replaces the original word "scientist" from the quote. Users insert a noun, profession, or identity here to complete the punchline, comically overstating their qualifications based on the context provided in the top caption.
This is a standard top caption area. Text placed here typically describes a situation or action that prompts the speaker's exaggerated claim in the image below, setting up the joke for the punchline.

You-know-Im-something-of-a--myself.image_description: This meme, known as "I'm Something of a Scientist Myself," features actor Willem Dafoe as Norman Osborn in the 2002 film "Spider-Man." In the scene, he awkwardly tries to relate to Peter Parker by claiming to be a scientist. The meme format is used to humorously claim expertise or membership in a group based on minimal or superficial qualifications, with the character's smug expression adding to the comedic irony.
You-know-Im-something-of-a--myself.display_name: You know Im something of a  myself

Laughing-Men-In-Suits.name: Laughing-Men-In-Suits

text_options.description: The bottom text, often starting with "And then I said...", delivers the punchline. This text represents the cynical, self-serving, or out-of-touch statement made by the powerful group that elicits their laughter, directly mocking the idea presented in the top text.

The top text serves as the setup for the joke. It typically presents a statement, question, or belief from the perspective of the general public or a less powerful group, often highlighting a societal problem or a naive hope.

Laughing-Men-In-Suits.image_description: This meme, known as "And Then I Said" or "Laughing Politicians," features a photograph of Ronald Reagan and other men in suits laughing boisterously at a party. The image is used to satirize and critique powerful, wealthy, or political figures. The format typically involves adding a two-part caption that frames their laughter as a cynical and mocking response to the concerns or naivety of ordinary people.

drowning-kid--skeleton.name: drowning-kid--skeleton

text_options.description: Placed on the skeleton at the bottom of the pool. This text identifies something that has been completely forgotten, neglected for a very long time, or is considered dead and irrelevant. It serves as the ultimate punchline, representing the final consequence of the neglect shown in the top panel.

Placed over the woman and the happy girl she is holding. This area is labeled with the entity giving attention and the entity receiving it, often as a single concept. They represent the current focus or priority, blissfully unaware of or ignoring the other struggling elements.

Positioned above the happy girl and woman. This label typically represents the favored person, task, or concept that is receiving all the positive attention and resources, often at the expense of others.

Positioned over the struggling, drowning girl in the foreground. This text identifies the person, task, or problem that is being actively ignored or neglected, despite being in immediate need of attention. It represents a current, pressing issue that is being overlooked.

drowning-kid--skeleton.image_description: A two-panel meme format illustrating different levels of neglect. The top panel shows a woman in a pool happily holding up one girl while another girl struggles to stay afloat nearby. The bottom panel shows a skeleton sitting in a chair at the bottom of the pool. This meme is used to compare three things: one that receives all the attention (happy girl), one that is currently being neglected (drowning girl), and one that has been forgotten for so long it's 'dead' (the skeleton).

Teachers-Copy.name: Teachers-Copy

text_options.description: This text box is positioned above the 'uncanny' or disturbed Mr. Incredible. It typically contains a shocking, dark, or horrifying fact or realization that directly contrasts with the text in the other panel. This is the punchline that reveals the disturbing truth, causing the character's transformation.

This text box is placed above the normal, smiling Mr. Incredible. It usually contains an innocent, positive, or seemingly harmless statement or belief. This sets up the initial, pleasant context before the disturbing revelation in the second panel.

Teachers-Copy.image_description: This meme, known as 'Mr. Incredible Becoming Uncanny,' features a two-panel comparison of the character Mr. Incredible from Pixar's 'The Incredibles.' On the left, he appears in his normal, smiling form, while on the right, he is shown as a heavily shadowed, black-and-white, and deeply unsettling version of himself. The format is used to contrast a pleasant, naive, or surface-level understanding of a situation with a much darker, more disturbing reality, representing a descent from blissful ignorance to horrifying realization.

Gentlemen-it-is-with-great-pleasure-to-i.name: Gentlemen-it-is-with-great-pleasure-to-inform-you-that

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or the main announcement. This is the piece of information that the meme creator wants to formally declare, which is often something humorous, mundane, or the classic phrase 'it is Wednesday my dudes'.

The top text box contains the setup phrase, typically 'Gentlemen, it is with great pleasure to inform you that'. This text establishes the formal and celebratory tone of the announcement that follows below.

Gentlemen-it-is-with-great-pleasure-to-i.image_description: This meme features an illustration of a distinguished-looking toad in a 19th-century suit, often referred to as the 'Wednesday Frog'. The format is used to make a formal, often mundane or silly announcement with an air of great importance. Its most common use is to declare 'it is Wednesday my dudes,' a self-referential nod to another popular frog meme.
Gentlemen-it-is-with-great-pleasure-to-i.display_name: Gentlemen it is with great pleasure to inform you that

Simpsons-so-far.name: Simpsons-so-far

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Homer and Bart in the bottom panel. It contains Homer's punchline, which is a seemingly comforting but ultimately demoralizing statement that reframes Bart's failure in a much worse light. A classic example is, 'This is the worst day of your life so far.'

Located in the top panel over a sad-looking Bart, this text describes the initial bad situation, failure, or disappointment that the user is experiencing. It sets up the context for Homer's misguided advice in the panel below.

Simpsons-so-far.image_description: This two-panel meme from 'The Simpsons' features Bart looking dejected in the top panel and his father, Homer, consoling him in the bottom panel. The format, known as 'The worst day of your life so far,' is used to present a bad situation, followed by Homer's flawed attempt at encouragement which ironically makes things worse. It highlights situations where an attempt to offer perspective backfires comically.

Too-Damn-High.name: Too-Damn-High

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always the phrase 'IS TOO DAMN HIGH.' It completes the statement from the top text, delivering the humorous and emphatic complaint that defines this meme format.
This top text area introduces the subject of the complaint. It sets up the punchline by naming a person, object, or concept whose price, number, or level is considered excessive.

Too-Damn-High.image_description: This image macro features Jimmy McMillan, a political activist, in a meme format known as 'The Rent Is Too Damn High.' The meme uses his passionate expression and gesture to humorously complain about the excessive cost or quantity of something. The setup is presented at the top, with the punchline 'IS TOO DAMN HIGH' at the bottom, mimicking McMillan's famous political platform.

Cute-Cat.name: Cute-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme. This caption usually delivers the punchline or the specific, often sad, consequence of the situation described in the top text. It's the core reason for the kitten's sorrowful expression.
The top text of the meme, which serves as the setup. This caption typically describes a situation, action, or statement that leads to the kitten's sad or pleading reaction.

Cute-Cat.image_description: This meme features a small, orange tabby kitten standing on its hind legs with large, dark, pleading eyes, giving it a very sad or innocent appearance. Often referred to as 'Sad Kitten' or 'Pleading Kitten,' the image is used as a reaction to express feelings of sadness, guilt, or to make a desperate, often humorously exaggerated, request. The format typically involves top and bottom captions to create a relatable scenario that evokes sympathy.

Yes-Honey.name: Yes-Honey

text_options.description: This text box is positioned under the sad, withered Wojak. It contains the number '0', which in a binary context represents 'false', 'off', or a negative/failed state. This label is used for the undesirable or losing side of the comparison presented in the meme.

This text box is located under the female Wojak character. It contains the number '1', which in a binary context represents 'true', 'on', or a positive/successful state. This label is assigned to the desirable or winning side of the comparison.

Yes-Honey.image_description: This meme features two Wojak characters side-by-side for comparison. On the left is the "Tradwife" or "Wojak Girl," looking calm and composed, and on the right is a sad, withered Wojak, looking defeated. The format contrasts two opposing ideas, outcomes, or groups. In this specific variant, the numbers "1" and "0" are used to represent a binary opposition, such as success vs. failure, true vs. false, or on vs. off.

Peter-Griffin-skin-color-chart-race-terr.name: Peter-Griffin-skin-color-chart-race-terrorist-blank

text_options.description: This text box labels the lower, less appealing color swatch. It is used to represent the inferior, undesirable, or negative subject in the comparison.
This text box covers the upper, more appealing color swatch. It is used for the superior, desirable, or positive subject being compared against the one below.

Peter-Griffin-skin-color-chart-race-terr.image_description: This meme, known as "Peter Griffin's Color Chart," originates from the animated show 'Family Guy.' It depicts Peter Griffin looking at a color palette, which is used to compare two contrasting concepts or items. The format typically presents the top option as superior or desirable, while the bottom option is framed as inferior or undesirable, with Peter's neutral expression adding to the comedic effect of the judgment being passed.
Peter-Griffin-skin-color-chart-race-terr.display_name: Peter Griffin skin color chart race terrorist blank

Smiling-Cat.name: Smiling-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text area, which often serves as the punchline or the internal thought of the subject. This text typically describes the polite but awkward reaction or behavior in response to the situation set up by the top text.
The top text area, used to establish the context of an uncomfortable or awkward social scenario. This text sets the stage for the cat's strained, "polite" expression.

Smiling-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Polite Cat" or "He Looks Very Polite," features a close-up selfie of a tabby and white cat with wide, dilated pupils and an awkward, forced smile. The cat's expression is the central element, perfectly capturing a feeling of social anxiety or discomfort while trying to maintain a composed and friendly demeanor. This image is widely used to represent situations where someone feels out of place but is trying their best to be polite and fit in.

Red-pill-blue-pill.name: Red-pill-blue-pill

text_options.description: This text box is associated with the blue pill, representing the choice of blissful ignorance or the status quo. The text here describes the 'easy' option, which allows someone to remain in their current, comfortable state without facing a difficult truth.

This text box corresponds to the red pill, symbolizing the choice to accept a difficult or challenging truth. The text in this area presents the 'hard' option, which leads to enlightenment or a new, often uncomfortable, understanding of reality.

Red-pill-blue-pill.image_description: This meme originates from a pivotal scene in the 1999 film "The Matrix," where the character Morpheus offers the protagonist a choice between a red pill and a blue pill. The red pill represents embracing a potentially harsh or life-changing truth, while the blue pill represents remaining in a state of blissful ignorance. This format is widely used to present a dilemma between two starkly contrasting options, often a difficult reality versus a comfortable illusion.

Cat-looks-inside.name: Cat-looks-inside

text_options.description: This is the final and most impactful line of the highlighted text. It typically contains the punchline or the most bizarre, awkward, or cringeworthy comment that prompts the cat's silent, judgmental stare.
This is the middle line of the conversation, often serving as a build-up or a direct reply that leads to the final, awkward comment in the line below (index 0).
This is the top line of the highlighted text, which usually sets the initial context or starts the exchange that will escalate into the awkward situation highlighted by the meme.

Cat-looks-inside.image_description: This meme features a close-up, wide-angle photo of a cat with large, staring eyes, often referred to as the "Staring Cat" or "Awkward Look Cat." The image is typically placed below a screenshot of an online conversation, often from Discord, with specific messages highlighted. The cat's intense and slightly judgmental gaze serves as a reaction to a strange, cringeworthy, or unexpected comment made in the conversation above, conveying a sense of silent, awkward scrutiny.

Friendship-ended-with-X-now-Y-is-my-best.name: Friendship-ended-with-X-now-Y-is-my-best-friend

text_options.description: This box is placed over the person on the left, who represents the protagonist or the creator of the meme (originally Asif Raza Rana). This is the person who is publicly declaring a change in their relationships or allegiances.

This box is placed over the person on the right, who represents the "new best friend" (originally Salman). This character is the one being newly embraced, replacing the "old friend" who is mentioned in the text but is not pictured.

Friendship-ended-with-X-now-Y-is-my-best.image_description: The "Friendship Ended with Mudasir" meme originates from a 2015 Facebook post by Asif Raza Rana, who dramatically announced he was no longer friends with Mudasir and that Salman was now his best friend. The image features Asif shaking hands with his new friend, Salman, with overlaid, colorful text declaring the change. This format is widely used to humorously and dramatically express a shift in loyalty or preference for anything, from products to ideologies.
Friendship-ended-with-X-now-Y-is-my-best.display_name: Friendship ended with X now Y is my best friend

Pointing-mirror-guy.name: Pointing-mirror-guy

text_options.description: This label is placed on the man's pointing arm. Text here typically represents the person making the vow or accusation, setting up the context of self-confrontation.

This label is placed over the heads of the man and his reflection. Text in this area usually describes the specific habit, action, or goal that is the subject of the confrontation, acting as the punchline or the core issue being addressed.

Pointing-mirror-guy.image_description: This meme, known as 'Man Pointing at Mirror' or 'Bro, Not Cool,' depicts a cartoon man pointing at his own serious, blue-hued reflection. The image captures a moment of intense self-confrontation or making a solemn promise to oneself. It's typically used to humorously illustrate someone vowing to change a bad habit, confronting their own flaws, or making a personal resolution.

Homer-Simpsons-Back-Fat.name: Homer-Simpsons-Back-Fat

text_options.description: This text, placed over the bottom panel, reveals the disappointing or messy reality behind the facade. It serves as the punchline, explaining the true, less appealing situation that corresponds to the visual of Homer's back fat being held by a clip.

This text, placed over the top panel, describes an idealized, impressive, or desirable situation. It sets up the joke by presenting a polished or appealing facade, which is then subverted by the bottom panel.

Homer-Simpsons-Back-Fat.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as "Homer's Back Fat," features Homer Simpson from the animated series The Simpsons. In the top panel, Homer appears fit and trim, while in the bottom panel, it's revealed his apparent fitness is a facade created by a clip holding his back fat in place. The meme is used to humorously contrast an appealing or impressive public image (top) with the less glamorous or deceptive reality (bottom), representing an "expectation vs. reality" scenario.

Put-It-Somewhere-Else-Patrick.name: Put-It-Somewhere-Else-Patrick

text_options.description: This text label is placed over the bottom panel where Patrick is grabbing something with a determined look. This area represents the preferred, accepted, or superior idea or object that the user is embracing.
This text label is placed over the top panel where Patrick is pushing something away with a look of disgust. This area represents the rejected, undesirable, or foolish idea or object.

Put-It-Somewhere-Else-Patrick.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Push It Somewhere Else Patrick," features the character Patrick Star from SpongeBob SquarePants. In the top panel, Patrick looks panicked and is pushing something away, while in the bottom panel, he has a determined expression and is grabbing something. The meme is used to contrast an undesirable idea or action (top) with a much more desirable or clever alternative (bottom), effectively showing a preference for one thing over another.

Creepy-Condescending-Wonka.name: Creepy-Condescending-Wonka

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below Wonka's face, delivers the sarcastic or condescending punchline. It directly follows the setup from the top text, often starting with phrases like 'Please, tell me more about...' to mock the subject's perceived naivete or lack of expertise.

The top text serves as the setup for the meme's punchline. It typically poses a question or states an observation that feigns interest or curiosity in something someone has said or done, setting a patronizing tone.

Creepy-Condescending-Wonka.image_description: This meme, known as 'Condescending Wonka' or 'Creepy Wonka,' features actor Gene Wilder as Willy Wonka from the 1971 film 'Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory.' The image captures Wonka with a patronizing, smug smile, leaning his head on his hand as if listening intently. This meme is used to express sarcasm or condescension by feigning interest in someone's statement before delivering a dismissive or mocking punchline.

For-the-better-right-blank.name: For-the-better-right-blank

text_options.description: This box is placed on Padmé's concerned face in the final panel. It represents her silent, shocked reaction to Anakin's dark statement. The text here is often ellipses ('...') or the panel is left blank to emphasize her stunned silence, which serves as the punchline's landing.

This box is on Padmé's smiling face in the second panel. It contains her optimistic and unsuspecting response to Anakin's initial comment. The canonical text is, 'For the better, right?', which sets up the subsequent dark reveal perfectly.

This box is on Anakin's face in the first panel, where he has a slight smile. The text here is the setup for the joke – a seemingly positive or neutral statement that will be twisted in the next panel. For example, 'I'm going to change the world.'

For-the-better-right-blank.image_description: A four-panel meme from Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones, featuring Anakin Skywalker and Padmé Amidala, also known as the 'For the Better, Right?' meme. The format depicts a conversation where Anakin makes an innocent-sounding statement, Padmé responds with cheerful optimism, Anakin follows up with a sinister or absurd clarification, and Padmé is left in stunned silence. This meme is used to create humor through an unexpected dark twist in a seemingly normal conversation.

My-body-is-machine.name: My-body-is-machine

text_options.description: This text box is the punchline of the meme, representing the 'output' of the body's conversion process. It typically contains something humorous, self-deprecating, or undesirable, such as 'anxiety,' 'diarrhea,' or 'regret,' subverting the expectation set by the powerful image.

This text box represents the 'input' that the body 'machine' processes. It usually contains a noun or phrase for something consumed or experienced, like 'caffeine,' 'stress,' or 'a full night's sleep,' setting up the punchline.

My-body-is-machine.image_description: This meme, known as 'My Body Is A Machine', features a skeleton lifting a heavy barbell. The image is used as a phrasal template that reads, 'My body is a machine that turns [input] into [output].' The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the powerful, hardcore image with a self-deprecating or absurd punchline about what the user's body actually produces or converts.

Mr-incredible-mad.name: Mr-incredible-mad

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the specific, infuriating example or punchline that causes Mr. Incredible's rage. It follows the general statement made in the top box, providing the frustrating context.

The top text box is used for a broad, emphatic statement that sets up the meme's premise. This is often a phrase like "MATH IS MATH!" or "CLEANING IS CLEANING!", which serves as the title for the frustrating scenario described below.

Mr-incredible-mad.image_description: This meme shows the character Mr. Incredible from the movie "The Incredibles 2" in a fit of rage, slamming his fist on a table and shouting. The image is a popular reaction format used to express extreme frustration, anger, or disbelief towards a particular subject. It is famously used with captions like "MATH IS MATH!" or "A GAME IS A GAME!" to emphasize that while a statement might be technically true, the reality of the situation is infuriating.

Disappointed-Man.name: Disappointed-Man

text_options.description: The text placed here, over the man's torso and hands-on-hips pose, typically identifies the person or entity causing the disappointment or being judged. This label establishes the subject of the meme's scenario.

The text in this upper region, often placed over the man's face, describes the disappointing action, event, or outcome. This serves as the punchline, explaining the reason for his iconic expression of frustration.

Disappointed-Man.image_description: This meme, known as 'Disappointed Cricket Fan' or 'Angry Pakistani Fan,' features Sarim Akhtar, a cricket fan reacting with visible disappointment during a match. His hands-on-hips pose and deadpan, frustrated expression have become a universal symbol for expressing disapproval, frustration, or resignation. The meme is widely used to comment on letdowns in various contexts, from sports and politics to everyday personal failures.

Spider-Man-Double.name: Spider-Man-Double

text_options.description: A text label placed over the Spider-Man on the right. This text identifies one of the two identical or similar subjects being compared or accused in the meme.
A text label placed over the Spider-Man on the left. This text identifies the second of the two identical or similar subjects, mirroring the first to create the humorous comparison or accusation.

Spider-Man-Double.image_description: This meme, known as 'Spider-Man Pointing at Spider-Man,' originates from the 1967 animated series. It depicts two identical Spider-Men pointing at each other, creating a visual representation of a standoff or mutual accusation. The format is widely used to humorously call out hypocrisy, highlight uncanny similarities between two different things, or represent situations where two parties blame each other for the same issue.

Overwatch-Mercy-Meme.name: Overwatch-Mercy-Meme

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the heroic image of Mercy. It typically contains the name of a person, group, or concept that acts as a powerful savior, providing a solution or aid to the problem described in the top panel.
This text box is placed over the image of the sad young girl. The text here describes a problem, a person or group in a state of distress, or a negative situation that requires help or a solution.

Overwatch-Mercy-Meme.image_description: A two-panel meme format from the video game Overwatch. The top panel shows a sad, vulnerable-looking young girl in a dimly lit, rubble-strewn environment. The bottom panel features the angelic healer character, Mercy, descending heroically in a blaze of golden light. This meme is used to contrast a problem, a person in need, or a state of suffering (top) with its powerful, often overwhelming solution or savior (bottom).

Dinkleberg.name: Dinkleberg

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It almost invariably reads '...IF I HAD ONE!', which completes the thought started in the top text and reveals the source of the character's frustration—the lack of the desired object or achievement.
The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a desirable item, achievement, or person that the user wishes they had, often phrased as 'This is where I'd put my [X]...'

Dinkleberg.image_description: This meme features Mr. Turner from the animated show 'The Fairly OddParents' with an angry and frustrated expression. Known as the 'This Is Where I'd Put My Trophy... If I Had One!' meme, it's used to express disappointment or longing for something one doesn't possess. The format sets up a desirable situation or item, only to reveal its absence with a punchline, creating a relatable and humorous complaint.

Illusion-of-free-choice.name: Illusion-of-free-choice

text_options.description: This label is placed on the lower of the two initial paths. It represents one of two seemingly distinct choices or options presented to the subject.
This label is placed on the upper of the two initial paths. It represents the second, alternative choice that appears to be different from the first option.

This label is on the single, merged path at the end. It represents the inevitable, singular outcome that both of the initial choices lead to, serving as the punchline that reveals the 'illusion' of choice.

Illusion-of-free-choice.image_description: This meme, known as "The Illusion of Free Choice," features a line drawing of a cow facing two separate paths that quickly merge into a single path. The image humorously critiques situations where seemingly different options or choices all lead to the same inevitable outcome. It is widely used to satirize political systems, consumer choices, or any scenario where agency is presented but is ultimately non-existent, highlighting a predetermined result.

Get-In-Loser.name: Get-In-Loser

text_options.description: This text box, typically placed at the bottom of the image, contains the punchline of the meme. It modifies the original quote from the movie, usually following the format "Get in loser, we're going [activity/place]" to create a humorous call to action.

This text box at the top of the image provides context or identifies the speaker. It sets up the joke by labeling the group in the car (e.g., "My last two brain cells"), which gives meaning to the modified quote in the bottom text box.

Get-In-Loser.image_description: This image is a popular meme template from the 2004 teen comedy film "Mean Girls." It features the character Regina George (played by Rachel McAdams), the leader of the popular clique "The Plastics," driving her convertible with her friends Gretchen Wieners and Karen Smith. The meme is based on Regina's iconic line, "Get in loser, we're going shopping," and is used to humorously and assertively invite someone to join an activity or adopt a certain viewpoint. The format typically involves replacing "shopping" with a different destination or action relevant to the meme's context.

Why-Cant-You-Just-Be-Normal.name: Why-Cant-You-Just-Be-Normal

text_options.description: This label is placed on the screaming child, Samuel. Text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is behaving in a chaotic, strange, or non-conforming manner, directly defying the plea for normalcy from the top panel.

This label is placed on the exasperated mother, Amelia. Text here typically identifies the person, group, or societal expectation that is demanding normal or predictable behavior from the subject in the bottom panel.

Why-Cant-You-Just-Be-Normal.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the 2014 horror film "The Babadook." It features a mother, Amelia, yelling in frustration at her son, Samuel, who is screaming wildly in the back seat of a car. The meme is used to represent a dynamic where one entity (the mother) pleads for another (the son) to behave in a conventional or expected way, while the other entity responds with chaotic, strange, or non-conforming behavior. It humorously highlights the clash between expectations of normalcy and a reality that is anything but.
Why-Cant-You-Just-Be-Normal.display_name: Why Cant You Just Be Normal

Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Red.name: Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Red

text_options.description: This is the bottom and main part of the phrase, typically starting with 'AND' followed by a verb or command. This section delivers the punchline or the specific instruction, replacing the original 'CARRY ON' with a humorous or customized action.
This is the top line of the phrase, which almost always reads 'KEEP CALM'. It establishes the familiar, stoic tone of the original poster, setting up the second part of the phrase.

Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Red.image_description: This meme is a template based on the iconic British "Keep Calm and Carry On" propaganda poster from World War II. It features a solid red background with a white Tudor Crown at the top. The format is widely parodied online, with users replacing the original text to create humorous, motivational, or situational slogans following the phrasal template "Keep Calm and [Action]".
Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Red.display_name: Keep Calm And Carry On Red

Incoming-call.name: Incoming-call

text_options.description: This area contains the two opposing choices: the red "Decline" button and the green "Accept" button. These options represent the binary decision at the core of the meme's conflict, forcing a choice for or against the concept presented as the caller.

This text area at the top of the screen replaces the caller's name or number. It introduces the central subject of the meme—an idea, a person, a temptation, or a responsibility—that the user must decide whether to engage with.

Incoming-call.image_description: This meme uses the recognizable user interface of an iPhone's incoming call screen to represent a metaphorical choice. The "caller" is replaced by a concept, person, or situation, forcing the viewer to consider whether they would "Accept" or "Decline" it. The format is versatile, often used to humorously depict internal conflicts, difficult decisions, or strong aversions to certain ideas or responsibilities.

Shut-Up-And-Take-My-Money-Fry.name: Shut-Up-And-Take-My-Money-Fry

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline, almost invariably reading 'SHUT UP AND TAKE MY MONEY!'. This phrase captures the meme's essence of being so impressed that one wants to buy something instantly, without any further sales pitch.
The top text describes a product, service, or idea that is highly desirable or innovative. This sets up the context for Fry's enthusiastic reaction.

Shut-Up-And-Take-My-Money-Fry.image_description: This meme features Philip J. Fry from the animated series Futurama, aggressively holding out a wad of cash with a determined expression. The image is from an episode where he is desperate to buy a new phone. Known as the 'Shut Up and Take My Money!' meme, it's used to express an overwhelming and immediate desire to purchase a product or support an idea, often before all the details are even known.
Shut-Up-And-Take-My-Money-Fry.display_name: Shut Up And Take My Money Fry

Jason-Momoa-Henry-Cavill-Meme.name: Jason-Momoa-Henry-Cavill-Meme

text_options.description: This label is placed on Jason Momoa, who represents the sneaky, disruptive, or unexpected element. Text here typically names a problem, a distraction, or a smaller entity that is about to surprise or undermine the larger, more composed subject in the foreground.

This label is placed on Henry Cavill, who represents the unsuspecting, composed, or stable entity. Text here usually describes a person, a plan, or a situation that is proceeding normally, completely unaware of the impending disruption represented by Jason Momoa.

Jason-Momoa-Henry-Cavill-Meme.image_description: This meme, known as 'Jason Momoa Sneaking Up On Henry Cavill,' features actor Jason Momoa playfully creeping up behind an unsuspecting Henry Cavill at a red carpet event. The format is used to represent an unexpected or disruptive force (Momoa) about to ambush a composed, unaware target (Cavill). It humorously illustrates situations like impending problems, temptations, or sudden events catching someone off guard.

Ben-affleck-smoking.name: Ben-affleck-smoking

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image is typically left empty. The meme's power comes from the visual of Ben Affleck's exhaustion, which usually serves as a reaction to a situation described elsewhere, making additional text in this location unnecessary.

The white space at the top is the primary location for a caption. This text describes a situation, event, or thought that causes the profound exhaustion and exasperation seen in Ben Affleck's expression. It sets up the joke, with Affleck's image serving as the punchline that represents the relatable feeling of being completely drained.

Ben-affleck-smoking.image_description: This meme features a paparazzi photo of actor Ben Affleck looking weary and stressed while smoking a cigarette. Known as "Sad Affleck" or "Tired Ben Affleck," the image has become a popular reaction image. It's used to express feelings of extreme exhaustion, burnout, disappointment, or being completely overwhelmed by life's challenges, making his unfiltered fatigue highly relatable.

I-See-Dead-People.name: I-See-Dead-People

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a parody of the original line. The text here names a group of people, objects, or a concept that the meme creator sees everywhere, playing on the boy's horrified expression to create humor.

This top text box serves as the setup for the punchline below. It often contains a question like "What do you see?" or a statement that establishes a context, leading into the reveal in the bottom text.

I-See-Dead-People.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Cole Sear, the terrified young boy from the 1999 film 'The Sixth Sense'. In the iconic scene, he whispers the line, "I see dead people." The meme format uses this image to express the overwhelming or ubiquitous presence of something, often comically or frustratingly, by replacing the original quote's subject.

Ol-Reliable.name: Ol-Reliable

text_options.description: This text, placed inside the glowing, open case, represents the 'Ol' Reliable' solution itself. It's the dependable, trusted, and often simple answer or tool used to resolve the problem described in the top panel, serving as the punchline.

This text, positioned over SpongeBob's worried face in the top panel, describes a challenging situation, a problem, or a predicament. It sets the context, establishing the need for a reliable solution.

Ol-Reliable.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Ol' Reliable," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants. In the top panel, SpongeBob has a worried expression while holding a closed case labeled "OL' RELIABLE." In the bottom panel, he opens the case, which emits a heavenly glow, and he looks relieved. This format is used to represent a go-to, dependable solution, person, or object that someone turns to when facing a difficult or specific situation.

Fernanfloo-Dresses-Up.name: Fernanfloo-Dresses-Up

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the "after" image of the man in a suit. The text here represents the superior, improved, or more sophisticated outcome or entity in the comparison. It serves as the punchline, highlighting the positive transformation from the state depicted on the left.

This text box is placed over the "before" image of the man in casual clothes. The text here typically describes the initial, less desirable, or chaotic state. It sets up the contrast for the improved version shown on the right.

Fernanfloo-Dresses-Up.image_description: This is a two-panel "glow up" or transformation meme, often featuring YouTuber elZeein. The left panel shows him dressed casually in pajamas in a messy room, representing a less desirable or chaotic state. The right panel shows him looking sharp and successful in a suit in a clean apartment, representing a positive transformation or superior outcome. The meme is used to contrast a "before" and "after," or to compare a simple/chaotic version of something with a sophisticated/improved one.

Philosoraptor.name: Philosoraptor

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which typically completes the philosophical question or paradoxical statement started in the top text. It often serves as the punchline, revealing the core of the conundrum or the humorous twist.
The top text of the meme, which introduces the premise or the first part of a philosophical question or a shower thought. It sets the stage for the punchline that follows at the bottom.

Philosoraptor.image_description: This is the "Philosoraptor" meme, an advice animal image macro featuring a Velociraptor in a thoughtful pose with its claw to its chin. The meme is used to pose paradoxical, humorous, or profound philosophical questions and shower thoughts. The raptor's contemplative expression paired with the often-absurd questions creates a comedic effect.

They-hated-jesus-because-he-told-them-th.name: They-hated-jesus-because-he-told-them-the-truth
