text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme: "They hated Jesus because He told them the truth." This phrase is almost always kept intact and serves to frame the user's preceding statement as a rejected truth, creating a humorous or dramatic effect.

This area is where the user inserts their own text, representing the "truth" that is being rejected by the angry crowd. This text is typically a controversial, unpopular, or mundane opinion presented as a profound revelation.

They-hated-jesus-because-he-told-them-th.image_description: This meme, known as "They Hated Jesus Because He Told Them the Truth," originates from a Christian comic book. It depicts an angry crowd shouting "Shut up!" at an unseen speaker. The meme is used to present an unpopular opinion or a "hard to swallow pill," with the user framing their statement as a profound truth that others reject out of ignorance or denial.
They-hated-jesus-because-he-told-them-th.display_name: They hated jesus because he told them the truth

But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business.name: But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline and the name of the meme: "But that's none of my business." This phrase is used to feign indifference and disengage from the provocative statement made above, adding a layer of passive-aggression to the joke.

The top text box is for the setup of the meme. It typically contains a critical, judgmental, or observational statement about a person, group, or situation, often pointing out hypocrisy or a flaw. This is the "tea" or gossip that Kermit is metaphorically spilling.

But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business.image_description: This meme, known as "But That's None of My Business," features the famous Muppet character Kermit the Frog sipping a glass of Lipton tea. The image is used to make a passive-aggressive or sarcastic comment about a person or situation. Kermit's calm, tea-sipping posture contrasts with the often shady or critical observation being made, implying a feigned indifference to the drama he's just instigated.
But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business.display_name: But Thats None Of My Business

Hard-To-Swallow-Pills.name: Hard-To-Swallow-Pills

text_options.description: This text is placed directly on the pills. It represents the core, inconvenient truth or unpopular opinion that the meme is conveying, which is the literal "pill" that is "hard to swallow."

This text is placed on the palm of the hand, above the pills. It often serves as a secondary statement, a category, or a setup for the main punchline on the pills (index 0), providing additional context or another related "hard truth."

Hard-To-Swallow-Pills.image_description: The "Hard to Swallow Pills" meme is a two-panel exploitable image macro used to present an uncomfortable or unpopular truth. The top panel shows an illustration of a hand holding a pill bottle with the label "Hard to swallow pills," which sets up the premise. The bottom panel shows pills in a hand, where the "hard truth" is written, metaphorically representing a fact that is difficult for people to accept or "swallow."

Wake-Up-Babe.name: Wake-Up-Babe

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the sleeping woman. It typically represents her supposed thoughts or what she imagines her partner is thinking, often something like, "He's probably thinking about other women." This text serves as the setup for the joke, establishing an expectation of relationship-focused thoughts.

This text box is placed above the man, representing his actual thoughts. This is the punchline, revealing a completely unrelated and often trivial or nerdy subject, such as video games, historical facts, or a silly hypothetical question. The contrast between his mundane thoughts and the romantic setting creates the humor.

Wake-Up-Babe.image_description: This meme, often called "He's Probably Thinking About Other Women," uses a stock photo of a man looking at his sleeping partner in bed. The format creates a humorous contrast between the seemingly romantic and intimate moment and the man's actual thoughts. The humor comes from subverting the expectation that he is thinking about their relationship, revealing instead a mundane, absurd, or nerdy internal monologue.

Milk-carton.name: Milk-carton

text_options.description: This area is for contact information, following the prompt 'If found, contact'. In the meme, this is often a humorous or fictional contact related to the subject in the image box, completing the parody of a real missing person ad.

This large blank square is the central focus of the meme, where an image of the 'missing' person, character, or object is placed. The choice of image is the main punchline, defining who or what is being humorously reported as lost or absent.

Milk-carton.image_description: The 'Missing on a Milk Carton' meme features a milk carton with a 'MISSING' notice, referencing a 1980s campaign to find missing children. This format is used as an exploitable template where an image of a person or object is placed in the designated square. The meme humorously points out someone's or something's absence, poor performance, or disappearance from a particular context.

fat-man-drinking-from-pipe.name: fat-man-drinking-from-pipe

text_options.description: This label is placed on the large, gluttonous figure. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is receiving an excessive amount of a resource, often undeservedly. This character represents the beneficiary of the unequal distribution.

This label is on the small, emaciated figure. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is being neglected or receiving only a tiny fraction of the resource. This character highlights the victim of the inequality.

This label is placed on the pipe, which is the source. The text here describes the resource being distributed, such as "praise," "government funding," "attention from the media," or any other commodity that is being shared unequally.

fat-man-drinking-from-pipe.image_description: This meme is a cartoon illustrating extreme inequality, often called "Two Guys on a Bus" or "Guy Drinking from a Firehose." It depicts a large, gluttonous character drinking a massive stream of water from a pipe, while a small, emaciated character below struggles to catch a few leaking drops. The meme is used to represent situations where one entity receives an overwhelming abundance of resources, attention, or praise, while another, often more deserving or in greater need, receives almost nothing.

Inside-you-there-are-two-wolves.name: Inside-you-there-are-two-wolves

text_options.description: This bottom panel is the primary location for the meme's punchline. The text here defines the two "wolves" or describes the outcome of their internal battle in a humorous or unexpected way, subverting the serious tone established by the image and the top text.

This area, positioned over the two wolves, is often used to add labels to each wolf. These labels specify the two conflicting ideas or desires (e.g., one wolf is 'ambition,' the other is 'procrastination'), setting up the specific context for the punchline.

Inside-you-there-are-two-wolves.image_description: A black-and-white image depicts a black wolf and a white wolf facing off in front of a full moon, under the text "INSIDE YOU THERE ARE TWO WOLVES." This meme format is based on a parable about internal conflict, but it's used humorously to represent any two opposing desires, thoughts, or traits. The punchline typically subverts the serious tone by presenting a mundane, absurd, or relatable conflict.
Inside-you-there-are-two-wolves.display_name: Inside you there are two wolves

Bilbo---Why-shouldnt-I-keep-it.name: Bilbo---Why-shouldnt-I-keep-it

text_options.description: Located on the bottom panel where Bilbo is frowning, this text describes the negative, disappointing, or rejected idea. It serves as the punchline, contrasting with the positive statement above and conveying strong disapproval.

Positioned on the top panel where Bilbo has a neutral-to-positive expression, this text typically represents a positive, appealing, or preferred concept or situation. It sets up the initial, more favorable part of the comparison.

Bilbo---Why-shouldnt-I-keep-it.image_description: This two-panel meme format features the character Bilbo Baggins from 'The Lord of the Rings'. The top image shows him with a gentle, slightly pleased expression, while the bottom image shows him with a sudden, pronounced frown of disapproval or disgust. The meme is used to contrast something positive, appealing, or expected (top) with a negative, disappointing, or rejected alternative (bottom), functioning similarly to a preference or reaction meme.
Bilbo---Why-shouldnt-I-keep-it.display_name: Bilbo   Why shouldnt I keep it

Crying-cat.name: Crying-cat

text_options.description: The bottom text caption, often serving as the punchline. This area typically contains the disappointing outcome, a sad internal thought, or an onomatopoeia for crying (e.g., '*cries*'), directly corresponding to the cat's sorrowful expression.

The top text caption, which sets up the premise of the meme. This text usually describes a situation, an expectation, or a statement that leads to the feeling of sadness or disappointment depicted by the cat.

Crying-cat.image_description: This meme, known as 'Crying Cat' or 'Schmuserkadser,' features a white cat with photoshopped, large, teary eyes, creating a comically sorrowful expression. The cat appears to be on the verge of tears, looking directly at the viewer with a pained look. This image is used to represent an exaggerated or melodramatic reaction of sadness, disappointment, or being emotionally overwhelmed, often in response to a minor inconvenience or a relatable sad situation.

Victoria-David-Beckham-Be-Honest.name: Victoria-David-Beckham-Be-Honest

text_options.description: Text here represents David Beckham's initial reaction or a label for him as he listens to the claim being made. This space can contain his internal thoughts or simply identify him as the person who knows the truth.
This box contains the initial statement or claim made by the person represented by Victoria Beckham. It's the setup for the joke, presenting a statement that is about to be challenged.

Text in this box is David Beckham's interjection or challenge. In the original clip, this is where he says 'Be honest!'. In meme variations, it's a prompt or a direct question challenging the statement from the previous panel.
This box shows Victoria Beckham continuing her claim, often doubling down or elaborating on the initial statement. This builds the comedic tension before the final reveal.
This is the punchline from David Beckham. The text here reveals the truth or the fact that directly contradicts the claims made by Victoria, exposing the lie or exaggeration.
This box captures Victoria Beckham's reaction to being called out. The text here often represents a flustered response, a weak defense, or a reluctant admission of the truth after being exposed.

Victoria-David-Beckham-Be-Honest.image_description: This meme features a three-panel comic strip of Victoria Beckham being interviewed while her husband, David Beckham, peeks from behind a door. Originating from the Netflix documentary 'Beckham,' it's used to humorously depict a situation where someone makes a questionable or exaggerated claim, and another person who knows the truth is about to expose them. Victoria represents the person making the claim, while David represents the fact-checker ready to interject with the truth.

Simba-Shadowy-Place.name: Simba-Shadowy-Place

text_options.description: This label is placed on Mufasa, who represents the authority figure or the established norm. The text here typically identifies the mainstream group or perspective that is about to explain why the 'shadowy place' should be avoided.

This label is placed over the vast, sunlit Pride Lands that Mufasa presents to Simba. The text here represents the 'good,' acceptable, or mainstream topic/group, setting up the contrast for Simba's question about the 'shadowy place' in the next panel.

Simba-Shadowy-Place.image_description: This three-panel meme originates from Disney's "The Lion King," featuring Mufasa and his son, Simba. In the scene, Simba asks his father, "But what's that shadowy place over there?" This format is used to contrast a mainstream or acceptable group/idea (the sunlit kingdom) with a forbidden, undesirable, or niche one (the shadowy place), which is often the subject of the punchline.

Marked-Safe-From-Big.name: Marked-Safe-From-Big

text_options.description: This text, which defaults to 'Today,' specifies the timeframe of the 'safety.' While often left as is, it can be edited to add context or another layer to the joke, such as 'this meeting' or 'this family gathering,' enhancing the satirical tone.

This is the core punchline of the meme. Users insert text describing a trivial, annoying, or undesirable event they are humorously glad to have avoided, treating it with the mock seriousness of a major catastrophe.

Marked-Safe-From-Big.image_description: This meme, known as 'Marked Safe From,' is a parody of Facebook's Safety Check feature. The original feature is used for serious situations like natural disasters, but the meme subverts this by allowing users to humorously declare themselves safe from trivial, annoying, or mundane events. The template consists of the phrase 'Marked Safe From' followed by a blank space for the user to fill in the 'danger' they've avoided, often concluding with 'Today'.

And-Just-Like-That.name: And-Just-Like-That

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the main punchline or statement of the meme. This text represents the simple, profound, or sometimes silly thought that Forrest is supposedly having, which gives context to his pensive expression.

The top text box is often used for setup or context, though it's frequently left blank. When used, it might introduce a scenario like "When you realize..." or "My brain at 3 AM:", setting the stage for the main thought presented in the bottom text.

And-Just-Like-That.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Tom Hanks as the character Forrest Gump from the 1994 film of the same name. He is sitting on a park bench with a serious and contemplative expression, looking slightly off-camera. The meme is typically used to express a simple yet profound realization, a "shower thought," or a naive question, playing on the character's earnest and simple-minded nature.

Jarvis.name: Jarvis

text_options.description: This lower section contains the punchline of the meme. The text here represents the user's internal, often inappropriate or smug, thought or reaction to the situation described above. Its placement over Tony Stark's smirk perfectly visualizes the mischievous or calculated nature of the thought.

The text in this upper section sets up the premise or context for the meme. It usually describes a situation, an action, or a quote from another person that prompts the reaction shown below. This is the setup that the punchline in the lower half responds to.

Jarvis.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Tony Stark from the Marvel movie Iron Man, as seen from inside his helmet's Heads-Up Display (HUD). Stark has a distinct, smug smirk, which is central to the meme's meaning. The format is typically used as a reaction image to convey a person's internal, often mischievous, inappropriate, or devious thoughts in response to a given situation. The high-tech overlay adds to the feeling of a calculated or processed internal monologue.

Traumatized-Mr-Incredible.name: Traumatized-Mr-Incredible

text_options.description: This text box is placed under the dark, uncanny version of Mr. Incredible. It typically contains a disturbing, negative, or shocking fact that contrasts with the statement on the left. This text serves as the punchline or the unsettling revelation that justifies the character's horrified expression.

This text box is located under the normal, smiling Mr. Incredible. The text here usually describes a seemingly positive, innocent, or normal situation. It acts as the setup for the meme, establishing a baseline of pleasantness before the disturbing contrast is introduced.

Traumatized-Mr-Incredible.image_description: This is the "Mr. Incredible Becoming Uncanny" meme, featuring two contrasting images of the character Mr. Incredible from Pixar's "The Incredibles." The left panel shows a normal, smiling Mr. Incredible, representing a positive or naive viewpoint. The right panel displays a dark, distorted, and unsettling version of him, representing a disturbing realization or a negative counterpart. This format is used to compare two related scenarios, where one is innocent and the other is deeply unsettling.

Spongebob-Yelling.name: Spongebob-Yelling

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically labels the person, group, or entity that is experiencing the intense struggle against temptation. It represents the subject of the meme who is desperately trying to maintain self-control.

The text in this upper region describes the object of desire, the tempting thought, or the urge that the subject (labeled in box 0) is fighting against. Its placement above SpongeBob's head signifies the overwhelming nature of the temptation he is trying to resist.

Spongebob-Yelling.image_description: This meme, known as "I Don't Need It" or "Struggling SpongeBob," originates from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants. It features SpongeBob looking extremely strained, with bloodshot eyes and his brain exposed, as he screams in a crowd. The image is used to humorously depict an intense internal struggle to resist a powerful temptation or urge, often for something trivial or relatable.

Stupid-dumb-drooling-puzzle.name: Stupid-dumb-drooling-puzzle

text_options.description: This area typically labels the crying Brainlet character. The text identifies the person, group, or entity being ridiculed for their perceived lack of intelligence or for making a foolish argument.

This top caption area sets the context for the meme. It usually contains the flawed statement, illogical idea, or frustrating situation that the Brainlet character is failing to comprehend or deal with, causing their distress.

Stupid-dumb-drooling-puzzle.image_description: This meme, often called "Square Peg, Round Hole" or "Brainlet Crying," features a crudely drawn Wojak-style character crying in frustration while trying to force a square block into a triangular hole of a shape-sorting toy. The character, known as a "Brainlet," is used to represent someone perceived as unintelligent or making a profoundly illogical argument. The meme is a reaction image used to mock a person or idea for failing to grasp a simple concept, portraying their flawed reasoning as a futile and pathetic struggle.

Yhorm-Dark-Souls.name: Yhorm-Dark-Souls

text_options.description: This label is placed on the small knight, representing the underdog, the challenger, or the user. This text typically identifies a person, group, or simple idea that is bravely but perhaps foolishly taking on a massive challenge.

This label is placed on the giant knight, representing the overwhelmingly powerful opponent or obstacle. This text identifies a large corporation, a difficult life problem, a complex academic subject, or any formidable force that the smaller entity is up against.

Yhorm-Dark-Souls.image_description: This meme format originates from artwork for the video game Dark Souls III, depicting the player character (Ashen One) facing the colossal boss, Yhorm the Giant. The dramatic size difference creates a classic David vs. Goliath dynamic. It's used to represent a small, often outmatched individual or entity confronting a much larger, more powerful, or complex opponent, problem, or institution.

Ill-Just-Wait-Here.name: Ill-Just-Wait-Here

text_options.description: This text is placed over the image of the skeleton. It typically repeats the text from the top panel or provides a punchline that emphasizes the immense passage of time, reinforcing the joke that the person has been waiting so long they've decayed.
This text is placed over the image of the man before he ages. It sets up the premise of the meme by describing the situation or action that initiates a long wait, such as 'Me waiting for...'.

Ill-Just-Wait-Here.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Waiting Skeleton' or 'Still Waiting,' originates from the movie 'Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade.' It depicts the character Walter Donovan before and after he rapidly ages into a skeletal figure. The format is used to humorously exaggerate the experience of waiting for an extremely long time for something to happen, such as a game release, a download to complete, or a reply to a message.

Satisfied-Seal.name: Satisfied-Seal

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the seal's mouth, serves as the punchline. It describes the satisfying outcome or the feeling of contentment that results from the setup in the top text, directly mirroring the seal's blissful expression.
The top text, placed across the seal's forehead, sets up the context or scenario. It typically describes a common situation or action that leads to a very pleasing or perfect conclusion.

Satisfied-Seal.image_description: This meme, known as the 'Satisfied Seal' or 'Sealed with a Kiss', features a close-up of a seal's face with its eyes closed in an expression of pure bliss and contentment. The image is used to represent a feeling of deep satisfaction or pleasure derived from a simple, relatable, or perfectly executed situation. The meme's humor comes from pairing this look of utter delight with mundane yet highly satisfying everyday scenarios.

batman-signal.name: batman-signal

text_options.description: This bottom area is typically used for a caption that sets up the context of the meme. It often contains a screenshot of a social media post, a quote, or a description of a scenario that includes a keyword or topic that triggers the 'summoning'.

This area covers the Bat-Signal. In the meme, the traditional bat emblem is replaced with a different symbol, logo, or text. This new symbol represents the specific subject or interest that acts as the 'signal' to summon the person (represented by Batman) who is an expert or fan of that subject.

batman-signal.image_description: This meme, known as the 'Bat-Signal' meme, features a silhouette of the superhero Batman against a night sky with his iconic signal shining. The format is used to humorously depict someone being 'summoned' or feeling an irresistible urge to appear when a topic they are passionate about is mentioned. The symbol in the Bat-Signal is typically edited to represent this specific trigger, making Batman a stand-in for any enthusiast or expert rushing to join a relevant conversation.

Dont-You-Squidward.name: Dont-You-Squidward

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or the action taken by the meme creator. This text explains the reason for SpongeBob's smug expression, often detailing a petty, sarcastic, or clever response to the situation set up in the top text.
The top text box sets up the scenario. It usually describes a situation, a question asked, or a statement made by someone else, which prompts the smug reaction.

Dont-You-Squidward.image_description: This meme, known as 'Smug SpongeBob' or 'SpongeBob's Smirk,' features the character SpongeBob SquarePants with a smug, self-satisfied expression. It's used to convey a feeling of pride or satisfaction, often in a petty, mischievous, or sarcastic context. The format typically presents a scenario or question, followed by a clever or defiant response that explains SpongeBob's smug look.

Woody-and-Buzz-Lightyear-Everywhere-Wide.name: Woody-and-Buzz-Lightyear-Everywhere-Widescreen

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, following the phrasal template 'X, X Everywhere.' This text represents Buzz Lightyear's dialogue, identifying the trend or item that has become overwhelmingly common, which is the core of the joke.

The top text box, positioned above the characters' heads, often contains a short phrase that sets the context or premise for the meme. This text establishes the situation that leads to the observation made in the bottom text, acting as a setup for the punchline.

Woody-and-Buzz-Lightyear-Everywhere-Wide.image_description: This meme format, known as "X, X Everywhere," originates from the movie Toy Story and features Buzz Lightyear enthusiastically pointing out something to a concerned Woody. Buzz's dialogue is typically modified to highlight the overwhelming prevalence of a certain trend, object, or idea. The meme humorously contrasts Buzz's confident declaration with Woody's worried expression, representing a common reaction to a sudden, inescapable phenomenon.
Woody-and-Buzz-Lightyear-Everywhere-Wide.display_name: Woody and Buzz Lightyear Everywhere Widescreen

Did-you-mean.name: Did-you-mean

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. It represents Google's 'correction' or suggestion, offering a humorous or satirical alternative to the original search term in the box above. The text here reframes the initial concept in a witty or critical way.

This is the Google search bar where the setup for the joke is placed. The text here is the initial search query, which is often a concept, a person's name, or a slightly misspelled word that the punchline will 'correct'.

Did-you-mean.image_description: This meme, known as "Did You Mean" or "Google Suggest," uses a screenshot of a Google search results page. The format creates a joke by having a user's search query be "corrected" by Google's suggestion feature, which serves as the punchline. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the initial search term with a witty, satirical, or cynical alternative, implying that Google is revealing a hidden truth.

i-dont-always.name: i-dont-always

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the punchline. It typically starts with 'But when I do, I...' followed by an exaggerated, superior, or humorous statement that contrasts with the setup in the top text, completing the 'I don't always X, but when I do, Y' format.

The top text of the meme, which serves as the setup. It usually begins with the phrase 'I don't always...' followed by a common or relatable activity, establishing the first part of the two-part joke.

i-dont-always.image_description: This meme features 'The Most Interesting Man in the World,' a character from a Dos Equis beer advertising campaign portrayed by actor Jonathan Goldsmith. The image shows a sophisticated, well-dressed man with a gray beard, looking directly at the viewer with a calm, confident expression. The meme format follows a two-part phrasal template: 'I don't always [X], but when I do, I [Y],' used to make a humorous or boastful claim about performing a common action in an exceptional way.

I-am-once-again-asking.name: I-am-once-again-asking

text_options.description: The bottom text, located here, delivers the punchline of the meme. It replaces the original phrase 'financial support' with a different, often humorous or mundane, request, creating a comedic contrast with Bernie's serious expression.
The top text, placed in this area, is the setup of the joke. It almost always reads 'I am once again asking for your' to mimic the original video's dialogue and establish the formal, pleading tone.

I-am-once-again-asking.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of US Senator Bernie Sanders from a 2019 presidential campaign fundraising video. In the original clip, he says, "I am once again asking for your financial support." The meme format uses this earnest appeal to humorously request something, often trivial or relatable, by replacing the original words with a different noun or phrase.

Gru-Gun.name: Gru-Gun

text_options.description: This bottom text area, positioned near the gun, typically contains the core demand or punchline of the meme. It's where the user states what they want from the viewer, for example, 'Hand it over' or 'Your opinion is required.' The proximity to the weapon emphasizes the humorous 'threat'.

The top text area is used to provide context or a setup for the demand made in the bottom text. It often contains a statement that justifies why Gru is pointing the gun, such as 'You've seen too much' or 'I heard you have the sauce.' This follows the classic top-text/bottom-text image macro format.

Gru-Gun.image_description: An image of Gru from the movie 'Despicable Me' pointing a handgun directly at the viewer with a neutral, slightly smug expression. This meme, often called 'Gru with a Gun,' is used as a reaction image to make a humorous demand or threat. The user is typically asking for something specific, like information, a file, or for the viewer to perform an action, using the image to add a layer of playful intimidation.

Success-Kid-Original.name: Success-Kid-Original

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the baby, serves as the punchline that reveals the successful outcome. It contrasts with the setup in the top text to create the humorous or satisfying moment of victory, perfectly matching the baby's triumphant expression. For example, if the top text is "Dropped my phone," the bottom text might be "It landed on the carpet."

The top text, placed above the baby's head, sets up a scenario that implies a potential problem, challenge, or negative expectation. This line establishes the context for the eventual success celebrated in the meme. For example, "Woke up 10 minutes before my alarm..."

Success-Kid-Original.image_description: This is the "Success Kid" meme, featuring a photo of a baby on a beach clenching a fistful of sand with a determined and satisfied expression. The image, originally of a boy named Sammy Griner, became an internet sensation representing small victories and personal triumphs. It's typically used in an image macro format to describe a situation that turned out better than expected, celebrating minor but gratifying wins in everyday life.

thanos-what-did-it-cost.name: thanos-what-did-it-cost

text_options.description: This is Thanos's response to the initial question. It's typically a simple confirmation of an achievement, such as "Yes.", setting up the second part of the dialogue.
This is the first line of dialogue, where young Gamora asks a question to initiate the exchange. The text is usually a question about whether a goal was accomplished, for example, "Did you do it?".
This is the final panel and the punchline of the meme. It contains Thanos's grave answer to the cost. The text here is almost always "Everything.", emphasizing the immense sacrifice made.
This is the second question from young Gamora, following up on Thanos's confirmation. The text is almost invariably the iconic line, "What did it cost?", which leads to the meme's punchline.

thanos-what-did-it-cost.image_description: This is a four-panel meme from the movie "Avengers: Infinity War," featuring the characters Thanos and a young Gamora. The scene depicts a somber conversation where Gamora questions Thanos about his actions. This format is used to represent a pyrrhic victory, where a goal is achieved at a great personal cost. The dialogue follows a set pattern, with Gamora asking if a task was completed and what it cost, culminating in Thanos's grave response, "Everything."

FINALLY.name: FINALLY

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It completes the phrase started in the top text, revealing the full, absurd name of the fictional invention or discovery.
The top text of the meme, which sets up the joke. This text often begins with the word "Finally," to build anticipation for the supposed groundbreaking discovery that will be revealed.

FINALLY.image_description: This meme, often called "Scientist" or "Finally," features a stock photo of a Black man in a lab coat intently examining a test tube. The format is used to humorously announce the discovery or creation of a nonsensical or absurd item, often by combining two unrelated concepts. The tone is satirical, applying the gravitas of scientific breakthrough to mundane or ridiculous ideas, typically presented as a top and bottom text caption.

Predator-Handshake.name: Predator-Handshake

text_options.description: This area, over the bicep of the arm on the right (belonging to Schwarzenegger's character), is labeled with one of the two groups or individuals. It represents the first party in the agreement.

Positioned over the clasped hands, this central text box contains the punchline. It describes the common ground, shared belief, or action that unites the two otherwise disparate entities labeled on the arms.

This area, over the bicep of the arm on the left (belonging to Weathers' character), is labeled with the second group or individual. This party is often presented as being in opposition or contrast to the first one.

Predator-Handshake.image_description: This meme, known as the 'Epic Handshake' or 'Predator Handshake,' originates from a scene in the 1987 film 'Predator' featuring Arnold Schwarzenegger and Carl Weathers. It depicts a muscular white arm and a muscular Black arm locked in a powerful handshake. The meme is used to illustrate an unexpected agreement or shared characteristic between two different, often opposing, groups or concepts.

blank-red-MAGA-hat.name: blank-red-MAGA-hat

text_options.description: This box covers the brim of the cap. In both the original MAGA hat and its meme variations, this area is typically left blank, as the focus of the meme is entirely on the slogan placed on the main panel above.

This is the main panel of the hat where the slogan is displayed. In the original hat, this reads 'MAKE AMERICA GREAT AGAIN'. In the meme format, this text is replaced with a custom phrase, often following a similar four-word structure, to create a humorous or satirical statement.

blank-red-MAGA-hat.image_description: This meme template features a red trucker-style baseball cap, famously known as the 'Make America Great Again' or MAGA hat from Donald Trump's political campaigns. The format involves photoshopping a new, often humorous or absurd, phrase onto the front of the hat, replacing the original slogan. This allows users to co-opt a politically charged symbol to make a completely different, and typically apolitical or satirical, statement.

Blank-Transparent-Square.name: Blank-Transparent-Square

text_options.description: Located in the bottom panel, this text describes the preferred, superior, or more enlightened option. It acts as the punchline, contrasting with the top panel to create a humorous comparison and show a clear preference.

Positioned in the top panel, this text describes the rejected, inferior, or less desirable option. It sets up the comparison by presenting the first element of the joke, which is then contrasted by the text in the bottom panel.

Blank-Transparent-Square.image_description: This is a minimalist, two-panel meme template consisting of two black rectangular spaces. It serves as a generic comparison format, similar to Drakeposting, where the humor comes from contrasting two ideas or choices. The top panel typically represents a less desirable or inferior option, while the bottom panel presents a superior or preferred alternative, with the joke relying entirely on the text.

Sad-guy-Happy-guy-bus.name: Sad-guy-Happy-guy-bus

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the happy passenger and the sunny landscape. It typically contains text describing a positive, optimistic, or desirable viewpoint, situation, or outcome. This side represents the 'glass half full' perspective in the meme's comparison.

This text box is placed over the sad passenger and the bleak cliff face. It usually contains text describing a negative, pessimistic, or undesirable viewpoint, situation, or outcome. This side represents the 'glass half empty' perspective, contrasting with the positive view on the other side.

Sad-guy-Happy-guy-bus.image_description: The 'Two Guys on a Bus' meme features a cartoon illustration of two men sitting on opposite sides of a bus. One man, on the right, smiles as he looks out at a bright, sunny landscape, while the other man, on the left, looks dejected as he stares at a bleak, rocky cliff face. This meme is used to represent the duality of perspective, contrasting optimistic and pessimistic viewpoints or showing two different outcomes of the same situation.

Prove-me-wrong.name: Prove-me-wrong

text_options.description: This area is the main canvas of the meme, located on the sign in front of the man. Users write a debatable statement, a controversial opinion, or a humorous hot take here. This text is the central premise that the phrase "CHANGE MY MIND" below it refers to, setting up the challenge.

This upper area is often used to add a label identifying the person or entity being challenged or who holds an opposing view. For example, it could be labeled "Society," "My Parents," or "The Internet." This provides context for who the opinion on the sign is directed at, though it is sometimes left blank.

Prove-me-wrong.image_description: This meme, known as "Steven Crowder's Change My Mind," features conservative commentator Steven Crowder sitting confidently at a table on what appears to be a college campus. He holds a mug and sits behind a sign with the fixed phrase "CHANGE MY MIND" at the bottom. The meme is used to state a controversial, unpopular, or humorous opinion on the sign, with the user challenging others to debate the point in a provocative but often lighthearted way.

Matrix-Morpheus.name: Matrix-Morpheus

text_options.description: The bottom text line, which delivers the punchline or the actual revelation. It completes the thought started in the top line, presenting a surprising, often obvious, or counter-intuitive truth.

The top text line, which serves as the setup for the meme. It almost always begins with the phrase "What if I told you," directly referencing a line Morpheus never actually says in the film but which captures the spirit of his dialogue.

Matrix-Morpheus.image_description: This is a meme template known as "What If I Told You" or "Matrix Morpheus." It features a close-up of the character Morpheus from the 1999 film The Matrix, looking serious in his signature sunglasses. The meme is used to present a profound or surprising revelation, often about a commonly held belief or everyday situation, mimicking Morpheus's role in revealing the true nature of reality in the film.

Do-all-the-things.name: Do-all-the-things

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the second half of the meme's catchphrase, typically a plural noun representing the objects of the action. It completes the snowclone "X all the Y," specifying what things are to be acted upon with the manic energy depicted by the character.
This top text box contains the first part of the meme's phrasal template, usually a verb or action phrase. It sets up the command or desire that the character is hyperbolically expressing.

Do-all-the-things.image_description: This meme, known as "X all the Y" or "All the Things," features a crudely drawn character from the webcomic "Hyperbole and a Half." The character, a representation of the author's over-enthusiastic younger self, is shown with a manic expression, waving its arms wildly against a yellow starburst background. The meme is used to express an overwhelming and often comically impossible desire to perform an action on a massive scale, following the phrasal template "[Verb] all the [plural noun]."

elmo-fire.name: elmo-fire

text_options.description: This area, placed over Elmo's body, is often left blank. When used, it labels the person or entity who is reveling in the chaos or feeling an overwhelming, destructive emotion.

Located at the top of the image, this is the main caption area. The text here describes the situation, event, or thought that triggers Elmo's chaotic and triumphant reaction, providing the context for his 'rise'.

elmo-fire.image_description: This meme, known as 'Elmo Rise' or 'Hellmo,' features the Sesame Street character Elmo raising his arms triumphantly in front of a fiery, hellish background. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the innocent children's character with a scene of chaos and destruction. It is used to represent an intense, often malevolent or chaotic, feeling of joy, power, or madness in response to a situation.

Sparta-Leonidas.name: Sparta-Leonidas

text_options.description: The bottom text, often in all caps, serves as the emphatic punchline or declaration. It's the character's powerful response to the setup in the top text, famously being "THIS IS SPARTA!" but frequently parodied with other phrases to create a humorous or dramatic statement.

The top text sets up the scenario or provides the context that prompts Leonidas's intense reaction. It's typically a quote, a question, or a description of a situation that the punchline at the bottom will vehemently oppose or respond to.

Sparta-Leonidas.image_description: This meme features King Leonidas from the 2006 film '300', yelling fiercely on a battlefield. The image captures a moment of intense defiance and is famously associated with the line "This is Sparta!". The meme is used to express a strong, often comically over-the-top, reaction to a preceding statement or situation, substituting "Sparta" with another concept for humorous effect.

Black-Girl-Wat.name: Black-Girl-Wat

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the girl's body and gesturing hand. This area is typically left blank, as the focus is on her facial expression and the caption above. The hand gesture it covers is integral to the meme's questioning and confused tone.

Located in the header space above the girl, this is the primary caption area. The text here describes the confusing, illogical, or questionable situation that is causing the girl's bewildered reaction. This setup provides the context to which her expression serves as the punchline.

Black-Girl-Wat.image_description: The 'Confused Black Girl' meme features a young girl with a bewildered and skeptical expression, gesturing with her hand as if questioning something unbelievable. Her face perfectly captures a mix of confusion, disbelief, and slight annoyance. This image is used as a reaction to express bewilderment or to challenge a nonsensical statement, effectively conveying a 'What are you talking about?' or 'Are you for real?' sentiment.

Jim-Halpert-Explains.name: Jim-Halpert-Explains

text_options.description: The text on the bottom whiteboard serves as the punchline, revealing the simple, blunt, or often cynical reality, outcome, or true motivation. Paired with Jim's smug look, this text undercuts the complexity of the top panel, creating a humorous or ironic contrast.

The text on the top whiteboard represents a complex, detailed, or seemingly well-thought-out plan, explanation, or official statement. Jim's earnest expression and pointing gesture in this panel suggest he is presenting this information seriously.

Jim-Halpert-Explains.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as "Jim Halpert Explaining" or "Jim's Whiteboard," features the character Jim Halpert from the TV show "The Office." In the top panel, Jim earnestly points to a whiteboard as if explaining a complex plan or idea. In the bottom panel, he smirks at the camera next to the same whiteboard, which now displays a much simpler, often cynical or blunt summary. The meme is used to contrast a stated intention or complicated explanation with the simple, underlying reality or true motive.

i-sleep-real-shit.name: i-sleep-real-shit

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to the "Real Shit?" panel. It contains the punchline of the meme—a concept, item, or situation that is considered superior, exciting, or highly desirable, causing the subject to become suddenly alert and intensely interested.
This text box corresponds to the "I Sleep" panel. It typically contains the setup for the joke—a mundane, conventional, or undesirable idea that the subject is indifferent or opposed to.

i-sleep-real-shit.image_description: This is a two-panel reaction meme featuring former basketball player Shaquille O'Neal, commonly known as the "I Sleep / Real Shit?" or "Sleeping Shaq" meme. The top panel shows a calm, sleeping Shaq to represent indifference or disapproval towards a certain idea. In contrast, the bottom panel features a deep-fried, distorted image of Shaq with glowing eyes, wide awake and alert, representing intense interest and approval. This format is used to compare two things, highlighting a strong preference for the second option.

Vince-McMahon-Reaction-wGlowing-Eyes.name: Vince-McMahon-Reaction-wGlowing-Eyes

text_options.description: This final text box, next to McMahon's ultimate, red-faced, glowing-eyes reaction, contains the punchline—the most absurd, desirable, or over-the-top option that trumps all others.
This text box aligns with McMahon's ecstatic, jaw-dropped reaction, and it usually describes a far superior or highly exciting alternative.
Paired with McMahon's growing interest and smile, this text box presents a better or more appealing option than the first, showing a clear upgrade.
This text box, corresponding to Vince McMahon's calm and unimpressed expression, typically contains the most basic, standard, or least desirable option in a list.

Vince-McMahon-Reaction-wGlowing-Eyes.image_description: This is a four-panel meme known as the 'Vince McMahon Reaction'. It features WWE chairman Vince McMahon with progressively more excited and exaggerated expressions, starting from unimpressed and culminating in an ecstatic, red-faced, glowing-eyed reaction. The meme is used to rank a series of items, concepts, or choices in ascending order of preference, appeal, or absurdity, with each panel representing a step up from the last.

Phoebe-Joey.name: Phoebe-Joey

text_options.description: This is Phoebe's final panel. The text here typically represents her exasperated summary or a concluding statement, often simplified in a last-ditch effort to get the point across, setting up Joey's final, incorrect response.

This is the punchline panel featuring Joey. The text here is his confident, but completely wrong, final conclusion based on his misunderstanding of Phoebe's entire explanation. His cheerful expression contrasts with the incorrectness of his statement.

This box is on the third panel of Phoebe's explanation. The text here is usually the second part of the concept she is trying to teach, breaking it down further into what should be a simple component.

This box is on the third panel for Joey. The text here represents his attempt to repeat or process the second piece of information from Phoebe, showing that his misunderstanding is growing as he looks increasingly confused.
This box is on the second panel of Phoebe's explanation. The text here is the first part of the breakdown of the main topic, where she tries to simplify the concept for Joey.

This box is on the second panel for Joey. The text here shows his initial, incorrect attempt to repeat or understand the first part of Phoebe's explanation. His expression is one of concentration and confusion.
This is the top-left panel, the setup for the meme. The text here is Phoebe introducing the complex topic or idea that she is about to explain to Joey.

This is the top-right panel, showing Joey's initial reaction. The text here is typically a simple response indicating he is ready to learn, but his confused expression foreshadows his impending failure to understand.

Phoebe-Joey.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Phoebe Teaching Joey," originates from a scene in the TV sitcom *Friends*. It depicts Phoebe Buffay (Lisa Kudrow) attempting to teach Joey Tribbiani (Matt LeBlanc) a concept, which he progressively misunderstands. The format is used to illustrate a situation where an explanation of a complex topic is met with a comically incorrect or oversimplified interpretation, highlighting a failure of communication or comprehension.

Aragorn-Black-Gate-for-Frodo.name: Aragorn-Black-Gate-for-Frodo

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the empty space between the charging Aragorn and his hesitant army. The text here represents the disappointing outcome or the group that fails to follow through, creating the anticlimactic punchline of the meme.

Positioned over Aragorn's face as he delivers his speech, this text represents an inspiring call to action, a confident plan, or a bold declaration. It serves as the setup for the joke, establishing a high-stakes or motivational premise.

Aragorn-Black-Gate-for-Frodo.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as 'For Frodo,' originates from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King.' It depicts Aragorn giving an inspiring speech to his army, followed by a shot of him charging forward while his army hesitates. The meme contrasts a motivating statement or plan (top panel) with the underwhelming or nonexistent response it receives (bottom panel), humorously highlighting failed leadership or a disconnect between expectations and reality.

Dr-Evil-Laser.name: Dr-Evil-Laser

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the word or phrase that Dr. Evil is sarcastically "quoting." This is the core of the joke, representing the concept that the meme creator finds dubious, unbelievable, or worthy of mockery.

The top text box provides the setup or context for the joke. It typically describes a situation, statement, or scenario that makes the word or phrase in the bottom text seem absurd or questionable, leading to Dr. Evil's sarcastic air quotes.

Dr-Evil-Laser.image_description: This meme features the character Dr. Evil from the Austin Powers film series, identifiable by his bald head, grey suit, and a distinctive scar near his eye. He is shown making his signature "air quotes" gesture with both hands, a comedic bit from the movies used to sarcastically emphasize a word or phrase. The meme format leverages this gesture to mock or express skepticism about a particular concept, statement, or claim, implying it's not legitimate or true.

black-guy-stopping.name: black-guy-stopping

text_options.description: Placed on the friend in the plaid shirt, this text represents a voice of reason, a better alternative, a responsibility, or a helpful influence that prevents the main subject from making a bad decision.
Over the man in the grey shirt, this text represents the subject or protagonist (often labeled "me") who is tempted or distracted by an appealing but ultimately poor choice.
This label is on the woman walking by, symbolizing the temptation, a bad habit, a fleeting desire, or an inferior option that is distracting the main subject.

black-guy-stopping.image_description: This two-panel meme, often called "Bro Not Cool" or "Distracted Boyfriend's Friend," originates from a 2017 Gillette commercial. It depicts a man being distracted by an attractive woman, only to be stopped by his friend who pulls him back to reality. The meme is used to illustrate a conflict between a tempting but poor choice and a more responsible or beneficial alternative, with the friend representing reason or duty.

Y-U-No.name: Y-U-No

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the core of the meme's question, always starting with the phrase "Y U NO," a deliberate, grammatically incorrect version of "Why don't you." This is followed by the simple, expected action that is not being performed, delivering the punchline with a tone of exasperation.

The top text box is used to identify the subject of the complaint. This is typically a single word or short phrase naming the person, entity, or object being addressed and questioned by the meme's creator (e.g., "FACEBOOK," "MATH TEACHERS," "MY BRAIN").

Y-U-No.image_description: This meme, known as "Y U NO Guy," is a classic rage comic character used to express frustration and disbelief. The image features a crudely drawn stick figure with a large, round head and a comically detailed, angry face, looking directly at the viewer with a pleading yet demanding expression. The meme's format is a direct question, humorously pointing out why a person, company, or object isn't performing an action that the creator considers simple, logical, or obvious.

I-fear-no-man.name: I-fear-no-man

text_options.description: This central blank space in the bottom panel is where an image of the feared object or concept is placed. This "thing" is the punchline, creating a comedic contrast to the Heavy's tough exterior by being something unexpectedly frightening, absurd, or seemingly harmless.

Text placed over the top panel, where the Heavy appears strong and confident. This area is typically used to label the Heavy, representing a person, group, or entity that is generally considered tough, brave, or unfazed by common challenges.

I-fear-no-man.image_description: This is a two-panel meme from the video game Team Fortress 2, featuring the character Heavy. In the top panel, the silhouetted Heavy confidently states, "I fear no man." The bottom panel shows him looking nervously at something off-screen, admitting, "But that thing... it scares me." The meme is used to humorously express a deep-seated or irrational fear of something, contrasting it with a persona of strength and fearlessness.

Always-you-three.name: Always-you-three

text_options.description: This label is placed over Harry Potter. Text here identifies the first, and often the main, member of a trio being blamed for a recurring problem.
This label is placed over Ron Weasley. Text here identifies the second member of the troublesome trio, often a close associate of the first.
This label is placed over Hermione Granger. Text here identifies the third and final member of the group that is consistently involved in the issue at hand.

Always-you-three.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from a scene in a Harry Potter film. In the top panel, Professor McGonagall looks exasperated and asks, "Why is it, when something happens, it is always you three?" The bottom panel reveals the trio in question: Hermione Granger, Ron Weasley, and Harry Potter, looking sheepish. This format is used to humorously blame a specific group of three people, concepts, or objects for a recurring problem or situation.

Pink-Guy-vs-Bane.name: Pink-Guy-vs-Bane

text_options.description: This label is placed on Pink Guy. The text here represents the weaker, sillier, or underdog element in the comparison, creating a humorous contrast with the powerful figure of Bane.
This label is placed on the muscular back of Bane. The text here represents the powerful, intimidating, or superior entity in the comparison, setting up the joke.

Pink-Guy-vs-Bane.image_description: This meme features a photoshopped image combining two distinct pop culture figures. In the foreground, the imposing villain Bane from 'The Dark Knight Rises' stands with his arms outstretched in a powerful pose. In the background, the comical internet character Pink Guy, known for his absurd antics, mirrors Bane's stance in a silly, non-threatening manner. This format is used to humorously contrast a powerful, serious, or expected entity (Bane) with a much weaker, absurd, or unexpected one (Pink Guy).

Maury-Lie-Detector.name: Maury-Lie-Detector

text_options.description: This area, often covering the card Maury holds, contains the punchline or the 'verdict'. It typically features the famous phrase 'The lie detector determined that was a lie' or a similar statement that reveals the truth and debunks the initial claim.
The top section of the image serves as the setup for the meme. It usually contains a statement, a quote, or a claim that is about to be fact-checked or proven false by Maury's 'results'.

Maury-Lie-Detector.image_description: This meme features Maury Povich, the host of the talk show 'Maury,' intently reading the results from a card, a scene iconic for its dramatic paternity test and lie detector reveals. The format is used to humorously debunk a statement or expose a truth. Typically, a claim is made, and Maury's image follows with a punchline like 'The lie detector determined that was a lie,' invalidating the initial statement.

Thats-the-neat-part-you-dont.name: Thats-the-neat-part-you-dont

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, delivered by Omni-Man. It's typically a blunt, often negative, or nonsensical answer to the question or desire expressed in the top panel, such as the classic phrase, "That's the neat part, you don't."

The text here labels Omni-Man, representing the person, entity, or concept delivering the disappointing or flawed information. This could be a parent, a company, or an abstract idea like "My brain at 3 AM."

This box contains the question, desire, or setup for the joke, posed from Invincible's perspective. For example, it might state a goal like "Getting 8 hours of sleep" or ask a question like "How do I afford a house?"

The text here labels Invincible, representing the person or group who is asking the question or expressing a desire, only to be met with the harsh reality presented by Omni-Man. This is the hopeful or naive party in the exchange.

Thats-the-neat-part-you-dont.image_description: This meme format, known as "That's the Neat Part, You Don't," originates from the animated series "Invincible." It features Omni-Man (bottom panel) confidently explaining something to his son, Invincible (top panel), who looks back with a concerned or confused expression. The meme is used to humorously illustrate a situation where a desired outcome is impossible or a problem has no real solution, with Omni-Man delivering the disappointing punchline.
Thats-the-neat-part-you-dont.display_name: Thats the neat part you dont

Happy--Shock.name: Happy--Shock

text_options.description: This text box, placed next to the disappointed face, describes the negative outcome or the disappointing reality of the situation. It serves as the punchline, creating a stark contrast with the initial positive expectation set in the top panel.

This text box, positioned next to the smiling face, describes a positive or hopeful scenario. It sets up the user's initial expectation for a good outcome, which is then subverted by the text in the panel below.

Happy--Shock.image_description: This meme, known as "Disappointed Black Guy," is a two-panel reaction image featuring a man's face. In the top panel, he is smiling widely and enthusiastically, representing a positive expectation or situation. In the bottom panel, his expression shifts dramatically to one of disappointment, shock, or sad realization. The meme is used to humorously depict a scenario that starts out promising but quickly leads to a letdown.

Straight-to-Jail.name: Straight-to-Jail

text_options.description: This bottom caption area contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically the phrase 'Believe it or not, jail,' 'Right away,' or 'Straight to jail.' It represents the absurdly severe punishment for the minor offense described in the top text.

The text in this top section describes a minor, often relatable, annoyance or social misstep. This text serves as the setup for the joke, presenting a trivial 'crime' that the character is seemingly passing severe judgment on.

Straight-to-Jail.image_description: A still from the TV show 'Parks and Recreation' featuring a Venezuelan diplomat in full military dress speaking with a serious expression. The meme, often called 'Believe it or not, jail' or 'Straight to jail,' uses this image to humorously propose extreme punishments for minor social infractions. The contrast between the official's stern demeanor and the triviality of the 'crime' creates the comedic effect.

DW-Sign-Wont-Stop-Me-Because-I-Cant-Read.name: DW-Sign-Wont-Stop-Me-Because-I-Cant-Read

text_options.description: This label is placed on D.W.'s back. It identifies the person, group, or entity that is deliberately ignoring the warning or information presented on the sign.
This box covers the sign on the door in the wide shot. While often left blank or edited, it represents the physical presence of the warning that D.W. is about to ignore.

This label is placed on D.W.'s head in the close-up shot. It serves the same purpose as the label at index 0, identifying the person or group ignoring the sign, but in the context of the focused, top panel.

This large, blank sign is the main focus of the meme's text. The user writes the rule, warning, advice, or piece of information that is being blatantly disregarded by the character labeled in boxes 0 and 2.

DW-Sign-Wont-Stop-Me-Because-I-Cant-Read.image_description: This two-panel meme features D.W. Read from the children's animated series 'Arthur'. In the bottom panel, D.W. stands before a sign on a door, with the caption "That sign won't stop me, because I can't read!" The top panel is a close-up of D.W. looking at the sign. The meme is used to humorously depict someone willfully ignoring a warning, rule, or obvious fact, pretending to be ignorant or incapable of understanding it.
DW-Sign-Wont-Stop-Me-Because-I-Cant-Read.display_name: DW Sign Wont Stop Me Because I Cant Read

Captain-Phillips-Im-The-Captain-Now.name: Captain-Phillips-Im-The-Captain-Now

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the bottom panel where the character Abduwali Muse looks directly and intensely at the viewer. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically the phrase "Look at me, I'm the captain now" or a variation of it. This text represents the new person or entity that has seized control, completing the power-shift narrative.

This text box is in the top panel and usually labels the two characters to set up the scenario. The text on the left (over Captain Phillips) represents the original authority figure, while the text on the right (over Abduwali Muse) represents the challenger or usurper. This panel establishes the initial power dynamic that is about to be overturned.

Captain-Phillips-Im-The-Captain-Now.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the 2013 film 'Captain Phillips'. It features Abduwali Muse (played by Barkhad Abdi) confronting Captain Phillips (played by Tom Hanks). The meme humorously depicts a sudden and often unexpected shift in power or authority. The iconic line, "Look at me, I'm the captain now," is used to show someone or something taking control of a situation from a previously established authority figure.
Captain-Phillips-Im-The-Captain-Now.display_name: Captain Phillips Im The Captain Now

Taylor-Swift-Travis-Kelce-engagement.name: Taylor-Swift-Travis-Kelce-engagement

text_options.description: This label is placed on the woman being embraced. It represents a desirable object, a niche hobby, a specific interest, or a concept that the person labeled on the man is deeply passionate about or protective of.

This label is placed on the man who is holding the woman. It typically represents the meme's creator ('Me') or a specific group of people who are shown to be possessive or protective of the thing labeled on the woman.

Taylor-Swift-Travis-Kelce-engagement.image_description: This meme format, known as "Guy Protecting Girl" or "Man Holding Woman," features a stock photo of a muscular man tenderly embracing a woman in a garden. It is an object-labeling meme where the man represents a person or group, and the woman he holds represents a cherished object, hobby, or idea. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the man's protective, masculine stance with the often niche, nerdy, or unexpected subject he is 'protecting'.

Trojan-Horse.name: Trojan-Horse

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or group naively accepting the Trojan horse. They represent the unsuspecting victim who is tricked by the appealing exterior of the offering.
This label represents the entity, system, or place being infiltrated. It is the "city" or the target that will be negatively affected by the hidden contents of the horse.

This label, placed on the soldiers inside the horse, reveals the hidden danger, malicious intent, or negative consequence. It's the "catch" or the true, harmful nature of the offering that is being smuggled in.
This label is placed on the Trojan horse itself and describes the deceptive gift or appealing offer. It's the seemingly positive thing that is used to disguise the harmful element hidden within.

Trojan-Horse.image_description: This meme format uses the Greek myth of the Trojan Horse to illustrate deception. It depicts people willingly bringing a large wooden horse into their city, unaware of the enemy soldiers hidden inside. The meme is used to represent situations where an appealing offer or idea (the horse) is accepted, only to reveal a hidden, negative consequence or malicious intent (the soldiers) that undermines the recipient (the city).

Scared-Cat.name: Scared-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the cat's face, delivers the punchline or the sudden realization. This is the 'epiphany' part of the meme that justifies the cat's shocked expression, often revealing a simple but overlooked truth.
The top text serves as the setup for the meme. It typically describes a common situation, a thought, or a premise that seems ordinary at first, paving the way for the realization in the bottom text.

Scared-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as 'Startled Cat' or 'Sudden Realization Cat,' features a close-up of a cat with wide, shocked eyes and a slightly agape mouth. The cat's expression perfectly captures a moment of sudden, profound, or often comically mundane realization. The meme is typically used in a two-part format to express an epiphany or a 'mind-blown' moment about a common situation.

Buddy-Christ.name: Buddy-Christ

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline or a clever response to the setup in the top text. This is the part of the joke that earns the approval signified by the winking Buddy Christ image.
The top text area typically contains the setup for the joke or a statement that prompts a response. This line establishes the context for the punchline that follows below.

Buddy-Christ.image_description: This meme features a winking statue of Jesus Christ known as 'Buddy Christ' from the 1999 film Dogma. The figure is pointing and giving a thumbs-up, conveying a sense of casual approval and camaraderie. The meme is typically used as a reaction image to express agreement, acknowledge a clever joke, or give a lighthearted 'attaboy' to someone's comment or action.

Big-book-small-book.name: Big-book-small-book

text_options.description: Text placed over the thin book represents a simple, concise, or superficial topic. It serves as the setup for the punchline or the less complex side of the comparison.

Text placed over the thick book represents a much more complex, detailed, or lengthy subject. This is the punchline, contrasting sharply with the topic on the thin book to create a humorous or insightful comparison.

Big-book-small-book.image_description: This meme, known as "Thick Book vs. Thin Book," is a comparison format featuring a very thin book next to a very thick one. It's used to contrast two subjects, where the thin book represents something simple, straightforward, or with little substance. In contrast, the thick book represents something complex, nuanced, lengthy, or requiring significant explanation.

astronaut-meme-always-has-been-template.name: astronaut-meme-always-has-been-template

text_options.description: This area is for the punchline, spoken by the astronaut holding the gun. The text here is almost always "Always has been," which confirms the absurd revelation made by the other astronaut. This phrase is the title of the meme and delivers the core joke, implying a hidden, long-standing conspiracy.

This text box contains the setup for the joke, representing the dialogue of the astronaut who is about to be shot. The text typically expresses a dawning realization in the format "Wait, it's all [X]?" where [X] is the subject of the meme, which is visually represented by the planet. This line establishes the absurd premise that the punchline will confirm.

astronaut-meme-always-has-been-template.image_description: This meme, known as "Always Has Been" or the "Ohio Astronauts" meme, depicts two astronauts in space. One astronaut has just realized a shocking or absurd truth about the world (represented by the planet), while the second astronaut holds them at gunpoint, revealing this has always been the reality. The meme is used to humorously frame a surprising revelation as a long-standing, hidden conspiracy. The flag of Ohio on the gunman's arm is a common feature, leading to many jokes about Ohio secretly controlling everything.
astronaut-meme-always-has-been-template.display_name: astronaut meme always has been template

Why-Cant-I-Hold-All-These-Limes.name: Why-Cant-I-Hold-All-These-Limes

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image, acting as the punchline. This text typically expresses the subject's ecstatic thoughts or reaction to the situation described in the top text, often in a simple, exclamatory way that matches his overly enthusiastic expression.
The top text of the image, which sets up the premise of the meme. This text usually describes a situation, object, or event that the person in the image is reacting to with immense excitement.

Why-Cant-I-Hold-All-These-Limes.image_description: This meme, known as "Excited Man Holding Limes," features a stock photo of a man with a shaved head looking down at a handful of limes with an expression of extreme, almost manic, delight. The humor comes from the disproportionate level of excitement for something as mundane as limes. It is used to express intense, over-the-top enthusiasm or obsession with a particular subject, often something niche or simple.
Why-Cant-I-Hold-All-These-Limes.display_name: Why Cant I Hold All These Limes

Spirit-Halloween.name: Spirit-Halloween

text_options.description: This is the first item in a bulleted list describing the 'contents' of the costume. The text here lists a key stereotypical trait or accessory of the person or concept being parodied, starting the breakdown of the joke.
This is the second item in the bulleted list of the costume's features. It continues to describe the stereotypical traits or accessories associated with the subject of the meme.
This is the third item in a bulleted list describing the costume's 'features' or 'contents'. It adds another specific, often humorous or stereotypical, detail that builds on the overall joke.
This is the title of the costume. The text here names the person, archetype, or concept being satirized, setting the entire premise for the joke.

Spirit-Halloween.image_description: This meme template is based on the packaging for a Spirit Halloween costume. The format is used to create fake, satirical costumes by adding an image and text to the blank template. The humor comes from packaging a person, stereotype, or abstract concept as a simple, purchasable Halloween costume, complete with a list of stereotypical 'accessories' or 'features'.

Guy-in-corner-of-party.name: Guy-in-corner-of-party

text_options.description: This text box is placed on one of the dancing partygoers. It's used to label the 'normal' people with mainstream interests or generic labels, highlighting their contrast with the main character.

Similar to the text at index 0, this box labels another person in the crowd. This text helps establish the partygoers as a uniform group who are unaware of the main character's unique knowledge or feelings.

This text box is positioned above the isolated character, acting as a thought bubble. It contains the meme's punchline, which typically starts with "They don't know..." followed by a niche fact, obscure interest, or personal secret, revealing the reason for their detachment.

Guy-in-corner-of-party.image_description: This meme, known as "They Don't Know" or "I Wish I Was at Home," features a Wojak character standing alone in the corner at a party while others socialize. The character, often representing an introvert or someone with niche interests, looks on melancholically. The meme is used to express feelings of social alienation by contrasting the character's internal thoughts with the oblivious partygoers.

I-believe-in-supremacy.name: I-believe-in-supremacy

text_options.description: This area is part of the background and does not typically contain text. It is positioned near the worshipping figure, emphasizing their posture of reverence towards the concept named above.
This blank space is the core customizable element of the meme. Users insert the name of a person, character, object, or idea they wish to praise, completing the phrase to declare its "supremacy."

I-believe-in-supremacy.image_description: This meme, known as "I Believe in X Supremacy," features a silhouette of a person kneeling in a worshipful pose. The template text reads "i believe in [blank] SUPREMACY," creating a space for users to insert their own subject. The meme is used to express intense, often humorous or hyperbolic, admiration and devotion for a person, character, concept, or object, declaring it superior to all others.

Black-background.name: Black-background

text_options.description: The text in the bottom panel describes the rejected, incorrect, or undesirable concept. It is associated with the binary digit '0', which symbolizes 'off', 'false', or 'no'.
The text in the top panel describes the preferred, correct, or desirable concept. It is associated with the binary digit '1', which symbolizes 'on', 'true', or 'yes'.

Black-background.image_description: This two-panel meme format uses the binary digits '1' and '0' to represent a choice or comparison. The top panel with '1' signifies a positive, desirable, or 'true' option, while the bottom panel with '0' represents a negative, undesirable, or 'false' option. The meme is a minimalist and direct way to express strong approval for one thing over another, often used in contexts related to programming, logic, or technology.

Skeletor-disturbing-facts.name: Skeletor-disturbing-facts

text_options.description: The text in the bottom panel, where Skeletor is running away, serves as the punchline. It typically presents a counter-argument, a fact-check, or the negative consequence that debunks the statement above, causing the hasty 'retreat'.

The text in the top panel, where Skeletor is lounging confidently, represents a bold, boastful, or often misleading statement. This is the setup, where the user presents a strong but ultimately flawed opinion or claim.

Skeletor-disturbing-facts.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as 'Skeletor's Lies' or 'Skeletor Running Away,' features the villain Skeletor from the 1980s cartoon 'He-Man and the Masters of the Universe.' The top panel shows Skeletor lounging confidently, while the bottom panel depicts him running away in a panic. The meme contrasts a bold, often false or provocative statement with the subsequent hasty retreat, humorously illustrating someone making a grand claim and then immediately fleeing the consequences when challenged or proven wrong.

Avatar-guy.name: Avatar-guy

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the image, this text typically describes the action or event that has just occurred, leading to the state of profound realization. It provides the context for the character's vacant stare, often detailing an impulsive, regrettable, or intense experience.

Positioned at the top of the image, this text usually represents the profound, often unsettling, thought or realization that the person is having. It's the 'clarity' part of the meme, verbalizing the deep contemplation suggested by the character's expression, which is a direct consequence of the action described in the bottom text.

Avatar-guy.image_description: A close-up screenshot of a blue-skinned Na'vi character from the movie *Avatar*, staring blankly into the distance with a somber expression. This meme, often called 'Avatar Stare' or 'Post-Nut Clarity,' is used to represent a moment of sudden, profound, and often grim realization or introspection after performing an action. The character's vacant expression perfectly captures the feeling of contemplating one's choices with a sense of emptiness or regret.

TOYSTORY-EVERYWHERE.name: TOYSTORY-EVERYWHERE

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline, which follows the phrasal template 'X, X Everywhere.' The 'X' refers to the subject introduced in the top text, humorously exaggerating its sudden prevalence, mirroring Buzz's expansive gesture.
The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically introduces a new topic, trend, or observation that the user has recently encountered.

TOYSTORY-EVERYWHERE.image_description: This meme features Buzz Lightyear and Woody from the movie 'Toy Story.' Buzz is gesturing widely with a broad smile, while Woody looks on with concern. Known as the 'X, X Everywhere' or 'Buzz Lightyear Everywhere' meme, it's used to humorously comment on the sudden and overwhelming proliferation of a particular trend, topic, or item.

This-Is-Brilliant-But-I-Like-This.name: This-Is-Brilliant-But-I-Like-This

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the white Volkswagen Up! in the bottom panel. This space is reserved for the item that the user personally prefers, despite acknowledging the quality of the other option. It represents the quirky, nostalgic, or subjectively better choice that is the punchline of the meme.

This text box is placed on the red Ford Fiesta in the top panel. Text here represents the object, idea, or person that is generally considered excellent, popular, or the standard choice. It serves as the setup, establishing the high quality of the option that will ultimately be rejected in favor of the user's personal preference.

This-Is-Brilliant-But-I-Like-This.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the TV show Top Gear, featuring host Jeremy Clarkson. In the top panel, Clarkson gestures towards one option, declaring, "This is brilliant," acknowledging its objective quality or popularity. However, in the bottom panel, he turns to a second, often less conventional or older option, stating, "But I like this," revealing his personal, sometimes illogical, preference. The meme is used to compare two things, humorously highlighting a subjective choice over a more mainstream or technically superior one.
This-Is-Brilliant-But-I-Like-This.display_name: This Is Brilliant But I Like This

Silence-X-a-Y-is-talking.name: Silence-X-a-Y-is-talking

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom contains the punchline of the meme. It identifies the person, group, or concept that is supposedly 'talking' and thus deserves everyone's undivided attention. The humor comes from this subject being unexpectedly mundane, niche, or silly, contrasting with the serious demand for silence.
