This text box, positioned at the top, is meant to be filled with the name of a person, group, or idea that the meme creator wants to silence. It follows the commanding word 'SILENCE,' setting up the joke by targeting something often considered important or popular.

Silence-X-a-Y-is-talking.image_description: This meme features a Son of the Harpy from the TV series *Game of Thrones*, an intimidating figure in a mask and white robes, raising their hand to command silence. The image is used as a reaction meme template with the phrasal structure 'Silence, [X], a [Y] is talking.' It's typically used to humorously demand respect or attention for something niche or personally important (Y) by silencing something more mainstream or widely accepted (X).
Silence-X-a-Y-is-talking.display_name: Silence X a Y is talking

milking-the-cow.name: milking-the-cow

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the buckets held by the farmer character (Obama). It is used to label the person, group, or institution that is making an excessive or unrealistic demand for resources. Examples include "The Government," "My Boss," or "Landlords."

This text box is placed over the emaciated cow. It represents the entity that is being exploited or is unable to meet the high demands placed upon it. Common labels here are "The Taxpayer," "The Middle Class," or simply "Me," representing an individual feeling drained.

milking-the-cow.image_description: This political cartoon meme depicts a caricature of former U.S. President Barack Obama dressed as a farmer, cheerfully carrying numerous empty buckets towards a very skinny, sad-looking cow. The original cartoon critiques government spending and taxation, but as a meme, it's broadly used to represent any situation where a demanding entity has unrealistic expectations of an over-burdened or depleted source. It humorously illustrates dynamics like a company demanding more from overworked employees or a government expecting more from taxpayers.

Lord-of-the-Rings-Meats-back-on-the-menu.name: Lord-of-the-Rings-Meats-back-on-the-menu

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline and the iconic quote from the movie: 'Looks like meat's back on the menu, boys!'. This phrase is the core of the meme, signifying the enthusiastic return of a previously absent opportunity or item.

The top text box sets up the context for the punchline. It typically describes a scenario where a restriction has been lifted or a long-awaited event is finally happening, making the Uruk-hai's declaration relevant and funny.

Lord-of-the-Rings-Meats-back-on-the-menu.image_description: This meme features a close-up of an Uruk-hai from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers'. The character, with a fierce and primal expression, is from a scene where he famously declares, 'Looks like meat's back on the menu, boys!'. The meme is used to humorously announce the return of something that was previously unavailable or restricted, often something desirable or indulgent.
Lord-of-the-Rings-Meats-back-on-the-menu.display_name: Lord of the Rings Meats back on the menu

Back-In-My-Day.name: Back-In-My-Day

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It delivers the specific, often exaggerated or absurd, old-fashioned complaint or the supposed superior alternative from "the good old days," completing the setup from the top text.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically introduces a modern concept, behavior, or technology that the character disapproves of, or it begins with a classic nostalgic phrase like "Back in my day...".

Back-In-My-Day.image_description: This meme features an elderly man in Victorian-style attire, including a top hat and scarf, with an angry and scolding expression. Often referred to as "Angry Old Man" or likened to Ebenezer Scrooge, he points his finger accusingly. The format is used to express curmudgeonly or old-fashioned complaints about modern society, trends, or technology, typically starting with a phrase like "Back in my day..." to create a humorous contrast between past and present.

Anthony-Adams-Rubbing-Hands.name: Anthony-Adams-Rubbing-Hands

text_options.description: This lower section of the image is often used to label the subject or situation that the man is eagerly anticipating. It represents the opportunity, the unsuspecting victim, or the event that is about to unfold, which the character in box 1 is excited about.

This text box is placed directly over the man, Anthony Adams. The text here identifies the person, company, or entity that is eagerly and greedily awaiting a particular outcome. This character is the schemer or opportunist in the meme's narrative.

Anthony-Adams-Rubbing-Hands.image_description: This meme, known as "Anthony Adams Rubbing Hands" or "Yellow Jacket Guy," features former NFL player Anthony Adams in a bright yellow suit peeking from behind a tree. He is rubbing his hands together and licking his lips with a greedy and mischievous expression. The image is used to represent someone eagerly, and often deviously, anticipating an event or situation they can exploit, perfectly capturing a sense of scheming or schadenfreude.

dog-vs-werewolf.name: dog-vs-werewolf

text_options.description: Text placed over the golden retriever represents the calm, normal, or seemingly innocent side of a person, object, or situation. It serves as the setup for the contrast, establishing a baseline of pleasantness or normalcy.

Text placed over the werewolf represents the aggressive, chaotic, or intense alter ego or hidden reality. This text delivers the punchline by revealing the stark and often humorous contrast to the initial, calmer subject labeled on the dog.

dog-vs-werewolf.image_description: This meme, often called "Dog vs. Werewolf" or "Two Dogs Inside You," features a friendly-looking golden retriever sitting next to a frightening, aggressive werewolf statue. The image is used as a comparison template to contrast two related but starkly different things. Typically, the dog represents a calm, innocent, or public-facing version of something, while the werewolf represents its intense, aggressive, or hidden inner nature, creating a humorous or relatable duality.

Weak-vs-Strong-Spongebob.name: Weak-vs-Strong-Spongebob

text_options.description: This text box, aligned with the muscular and intimidating SpongeBob, holds the 'stronger' or superior element of the comparison. This text serves as the punchline, revealing the more powerful, complex, or impressive counterpart to the text in the top box.

This text box, positioned next to the regular, cheerful SpongeBob, typically contains the 'weaker' or more mundane element of the comparison. It sets up the contrast by representing a simpler, less intense, or initial idea.

Weak-vs-Strong-Spongebob.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Buff SpongeBob' or 'SpongeBob vs. Man-Ray,' uses two contrasting images of SpongeBob SquarePants. The top panel shows a normal, cheerful SpongeBob, while the bottom panel depicts a muscular, aggressive version of him. The meme is used to compare two related things, humorously portraying one as significantly weaker or simpler than the other, which is shown as superior, more intense, or more complex.

sweating-bullets.name: sweating-bullets

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically identifies the person or entity experiencing the stress, often labeled simply as 'Me:'. This grounds the meme by specifying who is feeling the anxiety described in the top text, making the situation relatable.
The top text box sets up the entire premise of the meme. It describes the high-stakes, stressful, or awkward situation that is causing the character's extreme nervousness.

sweating-bullets.image_description: This meme features a close-up of comedian Jordan Peele from a 'Key & Peele' sketch, sweating profusely with a look of intense anxiety. It's widely used to represent nervousness, stress, or being in a precarious situation where one is trying to avoid a negative outcome. The image perfectly captures the feeling of being under pressure or on the verge of being caught.

Futurama-Zero-Days-Since-Last-Blank.name: Futurama-Zero-Days-Since-Last-Blank

text_options.description: This is the main customizable area of the meme. Users add text here to specify the event that is being tracked, which is often a personal failing, a recurring annoyance, or a humorous observation. The text in this box provides the context for the punchline delivered by the number in box 1.

This space is reserved for a number, which is almost invariably '0' or another low digit. This number represents the count of days since the event described in box 0 occurred. Placing a '0' here signifies that the event has just happened, completing the joke by highlighting its constant recurrence.

Futurama-Zero-Days-Since-Last-Blank.image_description: This meme originates from the animated TV show Futurama and features a large sign that reads "DAYS SINCE LAST". Modeled after workplace safety signs that track days since an accident, this format is used to humorously lament the frequent occurrence of a specific, often undesirable or silly, event. The humor lies in the fact that the number of days is almost always zero or a very low number, implying the event just happened again.
Futurama-Zero-Days-Since-Last-Blank.display_name: Futurama Zero Days Since Last Blank

I-Bring-a-Sort-of-X-Vibe-to-the-Y.name: I-Bring-a-Sort-of-X-Vibe-to-the-Y

text_options.description: This text box identifies the group of people who disapprove of the 'vibe' being introduced. It follows 'that' and precedes 'don't really like,' completing the sentence by specifying who is being annoyed, such as 'my family,' 'my coworkers,' or 'the group chat.'

This text box specifies the social setting, event, or context where the vibe is being brought. Placed after 'Vibe to,' it sets the scene for the humorous conflict, with examples like 'the function,' 'the group project,' or 'the family reunion.'

This text box, positioned between quotation marks, contains the punchline of the meme. It describes the specific, often undesirable or chaotic, 'vibe' the person brings to the situation, such as 'I don't give a fuck' in the original, or other user-generated traits.

I-Bring-a-Sort-of-X-Vibe-to-the-Y.image_description: This meme, known as 'I Bring a Sort of Vibe' or 'Quanmillz on the Balcony,' features a man looking over his shoulder with a knowing, slightly defiant expression. Originating from a TikTok video, it's used as a phrasal template to humorously describe a specific, often unwelcome or chaotic, energy one brings to a social situation or group. The man's defiant look perfectly complements the text, which confesses to a trait that others 'don't really like.'
I-Bring-a-Sort-of-X-Vibe-to-the-Y.display_name: I Bring a Sort of X Vibe to the Y

Stop-giving-me-your-toughest-battles.name: Stop-giving-me-your-toughest-battles

text_options.description: This area is reserved for the response from the Chad Jesus character. The text placed here is typically a short, stoic, and unsympathetic reply that dismisses the Wojak's plea, such as "But you are my strongest soldier," completing the humorous and relatable depiction of feeling unheard while struggling.

Stop-giving-me-your-toughest-battles.image_description: This meme, known as "Stop Giving Me Your Toughest Battles," features a distressed, suffering Wojak character pleading with a depiction of Jesus Christ drawn as the stoic and masculine "Chad" Wojak. The Wojak complains about the overwhelming challenges they face, subverting the inspirational phrase "God gives his toughest battles to his strongest soldiers." The meme is used to humorously express feelings of being overwhelmed by life's difficulties, portraying the user as the suffering "soldier" who can no longer handle the trials assigned by a higher power.
Stop-giving-me-your-toughest-battles.display_name: Stop giving me your toughest battles

Winter-Is-Coming.name: Winter-Is-Coming

text_options.description: This is the bottom text line, which serves as the punchline. It describes the action that is unexpectedly difficult, completing the phrase from the top line. For example, '...walk into Mordor' is the original, but it's often replaced with a humorous or relatable task.
This is the top text line of the image macro. It almost invariably contains the setup phrase 'ONE DOES NOT SIMPLY' in a large, capitalized font, establishing the meme's well-known format.

Winter-Is-Coming.image_description: This meme features a still of Sean Bean as Ned Stark from the TV show 'Game of Thrones,' though the quote it's famous for is from his role as Boromir in 'The Lord of the Rings.' Known as the 'One Does Not Simply' meme, it's used to humorously emphasize the difficulty or complexity of a task that might seem straightforward. The meme's format is a two-part statement expressing that an action is not as easy as it sounds.

Midwit-memes.name: Midwit-memes

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the high end of the IQ scale, next to the calm, hooded Wojak. It typically contains a simple, yet profound or correct statement that mirrors the text on the far left, representing the enlightened perspective.

Located at the peak of the bell curve, this text box represents the opinion of the average-IQ individual, depicted as a crying and angry Wojak (Soyjak). The text here is usually a mainstream, over-intellectualized, or emotionally charged argument that the meme intends to mock as incorrect.

This text box is on the far left of the bell curve, associated with the low-IQ Wojak (Brainlet). The text here represents a very simple, straightforward, and often correct opinion, which sets up the punchline of the meme.

Midwit-memes.image_description: This meme, known as the "IQ Bell Curve" or "Wojak Bell Curve," uses a normal distribution graph to satirize opinions on various subjects. It features three Wojak characters: a simple-minded one on the low-IQ end, an emotional and overthinking "midwit" at the average-IQ peak, and an enlightened, sage-like figure on the high-IQ end. The meme's format suggests that the simplest and most profound conclusions are often the same, while the average person holds a flawed, overcomplicated viewpoint.

A-lion-doesnt-concern-himself.name: A-lion-doesnt-concern-himself

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline or the profound, powerful statement. This text is meant to represent the 'lion's' mindset—a strong, independent, and wise perspective that counters or answers the text in the top panel.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically contains a question, a common saying, or a statement representing a conventional or 'weaker' viewpoint that the 'lion's' perspective will challenge.

A-lion-doesnt-concern-himself.image_description: This meme template features a black and white, dramatic photo of a majestic lion looking up. The image is placed between two black panels intended for text, creating a three-part vertical structure. This format is commonly used for motivational, philosophical, or "sigma male" quotes, where the lion symbolizes strength, independence, and wisdom. The meme contrasts a conventional idea or question (top) with a powerful, assertive, or profound statement (bottom), representing the lion's superior perspective.

Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-Happen.name: Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-Happen

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a direct and often condescending question reacting to the setup in box 1. It frequently uses variations of Regina George's line, 'So you agree? You think you're really pretty?', to call out perceived vanity or hypocrisy.
The top text box is the setup for the meme. It usually contains a statement, often a quote from someone or a description of a situation, that the meme creator finds arrogant or worthy of challenge.

Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-Happen.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Regina George from the movie "Mean Girls," wearing a Santa hat with a serious, questioning expression. The image is from the iconic 'Jingle Bell Rock' performance scene. This format is used to pose a leading or condescending question, setting up a premise and then delivering a punchline that often implies someone is conceited or hypocritical.
Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-Happen.display_name: Stop Trying to Make Fetch Happen

Bro-Please-Bro.name: Bro-Please-Bro

text_options.description: This area on the left is the setup for the meme. Text placed here typically describes a situation, a statement, or a fact that is sad, disappointing, or relatable in a painful way, which then justifies the crying man's reaction in the adjacent panel.

Bro-Please-Bro.image_description: This is a two-panel reaction meme featuring a blank space on the left and a close-up of a man crying on the right. The man, often called "Crying Guy" or "Sad Guy," displays an expression of intense sorrow and disappointment. The meme is used to show an exaggeratedly sad or emotional reaction to a statement, image, or situation placed in the left panel, which serves as the setup.

Dr-Evil-air-quotes.name: Dr-Evil-air-quotes

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned between Dr. Evil's hands, contains the word or phrase being put in "air quotes." This is the punchline of the meme, representing the concept that is being mocked, doubted, or used euphemistically.
The top text sets up the sarcastic statement. It's the first part of a sentence that leads into the word or phrase that Dr. Evil is ironically quoting.

Dr-Evil-air-quotes.image_description: This meme features the character Dr. Evil from the Austin Powers film series, sitting in a chair and making his signature "air quotes" gesture with both hands. This image is used to sarcastically emphasize a word or phrase, implying it is untrue, ironic, or a euphemism. The humor derives from the visual representation of sarcasm, with the quoted text often placed between his fingers.

Priest-tempted-by-girl.name: Priest-tempted-by-girl

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or entity trying to remain focused on a duty, responsibility, or virtuous goal. The monk's pious and focused expression represents the struggle to resist temptation.

This label represents the powerful temptation, distraction, or vice that threatens to derail the person from their goal. The woman's seductive pose embodies the alluring but ultimately detrimental alternative.

Priest-tempted-by-girl.image_description: This meme, often called 'Monk trying to ignore a thot,' depicts a monk fervently praying while a scantily clad woman attempts to distract him. The image is used to represent a struggle between a noble or important goal (the monk) and a powerful temptation or distraction (the woman). It humorously illustrates battles with self-control, procrastination, or conflicting desires.

There-is-no-war-in-ba-sing-se.name: There-is-no-war-in-ba-sing-se

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Joo Dee's body. It contains the statement of denial, often a variation of the original line, representing the person or group willfully ignoring the problem.

Positioned above Joo Dee's head, this text describes the undeniable, often catastrophic, problem or reality that is being ignored. The humor comes from the stark contrast between this text and the denial below.

There-is-no-war-in-ba-sing-se.image_description: This meme features Joo Dee from the animated series 'Avatar: The Last Airbender,' recognizable by her wide, unsettling smile which signifies she is brainwashed. In the show, she famously denies the existence of a major conflict by saying, 'There is no war in Ba Sing Se.' The meme is used to humorously depict a person or entity blatantly denying an obvious and often overwhelming problem.
There-is-no-war-in-ba-sing-se.display_name: There is no war in ba sing se

No-Take-Only-Throw.name: No-Take-Only-Throw

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the first panel where the dog is visibly angry. It typically contains an aggressive, hostile, or strongly opinionated statement that establishes the character's initial negative stance.

Located in the middle panel where a hand is petting the dog, this text box represents the pacifying action. It usually contains a simple compliment, a kind word, or a positive affirmation directed at the angry character, which causes their demeanor to change.

This text box is in the final panel, where the dog looks sad and remorseful. The text here reflects the character's change of heart, often expressing regret, sadness, or a softened, apologetic version of their initial angry statement.

No-Take-Only-Throw.image_description: This is a three-panel comic strip meme, often called the 'Petting Dog' or 'He's a Good Boy' meme. It depicts a dog's emotional journey from anger to regret. In the first panel, the dog is angry; in the second, a hand pets it, and its expression softens; in the final panel, it looks sad. The meme is used to humorously illustrate how a small compliment or act of kindness can instantly pacify someone who was previously aggressive or upset, causing them to regret their initial hostility.

Happy-dolphin-rainbow.name: Happy-dolphin-rainbow

text_options.description: This text box covers the detailed underwater scene. It typically contains a description of a complex, niche, obscure, or sometimes disturbing aspect of a topic, representing the 'deep' or hidden reality known only to insiders or experts.

This text box is placed over the bright, cheerful sky scene. The text here usually describes a simple, mainstream, or surface-level understanding of a subject, setting up the contrast with the 'deep' reality shown below.

Happy-dolphin-rainbow.image_description: This meme format, often called "Surface vs. The Deep" or "Dolphins in the Sky," presents a split view of a vibrant ocean scene. The idyllic top half, featuring jumping dolphins, rainbows, and hot air balloons, represents a simple, wholesome, or mainstream understanding of a topic. In contrast, the bustling and detailed underwater scene below represents the complex, niche, or darker reality lurking beneath the surface. The meme is used to contrast the superficial perception of something with its more intricate or hidden truth.

20-minute-adventure-rick-morty.name: 20-minute-adventure-rick-morty

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the bottom panel, which shows the disastrous aftermath. It serves as the punchline, describing the chaotic and unforeseen negative consequences of the initial plan.

This label is placed on Morty, who represents the hesitant or naive party being dragged into a situation. The text here typically identifies the person or group that is skeptical but ultimately goes along with the plan.
This label is placed on Rick, the overconfident planner. The text here represents the person or entity making an overly optimistic promise or underestimating the difficulty of a task.
This label is placed on the portal, which symbolizes the proposed mission or task. The text here describes the seemingly simple "adventure" or plan that is about to go wrong.

20-minute-adventure-rick-morty.image_description: This two-panel meme from the animated series "Rick and Morty" contrasts optimistic plans with disastrous outcomes. In the top panel, the scientist Rick Sanchez confidently proposes a "quick 20-minute adventure" to his hesitant grandson, Morty Smith. The bottom panel shows both characters looking exhausted and traumatized, implying the adventure went horribly wrong. The format is used to humorously depict situations where a seemingly simple task escalates into a chaotic and stressful ordeal.

What-Do-We-Want.name: What-Do-We-Want

text_options.description: Located in the bottom-right panel above the three sad-looking characters, this text describes the negative outcome or the fact that the problem persists despite the 'solution'. It serves as the punchline, showing the failure of the enthusiastic plan from the previous panel.

Positioned in the bottom-left panel above the hyper-excited character, this is the core of the meme. The text here presents the overly simplistic and enthusiastic solution, famously formatted as '[Verb] all the [Nouns]!' (e.g., 'Clean all the things!').

This text box is in the top-right panel, above the three sad-looking characters. It is used to state the problem, challenge, or negative situation that the meme's protagonist is facing, setting the stage for the manic solution.

This text box is in the top-left panel, above the single manic character. It often serves as a title or an initial thought that sets up the entire scenario, leading into the problem described in the panel to its right.

What-Do-We-Want.image_description: This is the 'X all the Y' meme, which originates from the webcomic 'Hyperbole and a Half' by Allie Brosh. The meme features a crudely drawn character expressing manic enthusiasm for a simple, often ineffective, solution to a complex problem. It's typically used in a multi-panel format to contrast a sad or problematic state with a burst of misguided energy, humorously highlighting the failure of the simplistic plan.

Feel-like-pure-shit.name: Feel-like-pure-shit

text_options.description: The bottom text caption, placed over the person's shirt. This area typically contains a punchline or a label for the crying person, often representing something or someone in a state of distress or failure.
The top text caption, placed above the person's eyes. This text usually sets up the scenario or describes the cause of the extreme emotional distress, providing context for the crying reaction.

Feel-like-pure-shit.image_description: A close-up photograph of a young person with red, bloodshot eyes and a distressed, crying expression. Known as the "Crying Kid" or "Sad Kid" meme, this image is used as a reaction to express intense sadness, disappointment, or being overwhelmed by a situation. It's often used humorously to represent an over-the-top emotional response to a relatable or trivial problem.

PTSD-Chihuahua.name: PTSD-Chihuahua

text_options.description: The text in this bottom section describes the past 'traumatic' event that the subject is flashing back to. This is the source of the stress, often a comically trivial or awkward memory that is being equated with the horrors of war.

The text in this top section describes the present-day, often innocuous, trigger that causes the flashback. This mundane stimulus is what makes the subject remember the more stressful event described at the bottom.

PTSD-Chihuahua.image_description: This meme, known as the 'PTSD Chihuahua' or 'Vietnam War Flashback Dog,' features a chihuahua with a thousand-yard stare. Superimposed over the dog's face are semi-transparent images of helicopters and soldiers, evoking a war flashback. The meme is used to humorously represent someone being triggered by a mundane event that reminds them of a past stressful or traumatic experience, often exaggerating the severity of the memory for comedic effect.

floating-boy-chasing-running-boy.name: floating-boy-chasing-running-boy

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the running boy. It represents the person or entity trying to escape. This is typically labeled with 'me' or a specific group to establish the protagonist of the scenario who is trying to avoid something.

This text box is placed over the unnervingly calm, floating figure. The text here identifies the inescapable threat, problem, or urge that is pursuing the running person. The humor often comes from this being something trivial, mundane, or an internal thought, contrasting with the panic of the person fleeing.

floating-boy-chasing-running-boy.image_description: This meme, known as 'Floating Boy Chasing Running Boy,' features a blurry person running down a hallway in apparent panic, pursued by another person who is ominously levitating. The running figure represents someone desperately trying to escape a situation, while the floating figure personifies an inevitable, often mundane or absurd, threat or responsibility. The meme is used to humorously depict the feeling of being relentlessly pursued by something one wishes to avoid.

two-castles.name: two-castles

text_options.description: Text placed over the dark, spooky castle represents the unconventional, difficult, or 'edgy' choice. This is the option the meme creator typically favors, presenting it as a more interesting or authentic path despite its negative connotations.

Text placed over the bright, sunny castle represents the conventional, socially acceptable, or 'correct' choice. This option serves as the foil to the darker path, highlighting the standard or expected behavior that the meme creator is rejecting.

two-castles.image_description: This meme, known as "Two Paths" or "Two Castles," depicts a person standing at a fork in the road, faced with a choice between two distinct destinations. One path leads to a bright, sunny castle representing a conventional, easy, or morally righteous option. The other path leads to a dark, spooky castle under a stormy sky, symbolizing a more difficult, unconventional, or tempting alternative. The meme is used to contrast two opposing choices, with the creator often ironically or genuinely favoring the 'darker' path.

3-Spiderman-Pointing.name: 3-Spiderman-Pointing

text_options.description: Text placed over the Spider-Man on the right identifies one of the parties in the confrontation. This label, along with the other two, names a person, group, or idea that is ironically similar to the others it is accusing.

Text placed on the central Spider-Man represents the second of the three identical or similar entities. The labels on all three characters are typically interchangeable and work together to create the joke about their shared hypocrisy or similarity.

Text placed on the Spider-Man on the left identifies the third party in the standoff. This label completes the set, with all three pointing fingers at each other for a flaw or characteristic they all share.

3-Spiderman-Pointing.image_description: This meme, known as 'Spider-Man Pointing at Spider-Man,' originates from the 1967 animated series and features three identical Spider-Man characters pointing at each other. The scene illustrates a moment of confusion and accusation among identical parties. It is widely used to humorously represent situations where two or more similar groups, individuals, or concepts are ironically blaming or confronting one another, highlighting hypocrisy or unexpected sameness.

Makima-is-listening.name: Makima-is-listening

text_options.description: This area on the notepad is where the subject of the meme is placed. It replaces the original character's name ('Makima') with any person, group, or concept that is perceived to be 'listening' or monitoring conversations, creating a humorous or cautionary statement about surveillance or being overheard.

Makima-is-listening.image_description: A black-and-white manga panel from Chainsaw Man featuring the character Kishibe, a world-weary man in a suit. He holds up a notepad with a handwritten message to communicate secretly, as the original speech bubble indicates a different conversation. This meme format, '[X] is listening,' is used to express paranoia or issue a warning about a person, organization, or algorithm that is perceived as being omniscient or constantly monitoring others.

math-is-math.name: math-is-math

text_options.description: This bottom section contains the punchline, corresponding to Mr. Incredible's outburst. The text here is typically a loud, emphatic, and often all-caps statement that forcefully rejects the premise from the top panel and asserts the original, simple truth of the matter.

The top panel of the image serves as the setup for the meme. It typically displays a statement, often a new name for something or a concept that has been changed, which the meme's creator finds absurd or unnecessary.

math-is-math.image_description: This meme, known as "Math is Math" or "Mr. Incredible Slamming Desk," originates from the movie "Incredibles 2." It shows the character Mr. Incredible (Bob Parr) furiously slamming his fist on a table. The meme is used to express frustration with unnecessary changes, rebranding, or euphemisms by forcefully asserting that something is what it is, regardless of attempts to call it something else.

Look-What-They-Need-To-Mimic-A-Fraction-.name: Look-What-They-Need-To-Mimic-A-Fraction-Of-Our-Power

text_options.description: Text placed on Omni-Man's chest represents the superior, more powerful, or more efficient subject. This is the entity that possesses the "power" mentioned in the caption.

Text placed over the fighter jets in the sky represents the inferior, weaker, or more complex subject being mocked. This is the entity that is trying, and failing, to imitate the power of the subject labeled on Omni-Man.

Look-What-They-Need-To-Mimic-A-Fraction-.image_description: This two-panel meme features Omni-Man from the animated series "Invincible" talking to his son. In the top panel, he gestures towards fighter jets, and in the bottom panel, he looks down with a contemptuous expression, saying, "Look what they need to mimic a fraction of our power." The meme is used to express superiority by comparing a powerful, original, or efficient entity (Omni-Man) to a weaker, derivative, or overly complicated alternative (the jets).
Look-What-They-Need-To-Mimic-A-Fraction-.display_name: Look What They Need To Mimic A Fraction Of Our Power

Please-sir-may-I-have-some-more.name: Please-sir-may-I-have-some-more

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the bottom of the image, near the boy holding the bowl. It typically contains the request or plea from the perspective of the user, often phrased as a question asking for "more" of something. This text represents the punchline and the central action of the meme.

Located at the top of the image, this text box is used to label the authority figure or the entity that has control over the resource being requested. This sets up the context for the plea that follows in the bottom text.

Please-sir-may-I-have-some-more.image_description: This meme features a still of the character Oliver Twist from the 1968 film "Oliver!", based on the Charles Dickens novel. In the image, a young, forlorn-looking boy in ragged clothes holds out an empty bowl, famously asking for more food. The meme is used to humorously depict someone humbly or desperately asking for more of something from a person or entity in a position of authority or control.
Please-sir-may-I-have-some-more.display_name: Please sir may I have some more

If-nobody-got-me-blank.name: If-nobody-got-me-blank

text_options.description: This text box is placed between "I know" and "got me." It is meant to be filled with the name of the person or thing the user is praising, mirroring the content in box 1. This repetition reinforces the central theme of unwavering reliance on the chosen subject.

This is the primary location where users insert an image or the name of the person, object, or concept they are devoted to. The silhouette points directly at this box, making it the focal point. The text or image placed here sets up the punchline of the meme, revealing the often humorous or absurd subject of the user's loyalty.

If-nobody-got-me-blank.image_description: This meme, known as "If Nobody Got Me, I Know X Got Me," features a silhouetted figure pointing upwards towards the sky. The format parodies inspirational or religious social media posts to express an exaggerated or humorous sense of loyalty and reliance on a particular person, object, or concept. Users edit the image to insert their chosen subject into the blank spaces, declaring it as the one thing they can always count on.

Free.name: Free

text_options.description: This is the 'Bottom Text' area. It typically contains the punchline or a concluding, often humorous or ironic, statement that relates to the setup in the top text and the image in the background.
This is the 'Top Text' area. It's used to establish a premise, set up a situation, or introduce a topic for the meme.

Free.image_description: This is a classic 'Top Text, Bottom Text' meme template, also known as an image macro. It features a transparent background where a user can insert any image. The format is used to create a simple, two-part joke or statement, with the top text typically providing setup and the bottom text delivering the punchline.

Aaaaand-Its-Gone.name: Aaaaand-Its-Gone

text_options.description: The text at the bottom is the punchline, delivered from the character's perspective. It almost always reads "Aaaand it's gone" or a slight variation, signifying the immediate and irreversible disappearance of whatever was introduced in the top text.

The text at the top of the image serves as the setup. It describes a positive situation or the acquisition of something desirable, such as receiving a paycheck or finally getting something you wanted, which sets the stage for the inevitable loss.

Aaaaand-Its-Gone.image_description: This meme, known as "Aaaand It's Gone," originates from the animated series "South Park." It features a bank employee with a deadpan expression who informs a client that their money has instantly vanished. The meme is used to humorously depict the sudden and complete loss of something valuable, like money, an opportunity, or a feeling, immediately after it was acquired.

No-thanks-brain.name: No-thanks-brain

text_options.description: This area typically labels the hand and brain, representing the logical, smart, or correct course of action. It sets up the sensible choice that is being presented to the individual.

This speech bubble contains the punchline of the meme. It's where the user writes the foolish, irrational, or simplistic idea that the person chooses over the sensible option represented by the brain.

No-thanks-brain.image_description: This meme, often called "Brain offering" or "No, thank you," depicts a hand offering a brain to a man who is dismissively waving it away. The brain represents a logical, intelligent, or sensible thought or action. The meme is used to humorously illustrate someone rejecting a good idea in favor of a foolish, irrational, or simpler alternative, which is expressed in the man's speech bubble.

Assassination-chain.name: Assassination-chain

text_options.description: This label is on the back of the sniper in the foreground. The text here represents the ultimate, often unseen, threat or the final, overriding reality that makes all the other problems in the chain irrelevant. It serves as the punchline of the meme.

This label is on the woman on the right, who is aiming a gun at the woman in the middle. The text here represents a significant problem or threat that is itself being targeted by an even larger, unseen force (the sniper).
This label is on the woman in the middle, who is aiming a gun at the smiling man. The text here represents an immediate or direct threat to the subject of the meme.
This label is on the smiling man who is unaware of the danger. The text here represents the initial person, idea, or plan that is naive or oblivious to the cascading series of threats aimed at it.

Assassination-chain.image_description: This meme format originates from the TV show "Person of Interest" and is often called the "Person of Interest Sniper" or "Three People Pointing Guns" meme. It depicts a chain of individuals aiming guns at each other in a church, culminating in a sniper aiming at the entire group from a distance. The meme is used to illustrate a hierarchy of escalating problems, threats, or superseding concepts, where each element is trumped by the next, often more powerful or unexpected, one.

Wait-its-all.name: Wait-its-all

text_options.description: This area covers the astronaut holding the gun, who represents the keeper of a hidden truth. In many versions of the meme, this astronaut is labeled to represent the entity or concept that is the subject of the revelation.

This area covers the astronaut who is having the realization. This character represents someone naive or the general public discovering the 'truth' for the first time. They are often labeled to represent the person or group being enlightened.

This text box is the punchline of the meme, completing the phrase "Wait, it's all ___?". The text inserted here reveals the surprising or absurd thing that everything is supposedly made of, which is the central joke of the meme.

Wait-its-all.image_description: The "Always Has Been" meme, also known as "Wait, it's all Ohio?", features two astronauts in space. One astronaut makes a shocking discovery about the nature of reality, asking "Wait, it's all [X]?". The second astronaut, aiming a pistol at the first, confirms the conspiracy with the line "Always has been." This format is used to humorously present a surprising, absurd, or conspiratorial revelation as a long-standing, hidden truth.

Thousand-Yard-Stare.name: Thousand-Yard-Stare

text_options.description: This area, centered on the soldier's face, represents the person or entity experiencing the 'trauma' or 'flashback.' The text here identifies the subject who is deeply affected by the event described above.

Positioned over the chaotic battle scene, this text describes the cause of the soldier's distress. In the meme's context, this is typically a mundane, frustrating, or comically stressful event that is being equated to the horrors of war, creating the humor.

Thousand-Yard-Stare.image_description: This meme, known as the "Thousand-Yard Stare" or "War Flashbacks," features a painting of a soldier with a shocked, vacant expression. The background depicts a chaotic warzone, symbolizing a traumatic event. The meme is used to humorously portray someone having an extreme, traumatized reaction to a stressful, overwhelming, or absurd situation, which is often mundane in reality.

3rd-Place-Celebration.name: 3rd-Place-Celebration

text_options.description: This label is on the third-place winner who is celebrating wildly. This text identifies the person, company, or concept that is achieving a minor victory but acting as if it's a major triumph.

This label is on the first-place winner, who stands calmly. This text represents the actual winner, the industry leader, or the superior entity that the third-place winner is often compared to or ignoring.

This label is on the second-place winner. This text represents the runner-up or another major competitor who, like the first-place winner, is not celebrating and serves as a point of contrast to the third-place winner's behavior.
This is a close-up of the third-place winner spraying champagne. This panel emphasizes the over-the-top celebration, and the label here would reiterate the identity of the overly proud subject.
This close-up shows the third-place winner being defiant and boastful. The label here reinforces the identity of the person celebrating their minor success with excessive arrogance.
This panel shows the third-place winner kissing a woman, part of his victory celebration. The label here would identify the triumphant subject, adding to the narrative of their exaggerated glory.
This close-up shows the third-place winner biting his medal. This action mimics a traditional pose for gold medalists, highlighting the irony and misplaced pride of the subject.

This panel shows the third-place winner emotionally receiving his medal. The label here identifies the subject at the beginning of their celebratory moment, setting the stage for their disproportionate reaction.

3rd-Place-Celebration.image_description: This meme, often called "3rd Place Celebration" or "Bronze Medal," is a multi-panel comic depicting an awards ceremony. An athlete who won third place celebrates with excessive, wild joy, as if he won first. In contrast, the first and second place winners stand stoically on their podiums. The meme is used to humorously represent someone celebrating a minor achievement or insignificant victory with disproportionate pride, often to the confusion of the actual winners or established leaders in a field.

first-time.name: first-time

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the dialogue '-First time?'. It is spoken by the experienced character and remains constant across all variations of the meme, establishing the condescending and humorous tone.

This area labels the experienced individual or group, represented by James Franco's character. The text here identifies the 'veteran' who is unfazed by the difficult situation that the 'newcomer' is experiencing for the first time.

first-time.image_description: This meme features a screenshot from the 2018 film 'The Ballad of Buster Scruggs,' showing a condemned man (played by James Franco) with a noose around his neck, smirking at another prisoner. He calmly asks, 'First time?', implying he's been in this life-threatening situation before. The meme is used to represent a seasoned veteran humorously or patronizingly welcoming a newcomer to a difficult, chaotic, or recurring negative experience.

Blank-Wild-Pokemon-Appears.name: Blank-Wild-Pokemon-Appears

text_options.description: This text box is the core of the meme, where the name of the unexpected person, object, or concept is inserted. It replaces the name of the Pokémon from the original game, serving as the main punchline that defines what has suddenly 'appeared'.

This large blank area is where an image of the subject mentioned in the text box below (at index 0) is placed. This visual component works with the text to illustrate the 'wild' thing that has just appeared, completing the joke.

Blank-Wild-Pokemon-Appears.image_description: A screenshot from the classic Pokémon games (Red/Blue/Yellow) showing the start of a random battle encounter. This 'A Wild [X] Appears' format is a popular exploitable meme used to humorously announce the sudden and unexpected arrival of a person, object, or abstract concept. The retro, pixelated aesthetic adds to its nostalgic appeal and widespread recognition.

Squidward-chair.name: Squidward-chair

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Squidward giving up. It typically contains the text describing the annoying person, event, or realization that ruins the initial plan and causes the disappointment.

This text box is placed next to the image of Squidward happily setting up his chair. It typically contains text describing a positive plan, a hopeful expectation, or an ideal situation that the user is looking forward to.

Squidward-chair.image_description: This two-panel meme features Squidward Tentacles from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants. In the top image, Squidward is happily setting up a blue lounge chair, ready to relax. In the bottom image, he looks dejected and annoyed as he carries the same chair back inside his house. The meme is used to contrast an initial hopeful plan or expectation with a subsequent disappointing reality or interruption that forces one to give up.

achievement-unlocked.name: achievement-unlocked

text_options.description: This large area below the notification banner is typically used for an image or text that provides context for the achievement. It visually depicts the situation or the person who has just 'unlocked' the achievement described in the banner above.
This text box contains the name of the custom achievement. It describes the specific, often mundane or funny, action that is being celebrated, serving as the core punchline of the meme.

achievement-unlocked.image_description: This meme features the 'Achievement Unlocked' notification pop-up from the Xbox 360 video game console. The template is used to humorously frame mundane, relatable, or unexpected real-life events as if they were significant in-game accomplishments. The humor arises from the contrast between the epic notification and the often trivial nature of the described 'achievement,' making it a popular reaction image or customizable template.

Galaxy-Brain-3-brains.name: Galaxy-Brain-3-brains

text_options.description: This bottom text box corresponds to the most illuminated, 'galaxy brain' image. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically an absurd, illogical, or hilariously unconventional take on the topic, presented as the highest level of enlightenment.

This middle text box corresponds to the brain with moderate activity. The text here represents a more nuanced, clever, or slightly unconventional idea that is a step up from the initial, simple concept.
This top text box corresponds to the simplest brain image. It typically contains a common, straightforward, or basic idea or action, setting the baseline for the meme's progression.

Galaxy-Brain-3-brains.image_description: This is the "Expanding Brain" or "Galaxy Brain" meme, a multi-panel exploitable format used to satirically compare different levels of intelligence or enlightenment regarding a certain topic. The meme progresses vertically, with each panel showing an increasingly illuminated and active brain, corresponding to a supposedly more profound or advanced idea. The humor often comes from the final panel, which presents an absurd, nonsensical, or comically over-the-top concept as the pinnacle of thought.

Normal-and-dark-mrincredibles.name: Normal-and-dark-mrincredibles

text_options.description: The text here, placed above the distorted, black-and-white image of Mr. Incredible, describes a negative, shocking, or horrifying situation. This represents the "uncanny" or traumatic realization that contrasts with the positive statement on the left, eliciting a horrified reaction.

The text in this position, above the normal, smiling Mr. Incredible, typically describes a positive, innocent, or desirable scenario. It sets up the initial, pleasant context before the horrifying reveal on the right.

Normal-and-dark-mrincredibles.image_description: This meme, known as "Mr. Incredible Becoming Uncanny" or "Traumatized Mr. Incredible," features two contrasting images of the character from Disney/Pixar's "The Incredibles." The left panel shows a normal, smiling Mr. Incredible, while the right panel shows a distorted, black-and-white, and unsettling version of him. The format is used to compare a positive or normal situation with a related, but deeply disturbing or negative realization, with the character's expression reflecting the tone of the accompanying text.

Giant-vs-man.name: Giant-vs-man

text_options.description: This label is placed on the small knight, representing the underdog or the person making a valiant but likely futile effort. Text here often describes a personal action, a small attempt, or the user themselves facing a larger challenge.

This label is placed on the massive Yhorm the Giant, symbolizing an overwhelming force, problem, or institution. The text here defines the challenge that the smaller entity is facing, highlighting the power imbalance and creating the humorous or relatable core of the meme.

Giant-vs-man.image_description: This meme format features artwork from the video game Dark Souls 3, depicting a small knight (the player character) facing the colossal boss, Yhorm the Giant. The stark contrast in size is used to represent an overwhelming challenge or an unequal confrontation. The small knight symbolizes a person or their minor effort, while the giant represents a massive, often insurmountable problem or entity they are facing.

Somehow-Palpatine-returned.name: Somehow-Palpatine-returned

text_options.description: This text, placed at the bottom, delivers the punchline. It provides an absurdly simple or nonsensical explanation for the problem presented in the top text, directly parodying the original line "Somehow, Palpatine returned."
The text at the top of the image sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a complex, confusing, or seemingly impossible event or problem that requires an explanation.

Somehow-Palpatine-returned.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the character Poe Dameron (played by Oscar Isaac) from the movie "Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker." The image is taken from the scene where he delivers the line, "Somehow, Palpatine returned," which was widely criticized by audiences as a lazy and nonsensical plot explanation. Consequently, the meme format is used to mock absurd, illogical, or overly simplistic explanations for complex or seemingly impossible situations.

Bad-Pun-Dog.name: Bad-Pun-Dog

text_options.description: This text box is in the bottom panel and delivers the pun or punchline of the joke. It aligns with the husky's wide, laughing expression, representing the teller's amusement at their own bad joke.
Positioned in the middle panel, this text introduces the second part of the setup, often a question that leads into the punchline. The dog's slight smile indicates the joke is building.
Located in the top panel, this text box contains the first part of the joke's setup. The dog's neutral expression corresponds to the beginning of the story or statement.

Bad-Pun-Dog.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as 'Bad Pun Dog' or 'Pun Husky,' features a Siberian Husky telling a cringeworthy joke or pun. The panels are read from top to bottom, with the dog's expression changing from neutral to a slight smile, and finally to an exaggerated, open-mouthed laugh. The format mimics the delivery of a classic 'dad joke,' where the teller finds their own pun hilarious, building up to the punchline in the final frame.

patrick-not-my-wallet.name: patrick-not-my-wallet

text_options.description: This label is on Patrick Star, who represents an individual or group being presented with something that belongs to them or is directly related to them.
This label is on Man Ray, who represents the person or entity trying to return an item or present a fact to the first individual.
This label is on Patrick, representing his initial, often confused, denial of the fact or ownership of the item.
This label is on Man Ray, showing his growing confusion and slight frustration as he insists on the truth.
This label is on Patrick, who now looks smug and confident in his continued denial.
This label is on Man Ray, who is now visibly angry and exasperated by Patrick's illogical stubbornness.
This label is on Patrick, representing the final, unwavering denial just before the conclusive proof is revealed.
This label is on Patrick's ID card inside the wallet. It serves as the punchline, representing the irrefutable proof or obvious truth that is being ignored.

patrick-not-my-wallet.image_description: This multi-panel meme, known as "Patrick's Wallet," features characters Patrick Star and Man Ray from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants. In the scene, the villain Man Ray is trying to return a lost wallet to Patrick, but Patrick repeatedly denies that it's his. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where someone stubbornly refuses to accept or acknowledge an obvious fact, identity, or piece of evidence, much to the frustration of the person presenting it.

even-harder.name: even-harder

text_options.description: This text box is placed in Michael Scott's dialogue. It represents the specific action that will be intensified in defiance of the warning in the top panel, completing the punchline 'I'm gonna [action] even harder'.
This text box is placed next to Pam, who is yelling. It typically labels the person, entity, or concept trying to stop the action, or it describes the initial action itself that is being discouraged.

even-harder.image_description: This two-panel meme features Pam Beesly and Michael Scott from the TV show 'The Office'. In the top panel, a distressed Pam yells at Michael to stop, representing an attempt to prevent or discourage an action. In the bottom panel, an angry and defiant Michael retorts that he will now do that action 'even harder', illustrating a situation where opposition only strengthens one's resolve, often out of stubbornness or spite.

Squidward-pointing.name: Squidward-pointing

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region describes the source of Squidward's (and the user's) panic. It represents the stressful reality, looming deadline, or unpleasant task that has just been realized.

The text in this top region typically labels the person or entity experiencing the panic, often starting with 'Me:'. It sets the context for the stressful realization described in the bottom text box.

Squidward-pointing.image_description: This meme features Squidward Tentacles from SpongeBob SquarePants looking up with a panicked and wide-eyed expression in a dark, red-hued room. The image captures a moment of sudden, dreadful realization or anxiety. It's typically used to represent someone confronting an overwhelming task, a looming deadline, or a stressful situation they had been ignoring.

Charlie-Day.name: Charlie-Day

text_options.description: This label identifies the person passionately explaining the convoluted theory. It represents the 'conspiracy theorist' or someone who is overthinking a situation and trying to connect unrelated things.
This text, placed over the conspiracy board, describes the subject of the wild theory. It's the topic or person that the character labeled '0' is obsessively trying to understand or explain.

Charlie-Day.image_description: This meme features Charlie Kelly from the TV show 'It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia' manically explaining a conspiracy theory. He stands in front of a corkboard covered in documents connected by red string, a scene famously associated with his rant about 'Pepe Silvia'. The image is used to humorously depict someone passionately explaining a complex, far-fetched, or nonsensical theory, often to an unimpressed or confused audience.

corporate-wants-you-to-find-the-differen.name: corporate-wants-you-to-find-the-difference

text_options.description: This box is placed on the picture on the right. It is one of the two subjects of comparison. Meme creators will overlay an image or text here representing one of the two things being humorously equated.

This box is placed on the picture on the left. It is the second subject of comparison. An image or text is placed here to be compared with the one in the other box, setting up the punchline that they are the same.

corporate-wants-you-to-find-the-differen.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the American sitcom 'The Office,' featuring the character Pam Beesly. In the first panel, an unseen person asks her to find the differences between two pictures, with the caption "Corporate needs you to find the differences between this picture and this picture." In the second panel, Pam deadpans to the camera, stating, "They're the same picture." The meme is used to humorously or critically assert that two different concepts, people, or things are functionally or essentially identical, despite appearing different.
corporate-wants-you-to-find-the-differen.display_name: corporate wants you to find the difference

X-All-The-Y.name: X-All-The-Y

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the object of the character's manic energy, completing the phrase. It most famously reads "ALL THE THINGS!" but can be substituted with any noun or concept to fit the context, such as "ALL THE COFFEE!" or "ALL THE CODE!".

The top text box sets up the meme by stating the action or verb that the character wants to perform with overwhelming enthusiasm. For example, it might say "CLEAN" or "DRINK," which is then followed by the object in the bottom text box.

X-All-The-Y.image_description: This meme, known as "X All The Y" or "All The Things," features a crudely drawn character from the webcomic "Hyperbole and a Half." The character, with a manic and wide-eyed expression, brandishes a broom, conveying an overwhelming and often irrational sense of enthusiasm or determination. The meme is used to humorously express a desire to perform an action on a massive, all-encompassing scale, often to the point of absurdity.

Lisa-Simpsons-Presentation.name: Lisa-Simpsons-Presentation

text_options.description: This text box is positioned on the stage floor next to Lisa Simpson. It is used to label the person or entity making the presentation, often representing the meme creator or a specific group they are channeling. This adds a layer of identity to the message being delivered.

This large area covers the projection screen, which is the central focus of the meme. The text placed here is the main statement or punchline—typically a controversial opinion, an unpopular fact, or a 'hot take' that is likely to be met with disagreement or shock, amplified by Lisa's serious expression.

Lisa-Simpsons-Presentation.image_description: This meme, known as "Lisa Simpson's Presentation," is an image macro from the animated TV show The Simpsons. It features the character Lisa Simpson on a stage, looking serious and concerned while pointing towards a large projection screen. The format is used to present a controversial opinion, a hard-to-swallow truth, or a bold statement that the creator believes needs to be said, with Lisa acting as the earnest messenger.

Peace-sign-tombstone.name: Peace-sign-tombstone

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Grant Gustin, the smiling figure. It is used to label the person, company, or concept that has triumphed over or replaced the entity represented by the gravestone. This is the 'victor' in the meme's narrative.

This text box is on the tombstone. It is used to label the person, idea, product, or institution that has 'died,' failed, or become obsolete. This represents the 'vanquished' party in the meme's scenario.

Peace-sign-tombstone.image_description: This meme, known as "Grant Gustin Next to Oliver Queen's Grave" or "Peace Sign at Grave," originates from a behind-the-scenes photo from the TV series "Arrow." It features actor Grant Gustin, who plays The Flash, smiling and flashing a peace sign while crouching next to the grave of Oliver Queen (Green Arrow). The meme's humor comes from the stark contrast between the somber setting of a funeral and Gustin's cheerful demeanor. It is used to represent someone celebrating the demise, failure, or replacement of a rival, an outdated concept, or a problem.

Daring-today-arent-we-squidward.name: Daring-today-arent-we-squidward

text_options.description: This final text box reveals the customer's ultimate decision. It contains the most common, predictable, or unoriginal choice, which serves as the punchline and justifies Squidward's sarcastic comments, "How original" and "Daring today, aren't we".

This box corresponds to the second stage of the customer's decision. The text here represents a slightly less original or more conventional option, showing the person's confidence wavering as they move towards a safer choice.

This text box is placed on the first panel of the customer's thought process. It typically contains an ambitious, unique, or interesting choice that the person is considering, setting up an expectation that will be subverted.

Daring-today-arent-we-squidward.image_description: This meme format, known as "How Original" or "Daring Today, Aren't We?", originates from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants. It features a fish customer at the Krusty Krab attempting to order, while the cashier, Squidward, reacts sarcastically. The meme is used to mock predictable, unoriginal, or "basic" choices by showing a progression from a potentially unique idea to a very common one, which is then ridiculed by Squidward's dialogue.

Cat-newspaper.name: Cat-newspaper

text_options.description: This is the punchline area, placed at the bottom of the image. It contains the contemplative or absurd thought of the cat, typically starting with "I should..." to convey a sudden realization or desire.
This top section provides the setup or context for the cat's thought. The text here describes a situation or event that prompts the sudden realization written in the bottom text, setting up the joke.

Cat-newspaper.image_description: This meme features a cat in a suit sitting at a table with a newspaper, looking thoughtfully into the distance. Known as the "I Should Buy a Boat Cat" or "Sophisticated Cat," this image captures a moment of sudden, often random or extravagant, realization. The meme is used to express an epiphany or a non-sequitur thought that occurs during a mundane moment, with the classic punchline being "I should buy a boat."

Average-Fan-vs-Average-Enjoyer.name: Average-Fan-vs-Average-Enjoyer

text_options.description: This text box is located above the "GigaChad" image. The text placed here represents the superior, based, or correct alternative to the subject in the other panel. It embodies the ideal behavior or viewpoint that the meme creator is endorsing, contrasting sharply with the negative example on the left.

This text box is positioned above the image of the angry young man. The text here typically describes a negative, foolish, or socially unacceptable action, opinion, or group. It represents the "wrong" or "cringe" side of the comparison, which is being mocked by the meme.

Average-Fan-vs-Average-Enjoyer.image_description: This is a two-panel comparison meme format that contrasts an angry-looking young man on the left with the idealized, muscular "GigaChad" on the right. The young man, often referred to as an "Angry Chav," represents a negative, weak, or foolish subject. In contrast, the black-and-white image of GigaChad represents a superior, positive, or "based" subject. The meme is used to express a strong preference for one idea, behavior, or group over another.

This-is-Worthless.name: This-is-Worthless

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Dipper's face. While not always used, it can be used to label Dipper as the person, group, or entity who finds the subject in box 1 to be worthless.

This is the primary editable area where the user places text or an image representing the subject of the meme. This subject is initially presented for consideration before being declared 'worthless' in the second panel.

This-is-Worthless.image_description: This two-panel meme features Dipper Pines from the animated show 'Gravity Falls' looking at a piece of paper. In the first panel, he seems intrigued, but in the second, he cheerfully declares, 'This is worthless!'. The format is used to humorously devalue or express disappointment in something, which is typically edited onto the blank paper. It's a popular reaction image for mocking things that are perceived as useless despite their presentation.

Hulk-Taco.name: Hulk-Taco

text_options.description: This text label is placed on the taco Hulk is holding. It represents the small, often insufficient, but well-intentioned gesture of comfort or help being offered. Examples include 'a pat on the back,' 'my condolences,' or 'a funny video.'

This label identifies Ant-Man, who represents the person or entity experiencing a significant problem, sadness, or loss. The text here describes the recipient of the small comfort, highlighting the scale of their issue.

This label is placed on Professor Hulk, who represents the person or entity offering the simple gesture of kindness. The text here identifies the well-meaning individual trying to help, whose solution is disproportionately small compared to the problem.

Hulk-Taco.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the movie 'Avengers: Endgame' and features Professor Hulk offering tacos to a dejected Ant-Man (Scott Lang). The first panel shows the interaction, while the second is a close-up of Hulk's offering. The meme is used to humorously depict a situation where someone offers a small, simple, and often inadequate gesture of kindness or a solution to someone facing a much larger, more complex problem.

Strong-dog-vs-weak-dog.name: Strong-dog-vs-weak-dog

text_options.description: This text box is positioned under Cheems, the smaller dog. It typically contains a label for the modern, weaker, or less impressive subject in the comparison. The text here often uses a simpler, sometimes intentionally misspelled style to emphasize its perceived inferiority.

Located under Swole Doge, the muscular dog, this text box is used to label the older, stronger, or more idealized version of the subject being compared. The text here represents the "glorious past" or the superior entity in the contrast.

Strong-dog-vs-weak-dog.image_description: This meme format, known as "Swole Doge vs. Cheems" or "Buff Doge vs. Cheems," presents a visual comparison between two Shiba Inu characters. On the left, Swole Doge is a large, muscular dog representing a superior, stronger, or glorified version of something, typically from the past. On the right, Cheems is a smaller, weaker-looking dog representing the current, inferior, or disappointing version of the same thing. The meme is used to humorously contrast a nostalgic past with a lackluster present, creating a "then vs. now" dynamic.

Giga-Chad.name: Giga-Chad

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the GigaChad's response. It is typically a short, simple, and confident statement that affirms his position without justification, such as "Yes," or a blunt summary of his actions. This text serves as the punchline, embodying the character's unbothered and superior attitude.

The top text area sets up the scenario. It usually contains a question, an accusation, or a complex explanation from another party, intended to challenge or question the GigaChad. This text provides the context for his simple and powerful response below.

Giga-Chad.image_description: This meme, known as "GigaChad" or "Yes Chad," features a black-and-white photograph of an extremely muscular man with a chiseled jawline. The character represents an idealized, hypermasculine archetype who is confident, unbothered, and superior. The meme is typically used in a two-panel format to contrast a complex question or criticism with GigaChad's simple, direct, and affirmative response, often just "Yes."

Bro-explaining.name: Bro-explaining

text_options.description: This label is placed over the woman who is the subject of the explanation. Text here represents the person, group, or concept that is being lectured or explained to, and who is typically portrayed as bored, unimpressed, or uninitiated in the topic at hand.

This label is placed over the man who is animatedly talking. Text here represents the person, group, or entity doing the explaining, often passionately and at great length, about a topic the other party finds uninteresting.

Bro-explaining.image_description: This meme, known as "Bro Explaining" or "Guy Explaining to His Girlfriend", features a man enthusiastically talking to a blonde woman who appears bored and uninterested at a sporting event. The format humorously represents a one-sided conversation where someone passionately explains a niche or complex topic to an unimpressed audience. The dynamic highlights the comedic gap between the speaker's passion and the listener's apathy.

Buzz-lightyear-clones.name: Buzz-lightyear-clones

text_options.description: This text is placed over the aisle of countless identical Buzz Lightyear toys. It serves as the punchline, representing the common, unoriginal, or widespread reality that deflates the uniqueness presented in the top panel.
This text is placed over the single, close-up shot of Buzz Lightyear. It typically describes a person, idea, or thing that is perceived as unique, special, or original, setting up the joke.

Buzz-lightyear-clones.image_description: This two-panel meme, also known as "Buzz Lightyear Aisle," originates from the 1999 film Toy Story 2. The top panel shows a close-up of the character Buzz Lightyear in his packaging, looking confident. The bottom panel reveals an entire store aisle filled with identical Buzz Lightyear toys. The meme is used to contrast something that someone believes is unique or original with the reality that it is actually very common, unoriginal, or ubiquitous.

Is-This-A-blank.name: Is-This-A-blank

text_options.description: This text box, placed after the words 'Is this', contains the incorrect label or misidentification. It serves as the punchline of the meme, revealing the character's flawed conclusion about the object represented by the butterfly.
Text here is placed over the butterfly to label the object, person, or concept that is being misunderstood or misidentified by the main character.
This text box is placed over the anime character's head to label the person or group who is making the incorrect assumption or misidentification.

Is-This-A-blank.image_description: This meme, known as 'Is this a pigeon?', features a screenshot of the android character Yutaro Katori from the anime 'The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird'. In the original scene, he gestures towards a butterfly and incorrectly identifies it. The meme format is used to humorously depict someone misinterpreting or mislabeling a person, object, or concept, often due to ignorance or a flawed perspective.

Im-going-to-change-the-world-For-the-bet.name: Im-going-to-change-the-world-For-the-better-right-Star-Wars

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Padmé's concerned expression in the final panel. The text here is typically a silent repetition of her earlier question, often just the word '...Right?', now filled with dawning horror or realization. It serves as the punchline, confirming that her optimistic assumption was wrong.

Positioned over a smiling Padmé, this text box contains her optimistic and often naive follow-up question to Anakin's statement. It typically takes the form of a hopeful assumption, seeking confirmation, and famously ends with the word 'Right?'.

This text box, placed over Anakin's initial panel, contains the setup for the joke. It's a statement made by Anakin that is often ambitious or seemingly positive, which prompts Padmé's hopeful question in the next panel.

Im-going-to-change-the-world-For-the-bet.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "For the Better, Right?" or the "Anakin and Padmé" meme, originates from a scene in Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones. The format depicts a conversation where Anakin Skywalker makes a statement, and Padmé Amidala responds with a hopeful, clarifying question, smiling. The punchline is delivered through the final two panels, where Anakin's silent, intense stare is followed by Padmé's smile vanishing, indicating a grim or unsettling truth. The meme is used to humorously contrast an optimistic expectation with a dark or disappointing reality.
Im-going-to-change-the-world-For-the-bet.display_name: Im going to change the world For the better right Star Wars

Calculating-meme.name: Calculating-meme

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically presents the confusing, illogical, or complex situation that is causing the person's bewilderment. It's the punchline or the core problem that the subject of the meme is trying to process.

This top text area usually serves as a label to identify the person or entity experiencing the confusion. It often starts with a simple identifier like "Me:" or describes the subject, setting the context for who is reacting to the situation described below.

Calculating-meme.image_description: The "Math Lady" or "Confused Lady" meme features Brazilian actress Renata Sorrah with a perplexed expression, surrounded by floating mathematical equations and formulas. The image visually represents a state of intense mental calculation, deep thought, or confusion. It is typically used to humorously illustrate someone trying to understand a complex, contradictory, or nonsensical situation.

Arm-wrestling-meme-template.name: Arm-wrestling-meme-template

text_options.description: This central area, placed over the clasped hands, contains the text for the shared belief, goal, or characteristic that unites the two parties. It acts as the punchline of the meme, revealing the surprising common ground between the two otherwise disparate groups labeled on the arms.

This text label, positioned over the white bicep, identifies one of the two groups or individuals. This group is typically distinct from or in opposition to the one labeled on the other arm, setting up the humorous contrast with their shared agreement.

This text label, positioned over the Black bicep, identifies the second group or individual. This entity is set up as a counterpart to the one labeled on the opposite arm, creating the dynamic where their eventual agreement is unexpected and comical.

Arm-wrestling-meme-template.image_description: The "Epic Handshake" meme shows a close-up of two muscular arms, one Black and one white, clasped in a powerful handshake. Originating from a scene in the 1987 film "Predator" featuring Arnold Schwarzenegger and Carl Weathers, the image is used to represent an unexpected agreement or shared trait between two otherwise different or opposing groups. The two arms represent the distinct entities, while the handshake symbolizes their surprising common ground, which serves as the punchline.

First-time.name: First-time

text_options.description: This label is placed on the calm, smirking man. The text here identifies the veteran or experienced individual who is unfazed by the dire situation, having been through it or something similar many times before.

This label is placed on the distressed, crying man. The text here identifies the novice or newcomer who is experiencing the difficult situation for the first time and is reacting with appropriate panic or complaint.

First-time.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'First Time?', originates from the 2018 film 'The Ballad of Buster Scruggs.' The top panel shows a man crying in distress at the gallows, while the bottom panel shows a calm, smirking man (played by James Franco) also about to be hanged, who asks, 'First time?'. The meme is used to humorously contrast an experienced person's nonchalance with a newcomer's panic when facing a shared difficult situation.

Swimming-Pool-Kids.name: Swimming-Pool-Kids

text_options.description: This label is placed on the skeleton at the bottom of the pool. It represents something that has been completely forgotten, abandoned, or neglected for so long that it is beyond saving. This is the final, most extreme level of neglect in the meme's hierarchy.
This label is placed on the woman in the pool. It typically represents the person, company, or entity that is giving out attention or resources unequally, setting up the premise of the meme.
This label is placed on the happy child being held up by the woman. It represents the person, task, or item that is receiving all the positive attention and favor, often at the expense of others.
This label is placed on the struggling child in the foreground. It represents something that is being actively neglected, is in trouble, or requires immediate attention but is being ignored.

Swimming-Pool-Kids.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format known as "Mom Drowning Kid" or "Skeleton at the Bottom of the Pool." The top panel shows a woman in a pool happily holding one child while another child struggles to stay afloat nearby. The bottom panel reveals a skeleton sitting in a chair at the bottom of the water.
