The meme is used to humorously represent different levels of priority, where one thing is favored, another is neglected, and a third is completely forgotten and metaphorically "dead."

Why-would-they-do-this.name: Why-would-they-do-this

text_options.description: This label is on Eric Andre in the bottom panel after he has committed the act. The text here represents the perpetrator feigning shock and asking a rhetorical question like "Why would X do this?" to deflect blame for the problem they just created.
This label is on Eric Andre in the top panel as he holds the smoking gun. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is actively causing a problem or harming something/someone.
This label is on Hannibal Buress, who has just been shot and is slumping in his chair. The text here identifies the victim, the concept, or the thing being harmed or destroyed by the entity in box 1.

Why-would-they-do-this.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Who Killed Hannibal?" or "Why Would X Do This?", originates from a skit on "The Eric Andre Show." In the top panel, host Eric Andre shoots his co-host Hannibal Buress. The bottom panel shows Eric Andre turning to the camera with a shocked expression, as if questioning who is responsible. The meme is used to satirize situations where an entity causes a problem and then feigns ignorance or blames an external factor for the negative consequences.

iceberg.name: iceberg

text_options.description: This area at the very bottom of the iceberg represents the most obscure, esoteric, disturbing, or speculative information about a topic. It's the final, deepest layer, containing theories or facts known only to the most dedicated experts or theorists.

This area at the top represents the "tip of the iceberg," containing the most well-known, surface-level information about a given topic. The text here describes concepts that are common knowledge or easily understood by a general audience.

iceberg.image_description: This is the "Iceberg" or "Iceberg Tiers" meme format, which uses an image of an iceberg to illustrate that a topic has more depth than is immediately apparent. The small, visible tip represents common, surface-level knowledge, while the vast, submerged portion represents increasingly obscure, complex, or disturbing information. This format is popular for creating tiered lists that explore the hidden depths of various subjects, from video games and movies to conspiracy theories.

Spiderman-Glasses.name: Spiderman-Glasses

text_options.description: Text in this box represents the moment of clarity or the superior concept. It's the punchline that reveals the 'correct' or more insightful perspective after metaphorically putting on the glasses.
Text in this box represents a blurry, incorrect, or less desirable idea. It sets up the premise or the 'before' state, which is then clarified or improved upon in the panel below.

Spiderman-Glasses.image_description: This two-panel meme features Tobey Maguire as Peter Parker from the 2002 film 'Spider-Man'. In the top panel, he is taking off his glasses with a blurred view, and in the bottom panel, he puts them on to see clearly. The meme is used to represent a moment of realization or clarity, where the top image represents a flawed, inferior, or misunderstood idea, and the bottom image represents the correct, superior, or true version.

man-taking-a-stand-in-a-town-hall-meetin.name: man-taking-a-stand-in-a-town-hall-meeting

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the audience members who are looking up at the speaker. It is used to label the group that disapproves of or is angered by the opinion being shared. Common labels include "The internet," "My friends," or any specific community, framing them as the opposition to the speaker's 'truth'.

This text box is positioned above the speaker's head, in the empty space of the blackboard. This is where the user's unpopular or controversial opinion is written. The placement directly attributes the statement to the brave speaker, making it the central focus and punchline of the meme.

man-taking-a-stand-in-a-town-hall-meetin.image_description: This meme is based on Norman Rockwell's 1943 painting "Freedom of Speech." It depicts a man standing to speak his mind at a town meeting, while others in the audience look on. In meme culture, the standing man represents a person bravely sharing a controversial or unpopular opinion, while the audience represents the disapproving majority or society at large. The format is used to frame a personal "hot take"—often humorous or trivial—as a profound truth that others are not ready to accept.
man-taking-a-stand-in-a-town-hall-meetin.display_name: man taking a stand in a town hall meeting

Crying-Hulk.name: Crying-Hulk

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the Hulk's crying face. It typically contains text that reveals the user's true, often sensitive or sad, inner feelings, which directly contradicts the tough exterior presented in the top panel. This is the punchline, exposing the vulnerability behind the facade.

This text box is placed over the Hulk's muscular back. It usually describes a situation where the user is putting on a tough, angry, or unbothered front. This text establishes the external persona of strength that is being projected.

Crying-Hulk.image_description: This two-panel meme features the Marvel superhero, the Hulk, to contrast outward appearance with inner feelings. The top panel shows the Hulk's incredibly muscular back, representing a facade of strength, anger, or toughness. The bottom panel is a close-up of his face with a tear running down his cheek, revealing his true feelings of sadness or vulnerability. The meme is used to express a disconnect between how one presents themselves and their actual emotional state, often in a humorous or relatable way.

PAtrick-Smart-Dumb.name: PAtrick-Smart-Dumb

text_options.description: This text, placed over the image of Patrick with a board nailed to his head, describes the simple, foolish, or actual action taken by someone. It serves as the punchline, contrasting with the more sophisticated idea in the top panel and representing the comically inept reality.

This text, positioned over the 'Scientist Patrick' image, describes a complex, intelligent, or ideal way to approach a problem. It sets up the joke by establishing the 'correct' or sophisticated method that will be contrasted with the simple-minded action in the panel below.

PAtrick-Smart-Dumb.image_description: This two-panel meme features Patrick Star from SpongeBob SquarePants to contrast a complex versus a simple approach to a task. The top panel shows 'Scientist Patrick' looking intelligent and analytical, representing the sophisticated or correct way of doing something. The bottom panel shows regular Patrick with a board nailed to his head, representing a foolish, simplistic, or incorrect method. The meme is used to highlight the difference between an ideal solution and a comically inept execution, often for self-deprecating humor.

Now-Thats-What-I-Call.name: Now-Thats-What-I-Call

text_options.description: This box contains the punchline of the meme, replacing the original word 'MUSIC' and its volume number. Users write the subject of their fake compilation here, such as 'Anxiety' or 'Bad Decisions', often including a number to complete the album parody.

This box contains the first word of the phrase, originally 'NOW'. This word is often edited to set up the punchline, for instance, changing it to 'WOW' or another emphatic word that fits the new theme.

Now-Thats-What-I-Call.image_description: This meme format is based on the logo for the 'Now That's What I Call Music!' series of compilation albums. The template is used to humorously re-brand a collection of related items, experiences, or feelings as a 'greatest hits' album. Users replace the original words to create a satirical title, applying the cheerful, commercialized branding of pop music to often mundane, niche, or negative topics for comedic effect.

Atlas-holding-Earth.name: Atlas-holding-Earth

text_options.description: This text label is placed on the rock Atlas is kneeling on. It represents the single, often underappreciated person or thing that is the sole foundation supporting the entire system above. This is the punchline, revealing the surprisingly small or simple base for a complex structure.

This text label is placed over the celestial sphere that Atlas is holding up. It describes a large, complex, or important system, community, or concept. This part of the meme sets up the context of what is being supported by the single entity below.

Atlas-holding-Earth.image_description: This meme features an illustration of the Greek Titan Atlas, a muscular figure, kneeling on a rock and straining to hold up the celestial sphere on his shoulders. The image is typically used as a three-panel exploitable meme format, although here it's a single image divided into sections. It humorously illustrates a situation where a single, often overlooked person, concept, or piece of code is single-handedly supporting a much larger, complex system.

Maja-Salvador-Hair-Commercial.name: Maja-Salvador-Hair-Commercial

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the woman's face, delivers the punchline or the harsh, contradictory reality. This text shatters the initial assumption made in the top text, often beginning with or implying the phrase "Akala mo lang 'yun" (You just think that).

The top text, placed above the woman's face, sets up the meme by presenting an initial, often optimistic or naive, assumption, belief, or situation. This is the statement that will be humorously contradicted by the bottom text.

Maja-Salvador-Hair-Commercial.image_description: This meme features Filipina actress Maricar Reyes-Poon with a shocked and horrified expression, taken from a hair product commercial. Known as the "Akala Mo Lang 'Yun" (You Just Think That) meme, it's used to represent a sudden, unpleasant realization that contradicts a previous assumption. The format typically presents a positive or confident statement, followed by a harsh reality that shatters that belief, with the actress's face serving as the reaction to this revelation.

Leave-Britney-Alone.name: Leave-Britney-Alone

text_options.description: The bottom text contains the punchline, which is almost always a variation of the original quote, "LEAVE [X] ALONE!". The "[X]" is replaced with the subject mentioned in the top text, delivering the meme's signature dramatic and defensive plea.
The top text area introduces the subject or situation that is being criticized or misunderstood, prompting the emotional outburst seen in the image. It acts as the setup for the punchline below.

Leave-Britney-Alone.image_description: This meme features a still image of vlogger Chris Crocker emotionally crying from their 2007 viral YouTube video, "LEAVE BRITNEY ALONE!". In the video, Crocker passionately defends pop star Britney Spears from media scrutiny, pleading for people to stop criticizing her. The meme is used to express an exaggerated, desperate plea or to satirize overly emotional reactions to criticism of a beloved person, thing, or concept.

Cool-Cat-Stroll.name: Cool-Cat-Stroll

text_options.description: This bottom text box is the punchline, describing the confident action or destination of the subject (represented by the cat). It often starts with phrases like "Me on my way to..." to directly link the text to the cat's strut, showing a proud or determined response to the situation described in the top text.

The top text box provides the setup or context for the meme. It typically describes a situation, a command, or a piece of information that prompts the confident strut from the cat. This text establishes the reason for the subject's proud or purposeful action.

Cool-Cat-Stroll.image_description: This meme, known as "Strutting Cat" or "Cat Walking," features a small tabby kitten walking with an exaggerated, confident strut. The image is used to humorously depict someone feeling proud, self-assured, or on their way to do something specific, often with a sense of purpose or mischief. The format typically presents a scenario in two parts, with the top text providing context and the bottom text describing the confident action represented by the cat.

Riley-Reid-meme.name: Riley-Reid-meme

text_options.description: This bottom text area is less commonly used in this specific meme format, as the image itself is the primary reaction. When used, it typically labels the person reacting (e.g., "Me:") to clarify who is experiencing the emotion depicted.

The top text sets up the entire premise of the meme. It describes an awkward, regrettable, or painful situation that the viewer is meant to relate to, to which the woman's expression serves as the reaction.

Riley-Reid-meme.image_description: This meme features a still image of adult film actress Riley Reid with a pained or distressed expression. The image is used as a reaction to represent feelings of intense regret, discomfort, or realizing a terrible mistake has been made. It's typically paired with a caption describing a relatable but unfortunate scenario, with her face serving as the punchline or emotional response.

Army-clown.name: Army-clown

text_options.description: This label is placed on the clown. The text here identifies the person, group, or idea that is comically out of place, foolish, or unprepared for the serious situation depicted by the soldiers.
This label is placed on the group of soldiers. The text here represents the serious context, the competent group, or the high-stakes situation that makes the clown's presence so absurd and humorous.

Army-clown.image_description: This meme, known as 'Clown in a War Zone,' features a person in a full clown costume standing alongside heavily armed soldiers in a combat environment. The stark contrast between the comical, out-of-place clown and the serious, prepared soldiers creates a humorous and absurd visual. The format is used to represent someone who is hilariously unprepared, foolish, or doesn't belong in a serious or high-stakes situation, contrasting them with the competent majority.

society-if.name: society-if

text_options.description: This lower portion of the image is part of the visual punchline and typically contains no text. It showcases the idyllic ground-level aspects of the utopian society, such as pristine parks and advanced personal transport, reinforcing the perfect world that has been achieved.

This is the primary location for the meme's text. The caption usually starts with a phrase like "Society if..." or "The world if..." followed by a condition that, if fulfilled, would lead to the utopia shown. This text sets up the entire premise of the joke.

society-if.image_description: This meme, known as "Society If" or "The World If," depicts a utopian futuristic city with flying cars, sleek architecture, and a clean environment. The image is used to humorously suggest what the world would look like if a particular problem, annoyance, or minor inconvenience were solved. The joke lies in the extreme, positive transformation of society resulting from a single, often trivial, change.

Silent-Movie-Card.name: Silent-Movie-Card

text_options.description: This small area in the bottom-right corner is typically used for a watermark, a signature, or a secondary, less important caption. It's not the main focus of the meme and is often left blank.

This is the main text area where a phrase indicating a passage of time is placed. Common examples from the source material include 'A few moments later' or 'One eternity later,' but users often create custom, sarcastic, or humorous time-related captions to set up a joke.

Silent-Movie-Card.image_description: This meme template features a silent film intertitle card with an ornate, vintage border on a black background. It originates from the animated series 'SpongeBob SquarePants,' where these cards are used as a comedic device to signify a passage of time. The format is used online to humorously narrate a situation, often with exaggerated time skips like 'One Eternity Later' to build up a punchline or express impatience.

Soyjak-Pointing.name: Soyjak-Pointing

text_options.description: This bottom caption area typically contains the name of a product, brand, or piece of media that the characters are excitedly reacting to. It serves as the punchline, revealing the object of their over-the-top enthusiasm. The humor often arises from the mundane or corporate nature of the subject.

The top text box serves as a label for the subject of the meme. The pointing character directs the viewer's gaze towards this area, which identifies the product, concept, or media that is eliciting the strong, often ironic, reaction from the two figures.

Soyjak-Pointing.image_description: This meme, known as "Two Soyjaks Pointing," features two crudely drawn Wojak-style characters with open mouths, expressing exaggerated excitement or shock. The character on the right points towards something, drawing the viewer's attention to it. This format is typically used to satirize or mock consumerism and hype culture, where the characters represent overly enthusiastic fans reacting to new products, media, or trends.

Gravestone.name: Gravestone

text_options.description: This is the main face of the gravestone. Text placed here represents the person, concept, or thing that is being declared 'dead' or obsolete, serving as the punchline of the meme.

This area above the gravestone is often used for a caption or title that provides context or sets up the joke. It might describe the 'cause of death' or the situation that rendered the subject on the tombstone irrelevant.

Gravestone.image_description: The 'Gravestone' meme features a blank, grey granite tombstone in a cemetery setting. This versatile template is used to humorously declare something as 'dead,' obsolete, or no longer relevant. Users edit text onto the gravestone to name the person, concept, or trend they are comically eulogizing.

You-guys-are-getting-paid-template.name: You-guys-are-getting-paid-template

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Kenny (Will Poulter), who has a confused and slightly hurt expression. This is the punchline of the meme, revealing that this person/group is receiving nothing or is completely unaware that a benefit was being offered. The text is often phrased as a question, like "You guys are getting [X]?"

This text box is over Casey (Emma Roberts). It represents the third person in the comparison, who is receiving a small or meager benefit, significantly less than the first two. This builds the comedic tension leading to the final punchline.

This text box is over Rose (Jennifer Aniston). The text here describes the second person or group in the comparison, who is receiving a decent but lesser benefit than the first. It continues the downward trend of rewards.

This text box is placed over David (Jason Sudeikis). The text here typically represents the person or group receiving the most significant benefit or reward, setting the high bar for the comparison that follows.

You-guys-are-getting-paid-template.image_description: This is a four-panel meme from the 2013 film "We're the Millers," featuring the main cast in a car. The characters, from top-left to bottom-right, are David (Jason Sudeikis), Rose (Jennifer Aniston), Casey (Emma Roberts), and Kenny (Will Poulter). The meme format is used to compare different groups' experiences or rewards for the same task, with each character receiving progressively less, culminating in Kenny's character revealing he received nothing at all. The punchline, often a variation of "You guys are getting paid?", expresses surprise and dismay at being left out or treated unfairly.
You-guys-are-getting-paid-template.display_name: You guys are getting paid template

Robotnik-Button.name: Robotnik-Button

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or entity making the impulsive choice. It's placed over Dr. Robotnik, whose enthusiastic expression provides the punchline, showing the subject's delight in choosing the less sensible option.
Text here describes the sensible, logical, or responsible choice. It's placed on the label above the blue button that the hand in the comic is about to press.

Text here describes the impulsive, chaotic, or tempting but ultimately worse choice. It's placed on the label above the red button, which is the option enthusiastically chosen by the character in the bottom panel.

Robotnik-Button.image_description: A two-panel meme format combining the "Daily Struggle" two-button comic with a still of Dr. Robotnik from the "Sonic the Hedgehog" movie. The top panel shows a hand hesitating over a blue button, ignoring a red one, representing a choice between a sensible option and an impulsive one. The bottom panel shows Dr. Robotnik, played by Jim Carrey, gleefully and emphatically pressing a red button, signifying the enthusiastic choice of the impulsive or chaotic option.

Talking-to-wall.name: Talking-to-wall

text_options.description: This label is placed on the man who is speaking. The text here identifies the person or group making a futile argument or explanation.

This label is placed on the brick wall. The text here identifies the unresponsive person, group, or abstract concept that is the target of the argument, highlighting their refusal or inability to listen or comprehend.

Talking-to-wall.image_description: This meme, known as 'Talking to a Brick Wall,' features a man passionately arguing with a brick wall. It originates from a YouTube video and is used to humorously depict the futility of trying to reason with someone who is unresponsive, stubborn, or incapable of understanding. The man represents the person making a point, while the wall symbolizes the unhearing audience, making the effort pointless.

Me-And-The-Boys.name: Me-And-The-Boys

text_options.description: This area across the characters' chests represents the subjects of the meme, implicitly labeled as 'Me and the boys'. While often left blank, this space identifies the group of friends who are about to engage in the activity described in the top caption.

The top caption box is where the main text of the meme is placed. It describes the activity that 'Me and the Boys' are doing, which is typically something mundane, silly, or wholesome. The humor comes from the contrast between the villainous appearance of the characters and the innocent or goofy nature of the described action.

Me-And-The-Boys.image_description: This meme, known as 'Me and the Boys,' features four supervillains from the 1960s Spider-Man cartoon: Rhino, Vulture, Electro, and Green Goblin. The characters are depicted smiling together, representing a group of friends embarking on a shared activity. The meme's humor arises from contrasting the villains' menacing looks with a caption describing a mundane, wholesome, or silly group activity.

Poke-with-stick.name: Poke-with-stick

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which typically serves as the punchline or the main, often absurd or unexpected, statement of the meme. Its position at the bottom provides the final word that recontextualizes the setup text and the image.
This is the top text, which functions as the setup or premise for the joke. It establishes a context or asks a question that the bottom text will answer or subvert.

Poke-with-stick.image_description: This meme features the character "Dick Butt," a crudely drawn anthropomorphic phallus. Originating from a webcomic, Dick Butt became a classic internet troll meme, often used as a bait-and-switch punchline or hidden in images to surprise the viewer, similar to a Rickroll. The image macro format allows for a setup and a punchline, where the humor comes from the absurdity of the character combined with the text.

orangutan-interview.name: orangutan-interview

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the news desk's lower third, where a news headline or ticker would normally be. This is where the punchline of the meme is written, famously "Where banana?", representing the simple, absurd, or primal question that the orangutans are focused on.

Text placed in this upper region typically provides context or sets up the joke. It might describe a complex, serious, or modern problem that the orangutans are comically ignoring in favor of the simple question presented in the box below.

orangutan-interview.image_description: This meme, known as "Where Banana?" or "Monke," features three orangutans sitting at a news desk as if they are news anchors. The image is a still from a video where the orangutans are comically dubbed over. It's used to express a simple, primal desire or a simplistic question in a complex situation, often humorously portraying a group as unintelligent, confused, or focused on a single, basic need.

willem-dafoe-looking-up.name: willem-dafoe-looking-up

text_options.description: This text box is at the bottom of the image, representing the person or group pleading or making a request. The text here sets up the scenario, often from a position of weakness or desperation, aligning with Dafoe's upward gaze.

This text box is at the top, representing the higher power, authority, or concept being appealed to. The text here often provides a response, a judgment, or simply identifies the entity being looked up to, completing the meme's narrative.

willem-dafoe-looking-up.image_description: A close-up shot of actor Willem Dafoe from the film 'The Lighthouse,' looking upwards with a desperate and pleading expression. This meme, known as 'Willem Dafoe Looking Up,' is used to depict someone begging or appealing to a higher power or authority figure. The humor arises from applying this dramatic scene to relatable, often trivial, everyday situations.

Cuphead-Flower.name: Cuphead-Flower

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to the calm, smiling flower. The text placed here describes a standard, acceptable, or preferred scenario that elicits a positive or neutral reaction. It sets up the comparison for the punchline in the top panel.

This text box corresponds to the enraged flower. The text here describes a frustrating, annoying, or triggering situation that causes the extreme negative reaction shown in the image. This serves as the punchline, revealing what makes the subject 'snap'.

Cuphead-Flower.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Cagney Carnation, a flower boss from the video game Cuphead, which is known for its 1930s cartoon art style. The bottom panel shows Cagney with a sweet, innocent smile, while the top panel depicts him in a fit of rage, screaming aggressively. The meme format contrasts these two reactions to highlight a significant shift in demeanor, typically used to show a calm response to one situation versus an extreme, angry overreaction to a similar but more frustrating one.

Limmy-waking-up.name: Limmy-waking-up

text_options.description: This bottom text box delivers the punchline or the harsh reality that causes the man's distressed expression. Positioned near his body, it represents the direct, often blunt, and unwelcome truth that has just dawned on him, contrasting sharply with the setup in the top text.

This top text box sets up the scenario, often describing a seemingly normal or hopeful situation, a question, or an internal monologue. It represents the moment just before the unpleasant realization hits.

Limmy-waking-up.image_description: This meme, known as 'Limmy Wakes Up' or 'Wrong House,' features Scottish comedian Limmy with a pained expression while lying in bed as someone points at his chest. The image captures a moment of sudden, jarring realization or waking up to an unpleasant or awkward situation. It's commonly used to express regret, anxiety, or the dawning horror of a bad decision from the night before.

okay-grandpa-lets-get-you-to-bed.name: okay-grandpa-lets-get-you-to-bed

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the walker and the men's feet, labeling the support system or foundation that the struggling entity relies on. This is often an object, concept, or another entity that is supposed to be helpful but is depicted as equally weak, outdated, or part of the overall problem, reinforcing the theme of a failing system.

This area covers both the 'helper' (middle-aged man) and the 'struggling entity' (elderly man). Text is usually placed over each person to identify them. The elderly man is labeled as something failing or outdated, while the man helping him is labeled as an entity that is ironically supposed to be the solution or support, creating the central joke of the meme.

okay-grandpa-lets-get-you-to-bed.image_description: This meme, often called "Help Is On The Way, Dear!" or "Old Man With Walker," features a stock photo of a middle-aged man helping an elderly man with a walker. The elderly man represents something weak, struggling, or outdated, while the younger man symbolizes a force that is supposedly helping but is often ineffective or part of the problem. This format is used to humorously critique failing systems, outdated technologies, or flawed support structures, where the "solution" is just as problematic as the issue it's meant to solve.
okay-grandpa-lets-get-you-to-bed.display_name: okay grandpa lets get you to bed

What-if-i-told-you.name: What-if-i-told-you

text_options.description: This is the bottom text line, which serves as the punchline of the meme. It contains the surprising revelation or counter-intuitive fact that challenges the reader's assumptions, completing the thought started in the top line.
This is the top text line, which typically contains the setup phrase for the meme. It almost always reads, "What if I told you," posing a hypothetical question to the audience.

What-if-i-told-you.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Morpheus, a character from the film *The Matrix*, portrayed by Laurence Fishburne. He is depicted as a wise mentor figure, wearing his signature rimless sunglasses. The meme format, known as "What If I Told You," is used to present a surprising or mind-bending revelation that challenges a commonly held belief. Despite the meme's popularity, the phrase "What if I told you" is a misquote and is never actually said by Morpheus in the movie, adding a layer of irony to its use.

Virgin-vs-Chad.name: Virgin-vs-Chad

text_options.description: This area is located under the 'Chad' character. It typically contains a specific, often exaggeratedly positive or absurd action, trait, or name associated with the 'Chad' side of the comparison. This text highlights the perceived superiority of the subject being praised.

This area is located under the 'Virgin' character. It typically contains a specific, often mundane or negative action, trait, or name associated with the 'Virgin' side of the comparison. This text highlights the perceived inferiority of the subject being criticized.
This text box is a header placed above the 'Chad' character. It's used to label the superior or preferred subject of the comparison, often formatted as 'The Chad [Subject]'.
This text box is a header placed above the 'Virgin' character. It's used to label the inferior or less desirable subject of the comparison, typically formatted as 'The Virgin [Subject]'.

Virgin-vs-Chad.image_description: This is the 'Virgin vs. Chad' meme format, a popular exploitable template used for comparison. It contrasts two subjects: the 'Virgin' on the left, depicted as a slouching, awkward man, representing something inferior or undesirable, and the 'Chad' on the right, a hyper-masculine, confident figure, representing the superior or desirable counterpart. The meme humorously exaggerates the perceived flaws of one subject and the strengths of another, creating a stark and often absurd dichotomy.

Oliver-Twist-Please-Sir.name: Oliver-Twist-Please-Sir

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region represents the humble or desperate plea from the person represented by Oliver Twist. It's the punchline of the meme, specifying what the user wants 'more' of, often something funny, absurd, or highly desirable.

The text in this top region typically identifies the person, entity, or situation that has provided something. This sets up the context for the request that follows, representing the authority figure or source from which more is desired.

Oliver-Twist-Please-Sir.image_description: This meme features a still of the character Oliver Twist from the 1968 film 'Oliver!', based on the Charles Dickens novel. In the scene, the young, impoverished orphan holds out his empty bowl and famously asks for more food. The image is used as a reaction meme to express a desire or plea for more of something, often in a humorous or relatable context.

Hypnotize.name: Hypnotize

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the spiral, this text box contains the punchline or the "hypnotic suggestion." It's typically an absurd, funny, or revealing statement that the viewer is supposedly being convinced to accept, often starting with "You want to...".

Positioned at the top of the spiral, this text serves as the setup for the joke. It usually poses a question or makes a statement about a common belief, preference, or identity, which is then humorously reinterpreted by the text at the bottom.

Hypnotize.image_description: This meme features a classic black and white hypnotic spiral, a visual trope used to represent mind control or a trance-like state. Known as the "You want to kiss boys, don't you?" or "Hypno-spiral" meme, it humorously suggests someone is being persuaded into admitting a hidden desire or belief. The format typically presents a statement at the top that is then twisted into an absurd or funny conclusion at the bottom, as if hypnotizing the reader into agreement.

Who-wants-change.name: Who-wants-change

text_options.description: This speech bubble in the bottom panel contains the unpopular or controversial statement that serves as the punchline. The text here is designed to be something that instantly kills the crowd's enthusiasm from the first panel, resulting in awkward silence.

This speech bubble in the top panel contains a popular, agreeable, or crowd-pleasing statement. The text here sets up the joke by showing something that everyone enthusiastically supports, creating a stark contrast with the second panel.

Who-wants-change.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, often called 'Politician Speech' or 'Who's with me?', depicts a speaker at a podium addressing a crowd. In the top panel, the speaker makes a statement that elicits enthusiastic agreement from the crowd, who all raise their hands. In the bottom panel, the speaker makes a second, contrasting statement that is met with dead silence and disapproval, humorously emphasized by a lone cricket. The meme is used to highlight hypocrisy or to contrast a popular opinion with a subsequent unpopular or controversial one.

Angela-scared-Dwight.name: Angela-scared-Dwight

text_options.description: This label is placed on Angela Martin, who is observing Dwight. The text here typically represents a secondary element, such as a person, an institution, or a concept that is watching the main subject's actions, often with a neutral or unimpressed expression. Angela's label can represent the cause of the situation or simply a bystander to the impending failure.

This label is placed on Dwight Schrute, the central figure of the meme. The text here represents the protagonist of the scenario—the person, group, or idea that is initially confident, happy, or optimistic. Dwight's character is the one who experiences the sudden, negative turn of events depicted in the second panel.

Angela-scared-Dwight.image_description: This two-panel meme features Dwight Schrute and Angela Martin from the TV show 'The Office'. In the top panel, Dwight looks happy and confident next to Angela in an arcade setting. The bottom panel shows his abrupt shift to panic and dismay as he brushes his shoulder and exclaims "F**k". The meme is used to illustrate a scenario where initial confidence or a positive situation is quickly shattered by a harsh realization or an immediate negative outcome.

Why-is-my-sisters-name-Rose.name: Why-is-my-sisters-name-Rose

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. The text inserted here is the son's name, which humorously reveals what the father loves. This is the main customizable part of the meme, where users insert funny, absurd, or niche references.
This text specifies the object that the mother loves, which corresponds to the sister's name mentioned in the first line. In the original meme, this word is "roses".

This is the sister's name, which sets up the premise of the joke. The son asks why his sister has this particular name, leading to the reveal of the family's naming convention. In the original meme, the name is "Rose".

Why-is-my-sisters-name-Rose.image_description: This is a "Dad Joke" meme format, also known as "No Problem, X". The image features a stock photo of a smiling father and son in a car, creating a wholesome atmosphere. The text above sets up a dialogue where a son asks why his sister is named Rose, and the dad explains it's because their mother loves roses. The punchline comes when the son says "Thanks Dad," and the dad replies, "No Problem," followed by a blank space for the son's name, implying the son is named after something the dad loves.
Why-is-my-sisters-name-Rose.display_name: Why is my sisters name Rose

Big-dog-small-dog.name: Big-dog-small-dog

text_options.description: This text box is associated with Cheems, the weaker dog on the right. It typically contains a description of the inferior or current version of the subject being compared, often written with Cheems' characteristic speech impediment (adding the letter 'm' to words).

This text box is associated with Swole Doge, the muscular dog on the left. It contains the description of the superior or past version of the subject, presented as powerful and impressive to contrast with Cheems' description.
This text box serves as a label for Cheems, the weaker dog. It usually contains a word like "Then," a specific year, or a group name to set the context for the inferior side of the comparison.

This text box is the label for Swole Doge, the stronger dog. It typically contains a word like "Now," a specific year, or a group name that represents the superior side of the comparison, directly contrasting with the label in box 2.

Big-dog-small-dog.image_description: This meme, known as "Swole Doge vs. Cheems," features a visual comparison between two Shiba Inu characters. On the left is Swole Doge, a muscular and confident version of the classic Doge meme character, representing something strong, superior, or from a glorified past. On the right is Cheems, a smaller, sadder-looking Shiba Inu, representing a weaker, inferior, or disappointing present-day version. The meme is used to humorously contrast two related subjects, often highlighting a perceived decline in quality or strength over time.

Thats-my-secret.name: Thats-my-secret

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, corresponding to Bruce Banner's reveal. It typically starts with "That's my secret, Cap..." followed by the surprising or absurd 'secret,' which is often a constant state of being (e.g., "I'm always tired").

The top text box sets up the joke by posing a question or statement, often from an unseen character like Captain America. This text asks how the subject (represented by Banner) is able to do something difficult or maintain a certain state (e.g., "How are you always ready for exams?").

Thats-my-secret.image_description: This is the "That's My Secret, Cap" meme, featuring Bruce Banner (played by Mark Ruffalo) from the 2012 film "The Avengers." In the scene, Banner stands amidst the destruction of the Battle of New York and reveals his secret to controlling his transformation into the Hulk. The meme format uses this moment to humorously reveal an unexpected or constant underlying state as the "secret" to achieving something, often with a sarcastic or relatable twist.

Mel-Gibson-and-Jesus-Christ.name: Mel-Gibson-and-Jesus-Christ

text_options.description: This label is placed on the actor portraying Jesus. The text here represents a person, group, or entity that has undergone a significant hardship, a painful experience, or a very complicated situation and is now trying to explain it.

This label is placed on director Mel Gibson. The text here represents the person, group, or entity listening to the explanation. This character is often the cause of the suffering, someone who doesn't understand the gravity of the situation, or simply the recipient of a long, complex story.

Mel-Gibson-and-Jesus-Christ.image_description: This meme features a behind-the-scenes photo from the film "The Passion of the Christ," showing director Mel Gibson talking to actor Jim Caviezel, who is in full costume as a bloodied and beaten Jesus Christ. The stark contrast between the suffering figure of Jesus and the casually dressed director creates a humorous dynamic. The meme is typically used to represent a scenario where someone who has gone through a difficult or absurd ordeal (Jesus) is explaining it to someone who is either responsible, oblivious, or simply listening (Gibson).

X-but-Y.name: X-but-Y

text_options.description: This text is placed on the blank presentation board. It contains the core idea or punchline of the meme, which Don Draper is supposedly pitching. This text is typically a simple, obvious, or humorous statement presented as a groundbreaking concept.
This text labels Don Draper, identifying the person, group, or entity making the presentation. It sets up who is pitching the idea shown on the board, adding another layer of context to the joke.

X-but-Y.image_description: This meme features Don Draper, the protagonist from the TV series Mad Men, giving a presentation. He stands confidently in a suit next to a blank presentation board, gesturing as if pitching a brilliant idea. The format is used to present a simple, obvious, or sometimes absurd concept as if it were a profound and innovative revelation, creating a humorous contrast between the serious presentation style and the mundane content.

Twilight-Aro.name: Twilight-Aro

text_options.description: This text, positioned in the lower half of the image, describes the person or action being judged. It serves as the punchline, revealing the often trivial or relatable reason for the intense scrutiny from the figures above.

This text, placed above the characters' heads, identifies the group or entity that is doing the judging. It sets up the premise by establishing the source of the condescending gaze, representing an authority figure or a peer group.

Twilight-Aro.image_description: This meme features the Volturi coven from the movie series *Twilight*, with the leader Aro in the center, flanked by Caius and Marcus. The characters are depicted with a condescending and judgmental gaze, looking down from a balcony. This image is used to humorously represent a group or individual judging someone for their actions, tastes, or habits, often contrasting the characters' dramatic authority with mundane situations.

let-me-in.name: let-me-in

text_options.description: This label is placed on Eric Andre's chest in the bottom panel, where he is screaming. The text here represents the person, group, or entity that is desperately demanding access or inclusion.

This label is placed on Eric Andre's chest in the top panel, where he is calm. The text here represents the same person, group, or entity from the bottom panel, but at the stage of making a polite, initial request.

This label is placed over the fence that is blocking Eric Andre. The text here represents the group, place, company, or concept that is denying entry or that the subject desperately wants to be a part of.

let-me-in.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Let Me In," features comedian Eric Andre from "The Eric Andre Show." In the top panel, he calmly asks to be let through a metal fence, with the caption "Let me in." The bottom panel shows him screaming and shaking the fence in desperation, with the caption "LET ME IIIIIIIIIN!". The meme is used to humorously depict a strong, often escalating desire to gain access to something, join a group, or obtain a desired object or outcome.

schefter-template.name: schefter-template

text_options.description: This is the main content area of the tweet where users insert their own fabricated text. The text is typically formatted to mimic a serious news announcement, often starting with 'BREAKING:' or citing sources. The humor of the meme is derived from the absurd or comical nature of the fake news placed in this box, contrasting with the legitimate source it appears to come from.

schefter-template.image_description: This meme is a blank tweet template from the Twitter account of Adam Schefter, a prominent ESPN NFL insider known for breaking major news stories, often called 'Schefter Bombs.' The format leverages Schefter's credibility to create humorous, fake news announcements. Users edit text into the blank space to fabricate absurd or comical 'breaking news' reports, playing on the expectation of legitimate information from his account.

Oops-All-Berries.name: Oops-All-Berries

text_options.description: This area, covering the bowl of cereal, is often edited to label the individual items that make up the whole. It serves as a visual representation of the concept introduced in the main text, showing a container full of whatever the punchline is.

This is the core punchline of the meme. The original word "Berries" is replaced with a word or phrase describing the single, overabundant element in a given situation, setting up the joke that the situation is "Oops! All [that thing]."

Oops-All-Berries.image_description: This meme is an exploitable template based on the box art for Cap'n Crunch's "Oops! All Berries" cereal. The original cereal's premise is a box accidentally filled with only the popular berry-shaped pieces. In the meme, the word "Berries" is replaced to humorously describe a situation that is overwhelmingly composed of a single, often negative or absurd, element.

It-aint-much-but-its-honest-work.name: It-aint-much-but-its-honest-work

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the fixed text "It ain't much, but it's honest work." This phrase conveys a sense of humble pride and satisfaction in the action described in the top panel, framing it as a worthwhile, albeit modest, effort.

This top section is a blank space where the user adds text describing a simple, often mundane or unimpressive, action or accomplishment. This text sets up the context for the punchline below, representing the "honest work" that is being celebrated.

It-aint-much-but-its-honest-work.image_description: This meme, known as "It Ain't Much, But It's Honest Work," features a screenshot of American farmer Dave Brandt. He is depicted outdoors in a field, wearing a plaid shirt, denim overalls, and a cap, with a gentle, sincere expression. The meme is used to express pride in a task or accomplishment that may seem small or unimpressive to others but is considered worthwhile and genuine by the person who did it.
It-aint-much-but-its-honest-work.display_name: It aint much but its honest work

Homer-Simpson-sleeping-peacefully.name: Homer-Simpson-sleeping-peacefully

text_options.description: This text label is placed on Homer's body, which is cozily tucked under the blankets. It identifies the person or entity that is comfortably and blissfully ignoring the problem or chaos described in the text above.

Positioned above the sleeping Homer, this text describes a stressful situation, a pressing responsibility, or a chaotic event. This creates a humorous contrast with Homer's peaceful state, emphasizing his ignorance or indifference to the issue.

Homer-Simpson-sleeping-peacefully.image_description: This meme, known as "Homer Simpson in Bed" or "Cozy Homer," features the character from "The Simpsons" sleeping soundly. The image humorously represents a state of blissful ignorance, comfort, and satisfaction. It is typically used to contrast a person who is comfortably ignoring their responsibilities or a chaotic situation with the problem itself.

Cars-Passing-Each-Other.name: Cars-Passing-Each-Other

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Number Five. It typically represents one side of a dichotomy or conflict, often the more established or traditional viewpoint. The character's surprised expression reflects the sudden encounter with an opposing idea.

This text box is placed over Vanya/Viktor. It represents the opposing or contrasting idea, person, or group to the one labeled in box 0. The shared look between the characters creates the core of the meme: a brief, mutual acknowledgment of two different worlds or perspectives colliding.

Cars-Passing-Each-Other.image_description: This meme format originates from a scene in the Netflix series "The Umbrella Academy," featuring characters Number Five and Vanya/Viktor Hargreeves. The image shows the two characters driving in separate cars, passing each other and sharing a look of surprise and recognition. The meme is used to represent two opposing ideas, groups, or individuals who briefly acknowledge each other's existence before continuing on their separate, often conflicting, paths.

Blackjack-and-Hookers.name: Blackjack-and-Hookers

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom contains Bender's defiant punchline. It's a declaration of creating a superior alternative to something he was excluded from, often following the phrasal template, "Fine, I'll build my own [X]... with blackjack and hookers!" This text represents the core comedic reaction of the meme.

The top text box sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a scenario of rejection, exclusion, or being told something is not allowed. This text provides the necessary context for Bender's boastful and spiteful reaction in the bottom text.

Blackjack-and-Hookers.image_description: This meme features the character Bender from the animated show Futurama, dressed in a white fur coat and pointing forward with a smug, determined expression. The format, known as "I'm Gonna Build My Own Theme Park," is used to express a defiant and over-the-top reaction to being excluded or denied something. Typically, the top text describes the rejection, and the bottom text is Bender's boastful plan to create his own, superior version of whatever he was denied, famously concluding with "...with blackjack and hookers."

OMG-hi.name: OMG-hi

text_options.description: This text box, positioned above the happy stick figure, typically contains the name of a person, often a crush or someone the figure admires. It represents the simple, positive stimulus that cuts through the mental chaos. The surrounding text "omg" and "hi!!!" emphasizes the excited and flustered reaction to this person.

Located within the chaotic scribbles of the top panel, this text box represents the overwhelming and complex inner thoughts of the stick figure. It is often blacked out or filled with dense, unreadable text to symbolize the mental noise, anxiety, and overthinking that the character is experiencing.

OMG-hi.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format illustrating the contrast between a person's chaotic inner thoughts and their simple, happy reaction to a positive stimulus. The top panel shows a stick figure engulfed in dense scribbles, representing anxiety, overthinking, or mental clutter. The bottom panel depicts the same stick figure, now blushing and happy in a clear space, reacting to a simple interaction, showing how a small positive event can instantly clear one's mind.

Guess-Ill-die.name: Guess-Ill-die

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over the man's hands, serves as the punchline. It almost always begins with "Guess I'll..." followed by a resigned action or outcome, such as "Guess I'll die." This text represents the subject's reluctant acceptance of their fate in response to the situation described above.

The top text, placed above the man's head, sets up the premise of the meme. It describes an unfortunate, ironic, or difficult situation that the subject is facing, which prompts their resigned reaction.

Guess-Ill-die.image_description: This meme features András Arató, also known as "Hide the Pain Harold," in a stock photo where he is shrugging with his palms up. The image, often called "Shrug" or "Guess I'll Die," is used to express resignation, helplessness, or passive acceptance in the face of an undesirable or absurd situation. The shrug and facial expression perfectly convey a feeling of giving up or having no better option. The meme format typically presents a problematic scenario followed by a reluctant or fatalistic conclusion.

is-calling-you.name: is-calling-you

text_options.description: This is the primary text area where the caller's name appears. In the meme, this is replaced by a person, concept, or situation the creator finds challenging or wants to avoid, such as 'My Responsibilities', 'Anxiety', or 'Adulthood'.

This smaller text field, positioned above the main caller ID, typically adds context or a secondary punchline. It might describe the nature of the call or the caller, for instance, 'calling again' or 'work', to amplify the joke established in the main text box.

is-calling-you.image_description: This meme template uses a screenshot of an iPhone's incoming call screen, presenting a choice between 'Accept' and 'Decline'. The format humorously personifies an abstract concept, an unwanted responsibility, or a difficult situation as the caller. The meme's core idea is framing a complex dilemma as the simple, relatable act of deciding whether to answer an undesirable phone call.

Shrek-For-Five-Minutes.name: Shrek-For-Five-Minutes

text_options.description: This label is placed near Donkey, who is the target of Shrek's laser-eyed rage. The text here identifies the person, entity, or action that is ignoring the request made in the top panel, thereby causing the extreme frustration.

This text is placed over Shrek in the top panel. It represents the initial, exasperated plea or request made by the user. It's often a variation of the original quote, asking something or someone to stop a particular annoying behavior.

Shrek-For-Five-Minutes.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the movie "Shrek 2." The top panel shows the character Shrek pleadingly asking, "Can you just be yourself... FOR FIVE MINUTES?" The bottom panel is an edited image showing Shrek with glowing red laser eyes staring intensely at the character Donkey. The meme is used to express extreme frustration when a simple request is repeatedly ignored, with Shrek representing the annoyed person and Donkey representing the persistent source of the annoyance.

Farquaad-Pointing.name: Farquaad-Pointing

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It represents the selfish, callous, or hypocritical statement, revealing the "sacrifice" the speaker is willing to let others make for their own benefit.

The top text box is used to set up the scenario or context. It typically describes a problem or a situation that affects a group of people, creating the premise for the selfish resolution that follows.

Farquaad-Pointing.image_description: This meme features Lord Farquaad from the animated movie Shrek, pointing forward with a smug and dismissive expression. The image is taken from a scene where he callously declares, "Some of you may die, but it's a sacrifice I am willing to make." The meme is used to humorously represent someone making a selfish or cold-hearted statement, showing a blatant disregard for the well-being of others for their own minor gain or convenience.

Stop-Hes-Already-Dead.name: Stop-Hes-Already-Dead

text_options.description: This area, covering the people beating Krusty, is labeled with the person, group, or entity delivering the excessive criticism or attack. They represent the aggressor who is continuing to pile on someone who is already down.

This area, covering the defeated Krusty the Clown on the ground, is labeled with the subject being mercilessly attacked or criticized. This represents the victim of the overkill, the one who is "already dead" in an argument, competition, or public opinion.

Stop-Hes-Already-Dead.image_description: This two-panel meme from "The Simpsons" shows horrified children in the top panel reacting to a scene below where Krusty the Clown is being beaten while already lying on the ground. The caption "STOP HE'S ALREADY DEAD" expresses the core sentiment of the meme. It is used to humorously comment on a situation where someone or something is being excessively criticized, attacked, or roasted long after they have already been defeated or have suffered enough, highlighting the overkill.

our.name: our

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below Bugs Bunny, delivers the punchline. It typically starts with the word "Our" followed by the same noun used in the top text, comically correcting the notion of individual ownership and imposing collective ownership.

The top text serves as the setup for the joke. It usually presents a statement of personal possession, often starting with "My" or "I have," which is then humorously challenged by the meme's punchline.

our.image_description: This meme, known as "Communist Bugs Bunny" or "Our Meme," features the Looney Tunes character Bugs Bunny with a smug expression, superimposed over the Soviet hammer and sickle. The format is used to humorously reframe a statement of individual possession (e.g., "my girlfriend") into one of collective ownership (e.g., "our girlfriend"). Bugs Bunny's confident pose adds to the comedic effect of unexpectedly enforcing a communist-style sharing of a personal item or concept.

Man-giving-sword-to-larger-man.name: Man-giving-sword-to-larger-man

text_options.description: Text in this position, placed directly on the sword, describes the 'gift' itself. This is the central object, skill, or piece of knowledge being transferred from the powerful figure to the recipient, and it often serves as the punchline of the meme.

Text here labels the kneeling knight, who is the recipient of the sword. This is typically used to represent 'me', a specific person, or a group that is receiving the power, burden, or knowledge from the larger entity.

Text in this area labels the giant, powerful figure. This character represents the source of the 'gift'—it could be a person, an organization, a concept, or an abstract force that is bestowing the item on the knight.

Man-giving-sword-to-larger-man.image_description: The 'Master's Blessing' meme features a giant, shadowy figure with glowing eyes bestowing a large sword upon a kneeling knight. The dramatic, red-toned image is used to represent a powerful entity or concept giving a tool, ability, or piece of information to a smaller, less powerful entity. The humor often arises from the specific, niche, or absurd nature of the 'gift' being transferred.
Man-giving-sword-to-larger-man.display_name: Man giving sword to larger man

Bush-Learning-About-911.name: Bush-Learning-About-911

text_options.description: This label is placed on President George W. Bush. It typically represents the person or entity receiving the 'news,' often labeled simply as 'Me.' Their serious expression is meant to contrast with the usually trivial information being delivered.

This label is placed over Andrew Card, who is whispering the news. The text here is the punchline, representing the trivial, absurd, or pop-culture-related information being delivered with utmost seriousness, contrasting with the historical gravity of the original moment.

Bush-Learning-About-911.image_description: This meme features a famous photograph of White House Chief of Staff Andrew Card whispering into President George W. Bush's ear. The original photo captures the moment Bush was informed of the second plane hitting the World Trade Center on 9/11. In meme culture, this format is used to humorously convey trivial, absurd, or shocking pop culture news, with Bush's somber expression representing an overly serious reaction to the information.

Pretending-To-Be-Happy-Hiding-Crying-Beh.name: Pretending-To-Be-Happy-Hiding-Crying-Behind-A-Mask

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains a short, often cheerful or dismissive phrase that the person is saying out loud. This text represents the 'mask' and is what they present to the world, such as 'I'm fine' or 'lol same', directly contrasting their inner turmoil.

The top text box is used to describe the underlying cause of the character's sadness or frustration. This caption provides the context for the hidden pain, explaining the difficult situation or internal thoughts that the person is struggling with.

Pretending-To-Be-Happy-Hiding-Crying-Beh.image_description: This meme features a Wojak character, also known as Feels Guy, who is crying profusely but holding a simple, smiling mask over his face. This image is a popular reaction meme used to represent someone hiding their true feelings of sadness, pain, or distress behind a facade of happiness or contentment. It powerfully conveys the concept of internal suffering while maintaining a brave or cheerful exterior for the public.
Pretending-To-Be-Happy-Hiding-Crying-Beh.display_name: Pretending To Be Happy Hiding Crying Behind A Mask

You-wouldnt-X-a-Y.name: You-wouldnt-X-a-Y

text_options.description: This text box is for a noun, which serves as the object of the verb in the first part of the sentence. In the meme, this noun is often something absurd or impossible to physically steal, completing the parody of the original anti-piracy ad's logic (e.g., "You wouldn't download a car").

This text box is for a verb that replaces the original verb "steal." The humor of the meme comes from inserting a mundane, silly, or specific action here to create a ridiculous comparison, mocking the serious tone of the source material.

You-wouldnt-X-a-Y.image_description: This meme format originates from the "Piracy. It's a Crime." anti-piracy public service announcements from the early 2000s. The original ads featured the phrase "You wouldn't steal a car..." to equate digital piracy with physical theft. The meme, known as "You Wouldn't Steal a Car," parodies this by replacing the original actions with absurd, humorous, or mundane ones to satirize the ad's dramatic tone and logical fallacy.

Hey-Guys---NOT-WHAT-IM-CALLED.name: Hey-Guys---NOT-WHAT-IM-CALLED

text_options.description: This area identifies the person, group, or concept being mislabeled. They are the subject of the meme who is being pointed at and who rejects the label from box 1.
This text box is for the incorrect, unwanted, or stereotypical label being applied to the character in box 0. The entire premise of the meme revolves around the content of this box being a misnomer.

Hey-Guys---NOT-WHAT-IM-CALLED.image_description: This meme, known as "Not What I'm Called," features a simple line drawing of one character pointing at another. The pointing character is applying a label to the other, who is implicitly rejecting it with the pre-written text "NOT WHAT I'M CALLED." The format is used to humorously or critically highlight instances where a person, group, or thing is given a name or stereotype they do not identify with.
Hey-Guys---NOT-WHAT-IM-CALLED.display_name: Hey Guys   NOT WHAT IM CALLED

morpheus-matrix-blue-pill-red-pill.name: morpheus-matrix-blue-pill-red-pill

text_options.description: This text label is placed over the hand holding the blue pill. It represents the 'blue pill' option: the choice to remain in blissful ignorance, accept the status quo, or take the easier, more comfortable path. The text here describes the less challenging or conventional of the two choices presented in the meme.

This text label is placed over the hand holding the red pill. It represents the 'red pill' option: the choice to accept a harsh or inconvenient truth, embrace a difficult reality, or see the world in a new, often challenging way. The text here describes the more profound, difficult, or eye-opening choice.

morpheus-matrix-blue-pill-red-pill.image_description: This meme features Morpheus from the movie 'The Matrix' offering a choice between two pills. In a stylized, mostly black-and-white image, he holds out a blue pill in one hand and a red pill in the other. The meme, known as 'Red Pill / Blue Pill,' is used to present a choice between a comfortable, ignorant falsehood (the blue pill) and a difficult, life-changing truth (the red pill). It's a versatile format for framing any binary choice where one option is easy and the other is revealing or challenging.
morpheus-matrix-blue-pill-red-pill.display_name: morpheus matrix blue pill red pill

Greedy-Pipe-Man.name: Greedy-Pipe-Man

text_options.description: The text over the large, well-fed man identifies the entity that receives the vast majority of the resource or benefit. This is the group or individual that is being favored or is hoarding the subject matter.
The text over the small, emaciated man represents the entity that is being deprived or neglected. This group or individual receives only a tiny, insufficient fraction of the resource.
The text on the large pipe identifies the resource, benefit, or attention that is being unequally distributed. This is the central subject of the meme's comparison.

Greedy-Pipe-Man.image_description: This is a political cartoon meme depicting a stark contrast in resource allocation. A large, well-dressed man greedily consumes a massive flow of water from a pipe, while a small, emaciated man below struggles to catch a few leaking drops. The meme is used to criticize and highlight extreme inequality, where one entity receives an overwhelming majority of benefits, resources, or attention, leaving very little for another deserving entity.

Kratos-and-my-life-is-yours.name: Kratos-and-my-life-is-yours

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a declaration of despair or defeat. It often contains the phrase "The gods have abandoned me" or a similar statement that reflects Kratos's anguished expression, humorously contrasting the dramatic reaction with the situation described above.
The top text box sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes a frustrating, disappointing, or inconvenient situation that serves as the cause for Kratos's dramatic reaction.

Kratos-and-my-life-is-yours.image_description: This meme features Kratos from the video game series God of War, specifically from a scene in God of War III where he is falling. Kratos is shown looking upwards with an expression of anguish and despair, his arms outstretched. The meme, often called "Kratos Falling" or "The Gods Have Abandoned Me," is used to express dramatic and exaggerated frustration or disappointment over a relatable, often trivial, problem.
Kratos-and-my-life-is-yours.display_name: Kratos and my life is yours

Chapelle-crack.name: Chapelle-crack

text_options.description: The bottom text, which is the punchline of the meme. It typically contains the phrase "Y'all got any more of that..." followed by the object of intense desire. This text directly voices the craving that the character's desperate expression represents.

The top text, which sets up the scenario or context for the craving. It usually describes a situation where someone has just finished something enjoyable and is left wanting more, such as finishing a great book or a season of a TV show.

Chapelle-crack.image_description: This meme features comedian Dave Chappelle as his character Tyrone Biggums from "Chappelle's Show." The character, a crack addict, is shown looking desperate and scratching his neck, a signature nervous tic. The meme, often captioned "Y'all Got Any More of That," is used to humorously express an intense craving or addiction to something, whether it's a new season of a TV show, a type of food, or any other desirable item.

Spongebob-looking-out-window.name: Spongebob-looking-out-window

text_options.description: This text box is placed over SpongeBob and Patrick, who are playing outside. It is used to label the people, events, or situations that are being enjoyed by others, representing the source of fun or success that the observer (Squidward) is missing out on.

This text box is placed over Squidward, who is inside looking out. It represents the person or entity who is feeling left out, sad, or resentful while watching others have a good time. This label identifies the subject of the meme's FOMO or longing.

Spongebob-looking-out-window.image_description: This meme, known as 'Squidward Watching SpongeBob and Patrick' or 'Squidward Looking Through Blinds,' originates from the cartoon *SpongeBob SquarePants*. It depicts the grumpy character Squidward looking out from his dark house through blinds at SpongeBob and Patrick having fun outside. The format is widely used to express feelings of FOMO (fear of missing out), jealousy, or being an outsider observing others enjoying themselves.

fat-guy-drinking-water.name: fat-guy-drinking-water

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the large, well-dressed man. It is used to label the powerful or privileged entity that is receiving the vast majority of the resource. This could be a large corporation, a government, or a favored group.

Located over the small, impoverished figure, this text identifies the disadvantaged party. This typically represents the general public, small businesses, or any group that is neglected or receives only a tiny fraction of the available resource.

This label is on the pipe from which the resource flows. The text here defines the resource itself that is being distributed unfairly, such as money, government aid, opportunities, or media attention.

fat-guy-drinking-water.image_description: This meme, originating from a political cartoon, depicts a stark contrast in resource distribution. A large, wealthy-looking man greedily drinks from a large pipe, while a small, emaciated man catches only a few drops. The meme is used to criticize situations of extreme inequality, where a powerful entity monopolizes resources, leaving very little for the common person or less-privileged groups.

No-Soup-For-You.name: No-Soup-For-You

text_options.description: This area over the counter typically represents the person, group, or idea that is being denied something or is the subject of a strict rule.
This label is placed on the Soup Nazi character, representing the authority figure, person, or entity that is enforcing a strict rule and denying something to the subject labeled in box 0.

No-Soup-For-You.image_description: This meme features the character Yev Kassem, famously known as the "Soup Nazi" from the 90s sitcom Seinfeld. In the show, he strictly enforces a set of ordering rules at his soup stand, and if anyone breaks them, he shouts his catchphrase, "No soup for you!" and refuses service. The meme is used to humorously depict a person, company, or any authority figure strictly denying something to someone else, often for arbitrary or rigid reasons.

John-Daly-and-Tiger-Woods.name: John-Daly-and-Tiger-Woods

text_options.description: This label is placed on golfer John Daly, whose flamboyant outfit and casual demeanor represent a chaotic, unconventional, or 'whatever works' approach. The text here describes the less serious or more maverick of the two subjects being compared.

This label is placed on golfer Tiger Woods, whose professional attire and athletic posture represent the serious, optimized, or 'by-the-book' method. The text here describes the ideal, standard, or more disciplined of the two subjects being compared.

John-Daly-and-Tiger-Woods.image_description: This meme features a photo of professional golfers Tiger Woods and John Daly on a golf course, creating a stark visual contrast. Tiger Woods (left) is dressed in sleek, professional athletic wear, while John Daly (right) sports colorful pants and smokes a cigarette. The meme uses this dichotomy to compare two opposing ways of approaching something: the serious, optimized method (Woods) versus the chaotic, unconventional, but often equally effective method (Daly).

spongebob-stupid.name: spongebob-stupid

text_options.description: This area at the bottom typically labels the subject of the meme, often starting with 'Me:', to identify the person or group feeling overwhelmed by the stressors listed above.

This top section is where the various stressors, tasks, or anxious thoughts are listed, often in a chaotic or overlapping manner. This text represents the overwhelming source of the panic that SpongeBob is experiencing.

spongebob-stupid.image_description: This meme, known as 'Exhausted SpongeBob' or 'Panicking SpongeBob,' features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the eponymous animated series. He has a wide-eyed, frantic expression, looking completely overwhelmed and panicked. The format is used to humorously depict feelings of extreme stress, anxiety, or being inundated with tasks and responsibilities.

Show-me-on-this-doll.name: Show-me-on-this-doll

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It's typically a variation of the phrase, 'Show me on this doll where the [person/thing] touched you,' directly referencing the subject introduced in the top text.
The top text box is used to introduce the person, thing, or situation that has supposedly caused harm, offense, or distress. This sets up the context for the punchline below.

Show-me-on-this-doll.image_description: This meme comes from the animated show South Park, featuring a lawyer holding a featureless doll while the school counselor, Mr. Mackey, looks on with concern. The scene originally involves the lawyer asking a character to point on the doll where a 'bad man' touched them. The meme is used humorously to mock overreactions or to sarcastically ask someone to pinpoint the source of a minor or metaphorical harm.

Fake-search.name: Fake-search

text_options.description: This large, empty area represents the search results. Its blankness is the punchline of the meme, visually confirming that the query entered in the search bar (box 1) yielded zero results, emphasizing the non-existence of the searched topic.

The text in the search bar is the setup for the joke. This is where a user types a query for something they believe is impossible, non-existent, or absurdly specific, setting the expectation that Google will find no matches.

Fake-search.image_description: This meme format uses a screenshot of a Google search page, often in dark mode, to create a joke. A user inputs a humorous, absurd, or impossible search query into the search bar. The punchline is the empty results page, signifying that what was searched for does not exist, which is used to make a statement about the non-existence or rarity of a particular thing or concept.

disappearing.name: disappearing

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the bottom of the image, spanning the initial and final panels. It typically describes the awkward or uncomfortable situation that prompts the person to want to disappear or leave.
Located at the top of the image over the person, this text box labels the individual or entity that is disappearing. This is the subject who is reacting to the situation described in the bottom text.

disappearing.image_description: A three-panel meme known as "Disappearing Guy" or "Peace Sign Guy Fading." The first panel shows a young Black man in a black polo shirt giving a peace sign with a concerned look. In the second panel, he begins to fade away, and in the third, he has vanished completely, leaving only the background. This meme humorously illustrates someone wanting to awkwardly or abruptly exit an uncomfortable, embarrassing, or undesirable situation.

Tyrone-Biggums-The-Addict.name: Tyrone-Biggums-The-Addict

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the object of the intense craving. It completes the phrase started in the top box, revealing what the person is desperately seeking, which is typically something relatable or humorous like 'weekend,' 'motivation,' or a specific food.

The top text box typically contains the first part of the catchphrase, "Y'all got any more of that..." This text sets up the meme's premise, establishing the desperate, questioning tone of someone fiending for something.

Tyrone-Biggums-The-Addict.image_description: This meme features a close-up of comedian Dave Chappelle as his character Tyrone Biggums from 'Chappelle's Show'. The character, a crack addict, is shown with a desperate expression, scratching his neck and looking up, wearing a red beanie with white residue around his mouth. The meme, known as "Y'all Got Any More of That," is used to humorously express an intense craving or addiction for something, often mundane items or concepts, by framing the desire in the context of a drug addict's desperation.

Hand-on-shoulder-guy.name: Hand-on-shoulder-guy

text_options.description: This bottom section typically contains the simple, often bewildered or dismissive response of the person being explained to. It's usually a very short phrase or a single word that contrasts sharply with the detailed explanation above, serving as the punchline.

The top section is where the long, detailed, and often convoluted explanation is placed. This text represents the passionate monologue about a niche or complex topic, corresponding to the character on the left who is animatedly speaking.

Hand-on-shoulder-guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Me Explaining to My Mom" or "Gundam explanation," originates from the anime series Mobile Suit Gundam. It features the character Ramba Ral (left) with a smug expression, seemingly explaining something complex to another person (right, mostly off-screen), while Amuro Ray (center) looks on. The format humorously contrasts a long, passionate explanation of a niche topic with a simple, often confused or dismissive response, highlighting a communication breakdown.

Sun-Tzu.name: Sun-Tzu

text_options.description: This text box contains the attribution for the quote, almost always credited to "- Sun Tzu, The Art of War". This attribution is essential for the meme's punchline, as it frames the absurd quote from the top box as a piece of profound military strategy, maximizing the comedic contrast.

This is the primary text area where a fake, humorous, or anachronistic quote is placed. The quote is designed to sound like ancient wisdom at first glance but is revealed to be nonsensical or modern, creating the core humor of the meme.

Sun-Tzu.image_description: This meme features a black and white image of a Terracotta Army soldier, often misidentified as the ancient Chinese general Sun Tzu. The format is used to present fake, often humorous or absurd quotes attributed to Sun Tzu, playing on the perceived wisdom of the figure from "The Art of War."
