The humor comes from the stark contrast between the soldier's stoic, ancient appearance and the modern, nonsensical, or comically obvious "proverb" presented as ancient wisdom.

Not-sure-if--fry.name: Not-sure-if--fry

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which completes the thought started at the top. It typically begins with 'or just...' and presents the second, often more cynical or self-deprecating, possibility that Fry is considering. This line serves as the punchline, creating the humorous or relatable conflict.

The top text of the meme, which introduces the first part of a dilemma or question. It almost always starts with 'Not sure if...' followed by a description of a situation or observation. This sets up the internal conflict that Fry's expression conveys.

Not-sure-if--fry.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Philip J. Fry from the animated series 'Futurama' with a suspicious, squinting expression. Known as 'Futurama Fry' or 'Not Sure If,' the meme is used to express internal debate or uncertainty between two conflicting possibilities. The format typically follows a 'Not sure if X, or just Y' structure, where X is a hopeful or naive interpretation and Y is a more cynical or realistic one.

Rick-and-Carl.name: Rick-and-Carl

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Carl in the bottom panel and typically contains the first part of the dad joke's punchline. Carl's annoyed or embarrassed expression is a direct reaction to hearing this terrible pun.

Positioned next to Rick in the bottom panel, this text box contains the second part of the punchline, completing the awful pun. Rick's pained, laughing expression is meant to accompany his delivery of this line.
This text box, placed over Carl in the top panel, contains the first part of the joke's setup. It's usually a question or statement from Rick directed at Carl to begin the joke.

Located next to Rick in the top panel, this text box contains the second part of the joke's setup. It continues the line from the previous box, completing the question or statement that baits the punchline.

Rick-and-Carl.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Rick Grimes' Dad Joke" or "Carl!", originates from the TV show The Walking Dead. It features Rick Grimes telling a terrible pun to his son, Carl, who reacts with disappointment. The top panel is used for the joke's setup, while the bottom panel delivers the cringeworthy punchline, showing Rick's pained laughter and Carl's shame. The humor comes from placing a corny dad joke within the show's grim, post-apocalyptic setting.

I-heart.name: I-heart

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the bottom and is the punchline or the main subject of the meme. The text here completes the phrase "I love [text]", specifying the person, place, thing, or concept the creator loves. This is the core customizable element of the meme.

This text box at the top of the image typically contains a setup, a preceding thought, or a contextual statement. It often adds a layer of humor or irony by providing a backstory or reason for the declaration of love that follows, for example, "My doctor told me to follow my heart, so...".

I-heart.image_description: This image is a meme template based on the iconic "I ❤️ NY" logo. It features the capital letter 'I' in a black slab-serif font, followed by a large red heart symbol, which stands in for the word 'love'. This format is widely used to express affection or passion for any subject, which is typically written below the logo. The template's simplicity and universal recognition make it a versatile tool for sincere declarations, ironic statements, or humorous juxtapositions.

Fantasy-Painting.name: Fantasy-Painting

text_options.description: This label is placed on the small knight, representing the protagonist or the underdog. The text here typically describes the individual, a small group, or a simple concept facing a much larger force.

This label is placed on the giant boss, Yhorm. The text here represents the overwhelming challenge, the powerful antagonist, or an abstract and difficult problem that the smaller entity must confront.

Fantasy-Painting.image_description: This meme, known as "Yhorm the Giant" or the "Dark Souls Boss Fight" meme, originates from the video game Dark Souls 3. It depicts the player character, the Ashen One (a small knight), confronting the colossal boss, Yhorm the Giant, in a dramatic, fiery setting. The stark contrast in size is used to represent an individual or a small entity facing an overwhelmingly large, powerful, or difficult challenge, problem, or opponent in a humorous or relatable way.

My-beloved.name: My-beloved

text_options.description: This area, the right side of the locket, is a placeholder where an image or text is inserted. It represents one of the two things the meme creator loves or holds dear, working in conjunction with the left side to complete the pairing or comparison that forms the meme's punchline.

My-beloved.image_description: This meme template features an open, pink, heart-shaped locket with two empty frames side-by-side. Known as the "Heart Locket" meme, it is used to express love or appreciation for two things, which are placed into the empty frames. The format humorously applies the sentimental gesture of carrying a locket to pop culture figures, objects, or abstract concepts, often creating a funny or wholesome comparison.

Ew-i-stepped-in-shit.name: Ew-i-stepped-in-shit

text_options.description: Located on the sole of the shoe, this is the punchline area. Users edit this space to feature a logo, name, or image of something they dislike, equating it to the 'shit' from the first panel.
This is the character's dialogue, "Ew, I stepped in shit." This text is the setup for the meme and is almost always kept in its original form, establishing the context of disgust.

Ew-i-stepped-in-shit.image_description: The "Ew, I Stepped in Shit" meme is a two-panel comic used to express disgust. The first panel shows a cartoon man reacting negatively after stepping in something, saying the titular line. The second panel is a close-up of the bottom of his shoe, revealing what he stepped on, which is the target of the meme's criticism.

Body-is-a-Machine.name: Body-is-a-Machine

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom represents the output of the transformation and serves as the punchline. It typically contains a humorous, undesirable, or mundane result (e.g., 'anxiety,' 'diarrhea,' 'regret') that contrasts with the input.
This text box represents the input that the 'machine' (the body) processes. Users typically place a noun here, such as a type of food, drink, or an abstract concept like 'stress' or 'caffeine'.

Body-is-a-Machine.image_description: This meme, known as 'My Body Is A Machine That Turns', features a skeleton lifting a heavy barbell. The format humorously frames the body as a machine that converts an input into an output. It is typically used for self-deprecating jokes about how one's body processes things, often turning something good or neutral into something undesirable or mundane, subverting the tough-guy aesthetic of the image.

NPC-Meme.name: NPC-Meme

text_options.description: This text box is for the statement or question posed by the simple, white-drawn character. It typically contains an opinion, fact, or question that challenges a popular or mainstream narrative, acting as the trigger for the NPC Wojak's angry reaction.

This text box represents the initial thought or statement of the NPC Wojak. It often contains a generic, conformist, or mainstream slogan (e.g., "I support the current thing"). This establishes the character's baseline as an uncritical follower before being challenged.

NPC-Meme.image_description: This four-panel comic meme features the NPC Wojak, a grey, emotionless character representing people who can't think for themselves. In the comic, another character says something that challenges a mainstream belief, causing the initially stoic NPC to become visibly angry in the final panel. The meme is used to mock individuals or groups perceived as blindly following popular narratives or trends, suggesting their outrage is a programmed, unthinking response.

Laughing-wolf.name: Laughing-wolf

text_options.description: Text over the wolf on the right, one of the two "laughing" wolves. This label typically represents one of the people making or enjoying a joke.

Text over the central, serious-looking wolf. This label represents the person who is the butt of the joke, doesn't find it funny, or is simply unimpressed, providing the punchline through their contrasting reaction.
Text over the wolf on the left, the second "laughing" wolf. This label represents the other person who finds the situation hilarious, often sharing the joke with the wolf on the right.

Laughing-wolf.image_description: The "Laughing Wolves" meme features three white wolves, where two on the sides appear to be laughing hysterically while the one in the middle maintains a deadpan, serious expression. This format is used to illustrate a scenario where a joke or comment is found hilarious by two parties but falls flat or is directed at a third, unamused party. The meme highlights the contrast between shared amusement and stoic disapproval.

Angry-Man-pointing-at-hand.name: Angry-Man-pointing-at-hand

text_options.description: This area labels the listener in the conversation. The text here typically identifies the person receiving the passionate but often confusing explanation, such as "My Mom," "My friend," or anyone who is not familiar with the niche topic being discussed. Their role is to be the patient but bewildered audience to the explainer's rant.

This text labels the person doing the explaining. It usually describes the speaker ("Me") and the very specific, complex, or esoteric subject they are passionately trying to explain. The text here sets up the core joke of the meme, highlighting the speaker's deep dive into a topic that is likely unrelatable to the listener.

Angry-Man-pointing-at-hand.image_description: This meme, known as "Bro Explaining" or "Me Explaining to My Mom," is a cropped section of the 19th-century painting "The Village Politicians" by John L. Krimmel. It features a man in a beige coat and cap intensely explaining something to another person, pointing emphatically at his own palm. The meme is used to humorously depict situations where someone passionately explains a complex, niche, or seemingly nonsensical topic to an uninitiated and likely confused listener.

BestBetter-Blurst.name: BestBetter-Blurst

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the distorted, grotesque version of Winnie the Pooh. It is used for a crude, simplistic, or incorrect term or idea, representing the lowest level of sophistication in the comparison and often serving as the punchline.

Positioned next to the sophisticated, tuxedo-clad Winnie the Pooh, this box contains a more refined, eloquent, or technically superior version of the concept being compared. It represents the most desirable or 'classy' option.
This text box is adjacent to the standard, unimpressed-looking Winnie the Pooh. It typically contains a common, simple, or standard term or phrase that serves as the baseline for the comparison.

BestBetter-Blurst.image_description: This is a three-panel exploitable meme featuring the character Winnie the Pooh, often called the 'Tuxedo Pooh' or 'Winnie the Pooh reaction' meme. It's used to compare three related concepts by presenting them with corresponding levels of sophistication. The top panel shows a standard Pooh for a common idea, the middle panel shows a dapper Pooh in a tuxedo for a superior or refined version, and the bottom panel shows a grotesque, distorted Pooh for an inferior or foolish alternative.

Old-man-cup-of-coffee.name: Old-man-cup-of-coffee

text_options.description: This bottom panel is the punchline, where text describes the internal, painful, or awkward reaction to the situation set up in the top panel. Harold's direct, pained gaze at the camera reinforces that this is the 'true' feeling being hidden.

The text in the top panel typically describes an action, event, or statement that sets up the scenario. It represents the external situation that Harold (and by extension, the meme creator) is pretending to be okay with.

Old-man-cup-of-coffee.image_description: This is a two-panel meme featuring András Arató, famously known as 'Hide the Pain Harold'. The meme captures his signature expression of a forced smile that seems to mask deep-seated pain, awkwardness, or regret. The format is typically used to contrast an external situation or statement (top panel) with the true, uncomfortable internal feeling (bottom panel), representing someone trying to act fine when they are not.

soup-nazi.name: soup-nazi

text_options.description: This text is the punchline of the meme, located over the counter. It adapts the character's iconic catchphrase to fit the context, typically reading "No [X] for you!", where [X] is the item or privilege being denied.
Text in this upper region identifies the person or entity acting as the strict gatekeeper or rule-enforcer. This sets up the context for who is denying the thing mentioned in the punchline below.

soup-nazi.image_description: This meme features the character known as the "Soup Nazi" from the 90s sitcom Seinfeld. In the show, he is an extremely strict soup vendor who denies service for any minor deviation from his ordering rules, famously shouting, "No soup for you!". The meme is used to represent a person, company, or entity that is arbitrarily or harshly denying something to someone, often for a trivial reason.

Willy-Wonka-Blank.name: Willy-Wonka-Blank

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the sarcastic or condescending punchline. It often starts with phrases like "Tell me more about..." or "Oh, so you're saying..." to mock the idea presented in the top text.
The top text, which sets up the premise of the meme. This line usually poses a rhetorical question or states an opinion that the meme creator intends to mock in a patronizing way.

Willy-Wonka-Blank.image_description: The "Condescending Wonka" meme features a still of actor Gene Wilder as Willy Wonka from the 1971 film "Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory." He is shown with a patronizing smirk, resting his head on his hand, looking directly at the viewer. This image is used to convey a sarcastic or condescending tone, typically by pairing a seemingly innocent question or statement at the top with a patronizing punchline at the bottom.

Futuristic-Utopia.name: Futuristic-Utopia

text_options.description: This area, covering the lower half of the image, is where the condition for the utopia is stated. Text here typically starts with "if" or describes a scenario, such as "if people used their turn signals." It sets up the premise of the meme, presenting the cause for the perfect society shown above.

This area, covering the top half of the image, is typically overlaid with the punchline, often simply the word "Society." This text labels the utopian scene as the direct result of the condition described in the text below, completing the "Society if..." format.

Futuristic-Utopia.image_description: This meme, often captioned "Society if...", depicts a utopian futuristic city with flying cars, sleek architecture, and lush greenery. The image is used to humorously and hyperbolically suggest that the world would be a perfect paradise if a specific, often trivial, event occurred or a certain annoyance were eliminated. The stark contrast between the mundane condition and the grand, idealized outcome is the core of the joke, expressing a strong opinion or pet peeve.

Whats-My-Purpose---Butter-Robot.name: Whats-My-Purpose---Butter-Robot

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the final panel showing the dejected robot. It represents the robot's reaction of despair, almost always containing the phrase 'Oh my god' to signify its existential crisis and the punchline of the meme.

This text box is over the middle panel where Rick Sanchez is speaking. It contains Rick's answer, which reveals a simple, mundane, or disappointing purpose, such as the original line 'You pass butter'.
This text box is placed over the first panel where the Butter Robot speaks. It typically contains the question 'What is my purpose?', initiating the existential dialogue.

Whats-My-Purpose---Butter-Robot.image_description: This is the "What is my purpose?" or "Butter Robot" meme from the animated show Rick and Morty. It features a small robot having an existential crisis after its creator, Rick Sanchez, reveals its sole purpose is to pass butter. The meme is used to humorously express feelings of futility, disappointment, or having a mundane and unfulfilling role, with the robot's despair representing the punchline.

Call-an-ambulance-but-not-for-me.name: Call-an-ambulance-but-not-for-me

text_options.description: This label identifies the older man who initially appears to be the victim. In the meme format, this text represents the person, group, or concept that seems to be at a disadvantage or losing.
This label points to the younger man holding a knife, who is the initial aggressor. This text represents the threat, challenge, or seemingly superior opponent that the 'victim' is facing.

Call-an-ambulance-but-not-for-me.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Call an ambulance, but not for me!", depicts a dramatic reversal of fortune. In the first panel, an older man appears to be the victim of a robbery by a younger man with a knife. However, the second panel reveals the older man has a gun, turning the tables on his would-be assailant. This format is used to illustrate situations where an apparent underdog surprisingly gains the upper hand.
Call-an-ambulance-but-not-for-me.display_name: Call an ambulance but not for me

Donald-Trump.name: Donald-Trump

text_options.description: The bottom text, often placed over or near the podium, typically serves as the punchline or the conclusion to the statement started in the top text. Trump's pose makes it seem as if he is presenting this text as an undeniable or final fact.

The top text, positioned above Donald Trump, is used to set up the joke or present the first part of a statement or question. This text establishes the context that the punchline at the bottom will play off of.

Donald-Trump.image_description: This meme features former U.S. President Donald Trump standing at a podium with his arms outstretched and palms up, in front of American flags. The gesture is often interpreted as a shrug or a presentation of a fact, conveying a sense of "What can you do?" or "It is what it is." The meme is typically used as a two-panel format with text added at the top and bottom to present a setup and a punchline, often for humorous, satirical, or controversial statements.

For-dummies-book.name: For-dummies-book

text_options.description: This speech bubble, placed next to the Dummies Man, is an optional area for adding a punchline or a simple, often foolish, statement. The text here represents the thoughts or words of the "dummy," reinforcing the theme established by the main title.

This is the main title section of the book cover. In the meme, this space is edited to contain the subject of the fake guide. The humor comes from the chosen topic, which is typically either absurdly simple, overly specific, or a complex concept being mockingly simplified.

For-dummies-book.image_description: This meme is a template based on the cover of the popular "For Dummies" instructional book series. It features the series' distinct yellow and black color scheme, the title font, and the mascot, the "Dummies Man," a cartoon figure with a pointy head and glasses. The format is used to create fake, humorous book titles for various subjects, often to simplify a complex topic sarcastically or to point out something that should be common sense.

Gentleman-frog.name: Gentleman-frog

text_options.description: The bottom text area is the punchline location. In this meme format, it almost always contains the signature phrase "It is Wednesday, my dudes," delivering the core message of the meme.

The top text area is typically used for a setup or introductory phrase. However, in many instances of the "Wednesday Frog" meme, this area is left blank, letting the image and the bottom text carry the entire joke.

Gentleman-frog.image_description: This meme features a painting of an anthropomorphic frog in formal, 19th-century attire, looking directly at the viewer with a serious expression. Known as the "Wednesday Frog," this image is famously used to announce that it is Wednesday, often accompanied by the phrase "It is Wednesday, my dudes." The humor comes from the formal and solemn delivery of a mundane fact, celebrating the midpoint of the workweek.

Leonardo-DiCaprio-Pointing.name: Leonardo-DiCaprio-Pointing

text_options.description: This bottom caption typically represents the meme creator's reaction or the specific thing they are recognizing. It often starts with phrases like "Me when I see..." to directly connect the user's experience to DiCaprio's pointing gesture.

The text in this top area sets the context or describes the media being consumed. It provides the background for the situation where the moment of recognition occurs, such as "Watching a movie and seeing an actor you know" or "When the show mentions your hometown."

Leonardo-DiCaprio-Pointing.image_description: This meme, known as "Pointing Leonardo DiCaprio" or "Rick Dalton Pointing," features a still of actor Leonardo DiCaprio from the 2019 film "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood." In the image, his character, Rick Dalton, is sitting in a chair holding a beer and a cigarette, pointing at a television screen with a look of recognition. The meme is used to express excitement or surprise when one recognizes something familiar or relatable in a piece of media, essentially conveying the feeling of "Hey, I know that!"

Press-button-hard-choice.name: Press-button-hard-choice

text_options.description: This label describes one of two conflicting options in a dilemma. It works in tandem with the other label to create the difficult choice that causes the character's distress.
This label describes the second of two conflicting options. Paired with the first label, it establishes the core conflict of the meme, forcing a difficult decision.

Press-button-hard-choice.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, often called "Daily Struggle" or "Two Buttons," illustrates a difficult choice. The top panel shows a hand hesitating between two labeled red buttons, while the bottom panel shows a man sweating nervously. The meme is used to represent a dilemma between two conflicting desires, ideas, or actions, with the man's anxiety humorously exaggerating the stress of the decision.

Protected-Kevin-Hart.name: Protected-Kevin-Hart

text_options.description: This label is placed on the woman with her back to the camera, representing the source of temptation, a problem, or an antagonist. The text here defines the undesirable thing or situation that the other characters are reacting to, setting up the conflict of the meme.

This label is on Kevin Hart, who represents the voice of reason, self-control, or a friend trying to intervene. The text here is typically the person or entity trying to prevent the action, acting as the restraining force in the humorous scenario.

This label is on the woman being held back, representing the person who is tempted or about to make a bad decision. The text here identifies the individual who is struggling against their better judgment (represented by Kevin Hart) to engage with the problem (the other woman).

Protected-Kevin-Hart.image_description: This meme, known as "Kevin Hart Holding Woman Back," originates from the reality TV parody "Real Husbands of Hollywood." It depicts comedian Kevin Hart with a scared expression, restraining a woman in a yellow dress who is reaching towards another woman in a blue dress. The meme humorously illustrates a scenario of someone trying to prevent themselves or a friend from making a poor decision, succumbing to a temptation, or engaging with a problem.

Surprised-Joey.name: Surprised-Joey

text_options.description: The text in this bottom panel delivers the punchline or a shocking twist that reframes the initial statement. This new information causes the sudden realization, mirroring Joey's abrupt shift to a horrified and alarmed expression.

The text in this top panel describes an initial, often positive or innocuous, statement or situation. It sets up the premise, corresponding with Joey's calm and confident expression before the shocking revelation.

Surprised-Joey.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Joey Tribbiani from the TV show 'Friends'. The top panel shows Joey with a calm, smug expression, while the bottom panel shows him with a shocked and wide-eyed look of realization. The format is used to contrast a seemingly normal or positive statement with a subsequent, shocking piece of information that completely changes the context, leading to alarm.

XKCD-Dependency.name: XKCD-Dependency

text_options.description: This label points to the single, small block at the very bottom of the stack. It typically names an obscure but critical open-source project, a single developer, or a small piece of code that the entire system unexpectedly relies on, serving as the punchline that highlights the system's fragility.

This label is placed at the top, with a bracket encompassing the entire large structure. It identifies the complex, important system being discussed, such as 'All modern digital infrastructure' in the original comic. In memes, this is often replaced with other large-scale systems to create a relatable scenario of precarious dependency.

XKCD-Dependency.image_description: This meme, originating from an xkcd comic titled "Dependency", illustrates the fragility of complex systems. It depicts a massive, intricate structure of stacked blocks representing a modern system, all precariously balanced on a single, tiny, overlooked block at its base. The meme is widely used in tech and programming circles to highlight how critical infrastructure often relies on small, obscure, and poorly maintained open-source projects, humorously pointing out the precariousness of software dependencies.

Marvel-Civil-War-1.name: Marvel-Civil-War-1

text_options.description: This text, placed over Iron Man, represents one side of a disagreement. It's typically a simple statement, opinion, or action that will be challenged.
This text, placed over Captain America, presents the opposing viewpoint or a contradictory statement to the one on Iron Man's panel. This creates the conflict that the meme escalates.

Marvel-Civil-War-1.image_description: This meme format originates from the film 'Captain America: Civil War' and features a tense staredown between Captain America (Steve Rogers) and Iron Man (Tony Stark). It's used to humorously exaggerate a minor disagreement into a major conflict. The first two panels present opposing viewpoints or actions, and the final panel, showing the movie's title, frames the trivial argument as an epic 'civil war'.

Pie-Chart-Meme.name: Pie-Chart-Meme

text_options.description: This text box is part of the legend, corresponding to the overwhelmingly large orange section of the pie chart. It typically contains the humorous, relatable, or absurd option that constitutes the vast majority, forming the punchline of the meme.

This text box is part of the legend, corresponding to the tiny blue sliver in the pie chart. It represents the insignificant, often more logical or expected, alternative that is being humorously contrasted with the dominant option.
This is the title of the pie chart. The text here sets up the premise or question that the chart is supposedly answering, providing context for the humorous comparison between the two categories.

Pie-Chart-Meme.image_description: This is a pie chart meme format used to humorously illustrate a lopsided comparison or an overwhelming preference for one thing over another. The chart visually exaggerates a point by showing one category (the large orange section) as vastly more significant than the other (the tiny blue sliver). This meme is typically used to make a satirical or relatable statement about habits, choices, or situations by presenting them as statistical data.

the-circle-of-life.name: the-circle-of-life

text_options.description: This box, positioned on the left, typically contains the first step or the initial state of the cycle. It sets up the premise or problem that initiates the loop.
Located at the bottom of the cycle, this box describes the second step, which is a direct consequence of or reaction to the event described in box 0.
This box on the right represents the third step in the sequence. The text here describes the outcome or a subsequent action resulting from the step in box 1.

Positioned at the top, this is the final step of the cycle. The text in this box describes the action or state that leads directly back to the initial condition in box 0, thus completing and reinforcing the inescapable loop.

the-circle-of-life.image_description: A simple diagram meme template showing four empty rectangular boxes arranged in a square. Curved black arrows point from one box to the next in a clockwise direction, forming a continuous loop. This format is used to illustrate a self-perpetuating cycle of events, actions, or thoughts, often to highlight a frustrating, ironic, or flawed process where the final step leads directly back to the first.

black-guy-pointing-at-head.name: black-guy-pointing-at-head

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It presents the illogical or foolish 'solution' to the problem stated in the top box, which the character is supposedly thinking of.
The top text box typically sets up the scenario or poses a problem. This text establishes the context for the absurd advice that follows, creating a two-part joke structure.

black-guy-pointing-at-head.image_description: This meme, known as 'Roll Safe' or 'Think About It,' features actor Kayode Ewumi as Reece Simpson. He is smiling knowingly and tapping his temple, as if sharing a brilliant piece of wisdom. The format is used to present comically flawed logic or terrible life advice, where an absurd 'solution' is offered for a problem.

I-wish-all-x-a-very-y.name: I-wish-all-x-a-very-y

text_options.description: This text box, following "a very," is where the user specifies the outcome or experience they are wishing upon the group. This can range from something positive like "pleasant evening" to something negative or comically specific like "stubbed toe," defining the meme's humorous or sarcastic punchline.

This text box, positioned after "i wish all," is used to identify the specific group of people, objects, or entities that the wish is directed towards. The user customizes this part to target a particular audience, such as "gamers," "people who don't use turn signals," or "students."

I-wish-all-x-a-very-y.image_description: This meme features the cartoon character Bugs Bunny from Looney Tunes, dressed formally in a tuxedo against a black background with a smug expression. The format, "i wish all [group] a very [outcome]," is used to express a wish, either sincere or sarcastic, towards a specific group of people. The formal attire and Bugs's confident demeanor lend a mock-serious or official tone to the statement, making it versatile for both genuine well-wishes and passive-aggressive jabs.
I-wish-all-x-a-very-y.display_name: I wish all x a very y

Its-been-84-years.name: Its-been-84-years

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the original quote from the movie: "it's been 84 years...". This text is crucial as it delivers the exaggerated sense of a long wait. While the number '84' is sometimes edited for comedic effect, the core phrase remains the same to convey the meme's meaning.

The top section of the image is where the setup text is placed. This text describes the situation or event that the user has been waiting for, providing context for the punchline below. For example, it might say, "Me waiting for my food to be ready after ordering it 5 minutes ago."

Its-been-84-years.image_description: This meme features a still image of the elderly character Rose from the 1997 film Titanic, looking down with a weary and nostalgic expression. The image is used to humorously exaggerate the feeling of waiting for a very long time for something to happen, often for mundane or trivial events. The punchline is her iconic line, "It's been 84 years...", which expresses a feeling of impatience or that a long-awaited moment has finally arrived.

Narcos-waiting.name: Narcos-waiting

text_options.description: This text, spanning the two bottom panels, typically describes a scenario or group activity that the meme's creator is not a part of. It sets the context for why the subject feels left out or is waiting, for example, "Everyone else at the party having fun."

Positioned over the main, top panel, this text represents the punchline. It describes the creator's own lonely or boring situation in contrast to the scenario mentioned below, such as "Me waiting for my ride to show up." The image of Escobar looking sad and alone reinforces this feeling.

Narcos-waiting.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Pablo Escobar Waiting" or "Sad Pablo Escobar," features actor Wagner Moura as the character from the TV series "Narcos." The images depict Escobar looking pensive and lonely in various settings: sitting on a swing, at a table, and by an empty pool. The meme is used to humorously express feelings of boredom, loneliness, or waiting for something to happen, often contrasting one's own mundane situation with more exciting events.

Burning-House-Girl.name: Burning-House-Girl

text_options.description: Text placed here, over the girl, represents the person or entity that is secretly pleased with or has caused the disaster. This is the main character of the meme, often representing the user or a specific group finding satisfaction in the misfortune of others.

Text in this box, placed over the burning house, describes the disaster, problem, or unfortunate situation. This is the event that the 'Disaster Girl' (labeled in box 0) is observing with glee, creating the central joke of the meme.

Burning-House-Girl.image_description: The "Disaster Girl" meme shows a young girl with a mischievous, knowing smirk looking towards the camera. In the background, a house is engulfed in flames, with firefighters and a fire truck visible, suggesting a recent disaster. This iconic image is used to humorously imply that the subject (the girl) is responsible for or takes pleasure in a chaotic or destructive event. The contrast between her seemingly innocent appearance and the disastrous background creates a dark, comedic tone.

I-am-going-to-create-an-environment-that.name: I-am-going-to-create-an-environment-that-is-so-toxic-blank

text_options.description: This text box replaces the original word "toxic." It serves as the punchline, containing a descriptive adjective that characterizes the absurd or extreme nature of the situation being created.
This text box replaces the original phrase "an environment." It contains the noun or concept that the user intends to create, setting up the punchline in the next part of the sentence.

This area highlights the face of Sue Sylvester, the character making the declaration. Her stern expression is central to the meme's humor, conveying a serious commitment to the absurd threat described in the text.

I-am-going-to-create-an-environment-that.image_description: This meme features Sue Sylvester, a character from the TV show Glee played by Jane Lynch, with a determined and menacing expression. The image is a reaction template based on her line, "I am going to create an environment that is so toxic." The meme is used to humorously declare an intention to create a very specific, often absurd or unpleasant, situation or atmosphere by replacing key words in the original quote.
I-am-going-to-create-an-environment-that.display_name: I am going to create an environment that is so toxic blank

Nemo-Seagulls-Mine.name: Nemo-Seagulls-Mine

text_options.description: Text in this bottom region typically labels the object of desire or the thing that the group is clamoring for. It represents the 'what' in the scenario, such as 'free food samples' or 'a new product release'.

Text in this top region identifies the group of people or entities making the demand. This label represents the 'who' that is acting like the seagulls, for example, 'My siblings' or 'The entire internet'.

Nemo-Seagulls-Mine.image_description: This meme features a flock of seagulls from the Disney/Pixar movie 'Finding Nemo,' famous for their repetitive chant of 'Mine!'. The image captures their intense, single-minded focus as they stare intently towards the viewer. Culturally, this meme is used to represent a group of people, companies, or entities all greedily demanding or claiming something for themselves, often in a simplistic or overwhelming manner.

Going-to-need-a-bigger-boat.name: Going-to-need-a-bigger-boat

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the punchline, which is typically the famous quote from the movie: 'You're gonna need a bigger boat.' This line serves as the reaction to the problem presented, concluding that the current resources are insufficient.

This text box at the top of the image is used to label the unexpectedly large or difficult problem that the subject (Chief Brody) is facing. It sets up the context for the punchline, representing the 'shark' in the meme's scenario.

Going-to-need-a-bigger-boat.image_description: This meme features a still of Chief Brody (played by Roy Scheider) from the 1975 film 'Jaws'. In the scene, Brody has just seen the enormous shark for the first time and delivers the iconic line, 'You're gonna need a bigger boat.' The meme is used as a reaction to express that a current plan, tool, or approach is completely inadequate for an unexpectedly massive or difficult problem, with Brody's shocked face capturing the feeling of being overwhelmed.
Going-to-need-a-bigger-boat.display_name: Going to need a bigger boat

What-a-week-huh.name: What-a-week-huh

text_options.description: This speech bubble is for Tintin's dialogue and serves as the setup for the joke. The text here is typically a straightforward question or a serious statement that establishes a normal context, creating an expectation for a logical reply.

This larger speech bubble contains Captain Haddock's response, which is the punchline of the meme. The text is intentionally absurd, off-topic, or a bizarrely literal interpretation of Tintin's prompt, creating a comedic contrast that is amplified by Haddock's disoriented expression.

What-a-week-huh.image_description: This meme format is a comic panel from "The Adventures of Tintin," featuring Tintin, Captain Haddock, and Snowy the dog. In the scene, a concerned Tintin speaks to a dazed and seemingly drunk Captain Haddock. The meme is a dialogue format where Tintin poses a serious question or makes a statement, and Haddock delivers an absurd, nonsensical, or comically literal punchline, with his confused state being the source of humor.

Two-paths.name: Two-paths

text_options.description: This label is placed on the character at the fork in the road. It identifies the person, group, or entity that is facing a critical decision between the two paths presented.

This label is on the path leading to the dark, spooky castle. It represents the more difficult, less conventional, or often ironically more appealing choice. The ominous setting reinforces the idea of a challenging or 'evil' path.

This label is on the path leading to the bright, sunny castle. It represents the easier, more straightforward, or socially accepted choice. The cheerful scenery visually supports the idea of a 'good' or desirable outcome.

Two-paths.image_description: This meme, known as "Two Paths" or "Two Choices," features a cartoon character standing at a fork in the road, presenting a dilemma. One path leads to a bright, sunny castle, symbolizing a positive or conventional choice, while the other leads to a dark, stormy castle, representing a negative, difficult, or edgy alternative. The meme is used to humorously contrast two different options or outcomes for a given situation.

Blank.name: Blank

text_options.description: The text in this bottom panel represents the undesirable, rejected, or inferior option in the comparison. It's the thing that the meme creator disapproves of, similar to the 'dislike' panel in other comparison memes.
The text in this top panel represents the desirable, approved, or superior option. It's the preferred choice or positive concept being endorsed by the meme creator.

Blank.image_description: This is a minimalist two-panel meme format that uses binary digits to represent a strong preference. The top panel, labeled "1", signifies something positive, approved, or superior. The bottom panel, labeled "0", represents something negative, rejected, or inferior. This meme is used to make a stark and often humorous comparison, declaring one option as the only correct choice while completely dismissing the other.

Dead-Baby-Voldemort--What-Happened-To-Hi.name: Dead-Baby-Voldemort--What-Happened-To-Him

text_options.description: This text box is positioned over Albus Dumbledore. It typically contains a question or a statement from a wise, authoritative, or parental figure, setting up the premise of the joke.
This text box is placed over Harry Potter. It contains the punchline, which is usually a naive, foolish, or unexpected response to Dumbledore's prompt, creating a humorous contrast.

Dead-Baby-Voldemort--What-Happened-To-Hi.image_description: This three-panel meme originates from a scene in "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 2" set in a limbo-like King's Cross station. It depicts a shriveled, baby-like creature (a piece of Voldemort's soul), Harry Potter looking down, and Albus Dumbledore. The format is typically used for a humorous dialogue where Dumbledore, as a figure of wisdom, asks a serious question, and Harry provides a naive or absurd answer, while the Voldemort creature represents a neglected problem or responsibility.
Dead-Baby-Voldemort--What-Happened-To-Hi.display_name: Dead Baby Voldemort  What Happened To Him

Say-it-Again-Dexter.name: Say-it-Again-Dexter

text_options.description: This text, placed over a close-up of Dexter's face, represents the simple, often absurdly effective solution to the problem above. It is almost always the phrase 'Omelette du Fromage,' which acts as the punchline, symbolizing a simplistic key to success.

The text in the top panel sets up the meme by describing a complex problem, a difficult social situation, or a task requiring great effort. This establishes the challenge that will be unexpectedly overcome by the simple phrase in the bottom panel.

Say-it-Again-Dexter.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Omelette du Fromage,' originates from the cartoon 'Dexter's Laboratory.' It depicts the main character, Dexter, being adored by two girls after only being able to say the French phrase for 'cheese omelette.' The meme contrasts a complex problem or situation (top panel) with a simple, often nonsensical, but surprisingly effective solution (bottom panel), humorously suggesting that a simple approach can lead to great success.

My-job-here-is-done.name: My-job-here-is-done

text_options.description: This area, showing Tuxedo Mask's disappearing cape, is part of the punchline and is usually left blank. It visually represents the unceremonious and swift exit of the person who claimed to have helped but did nothing, ignoring the criticism.

This label is on Sailor Moon, who represents the person or group pointing out the uselessness of the first character's actions. The text here is typically an accusation or a statement of fact that undermines the other's claim of accomplishment.

This label is on Tuxedo Mask, who represents a person, company, or entity that contributes little to nothing to a situation. The text here is used to identify this unhelpful party who is about to take credit and leave.

My-job-here-is-done.image_description: This three-panel meme format originates from the anime series Sailor Moon, featuring the characters Tuxedo Mask and Sailor Moon. In the scene, Tuxedo Mask dramatically declares his work is finished, to which Sailor Moon points out he did nothing, and he promptly disappears. The meme is used to humorously represent someone taking credit for a task they didn't contribute to, or making a minimal, unhelpful appearance before leaving a situation.

You-cant-defeat-me.name: You-cant-defeat-me

text_options.description: This area, over the exploding Asgard representing Surtur, is labeled with the powerful, often extreme or unexpected, solution to the problem. It serves as the punchline, revealing the 'he' that Thor refers to who can defeat the antagonist.

This box, placed over Thor, typically represents the protagonist or the person facing the problem. This character acknowledges the difficulty of the challenge but introduces a third, more powerful entity as the solution.
This box, positioned over the villain Hela, is used to label an overwhelming problem, a powerful antagonist, or an unbeatable challenge. It sets up the conflict for the meme.

You-cant-defeat-me.image_description: This meme format, known as "I Know, But He Can," originates from the movie Thor: Ragnarok. It features a three-panel sequence where the villain Hela confidently states, "You can't defeat me," followed by the hero Thor replying, "I know, but he can," and a final panel showing the fiery giant Surtur destroying Asgard. The meme is used to illustrate a scenario where a seemingly insurmountable problem is overcome by introducing an even greater, often more destructive or chaotic, force as the solution.

huell-money.name: huell-money

text_options.description: This text box typically identifies the subject of the meme, often starting with 'Me after...' or describing the person who has acquired the abundance shown. It sets up the scenario for the punchline.

This text box describes what the pile of money represents in the meme's context. The humor often comes from replacing the literal money with something mundane, relatable, or highly desired, such as 'my $12 tax refund' or 'getting 8 hours of sleep'.

huell-money.image_description: This meme features the character Huell Babineaux from the TV series 'Breaking Bad', lying contentedly on a massive pile of cash. The image is used to represent extreme wealth, abundance, or the feeling of having 'made it.' It's often used as a reaction image to express what one would do with a sudden windfall or an excess of something desirable, symbolizing ultimate comfort and satisfaction.

Are-we-the-baddies.name: Are-we-the-baddies

text_options.description: Text placed here labels the person or group who is beginning to question their own morality or position. This represents the 'we' in the phrase 'Are we the baddies?'.

Text in this area identifies the specific, often damning, detail or action that triggers the self-doubt. In the original sketch, this is the skull insignia on the cap, so this label represents the undeniable evidence that they might be on the wrong side.

Are-we-the-baddies.image_description: This meme, known as "Are We the Baddies?", originates from a sketch in the British comedy show "That Mitchell and Webb Look." It depicts a German SS officer having a moment of dawning realization that his side might be the villains, prompted by noticing the skull insignia on their caps. The meme is used to represent a moment of sudden, uncomfortable self-awareness where a person or group questions if their own actions, beliefs, or affiliations are morally wrong.

Waiting-skeleton.name: Waiting-skeleton

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the setup for the joke, often starting with a phrase like 'Me waiting for...' or 'Still waiting for...'. It describes the person or entity that is doing the waiting, establishing the context for the visual punchline of the skeleton.

The top text box usually contains the punchline, specifying what is being waited for. For example, it might say '...the game to load' or '...my friend to be ready'. This text completes the joke by revealing the cause of the comically long wait that has turned the person into a skeleton.

Waiting-skeleton.image_description: The 'Waiting Skeleton' meme features a skeleton sitting patiently on a park bench, looking slightly to the side. This image is used to humorously convey an extremely long, often indefinite, wait for something to happen, such as a video game release, a reply to a message, or a significant event. The joke is that the person has been waiting so long they have turned into a skeleton, representing extreme impatience or the feeling that something is taking forever.

Donald-trump-approves.name: Donald-trump-approves

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which typically serves as the punchline or the main declaration. This text often completes the thought from the top text with a boastful, exaggerated, or definitive statement, playing on Donald Trump's characteristic speaking style.

The top text of the image macro, which serves as the setup for the joke or statement. It introduces a topic or a person, often in a way that mimics Donald Trump's manner of speaking, setting the stage for the punchline below.

Donald-trump-approves.image_description: This meme features a photograph of Donald Trump with a slight, confident smirk. It's a classic image macro format where text is added to the top and bottom. The meme is typically used to make a boastful, definitive, or often humorous statement, mimicking Trump's public persona and speaking style.

captain-america-so-you.name: captain-america-so-you

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the punchline of the meme. It's Captain America's unhelpful, obvious, or condescending advice or observation that directly follows the setup in the top text. The humor derives from the uselessness of the statement delivered with his earnest expression.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically describes a situation where someone has made a mistake or is in a predicament, often starting with 'So, you...' to imitate the PSA format.

captain-america-so-you.image_description: This meme features the Marvel superhero Captain America, as portrayed by Chris Evans, in a still from a Public Service Announcement (PSA) scene in the movie 'Spider-Man: Homecoming'. He is sitting backwards on a chair with a friendly, slightly patronizing smile. The meme, known as 'Captain America's PSA' or 'So, You've Got Detention', is used to deliver obvious, unhelpful, or condescending advice, mimicking the tone of a cheesy educational video.

This-is-Fine-Blank.name: This-is-Fine-Blank

text_options.description: This speech bubble contains the punchline of the meme. Originally saying 'This is fine,' it's often edited to contain a statement of denial or a calm acceptance of a chaotic situation, reflecting the dog's obliviousness to the surrounding fire.

This area above the dog in the first panel is often used to add a label or title that provides context for the disastrous situation. Text here typically identifies the person, group, or concept that is ignoring the 'fire' (the problem).

This-is-Fine-Blank.image_description: This two-panel comic strip meme, known as 'This is Fine,' features an anthropomorphic dog wearing a hat, sitting in a room engulfed in flames. In the first panel, the dog looks on with a placid smile, and in the second, he cheerfully says 'This is fine,' despite the obvious disaster. The meme is widely used to represent a state of denial, willful ignorance, or extreme calm when faced with a catastrophic or unmanageable situation.

Three-dragons.name: Three-dragons

text_options.description: This label is placed on the neck of the goofy, derpy-looking dragon head on the right. The text here represents the outlier, the foolish, or the comically inferior option in a group of three, serving as the punchline of the meme.

This label is on the neck of the central, serious-looking dragon head. Text placed here represents one of the two competent, serious, or well-regarded subjects being compared, establishing the standard that the third option fails to meet.

This label is on the neck of the menacing dragon head on the left. Similar to the central head, the text here represents the second competent or impressive item in the trio, working with the central head to set up the humorous contrast with the goofy head.

Three-dragons.image_description: This meme, known as "Three-Headed Dragon" or "King Ghidorah meme," features a fan-art depiction of the Godzilla monster King Ghidorah. Two of the dragon's heads are portrayed as menacing and serious, while the third head on the right is drawn in a goofy, derpy style. The meme is used to compare three related things, where two are competent or impressive, and the third is a comically inept or absurd outlier, represented by the silly-looking head.

Bart-Simpson---chalkboard.name: Bart-Simpson---chalkboard

text_options.description: The bottom-most line on the chalkboard. This space is used for a repeated statement that forms the core message of the meme. The repetition across all lines emphasizes the point being made.
The second line from the bottom. It contains the same text as all other lines to create the effect of Bart repeatedly writing a punishment phrase.
A line on the chalkboard. Like all the other lines, it features the same repeated text, which is the central joke or statement of the meme.
A line in the middle of the chalkboard. It contains the repeated phrase, contributing to the visual gag of a punishment being written out multiple times.
A line in the upper-middle section of the chalkboard. This space is filled with the same text as the other lines to reinforce the meme's message through repetition.
An upper line on the chalkboard. It repeats the central statement of the meme, consistent with the format of the chalkboard gag.
The second line from the top. This area contains the same repeated text as the rest of the board, driving home the meme's point.
The top-most line on the chalkboard. It features the repeated phrase, completing the set of lines that deliver the meme's punchline or opinion.

Bart-Simpson---chalkboard.image_description: This meme template features Bart Simpson from the animated series 'The Simpsons' writing lines on a chalkboard as punishment, a recurring gag from the show's opening sequence. The meme is used to express an opinion, complaint, or observation that the creator feels needs to be repeated for emphasis. The humor comes from the act of Bart being forced to write a statement over and over, implying it's a lesson that needs to be learned by a wider audience.

Simpsons-Monkey-Fight.name: Simpsons-Monkey-Fight

text_options.description: This box labels the aggressive grey monkey. The text here represents one of the two entities engaged in a conflict, often the one perceived as the instigator or more aggressive party.
This box labels the brown monkey, which appears to be on the defensive. The text here represents the second entity in the conflict, often portrayed as the rival or opposing force to the first.

This box is placed in the sky above the crowd of onlookers. Text here identifies the group of people, organizations, or concepts that are observing, encouraging, or benefiting from the conflict between the two parties represented by the monkeys.

Simpsons-Monkey-Fight.image_description: This meme, known as 'Monkey Knife Fight,' originates from The Simpsons. It depicts a chaotic scene where two monkeys fight on a boat deck, surrounded by a crowd of men enthusiastically betting on the outcome. The meme is used to satirize situations where two opposing groups or individuals are locked in a fierce, often pointless, conflict, while a third party watches, instigates, or profits from the chaos.

i-hate-you-and-hope-you-die.name: i-hate-you-and-hope-you-die

text_options.description: This area is for labeling the small, happy character on the right, who is the target of the rage. The text here describes something that is typically seen as positive, helpful, or innocent, which makes the extreme anger directed at it absurd and humorous.

The speech bubble for the enraged character on the left. This text is the punchline's setup, expressing intense, over-the-top hatred or frustration towards the subject identified in the other text box.

i-hate-you-and-hope-you-die.image_description: This meme, known as 'I Hate You Annuity' or 'Retirement Kid,' features a rage comic character screaming with intense hatred at a small, obliviously happy child-like figure. The format humorously contrasts an irrational, visceral anger with a seemingly innocent or even beneficial subject. It's typically used to express extreme frustration over things that are supposed to be good for you or are simply unbothered by your anger.
i-hate-you-and-hope-you-die.display_name: i hate you and hope you die

And-everybody-loses-their-minds.name: And-everybody-loses-their-minds

text_options.description: The bottom text box introduces a contrasting scenario. This text describes a minor deviation from the norm or a small, often sensible action, which paradoxically causes people to 'lose their minds' and panic, completing the meme's satirical point about societal double standards.

The top text box presents a scenario that is chaotic, harmful, or absurd but is considered normal or 'part of the plan' by society. This text establishes the 'horrifying plan' that, according to the Joker's logic, people accept without question.

And-everybody-loses-their-minds.image_description: A still from the movie 'The Dark Knight' (2008) shows Heath Ledger's Joker in a nurse's uniform, speaking with a crazed expression. This meme, often captioned with his line 'Nobody panics when things go according to plan,' is used to highlight hypocrisy. It contrasts a major, terrible, but accepted societal issue with a minor, often harmless, deviation that causes widespread outrage.

Jack-Sparrow-Being-Chased.name: Jack-Sparrow-Being-Chased

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Captain Jack Sparrow. It typically labels the person, entity, or concept that is frantically running away or escaping.

This text box is placed at the top of the image, acting as a caption for the entire scene, but specifically labeling the chasing mob. It describes the overwhelming force, problem, or group that is pursuing the subject labeled in box 0.

Jack-Sparrow-Being-Chased.image_description: This meme, known as "Jack Sparrow Running," originates from the film "Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest." It features Captain Jack Sparrow running frantically along a beach, pursued by a large group of cannibal islanders. The meme is used to humorously represent someone fleeing from an overwhelming situation, an undesirable responsibility, or a large, intimidating group.

throw-out-of-the-window.name: throw-out-of-the-window

text_options.description: This speech bubble belongs to the third employee who gets thrown out the window. The text here is the punchline of the meme, representing a simple, obvious, or undesirable suggestion that triggers the boss's extreme reaction.

This speech bubble is for the female employee. Her text typically contains a sensible, corporate-approved, or conventional suggestion, which serves as a setup for the third employee's contrasting and unwelcome idea.

This speech bubble belongs to the first male employee offering a suggestion. Like his female colleague, his text is usually a safe, standard business proposal that helps establish a serious tone before the punchline.
This is the boss's speech bubble in the first panel. The text here sets up the entire scenario, usually by posing a problem or asking for ideas and suggestions from the team.

throw-out-of-the-window.image_description: This meme, known as "Boardroom Suggestion," is a three-panel comic strip depicting a business meeting. In the first panel, a boss asks his employees for suggestions. In the second panel, two employees offer earnest, conventional ideas, while a third, more relaxed employee gives a simple, blunt, or undesirable opinion. The final panel shows the boss, enraged, having thrown the third employee out of the office window, humorously illustrating a comically extreme rejection of an unwelcome idea.

Maybe-i-am-a-monster-blank.name: Maybe-i-am-a-monster-blank

text_options.description: This text box is the punchline of the meme, completing the sentence "Maybe I am a...". It contains the noun or label that the subject is reluctantly realizing they embody, often something humorous, specific, or self-deprecating.

This top text area provides the context or setup for the meme. It usually contains an accusation, a description of a behavior, or a scenario that prompts the self-realization shown in the image and completed by the text in box 0.

Maybe-i-am-a-monster-blank.image_description: This meme features the Marvel character Vision from 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' looking down with a contemplative expression. The original line is "Maybe I am a monster," and the meme is used to express a moment of reluctant self-realization. It's typically used for self-deprecating humor, where a person realizes they fit a particular, often unflattering or funny, description after being accused of it or observing their own behavior.
Maybe-i-am-a-monster-blank.display_name: Maybe i am a monster blank

cnn-breaking-news-template.name: cnn-breaking-news-template

text_options.description: This is the main text area of the meme, located on the news ticker banner. It's where the user writes the fake 'breaking news' headline, which serves as the punchline. This text is typically a humorous, absurd, or relatable statement presented with mock seriousness.

This label is placed over the news anchor's face. It's used to identify the person, group, or concept that is reacting with concern to the 'breaking news' in the banner below. The anchor's serious expression is meant to represent the reaction of the entity labeled here.

cnn-breaking-news-template.image_description: This meme format features a screenshot of a CNN 'Breaking News' segment with anchor Jake Tapper looking serious. The template is used to present humorous, absurd, or relatable statements as if they are urgent, important news. The humor comes from the stark contrast between the serious news presentation and the often trivial or silly content of the user-added text.

Will-Smith-punching-Chris-Rock.name: Will-Smith-punching-Chris-Rock

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Will Smith, who is delivering the slap. The text here represents the aggressor, a powerful force, or an unexpected event that disrupts or overpowers something else.

This text box is placed over Chris Rock, the recipient of the slap. The text here represents the victim, a weaker concept, or an established plan that is being violently disrupted by the entity labeled on Will Smith.

Will-Smith-punching-Chris-Rock.image_description: This meme, known as "Will Smith Slapping Chris Rock," captures the moment actor Will Smith slaps comedian Chris Rock on stage at the 2022 Academy Awards. The image is used to represent a sudden, aggressive, or unexpected action (Will Smith) forcefully overriding or impacting a person, idea, or event (Chris Rock). It humorously illustrates a conflict where one entity completely and unexpectedly overwhelms another.

Im-tired-boss.name: Im-tired-boss

text_options.description: The punchline of the meme, containing the original quote "I'm tired, boss." This text is almost always kept as is, as it delivers the core emotion of exhaustion and is the most recognizable part of the format.

The setup text, placed at the top of the image. This area is used to describe the specific context or scenario that is causing the feeling of exhaustion, making the meme relatable to a wide range of experiences.

Im-tired-boss.image_description: This meme features a close-up of John Coffey, played by Michael Clarke Duncan, from the 1999 film "The Green Mile." With a weary and sorrowful expression, he delivers the line "I'm tired, boss." The meme is used to express a profound sense of physical, mental, or emotional exhaustion and burnout, often in response to overwhelming or frustrating situations in everyday life, work, or gaming.

Walter-White-Screaming-At-Hank.name: Walter-White-Screaming-At-Hank

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the setup for the joke. It describes a seemingly normal or mundane situation, action, or statement.

The top text box delivers the punchline, which is a shocking, disturbing, or unexpected twist to the setup described below. The contrast between the mundane setup and the horrifying punchline is what creates the humor, with Walter's expression acting as the reaction.

Walter-White-Screaming-At-Hank.image_description: This meme features the character Walter White from the TV series 'Breaking Bad', looking out of a car window with an expression of pure horror and shock. The scene captures a moment of intense distress and is used as a reaction image to express disbelief, despair, or shock at a preceding statement or revelation. The meme format often contrasts an innocent setup with a disturbing punchline, with Walter's face representing the reaction to the twist.

Cheating-Coldplay.name: Cheating-Coldplay

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Bill Simmons' wife. It represents the person, entity, or concept that is in an awkward, uncomfortable, or compromised position, often being held or presented by the entity behind them.

This text box is placed over the smiling Bill Simmons. It represents the person or force that is obliviously or cheerfully causing the awkward situation, exposing the subject in the foreground to public view or judgment.

Cheating-Coldplay.image_description: This meme, known as 'Bill Simmons on Kiss Cam,' features sports analyst Bill Simmons smiling while standing behind his wife at a sporting event, with the moment displayed on a Jumbotron. Her more reserved expression contrasts with his cheerful one, creating a sense of public awkwardness. The meme is typically used to represent a situation where someone is caught in an embarrassing or compromising position, with one party being oblivious while the other is aware of the uncomfortable scrutiny.

sleeping-Squidward.name: sleeping-Squidward

text_options.description: This text box is paired with the image of Squidward in a state of panic. The text here represents the disruptive thought, sudden realization, or stressful information that shatters the calm from the top panel, serving as the punchline.

This text box is placed next to the peacefully sleeping Squidward. The text here typically describes a calm, desirable, or ignorant state, setting up the initial peaceful scenario before the panic-inducing realization.

sleeping-Squidward.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Sleeping Squidward" or "Squidward's Clock," features the character Squidward Tentacles from SpongeBob SquarePants. The top panel depicts him sleeping peacefully, representing a state of calm or ignorance. In contrast, the bottom panel is a dramatic, red-tinted close-up of his wide-awake, bloodshot eyes, signifying a sudden, jarring realization or panic. The meme is used to contrast a peaceful situation with a sudden, stressful thought, like relaxing versus remembering an overdue assignment.

big-yellow-ball-and.name: big-yellow-ball-and

text_options.description: This text on the yellow orb in the bottom panel is typically identical to the text at index 2. It represents the desired goal or outcome that is now being thwarted, emphasizing the character's frustration.

This text labels the large pink character, representing the obstacle, responsibility, or unexpected problem that prevents the main character from achieving their goal. This element introduces the conflict and serves as the punchline.
This text on the yellow orb in the top panel describes a desirable goal, a positive plan, or something the protagonist wants to achieve. It sets up the initial, hopeful scenario.
This text typically labels the white character, often with "Me" or a description of a person with a specific intention. It establishes the protagonist of the meme's narrative.

big-yellow-ball-and.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as "Running Away Balloon" or "Pink Guy Holding Back," illustrates a conflict between desire and responsibility. In the top panel, a simple white character happily reaches for a yellow orb representing a goal. In the bottom panel, the character is held back by a large pink figure, representing an obstacle or duty, preventing them from reaching the now-unattainable goal.

Happy-Wojak-vs-Depressed-Wojak.name: Happy-Wojak-vs-Depressed-Wojak

text_options.description: This text box, placed next to the distressed Wojak, contains the punchline of the meme. It describes the grim, complex, or negative reality that shatters the initial positive perception, explaining the character's transformation into a state of despair.

This text box, positioned next to the happy Wojak, sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a simple, positive, or naive viewpoint on a particular topic or situation, representing a state of blissful ignorance.

Happy-Wojak-vs-Depressed-Wojak.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format known as "Traumatized Wojak" or "Wojak Becomes Uncanny." It features two variations of the Wojak character to create a stark contrast. The top panel shows a smiling, smug Wojak representing a naive, happy, or simple perspective, while the bottom panel shows a dark, hollow-eyed, and distressed Wojak representing a subsequent grim realization or traumatic understanding. The meme is used to illustrate a shift from a positive or ignorant state to one of horror, disillusionment, or deep sadness upon learning more about a situation.

Happy-Star-Congratulations.name: Happy-Star-Congratulations

text_options.description: Located above the word 'Signed', this text box is for the signature of the authority figure granting the award. In the meme, this is often a sarcastic or absurd name to enhance the comedic effect of the trivial achievement being celebrated.
This text box is traditionally for the date of the award. In the meme, it can be used for a secondary punchline, a relevant date, or left blank, as it's less central to the main joke.
Following the word 'for', this text box contains the core punchline of the meme. It describes the mundane, unimpressive, or ridiculous 'achievement' that is being sarcastically celebrated.
Following the words 'Presented to', this text box is for the name of the recipient of the 'award'. This can be a person, a group, or an abstract concept that is the target of the joke.

Happy-Star-Congratulations.image_description: The "Congratulations Certificate" meme features a colorful, child-like award certificate with a smiling star. This format is used ironically to "congratulate" someone for a very low-effort, mundane, or dubious achievement. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the enthusiastic award and the trivial or nonsensical reason for it, often highlighting a "participation trophy" culture or simply making a sarcastic point.

A-center-for-ants.name: A-center-for-ants

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the architectural model. It is used to label the object that is being ridiculed for its small size, representing the "center for ants" in the original quote.

This is the top text area where the punchline is written, typically following the format "What is this? A [something] for ants?" This text sets up the joke by posing a rhetorical question that highlights the perceived smallness of the object labeled in box 0.

A-center-for-ants.image_description: This meme features Ben Stiller as the clueless male model Derek Zoolander from the 2001 film "Zoolander." In the scene, he is presented with an architectural model for a school and, failing to understand scale, angrily asks, "What is this? A center for ants?" The meme is used to humorously question or mock the surprisingly small size of an object or concept.

Badass-Skeleton.name: Badass-Skeleton

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, typically serving as the punchline or the main statement. This text often describes a mundane activity, a strong personal opinion on a trivial matter, or an absurdly aggressive take on a simple situation, which contrasts humorously with the intimidating skeleton.
The top text of the meme, which acts as the setup or introduces the topic. It often poses a question or sets a scene that the bottom text will then react to, establishing the context for the joke.

Badass-Skeleton.image_description: This meme features a menacing skeleton, reminiscent of the Grim Reaper, wearing a black hooded cloak and pointing two revolvers at the viewer. The image is a popular template from online communities like /r/THE_PACK, known for its ironically "badass" and "edgy" aesthetic. The humor comes from pairing this intense, hyper-masculine imagery with text that is often mundane, wholesome, or absurdly specific, creating a comedic contrast.

I-love-the-smell-of-napalm-in-the-mornin.name: I-love-the-smell-of-napalm-in-the-morning

text_options.description: The bottom text describes the chaotic, stressful, or negative situation that is occurring. It sets the scene of turmoil that affects the soldiers in the foreground and serves as the source of distress for most people.

The top text represents the perspective of the person or entity (symbolized by Kilgore) who is unfazed or even finds enjoyment in the chaos described by the bottom text. This caption highlights their unusual and often darkly humorous positive reaction to the negative situation.

I-love-the-smell-of-napalm-in-the-mornin.image_description: This meme originates from a scene in the 1979 film "Apocalypse Now," featuring Lieutenant Colonel Bill Kilgore amidst a chaotic battlefield. Kilgore, the shirtless man in the cavalry hat, appears calm and even pleased by the surrounding destruction, famously saying, "I love the smell of napalm in the morning." The meme is used to contrast someone who thrives in or enjoys a chaotic, stressful situation with others who are overwhelmed by it.
I-love-the-smell-of-napalm-in-the-mornin.display_name: I love the smell of napalm in the morning

the-silent-protector.name: the-silent-protector

text_options.description: This label is placed on the sleeping person in bed. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is oblivious to or benefiting from the protector's sacrifice. This is the entity being 'protected'.

This label is on the soldier who is taking damage. The text here represents the 'protector' or the entity making a sacrifice, often for a cause that is portrayed as trivial or humorous in the meme's context.

This label is placed over the incoming projectiles (knives, grenades, bullets). The text here describes the 'dangers' or annoyances that the protector is shielding the sleeping person from. In the meme, these are typically exaggerated or mundane problems.

the-silent-protector.image_description: The "Silent Protector" meme is an exploitable comic panel showing a soldier in camouflage kneeling to shield a sleeping person from a barrage of projectiles like knives, bullets, and grenades. The soldier is depicted as wounded and on fire, symbolizing a great sacrifice. This meme format is used ironically to portray someone or something making a trivial or absurd sacrifice to protect an oblivious party from minor inconveniences or perceived threats.

2-nickels.name: 2-nickels

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme: "Which isn't a lot, but it's weird that it happened twice." This text is placed on the bottom panel to align with Doofenshmirtz's shocked expression, emphasizing the surprising and strange nature of the coincidence he has just realized.

This text box typically contains the setup of the meme's phrase: "If I had a nickel for every time [a specific, weird event happened], I'd have two nickels." This text establishes the hypothetical scenario and is placed on the top panel where Doofenshmirtz looks like he is beginning a story or making a statement.

2-nickels.image_description: This two-panel meme features Dr. Doofenshmirtz from the animated series "Phineas and Ferb." In the top panel, he looks confident while presenting something, and in the bottom panel, his expression shifts to one of shock and concern. The format is used for the "If I had a nickel for every time X, I'd have two nickels" meme, which points out a specific and strange coincidence that has happened twice. The humor comes from the realization that while two occurrences aren't many, the fact that such a bizarre event happened more than once is noteworthy.

Oh-dear-dear-gorgeus.name: Oh-dear-dear-gorgeus

text_options.description: This text box labels the person, group, or concept that is being harshly criticized or treated with disdain, corresponding to Ramsay's insult "You fucking donkey."
This text box labels the person, group, or concept that is treated with care, praise, or favoritism, corresponding to Ramsay's gentle demeanor towards the child.

Oh-dear-dear-gorgeus.image_description: This is a two-panel meme featuring celebrity chef Gordon Ramsay, showcasing his contrasting personas. On the left, he is gentle and encouraging towards a young girl, with the caption "Oh dear, oh dear. Gorgeous." On the right, he is angry and insulting, with the caption "You fucking donkey." The meme is used to represent a stark difference in how someone treats two different things, often to highlight hypocrisy, favoritism, or a strong preference.

Blank-T-Shirt.name: Blank-T-Shirt

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the shirt contains the punchline or the 'lousy' part of the souvenir. It's typically a short, often self-deprecating or ironic phrase that describes the outcome or consequence of the subject mentioned above, completing the classic "...and all I got was..." joke structure.

The main chest area of the t-shirt is where the subject of the meme is placed. This is usually text or an image representing a place, event, fandom, or personal struggle (e.g., "I survived the 2020 pandemic," a band logo, or "Anxiety"). It sets up the context for the punchline below.

Blank-T-Shirt.image_description: This meme format uses a plain black t-shirt as a template to make a statement about an experience or identity. It follows the classic souvenir t-shirt trope, often expressed as "I went to [place/event] and all I got was this lousy t-shirt."
