The meme is used to humorously or ironically summarize the net result or key takeaway from being part of a group, attending an event, or having a particular condition.

my-aunts-wedding.name: my-aunts-wedding

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the man in the suit, representing the "after" or improved state. The text here describes the superior, more desirable, or upgraded version of the subject being compared.

This text box is positioned over the casually dressed man, representing the "before" state. The text in this area typically describes the initial, inferior, or less developed version of a concept, setting up the comparison.

my-aunts-wedding.image_description: This meme, often featuring YouTuber Fernanfloo, presents a two-panel "glow-up" or transformation format. On the left, a young man is dressed casually in a hoodie and pajama pants, representing a "before" or less desirable state. On the right, the same person is dressed smartly in a suit, symbolizing an "after" or superior state. The meme is used to contrast two things, humorously highlighting a significant improvement, upgrade, or positive change between them.

For-Dummies.name: For-Dummies

text_options.description: This space is often used for a secondary punchline, a subtitle, or the name of the fictional author. It's less crucial than the main title but can be used to add another layer to the joke. In many variations of the meme, this area is left blank.
This is the main title area of the book cover. Users insert the subject of the joke here, which can be a person, an idea, or an activity that is being mocked or oversimplified.

For-Dummies.image_description: This meme template is based on the iconic cover of the 'For Dummies' series of instructional books. The format is used to satirize or mock a person, group, or concept by suggesting a simplified guide is needed for them. By placing a subject on the cover, the meme implies that the subject is basic, foolish, or needs to be explained in the simplest possible terms.

side-eye-teddy.name: side-eye-teddy

text_options.description: This text box, located at the bottom of the image, typically labels the person or group who is experiencing the awkward situation. It represents the subject of the meme who is giving the guilty side-eye.

This text box at the top of the image describes the awkward situation, question, or statement that causes the puppet's reaction. It provides the context that makes the subsequent side-glance funny and relatable.

side-eye-teddy.image_description: This meme, known as "Monkey Puppet" or "Awkward Look Monkey Puppet," features a two-panel image of a puppet character named Kenta. In the first frame, the puppet looks forward, and in the second, it nervously darts its eyes to the side. The meme is used to humorously depict a person's guilty or uncomfortable reaction when caught in an awkward situation or confronted with an inconvenient truth.

I-Was-Told-There-Would-Be.name: I-Was-Told-There-Would-Be

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Milton's desk and hands, delivers the punchline. It typically contains a variation of Milton's passive-aggressive lines from the movie, such as "I was told..." or "I'm going to have to ask you to..." followed by a complaint or an extreme, often violent, threat in response to the setup text.

The top text, positioned above Milton's head, sets up the scenario for the meme. This text describes an annoying situation, an unreasonable request from a boss or authority figure, or a frustrating event that prompts Milton's reaction.

I-Was-Told-There-Would-Be.image_description: This meme features Milton Waddams, a character from the 1999 film "Office Space," sitting at his desk in a cubicle. Milton is a meek and mumbling office worker who is famously possessive of his red stapler. The meme is used to express passive-aggressive frustration or a disproportionately angry reaction to a minor annoyance or unreasonable request, often threatening to "burn the building down," as Milton does in the movie.
I-Was-Told-There-Would-Be.display_name: I Was Told There Would Be

Red-MM-angry.name: Red-MM-angry

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the character, typically contains the punchline or the specific mischievous action or thought that the user is having. This text reveals the reason for the character's smug expression.
The top text, placed above the character's head, sets up the scenario or context for the meme. It describes a situation that prompts the reaction depicted by the red M&M.

Red-MM-angry.image_description: This is a low-resolution, deep-fried meme featuring the red M&M character. He has a sinister, smug grin and is holding up his fists in a vaguely threatening or confident manner. The meme is typically used to express a feeling of mischievousness, smug satisfaction, or a humorous, low-stakes threat after outsmarting someone or planning something chaotic.

Virgin-and-Chad.name: Virgin-and-Chad

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the "Chad" character. It is intended to be filled with the name of a person, object, or concept that the creator deems superior, desirable, or correct in the comparison.

This text box is located above the "Virgin" character. It is meant to be labeled with the name of a person, object, or concept that is being portrayed as inferior, weak, or undesirable in the context of the meme's comparison.

Virgin-and-Chad.image_description: This is the "Virgin vs. Chad" meme, a popular exploitable format used for comparing two subjects. The "Virgin" character on the left is depicted as a slumped, insecure, and undesirable figure, representing the inferior option. In contrast, the "Chad" on the right is a confident, muscular, and absurdly postured figure representing the superior option. The meme satirically highlights the perceived flaws of one subject and the exaggerated strengths of another, often with a humorous and ironic tone.

party-loner.name: party-loner

text_options.description: This label is placed on one of the happy, dancing couples. Text here typically represents the oblivious, socially engaged crowd, often labeled with a generic social activity or a mainstream interest that contrasts with the main character's thoughts.

This label is on the second dancing couple, further emphasizing the lively party atmosphere from which the main character is disconnected. The text here serves the same purpose as the other group, representing the mainstream social scene.

This area functions as a thought bubble for the isolated Wojak character. The text here is the punchline, revealing his internal monologue, which usually starts with 'They don't know...' followed by an obscure fact, a niche interest, or a personal secret that sets him apart from the others.

party-loner.image_description: This meme, known as 'They Don't Know' or 'I Wish I Was at Home,' features a Wojak character wearing a party hat and standing alone in a corner, looking sad and isolated. In the foreground, other crudely drawn figures are happily dancing and socializing, completely unaware of the main character's internal state. The meme is used to express feelings of social anxiety, having niche interests that others don't understand, or being in a situation where one feels out of place.

Beyonc--Tiffany-Pollard.name: Beyonc--Tiffany-Pollard

text_options.description: The bottom text, often a punchline or an internal thought. It represents the reaction of the observer (personified by Tiffany Pollard) to the event described in the top text. This text completes the cause-and-effect setup of the meme.
The top text, which sets up the scenario. This caption typically describes an action, statement, or situation that is shocking, unexpected, or dramatic, prompting the reaction seen in the image.

Beyonc--Tiffany-Pollard.image_description: This meme features reality TV star Tiffany "New York" Pollard from the show 'Flavor of Love', looking shocked with wide eyes and an open mouth. The image captures a moment of intense, almost theatrical surprise or disbelief. It is widely used as a reaction image to express shock, astonishment, or to represent someone witnessing drama unfold, often in a humorous or exaggerated way.

Face-You-Make-Robert-Downey-Jr.name: Face-You-Make-Robert-Downey-Jr

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the punchline or the specific, often cringeworthy or frustrating, statement/action that causes the exasperated reaction. It acts as a caption that clarifies what Tony Stark is reacting to, making his eye-roll the visual punchline.
The top text box sets up the scenario or presents a general statement that the meme creator finds annoying or foolish. This text provides the context for Tony Stark's subsequent reaction.

Face-You-Make-Robert-Downey-Jr.image_description: This meme features actor Robert Downey Jr. as his character Tony Stark from the Marvel Cinematic Universe, often referred to as 'Tony Stark Eye Roll' or 'Stark's Reaction'. He is shown with his arms crossed and rolling his eyes back in an expression of extreme annoyance, exasperation, or disbelief. The meme is typically used as a two-panel reaction image to express frustration or sarcasm towards a statement, situation, or another person's foolishness.
Face-You-Make-Robert-Downey-Jr.display_name: Face You Make Robert Downey Jr

Tony-Soprano-in-this-house.name: Tony-Soprano-in-this-house

text_options.description: This bottom text represents Tony Soprano's loud and assertive response or punchline. It's typically a strong opinion, a demand, or an exclamation that directly addresses the setup text above, matching his aggressive posture and expression.
The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It usually presents a situation, a question, or a statement that will provoke Tony Soprano's passionate reaction in the text below.

Tony-Soprano-in-this-house.image_description: A meme featuring Tony Soprano from the TV show 'The Sopranos', looking angry and yelling while pointing his finger. He is wearing a white undershirt and a bathrobe. This image is used as a two-panel reaction meme to express a strong, often comically aggressive or passionate opinion in response to a preceding statement.

Wont-somebody-think-of-the-children.name: Wont-somebody-think-of-the-children

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically contains the punchline and the meme's namesake phrase, "Won't somebody please think of the children?" or a creative variation. It represents the exaggerated, often disingenuous, plea that is the core of the meme's humor.

The top text area is used to establish the context or the subject that prompts the panicked reaction. This text usually describes a trivial, controversial, or modern trend that the meme's subject is overreacting to, setting up the joke.

Wont-somebody-think-of-the-children.image_description: This meme features a distressed-looking woman from the animated series The Simpsons, with a panicked expression. Known as "Won't somebody please think of the children?", the meme is used to satirize moral panic, over-the-top emotional appeals, or feigned concern. The format juxtaposes the character's extreme distress with a typically mundane or trivial issue, mocking the overreaction.
Wont-somebody-think-of-the-children.display_name: Wont somebody think of the children

Spongebob-Waiting.name: Spongebob-Waiting

text_options.description: This bottom text area represents the person or entity experiencing the sad situation. It's often labeled with 'Me' or a specific group to establish the subject of the meme's punchline.

The top text provides the context or the specific reason for the character's dejection. This caption acts as the punchline, explaining the disappointing event that led to the moment of sad contemplation.

Spongebob-Waiting.image_description: This meme features SpongeBob SquarePants from the show of the same name, sitting alone in a diner with a forlorn expression. The image is used to convey feelings of loneliness, disappointment, or deep contemplation after being left out or experiencing a minor setback. Known as 'Contemplative SpongeBob' or 'SpongeBob Waiting,' its humor comes from exaggerating relatable moments of isolation.

Im-tired-of-pretending-its-not.name: Im-tired-of-pretending-its-not

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the Joker. The text here represents the negative consequence or the entity delivering the comeuppance. It's the punchline of the meme, representing the "deserved" outcome for the action or statement in the top panel.

This text box is placed over the talk show host, Murray Franklin. The text here typically describes a person, group, or action that is seen as arrogant, overconfident, or deserving of a negative repercussion. This sets up the premise for the punchline in the bottom panel.

Im-tired-of-pretending-its-not.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the 2019 film "Joker." The top panel shows talk show host Murray Franklin (Robert De Niro) confronting Arthur Fleck, while the bottom panel shows Fleck in his Joker persona (Joaquin Phoenix) smiling chillingly back at him. The meme, known as "You Get What You Fucking Deserve," is used to illustrate a cause-and-effect scenario where an arrogant or foolish action (top panel) receives a fittingly negative and deserved consequence (bottom panel).
Im-tired-of-pretending-its-not.display_name: Im tired of pretending its not

Woman-Shouting-Knives.name: Woman-Shouting-Knives

text_options.description: This label is placed on the man who is being stabbed by the knives. The text here identifies the victim or recipient of the harsh words, who is being emotionally wounded.
This label is placed on the woman yelling the knives. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity delivering the hurtful, critical, or damaging words.

Woman-Shouting-Knives.image_description: This meme, often called "Words Are Like Knives," depicts a woman yelling, with knives flying out of her mouth and stabbing a man in the chest. The man recoils in pain, bleeding from his wounds. The meme is a literal and dramatic illustration of the saying "words can cut like a knife," used to represent someone saying something extremely hurtful, critical, or emotionally damaging to another person.

Note-passing.name: Note-passing

text_options.description: This text is placed on the note being read by the angry character. It contains the punchline of the meme—a statement, fact, or opinion that is infuriating, disappointing, or absurd, causing the character's angry reaction and subverting the neutral context of the first panel.

This area typically labels the two characters involved in the exchange. The character on the left is the giver of the information (the note), and the character on the right is the recipient. These labels set up the context for the interaction before the punchline is revealed.

Note-passing.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as "Passing Notes" or "Angry Note," depicts a classroom scene where one student passes a note to another. The first panel shows the seemingly innocuous exchange, while the second panel reveals the recipient's angry reaction after reading the note. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where an initial offer, statement, or piece of information leads to an unexpectedly frustrating or disappointing outcome, with the note's content serving as the infuriating punchline.

Old-man-yells-at-cloud.name: Old-man-yells-at-cloud

text_options.description: This area shows the cartoon image of Grampa Simpson yelling. In meme variations, this image is often replaced by a picture of the person or entity being mocked for their perceived out-of-touch or irrational complaint.

The newspaper headline, originally "OLD MAN YELLS AT CLOUD". The word "CLOUD" is the key element that is typically edited. It's replaced with the name of a modern trend, technology, or concept that someone is complaining about, framing their complaint as absurd and pointless.

Old-man-yells-at-cloud.image_description: This meme, known as "Old Man Yells at Cloud," originates from the animated series The Simpsons. It features a newspaper with a headline about Abraham "Grampa" Simpson angrily shaking his fist at a cloud. The meme is used to satirize and dismiss opinions that are perceived as outdated, out of touch, or irrationally angry at trivial or unchangeable things, like new technology or cultural trends.

Everywhere-I-go-I-see-his-face.name: Everywhere-I-go-I-see-his-face

text_options.description: This area in the bottom panel is where the object of remembrance is displayed, often edited onto the brick wall. The accompanying text, "I see his face...", acts as the punchline, revealing what the subject is constantly seeing. In meme variations, this is where an image of the annoying or ubiquitous thing is placed.

This text box is in the top panel and introduces the setup of the meme. It represents the person or entity who is feeling overwhelmed or constantly reminded of something. The text "Everywhere I go..." establishes the feeling of inescapability.

Everywhere-I-go-I-see-his-face.image_description: A two-panel meme from the movie 'Spider-Man: Far From Home' featuring Peter Parker (Spider-Man) looking sad. The original dialogue, "Everywhere I go... I see his face...", refers to him mourning his mentor, Tony Stark (Iron Man). This format is used to humorously express the feeling of being constantly and unavoidably reminded of something or someone, often replacing the image of Iron Man with a different, often annoying or funny, subject.
Everywhere-I-go-I-see-his-face.display_name: Everywhere I go I see his face

Arthur-Fist.name: Arthur-Fist

text_options.description: This bottom section is typically left blank. The clenched fist image above it serves as the entire punchline or reaction, making additional text unnecessary to convey the feeling of frustration.

The top text box describes a frustrating or annoying scenario that elicits the angry reaction. This text sets up the context for the meme, presenting the cause of the anger that Arthur's fist represents.

Arthur-Fist.image_description: This meme, known as "Arthur's Fist," features a close-up of a clenched fist from the main character of the children's animated series, "Arthur." The image is used to express intense, often suppressed, anger or frustration in response to a relatable, everyday annoyance. The humor arises from applying this strong emotion, represented by the simple cartoon fist, to various irritating situations.

Peter-Griffin-running-away.name: Peter-Griffin-running-away

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Peter Griffin and the ground he is running on. It is used to label the person, group, or entity that is trying to escape or avoid a particular situation.
Located in the sky near the pursuing biplane, this text box labels the threat, problem, or annoying entity that is chasing the subject identified in the bottom text box.

Peter-Griffin-running-away.image_description: This meme, known as 'Peter Griffin Running From Plane,' features the character Peter Griffin from the animated show 'Family Guy' frantically running away from a biplane. The scene is a parody of the famous crop-duster chase in Alfred Hitchcock's film 'North by Northwest.' The meme is used to represent a person or group desperately trying to escape an unavoidable, annoying, or overwhelming problem or entity.

Judgemental-Volturi.name: Judgemental-Volturi

text_options.description: This area contains the reaction part of the meme, featuring the three vampires. Text is not typically placed here, as their unimpressed and condescending expressions are the punchline. They represent a superior or judgmental group reacting to the statement above.

The top panel is where the setup text is placed. This text usually presents a statement, a boast, or an achievement that the user wants to frame as unimpressive or laughable from the perspective of the characters below. The humor arises from the condescending reaction of the powerful vampires to a mundane or comparatively weak statement.

Judgemental-Volturi.image_description: This meme features the Volturi, a coven of vampires from the movie "The Twilight Saga: New Moon." The central character, Aro, looks on with a smug and condescending expression, flanked by his two bored-looking companions. The meme is used as a reaction image to express that something is unimpressive, pathetic, or amusingly inferior. It's often used to mock a statement or achievement that is presented as significant but is seen as trivial by the judgmental figures.

Thats-how-you-do-it.name: Thats-how-you-do-it

text_options.description: This label is placed on the distraught child, who represents the person, group, or concept that is being overwhelmingly attacked or criticized. This is the entity that is 'already dead' metaphorically.

This label points to where the man is gesturing, representing the source of the overwhelming attack or criticism. This is the person or entity inflicting the 'damage' that the meme creator feels is excessive.

This label is on the man who is trying to stop the 'attack'. He often represents the meme creator or a third party who observes the situation and feels that the criticism or negative action has gone too far.

Thats-how-you-do-it.image_description: This meme, known as 'Stop! He's Already Dead!', originates from The Simpsons. It depicts a distressed man holding back a distraught child, gesturing for an unseen party to stop. The format is used to humorously describe a situation where someone or something is being excessively attacked, criticized, or is already suffering, implying that any further negativity is overkill.

Black-Box-Meme.name: Black-Box-Meme

text_options.description: This bottom panel represents the first, most basic, or 'small brain' level of thought. The text here establishes a common or simple idea, which serves as the starting point for the intellectual or humorous escalation.

This top panel represents the next, more 'enlightened' or 'expanded brain' level of thought. The text here presents a concept that is supposedly superior, more complex, or ironically more profound than the idea in the panel below it.

Black-Box-Meme.image_description: This is a simplified, two-panel version of the "Expanding Brain" or "Galaxy Brain" meme format. The meme is used to show a progression of intelligence or enlightenment regarding a certain topic, often in an ironic or humorous way. The bottom panel represents a simple or conventional idea, while the top panel represents a more advanced, superior, or absurdly complex thought.

I-dont-think-about-you-at-all-Mad-Men.name: I-dont-think-about-you-at-all-Mad-Men

text_options.description: This label identifies Don Draper, the character delivering the dismissive punchline. Text here represents the person, brand, or entity that is completely indifferent to the perceived rivalry or concern expressed by the other party.

This label identifies Michael Ginsberg, the character expressing pity. Text here represents the person, brand, or entity that holds a one-sided rivalry or a misplaced sense of superiority or concern for the other party.

I-dont-think-about-you-at-all-Mad-Men.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from a scene in the TV show "Mad Men" featuring characters Michael Ginsberg and Don Draper. Ginsberg expresses condescending pity towards Draper with the line "I feel bad for you," to which Draper coldly replies, "I don't think about you at all." The format is used to represent a one-sided rivalry where one party's concern or animosity is met with complete indifference by the other, delivering a powerful burn.
I-dont-think-about-you-at-all-Mad-Men.display_name: I dont think about you at all Mad Men

Jim-Halpert-Pointing-to-Whiteboard.name: Jim-Halpert-Pointing-to-Whiteboard

text_options.description: The text on the whiteboard in the bottom panel. This is the punchline, revealing the simple, often selfish or lazy, true motivation behind the elaborate plan shown in the top panel. Jim's smug expression in this panel reinforces that this was the real goal all along.

The text on the whiteboard in the top panel. This area is used for a complex, detailed, or official-sounding plan or explanation. It serves as the setup for the joke, creating a facade of reasonableness that is then subverted by the text in the second panel.

Jim-Halpert-Pointing-to-Whiteboard.image_description: This two-panel meme features Jim Halpert from the TV show "The Office." In the top panel, Jim earnestly points to a whiteboard, presenting what appears to be a complex or well-thought-out plan. In the bottom panel, he sits back with a smug smirk, looking at the camera, while the whiteboard now displays a much simpler, often selfish or comically blunt alternative. The meme is used to contrast an elaborate, official-sounding justification with the simple, underlying, and often humorous true motive.

Small-knight-giant-knight.name: Small-knight-giant-knight

text_options.description: The text here labels the small knight, representing the underdog, the challenger, or a relatable individual. This entity is facing a massive, overwhelming force, making it the focal point of the struggle.

This label is placed on the giant, Yhorm, who represents an overwhelming obstacle, a powerful adversary, or a daunting task. The text here defines the massive challenge that the smaller figure is confronting.

Small-knight-giant-knight.image_description: This meme features artwork from the video game Dark Souls III, depicting the player character (Ashen One) confronting the massive boss, Yhorm the Giant. The format is used to represent an underdog situation, where a small or seemingly insignificant entity takes on a much larger, more powerful, or overwhelming force. The stark contrast in size between the two figures creates a powerful visual metaphor for facing insurmountable odds, often with a humorous or relatable twist.

telltale-will-remember-that.name: telltale-will-remember-that

text_options.description: This area, over the character Clementine, is labeled with the person or entity who performs the minor, often awkward, action that is the subject of the meme.
This area, over the character Lee Everett, represents the person or group who witnesses the action and is comically portrayed as being deeply affected by it.

This text box is the punchline, mimicking the game's user interface. The original text "Clementine will remember that" is often edited, but it always serves to confirm that the trivial action from box 0 has been noted and will have future (comedic) consequences.

telltale-will-remember-that.image_description: This meme originates from a screenshot of Telltale Games' "The Walking Dead," featuring the characters Lee Everett and Clementine. The format, known as "[X] Will Remember That," humorously applies the game's dramatic choice-and-consequence notification to trivial, awkward, or mundane social situations. It's used to exaggerate the significance of a minor action or statement, implying it will be remembered as a major transgression.

I-dont-care-if-you-win-I-just-need-X-to-.name: I-dont-care-if-you-win-I-just-need-X-to-lose

text_options.description: This text box is on the bottom panel where General Hux has a more intense, almost shouting expression. This is where the punchline is delivered, often simply the word "Ironic," or a phrase that reveals the hypocrisy or contradiction to the setup in the top panel.

This text box is on the top panel, corresponding to General Hux's more contemplative expression. This text serves as the setup, presenting a statement, an observation, or a piece of advice that will be ironically contradicted in the second panel.

I-dont-care-if-you-win-I-just-need-X-to-.image_description: This two-panel meme features General Hux from the Star Wars sequel trilogy, looking increasingly intense. It's a variation of the "Ironic" meme format, used to point out hypocrisy or a contradictory situation. The top panel presents a statement or observation, and the bottom panel delivers the ironic punchline, revealing a twist that contradicts the initial statement.
I-dont-care-if-you-win-I-just-need-X-to-.display_name: I dont care if you win I just need X to lose

Peter-parker-reading-a-book.name: Peter-parker-reading-a-book

text_options.description: This text is on the open page of the book, where Peter Parker is pointing. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is a statement that contradicts or is a hypocritical exception to the rule or topic established on the book's cover (index 1). This revelation is what causes Peter's confused reaction in the final panel.

This text is placed on the cover of the book. It serves as the setup for the joke by establishing a general topic, rule, or statement. The humor of the meme is created by the direct contradiction between this text and the text found inside the book (index 0).

Peter-parker-reading-a-book.image_description: This three-panel meme features Peter Parker from the 1960s Spider-Man animated series reading a book. In the first panel, he holds the book, in the second he points to a specific passage, and in the third, he looks up with a concerned and confused expression. The format is used to highlight a contradiction or logical fallacy, where the book's cover presents a concept and the inside page reveals something that completely undermines or contradicts it, leading to Peter's shocked reaction.

Youre-going-to-make-me.name: Youre-going-to-make-me

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the lower part of the image, describes the specific, often mundane but difficult task that is causing the strained expression. This is the punchline that contextualizes her face as a reaction to an overwhelming effort.
The top text, placed above the subject's face, sets up the scenario or identifies the person experiencing the struggle. It provides the context for the punchline that follows below.

Youre-going-to-make-me.image_description: This meme features a close-up of adult film actress Riley Reid with a strained and pained expression. The image is taken out of its original context and used to humorously represent feelings of intense struggle, stress, or being overwhelmed. It's typically used in a top-text, bottom-text format to depict a relatable, difficult, or frustrating situation, where the expression exaggerates the struggle for comedic effect.

What-did-it-cost.name: What-did-it-cost

text_options.description: This is the final panel and the punchline of the meme. It contains Thanos's solemn answer, revealing the price of his achievement. The original and most common text is "Everything," but it's often replaced with a specific, often humorous or relatable, sacrifice.

This panel contains the pivotal question from young Gamora that sets up the punchline. The text here is almost always "What did it cost?", directly inquiring about the sacrifice made to achieve the goal mentioned in the previous panels.

This panel shows Thanos's initial, often simple, response confirming his success. The text is typically a short, affirmative answer like "Yes.", which confirms the action from the first panel was completed.

This is the first panel, where young Gamora poses an initial question to Thanos. The text here usually establishes the context by asking if a specific task was completed, for example, "Did you do it?".

What-did-it-cost.image_description: This four-panel meme format, known as "What Did It Cost? Everything," originates from a scene in the film *Avengers: Infinity War*. It features the villain Thanos speaking with a vision of his young adopted daughter, Gamora. The meme illustrates a scenario where someone achieves a goal but at a great personal sacrifice, with Gamora asking about the cost and Thanos solemnly revealing it.

Heres-Johnny.name: Heres-Johnny

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image usually serves as the punchline, revealing the object of Jack's intense desire or the reason for his forceful entry. This is what he is breaking down the door to get to.
The text at the top of the image typically identifies the person or entity represented by Jack Torrance. It sets up the context for his aggressive intrusion.

Heres-Johnny.image_description: This meme features Jack Nicholson as Jack Torrance from the 1980 film 'The Shining,' peering maniacally through a hole in a door he just chopped open. Known as the 'Here's Johnny!' meme, it's used to humorously depict an intense, obsessive, or intrusive desire for something. The format typically shows Jack representing a person or entity, while the text explains what they are so desperately trying to reach.

Mr-bean-copying.name: Mr-bean-copying

text_options.description: This label is placed over Mr. Bean. The text here represents the person, company, or entity that is copying, imitating, or stealing work from someone else. This character embodies the role of the less knowledgeable or less original party in the comparison.

This label is placed over the student Mr. Bean is copying from. The text here represents the original creator, the knowledgeable source, or the entity that is being copied. This character is portrayed as the competent or original party in the scenario.

Mr-bean-copying.image_description: This meme, known as "Mr. Bean Cheating," originates from the British sitcom "Mr. Bean." It depicts the titular character, played by Rowan Atkinson, comically trying to copy answers from a fellow student during an exam. The meme is used to represent situations where one entity (Mr. Bean) blatantly and often poorly imitates or steals ideas from another, more competent entity (the other student).

Undertaker-teleports-behind-AJ-Styles.name: Undertaker-teleports-behind-AJ-Styles

text_options.description: This text box labels AJ Styles, who represents a person, group, or idea that is happy, overconfident, or blissfully ignorant of a looming problem. This is the setup of the joke, showing the 'victim' before the inevitable negative event occurs.

This text box labels The Undertaker, representing the impending threat, unavoidable responsibility, or negative consequence that is about to strike. This label serves as the punchline, revealing the danger that the subject in the foreground is unaware of.

Undertaker-teleports-behind-AJ-Styles.image_description: This meme, known as "Undertaker Standing Behind AJ Styles," originates from a WWE WrestleMania match. It depicts the wrestler The Undertaker ominously appearing behind a cheerful and unsuspecting AJ Styles. The format is used to represent an impending doom or an inevitable, often negative, consequence that is about to catch someone off guard. The humor lies in the dramatic irony of the oblivious subject being stalked by a powerful, unavoidable threat.

Vicious-cycle.name: Vicious-cycle

text_options.description: This text box, located on the first arrow pointing upwards, represents the initial step or starting condition of the cycle. It sets the entire sequence in motion.
Positioned on the second arrow pointing to the right, this text describes the consequence or the next action that directly follows the initial step (0).
This text, on the third arrow pointing downwards, outlines the third stage of the process, which results from the second step (1) and continues the cycle.
Located on the final arrow pointing left, this text describes the concluding action or outcome that leads back to the initial state (0), thus completing and restarting the loop.

Vicious-cycle.image_description: This meme template features four arrows arranged in a square, pointing clockwise to illustrate a self-perpetuating cycle. Each arrow represents a step in a process that leads to the next, ultimately looping back to the beginning. The format is used to humorously or critically depict vicious cycles, feedback loops, or any recurring sequence of events.

Yes-Dear.name: Yes-Dear

text_options.description: This text box is positioned under the sad, aged Wojak. It typically contains a label or description that contrasts with the one on the left, representing a more negative, complex, or unfortunate perspective or outcome. This creates the punchline of the meme by highlighting a stark, often humorous or depressing, difference.

This text box is located under the female Wojak character. It is used to label the first subject of the comparison, often representing a "normal," simple, or positive viewpoint or group. This sets up the premise of the meme before the contrasting punchline is revealed on the right.

Yes-Dear.image_description: This is a Wojak comparison meme featuring two characters side-by-side. On the left is a female Wojak, often called "Trad Girl," looking composed, and on the right is a withered, sad Wojak, representing a defeated or distressed individual. The meme format contrasts two different groups, perspectives, or outcomes, typically portraying the female side as simple and positive and the male side as complex and negative. This template is used to highlight ironic or humorous differences in how different people react to the same situation.

Swerving-Car.name: Swerving-Car

text_options.description: This label is placed on the swerving car. The text here identifies the subject of the meme – the person or entity making the abrupt and impulsive decision.
This label is on the right side of the highway sign, indicating the exit ramp. The text here represents the impulsive, tempting, or often negative choice that the subject suddenly decides to pursue.
This label is on the left side of the highway sign, indicating the path straight ahead. The text here represents the sensible, responsible, or expected path that the subject chooses to abandon.

Swerving-Car.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Left Exit 12 Off-Ramp," contrasts a rational choice with an impulsive one. The top panel shows a highway sign with two options, while the bottom panel depicts a car recklessly swerving to take the off-ramp at the last second. The meme is used to humorously illustrate someone making a sudden, chaotic, or poor decision over a more sensible or planned-out alternative.

screaming-seagull.name: screaming-seagull

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the 'screaming' seagull in the bottom panel. It contains the punchline or the loud, emphatic statement that is being yelled. The text is often in all caps to convey volume and is the comedic payoff to the setup in the top panel.

This text box is in the top panel, next to the 'inhaling' seagull. It typically contains the setup, a quiet thought, or a preceding line of dialogue that prompts the outburst shown in the bottom panel. It represents the moment of restraint before the loud reaction.

screaming-seagull.image_description: The 'Inhaling Seagull' meme is a two-panel image macro. The top panel shows a seagull with its neck pulled back, seemingly taking a deep breath or holding something in. The bottom panel depicts the same seagull with its beak wide open, appearing to scream, with a red overlay and motion blur to emphasize loudness and intensity. The meme is used to contrast a quiet or internal thought (top) with a loud, unrestrained outburst or statement (bottom).

Objects-in-mirror-are-closer-than-they-a.name: Objects-in-mirror-are-closer-than-they-appear

text_options.description: Text placed on the runner's shirt in the final panel. This label represents the primary subject of the meme – the inevitable problem, person, or concept that is relentlessly pursuing the driver. It serves as the punchline, revealing the source of the driver's anxiety.

Text placed on the runner as seen in the car's side mirror. This label typically mirrors the text in the final panel, representing the approaching threat that the driver is just becoming aware of. It helps build the narrative of a problem getting closer.

Objects-in-mirror-are-closer-than-they-a.image_description: This four-panel comic, known as "Objects In Mirror Are Closer Than They Appear" or "Fast Guy", depicts a nervous driver being pursued by a relentlessly fast runner. The driver represents someone trying to escape a situation, while the runner, often labeled "Fast Guy," symbolizes an inevitable or rapidly approaching problem, responsibility, or concept. The meme's humor and relatability come from personifying abstract anxieties as an absurdly fast individual who can catch up to a car.
Objects-in-mirror-are-closer-than-they-a.display_name: Objects in mirror are closer than they appear

venn-diagram.name: venn-diagram

text_options.description: This central text box is in the overlapping section of the two circles. It contains the punchline of the meme, describing the unexpected or funny characteristic that the two subjects share.

Located at the bottom of the overlapping section, this text box serves a similar purpose to the central one (index 0). It typically contains the shared trait or punchline, sometimes as an alternative or additional label.
This text box is within the right circle's non-overlapping area. It is used to label the second subject or list a characteristic that is unique to it, setting up one side of the comparison.

venn-diagram.image_description: This is a Venn diagram meme template featuring two overlapping circles. The format is used to compare two different subjects, with the non-overlapping sections listing their unique qualities. The central, overlapping section is reserved for a surprising or humorous trait that they both share, which serves as the punchline of the meme.

Am-I-The-Only-One-Around-Here.name: Am-I-The-Only-One-Around-Here

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which completes the question started at the top. This is where the user places their specific grievance, opinion, or observation they believe is being overlooked, for example, "Who uses a turn signal?".
The top text of the meme, which almost always reads "Am I the Only One Around Here". This text sets up the rhetorical question and establishes the meme's format, expressing the user's exasperation.

Am-I-The-Only-One-Around-Here.image_description: This meme features Walter Sobchak, a character played by John Goodman in the 1998 film 'The Big Lebowski'. In the image, Walter is in a bowling alley, looking stern and holding up a handgun. The meme format is known as "Am I the Only One Around Here" and is used to express frustration or a strong, often common-sense opinion that the user feels is being ignored by everyone else.
Am-I-The-Only-One-Around-Here.display_name: Am I The Only One Around Here

Captain-Kirk-Khan.name: Captain-Kirk-Khan

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Kirk's mouth and lower face, is the punchline of the meme. It typically contains the name or object of his rage, written in all caps to represent a loud, furious scream (e.g., 'ROOMMATE!').
The top text serves as the setup, describing a situation that would provoke an extremely angry or frustrated reaction. This context builds up to the outburst depicted in the image.

Captain-Kirk-Khan.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Captain Kirk, played by William Shatner, from the film 'Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan.' The image captures Kirk in a moment of pure rage, screaming with a contorted face. This meme, often called 'Screaming Kirk' or 'KHAAAN!', is used to express intense frustration, anger, or hatred towards a specific person, thing, or situation.

Angry-lady-cat.name: Angry-lady-cat

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the cat, Smudge. It typically contains the cat's deadpan, witty, or literal response to the accusation from the other panel. This text serves as the punchline, humorously undermining the emotional outburst of the woman.

This text box is positioned over the yelling woman, Taylor Armstrong. The text here represents an emotional accusation, a dramatic statement, or an unreasonable complaint directed at the cat. This serves as the setup for the meme's joke.

Angry-lady-cat.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Woman Yelling at a Cat," juxtaposes a screenshot of Taylor Armstrong from "The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills" emotionally yelling and pointing, with a photo of a confused-looking white cat named Smudge sitting at a dinner table behind a plate of salad. The meme format is used to represent a conflict where one party (the woman) makes an emotional, often irrational, accusation, and the other party (the cat) responds with a calm, literal, or witty comeback, creating a humorous contrast.

Sad-Hamster.name: Sad-Hamster

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the hamster's face, typically identifies the person or entity having the panicked reaction. This text works as the punchline, connecting the hamster's expression of shock to the subject who is reacting to the situation described in the top text.

The top text sets up the scenario or poses a question that elicits the hamster's fearful or shocked reaction. It provides the context for the punchline, often describing an action, statement, or situation that would cause someone to freeze in panic or guilt.

Sad-Hamster.image_description: This meme features a blurry, low-resolution close-up of a hamster with wide, dark eyes staring directly into the camera. Known as the "Staring Hamster" or "Scared Hamster," its expression conveys intense shock, fear, or a sudden, awkward realization. The meme is typically used as a reaction image to represent someone being caught, judged, or confronted with an uncomfortable truth, often with a sense of comedic panic.

Silence-Crab.name: Silence-Crab

text_options.description: This text box labels the target being silenced or destroyed by the laser crab. It typically contains the name of a group, ideology, brand, or individual that the meme creator wishes to dismiss, such as "Liberal," "Brand," or "Boomer."

This text box contains the command issued by the powerful crab. It almost always begins with "silence," followed by the label placed in box 0, forming a complete dismissive phrase like "silence, brand."

Silence-Crab.image_description: This is a surreal, edited meme image known as "Silence, Liberal" or "Silence, Brand." It depicts two giant spider crabs, likely in a museum display, where the top crab is shooting blue lasers from its eyes at the bottom crab, which is exploding. The meme is used to express a forceful and often absurd dismissal of an opinion, group, or brand, with the laser-eyed crab representing a powerful entity silencing another.

Knights-of-the-Round-Table.name: Knights-of-the-Round-Table

text_options.description: This text is placed at the center of the table where all the swords meet. It represents the common idea, goal, or action that all the labeled parties agree upon, serving as the core subject or punchline of the meme.
This label is placed over the knight on the right. The text here identifies one of the parties, individuals, or groups involved in the agreement.
This label is placed over the central figure, the king. The text here identifies the main person or another key entity that is part of the unanimous decision.
This label is placed over the knight on the left. The text here identifies another one of the parties, individuals, or groups that support the central idea, reinforcing the theme of unity.

Knights-of-the-Round-Table.image_description: This meme, known as 'Knights of the Round Table,' features a fantasy illustration of a king and his knights standing around a stone table, all pointing their swords towards the center in a gesture of unity. The solemn and epic atmosphere of the image is used ironically to represent different people or groups coming to a unanimous agreement on a topic. This topic is often something mundane, humorous, or a shared relatable experience, highlighting a moment of unexpected solidarity.

Squid-Game-Season-1-vs-Season-2.name: Squid-Game-Season-1-vs-Season-2

text_options.description: This text label, positioned next to the character's grim expression, describes the negative, harsh, or disappointing reality that follows the initial scenario. It serves as the punchline, representing the 'after' state or the disillusioning outcome.
This text label, placed next to the smiling character, describes a positive, optimistic, or naive scenario. It represents the 'before' state or the initial expectation in the meme's comparison.

Squid-Game-Season-1-vs-Season-2.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Seong Gi-hun from the popular Netflix series 'Squid Game.' The top image shows him smiling brightly, representing a state of happiness, naivety, or high expectations. In contrast, the bottom image shows him with a grim, serious expression, symbolizing the harsh reality, disillusionment, or negative outcome that follows. The meme is used to compare an optimistic 'before' state with a disappointing 'after' state.

But-It-Might-Work-For-Us.name: But-It-Might-Work-For-Us

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the first panel of the meme. It typically contains text that identifies the specific group of "people" for whom the action failed, setting up the rest of the dialogue. For example, if the topic is a failed ideology, this box might list countries that tried it.

This text box is positioned at the very top of the meme, acting as a title or a label for the subject being discussed. It introduces the flawed idea, failed strategy, or doomed endeavor that the characters are considering, setting the stage for the punchline.

But-It-Might-Work-For-Us.image_description: This meme format, from the show "Arrested Development," features Tobias Fünke explaining to Lindsay Fünke that a particular action has failed for everyone who has tried it. He then concludes with the illogical and self-deluding statement, "...but it might work for us." The meme is used to satirize people or groups who repeat historical mistakes or pursue failed strategies, believing they will be the exception to the rule.
But-It-Might-Work-For-Us.display_name: But It Might Work For Us

if-i-had-a-nickel-for-everytime.name: if-i-had-a-nickel-for-everytime

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the bottom panel next to Doofenshmirtz's horrified expression. The text here represents the shocking, terrible, or unexpected outcome of the initial idea, serving as the punchline.

This text box is on the top panel where Doofenshmirtz is calmly presenting his creation. The text here describes the initial plan, statement, or setup, which seems reasonable or innocuous before the horrifying reveal in the bottom panel.

if-i-had-a-nickel-for-everytime.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Dr. Doofenshmirtz from the animated show "Phineas and Ferb." In the top panel, he calmly presents a strange-looking dog puppet, setting up an expectation. The bottom panel shows his horrified reaction to his own creation, creating a format used to express shock and dismay when an idea or plan turns out to be much worse than anticipated.
if-i-had-a-nickel-for-everytime.display_name: if i had a nickel for everytime

Drake-Josh-Megan.name: Drake-Josh-Megan

text_options.description: This area, typically placed over Josh's torso, is where a label is added to identify an object or concept. This label represents the obvious answer to the question posed in the top text, creating the punchline by showing that the thing being sought is in plain sight.
The top section of the image is where the setup text is placed. This text usually poses a question or a statement from a person who is confused or looking for something, setting up the joke.

Drake-Josh-Megan.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the character Josh Nichols, played by Josh Peck, from the Nickelodeon show "Drake & Josh." Josh has a confused and slightly distressed expression, looking directly at the viewer. This image is used as a reaction meme, often in a two-panel format, to represent someone overlooking something incredibly obvious that is right in front of them, highlighting their obliviousness.

James-Franco-First-Time.name: James-Franco-First-Time

text_options.description: This area represents the newcomer or novice who is experiencing a negative situation for the first time. The text here typically describes someone complaining, panicking, or being shocked by an event.

This area represents the veteran or experienced person who is already accustomed to the negative situation. The text here identifies a group or individual who has endured this problem many times before and is now unfazed.

James-Franco-First-Time.image_description: This meme, known as "First Time?", originates from a scene in the Coen Brothers' film "The Ballad of Buster Scruggs." It depicts an experienced outlaw (played by James Franco) calmly asking a distraught man next to him on the gallows, "First time?". The meme is used to humorously portray a veteran of a difficult or absurd situation condescendingly addressing a newcomer who is experiencing it for the first time. It highlights a sense of cynical resignation to a recurring problem.

babe-please.name: babe-please

text_options.description: This text box is positioned above the "Yes Chad" character. It typically contains the label for the "Average Enjoyer," describing a person or group with a supposedly superior, refined, or non-mainstream taste. The text here contrasts with the text over the crying girl to create the meme's punchline.

This text box is located above the crying anime girl. It is used to label the "Average Fan," representing a person or group with a viewpoint that the meme creator considers inferior, mainstream, or overly emotional. This label sets up the comparison with the "enjoyer" on the right.

babe-please.image_description: This is the "Average Fan vs. Average Enjoyer" meme format, which contrasts two opposing viewpoints. On the left, a distraught anime girl, often representing the emotional or mainstream "fan," is shown crying. On the right, the stoic and masculine Nordic Gamer, also known as "Yes Chad," represents the calm and confident "enjoyer." The meme is used to humorously portray one preference or group as inferior and overly emotional, while the other is depicted as superior and enlightened.

Confused-Gandalf.name: Confused-Gandalf

text_options.description: This area, positioned next to Gandalf's most confused and concerned face, contains the punchline. The text here reveals the absurd, shocking, or nonsensical element of the story that triggers the extreme reaction.

In the middle panel, the text builds upon the initial premise with a detail that is slightly odd or questionable. This corresponds with Gandalf's expression turning from neutral to slightly puzzled, escalating the narrative towards the final reveal.

The top panel serves as the setup for the meme. The text here typically describes a normal or innocuous situation, statement, or the beginning of a story, matching Gandalf's relatively calm and contemplative expression.

Confused-Gandalf.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as 'Confused Gandalf' or 'Saruman, what are you doing?', features the wizard Gandalf from 'The Lord of the Rings' with a progressively more bewildered expression. The sequence shows him going from thoughtful to slightly puzzled, culminating in a close-up of his face showing deep confusion. This format is used to represent a dawning realization of a strange, nonsensical, or disturbing situation, with the final panel capturing the peak of the user's bafflement.

Needs-More-Cowbell.name: Needs-More-Cowbell

text_options.description: This bottom panel contains the punchline, representing the meme creator's emphatic and often humorous choice or demand. It mirrors Walken's insistence in the sketch, stating the preferred, sometimes absurd, option (e.g., "More Cowbell").

The top panel sets up the scenario or presents a list of conventional options. This text provides the context for the punchline in the bottom panel, establishing what is being compared or chosen from.

Needs-More-Cowbell.image_description: This meme features actor Christopher Walken as music producer Bruce Dickinson from the iconic "More Cowbell" sketch on Saturday Night Live. In the sketch, he famously and inexplicably insists that the band Blue Öyster Cult needs "more cowbell" in their song. The meme format uses this image to express a strong, often quirky or unexpected, preference for something over other, more conventional options.

crying-cat.name: crying-cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the cat's face, typically represents the sad or pathetic reaction, internal thought, or denial of the subject (the cat). It serves as the punchline or the emotional response to the situation set up by the top text, amplifying the feeling of sorrow or injustice.

The top text, placed above the cat's head, sets up the context or scenario that causes the cat's sad reaction. This text usually describes an accusation, a disappointing event, or a statement that leads to the feeling of distress depicted by the cat's face.

crying-cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Crying Cat" or "Sad Cat," features a close-up of a white cat with large, teary, photoshopped eyes, giving it an intensely sorrowful and human-like expression. The cat sits in front of a laptop, looking directly at the viewer with a look of profound sadness and disappointment. This image is used to represent feelings of sadness, being misunderstood, or reacting to an unfortunate or emotionally painful situation, often in a humorous or relatable way.

Normal-Distribution-meme.name: Normal-Distribution-meme

text_options.description: This text box, positioned above the calm, hooded Wojak on the high-IQ end of the spectrum, contains a simple, profound, or enlightened take on a subject. Crucially, this text is often identical or very similar to the text for the low-IQ character, creating the meme's punchline that true wisdom circles back to simplicity.

Located at the peak of the bell curve above the crying 'Soyjak,' this text box represents the opinion of the average-IQ majority. The text here is typically an overcomplicated, pretentious, or emotionally charged viewpoint that is presented as the 'correct' mainstream opinion, which the meme satirizes as being misguided.

This text box is placed over the 'Brainlet' Wojak on the low-IQ side of the curve. It contains a very simple, often blunt or seemingly unintelligent opinion. This statement serves as the baseline and is contrasted with the average opinion, only to be validated by the high-IQ character's identical conclusion.

Normal-Distribution-meme.image_description: This meme, known as the "IQ Bell Curve" or "Galaxy Brain," uses a normal distribution graph to satirize different perspectives on a topic. It features three Wojak characters: a simple-minded "Brainlet" on the low IQ end, an angry and crying "Soyjak" representing the average majority in the middle, and a calm, enlightened figure on the high IQ end. The meme's punchline is that the simplest and most profound opinions, held by the lowest and highest IQ individuals respectively, are often the same. This contrasts with the overcomplicated and emotionally charged viewpoint of the average person, mocking intellectual pretension.

Buzz-And-Woody.name: Buzz-And-Woody

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the second part of the punchline. It typically repeats the subject from the top text followed by the word 'Everywhere,' completing the famous catchphrase 'X, X Everywhere' and emphasizing the subject's ubiquity.

This text box at the top of the image introduces the subject of the meme. It contains the first part of the punchline, 'X,' which names the trend, object, or topic that is being observed in overwhelming numbers.

Buzz-And-Woody.image_description: This meme, known as 'X, X Everywhere' or 'Buzz Lightyear Everywhere,' features characters Buzz Lightyear and Woody from the Disney/Pixar film 'Toy Story.' In the image, Buzz gestures enthusiastically while Woody looks on with concern. The meme is used to humorously point out the sudden and overwhelming prevalence of a particular subject, trend, or object, with Buzz's dialogue expressing this observation.

ralph-wiggum.name: ralph-wiggum

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, famously 'Chuckles, I'm in danger.' It represents the speaker's delayed and naive realization that the situation described above is actually perilous or disadvantageous, contrasting their initial obliviousness.

This top text box establishes a scenario or context. It often describes an action, belief, or situation that seems harmless or even positive from the perspective of the person involved, setting up the punchline.

ralph-wiggum.image_description: This meme features Ralph Wiggum from "The Simpsons," a character known for his childlike innocence and nonsensical remarks. In this scene, he stands awkwardly in front of school lockers, waving with a clueless expression. The meme, often captioned "Chuckles, I'm in danger," is used to humorously convey a delayed or naive realization of being in a threatening, awkward, or disadvantageous situation, capturing the moment of blissful ignorance before the understanding of an impending problem sets in.

Geordi-Drake.name: Geordi-Drake

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Geordi pointing approvingly. It contains the text for the preferred, superior, or more desirable option that the meme creator is endorsing.
This text box is positioned next to the image of Geordi looking dismissive. It typically contains text describing an undesirable, less appealing, or rejected option.

Geordi-Drake.image_description: This two-panel meme features Geordi La Forge from Star Trek: The Next Generation, serving as a variation of the 'Drake Hotline Bling' format. In the top panel, Geordi appears dismissive, holding up his hand to reject something. In the bottom panel, he points forward with an expression of approval. The meme is used to express a preference for the item in the bottom panel over the item in the top panel.

lets-see-paul-allens-card.name: lets-see-paul-allens-card

text_options.description: The bottom text, representing Patrick Bateman's (the meme creator's) internal thought or response. This line serves as the punchline, revealing a sense of superiority, a counter-flex, or a condescending judgment that contrasts with his polite smile.
The top text, which sets up the scenario. It typically describes an action or statement from another person who is proudly showing off an accomplishment, possession, or opinion.

lets-see-paul-allens-card.image_description: A still image of Patrick Bateman, played by Christian Bale, from the film 'American Psycho'. He is smiling smugly with a look of feigned admiration, which is used in memes to represent someone looking at another person's achievement or possession with concealed jealousy and a desire to one-up them. The meme format typically involves a setup where someone presents something they are proud of, followed by Bateman's reaction, implying he has something far superior.

Oh-no-anyway.name: Oh-no-anyway

text_options.description: This area in the bottom panel is often left blank. When text is placed here, it typically labels the person or entity who is feigning concern but is actually indifferent or benefits from the situation described in the top panel, providing context for the dismissive "ANYWAY" reaction.

This area in the top panel is used to describe a negative event, a problem, or some unfortunate news. This text serves as the setup for Jeremy Clarkson's feigned reaction of shock and concern, which is emphasized by the "OH NO!" caption.

Oh-no-anyway.image_description: This two-panel meme features TV presenter Jeremy Clarkson from the show Top Gear. In the top panel, he feigns a look of shock and concern with the caption "OH NO!", and in the bottom panel, his expression shifts to one of nonchalant dismissal with the caption "ANYWAY". The meme is used to humorously portray someone pretending to care about a negative event or consequence, only to immediately reveal their indifference and move on, often because the event benefits them in some way.

Me-explaining-to-my-mom.name: Me-explaining-to-my-mom

text_options.description: This text represents the simple, often comically detached or confused response of the listener. It's typically a very short phrase or question that shows they completely missed the point of the long explanation, weren't paying attention, or are just unimpressed, contrasting with the detailed text in the other panel.

This area contains the text of a long, passionate, and often overly detailed explanation. The text here is usually a lengthy paragraph detailing a complex situation, a niche interest, or a dramatic story, matching the earnest and emotional expression of the person speaking.

Me-explaining-to-my-mom.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Me Explaining to My Mom' or 'Girl Explaining,' contrasts a passionate, detailed explanation with a simple, unimpressed reaction. The left panel shows a young woman earnestly explaining something, while the right panel shows a woman (often identified as Ms. Juicy Baby) looking up with a skeptical or confused expression. The format is used to humorously depict communication breakdowns, where one person's complex or emotional monologue is met with a complete lack of understanding or interest from the listener.

Bender.name: Bender

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. It typically reads, "With blackjack and hookers!" This phrase completes Bender's declaration from the top text, revealing his comically self-serving and vice-filled criteria for his new creation. The nouns are often replaced with other items to fit a specific context, but they always serve to humorously one-up the original concept.

This is the setup text, where the user states their intention to create their own version of something they are unhappy with. It often starts with a phrase like, "You know what? I'm gonna build my own [X]..." This text establishes the context for Bender's defiant and boastful statement.

Bender.image_description: This meme features the character Bender from the animated series 'Futurama', wearing a white fur coat and pointing forward with a smug expression. The format, known as "I'm Gonna Build My Own Theme Park," is used to express dissatisfaction with something by declaring an intention to create a superior, often more hedonistic or comically specific, alternative. The punchline famously involves "blackjack and hookers," reflecting Bender's character and serving as a template for humorous substitutions.

I-am-the-one-who-knocks.name: I-am-the-one-who-knocks

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is almost always the quote "You're goddamn right." This text serves as an intense and confident confirmation of the statement or answer to the question in the top text, matching Walter White's expression.
This top text box serves as the setup. It typically contains a question, an accusation, or a statement directed at the subject of the meme, prompting the aggressive confirmation in the text below.

I-am-the-one-who-knocks.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Walter White from the TV series Breaking Bad, looking intensely angry and baring his teeth. The image captures a moment of powerful and aggressive confirmation, stemming from the scene where he says "You're goddamn right." It is typically used as a reaction meme where the top text poses a question or makes an accusation, and the bottom text provides an emphatic, affirmative answer.
I-am-the-one-who-knocks.display_name: I am the one who knocks

Screaming-bird.name: Screaming-bird

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme. The text is typically written in all-caps to represent shouting or a very loud statement, corresponding to the seagull's exaggerated exhale or scream in the red-tinted, blurry image.
This text box contains the setup for the joke. It's usually a quieter, introductory phrase or the first part of a sentence, representing the seagull "inhaling" or preparing to say something loudly.

Screaming-bird.image_description: This meme, known as "Inhaling Seagull" or "Breathing In Seagull," features a two-panel image of a seagull. The top panel shows the bird leaning back as if taking a deep breath, while the bottom panel shows a motion-blurred, red-tinted version of the seagull with glowing eyes, seemingly screaming. The format is used to represent a dramatic pause before delivering a loud, emphatic, or obvious statement. The top panel sets up a situation or phrase, and the bottom panel delivers the punchline with heightened intensity.

Is-This-a-Pigeon.name: Is-This-a-Pigeon

text_options.description: This area covers the anime character's body and is typically labeled with the name of the person, group, or entity that is making the incorrect assumption or misidentification.
This box is placed over the butterfly, which is the object being observed. Text here identifies the actual object, concept, or person that is being misunderstood.

This space is where the punchline of the meme goes. It contains the incorrect label or question, often in the format "Is this a [wrong thing]?", representing the character's naive and incorrect conclusion.

Is-This-a-Pigeon.image_description: This meme, known as "Is this a pigeon?", originates from a scene in the 1990s anime series "The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird." It features an android character who, being unfamiliar with Earth, looks at a butterfly and mistakenly asks if it's a pigeon. The meme is widely used to humorously portray a person or group naively misidentifying or misunderstanding something.

problems-stress-pain.name: problems-stress-pain

text_options.description: This label is on the yellow character performing the suplex. The text here represents the unexpected, catastrophic event or 'solution' that makes the initial situation dramatically worse.
This label is on the sad, white character who is the victim. The text here describes the person or entity already facing a difficult situation or problem.
This label is on the green character kicking the victim. The text here represents one of the initial, smaller problems or antagonists causing the victim's distress.
This label is on the red character in the background, part of the bullying group. The text here typically represents another one of the initial problems facing the main subject.
This label is on the purple character, also part of the bullying group. The text here is used to identify an additional, smaller problem contributing to the main character's suffering.

problems-stress-pain.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Suplex" or "Unexpected Help," illustrates a situation escalating from bad to worse. In the first panel, a sad white character is being bullied by a group. In the second, a new yellow character appears to offer help, but in the final panel, this supposed savior violently suplexes the victim. The meme is used to represent a problem being compounded by a disastrous 'solution' or an even greater, unexpected problem.

Sad-wojak-cycle.name: Sad-wojak-cycle

text_options.description: This box, located on the left, typically represents the starting point of the negative cycle. It often describes an initial problem, a feeling of discontent, or a trigger that initiates the loop.

Positioned at the bottom, this box represents the final stage before the cycle repeats. It describes the ultimate negative outcome or a state of despair that directly leads back to the initial problem in box 0, thus closing the loop.

This box, on the right, shows the negative consequence or the immediate fallout from the action described in box 3. It's the point where the attempted solution fails, leading to disappointment or a worse situation.

Located at the top, this box follows the initial problem from box 0. It typically describes a flawed plan, a poor decision, or a temporary coping mechanism that the person adopts in an attempt to solve the problem.

Sad-wojak-cycle.image_description: This meme features the Wojak character, also known as Feels Guy, looking sad and weary in the center of a four-stage cycle. The cycle is represented by four text boxes connected by arrows, illustrating a repetitive and inescapable loop of negative events, thoughts, or actions. The meme is used to express feelings of futility, despair, and being trapped in a self-defeating pattern.

Girls-gossiping.name: Girls-gossiping

text_options.description: The bottom text box often identifies the person or group reacting to the secret. This text provides context for who would be shocked by the information presented in the top caption, grounding the punchline.
The top text box contains the 'secret' or shocking statement being whispered. This text serves as the setup or punchline of the meme, intended to provoke the surprised reaction seen in the image.

Girls-gossiping.image_description: This meme, from the 2006 film 'Aquamarine,' features singer JoJo whispering to actress Emma Roberts, who has a shocked expression. The image is used to represent sharing a surprising, scandalous, or absurd secret. The format highlights the contrast between the secretive whisper and the dramatic, wide-eyed reaction.

train-crashes-bus.name: train-crashes-bus

text_options.description: The text here, placed on the train as it collides with the bus, represents the overwhelming, unstoppable force or the inevitable consequence. This is the punchline of the meme, revealing what ultimately destroys the subject represented by the bus.

The text placed on the school bus identifies a person, idea, or plan that is in a vulnerable or foolish position, about to be destroyed. This sets up the premise of the meme, representing the 'victim' of the impending disaster.

train-crashes-bus.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Train Hitting School Bus," depicts a train colliding with a school bus stuck on railroad tracks. The top panel shows the impending doom, while the bottom panel shows the violent impact. The meme is used to represent an overwhelming or unstoppable force (the train) completely destroying a vulnerable or oblivious entity (the bus). It's often used to mock a person, idea, or plan that is clearly destined for failure due to a powerful, unavoidable consequence.

Adam-Silver-Get-Ready-To-Learn-Buddy.name: Adam-Silver-Get-Ready-To-Learn-Buddy

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is the exaggerated or absurd 'punishment' for the action described above. Delivered in a formal tone mimicking an official NBA announcement, it creates a comedic contrast with the triviality of the 'offense'.
This top text box describes the action or 'offense' that is being punished. It's the setup for the joke, often stating a mundane, relatable, or slightly mischievous act.

Adam-Silver-Get-Ready-To-Learn-Buddy.image_description: This meme features NBA commissioner Adam Silver at a press conference, looking serious. The format, known as 'Adam Silver announces punishment,' is used to humorously assign a formal and overly severe consequence to a minor, everyday action. The contrast between Silver's official demeanor and the trivial nature of the 'crime' and 'punishment' creates the comedy.
Adam-Silver-Get-Ready-To-Learn-Buddy.display_name: Adam Silver Get Ready To Learn Buddy

1984-Calendar.name: 1984-Calendar

text_options.description: This label is placed on the man in the yellow shirt who is reacting to the calendar. Text here identifies the person, group, or entity experiencing a shocking and negative realization about how things have changed for the worse over time.

This speech bubble originates from the woman looking at her phone. The text here typically represents a contrasting, often oblivious or less significant, comment or reaction that highlights a different, sometimes trivial, concern compared to the man's profound discovery.

1984-Calendar.image_description: This meme is a political cartoon depicting a man looking shocked as he peels back a calendar page for "January 1984" to reveal "December 2020" underneath, referencing George Orwell's dystopian novel "Nineteen Eighty-Four." A woman in the background is also shocked while looking at her phone. The meme is used to express dismay that a current situation (2020) has become as bad as, or worse than, a past dystopian fiction (1984), often with the years being edited to fit various contexts.

Milk-Girls.name: Milk-Girls

text_options.description: This label is placed on the brunette woman who is being forced to drink. The text here represents the person, group, or entity that is being compelled to accept or consume something, often against their will or to an excessive degree.
This label is on the milk bottle. The text here identifies the specific thing, idea, product, or content that is being forcefully given to the recipient. It is the subject of the compulsion.

This label is on the blonde woman who is holding the bottle and the other woman's hair. The text here represents the dominant or controlling force—a person, company, institution, or abstract concept—that is imposing its will on the other.

Milk-Girls.image_description: This meme, known as 'Forced to Drink Milk,' features a blonde woman holding a brunette woman by the hair and making her drink milk from a bottle. It's an object-labeling format used to depict a situation where a powerful entity (the blonde woman) forces something (the milk) onto a reluctant or overwhelmed recipient (the brunette woman). The meme humorously illustrates scenarios of compulsion, unwanted updates, or being made to accept something against one's will.

Sybau.name: Sybau

text_options.description: A caption is typically placed here describing the negative or embarrassing situation that the person is reacting to. This text sets up the context for the joke, detailing the event that caused the underlying sadness.

This upper area, often placed as a header, contains the reaction text. It usually represents the person's attempt to act tough, indifferent, or defiant in response to the situation described in the bottom text, directly contrasting with the sad expression on their face.

Sybau.image_description: This meme features a young man, reportedly a rapper, with the text "Sybau" and a broken heart emoji in the background. "Sybau" stands for "Sad Year But All is Up." The man is flipping off the camera with a somber expression, creating a contradiction between his defiant gesture and his sad demeanor. The meme is used to humorously depict someone trying to act tough and unbothered after experiencing something upsetting, embarrassing, or hurtful, while their true feelings of sadness are still apparent.

madness---this-is-sparta.name: madness---this-is-sparta

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the dark pit, representing the punchline of the meme. The text here labels the undesirable destination or consequence for the person or thing being kicked, signifying where it is being forcefully sent. Common examples include "the friend zone," "my responsibilities," or any concept being banished.
