This text box is located at the top of the image, typically used to label the group of onlookers (the Spartans). In the context of the meme, this area can represent a larger entity or concept that supports the main action of rejection, or it can be used to set up the general context for the scene.

madness---this-is-sparta.image_description: This meme originates from a dramatic scene in the 2006 film "300," where King Leonidas kicks a Persian messenger into a large well after shouting the iconic line, "This is Sparta!". The image is widely used to represent a forceful, decisive, and often overly dramatic rejection or dismissal of something. The kicker embodies the entity doing the rejecting, the one being kicked represents the rejected idea or person, and the pit symbolizes the undesirable outcome or destination.

Skyrim-skill-meme.name: Skyrim-skill-meme

text_options.description: This is the core of the meme's punchline. Text placed here names the 'skill' that has supposedly reached level 100. This is typically a single word or short phrase like 'Sneak', 'Speech', or 'Illusion', often applied to a completely unrelated, humorous real-life context.

This upper area is often used for a caption or title that provides context for the meme. It usually describes the situation or action that demonstrates the 'skill' mentioned below, setting up the punchline that follows with the skill name and the number 100.

Skyrim-skill-meme.image_description: This meme template originates from the user interface of the video game The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim, specifically the notification for a skill reaching the maximum level of 100. It is widely used to humorously label a real-life action, trait, or situation as a 'skill' that has been mastered. The humor comes from the ironic juxtaposition of the epic, in-game achievement with often mundane, awkward, or cleverly simple real-world scenarios.

The-Cooler-Daniel.name: The-Cooler-Daniel

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the photo of "The cooler Daniel." Text here represents the superior, improved, or more desirable version of the subject being compared. It serves as the punchline, highlighting why this version is better than the original.

This text box is placed above the photo of "Daniel." Text here typically represents the original, standard, or less impressive version of a person, object, or concept. It sets up the comparison for the "cooler" version on the right.

The-Cooler-Daniel.image_description: The "Daniel vs. The Cooler Daniel" meme features two side-by-side yearbook photos of the same Black man. The photo on the left, labeled "Daniel," shows him smiling, representing a standard or original version of something. The photo on the right, labeled "The cooler Daniel," shows him wearing sunglasses with a more stoic expression, representing an improved or more desirable version. This format is widely used to humorously compare two similar things, with the second being presented as the superior one.

Liam-Neeson-Taken.name: Liam-Neeson-Taken

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the image of Liam Neeson, contains the punchline of the meme. This text is a variation of the character's famous quote, "I will find you, and I will kill you," adapted to fit the context set up by the top text. It delivers a mock-serious threat or a statement of intense determination.
The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a frustrating situation or identifies a person, object, or concept that has become the target of the user's mock-serious threat.

Liam-Neeson-Taken.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of actor Liam Neeson as Bryan Mills from the 2008 film "Taken." The image captures the intense moment during a phone call where he delivers his iconic monologue, threatening his daughter's kidnappers with his "very particular set of skills." The meme format uses this image to express a comically serious and determined promise to find someone or something, often in mundane or trivial situations, by adapting his famous line, "I will find you, and I will kill you."

Corporate-needs-you-to-find-the-differen.name: Corporate-needs-you-to-find-the-differences

text_options.description: This area contains the character Pam Beesly and the punchline of the meme, "They're the same picture." This text is the core of the meme format and expresses the user's opinion that the two items in the top panel are identical.

This area covers the two pieces of paper being held up for comparison. Users typically place images, text, or labels here representing two different concepts, people, or things that they want to humorously declare are the same.

Corporate-needs-you-to-find-the-differen.image_description: This is a two-panel meme from the TV show "The Office," featuring the character Pam Beesly. In the top panel, someone is asked to find the differences between two pictures, and in the bottom panel, Pam states with a deadpan expression, "They're the same picture." The meme is used to humorously claim that two different things are, in fact, identical or indistinguishable.
Corporate-needs-you-to-find-the-differen.display_name: Corporate needs you to find the differences

Run.name: Run

text_options.description: This label is placed on the panicked girl running away. The text here typically represents the user ('Me') or anyone trying to escape from a stressful or undesirable situation.

This label is placed on the orangutan riding the bicycle. The text here identifies the pursuer, which is often an unavoidable responsibility, a looming deadline, a consequence of one's actions, or any overwhelming problem.

Run.image_description: This meme, known as "Orangutan Chasing Kid," features a young girl running in terror from an orangutan riding a small bicycle. The image humorously depicts a situation of being pursued by an overwhelming, absurd, or inevitable force. The girl represents someone trying to escape, while the orangutan symbolizes the relentless problem, responsibility, or consequence that is chasing them.

Aye-I-Could-Do-That-Blank.name: Aye-I-Could-Do-That-Blank

text_options.description: This text box is on the bottom panel, where Gimli is looking up expectantly. The text here represents the initial statement, boast, or accomplishment made by the first person in the exchange.

Located in the middle panel over a smug-looking Legolas, this text represents the superior counter-argument or the "one-up." It's a direct, and often witty, response that tops the statement made in the first panel.

This text box is on the top panel, where Gimli has a stern, slightly annoyed expression. The text here represents the final reaction of the first person, often expressing begrudging respect, annoyance, or defeat after being outdone.

Aye-I-Could-Do-That-Blank.image_description: This three-panel meme features the characters Gimli and Legolas from the movie "The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers." The format depicts a friendly rivalry or competition where one person is unexpectedly outdone by another. The bottom panel shows Gimli making a statement, the middle panel shows Legolas with a smug look delivering a superior counter-statement, and the top panel shows Gimli's stern, defeated reaction. It's commonly used to illustrate scenarios of being one-upped in any kind of contest.
Aye-I-Could-Do-That-Blank.display_name: Aye I Could Do That Blank

Worst-day-of-my-life.name: Worst-day-of-my-life

text_options.description: This text is placed over Homer as he consoles Bart in the bottom panel. It represents Homer's misguided, incorrect, or ironically unhelpful advice or statement, which serves as the punchline of the meme.

Located in the top panel over the sad-looking Bart, this text describes the problem or the reason for Bart's sadness. It sets up the premise of the joke, establishing what Homer is about to give terrible advice about.

Worst-day-of-my-life.image_description: This two-panel meme from 'The Simpsons' features Bart looking sad and alone in the top panel, and his father, Homer, putting an arm around him to console him in the bottom panel. The format is typically used to show someone offering misguided, unhelpful, or ironically bad advice to another person who is upset. The humor arises from the contrast between the caring gesture and the absurd or incorrect statement made by the consoler (Homer).

es-de-mi-agrado-informarles.name: es-de-mi-agrado-informarles

text_options.description: The bottom caption typically delivers the punchline, expressing a desire to escape the burden mentioned in the top text. It often voices a wish to return to a simpler, more natural state, contrasting with the frog's sophisticated human-like appearance. A classic example is, "I wish I were a little froggy in a pond."

The top caption area is used to set up the scenario or introduce a complex, burdensome thought or piece of information. This text establishes the cause of the character's existential weariness and sophisticated sadness.

es-de-mi-agrado-informarles.image_description: This meme features an illustration of the character Toad from the children's book series "Frog and Toad", dressed in formal 19th-century attire with a somber, weary expression. The image is used to convey a sense of sophisticated melancholy, existential dread, or the burdens of adult life and consciousness. The humor stems from the contrast between the character's dapper appearance and the relatable, often simple despair expressed in the captions, creating a mood of refined ennui.

I-fear-no-man-But-that-thingit-scares-me.name: I-fear-no-man-But-that-thingit-scares-me

text_options.description: This central blank space is where the user places an image of the "thing" that the subject fears. The humor comes from this object being something unexpected, mundane, or ironically frightening, creating a stark contrast with the subject's initial bravado.

Text placed over the Heavy's silhouette in the top panel identifies a person, group, or concept that is generally considered strong, fearless, or powerful. This sets up the premise of the meme, establishing a character who is not easily intimidated.

I-fear-no-man-But-that-thingit-scares-me.image_description: This three-panel meme originates from the "Meet the Pyro" promotional video for the video game Team Fortress 2. It features the character Heavy Weapons Guy, a large, intimidating mercenary, who first confidently states, "I fear no man." The subsequent panels show him looking nervously at an unseen subject, admitting, "But that thing... it scares me." The meme is used to humorously contrast a person's supposed bravery or toughness with an unexpected or trivial fear, which is placed in the blank space.
I-fear-no-man-But-that-thingit-scares-me.display_name: I fear no man But that thingit scares me

Nicki-Minaj-So-theres-this.name: Nicki-Minaj-So-theres-this

text_options.description: This space is intended to be filled in by the user to complete the sentence "So There's This...". Typically, words like "boy" or "girl" are inserted here to specify the object of the user's affection, making it the punchline that reveals who the meme is about.

Nicki-Minaj-So-theres-this.image_description: This meme features a still image of rapper Nicki Minaj with a half-blonde, half-blue wig, smiling mischievously. The text "So There's This" is overlaid on the image, setting up a conversational, gossipy tone. This format, often called "So There's This Boy," is used to express having a crush or a strong liking for someone, with Nicki's expression perfectly capturing the feeling of excitedly wanting to talk about them.

khan.name: khan

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which serves as the punchline. It almost always contains the name of the person or thing that is the target of the frustration, formatted as a scream (e.g., 'KHAAAAAN!'). The text here is the climax of the meme, directly corresponding to Kirk's furious expression.

This is the top text area, used to provide the setup or context for the meme. The text here describes a frustrating scenario or an action that would provoke the intense, screaming reaction shown in the image, setting the stage for the punchline below.

khan.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Captain Kirk from 'Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan', played by William Shatner, screaming in anguish and rage. The image captures a moment of intense frustration, making it a popular reaction meme. It is typically used to express extreme anger or despair towards a person, situation, or concept, often by replacing the original screamed name, 'Khan', with the source of the user's frustration.

I-think-I-forgot-something.name: I-think-I-forgot-something

text_options.description: This text label identifies the important person, task, or object that has been forgotten. Positioned over the abandoned child in the final panel, this serves as the punchline of the meme.
This label represents the person who is easily convinced to ignore their responsibilities. In this panel, the character agrees with the bad advice, setting up the final reveal.
This text labels the enabler or the source of bad advice. This character dismisses the initial concern, persuading the other that whatever they forgot is not important.
This text represents the person who has a nagging feeling that they are forgetting something important. This sets up the premise of the meme.

I-think-I-forgot-something.image_description: This four-panel meme originates from the sitcom "Two and a Half Men," featuring characters Alan Harper, his brother Charlie, and Alan's son Jake. The first three panels depict a conversation where Alan feels he's forgotten something, but Charlie reassures him it must be unimportant. The final panel reveals the punchline: they have forgotten Jake, leaving him stranded in the rain. This format is widely used to humorously illustrate forgetting something or someone obviously important.

Go-Fund-Me.name: Go-Fund-Me

text_options.description: This large blank area is the main punchline of the meme. Users add text here to describe the ridiculous or trivial reason for the fake GoFundMe campaign, creating a humorous or critical statement.
This top section is typically used for the title of the fake fundraising campaign. The text placed here sets up the joke that is delivered in the box below, often with a dramatic or misleading title.

Go-Fund-Me.image_description: This meme is an exploitable template featuring the logo of the crowdfunding website GoFundMe. The format consists of the logo at the top and a large blank space below, which is filled in with text. It is used to satirize or mock what the creator perceives as frivolous, absurd, or illegitimate reasons for starting a fundraising campaign, contrasting them with the platform's intended use for serious causes.

Bugs-Bunny-no.name: Bugs-Bunny-no

text_options.description: This bottom panel delivers the punchline, which is almost always a blunt and simple "no." The text here, combined with Bugs Bunny's smug expression, serves to dismissively reject the premise established in the top panel.
This top panel contains the setup for the joke. It typically features a question, a request, or a statement that someone might make, creating an expectation for a particular response.

Bugs-Bunny-no.image_description: This meme features a close-up of the cartoon character Bugs Bunny from Looney Tunes with a smug and dismissive expression. The format is a two-panel reaction image used to humorously and bluntly reject a proposition, question, or statement. The top panel presents the initial context, while the bottom panel delivers a simple, often one-word "no" as the punchline, emphasizing a carefree or superior refusal.

Thats-a-paddlin.name: Thats-a-paddlin

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the paddle Jasper is holding. It typically contains the punchline, "That's a paddlin'," or a variation of it, representing the comically severe consequence or punishment for the action described above.

The top text box is used to describe a minor offense, a disliked opinion, or a trivial action. This text sets up the premise for which the disproportionate punishment (the "paddlin'") will be administered.

Thats-a-paddlin.image_description: This meme features Jasper Beardsley, an elderly character from "The Simpsons," holding a wooden paddle with a stern expression. The meme, known as "That's a Paddlin'," originates from a scene where Jasper, as a substitute teacher, doles out corporal punishment for any minor infraction. It is used to humorously suggest an overly harsh or disproportionate punishment for a trivial action, statement, or preference that the user dislikes.

Pippin-Second-Breakfast.name: Pippin-Second-Breakfast

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, placed over Pippin as he asks a question. The text here is a variation of the original line, "What about second breakfast?", adapted to the meme's specific context. It represents a naive or greedy request for more of something.

This text box is placed over the character Aragorn, who represents an authority figure or someone being pestered. The text here is typically a short, dismissive response or is sometimes left blank to imply an annoyed stare. It serves as the reaction to the initial statement in the top panel.

This is the setup for the joke, placed over the hobbits Merry and Pippin. The text here usually states a fact or something that has just been accomplished, analogous to the hobbits having already had their first breakfast. It establishes the context that makes the final question in the bottom panel humorous.

Pippin-Second-Breakfast.image_description: This is a three-panel meme from the movie "The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring." It features the hobbits Pippin and Merry talking to the human character Aragorn. In the scene, after having just eaten, Pippin asks Aragorn about having a "second breakfast." The meme is used to humorously depict a situation where someone asks for more of something they have just received, much to the exasperation of an authority figure.

Gordon-Ramsay-kids-vs-adults.name: Gordon-Ramsay-kids-vs-adults

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Gordon Ramsay's angry face. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is being treated harshly, criticized, or viewed unfavorably in the comparison.

This text box is placed over Gordon Ramsay's gentle and caring expression. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that receives praise, favoritism, or gentle treatment, contrasting with the subject in the other panel.

Gordon-Ramsay-kids-vs-adults.image_description: This is a two-panel meme featuring celebrity chef Gordon Ramsay, showcasing his drastically different demeanor in different contexts. On the right, he is aggressively yelling "You fucking donkey," a scene from Hell's Kitchen. On the left, he is gently comforting a young girl, saying "Oh dear, oh dear. Gorgeous," from MasterChef Junior. The meme is used to contrast how someone treats two different things, showing harshness towards one and favoritism or kindness towards the other.

MrKrabs-Give-it-up-for-day.name: MrKrabs-Give-it-up-for-day

text_options.description: This text box, located on Mr. Krabs' body, typically contains the specific day number being celebrated or endured, such as "Day 15." It grounds the meme in a specific point in time during the ongoing event.

Positioned at the top of the image, this is where the main caption goes, usually reading "Give it up for Day [X]!" This phrase, combined with Mr. Krabs' panicked expression, creates a sarcastic and relatable sense of shared struggle.

MrKrabs-Give-it-up-for-day.image_description: This meme features Mr. Krabs from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants, looking frantic and disheveled while ringing a large bell at night. The image is taken from a scene where he's in a state of panic. This format, known as "Give it up for Day X," is used to humorously mark the passage of time during a prolonged, often stressful event, like a quarantine or a long work week, with Mr. Krabs' chaotic energy representing the struggle to keep it together.
MrKrabs-Give-it-up-for-day.display_name: MrKrabs Give it up for day

Chernobyl-meme-postfity.name: Chernobyl-meme-postfity

text_options.description: This bottom text box serves as the punchline, delivering the understated and often dismissive assessment of the situation. It typically contains the quote "Not great, not terrible" or a similar phrase that ironically downplays the severity of the problem described in the top text box.

This top text box sets up the context of the meme by describing a disastrous, terrible, or catastrophic situation. This text establishes the high stakes that are then ironically minimized by the text in the bottom box.

Chernobyl-meme-postfity.image_description: This meme originates from the HBO miniseries "Chernobyl" and features Soviet engineer Anatoly Dyatlov (left) in the control room during the nuclear disaster. The scene depicts the initial, misleadingly low radiation reading of 3.6 roentgen, which Dyatlov dismisses as "not great, not terrible." The meme format uses this ironic understatement to downplay a catastrophic or terrible situation, juxtaposing the severity of an event with a deceptively mild assessment.

he-man-skeleton-advices.name: he-man-skeleton-advices

text_options.description: Text in this bottom panel typically describes the consequence, the reason for the retreat, or the action of running away. It serves as the punchline, undermining the statement made in the top panel and showing the failure of the initial plan or boast.

Text in this top panel represents a confident, boastful, or declarative statement. This is the setup, where a person or group makes a bold claim or presents a grand plan, which will be immediately contradicted by the second panel.

he-man-skeleton-advices.image_description: This two-panel meme features the villain Skeletor from the 1980s cartoon "He-Man and the Masters of the Universe." In the top panel, Skeletor stands confidently, presenting an idea or making a bold statement. The bottom panel shows him running away, seemingly in retreat or defeat. The meme is used to contrast a confident declaration with an immediate, often embarrassing, failure or retreat, highlighting hypocrisy or a failed plan.

Shocked-black-guy.name: Shocked-black-guy

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline or the specific detail that causes the shock. It provides the crucial, often unexpected, context to the setup presented in the top text, triggering the exaggerated reaction shown in the image.

The top text box sets up the scenario or presents an initial statement. This text establishes the context for the meme, preparing the viewer for the surprising reveal or punchline that follows in the bottom text box.

Shocked-black-guy.image_description: A still image of a young Black man with an extremely shocked and wide-eyed expression. His mouth is agape, and he holds his hands to his head in disbelief. This reaction image is used to convey intense surprise, astonishment, or a sudden, overwhelming realization in response to a preceding statement or situation.

Im-the-dumbest-man-alive.name: Im-the-dumbest-man-alive

text_options.description: This area is used to label the character who has just said something foolish. The label typically identifies a person, group, or entity that the meme creator is criticizing for their perceived lack of intelligence, directly connecting them to the dumb statement made in the previous panel.

This speech bubble is the core of the meme's joke. It contains a quote, statement, or action that is presented as being exceptionally stupid, illogical, or misinformed. The content here is what convinces the king to give up his crown, serving as the punchline.

Im-the-dumbest-man-alive.image_description: This three-panel comic meme, known as "I'm the Dumbest Man Alive" or "Dumbest Fella" by artist SrGrafo, illustrates a competition for being the most foolish. A character wearing a crown proudly declares himself the dumbest, only to be one-upped by another character who says something even more nonsensical or ignorant. In the final panel, the original king concedes his title, placing the crown on the head of the new, 'clearly dumber' individual, making this meme a popular format for mocking foolish statements or beliefs.

Superman-starman-meme.name: Superman-starman-meme

text_options.description: This text is placed over Superman's iconic 'S' symbol on his chest. It represents the user's lengthy, passionate, and overly detailed answer or explanation. Its placement on the hero's chest signifies the pride and importance the user attaches to this knowledge, delivering it with heroic conviction.

Located in the top panel, this text serves as the prompt or question that triggers Superman's response. It's typically a simple, often condescending or dismissive phrase, such as someone questioning the user's expertise or making a simplistic statement, setting up the elaborate punchline below.

Superman-starman-meme.image_description: This meme features a heroic-looking illustration of the DC Comics superhero Superman, smiling confidently with a bright light behind him. The format is used to humorously contrast a simple or dismissive question with an overly detailed, passionate, and elaborate answer. The user presents themselves as Superman, heroically providing an extensive explanation for a topic they are an expert in or care deeply about, often in response to a trivializing prompt.

My-child-will.name: My-child-will

text_options.description: This thought bubble belongs to Jesus. The text placed here represents the morally correct, kind, or socially acceptable thought or action in a scenario. It serves as the 'good advice' or the righteous path.

This thought bubble belongs to the Devil. The text here is typically a mischievous, selfish, or evil suggestion that acts as a temptation. This is usually the punchline, contrasting with Jesus's wholesome thought to create humor.

My-child-will.image_description: This meme format features a classic shoulder angel/devil dynamic, represented by Jesus Christ and Satan. Jesus, on the right, embodies the moral, righteous, or 'good' choice, while the Devil on the left represents a tempting, malicious, or chaotic suggestion. The meme is used to contrast two opposing internal thoughts or potential actions in a given situation, with the Devil's suggestion often being the humorous punchline.

Here-we-go-again.name: Here-we-go-again

text_options.description: This area contains the iconic quote and punchline, "Ah shit, here we go again." This text is the constant element of the meme, expressing the user's feeling of exasperated resignation towards the situation described above it.

This space is typically used to add a caption or label describing the recurring, unpleasant, or tedious situation that the user is about to face. It sets the context for CJ's (and the user's) reaction in the subtitle below.

Here-we-go-again.image_description: This meme, known as "Ah shit, here we go again," originates from the video game Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas. It features the protagonist, Carl "CJ" Johnson, walking in his old neighborhood with a look of resignation. The meme is widely used to express frustration, annoyance, or weariness when facing a familiar, often undesirable, recurring situation or problem.

I-can-has-cheezburger-cat.name: I-can-has-cheezburger-cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, often in a bold, sans-serif font, serves as the punchline or the specific object of desire. It completes the phrase started in the top text. In the original, iconic version of this meme, this text reads "CHEEZBURGER?".

The top text sets up the premise of the meme, written in "lolspeak." It typically poses a question or makes a statement from the cat's point of view. The classic example for this location is "I CAN HAS".

I-can-has-cheezburger-cat.image_description: This meme features a gray British Shorthair cat with wide, hopeful eyes and a slightly open mouth, giving it an eager expression. Known as the "I Can Has Cheezburger?" cat, it is one of the most iconic early internet memes that popularized the "lolcat" phenomenon. The format uses a specific type of broken English called "lolspeak" to humorously caption photos of cats from their perspective, typically expressing a simple desire.

where-banana.name: where-banana

text_options.description: Text placed on the news desk typically describes a complex or serious topic that the apes are meant to be discussing. This sets up the context that the punchline will humorously ignore or subvert.

This text box contains the punchline of the meme, representing the simple, direct thought of the orangutan. It is usually a short question in broken English, like the titular 'where banana', which contrasts sharply with the serious setting.

where-banana.image_description: This meme, known as 'Where Banana', features three orangutans photoshopped onto the set of a news program, likely BBC News. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the serious, formal news setting with the simple, primal desires of the apes. The meme is used to express a simplistic or blunt question in response to a complex situation, often conveying a sense of confusion or a single-minded focus on a basic need.

Bill-Murray-Groundhog-Day.name: Bill-Murray-Groundhog-Day

text_options.description: This bottom text box is the main punchline of the meme. It typically contains a statement describing the repetitive or tiresome event that the user is experiencing, drawing a parallel to the endless loop in the movie.

The top text box is used to set up the context or identify the subject of the repetition. It often labels the person, thing, or situation that is causing the monotonous experience described in the bottom text.

Bill-Murray-Groundhog-Day.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of actor Bill Murray as the character Phil Connors from the 1993 movie "Groundhog Day." In the scene, Phil, a cynical weatherman, looks weary and unenthusiastic while reporting on the annual Groundhog Day ceremony, an event he is forced to relive endlessly due to a time loop. The meme is used to express feelings of monotony, exhaustion, or frustration with a recurring situation, often captioned with variations of the line, "Well, it's Groundhog Day... again."

honey-its-time-to-x.name: honey-its-time-to-x

text_options.description: This area, located below the sad Wojak, typically contains text representing his internal thoughts or a label for his state of mind. It often expresses a simple, sad, or unrelated thought that contrasts sharply with the woman's complex explanation, highlighting his misery or disinterest.

Positioned below the woman, this text box contains her long, often rambling and overly detailed explanation. The text here is usually about a niche topic, a complex theory, or a personal story, serving as the core monologue that overwhelms the male character.

This text box is placed over the sad Wojak's head, functioning as a label or a thought bubble. It usually contains a short phrase summarizing the source of his distress, which is often completely different from the topic the woman is discussing, emphasizing their disconnect.

This label is placed on the woman, often over her chest. It typically introduces her or the topic she is about to explain in detail. For example, it might say "My girlfriend" or "Her," setting the stage for the monologue that follows in the text box below her.

honey-its-time-to-x.image_description: This meme, often called "Girl Explaining" or "Bro Girl," features two Wojak characters side-by-side. On the left, a smug-looking woman (Tradwife Wojak) appears to be passionately explaining something, while on the right, a sad, distressed man (Wojak/Feels Guy) looks on, appearing overwhelmed or dejected. The format humorously contrasts someone's enthusiastic, often lengthy explanation of a niche interest with the listener's complete apathy, confusion, or unrelated internal suffering.

Really-right-in-front-of-my.name: Really-right-in-front-of-my

text_options.description: This area is typically used to label the Flork character, representing the person or entity feeling indignant. It provides context by identifying who is being offended by the situation described in the meme.

This text box completes the phrase "Really? Right in front of my ___". It contains the punchline of the meme, which is the object or concept that makes the unseen action so offensive. The original word is "salad," but it is replaced with something else to create a humorous and relatable context.

Really-right-in-front-of-my.image_description: This meme features a crudely drawn, sock-puppet-like character from the "Flork of Cows" webcomic, shown with an angry and indignant expression. The image is part of the "Really? Right in front of my salad?" meme format, which expresses humorous outrage or disbelief at an inappropriate or unexpected action. Users customize the meme by replacing the word "salad" to fit various relatable scenarios, making it a versatile reaction image.
Really-right-in-front-of-my.display_name: Really right in front of my

4-headed-dragon.name: 4-headed-dragon

text_options.description: This label is placed on the neck of the goofy, derpy-looking dragon head. The text here represents the outlier, the punchline, or the comically inferior item in a group of four, contrasting sharply with the other three.

This label is on the neck of one of the three serious, menacing dragon heads. The text here typically represents one of the competent, serious, or standard examples in a comparison, helping to establish a pattern that the fourth head will break.

This label is on the neck of the central serious dragon head. Like the other serious heads, the text here represents another competent or standard example in the group, reinforcing the pattern before the punchline.

This label is on the neck of the leftmost serious dragon head. The text in this position serves as the first of three serious or impressive examples, setting up the expectation that is ultimately subverted by the goofy head.

4-headed-dragon.image_description: This meme, known as "King Ghidorah" or "Three-Headed Dragon," features a fan-art depiction of the Godzilla monster. Three of its golden dragon heads are portrayed as menacing and serious, while the fourth head on the right is drawn in a comically goofy and derpy style, with googly eyes and its tongue sticking out. The meme is used to compare three competent or serious examples of something with one foolish or inferior outlier, which is represented by the goofy head.

Samuel-L-Jackson-say-one-more-time.name: Samuel-L-Jackson-say-one-more-time

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, delivered from Jules's perspective. It's typically a variation of his famous line, such as "Say '[X]' again, I dare you," challenging the person who made the initial absurd statement.

The top text box sets up the meme by presenting a statement, quote, or idea that the creator finds ridiculous, frustrating, or worthy of mockery. This text is the catalyst for Jules's intense and challenging reaction.

Samuel-L-Jackson-say-one-more-time.image_description: This meme features a close-up, intense shot of Samuel L. Jackson as Jules Winnfield from the film *Pulp Fiction*. His wide-eyed, confrontational stare is used to express extreme disbelief, frustration, or to challenge a statement the user finds absurd or nonsensical. The format is often called "Say 'What' Again" and is used to mock or dare someone to repeat a foolish or incorrect assertion.
Samuel-L-Jackson-say-one-more-time.display_name: Samuel L Jackson say one more time

Por-que-tan-elegante-homero.name: Por-que-tan-elegante-homero

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image, labeled with index 0, describes the mundane or 'low-brow' reality of the situation. It contrasts with the sophisticated appearance, revealing the true, often unimpressive, context of the event or action.

The text at the top of the image, labeled with index 1, presents a sophisticated, elegant, or high-class description of an event or feeling. This sets up the joke by creating an expectation of refinement that is then humorously undercut by the image and the bottom text.

Por-que-tan-elegante-homero.image_description: This meme features Homer Simpson from 'The Simpsons' dressed in a tuxedo while casually eating pizza and drinking soda on a couch, as his son Bart looks on. The format, known as 'Homer in a Tuxedo' or 'Fancy Homer,' humorously contrasts a sophisticated appearance with a mundane or low-brow reality. It's typically used to mock pretentiousness or to describe feeling overdressed and out of place for a casual event.

Google-Translate.name: Google-Translate

text_options.description: This is the output field in the Google Translate interface. In the meme, this area contains the punchline, which is the supposed "true" or literal translation of the text from the input box (1). It's the humorous or cynical reveal that the meme builds up to.

This is the input field where the user types the text to be translated. In this meme format, it contains the initial phrase, statement, or idea that will be humorously or ironically reinterpreted in the output box (0).

This box indicates the target language for the translation. In the meme, it's often set to a real language like "English" to imply a translation into plain, understandable truth. It can also be another metaphorical group to create a contrast with the source language.

This box indicates the source language of the text to be translated. In the meme, this is often replaced with a social group, profession, or concept (e.g., "Men," "Corporate Jargon") to set up the context for the joke, implying that this group has its own unique way of speaking that needs translation.

Google-Translate.image_description: This meme format uses the user interface of Google Translate to create a humorous or satirical comparison. A phrase or concept is placed in the input box, and the output box reveals its supposed "true" or underlying meaning, often with a sarcastic or cynical twist. The languages selected for translation are also part of the joke, frequently representing social groups or abstract concepts rather than actual languages, framing the meme as a translation of subtext into plain speech.

Not-that-but-this.name: Not-that-but-this

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to Drake's approving gesture. It is intended for the preferred, superior, or desired option in the comparison. The text or image here represents the thing the meme creator is endorsing.

This text box is positioned next to Drake's gesture of rejection. It is used to display the undesirable, inferior, or disliked option. The text or image placed here is what the meme creator is expressing disapproval of.

Not-that-but-this.image_description: This two-panel meme, widely known as "Drakeposting" or "Drake Approves," features stills of the rapper Drake from his "Hotline Bling" music video. In the top panel, Drake holds up a hand in a gesture of rejection, looking displeased. In the bottom panel, he smiles contentedly and points in a gesture of approval. The format is used to express a strong preference for one thing (the approved item in the bottom panel) over another (the rejected item in the top panel).

Go-and-get-the-guitar.name: Go-and-get-the-guitar

text_options.description: This bottom text box delivers the punchline. It's typically a question or a statement that reveals the fundamental flaw, absurdity, or ignorance in the initial statement from the top box, creating the comedic effect.

This top text box contains the setup of the joke, representing David Brent's condescending or overly simplistic statement. It's a declaration presented as fact or wisdom, which will be immediately undermined by the text below.

Go-and-get-the-guitar.image_description: This meme features David Brent (Ricky Gervais) condescendingly explaining something to his unimpressed colleague Gareth Keenan (Mackenzie Crook) from the British sitcom 'The Office'. The format is used to mock simplistic or flawed arguments. A patronizing statement is presented, followed by a question or punchline that exposes its absurdity, highlighting the speaker's ignorance.

Thinking-Black-Guy.name: Thinking-Black-Guy

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It presents the flawed, illogical, or overly simplistic 'solution' to the problem stated in the top text. The man's self-satisfied expression is meant to be a reaction to this supposedly brilliant idea.

This top text box sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a problem, a negative situation, or a goal that the user wants to achieve or avoid. This text provides the context for the 'brilliant' but flawed advice that follows below.

Thinking-Black-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as 'Roll Safe' or 'Think About It,' features actor Kayode Ewumi as the character Reece Simpson. He is depicted with a sly, knowing smile while tapping his index finger on his temple, suggesting a moment of supposed genius. The meme is used to humorously present a piece of flawed logic, a terrible life hack, or an obviously simple solution as a profound realization.

umbrella-academy-meme.name: umbrella-academy-meme

text_options.description: This text is placed next to Number Five in the bottom panel. It represents the second, contrasting element in the meme, often a surprising, niche, or controversial opinion or identity that causes the reaction.
This text is placed next to Vanya in the top panel. It represents the first person, group, or idea, typically setting up the scenario with a more conventional or mainstream viewpoint.

umbrella-academy-meme.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from a scene in the Netflix series 'The Umbrella Academy', featuring characters Vanya Hargreeves (top) and Number Five (bottom) driving past each other. They exchange concerned and surprised looks, respectively, from their car windows. The meme is used to contrast two opposing ideas, groups, or individuals who briefly encounter each other, with the top panel often representing a more conventional viewpoint and the bottom panel introducing a surprising or conflicting perspective.

Clippy.name: Clippy

text_options.description: The bottom text represents Clippy's dialogue. It typically starts with a phrase like "It looks like you're..." and rephrases the action from the top text in a condescending or overly simplistic way, delivering the punchline of the meme.
The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It usually describes an action, statement, or situation that the user is engaged in, which then prompts Clippy's unwanted 'help'.

Clippy.image_description: This meme features Clippy, the anthropomorphic paperclip who was the default office assistant in older versions of Microsoft Office. Clippy is infamous for offering unsolicited, and often unhelpful, advice, such as the classic "It looks like you're writing a letter." The meme format leverages this reputation to mock condescending or obvious observations, where a user's action is met with a simplistic and annoying interjection from Clippy.

patrick-scared.name: patrick-scared

text_options.description: This label identifies Patrick Star, who represents the person or entity reacting with fear, shock, or guilt to the information presented in the top panel.
This label is on the paper held by the police officers. The text here typically contains the accusation, a piece of evidence, or a revealing statement that causes Patrick's panicked reaction.

patrick-scared.image_description: This two-panel meme from SpongeBob SquarePants features two police officers smugly holding up a piece of paper in the top panel, and a terrified Patrick Star in the bottom panel. The format is used to represent an accusation or a revealing piece of information, followed by a panicked or guilty reaction. The police officers represent the accuser, the paper is the evidence, and Patrick is the guilty party.

South-Park-Underpants-Gnomes.name: South-Park-Underpants-Gnomes

text_options.description: This text box, located under "Phase 3," contains the ultimate goal of the plan, which is "Profit" in the original meme. It represents the desired, often ambitious, outcome. The certainty of this final step makes the missing logic of the intermediate "Phase 2" all the more absurd, forming the core of the meme's punchline.

This text box, positioned under "Phase 1," is where the initial step of the plan is described. In the original scene, this step was "Collect Underpants." In meme variations, this text is edited to represent the first action or premise of whatever flawed plan is being mocked.

South-Park-Underpants-Gnomes.image_description: This meme, known as the "Underpants Gnomes" or "Profit" meme, originates from the animated TV show South Park. It features a three-step business plan presented by the gnomes: Phase 1 is a concrete action, Phase 2 is a large question mark, and Phase 3 is "Profit." The meme is used to satirize poorly-conceived plans or arguments that have a clear start and a desired end but lack a coherent or logical process to connect the two.

Jack-Torrance-axe-shining.name: Jack-Torrance-axe-shining

text_options.description: This text, placed over Jack Torrance's face, represents the person, group, or concept that is being intrusive, aggressive, or overly enthusiastic. It is the primary subject initiating the action.
This label over the terrified Wendy Torrance represents the person, entity, or situation being disturbed or overwhelmed by the subject in box 0. It is the target of the intrusion.
Placed on the axe, this text typically represents the specific tool, reason, or method used by the intruder (box 0) to disrupt the victim (box 1). It adds a layer of context to the intrusion.

Jack-Torrance-axe-shining.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the iconic "Here's Johnny!" scene in the 1980 horror film "The Shining." The top panel shows Wendy Torrance (Shelley Duvall) screaming as an axe breaks through a door, while the bottom panel shows the crazed face of Jack Torrance (Jack Nicholson) peering through the hole. The meme is used to humorously depict an aggressive, unwelcome, or overly enthusiastic intrusion of one subject into another's space, life, or peace.

dad-belt-template.name: dad-belt-template

text_options.description: This speech bubble is for the son, who is on the ground. The text here typically represents the action, statement, or belief that has provoked the father's wrath. It's often a meek or defensive reply, or a simple statement of what he's doing that is considered unacceptable by the father figure.

This large, spiky speech bubble belongs to the angry father. The text placed here is the father's furious question or exclamation, expressing his shock and disapproval. It's the setup for the son's response in the other text box, often a variation of "What is this?" or a direct condemnation of the son's activity.

dad-belt-template.image_description: This meme, often called "Dad with a Belt" or "Art Thou Winning, Son?", is a dark twist on the wholesome "Are Ya Winning, Son?" meme. It depicts an angry, large father figure holding a belt and looming over his son, who is cowering on the floor. The template is used to express extreme disapproval or a comically over-the-top negative reaction to something the son is doing, saying, or viewing, which is revealed in the text.

F-dinosaur.name: F-dinosaur

text_options.description: The bottom text region, labeled with index 0, typically contains the second half or the concluding part of the philosophical question. It completes the thought introduced in the top text, delivering the punchline or the core of the paradox.

The top text region, labeled with index 1, is where the first part of the philosophical question or paradoxical statement is placed. It sets up the premise for the "deep thought" that the Philosoraptor is contemplating.

F-dinosaur.image_description: This image is the "Philosoraptor" meme template, featuring a blue toy Tyrannosaurus Rex with a pensive expression. The meme is used to pose philosophical questions, paradoxes, or "shower thoughts" that are often humorous or thought-provoking. The format typically presents a two-part question, split between the top and bottom of the image, mimicking a deep contemplation.

Thanos-Infinity-Stones.name: Thanos-Infinity-Stones

text_options.description: This label is placed on Thanos. The text here represents the final product, the ultimate achievement, or the person who has successfully gathered all the 'stones' (items listed above). It serves as the punchline of the meme.
This label is on the Reality Stone (red). It represents one of the six necessary components or ingredients needed to achieve the final form represented by Thanos.
This label is on the Time Stone (green). It represents another one of the six essential items or qualities that contribute to the final outcome in the bottom panel.
This label is on the Soul Stone (orange). Like the other stones, this text box is for one of the six parts that make up the whole.
This label is on the Power Stone (purple). It's another slot for a component, contributing to the collection that results in the 'Thanos' entity.
This label is on the Space Stone (blue). This is another of the six required elements that are being collected.
This label is on the Mind Stone (yellow). This is the final component in the set of six, completing the collection required to achieve the ultimate power or state depicted by Thanos.

Thanos-Infinity-Stones.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from Marvel's 'Avengers: Infinity War,' featuring the villain Thanos and the six powerful Infinity Stones. The meme is used to represent the act of collecting a complete set of related items. The six stones are labeled with different components, and the image of Thanos below represents the final, powerful, or often humorous result of combining them all, as if saying 'Finally, I have them all.'

Sad-Cat-Holding-Dog.name: Sad-Cat-Holding-Dog

text_options.description: This text box is on the final, extreme close-up of the cat's face. It typically contains the punchline or the most dramatic reaction, often a direct, emotional question or accusation from the cat's perspective, representing the peak of its feeling of betrayal.

Located on the third panel, which is a closer shot of the cat, this text box usually contains a thought or statement that builds suspense or expresses the cat's growing disbelief and hurt before the final panel's reaction.

Positioned over the cat in the background of the second panel, this text box often represents the cat's initial, quiet observation of the situation, marking the beginning of its realization that it is being ignored.

This text box is placed over the person hugging the dog. It's used to label the object of affection (the dog) or to show what the person is saying, usually something positive or loving, which contrasts with the cat's negative feelings.
This label, placed in the first panel, typically identifies the person giving the affection (e.g., 'Me,' 'My parents,' 'Gamers'). It sets up the main actor in the scenario of favoritism or neglect.

Sad-Cat-Holding-Dog.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as 'Jealous Cat,' depicts a person affectionately hugging a brown dog while a ginger cat watches from the background. The panels progressively zoom in on the cat's face, which shows an expression of shock, betrayal, and sadness. The meme is used to illustrate situations where someone or something feels neglected or replaced by a new favorite, highlighting feelings of jealousy and abandonment.

4-Spiderman-pointing-at-each-other.name: 4-Spiderman-pointing-at-each-other

text_options.description: Text placed here labels one of the entities in the standoff. This Spider-Man, along with the others, represents a group, person, or idea that is identical or hypocritically similar to the others it's confronting.
Text here identifies another one of the identical parties involved in the mutual accusation. This character is often labeled with a concept or group that is indistinguishable from the others.
This position is used to label a third identical party in the confrontation. The text here contributes to the core joke of the meme, which is the lack of self-awareness among similar entities.
In this expanded version of the meme, text here labels a fourth identical entity, further emphasizing the absurdity and scale of the hypocrisy or similarity being depicted.

4-Spiderman-pointing-at-each-other.image_description: This meme, known as "Spider-Man Pointing," originates from a 1967 animated Spider-Man episode. It depicts multiple identical Spider-Men pointing at each other in a circle, creating a visual standoff. The meme is used to humorously call out hypocrisy, irony, or situations where two or more parties are guilty of the same thing they are accusing the other of. It perfectly captures the absurdity of a "pot calling the kettle black" scenario or when similar entities clash.

You-Guys-always-act-like-youre-better-th.name: You-Guys-always-act-like-youre-better-than-me

text_options.description: This label is on Peter Griffin, the father. Text here represents one of the superior options or entities that look down on the subject in the top panel. It's a key part of the punchline.

This label is on Lois Griffin, the mother. Text here represents another superior option, working in conjunction with the other labels in the bottom panel to create a sense of overwhelming superiority.
This label is on Chris Griffin, the son. Text here provides a third example of something superior, completing the trio that is "better than" the subject labeled on Meg.
This label is on Meg Griffin. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is complaining about being treated as inferior. This sets up the premise of the meme.

You-Guys-always-act-like-youre-better-th.image_description: This is a two-panel meme from the animated TV show "Family Guy." The top panel shows the character Meg Griffin looking frustrated and saying, "You guys always act like you're better than me." The bottom panel shows the other family members—Peter, Lois, and Chris Griffin—dressed in fancy, aristocratic clothing, silently confirming her statement with their smug, superior appearance. The meme is used to contrast something considered inferior (Meg) with several things that are presented as obviously superior (the rest of the family).
You-Guys-always-act-like-youre-better-th.display_name: You Guys always act like youre better than me

Roblox-Ban.name: Roblox-Ban

text_options.description: This box highlights a button, typically for the user to acknowledge the message, such as "Reactivate Account" or "I Agree". In the meme, this is the final, often unchanged, element of the official notice.

This large central area is for the "Offensive Item." This is a primary customizable part of the meme, where a user inserts a humorous image or text that serves as the visual punchline for the fake ban.

This section displays the "Reason" for the moderation. Along with the "Offensive Item," this is a key area for customization in the meme, where a user writes a funny or absurd justification for the ban.
This is the "Moderator Note" field. It provides an optional space for an additional layer of humor, where a creator can add a funny comment from the perspective of the fictional moderator.
This field, labeled "Reviewed," typically contains a timestamp. In the meme format, this detail is often left as is or ignored, as it's not central to the main joke.

This is the header or title of the notification, which usually states the severity of the moderation (e.g., "Warning," "Your account has been deleted"). This text can be edited to set up the premise of the joke.

Roblox-Ban.image_description: This is the "Roblox Ban" meme template, which is a screenshot of an account moderation notice from the online game platform Roblox. The humor of the meme comes from editing the official-looking notice to display absurd, funny, or satirical reasons for the user's ban. Users typically replace the "Reason" and "Offensive Item" fields with comical text and images to create a joke about being banned for a ridiculous action.

girl-running.name: girl-running

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region, often placed over the running girl, identifies the person or group that is running. It acts as the subject of the meme, representing who is hastily reacting to the situation described in the top text.

The text in this top region describes the situation or context that prompts the urgent action. It sets up the scenario from which the subject (the girl) is either fleeing or to which she is rushing, providing the punchline or reason for her haste.

girl-running.image_description: This meme, known as "Chubby Bubbles Girl" or "Girl Running," features a young girl in a yellow raincoat running with a sense of urgency across a grassy field. Her wide-eyed, determined expression while clutching a bubble wand makes the image highly relatable for situations requiring a hasty retreat or eager pursuit. The meme is typically used to humorously depict someone quickly leaving an awkward situation or rushing towards something they want.

Peasants.name: Peasants

text_options.description: Text in this area identifies the group or individual who is doing the judging. It often takes the form of "Me and the boys" or a similar collective pronoun to establish the user and their friends as the superior, judging party represented by the Volturi.

The top text box describes the person, action, or thing being looked down upon and judged by the Volturi. Its position at the top, separate from the characters, implies that this is what they are observing from their elevated position on the balcony.

Peasants.image_description: This meme features Aro and other members of the Volturi from the movie "The Twilight Saga: New Moon," looking down from a balcony with expressions of disdain and judgment. The characters are powerful, ancient vampires who act as royalty, and their condescending posture is central to the meme's meaning. This format is used to express a sense of superiority or to mock something perceived as common, unsophisticated, or inferior from a detached, judgmental perspective.

Evil-Toddler.name: Evil-Toddler

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, acting as the punchline. This caption reveals the mischievous or 'evil' plan, directly corresponding to the baby's scheming expression.
The top text of the meme, which sets up the context or situation. This line provides the premise that leads to the mischievous thought expressed in the bottom text.

Evil-Toddler.image_description: This meme, known as "Evil Plotting Baby" or "Scheming Baby," features a toddler with a mischievous and cunning expression, clasping their hands together. The image humorously juxtaposes the baby's apparent innocence with a devious plan or thought. It's typically used to express a clever, sometimes slightly malevolent, idea in a two-line setup and punchline format.

gandalf-you-shall-not-pass.name: gandalf-you-shall-not-pass

text_options.description: This text is placed over Gandalf and serves as the punchline, representing the confused reaction. The classic text here is 'I have no memory of this place,' which is a direct quote from the movie that perfectly matches his bewildered expression and the meme's theme of forgetfulness.

The top text box provides the setup or context for Gandalf's confusion. It typically describes a relatable scenario where someone would feel lost or forgetful, such as a question from a teacher or a common moment of absent-mindedness.

gandalf-you-shall-not-pass.image_description: This meme features the wizard Gandalf from 'The Lord of the Rings' looking confused and disoriented. He has long white hair and a beard, and is holding a sword and a staff. The meme, often called 'I Have No Memory of This Place,' is used to express confusion, forgetfulness, or being completely lost in a situation. It humorously captures the feeling of entering a room and forgetting why, or being asked a question about something one has just learned but cannot recall.

Guy-smoking-while-two-people-fight.name: Guy-smoking-while-two-people-fight

text_options.description: This label is placed on the young man dabbing. The text here represents the person, group, or entity that is ignoring a significant problem or responsibility, choosing instead to focus on a trivial or self-indulgent activity.
This label is placed on the two women fighting. The text here describes the chaotic situation, urgent problem, or important responsibility that is being ignored by the subject in the other panel.

Guy-smoking-while-two-people-fight.image_description: This two-panel meme, often called 'Dabbing Guy' or 'Guy Dabbing in the Background,' contrasts a chaotic event with blissful ignorance. The left panel shows two women physically fighting, representing a major problem, conflict, or responsibility. The right panel shows a shirtless young man calmly hitting a dab rig, symbolizing someone who is completely ignoring the adjacent turmoil in favor of their own enjoyment.
Guy-smoking-while-two-people-fight.display_name: Guy smoking while two people fight

Relief.name: Relief

text_options.description: This lower section of the image typically contains text describing the stressful, anxiety-inducing, or dangerous situation that has just been averted. It serves as the setup for the reaction shot of Robert Downey Jr.

This top section often contains a label identifying the person or group experiencing the relief, such as "Me:" or a more specific description. It provides context for who is reacting to the situation described below.

Relief.image_description: This meme features a candid photo of actor Robert Downey Jr. with his eyes closed and a hand over his chest, conveying a strong sense of relief. Known as "Robert Downey Jr. Relieved" or "Tony Stark's Relief," the image is used to represent the feeling of narrowly avoiding a disaster or a stressful situation. The format typically involves a caption describing a high-anxiety scenario, with the image serving as the punchline of profound relief.

Red-Button-Hand.name: Red-Button-Hand

text_options.description: Text placed on the red button describes a tempting offer, a desirable action, or a relatable situation. This is the choice or option that elicits the enthusiastic response from the person represented by the hand.

Text labeling the hand identifies the person, group, or entity that is eagerly making the choice. It's often labeled with "Me" or a specific demographic to create a relatable scenario where the subject can't resist the option on the button.

Red-Button-Hand.image_description: This meme, often called the "Nut Button" or "Slapping a Button," features a motion-blurred image of a hand about to slam a large red button. It humorously represents an immediate, enthusiastic, and often impulsive reaction to a tempting offer, idea, or situation. The meme's format emphasizes the eagerness and lack of hesitation in making a particular choice, highlighting a relatable or desirable scenario.

Babe-Its-4PM-time-for-your.name: Babe-Its-4PM-time-for-your

text_options.description: This text box is placed under the sad, deformed Wojak. It typically contains the argument, statement, or identity that the meme creator is mocking or portraying as inferior and pathetic.

This text box is positioned under the composed, smug-looking woman. The text here represents the viewpoint, statement, or identity that is being presented as superior, correct, or desirable in the comparison.

Babe-Its-4PM-time-for-your.image_description: This meme, often called "Tradwife vs. Brainlet," is a comparative Wojak format. It features a smug-looking woman in a red sweater on the left, representing a supposedly superior, traditional, or correct viewpoint. On the right is a sad, deformed Wojak character, representing an inferior, foolish, or losing argument. The meme is used to contrast two opposing ideas or groups, framing one as intelligent and the other as pathetic.

what-is-my-purpose.name: what-is-my-purpose

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the robot in the final panel as it looks down in despair. This is where the robot's reaction to its purpose is written, typically "Oh my God" as in the original scene, or another phrase expressing existential dread or disappointment, which serves as the punchline.

Positioned near Rick Sanchez in the middle panel, this text box contains his answer to the robot's question. The text here defines the mundane or underwhelming purpose, with the canonical line being "You pass butter." This line is central to the meme's humor, as it's a comically simple answer to a profound question.

This text box is placed over the robot in the first panel, where it looks up expectantly. This is where the robot's question is placed, usually "What is my purpose?" This text sets up the entire premise of the meme, initiating the existential inquiry.

what-is-my-purpose.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "What is my purpose?" or "Butter Robot," originates from the animated series Rick and Morty. It depicts a small robot having an existential crisis after its creator, Rick Sanchez, tells it that its sole purpose is to pass butter. The format is used to humorously express feelings of uselessness, having a mundane or unfulfilling role, or the disappointment of a grand expectation meeting a simple reality.

Trying-to-explain.name: Trying-to-explain

text_options.description: This area typically represents the person or entity listening to the convoluted explanation. The text here is often a simple name or a short, dismissive question, providing a stark contrast to the complex theory being presented above.

This section, placed over the conspiracy board, contains the main text of the meme. It's used for a long, rambling, and often absurd explanation or theory that the user is trying to convey, mimicking Charlie's frantic energy in the original scene.

Trying-to-explain.image_description: This meme features Charlie Kelly from the TV show 'It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia' manically explaining a conspiracy theory. He stands in front of a wall covered in papers connected by red string, a setup often called a "conspiracy board." The meme is used to humorously depict someone trying to explain a complex, far-fetched, or nonsensical theory, often to an unimpressed audience. It perfectly captures the feeling of overthinking or connecting unrelated dots in a frantic manner.

Blank-Trophy.name: Blank-Trophy

text_options.description: This text box is on the plaque at the base of the trophy. It typically names the person, group, or entity receiving the sarcastic award, functioning as the 'recipient' field.

Located on the main cup of the trophy, this text describes the 'achievement' for which the award is being given. This is the punchline, detailing the funny, embarrassing, or negative reason for the fake award.

Blank-Trophy.image_description: This meme features a generic gold trophy, a universal symbol for first place or a significant achievement. The format is used ironically to create a fake award for something mundane, absurd, or undesirable. The humor arises from sarcastically celebrating a failure, a cringeworthy action, or a relatable frustration as if it were a grand accomplishment.

Inspirational-Quote.name: Inspirational-Quote

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the water, which reflects the sky. It contains the punchline or the 'reflection' of the statement made in the top panel. The text here is a direct response or consequence, deriving its meaning from the setup above.
This text box is located in the top half of the image, over the sky. It serves as the setup for the meme, presenting an initial statement, question, or concept.

Inspirational-Quote.image_description: This meme format uses a serene landscape image of a sky reflecting perfectly in a calm body of water at sunset. The image is split into two panels, the sky and its reflection, to create a visual metaphor. It's typically used to compare a concept or statement (in the sky) with its 'reflection' or consequence (in the water), which is often a humorous twist, a literal interpretation, or an unexpected outcome.

old-lady-at-computer.name: old-lady-at-computer

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline. It typically contains a humorous, naive, or literal interpretation of the setup from the top text, often formatted as a search query the grandma might type, highlighting her unfamiliarity with the internet.

The top text area sets up the scenario. It usually contains a phrase or question that leads to the grandma's surprised reaction, often from the perspective of someone asking her to do something or a thought she has.

old-lady-at-computer.image_description: This meme, known as 'Grandma Finds the Internet' or 'Internet Grandma,' features an elderly woman squinting at a laptop screen with a look of shock and confusion. She is adjusting her glasses as if she's just discovered something unbelievable online. The meme humorously captures the perspective of someone unfamiliar with internet culture, often using a top/bottom text format to represent their naive or funny search queries and reactions to modern online content.

Disappointed-Muhammad-Sarim-Akhtar.name: Disappointed-Muhammad-Sarim-Akhtar

text_options.description: This bottom text box is typically used for the punchline, describing the specific action, event, or person that is causing the disappointment. It provides the context for the man's disapproving reaction.
This top text box usually represents the person or entity who is feeling disappointed or judgmental, often labeled as "Me," "My parents," or any group that had certain expectations that were not met.

Disappointed-Muhammad-Sarim-Akhtar.image_description: This meme, known as "Disappointed Cricket Fan" or "Angry Pakistani Fan," features a man named Sarim Akhtar with his hands on his hips, staring with a look of profound disappointment. The image was captured at a 2019 Cricket World Cup match after a Pakistani player dropped a catch, perfectly encapsulating his frustration. The meme is widely used to express disapproval, frustration, or being let down by someone's actions, a failed expectation, or a disappointing outcome.

GTA-5-Franklin-and-his-dog-Chop.name: GTA-5-Franklin-and-his-dog-Chop

text_options.description: This label is placed on the aggressively barking Rottweiler, Chop. Text here typically represents a chaotic, aggressive, or problematic force, person, or idea that is being controlled or unleashed by the entity labeled on Franklin.

This label is placed on the character Franklin Clinton, who is holding the dog's leash. Text here represents the person, group, or concept that is in control of, enabling, or about to unleash the aggressive entity represented by Chop.

GTA-5-Franklin-and-his-dog-Chop.image_description: This image is a promotional artwork from the video game Grand Theft Auto V, featuring the character Franklin Clinton holding his aggressive Rottweiler, Chop, on a leash while also holding a baseball bat. In meme culture, this image is used as an object-labeling format to depict a dynamic of controlled aggression. Franklin represents a person or entity that controls or is about to unleash a more aggressive or chaotic force, which is represented by Chop.
GTA-5-Franklin-and-his-dog-Chop.display_name: GTA 5 Franklin and his dog Chop

No-Fear-One-Fear.name: No-Fear-One-Fear

text_options.description: This central panel is where the object of fear is placed. Meme creators insert an image of something, often mundane or humorous, that causes the character's sudden terror, creating the punchline.
This is the title banner of the original comic strip, reading "TEEN COMIX" and "ONE BIG MEME '15". It provides attribution and context but is often cropped out in modern versions of the meme.

No-Fear-One-Fear.image_description: This is the "One Fear" meme, a three-panel comic strip. In the first panel, a character wearing sunglasses and a t-shirt that says "NO FEAR" stands confidently. In the second, hidden panel, they encounter something that terrifies them, leading to the third panel where they are visibly scared and their shirt has changed to read "ONE FEAR". The meme is used to humorously express a single, often specific or trivial, fear that contradicts a person's otherwise brave facade.

Suspicious-Dog.name: Suspicious-Dog

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, acting as the punchline. This text typically contains a skeptical or judgmental response to the setup in the top text, often phrased as a suspicious question or a cynical internal thought that reflects the dog's expression.

The top text of the meme, which serves as the setup. This area usually contains a statement, quote, or description of a scenario that is meant to be viewed with suspicion or judgment, providing the context for the dog's side-eye reaction.

Suspicious-Dog.image_description: This meme, known as "Judgmental Dog" or "Side-eyeing Dog," features a close-up photo of a brown dachshund giving a suspicious sideways glance. The dog's squinted eyes and slight head turn create a powerful expression of skepticism, disapproval, or judgment. This image is typically used in a two-panel advice animal format to react to a questionable statement or situation, with the dog's expression embodying the viewer's doubt.

Happy-sad.name: Happy-sad

text_options.description: This text box, positioned next to the man's disappointed face, delivers the punchline. It describes the negative outcome, the harsh reality, or the disappointing truth that shatters the initial positive expectation set up in the top panel.

This text box, located next to the smiling man, sets up the meme's premise. It typically contains a statement describing a positive expectation, a hopeful situation, or something that would initially cause happiness or excitement.

Happy-sad.image_description: This is the "Disappointed Black Guy" meme, also known as "Smiling and Disappointed Black Guy." The two-panel format features a man from the web series "Hood Documentary" first smiling with excitement and then looking down with a crestfallen, disappointed expression. The meme is used to illustrate a stark contrast between a positive expectation or initial situation and the subsequent disappointing reality. It perfectly captures the feeling of being let down or realizing something is not as good as it first seemed.

who-is-that-pokemon.name: who-is-that-pokemon

text_options.description: This area displays the Pokémon logo. In the meme format, this logo is replaced by the punchline, which is an intentionally incorrect name for the character or object revealed. A classic example of the punchline text here would be "It's Pikachu!" regardless of what is actually shown.

This upper area is where the full, revealed image of the character or object is displayed, replacing the silhouette from the first part of the meme. This reveal sets up the punchline that appears in the text box below (index 0).

who-is-that-pokemon.image_description: This image is from the "Who's That Pokémon?" segment of the original Pokémon anime series. In the show, this screen would appear after a commercial break to reveal the identity of a Pokémon previously shown only in silhouette. The format has become a popular meme where a silhouette of a character or object is shown, followed by this reveal screen, but with an absurdly incorrect name as the answer, subverting expectations for comedic effect.

Guy-talking-to-girl-in-club.name: Guy-talking-to-girl-in-club

text_options.description: Text in this lower region typically identifies the woman or her simple preceding question/action. This serves as the punchline, contrasting her simple state with the man's overly complex explanation and highlighting the absurdity of the situation.

The text in this upper area, placed over the man shouting, represents the long, niche, or mundane topic he is passionately 'explaining.' This text is the setup of the joke, presenting information that is comically out of place in a loud club and demonstrates his social unawareness.

Guy-talking-to-girl-in-club.image_description: This meme, known as 'Bro Explaining' or 'Man Explaining to Woman in Club,' features a man enthusiastically shouting into a woman's ear in a loud nightclub, while she looks bored and unimpressed. The format is used to satirize situations where someone passionately explains a niche or uninteresting topic to an unwilling listener, often representing mansplaining or social cluelessness. The humor comes from the contrast between his intense delivery and her utter disinterest.
Guy-talking-to-girl-in-club.display_name: Guy talking to girl in club

Look-Marge.name: Look-Marge

text_options.description: The bottom text box is the punchline, which Homer is pointing at. It typically contains a single word or short phrase, such as 'Me' or 'My last brain cell,' identifying the subject of the statement in the top box.
The top text box sets up the joke. It usually contains a statement describing a negative trait, a foolish action, or an undesirable situation.

Look-Marge.image_description: This meme features the character Homer Simpson from the animated series 'The Simpsons', looking worried and pointing downwards with both index fingers against a black background. The format is typically used as a demotivational poster for self-deprecating humor. A general statement or description of a person is placed at the top, and Homer points to the bottom text, which identifies the subject, often the creator of the meme themselves.

More-likely-than-you-think.name: More-likely-than-you-think

text_options.description: This area contains the fixed tagline of the meme, "It's more likely than you think." It serves as the punchline, ironically framing the absurd scenario presented in the text box above as a common, statistically probable event, which is the core of the meme's humor.

This is the primary editable text area of the meme. Users insert a surprising, absurd, or niche statement here, often about a specific online activity or a relatable but unspoken thought. This text sets up the joke that is completed by the tagline below.

More-likely-than-you-think.image_description: This meme, known as "It's More Likely Than You Think," originates from a 2005 banner ad for ContentWatch internet filtering software. The image features a stock photo of a Black woman with a serious, concerned expression. The meme's humor comes from replacing the original context with an absurd, niche, or embarrassing statement, which is then validated by the tagline, creating a comedic juxtaposition.

We-are-not-the-same.name: We-are-not-the-same
