text_options.description: This bottom section contains the punchline of the meme. It typically presents the creator's contrasting, often more elaborate or absurd, reason for an action, followed by the signature phrase, "We are not the same."
The top text box introduces the premise of the meme. It usually describes a common action and a simple or conventional motivation for it, often starting with "You..." to set up the comparison.

We-are-not-the-same.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor Giancarlo Esposito, often associated with his role as the calm and calculating villain Gus Fring from "Breaking Bad" and "Better Call Saul". The image is the foundation for the "We Are Not the Same" meme format. This format is used to humorously contrast two different motivations for the same action, with the speaker's motivation presented as superior, more complex, or simply different, echoing the character's composed and superior demeanor.

wanted-poster.name: wanted-poster

text_options.description: The bottom panel, which delivers the punchline of the meme. This section typically describes the 'crime' committed by the subject or the 'reward' for their capture, providing the humorous twist that completes the joke.
The middle panel, serving as the setup or a descriptive line. This text builds upon the subject from the top panel, often listing a specific trait, action, or reason why the subject is being sought.

The topmost panel, directly under the 'WANTED' heading. This space is typically used to introduce the main subject of the meme, often with a name, a title, or an image of the person or thing being 'wanted'.

wanted-poster.image_description: This meme template is a classic Old West-style 'Wanted' poster, featuring weathered parchment on a wooden background. The bold 'WANTED' text at the top sets a humorous tone for calling someone or something out. The three blank panels below are used to build a joke, typically by introducing a subject, describing a characteristic, and delivering a punchline or 'crime'.

sleepy-donald-duck-in-bed.name: sleepy-donald-duck-in-bed

text_options.description: This text presents a comforting thought, a simple solution, or a satisfying realization that allows the person to sleep soundly, corresponding to Donald Duck's peaceful slumber in the bottom panel.
This text describes a worry, an intrusive thought, or a complex problem that keeps someone awake at night, corresponding to Donald Duck's distressed, sleepless expression in the top panel.

sleepy-donald-duck-in-bed.image_description: This two-panel meme features the Disney character Donald Duck in bed. In the top panel, he is wide awake with a look of concern or annoyance, representing a thought that keeps someone up at night. In the bottom panel, he is sleeping peacefully, representing a comforting or satisfying thought that allows them to rest. The meme is used to contrast anxieties or complex problems with simple, often humorous, solutions or realizations.

Disloyal-Boyfriend.name: Disloyal-Boyfriend

text_options.description: This label is placed on the girlfriend, who looks shocked and offended. The text here represents the current, sensible, or responsible option that is being neglected or ignored by the subject.
This label is placed on the man who is looking away from his girlfriend. The text here represents the subject or person who is being distracted or making a poor choice.
This label is placed on the woman in the red dress who the man is looking at. The text here represents the new, attractive, or tempting alternative that is causing the distraction.

Disloyal-Boyfriend.image_description: The "Distracted Boyfriend" meme is a stock photo showing a man in a plaid shirt looking back admiringly at a woman in a red dress, while his own girlfriend looks at him with an expression of shock and disgust. This image is used as an object-labeling meme to represent someone being tempted by something new or desirable while neglecting their current responsibilities or commitments. The man represents the user, his girlfriend represents the thing they should be doing, and the woman in red represents the alluring distraction.

my-sisters-wedding.name: my-sisters-wedding

text_options.description: This text box is located above the well-dressed version of Fernanfloo. It labels the 'after' state, the upgraded version, or the more desirable outcome, completing the humorous contrast.
This text box is positioned above the casual version of Fernanfloo. It typically labels the 'before' state, the less impressive option, or the first element in a comparison.

my-sisters-wedding.image_description: This two-panel meme features Salvadoran YouTuber Fernanfloo, showing a stark contrast in his appearance. On the left, he's dressed casually in a hoodie and plaid pajama pants, representing an ordinary or 'before' state. On the right, he's dressed formally in a black suit, representing a 'glow-up' or an impressive 'after' state. The format is used to humorously compare two vastly different situations, versions of a person, or outcomes.

What-if-you-But-god-said.name: What-if-you-But-god-said

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme. It represents the absurd, often nonsensical, statement from "God" that prevents the user from achieving their goal stated in the top panel. The humor comes from how bizarre or unrelated this statement is to the initial request.

This text box is where the user states their desire or goal, completing the phrase "What if you wanted to...". This sets up the premise of the meme, establishing what the user wants before it is comically denied in the second panel.

What-if-you-But-god-said.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format known as "What if You Wanted to Go to Heaven But God Said." The meme features a young Black man first pointing at the viewer and then holding up a finger as if making a point. It's used to express frustration or humor when a simple desire is thwarted by an absurd or nonsensical obstacle. The format follows the structure: "What if you wanted [a desirable outcome], but God said [an absurd reason why not]."
What-if-you-But-god-said.display_name: What if you But god said

Harry-You-Dont-Need-to-Sell-It-To-Me.name: Harry-You-Dont-Need-to-Sell-It-To-Me

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to Peter Parker in the final panel. It typically contains the punchline, revealing Peter's hidden, often dark or complex, thoughts or experiences that contrast with Harry's naive statement. This text explains his smug expression.

This text box is placed next to Harry Osborn. It contains a naive question or statement from Harry, who is unaware of the full context of the situation being discussed. This sets up the punchline in the final panel.
This text box is placed next to Peter Parker in the first panel. It represents an initial statement or topic introduced by Peter, which prompts Harry's naive response in the next panel.

Harry-You-Dont-Need-to-Sell-It-To-Me.image_description: This three-panel meme format, known as "So Good" or "Harry, You Have No Idea," features Peter Parker (Tobey Maguire) and Harry Osborn (James Franco) from the film Spider-Man 3. In the meme, Harry makes a naive or innocent statement, to which Peter reacts with a knowing, somewhat smug or sad smile. This format is used to contrast someone's ignorance with another's deeper, often darker, experience or knowledge on a particular subject.
Harry-You-Dont-Need-to-Sell-It-To-Me.display_name: Harry You Dont Need to Sell It To Me

Forever-alone.name: Forever-alone

text_options.description: This area, spanning the two bottom panels, is typically left blank. The images of Escobar looking dejected at a table and by an empty pool serve as the visual punchline, emphasizing the feeling of loneliness or prolonged waiting established by the text in the top panel.

The text in this top panel sets up the scenario. It usually describes a situation where the user is waiting for something to happen, feeling left out, or contemplating a mundane problem, creating a humorous contrast with Escobar's dramatic, pensive expression.

Forever-alone.image_description: This meme, known as "Sad Pablo Escobar" or "Waiting Pablo Escobar," features three stills of actor Wagner Moura as the character from the show "Narcos." He appears pensive, lonely, and lost in thought in various settings, such as on a swing set or by an empty pool. The meme is used to humorously convey feelings of waiting, boredom, or solitude in relatable, everyday situations.

megamind-no-b.name: megamind-no-b

text_options.description: This lower portion of the image, near Megamind's chin, typically contains the subject of the condescending question, followed by a question mark. For example, in the classic "No bitches?" format, this is where "bitches?" would be placed, completing the punchline.

The text placed on Megamind's prominent forehead sets up the joke. It usually starts with "No" and is followed by the thing the viewer or subject of the meme is presumed to be lacking, leading into the punchline at the bottom.

megamind-no-b.image_description: A close-up shot of the character Megamind from the animated film of the same name, peeking through a peephole with a sad, disappointed expression. This meme format, popularly known as "No Bitches?" or "Megamind Peeking," is used to humorously question or mock someone for lacking something desirable or expected. The large forehead provides ample space for text, and the character's pitiful gaze adds a layer of comedic condescension.

Hector.name: Hector

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned near Achilles' shouting mouth, names the person or thing being sought. This text is typically written in all caps to emulate the act of shouting, directly replacing 'HECTOR!' from the original scene with the meme's subject.

The top text sets the context for the meme, identifying the person, group, or entity that is doing the intense searching or calling out. It provides the 'who' or 'why' behind Achilles' dramatic shout.

Hector.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Brad Pitt as Achilles from the 2004 film 'Troy,' wearing a helmet and shouting intensely. The scene depicts Achilles calling out for his rival, Hector, before their duel. The meme is used to humorously and dramatically represent someone searching for or calling out to another person, group, or even an inanimate object with great urgency or frustration.

Puppet-hierarchy.name: Puppet-hierarchy

text_options.description: This label is placed on the smallest puppet at the front of the line. It represents the most visible entity or the apparent actor in a situation, who is perceived to be acting independently but is actually being controlled.
This label is on the puppet directly controlling the smallest one. It represents the first layer of hidden influence or the immediate power behind the visible actor.
This label identifies the third puppet in the chain, which controls the one at index 1. This layer typically represents a more significant or systemic force that is manipulating the manipulator.

This label is on the second-largest puppet, representing an even higher and more concealed level of power in the hierarchy. This is often where the meme starts to introduce more abstract or conspiratorial elements.

This label is placed on the largest puppet at the very back, the ultimate puppeteer. This position is reserved for the final reveal or punchline, identifying the supposed true source of control, which can range from a serious accusation to an absurd or comical entity.

Puppet-hierarchy.image_description: This meme, known as "Puppet Master" or "Layers of Control," features a stock image of a series of orange mannequins in a line, each one acting as a puppeteer for a smaller one in front of it. The visual creates a powerful metaphor for a hierarchy of control or influence, often used to illustrate conspiracy theories or complex power dynamics in a humorous or critical way. The meme works by labeling each puppet to show who is supposedly controlling whom, with the largest puppet representing the ultimate, often hidden, power.

Ive-only-had-Arlo-for-a-day-and-a-half.name: Ive-only-had-Arlo-for-a-day-and-a-half

text_options.description: This box is placed on Rosa Diaz's chest in the second panel. This area can be used to label the person feeling the intense protective emotion, often with text like 'Me'. It represents the meme creator or anyone who identifies with this sudden, extreme devotion to the subject in the top panel.

This box is placed over the puppy in the first panel, covering its original name, 'Arlo'. In the meme, this is where the user places the name or an image of the new person, character, or object they have become instantly attached to, setting up the punchline about their fierce protectiveness.

Ive-only-had-Arlo-for-a-day-and-a-half.image_description: A two-panel meme from the TV show Brooklyn Nine-Nine featuring the character Rosa Diaz. In the top panel, she holds a small white puppy, and in the bottom panel, her expression is fiercely protective. The meme humorously captures the feeling of becoming instantly and intensely attached to something new, expressing a comically over-the-top desire to protect it at all costs.
Ive-only-had-Arlo-for-a-day-and-a-half.display_name: Ive only had Arlo for a day and a half

Whats-on-your-mind.name: Whats-on-your-mind

text_options.description: This area inside the head is the punchline of the meme. Users insert an image or text depicting a silly, random, or obsessive thought, which is humorously juxtaposed with the serious question asked above. This could be anything from a catchy song lyric to a complex but pointless internal debate.

Whats-on-your-mind.image_description: This meme format, often captioned "Why you so quiet? What's on your mind?", features a line drawing of a person's head with a blank space representing their brain. It's used to humorously contrast someone's quiet, pensive exterior with the often absurd, mundane, or niche thoughts occupying their mind. The humor comes from the relatable experience of being lost in trivial or silly thoughts while appearing deep and serious to others.

Welcome-To-The-Internets.name: Welcome-To-The-Internets

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area in a standard image macro format. The text here typically provides the punchline, a concluding statement, or a label that humorously summarizes the over-the-top scene above.

This is the top text area in a standard image macro format. The text placed here usually sets up a premise or introduces a situation that the absurdly epic image below serves to illustrate or react to.

Welcome-To-The-Internets.image_description: This image is a quintessential example of early 2010s internet culture, featuring a tabby cat with a red headband and a golden gun riding a majestic, rearing unicorn with glowing red eyes. The scene is a chaotic and "epic" mashup of various internet phenomena, including a rainbow, a pixelated background resembling Minecraft, and the Nyan Cat meme. This image is not a typical meme format but rather an embodiment of internet randomness, often used to represent something overwhelmingly awesome, absurd, or the pinnacle of internet culture.

Youre-a-wizard-harry.name: Youre-a-wizard-harry

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost invariably the direct quote from the movie: "I should not have said that." This text solidifies the theme of regret and is the core element that makes the meme recognizable.
The top text box sets up the context for the meme. It typically describes a situation where the user has revealed sensitive information, made a social gaffe, or overshared details they now regret.

Youre-a-wizard-harry.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Rubeus Hagrid from the Harry Potter film series, looking concerned and regretful. The image captures the moment after he accidentally reveals a secret, famously followed by his line, "I should not have said that." The meme is used to express immediate regret or remorse after saying something one shouldn't have, often something that was supposed to be a secret or was simply inappropriate for the situation.

Impressive-very-nice.name: Impressive-very-nice

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the image of Patrick Bateman speaking enthusiastically. It contains the user's own idea, creation, or opinion, which is presented as being superior to or a one-up of the concept mentioned in the top panel. This is the punchline of the meme, showcasing the user's supposedly better contribution.

Located on the top panel where Patrick Bateman is listening with a forced smile, this text box typically contains a statement, idea, or creation from another person. This serves as the setup, representing something that the user is pretending to be impressed by before revealing their own, superior version in the panel below.

Impressive-very-nice.image_description: This two-panel meme features Patrick Bateman from the film "American Psycho." In the top panel, he listens with a forced, slightly pained smile, feigning admiration. In the bottom panel, he leans forward enthusiastically, ready to present his own idea. The meme is used to represent a situation of one-upmanship, where someone pretends to be impressed by something before immediately trying to top it with their own, supposedly superior, version.

help-me-obi-wan.name: help-me-obi-wan

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the second half of the iconic quote: 'You're my only hope.' This text solidifies the desperation of the plea and emphasizes that the entity named in the top text is the final and singular resort for solving a problem.

The top text box typically contains the first part of the plea, beginning with 'Help me,' followed by the name of a person, group, or entity being addressed. This text establishes who the 'savior' or 'only hope' is in the context of the meme's joke.

help-me-obi-wan.image_description: This meme features a still from the 1977 film 'Star Wars: A New Hope,' showing a holographic projection of Princess Leia. In the scene, she delivers the famous line, 'Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi. You're my only hope.' The meme format adapts this plea to express desperation, where 'Obi-Wan Kenobi' is replaced by any person, object, or concept that is seen as the last and only solution to a problem.

Say-what-again.name: Say-what-again

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically contains the punchline, which is an aggressive and demanding phrase from Jules. It often includes variations of his famous lines like "Say 'what' again, I dare you" or "English, motherfucker, do you speak it?" to mock the statement in the top text.

The top text area is used to set up the joke by presenting a confusing, annoying, or nonsensical statement that Jules is reacting to. This text represents the initial comment that triggers the aggressive demand for clarification seen in the image.

Say-what-again.image_description: This meme features Jules Winnfield, played by Samuel L. Jackson, from the movie Pulp Fiction, intensely pointing a gun and yelling at someone. The scene is from an interrogation where he repeatedly dares a character to "say 'what' again." The meme is used to express extreme frustration or mock someone for making a confusing, nonsensical, or poorly worded statement, often challenging them to repeat it.

spongebob-fire.name: spongebob-fire

text_options.description: Text in this bottom region typically describes the person, group, or system experiencing the overwhelming chaos. It often represents the user's own state of mind or a specific entity in turmoil, for example, 'My last two brain cells during an exam'.

Text placed in this top region usually provides the context or the cause of the chaotic situation depicted. It sets the scene for the panic, often labeling a larger event or environment, such as 'The company servers after a single line of code is changed'.

spongebob-fire.image_description: This meme originates from the TV show SpongeBob SquarePants, depicting a scene inside SpongeBob's brain which is an office engulfed in flames. Multiple miniature SpongeBobs run around in panic amidst the chaos of burning desks and scattered papers. The image is widely used to represent a state of extreme chaos, panic, or mental overload in a relatable situation, such as a stressful work environment or a brain trying to process too much information.

Captain-america-elevator.name: Captain-america-elevator

text_options.description: This text box is placed where Captain America is whispering. It typically contains the first part or the setup of a terrible pun or dad joke.
This text box is placed over the agent Captain America is whispering to (Jasper Sitwell). It contains the punchline of the bad joke, completing the phrase from the first text box.

This text box is placed over another agent in the elevator (Brock Rumlow). This character often serves as the straight man, with text that sets up the joke, such as a question or a statement that Captain America can twist into a pun.

Captain-america-elevator.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Captain America Elevator Fight" or "Captain America Dad Joke," is from the film *Captain America: The Winter Soldier*. The format shows Captain America in an elevator, then whispering to an agent, and finally being attacked by everyone. The meme's humor relies on this violent overreaction being the punchline to a terrible pun or dad joke that Captain America tells.

Brace-Yourself.name: Brace-Yourself

text_options.description: The bottom text, which completes the phrase from the top, specifying the impending event. This is the punchline of the meme, such as 'Winter is coming' or any other anticipated, often dreaded, occurrence.
The top text of the meme, which almost always reads 'Brace yourselves'. This phrase acts as a setup, preparing the viewer for the warning that follows in the bottom text.

Brace-Yourself.image_description: This meme features the character Ned Stark from the HBO series 'Game of Thrones,' played by actor Sean Bean. The image is famously used for the 'Brace Yourselves, X is Coming' meme format, which humorously warns of an impending, often overwhelming, event. Ned's serious expression and heavy winter clothing create a tone of preparing for a significant challenge, making it a versatile template for various relatable situations.

water-tank-leaking-fix.name: water-tank-leaking-fix

text_options.description: This text, placed over the hand slapping the Flex Tape onto the leak, represents the comically inadequate or superficial solution being applied to the problem. It's the punchline of the meme, highlighting a quick fix that fails to address the root cause.

This label is placed over the gushing water, which symbolizes a significant, often complex or severe, problem, crisis, or flaw. The visual of the leak represents the damage or issue that needs to be addressed.

This text identifies the person, company, or entity responsible for applying the simplistic fix. In the meme, this figure (originally Phil Swift) is the one offering the half-hearted or misguided solution to the problem.

water-tank-leaking-fix.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as "Slapping on Flex Tape," features spokesperson Phil Swift from a Flex Tape infomercial. The top panel depicts a significant problem, represented by a leaking water tank, while the bottom panel shows the problem being hastily patched with a piece of tape. The meme is used to satirize the application of a simplistic, inadequate, or temporary solution to a much larger, more complex problem.

Trump-Executive-Order-2025.name: Trump-Executive-Order-2025

text_options.description: This text box is on the right-hand page of the folder Trump is holding. It's the primary space for the meme's main text or punchline, often framed as the title or key point of a fake executive order. Its prominent position makes it the focal point of the joke.

This text box is on the left-hand page of the folder. It typically contains supplementary text, a setup for the main punchline on the right, or sometimes a humorous drawing or doodle. This area is used to add context or an extra layer to the joke presented on the opposite page.

Trump-Executive-Order-2025.image_description: This meme features former US President Donald Trump in the Oval Office, holding up an open folder with two blank pages. Known as 'Trump's First Order' or 'Trump Drawing', the format is used to present humorous, absurd, or controversial statements as official executive orders. The humor comes from the contrast between Trump's serious demeanor and the often silly content edited onto the pages.

Travis-Kelce-screaming.name: Travis-Kelce-screaming

text_options.description: This area is used to label the two subjects of the meme. The text placed over the calm coach, Andy Reid (left), represents the stoic or indifferent entity, while the text over the yelling player, Travis Kelce (right), represents the passionate or demanding person making a plea.
This top caption describes the subject of the passionate outburst. It provides the context for what the yelling figure (Travis Kelce) is demanding or complaining about to the calm figure (Andy Reid).

Travis-Kelce-screaming.image_description: This meme features Kansas City Chiefs player Travis Kelce passionately yelling at his seemingly unfazed coach, Andy Reid. The image captures a moment of intense emotion from the player contrasted with the coach's calm demeanor. This format is typically used to represent a one-sided, passionate, or desperate plea directed at an indifferent, unbothered, or authoritative entity.

perfection.name: perfection

text_options.description: This bottom text box corresponds to Magneto's final, satisfied expression. The text here represents the ultimate, ideal, or 'perfect' version of a concept, delivering the punchline of the meme.

This middle text box aligns with Magneto's slightly more focused and approving expression. The text here typically describes a better or more desirable version of the concept introduced in the top panel, escalating the comparison.
This top text box is paired with Magneto's initial, neutral expression. The text here introduces a good or standard option, setting the baseline for the comparison that follows in the panels below.

perfection.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Magneto Perfection,' features three vertically stacked panels of the character Erik Lehnsherr (Magneto), played by Michael Fassbender, from the film X-Men: First Class. His expression subtly shifts from neutral observation to focused approval, culminating in a look of satisfaction. The meme is used to present a hierarchy of three related concepts or items, with each subsequent panel representing a better or more ideal version, with the final one being 'perfection'.

You-can-excuse-racism-blank.name: You-can-excuse-racism-blank

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the bottom panel where Shirley is reacting. It typically contains her sarcastic line, "Oh, that's nice," which serves as the punchline and judgmental reaction to the text in the top panel.

This text box is in the top panel, usually labeling Britta or the situation she represents. The text here describes a person, group, or statement that is being judged or reacted to negatively in the panel below.

You-can-excuse-racism-blank.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the TV show "Community" and features characters Shirley Bennett and Britta Perry. In the bottom panel, Shirley looks at someone off-screen with a shocked and judgmental expression, while the top panel shows Britta looking on with disgust. The meme is used to sarcastically react to a statement or action that is presented as positive but is actually hypocritical, cringeworthy, or unpleasant. Shirley's line, "Oh, that's nice," is the typical punchline, dripping with disapproval.

Are-ya-winning-son.name: Are-ya-winning-son

text_options.description: This area, positioned above the son at his computer, typically displays the son's response or what is on his computer screen. It serves as the punchline of the meme, revealing an absurd, humorous, or unexpected situation that contrasts with the father's simple question about 'winning'.

This box is placed over the father figure. In variations of the meme, this space can be used to label or re-identify the 'father' character to change the context of the joke. For example, labeling him 'My responsibilities' checking in on the son, who would be labeled 'Me'.

Are-ya-winning-son.image_description: This is the 'Are Ya Winning, Son?' meme, a two-panel exploitable comic featuring crudely drawn stick figures. A father figure peeks into his son's room and asks the titular question, while the son is engrossed at his computer. The humor arises from the unexpected, often bizarre, or inappropriate activity the son is engaged in, which is revealed in the second panel, creating a comedic contrast with the father's innocent query.

Office-Space-Bill-Lumbergh.name: Office-Space-Bill-Lumbergh

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which completes the phrase started at the top. This is the punchline and almost always reads '...That'd be great' or a variation thereof, delivering the signature passive-aggressive tone of the character.

The top text, positioned above Bill Lumbergh's head, sets up the sarcastic request. It typically begins with 'Yeah, if you could just...' followed by the annoying task or favor being asked, mimicking the character's speech pattern from the movie.

Office-Space-Bill-Lumbergh.image_description: This meme features Bill Lumbergh, the condescending boss from the 1999 cult classic film 'Office Space'. The image captures him in a typical office environment, making a passive-aggressive request. This format is widely used to sarcastically ask someone to perform a task, often an inconvenient or annoying one, by framing it as a polite suggestion ending with his catchphrase, '...that would be great.'

Hand-clasping.name: Hand-clasping

text_options.description: This central position over the clasped hands is reserved for the punchline—the shared belief, goal, or characteristic that unites the two parties. It represents the common ground or the point of agreement.
The text here labels the muscular white arm on the right, typically representing the first of two different groups, individuals, or concepts. This sets up one side of the comparison.

The text here labels the muscular Black arm on the left, representing the second group or concept. This entity is often presented as an opposite or rival to the first, making their eventual agreement in the center more impactful or humorous.

Hand-clasping.image_description: This meme, known as "Epic Handshake" or "Predator Handshake," depicts a close-up of two muscular arms, one Black and one white, clasping hands in a powerful arm-wrestle-like grip. Originating from a scene in the 1987 film *Predator* between characters played by Arnold Schwarzenegger and Carl Weathers, the image is used to illustrate an unexpected agreement or a shared trait between two different or opposing groups. The two arms represent the distinct entities, while the handshake symbolizes their surprising common ground.

Chef-Gordon-Ramsay.name: Chef-Gordon-Ramsay

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, typically the phrase "fucking [noun]". The noun specifies the high-quality item or content that has finally been discovered, completing the iconic quote and delivering the humorous point of the meme.

The top text box contains the setup for the meme's punchline, usually reading "Finally, some good". This text establishes the context that the subject has been searching for something of quality for a long time, building anticipation for the reveal in the bottom text.

Chef-Gordon-Ramsay.image_description: This meme features celebrity chef Gordon Ramsay in a kitchen, yelling with an intense expression. The image is a still from his reality TV show "Hell's Kitchen," where he is known for his fiery temper. This specific image is famously used for the "Finally, some good fucking [X]" meme format, which expresses immense satisfaction and relief after finding something of high quality following a period of disappointment.

Socially-Awesome-Awkward-Penguin.name: Socially-Awesome-Awkward-Penguin

text_options.description: Located in the bottom blue section, this text describes the socially awkward, embarrassing, or clumsy follow-up to the action described above. This part serves as the punchline, contrasting sharply with the initial 'awesome' setup and highlighting a relatable social failure.

Located in the top red section, this text describes a socially successful, confident, or 'awesome' action or situation. This sets up the first part of the narrative, where the subject does something cool or positive in a social context.

Socially-Awesome-Awkward-Penguin.image_description: This meme, known as Socially Awesome/Awkward Penguin, is an advice animal template used to contrast social situations. It features a penguin against a background split horizontally into red (top) and blue (bottom). The meme format sets up a socially successful or 'awesome' scenario in the top half, followed by a socially clumsy or 'awkward' outcome in the bottom half, creating a relatable and humorous narrative of social missteps.

panie-areczku.name: panie-areczku

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or the core declaration. This is the official-sounding, often humorous or absurd, statement being made by the "CEO" figure, which concludes the joke set up by the top text.

The top text box typically sets up the premise of the meme. It often introduces the man with a humorous title, such as "The CEO of [Concept]" or describes the person making the statement (e.g., "Me announcing to my friends that...").

panie-areczku.image_description: This meme features a close-up of a stern-looking man with a mustache, identified as lawyer Mark Wolters, often humorously dubbed the "CEO of" various concepts. The format is used to make a declarative, often absurd or funny, statement with an air of official authority. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of his serious, authoritative expression with a ridiculous proclamation, as if he is the ultimate decision-maker on the subject.

Finding-Nemo-Seagulls.name: Finding-Nemo-Seagulls

text_options.description: This text box, positioned at the bottom near the foreground seagull, typically labels the individual or object that is the target of the group's intense focus. It represents the person or thing that possesses something the others desperately want.

This text box is placed over the flock of seagulls in the background. It represents the collective, repetitive demand of the group, often a single word or short phrase that corresponds to what the individual in box 0 has. This mimics their famous "Mine!" chant from the movie.

Finding-Nemo-Seagulls.image_description: This meme features a flock of seagulls from the Disney/Pixar movie "Finding Nemo." In the film, these seagulls are known for their iconic and repetitive chant of "Mine!" The meme format uses this scene to represent a situation where a large, demanding group collectively clamors for something held by a single individual. The single seagull in the foreground often represents the meme creator or a specific entity, while the flock in the background represents the demanding crowd.

Anime-girl-buying.name: Anime-girl-buying

text_options.description: Text here labels Hana Shirosaki, who represents the person, group, or entity eagerly and happily receiving the item or concept presented in the panel above. Her excited expression signifies a positive reception to the offering.
This area on the wooden tray contains the main subject or punchline of the meme. It represents the actual thing being offered or presented, which is revealed after the setup in the first panel.
Text placed on Miyako's hand as it covers the tray typically serves as the setup or a misdirection. It introduces an initial idea before the actual subject is revealed in the next panel.

Anime-girl-buying.image_description: This three-panel meme format, known as "Wataten Presentation" or "Miyako presenting something to Hana," originates from the anime series *Wataten!: An Angel Flew Down to Me*. It features the character Miyako Hoshino presenting something on a tray to the eagerly awaiting Hana Shirosaki. The meme is used to showcase something desirable, wholesome, or exciting being offered to a receptive audience, with the first panel often acting as a setup and the second as the reveal.

Car-Drift-Meme.name: Car-Drift-Meme

text_options.description: The text here labels the car, representing the person or entity making an impulsive and sudden decision.
This area on the highway sign represents the sensible, expected, or responsible choice that is being ignored. It's the path the subject was on before making a last-minute change.
This area on the highway sign, pointing to the exit, represents the tempting, impulsive, or more desirable option that causes the sudden change in direction. This is often the punchline of the meme.

Car-Drift-Meme.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Left Exit 12 Off-Ramp,' depicts a car making a sudden, reckless turn to take a highway exit. The top panel shows a highway sign presenting two choices, while the bottom panel shows the car swerving dramatically to choose the exit. This format is used to illustrate someone abruptly choosing a more tempting, impulsive, or unconventional option over a more sensible or planned-out one.

Captain-Picard-Facepalm.name: Captain-Picard-Facepalm

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which typically describes the specific foolish action, statement, or event that elicits the facepalm reaction. This serves as the punchline or the direct cause of the frustration.
The top text, which sets up the context or presents a situation. This text establishes the premise that leads to the frustrating or disappointing outcome described in the bottom text.

Captain-Picard-Facepalm.image_description: This meme, known as "Picard Facepalm" or "Facepalm," features Captain Jean-Luc Picard from Star Trek: The Next Generation. The image captures Picard with his palm covering his face in a gesture of extreme frustration, disappointment, or exasperation. It is widely used as a reaction image to express disbelief at something perceived as incredibly foolish, illogical, or embarrassing.

Fancy-pooh.name: Fancy-pooh

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the most sophisticated version of Winnie the Pooh, who is wearing a tuxedo, top hat, monocle, and mustache. The text here represents the most elaborate, verbose, or comically pretentious version of a concept, completing the escalation from simple to fancy.

This text box corresponds to the middle panel, where Winnie the Pooh is wearing a tuxedo and looking smugly pleased. The text here is a more formal, sophisticated, or refined version of the initial concept presented in the top panel, serving as an intermediate step in the escalation of fanciness.

This text box is adjacent to the top panel, which shows the standard, unimpressed-looking Winnie the Pooh in his red shirt. The text placed here is typically a simple, common, or mundane word, phrase, or concept that serves as the baseline for the comparison.

Fancy-pooh.image_description: This is the "Tuxedo Winnie the Pooh" or "Fancy Pooh" meme, a multi-panel exploitable format. It features three images of Winnie the Pooh that show him becoming progressively more sophisticated and formal in his attire, from his regular red shirt to a tuxedo, and finally a tuxedo with a top hat, monocle, and mustache. The meme is used to compare different ways of saying or doing something, ranking them from simple and common to increasingly refined, verbose, or pretentious, mirroring Pooh's escalating elegance.

Rainbow-Six---Fuze-The-Hostage.name: Rainbow-Six---Fuze-The-Hostage

text_options.description: Text placed over the crawling hostage represents something vulnerable, a problem, or a person in a difficult situation that is about to be made worse by a misguided attempt to help.
Text placed over the diving soldier, Fuze, represents the supposed savior, solution, or well-intentioned force that is ironically the cause of the impending disaster for the entity labeled in box 0.

Rainbow-Six---Fuze-The-Hostage.image_description: This meme, known as 'Fuze Elbow Dropping a Hostage', depicts a scene from the video game Rainbow Six Siege. In the illustration, the operator Fuze is shown in mid-air, about to land on a terrified female hostage who is crawling on the ground. The humor stems from the in-game reputation of Fuze, whose special ability often accidentally kills the hostage he is supposed to rescue. The meme is used to represent a situation where a supposed solution or protector ends up being the primary source of harm or failure.

Simpsons-bart-no.name: Simpsons-bart-no

text_options.description: This label is on Bart Simpson. He represents the usual or expected subject of the reaction. In the meme's narrative, he is the person or thing that Marge habitually reacts to, even when the initial stimulus is different.

This is the setup for the joke. The text placed here describes an unusual or unexpected event, statement, or piece of news that prompts Marge's shocked reaction. It establishes a new context that makes her subsequent habitual response humorous or ironic.

This label is on Marge Simpson. She represents the person, entity, or group that has a deeply ingrained, almost pavlovian, response to a certain stimulus. Her shocked face is the initial part of this habitual reaction, which is then explained away in the final panel.

Simpsons-bart-no.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Sorry, Force of Habit," features Marge and Bart Simpson from the animated series The Simpsons. In the top panel, Marge has a shocked expression in response to a statement. The bottom panels show her questioning Bart, then apologizing with "Sorry, force of habit." The meme is used to illustrate an ingrained, automatic reaction to a situation where that reaction is no longer appropriate or correct, highlighting the power of habit.

Squidward.name: Squidward

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the image of the normal, stressed-out Squidward. The text here represents the inferior, disappointing, or realistic outcome that contrasts with the ideal presented in the top panel. It serves as the punchline of the comparison.

This text box is placed over the image of "Handsome Squidward." The text here typically describes an idealized, superior, or desirable concept or situation. It sets up the positive side of the comparison that will be contrasted with the bottom panel.

Squidward.image_description: This meme, known as "Handsome Squidward vs. Normal Squidward," is a two-panel comparison format from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants. The top panel features a chiseled, serene "Handsome Squidward," representing an idealized, superior, or desired state. The bottom panel shows the regular, stressed-out Squidward, representing a disappointing reality, an inferior state, or a negative outcome. The meme is used to humorously contrast expectations versus reality or a positive concept against its negative counterpart.

Knight-with-arrow-in-helmet.name: Knight-with-arrow-in-helmet

text_options.description: This label is placed directly on the arrow that has pierced the knight's helmet. The text here represents the punchline of the meme—the specific, often mundane or silly obstacle that completely derails the plan or goal mentioned in the top panel.

Text in this position, over the image of the capable-looking knight, establishes the setup. It describes a user's plan, goal, or positive intention, setting an expectation of success that will be subverted by the bottom panel.

Knight-with-arrow-in-helmet.image_description: This two-panel meme features a knight in full plate armor. The top panel shows the knight looking proud and ready, representing a plan, goal, or ideal situation. The bottom panel is a close-up showing the same knight with an arrow shot through the eye slit of their helmet, symbolizing a specific, often unexpected obstacle that derails the original intention. The meme is used to humorously contrast high aspirations with the single, simple thing that ruins them.

gotta-be-one-of-my-favorite-genders.name: gotta-be-one-of-my-favorite-genders

text_options.description: This is the customizable part of the meme, where the user inserts the name of a person, group, or concept they want to praise. The text here serves as the subject of the 'shout out' and the setup for the punchline below, completing the phrase 'Shout out to [text 0]'.

gotta-be-one-of-my-favorite-genders.image_description: This meme, known as 'Shout Out To... Gotta Be One of My Favorite Genders,' features a young man with his hands clasped in a gesture of appreciation in front of a Mercedes-Benz. The format is used to give a 'shout out' or express strong, often humorous, admiration for a person, group, or even an inanimate object or concept. The punchline, 'Gotta be one of my favorite genders,' hyperbolically elevates the subject of praise to a fundamental category of being, creating a comedic effect.
gotta-be-one-of-my-favorite-genders.display_name: gotta be one of my favorite genders

Im-tired-of-this-Grandpa.name: Im-tired-of-this-Grandpa

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline, representing the old man's frustrated or pained reaction. It's his response to being reminded of a past promise, often an outburst, an excuse, or the original line from the movie, "Well, that's too damn bad!"

This text box represents the setup, where the young girl reminds the old man of a promise he made. The text is typically phrased as a direct quote, starting with something like "Grandpa, you said..." or "But you promised..." to establish the context for his frustrated reaction in the panel below.

Im-tired-of-this-Grandpa.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Well That's Too Damn Bad" or "Grandpa, You Said," originates from the 2003 movie "Holes." The top panel features a young girl looking expectantly, while the bottom panel shows an elderly man yelling in frustration. The meme's format humorously contrasts a past promise or statement (recalled by the girl) with the man's current regretful or annoyed reaction, making it perfect for situations where past words come back to haunt someone.

im-in-danger.name: im-in-danger

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, '(chuckles) I'm in danger.' It is almost always left unchanged and expresses the character's dawning, yet cheerful, realization of their predicament.

This area is used to label the person or entity represented by Ralph Wiggum. The text describes the subject who is naively or obliviously walking into a dangerous or undesirable situation, setting up the punchline below.

im-in-danger.image_description: This meme features Ralph Wiggum from The Simpsons sitting alone on a bus, smiling cheerfully. The humor and core of the meme come from the contrasting subtitle below him, which reads '(chuckles) I'm in danger.' It is widely used to express a belated and naive realization of being in a difficult, awkward, or perilous situation, often due to one's own actions.

neo-dodging-a-bullet-matrix.name: neo-dodging-a-bullet-matrix

text_options.description: This label is placed on Neo's body and identifies the person, group, or entity that is skillfully avoiding something.
This label represents one of the 'bullets' being dodged. It typically describes a responsibility, problem, or an undesirable task.
Positioned above the first bullet, this label represents another thing being dodged, often related to the first, to emphasize the extent of the avoidance.

neo-dodging-a-bullet-matrix.image_description: This meme, known as 'Matrix Dodge' or 'Neo Dodging Bullets', features the character Neo from the film 'The Matrix' leaning back to avoid bullets in slow motion. The iconic 'bullet time' scene is used to humorously depict someone skillfully avoiding responsibilities, problems, or undesirable situations. The subject doing the avoiding is labeled over Neo, while the things being dodged are represented by the bullets.

Its-Not-Going-To-Happen.name: Its-Not-Going-To-Happen

text_options.description: This is the punchline area, typically containing a variation of Regina George's line. It begins with 'So you agree?' and then rephrases the statement from the top text into an absurd, narcissistic, or funny conclusion.
This top text area serves as the setup for the meme. It usually presents an innocuous statement, compliment, or observation that the meme creator pretends someone else has said.

Its-Not-Going-To-Happen.image_description: This meme features Regina George, played by Rachel McAdams, from the 2004 film 'Mean Girls'. In the scene, she asks a manipulative question, which forms the basis of the meme format. The meme is used to humorously twist an innocent statement into an absurd or self-aggrandizing agreement, creating a conversational trap.

Breaking-News-template.name: Breaking-News-template

text_options.description: This yellow banner at the very bottom mimics a news ticker. It's used for secondary information or another punchline that adds detail or absurdity to the main headline above it, enhancing the parody of a real news broadcast.

This is the primary headline space, located directly under the 'BREAKING NEWS' title. The text here presents the main joke of the meme, which is typically a mundane or ridiculous statement framed as important news.

Breaking-News-template.image_description: This meme format is a template resembling a television 'Breaking News' broadcast screen, complete with a 'LIVE' indicator and a prominent red and blue lower third graphic. The humor arises from using this serious, urgent format to announce mundane, personal, or absurdly trivial information, creating a sense of ironic over-importance. The main black area is typically filled with a relevant, often low-quality or funny image corresponding to the fake news headline.

Fancy-Winnie-The-Pooh-Meme.name: Fancy-Winnie-The-Pooh-Meme

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the sophisticated, tuxedo-wearing Winnie the Pooh. It typically contains a more refined, elegant, or complex word or concept that is presented as the superior alternative to the one in the top panel.

This text box corresponds to the regular, unimpressed Winnie the Pooh. It is used for a simple, common, or less sophisticated version of a word, idea, or action, which serves as the setup for the punchline in the panel below.

Fancy-Winnie-The-Pooh-Meme.image_description: This meme, known as "Tuxedo Winnie the Pooh," uses a two-panel format to compare two things, presenting one as simple or standard and the other as sophisticated or superior. The top image shows a regular, unimpressed Pooh Bear, while the bottom image features a smug Pooh in a tuxedo. This format is used to humorously elevate one concept, word, or idea over another, often highlighting subtle but important differences in taste or intelligence.

blank-black.name: blank-black

text_options.description: The bottom text box, labeled with index 0, typically contains the punchline or the contrasting element of the meme. It represents the reality, the obstacle, or the unexpected outcome that humorously undermines the statement or goal presented in the top box.

The top text box, labeled with index 1, serves as the setup for the joke. This area usually contains a statement representing a goal, an intention, an expectation, or the first part of a comparative phrase (e.g., "My plans:").

blank-black.image_description: This is a minimalist two-panel meme template on a black background, used for comparisons. The format juxtaposes two related but often conflicting ideas, placing one in the top panel and the other in the bottom. It's commonly used to create humor by contrasting an expectation with a disappointing or funny reality, such as a goal versus an obstacle, or a serious statement followed by a silly one.

Amateurs.name: Amateurs

text_options.description: This label is placed on the chest of the final, hooded character who delivers the punchline. The text here represents the ultimate, most extreme, or superior version of the concept being compared, revealing why the other two characters are mere "amateurs" in comparison.

This label is on the chest of the first character in the argument. The text here introduces the first of two related concepts or groups that are being compared, setting up the initial level of the escalating comparison.

This label is on the chest of the second character arguing with the first. The text here represents the second concept or group, often a rival or a slightly more intense version of the first one, continuing the setup for the final punchline.

This is a speech bubble for the first two characters who have united against the third. The original text is "AMATEURS." and is often left unchanged. It signifies the two initial subjects looking down on what they perceive to be an inferior third party.

This is a speech bubble from the second character in the initial argument. This text is often edited to establish the context of the argument or the topic of comparison between the first two characters.

Amateurs.image_description: This meme, known as "Amateurs," is a four-panel comic by Shen Comix. It depicts two characters arguing, who then unite to dismiss a third, smaller character as an "amateur." In the final panel, the third character reveals their own superior or more extreme status, turning the insult back on the original two. The meme is used as a three-tiered comparison to show escalating levels of intensity, absurdity, or dedication to a particular topic, with the final character representing the ultimate form.

Blank-protest-sign.name: Blank-protest-sign

text_options.description: This box highlights a smaller, secondary sign in the background. In the original photo, it likely contains information relevant to the actual protest, but in the context of the meme, it is an irrelevant background detail that is often cropped out or ignored.

This large, blank sign is the focal point and the customizable part of the meme. Users place their own text here to express an opinion, make a joke, or state a relatable fact. This text becomes the punchline, presented as a passionate belief being protested in public.

Blank-protest-sign.image_description: This meme, known as "Protester with a Sign" or "Blank Sign," features a person holding a large, blank white sign at a protest. The format is an exploitable template where users can add their own text to the sign. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the serious protest setting with the often mundane, absurd, or personal opinions written on the sign, as if they are worthy of a public demonstration.

South-Park-JIzz.name: South-Park-JIzz

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline or reaction. It often contains a crude or direct expression of overwhelming excitement that complements the visual gag, though sometimes it's left blank to let the image speak for itself.
The top text, which sets up the scenario or describes the event that causes the extreme reaction depicted in the image. This is the context for the overwhelming excitement.

South-Park-JIzz.image_description: This meme features Randy Marsh from the animated show South Park, sitting in front of a computer and covered in a white, sticky substance, which has also splattered all over the room. The scene originates from an episode where characters regain internet access after a long outage, and Randy has an overly enthusiastic reaction. The meme is used to humorously and hyperbolically express extreme excitement, satisfaction, or being overwhelmed by something, often related to new content online, video games, or other highly anticipated events.

Giant-Thumb-Guy.name: Giant-Thumb-Guy

text_options.description: This text labels the large figure giving a thumbs-up. This character represents the oblivious outsider, corporation, or concept that is cluelessly interrupting or trying to co-opt the group's interest, often in a cringeworthy way.
This text labels the group of three stick figures. They represent a niche community, fandom, or group of friends enjoying a shared interest or having a private conversation before being interrupted.

Giant-Thumb-Guy.image_description: This is a three-panel comic meme known as "Giant Thumbs Up" or "Thumbs Up Guy." The meme depicts a group of people having a conversation, who are then interrupted by a large, oblivious character giving a thumbs-up, much to their annoyance. It is typically used to satirize a person, company, or entity awkwardly and unwelcomely inserting themselves into a niche community or conversation they don't understand, often ruining the vibe.

angry-flower.name: angry-flower

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the cute, innocent version of the flower. It typically describes a calm, simple, or positive situation, a person's public persona, or the 'before' state in a before-and-after scenario.

This text box corresponds to the monstrous, aggressive version of the flower. The text here describes the chaotic, intense, or negative outcome that contrasts with the initial state described in the bottom panel. It serves as the punchline, revealing the 'after' state or the true, unfiltered reaction.

angry-flower.image_description: This is a two-panel meme featuring the character Cagney Carnation from the video game "Cuphead." The bottom panel shows the character as a cute, smiling, innocent-looking flower. In contrast, the top panel depicts the same character transformed into a monstrous, aggressive version, screaming and wildly drinking from a cup. The meme is used to contrast a calm, initial state with a subsequent chaotic or intense state, often representing a drastic change in mood or situation.

breaking-bad-smile-frown.name: breaking-bad-smile-frown

text_options.description: This text box is placed under the distressed, serious portrait of Dean Norris. It typically contains the punchline or the negative realization that contrasts with the initial statement. This text represents the harsh reality, the downside, or the unpleasant truth that dawns on someone after considering the first idea.

This text box is located under the smiling, happy portrait of Dean Norris. The text here usually describes a positive, optimistic, or naive situation or idea. It sets up the joke by presenting the initial, cheerful thought before the contrasting realization.

breaking-bad-smile-frown.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Dean Norris Reaction" or "Hank Schrader Reaction," features actor Dean Norris with contrasting expressions. The left panel shows him smiling widely and cheerfully, while the right panel shows a starkly different portrait of him looking serious, distressed, or angry. The meme is used to illustrate a sudden, often grim, realization by contrasting an initial positive or naive thought (left) with a subsequent negative or harsh reality (right).

Those-who-know.name: Those-who-know

text_options.description: This text box is under the uncanny, distorted image of Mr. Incredible. It contains the disturbing, horrifying, or negative counterpart to the statement on the left. This text represents the 'dark realization' that causes the character's traumatized expression.

Located under the normal, smiling Mr. Incredible, this text box typically contains a positive, innocent, or seemingly harmless statement. It establishes the initial, pleasant context before the horrifying reveal on the right.

Those-who-know.image_description: This meme, known as 'Mr. Incredible Becomes Uncanny' or 'Traumatized Mr. Incredible,' features a two-panel comparison of the character from Pixar's 'The Incredibles.' The left panel shows a normal, smiling Mr. Incredible, while the right panel displays a heavily distorted, black-and-white, and unsettling version of his face. This format is used to contrast a positive or naive statement with a disturbing or horrifying realization, representing a descent into unsettling knowledge.

Natalie-Portman.name: Natalie-Portman

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the final panel over Padmé's concerned expression. It typically contains the second part of her question, '...right?', signifying her dawning horror and disbelief after realizing the true, negative meaning of Anakin's plan. Her changed expression and this text deliver the punchline.

Positioned over Padmé's smiling face in the second panel, this text represents her optimistic and naive response to Anakin's initial statement. This is famously where the line 'For the better, right?' is placed, setting up the expectation that will be subverted.
This text box corresponds to the first panel, showing a neutral-looking Anakin Skywalker. The text here is the setup for the joke—a statement or plan that seems reasonable or positive on the surface.

Natalie-Portman.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as 'Anakin and Padmé' or 'For the Better, Right?', originates from a scene in Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones. It depicts a dialogue between Anakin Skywalker and Padmé Amidala where an initially positive-sounding statement from Anakin is met with a hopeful reaction from Padmé, only for her to realize its sinister undertone. The meme's humor comes from this bait-and-switch, contrasting Padmé's initial optimism with her final look of concern.

Nyan-Cat.name: Nyan-Cat

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which typically serves as the punchline or the main point of the meme. It complements the top text to complete the joke or statement.
This is the top text, which usually provides the setup or context for the meme. It's the first part of the statement that the bottom text will complete.

Nyan-Cat.image_description: This meme features Nyan Cat, an iconic character from early 2010s internet culture. The image shows a pixelated cat with a Pop-Tart for a body flying through space, leaving a vibrant rainbow trail. Nyan Cat is a symbol of internet randomness, joy, and nostalgia. As a meme format, it typically uses top and bottom text to add a simple, often unrelated, caption to the whimsical scene.

Spongebob-diapers-meme.name: Spongebob-diapers-meme

It depicts SpongeBob's increasingly desperate attempts to dispose of a large, stinky pile of something, which he ultimately gives to his friend Patrick Star. The meme is used to illustrate someone trying to offload an undesirable opinion, problem, or object onto another person or group, with Patrick representing the final, often unsuspecting or ironically appropriate, recipient.

no-maidens.name: no-maidens

Change-my-mind-Crowder.name: Change-my-mind-Crowder

I-said-we-sad-today.name: I-said-we-sad-today

Spongebob-time-card-background.name: Spongebob-time-card-background

Text here often represents a contrasting, less common scenario, such as someone starting a new, fruitless endeavor or working hard with a completely flawed strategy, serving as a secondary example of failure.

Never-give-up.image_description: This motivational cartoon, often called '90% of Gamblers Quit Before They Win Big' or the 'Gambler's Fallacy' meme, depicts two miners digging for diamonds. The bottom miner, looking dejected, has given up and is walking away, unaware that he is just inches from a massive trove of diamonds. This image is widely used to represent the idea of quitting just before achieving a major success, encouraging perseverance in various contexts like gaming, investing, or personal goals.

Dean-Norriss-reaction.name: Dean-Norriss-reaction

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the image of Dean Norris looking stern and angry. The text here typically describes a negative, disappointing, or harsh reality that contrasts with the text in the other panel.
This text box is positioned above the image of Dean Norris smiling happily. The text here usually presents a positive, appealing, or naive concept that sets up the punchline in the adjacent panel.

Dean-Norriss-reaction.image_description: This is a two-panel reaction meme featuring actor Dean Norris, known for his role as Hank Schrader in "Breaking Bad". The left panel shows him smiling ecstatically, while the right panel shows him with a stern and angry expression. The meme is used to contrast two related things, showing a positive reaction to one and a negative reaction to the other, or to depict a sudden, grim realization that changes one's mood from happy to upset.

Swords-united.name: Swords-united

text_options.description: Positioned in the center of the round table where all the swords meet, this text describes the common goal, shared opinion, or unifying cause that brings the different parties together.
This label is placed over the knight on the right. It typically represents one of the individuals or groups who are part of the agreement.
This label is placed over the central king figure. It represents another, often the main or most important, party involved in the shared agreement.
This label is placed over the knight on the left. It represents a third individual or group, completing the trio shown to be in consensus.

Swords-united.image_description: This meme, known as 'Knights of the Round Table,' features a king and two knights in a solemn meeting, pointing their swords together at the center of a stone table. The image originates from artwork for the board game 'Avalon'. It is used to represent different people, groups, or entities coming to a unanimous agreement on a particular topic, with the swords meeting in the middle symbolizing their shared opinion or goal.

What-if-you-wanted-to-go-to-Heaven.name: What-if-you-wanted-to-go-to-Heaven

text_options.description: This is the punchline panel. Text or an image placed here represents the unexpected, often absurd or humorous, response from "God" that denies the request from the first panel. This is the core customizable part of the meme.
This panel represents the user's desire or goal. While the original text is "Wanted to go to Heaven," this is often replaced with another desirable outcome, setting up the premise of the joke.

What-if-you-wanted-to-go-to-Heaven.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "What if You Wanted to Go to Heaven," presents a hypothetical conflict. The first two panels establish a desire: "What if you wanted to go to heaven?". The third panel introduces a prohibitive authority figure with "But god said," setting up a punchline in the final, customizable panel. The humor comes from the absurd, nonsensical, or disappointing response from "God" that prevents the user from achieving their goal.
What-if-you-wanted-to-go-to-Heaven.display_name: What if you wanted to go to Heaven

In-terms-of-money-we-have-no-money.name: In-terms-of-money-we-have-no-money

text_options.description: This text box is at the bottom of the image, covering the Minions and the girls. It represents the disruptive element, the unexpected consequence, or the contrasting reality that undermines the statement made in the top text. Its placement near the other characters suggests they are the source of the complication.

Located at the top of the image, this text box represents a statement, a plan, a belief, or a general situation. It sets up the premise of the meme from the perspective of the person represented by Gru.

In-terms-of-money-we-have-no-money.image_description: This meme features Gru from the animated movie "Despicable Me" looking up with a concerned or contemplative expression. He is in his lab, surrounded by his Minions, with his three adopted daughters peeking out from the side. The format is typically used to show a contrast between a statement or belief (top text) and a conflicting or disruptive reality (bottom text), with Gru representing someone realizing the contradiction.
In-terms-of-money-we-have-no-money.display_name: In terms of money we have no money

Were-the-millers.name: Were-the-millers

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is the character's surprised utterance. It reveals the unexpected benefit that others are receiving, contrasting with the speaker's situation. The classic text is "You guys are getting paid?", which perfectly captures the character's bewildered expression.

The top text box is used to establish the context or scenario. It typically describes a situation, task, or group that the meme creator is a part of, setting the stage for the surprising revelation in the punchline below.

Were-the-millers.image_description: This meme features a still of actor Will Poulter as Kenny in the movie "We're the Millers," looking confused and incredulous. Known as the "Wait, You Guys Are Getting Paid?" meme, it's used to express surprise and dismay upon discovering that others are receiving a benefit, reward, or positive outcome that oneself is not. The meme humorously highlights a feeling of being left out or realizing one's efforts are uncompensated compared to others in the same situation.

You-Should-Feel-Bad-Zoidberg.name: You-Should-Feel-Bad-Zoidberg

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Zoidberg and the lower part of the audience, delivers the punchline. This is the reaction to the statement above, famously formatted as "Your [X] is bad and you should feel bad," where X is the subject from the top text.

The top text, positioned above the main characters, serves as the setup for the meme. It typically describes an action, a creation, or a statement that is about to be harshly criticized by the punchline below.

You-Should-Feel-Bad-Zoidberg.image_description: This meme features the character Dr. Zoidberg from the animated series Futurama, looking shocked and dejected while sitting in an audience. The format is a two-part reaction meme where a statement or action is presented at the top, and Zoidberg's reaction at the bottom signifies a harsh, negative judgment. It's famously used with the phrase "Your [thing] is bad and you should feel bad" to humorously critique or mock something.

Hank.name: Hank

text_options.description: This text box is located under the serious, concerned portrait of Dean Norris. It contains the punchline, which is a contrasting, often negative or disappointing, realization that follows the initial positive thought from the first panel.

This text box is placed under the smiling, happy portrait of Dean Norris. It typically contains a description of a positive, optimistic, or ideal situation, setting up the 'before' part of the comparison.

Hank.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Dean Norris Reaction' or 'Hank Schrader's Reaction,' features actor Dean Norris with contrasting expressions. The left image shows him smiling broadly, while the right shows a stern, concerned look. The format is used to juxtapose an initial happy or naive thought with a subsequent, often grim or disappointing, realization.

So-You-Agree.name: So-You-Agree

text_options.description: This is the primary text location for the meme's punchline. The text here represents the condescending or sarcastic question being asked by Regina George, directly tying into her feigned-interest expression. It often begins with phrases like "So you're telling me..." or "So you agree...".

This upper text area is often used to provide context or set up the scenario. It typically describes the person, group, or idea that Regina George is about to question or mock in the bottom text. While not always present, it helps frame the joke.

So-You-Agree.image_description: This meme features Regina George, played by Rachel McAdams, from the 2004 film "Mean Girls." In the scene, she leans forward with a patronizing smile while asking a seemingly innocent but loaded question. The meme is widely used to express condescension, feigned interest, or to pose a rhetorical or sarcastic question, often starting with the phrase "So you're telling me..." to mock a particular statement or belief.

Nah-Id-Win.name: Nah-Id-Win

text_options.description: This area on the character's chest is typically used to label the person, group, or concept that is being challenged or asked if they would lose. It sets up the context for who is expressing the confidence.

This is the speech bubble where the punchline is placed. The text here is almost always the iconic phrase "Nah, I'd win" or a contextual variation, representing the character's unwavering and dismissive response to the idea of losing.

Nah-Id-Win.image_description: This black and white manga panel features Satoru Gojo from the series Jujutsu Kaisen, smirking confidently at the viewer. The meme, known as "Nah, I'd win," originates from this scene where Gojo expresses absolute certainty in his ability to defeat a powerful foe. It is widely used to convey extreme, often over-the-top or ironically misplaced, confidence in the face of a daunting challenge.

Black-Panther---Get-this-man-a-shield.name: Black-Panther---Get-this-man-a-shield

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is a variation of the original quote. It typically follows the phrasal template 'And get this man a [X],' where 'X' is replaced with an object, title, or concept relevant to the setup text. This line delivers the main joke or point of the meme, expressing strong endorsement.

The top text box provides the context or setup for the meme. It usually describes a scenario, a person's action, or a statement that prompts the reaction from Black Panther. This setup is designed to make the punchline in the bottom text a fitting and often humorous response.

Black-Panther---Get-this-man-a-shield.image_description: This meme features a still of the character T'Challa, also known as Black Panther, from the Marvel movie 'Avengers: Infinity War.' In the original scene, he authoritatively says, 'And get this man a shield.' The meme format, known as 'Get This Man a [X],' uses this image to emphatically demand that someone be given something they supposedly deserve, whether it's an object, an award, or recognition, often in a supportive or humorous way.
Black-Panther---Get-this-man-a-shield.display_name: Black Panther   Get this man a shield

Kurt-Angle-Stare.name: Kurt-Angle-Stare

text_options.description: The bottom text describes the bizarre, confusing, or unsettling situation that elicits the intense stare. It's the setup or the cause of the reaction, often detailing an action or statement that is strange or out of the ordinary.

The top text describes the person or entity having the reaction, often framed from a first-person perspective (e.g., 'Me watching...'). It contextualizes the stare, attributing it to someone observing the situation described in the bottom text.

Kurt-Angle-Stare.image_description: This meme features a close-up of professional wrestler Kurt Angle with a wide-eyed, intense, and somewhat unsettling stare, often referred to as the 'Thousand-Yard Stare.' This image is a reaction meme used to convey feelings of shock, confusion, or being deeply disturbed by a preceding statement or situation. The format typically involves a top caption describing the observer's reaction and a bottom caption detailing the bizarre or concerning event they are witnessing.

Stan-Meter.name: Stan-Meter

text_options.description: This label is placed on the 'safe' or low end of the threat dial. The text here describes a normal, expected, or desirable state, setting up the contrast for the punchline.

This label is on the 'danger' or high end of the threat dial, where the needle is pointing. The text here represents the extreme, unexpected, or alarming outcome that triggers Stan's shocked reaction.
This label is placed over Stan Smith's face. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is reacting with shock and alarm to the situation depicted on the dial.

Stan-Meter.image_description: A still from the animated show 'American Dad!' featuring the character Stan Smith looking shocked at a color-coded threat level dial. The needle on the dial is pointing to the highest, red-colored level, indicating extreme danger or a critical state. This meme format, known as 'Stan's Threat Level,' is used to humorously depict a situation escalating to an alarming degree, with Stan representing the person reacting to the extreme outcome shown on the dial.

Mental-Gymnastics.name: Mental-Gymnastics

text_options.description: This text box labels the bottom panel, which depicts the boys' chaotic activities. It typically reads "Boys:" or a similar phrase, serving as a punchline that contrasts sharply with the scenario set up in the top panel.

This text box labels the top panel, which shows the girls. The text here sets up the premise for the comparison, often describing a situation like "Girls' sleepover:" or "Girls when the substitute teacher leaves:", portraying their reaction as mundane or orderly.

Mental-Gymnastics.image_description: This is a two-panel "Girls vs. Boys" meme format that humorously contrasts stereotypical gendered behaviors in an exaggerated way. The top panel depicts girls in a calm, orderly, or unenthusiastic manner, in this case, performing simple gymnastics. The bottom panel shows boys engaged in chaotic, destructive, and absurdly energetic activities, like swinging wildly and surfing on a flaming car. The meme is used to compare reactions to a shared situation, highlighting the supposed difference between girls' reserved behavior and boys' wild antics.

After-all-why-not.name: After-all-why-not

text_options.description: This text, placed over the second panel where Bilbo's expression turns greedy, represents the tempting and often irrational action the person decides to take. It's the punchline of the meme, revealing the specific desire they are succumbing to, often phrased as a question like "Why shouldn't I [do the thing]?".

The text in this top box establishes the context or situation where a temptation arises. It typically describes a scenario where the user already has enough of something or is in a stable state, setting the stage for them to consider an unnecessary or indulgent action.

After-all-why-not.image_description: This two-panel meme features Bilbo Baggins from 'The Lord of the Rings' contemplating the One Ring. The first panel shows him pondering with the caption "After all... why not?", while the second shows his face contorting with greed as he decides to keep it. The meme is used to humorously depict someone giving in to a tempting, often unnecessary or irrational, desire, justifying it with a simple "why not?" before committing to the ill-advised action.

Vegeta-over-9000.name: Vegeta-over-9000
