text_options.description: This bottom text area, often styled as a subtitle, contains the punchline of the meme: "IT'S OVER 9000!!". This text represents the shockingly high number or value that causes Vegeta's extreme reaction, delivering the core of the joke.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically labels the subject or quantity being measured, providing context for the punchline. For example, it might say "My unread emails" or "The number of times I've rewatched this show," setting the stage for the reveal of an absurdly high number.

Vegeta-over-9000.image_description: This meme features the character Vegeta from the anime series Dragon Ball Z, looking shocked and angry as he crushes his scouter (a power-level reading device). The image captures the iconic "It's Over 9000!" scene, where Vegeta is overwhelmed by his opponent Goku's unexpectedly high power level. Culturally, this meme is used to express extreme surprise, disbelief, or hype about a number or quantity that is incredibly large or has exceeded all expectations.

Kong-Godzilla-Doge.name: Kong-Godzilla-Doge

text_options.description: This label is placed on Cheems, the Shiba Inu dog holding a baseball bat. This position represents the unexpected winner, underdog, or third option that surprisingly triumphs over the two main competitors shown in the top panel. The text here is the punchline of the meme.
This label is placed on King Kong, one of the two titans fighting in the top panel. The text here represents one of the two main competitors, ideas, or groups in a conflict.

This label is placed on Godzilla, the other titan in the conflict. The text here represents the second of the two main competitors, who is often seen as the default or established power, about to be defeated by the unexpected third party in the bottom panel.

Kong-Godzilla-Doge.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format based on the movie "Godzilla vs. Kong," featuring an edited second panel. The top panel shows Godzilla and King Kong about to fight on an aircraft carrier, representing two powerful rivals. The bottom panel replaces King Kong with the Shiba Inu meme character Cheems (often called the "Bonk Doge"), who is about to hit Godzilla with a baseball bat. This template is used to illustrate a scenario where two major competitors are locked in a struggle, only for a third, often underestimated or unexpected party, to emerge victorious.

People-Raising-Hands.name: People-Raising-Hands

text_options.description: This speech bubble contains the speaker's second statement, which serves as the punchline. This text is usually an unpopular opinion, a disappointing truth, or a condition that negates the initial positive statement, causing the crowd's enthusiasm to instantly disappear.

This speech bubble contains the first statement made by the speaker. It's typically a popular, exciting, or universally agreeable idea that elicits a positive and enthusiastic response from the crowd, setting up the punchline.

People-Raising-Hands.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, often called 'Audience Reaction' or 'Politician Speech,' contrasts a crowd's reaction to two different statements from a speaker at a podium. In the top panel, the crowd enthusiastically agrees with the speaker's first statement. In the bottom panel, the same crowd is silent and dejected after hearing the speaker's second, less popular statement, humorously illustrating a buzzkill or an unpopular truth.

Back-in-my-day.name: Back-in-my-day

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, describing the modern situation or behavior that the character finds contemptible. It directly contrasts with the setup in the top text, highlighting the perceived absurdity or inferiority of the present day.

The top text sets up the premise of the joke, often starting with a phrase like "Back in my day..." to establish a nostalgic or old-fashioned context. This text describes a past hardship, a simpler way of life, or a traditional value that will be contrasted with a modern equivalent.

Back-in-my-day.image_description: This meme features an elderly man in Victorian-style clothing, including a top hat and spectacles, with an angry and scolding expression while wagging his finger. Often referred to as "Angry Old Man" or associated with Ebenezer Scrooge, the character embodies a curmudgeonly, old-fashioned perspective. The format is typically used to complain about modern trends, behaviors, or technology in a "back in my day" style, contrasting a supposedly simpler or tougher past with a perceivedly soft or nonsensical present.

Shrek-Cat.name: Shrek-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text typically contains the punchline, which is the specific plea, question, or apology. This text works in conjunction with Puss in Boots' expression to deliver the core message of the meme, often a request for forgiveness or a favor.
The top text sets up the context for the meme. It usually describes a situation or an action that the creator has done, which necessitates the pleading expression shown in the image.

Shrek-Cat.image_description: This meme features the character Puss in Boots from the 'Shrek' film series. He is depicted making his signature 'puppy dog eyes' face, with large, glossy, and pleading eyes, to appear innocent and elicit sympathy. The meme is used to represent a situation where someone is trying to get their way, ask for a big favor, or apologize for a mistake by acting overwhelmingly cute and helpless.

Drakeposting.name: Drakeposting

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the approving Drake. It contains the text, image, or concept that the creator prefers or considers superior.
This text box is placed next to the disapproving Drake. It contains the text, image, or concept that the creator is rejecting or finds undesirable.

Drakeposting.image_description: This is the "Drake Hotline Bling" or "Drakeposting" meme format, featuring two stills of the rapper Drake from his 2015 music video. In the top panel, Drake holds up a hand in a gesture of rejection, looking displeased. In the bottom panel, he smiles and points approvingly. The meme is used to express a preference for one thing (bottom) over another, often related, thing (top), making it a versatile format for showing approval and disapproval.

Jojos-Walk.name: Jojos-Walk

text_options.description: This label is placed on Jotaro Kujo, the protagonist who is confidently approaching his enemy. In the meme, this text represents the challenger, the underdog, or someone initiating a confrontation with a seemingly insurmountable or absurd obstacle.

This label is placed on the antagonist, Dio Brando, who stands defiantly. The text here typically represents the powerful opponent, the obstacle, or the challenge being approached. The humor of the meme often arises from the absurd or mundane nature of the challenge labeled here.

Jojos-Walk.image_description: This meme, known as "Oh? You're Approaching Me?" or "Jotaro vs. Dio," originates from the manga series "JoJo's Bizarre Adventure." It depicts a dramatic confrontation between the protagonist, Jotaro Kujo (right), and the antagonist, Dio Brando (left), as they menacingly walk towards each other. The format is used to represent two opposing forces, ideas, or individuals confronting each other, often for trivial or humorous reasons, contrasting the mundane labels with the epic visual.

Trolley-Problem.name: Trolley-Problem

text_options.description: This label is placed on the group of five people tied to the main track. In the meme, this position represents the default, often more catastrophic, outcome that will occur if no action is taken. It's typically labeled with a concept, group, or situation that is widely considered negative or undesirable, representing the 'greater of two evils'.

This label is on the single person tied to the alternate track. This represents the alternative outcome that results from an active choice (pulling the lever). It's often the 'lesser of two evils,' but can also be something personally valuable to the decision-maker, creating a selfish dilemma, or an equally absurd negative outcome for comedic effect.

This label is on the trolley itself. The trolley represents the unstoppable force, problem, or impending event that is causing the dilemma. In memes, this is often labeled with an abstract concept, a powerful entity, or an inevitable trend that forces the choice between the two groups on the tracks.

Trolley-Problem.image_description: This image depicts the classic "Trolley Problem" ethical dilemma in a simple, hand-drawn style. A trolley is about to run over five people tied to a track, but a person nearby can pull a lever to divert it to another track where only one person is tied up. As a meme, this format is used to present a difficult or humorous choice between two undesirable options by labeling the people on the tracks and sometimes the trolley or the lever-puller with different concepts, people, or situations.

2-gay-black-mens-kissing.name: 2-gay-black-mens-kissing

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the lower half of the image. It typically contains the name of one of the two entities being depicted. This entity is often an opponent or an unlikely partner to the one labeled in the top text box.

This text box is positioned on the upper half of the image. The text here identifies one of two groups, individuals, or concepts. The humor of the meme is generated by juxtaposing this label with the one at the bottom, suggesting they are in an unexpected and intimate agreement.

2-gay-black-mens-kissing.image_description: This meme, known as "Now Kiss," features a still image from a gay pornographic film depicting two Black men kissing. It is used humorously to suggest an unexpected alliance, agreement, or reconciliation between two opposing or unrelated entities. The two individuals are typically labeled with the names of these entities, and the intimate act of kissing metaphorically represents their sudden collaboration or shared ground, creating an ironic and comedic effect.

elmo-nuclear-explosion.name: elmo-nuclear-explosion

text_options.description: The bottom text box is typically used to describe the initial event or trigger that causes the extreme reaction. This is the 'cause' in the meme's cause-and-effect format, often presenting a mundane, frustrating, or seemingly innocent situation.

The top text box contains the punchline, representing the chaotic, destructive, or vengeful reaction to the trigger described at the bottom. This text articulates the over-the-top response embodied by the image of Elmo and the explosion.

elmo-nuclear-explosion.image_description: This meme, often called 'Elmo Rise' or 'Hellmo,' depicts the Sesame Street character Elmo with glowing red eyes in front of a massive fiery explosion. The image juxtaposes a beloved children's character with a scene of apocalyptic destruction, creating a dark and chaotic humor. It is typically used to represent an extreme, disproportionate, and vengeful reaction to a minor annoyance or frustrating situation, personifying the unleashing of inner rage.

Interstellar-Smoking.name: Interstellar-Smoking

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically identifies the speaker (usually as "Me") and describes the convoluted or absurd topic they are passionately explaining. It represents the user's exhaustive monologue, which is the core punchline of the meme.

The top text box sets up the context by identifying the audience who is listening to the long-winded explanation. This is often a person or group who is likely unprepared for the intensity of the theory, such as "My friends," "The cashier," or "My therapist."

Interstellar-Smoking.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Matthew McConaughey as the character Rust Cohle from the TV series "True Detective." Cohle is shown smoking a cigarette with a stressed, wide-eyed, and exhausted expression, looking as if he's in the middle of a long, intense explanation. The meme is used to represent someone passionately and perhaps manically explaining a complex, niche, or conspiracy-like theory to an uninitiated audience, highlighting the speaker's mental exhaustion and the absurdity of the topic.

Pepe-Silvia.name: Pepe-Silvia

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image typically labels the person or audience who is being subjected to the long, convoluted explanation. It provides context for who is receiving the frantic theory, such as "My friends" or "My boss."

The text placed here, over the conspiracy board, represents the complex, absurd, or niche topic that the person (represented by Charlie) is obsessively trying to explain. It's the core subject of the convoluted theory.

Pepe-Silvia.image_description: This meme, known as "Conspiracy Charlie" or "Pepe Silvia," features the character Charlie Kelly from the TV show "It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia." The image captures a scene where a wild-eyed, disheveled Charlie frantically explains a convoluted conspiracy theory, gesturing at a wall covered in notes, pictures, and red string connecting them. The meme is used to humorously represent someone trying to explain a complex, far-fetched, or nonsensical theory, often connecting unrelated pieces of information to prove a point.

Don-Draper-Whiteboard.name: Don-Draper-Whiteboard

text_options.description: This bottom text represents Don Draper's 'pitch' or the punchline. It contains a sophisticated, eloquent, or emotionally charged rebranding of the simple concept introduced in the top text, making it sound much more appealing or important than it is.
The top text serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a simple, mundane, or sometimes undesirable activity or concept.

Don-Draper-Whiteboard.image_description: This meme features Don Draper, the protagonist from the TV series Mad Men, during his iconic pitch for the Kodak Carousel. In the scene, he eloquently rebrands the slide projector as a nostalgic 'time machine'. The meme format uses this image to humorously reframe a simple or negative concept into something sophisticated, profound, or desirable, mimicking Don Draper's persuasive advertising prowess.

Scumbag-Steve.name: Scumbag-Steve

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It describes the selfish, inconsiderate, or mooching action that Scumbag Steve commits, completing the scenario set up by the top text.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a social situation or context. This line establishes the premise for the scummy behavior that will be described in the bottom text.

Scumbag-Steve.image_description: This meme, known as "Scumbag Steve," features a young man in a doorway wearing a sideways flat-brimmed hat and a fur-collared jacket. The character embodies selfish, inconsiderate, and mooching behavior, representing a stereotypical freeloader or ungrateful friend. The meme format typically presents a relatable social situation in the top text, followed by a punchline at the bottom describing Steve's scummy or unethical action within that context.

two-buttons-1-blue.name: two-buttons-1-blue

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or group making the impulsive choice. It's placed on the hand in the bottom panel to emphasize who is enthusiastically choosing the option represented by the blue button.
This text box describes the tempting, desirable, or impulsive option. It is positioned above the blue button that the hand is about to press in the top panel and ultimately slams in the bottom panel.
This text box represents the more logical, responsible, or less appealing alternative. It is placed above the red button, which is ultimately ignored in favor of the blue button's option.

two-buttons-1-blue.image_description: This two-panel meme format, often called "Two Buttons" or "Daily Struggle," contrasts a difficult choice with an impulsive decision. The top panel, a cartoon, shows a hand hesitating between a red and a blue button, representing a dilemma. The bottom panel is a photograph of a hand enthusiastically slamming the blue button, signifying the immediate and overwhelming choice of the more tempting or desirable option over the more rational one.

Szia-uram-uncropped.name: Szia-uram-uncropped

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image is typically where the punchline or the specific offer is placed. In derivative memes, user-added text here reveals the absurd or shady product being sold, completing the joke initiated by the greeting at the top.

The text reads 'SZIA URAM!', which is Hungarian for 'Hello, sir!'. This is the fixed catchphrase of the meme, representing the initial, slightly intrusive greeting from the character to an unsuspecting person on the street, setting up the sales pitch.

Szia-uram-uncropped.image_description: This meme, known as 'Szia Uram!', features a large man standing on a tram platform. The Hungarian text 'SZIA URAM!' translates to 'Hello, sir!' and serves as the opening line from a persistent street vendor. The meme is used to humorously represent unsolicited or suspicious offers, often for counterfeit goods like perfumes or phones.

Ok-ima-fight.name: Ok-ima-fight

text_options.description: Positioned next to the defeated boxer and the word 'damn', this text box describes the negative outcome or the reason for the failure. It often contains a humorous or self-deprecating statement that highlights how badly the attempt went, providing the punchline to the meme.

This text box is placed next to the confident boxer and the phrase 'ok ima fight'. It's used to identify the opponent, challenge, or task that the subject is about to take on with misplaced confidence, setting up the expectation for the subsequent failure.

Ok-ima-fight.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'ok ima fight', features a low-poly 3D boxer. In the first panel, he stands confidently ready for a fight, and in the second, he sits defeated and exhausted. The meme humorously depicts a scenario of overconfidence followed by a swift and humbling failure, contrasting the initial bravado with the harsh reality of the outcome.

Girl-on-couch.name: Girl-on-couch

text_options.description: Text placed over the woman on the couch represents the smaller, often unsuspecting or outmatched subject. This label identifies the entity that is about to face an overwhelming situation or force.

Text placed over the five men standing behind the couch represents the overwhelming, powerful, or numerous force. This label describes the challenge, problem, or group that is about to dominate the subject labeled in box 0.

Girl-on-couch.image_description: This meme, known as 'Piper Perri Surrounded' or 'Girl on Couch,' features a small blonde woman sitting on a white couch while five large Black men stand behind her. Originating from an adult film, the image is used to humorously depict a situation where a single, often outmatched entity is about to be overwhelmed by a much larger, more powerful force. The stark visual contrast between the woman and the men is central to its use in representing lopsided or daunting scenarios.

Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-grossed-reverse.name: Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-grossed-reverse

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to the disheveled-looking Winnie the Pooh. It typically contains a word, phrase, or concept that is considered common, simple, or inferior. This sets up the 'before' or 'low-class' part of the comparison.

This text box is placed next to the sophisticated, tuxedo-clad Winnie the Pooh. It contains a more elegant, verbose, or pretentious synonym or description of the concept in the box below. This text represents the 'after' or 'high-class' element, creating the humorous contrast that defines the meme.

Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-grossed-reverse.image_description: The "Tuxedo Winnie the Pooh" meme is a two-panel comparison format featuring the character Winnie the Pooh. The bottom panel shows a crudely drawn Pooh in his regular red shirt, representing a simple or inferior concept. In contrast, the top panel depicts a smug-looking Pooh dressed in a tuxedo, representing a more sophisticated, refined, or pretentious version of the same concept. The meme is used to humorously highlight the difference between two things, elevating one over the other.
Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-grossed-reverse.display_name: Tuxedo Winnie the Pooh grossed reverse

Butterfly-man.name: Butterfly-man

text_options.description: This text box covers the last part of the subtitle, originally "a pigeon?". In the meme format, this space is used for the incorrect label or conclusion that the character (labeled at index 2) comes to about the object (labeled at index 1). It serves as the punchline, highlighting the absurdity of the misidentification.
This box is placed over the butterfly. In the meme, this area is labeled with the actual person, object, or concept that is being misunderstood or misidentified by the character.

This box is placed over the anime character. This area is typically labeled to represent a person, group, or entity that is naively or incorrectly assessing the situation or object represented by the butterfly (at index 1).

Butterfly-man.image_description: This meme, known as "Is This a Pigeon?", originates from a screenshot of the 1990s anime series 'The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird'. It features the android character Yutaro Katori looking at a butterfly and incorrectly identifying it with the subtitled question. The meme is widely used to humorously depict someone misinterpreting or mislabeling a person, object, or situation due to ignorance or a different perspective.

Be-Like-Bill.name: Be-Like-Bill

text_options.description: This is the bottom panel, representing the most basic, conventional, or entry-level idea or choice. It sets the baseline for the escalating progression.
This panel, located above the baseline, typically contains a slightly more advanced, nuanced, or less common idea than the first one. It shows a step up in thinking.
This panel represents a significantly more sophisticated or unconventional thought or action. It continues the upward trend of complexity or absurdity.
This is the top panel and the punchline of the meme. It contains the most absurd, enlightened, or 'galaxy brain' concept, representing the peak of the progression and delivering the humor.

Be-Like-Bill.image_description: This meme format features a stick figure wearing a beanie next to a vertical stack of four panels, representing a hierarchy of ideas. It's a variation of the 'Expanding Brain' meme, used to illustrate an escalating scale of intelligence, absurdity, or sophistication regarding a certain topic. The panels are filled with text to show a progression, starting from a simple or common concept at the bottom and culminating in a complex, nonsensical, or 'enlightened' one at the top, which serves as the punchline.

Happy-then-sad.name: Happy-then-sad

text_options.description: This text box, corresponding to the disappointed expression, contains the punchline or the negative twist. It reveals the disappointing reality that contrasts with the initial positive expectation set up in the top panel.
This text box, placed next to the smiling face, describes a positive situation, a hopeful expectation, or a desirable outcome. It serves as the setup for the meme's joke.

Happy-then-sad.image_description: This meme, known as 'Disappointed Black Guy,' features two reaction images of the same man. The top panel shows him smiling happily, representing a positive expectation or a favorable situation. The bottom panel shows his expression changing to one of shock and disappointment, signifying a negative turn of events or a harsh reality. The format is used to create a humorous contrast between an ideal scenario and a subsequent letdown.

conspiracy-theory.name: conspiracy-theory

text_options.description: This text identifies the person or group passionately and perhaps nonsensically explaining the theory. It's the subject of the sentence, the one doing the over-analyzing.
This area describes the complex, confusing, or absurd topic that the person in box 0 is trying to explain. It represents the subject of the conspiracy or the intricate plan itself.

conspiracy-theory.image_description: A low-resolution image from the TV show "It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia" depicts the character Charlie Kelly, looking disheveled and manic, in front of a conspiracy board. The board is covered with papers connected by red string, and Charlie is gesturing wildly as if explaining a complex theory. This meme, often called "Pepe Silvia" or "Charlie Kelly Conspiracy," is used to represent someone obsessively trying to explain a far-fetched theory, a complex plan, or connecting unrelated things in a convoluted way.

Guy-with-sand-in-the-hands-of-despair.name: Guy-with-sand-in-the-hands-of-despair

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the image, this text box typically sets up the scenario. It describes the context or the action that leads to the feeling of despair depicted in the image.

Positioned at the top, this text box usually contains the punchline. It represents the internal monologue or the specific, often trivial, thought that is causing the man's exaggerated emotional breakdown.

Guy-with-sand-in-the-hands-of-despair.image_description: This meme, often called 'Man on Beach,' features a man in various states of despair and contemplation on a sandy shore. A large, pensive close-up of the man is overlaid on smaller images of him looking distraught. The meme is used to humorously exaggerate feelings of sadness, regret, or overthinking, typically in response to a minor or absurd problem.
Guy-with-sand-in-the-hands-of-despair.display_name: Guy with sand in the hands of despair

Black-Scientist-Finally-Xium.name: Black-Scientist-Finally-Xium

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the setup for the joke. It often starts with a phrase like 'Finally,' or 'After years of research,' to create a sense of anticipation for a significant scientific achievement.

The top text box delivers the punchline, revealing the absurd 'discovery.' This text names the newly created item or concept, which is usually a funny portmanteau, a pun, or a literal interpretation of a phrase, representing the contents of the test tube.

Black-Scientist-Finally-Xium.image_description: This meme, known as 'The Scientist' or 'Finally', features a stock photo of a man in a lab coat and safety goggles intently examining a test tube. The image is used to humorously announce the creation or discovery of an absurd or long-awaited concept, often a pun or a combination of two unrelated things. The format presents a scientific breakthrough that is comically nonsensical, playing on the serious expression of the scientist.

Lebron-James-Reportedly-forgot-to.name: Lebron-James-Reportedly-forgot-to

text_options.description: This text box is intended for the punchline of the meme. It completes the sentence "LEBRON JAMES REPORTEDLY FORGOT TO," specifying the trivial or everyday task that caused his exaggerated emotional reaction.

This large black area is a placeholder for an image that visually represents the thing LeBron forgot or the consequence of his forgetfulness. This image works with the text in box 0 to complete the joke, providing visual context for his distress.

Lebron-James-Reportedly-forgot-to.image_description: This meme, known as "LeBron James Reportedly Forgot," features a split-panel image with a distressed-looking LeBron James on the right and a blank space on the left. Below, a fake news-style headline reads "LEBRON JAMES REPORTEDLY FORGOT TO...", creating a template for a humorous punchline. The meme's humor comes from juxtaposing LeBron's intense emotional reaction with a mundane or trivial thing he supposedly forgot to do.

Monkey-looking-away.name: Monkey-looking-away

text_options.description: Text in this bottom region typically identifies the subject of the meme, often starting with "Me:" or describing a person or group. This text sets up the actor who is about to experience an awkward or incriminating situation, making their reaction in the panels relatable.

Text in this top region describes the situation or external factor that causes the awkward reaction. This is the trigger for the puppet's side-eye glance, representing the thing that is being noticed, said, or realized, which creates the uncomfortable context for the meme.

Monkey-looking-away.image_description: This meme, known as "Monkey Puppet" or "Awkward Look Monkey Puppet," features a two-panel image of a puppet character. In the first panel, the puppet looks forward, and in the second, it nervously darts its eyes to the side. This format is used to represent a person's guilty, anxious, or awkward reaction when caught in an uncomfortable or incriminating situation. The first panel sets up a scenario, and the second panel shows the silent, shifty-eyed response to a sudden, awkward realization or confrontation.

Kermit-sipping-tea.name: Kermit-sipping-tea

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the punchline and the name of the meme: "But that's none of my business." This phrase is essential as it delivers the passive-aggressive tone, implying that the speaker is nonchalantly observing and judging from a distance after making their critical point in the text above.

The top text area is for the setup of the meme. It typically contains a critical, sarcastic, or shady observation about a person, group, or situation. This text is the "tea" or gossip that the user is commenting on before feigning detachment with the punchline below.

Kermit-sipping-tea.image_description: This meme, known as "But That's None of My Business," features the Muppet character Kermit the Frog sipping a glass of Lipton tea. The image is used to make a passive-aggressive, sarcastic, or judgmental observation about a person or situation. The format involves stating an opinion or criticism, followed by the titular phrase to feign indifference, with Kermit's calm demeanor adding to the sarcastic effect.

Real-Shit.name: Real-Shit

text_options.description: This text box, positioned next to the awakened, glowing-eyed Shaq, describes a superior, more exciting, or highly desirable alternative to the concept above. This is the 'real shit' that grabs the subject's full attention and approval.
This text box, placed next to the sleeping Shaq, describes a concept, action, or item that is considered mundane, inferior, or uninteresting, eliciting a reaction of indifference.

Real-Shit.image_description: This meme, known as "Sleeping Shaq" or "I Sleep / Real Shit," features two contrasting images of Shaquille O'Neal. The top panel shows him sleeping peacefully to represent indifference or rejection of a concept. The bottom panel shows a deep-fried, intense version of him with glowing eyes, signifying sudden, strong interest or approval of a superior or more appealing concept. The format is used to highlight a strong preference for one thing over a similar, but less desirable, alternative.

They-dont-even-have-dental.name: They-dont-even-have-dental

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically the phrase "FOR FIVE MINUTES?". It represents Shrek's exasperated plea for the annoying behavior to stop, even if only for a short time.

This top text box introduces the subject of Shrek's frustration. It usually identifies a person, group, or action that is being called out for its annoying behavior, setting the context for Shrek's outburst.

They-dont-even-have-dental.image_description: A screenshot from the movie Shrek 2 featuring the character Shrek looking upwards and yelling with a frustrated expression. This image is from the "For Five Minutes" meme format, used to express extreme annoyance at a persistent person, group, or situation. The meme's punchline is Shrek's plea for a brief moment of peace from whatever is bothering him.

He-was-a-boy-she-was-a-girl.name: He-was-a-boy-she-was-a-girl

text_options.description: Text placed at the bottom of the image, often describing the first person in the pairing, who corresponds to Jesse Pinkman's slacker or skater boy archetype. This text sets up the first half of the comparison.

Text placed at the top of the image, which describes the second person in the pairing, corresponding to Jane Margolis's alternative or goth girl archetype. This text usually presents this person in relation to the first (e.g., "his girlfriend"), completing the contrasting couple dynamic that defines the meme.

He-was-a-boy-she-was-a-girl.image_description: This meme features Jesse Pinkman and Jane Margolis from the TV series Breaking Bad, standing outside. Jesse, on the left, is dressed in baggy clothes and lighting a cigarette, while Jane, on the right, wears a dark, alternative-style outfit. The image is famously used to represent the "skater boy and alt girl" couple trope, highlighting a popular dynamic of contrasting aesthetics in a relationship.
He-was-a-boy-she-was-a-girl.display_name: He was a boy she was a girl

Jealous-Girlfriend.name: Jealous-Girlfriend

text_options.description: This label is placed over the woman in the red dress. It represents the new, appealing, or distracting object of desire that is tempting the main subject away from their current commitment.

This label covers both the 'distracted boyfriend' and his 'disgusted girlfriend'. Text here typically labels the man as the subject (e.g., 'Me') and the girlfriend as the current responsibility or established choice that is being neglected (e.g., 'My work').

Jealous-Girlfriend.image_description: The 'Distracted Boyfriend' meme is a stock photo showing a man in a plaid shirt looking back admiringly at a passing woman in a red dress, while his own girlfriend looks at him with shock and disapproval. This format is widely used to humorously depict situations of temptation, disloyalty, or choosing a new, often less responsible, option over an existing commitment. The man represents the subject, his girlfriend represents the current or proper choice, and the woman in red symbolizes the alluring distraction.

Church-gun.name: Church-gun

text_options.description: This label is on the sniper in the bottom panel, who is aiming at the group above. The text here represents the ultimate, often hidden, threat or solution that trumps all others in the chain. It's the final and most powerful element in the escalating hierarchy.
This label is on the first person in the chain of threats in the top panel. The text here typically represents an initial problem, a smaller threat, or a less powerful entity in the comparison.

This label is on the second person, who is aiming a gun at the person labeled '1'. This text represents a counter, a bigger problem, or a more powerful entity that directly challenges the first element.

This label is on the smiling man aiming at the person labeled '2'. This text represents an even greater threat that counters the second element, continuing the chain of escalation. The character's confident smile often adds irony, as they are unaware of the ultimate threat posed by the sniper.

Church-gun.image_description: This meme, known as 'PoI Mexican Standoff' or 'Person of Interest Sniper,' originates from the TV show 'Person of Interest.' It depicts a complex standoff with three people aiming guns at each other in the top panel, while a sniper takes aim from afar in the bottom panel. The format is used to illustrate a hierarchy of threats or problems, where each one is superseded by a greater one, with the sniper representing the ultimate, often unforeseen, counter or solution.

Kylo-Ren-MORE.name: Kylo-Ren-MORE

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the punchline, which is almost always the word "MORE" in all caps. It directly quotes Kylo Ren's line from the movie, verbalizing the intense and demanding expression on his face.

The top text box provides the context or setup for the meme. It typically identifies the person, group, or entity that is making the insatiable demand, setting the stage for the punchline below. For example, it might say "My brain when I find a new hyperfixation".

Kylo-Ren-MORE.image_description: This meme features an intense close-up of Kylo Ren from Star Wars: The Force Awakens, played by Adam Driver, as he yells with a furious expression. The scene captures his command to "More!" during a battle, conveying a sense of unbridled and almost childish demand. This image is widely used as a reaction meme to humorously express an insatiable desire or a powerful craving for more of something, often in an exaggerated way.

small-brain-yelling-at-big-brain.name: small-brain-yelling-at-big-brain

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the chest of the calm, large-brained character. Text here represents the superior, more intelligent, or preferred idea, group, or individual in the comparison.
This text box is placed on the chest of the yelling, small-brained character. Text here represents the inferior, simplistic, or undesirable idea, group, or individual being ridiculed in the meme.

small-brain-yelling-at-big-brain.image_description: This meme, known as "Small Brain vs. Large Brain" or "IQ," contrasts two opposing viewpoints or individuals. On the left, a man with a small brain is yelling, representing an inferior, simplistic, or irrational perspective. On the right, a calm man with a large brain represents a superior, intelligent, or more nuanced perspective. The format is used to satirically compare two subjects, with the creator's preferred option assigned to the large-brained character.
small-brain-yelling-at-big-brain.display_name: small brain yelling at big brain

Gollum.name: Gollum

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline. This is where the iconic phrase "My precious" is typically placed, representing the speaker's intense and possessive reaction to the situation described in the top text. The text aligns with Gollum's greedy and excited expression.
The top text, which sets up the scenario for the meme. It usually describes an object, person, or situation that is highly desirable or coveted by the meme's creator.

Gollum.image_description: A close-up image of the character Gollum from The Lord of the Rings, looking directly at the viewer with wide, crazed eyes and a toothy, unsettling grin. This meme, often captioned with his famous line "My precious," is used to express an intense, almost obsessive desire or excitement for something. The format typically involves a top text setting up a scenario and a bottom text expressing this possessive longing.

Yugioh-card.name: Yugioh-card

text_options.description: This is the card's effect description box. In the meme, this area is used to write a humorous or exaggerated description of the subject's abilities, traits, or a specific scenario, often mimicking the formal language of actual Yu-Gi-Oh! card effects to create a punchline.
This is the name field for the card. In the meme, this text box is used to label the person, object, or concept being depicted, often with a creative, funny, or grandiose title that sets up the joke.

Yugioh-card.image_description: This meme template is a blank monster card from the popular trading card game and anime series, Yu-Gi-Oh!. The template allows users to create their own custom cards by adding an image in the central frame and text in the designated areas. This format is used to humorously or satirically portray a person, object, or concept as a powerful or absurd monster, complete with a name, type, and special effects that describe its characteristics.

npc-crowd.name: npc-crowd

text_options.description: This area highlights the crowd of NPC Wojaks. This group represents the 'herd' or 'mob' that is being satirized for its perceived lack of individuality and critical thinking. They are visually uniform to emphasize the idea of conformity.

The large speech bubble is where the meme's punchline is placed. This text represents a common phrase, slogan, or popular opinion that the creator believes is parroted without thought by the 'NPC' crowd below. It's the specific idea being mocked as a product of groupthink.

npc-crowd.image_description: This meme, known as 'NPC Wojak' or 'Grayons', depicts a large crowd of identical, expressionless grey figures. These characters represent people who are perceived as lacking independent thought and blindly repeating popular opinions, much like non-player characters (NPCs) in a video game. The meme is used to satirize herd mentality and groupthink by placing a common or cliché phrase in the speech bubble, as if the entire crowd is chanting it in unison.

It-cant-hurt-you.name: It-cant-hurt-you

text_options.description: This text label introduces the supposedly fictional character who is the subject of the patient's fear. It acts as a prompt for the punchline image that follows, as if the character itself is about to appear or speak.
This text is part of the therapist's dialogue, identifying the specific absurd or frightening character that they claim is not real. It sets up the joke by establishing what the patient is afraid of.

It-cant-hurt-you.image_description: This is the setup for the "Therapist: X Isn't Real" meme format. The meme presents a dialogue where a therapist reassures a patient that a specific, often absurd or unsettling, character isn't real and can't harm them. The punchline, typically an image below this text, then reveals that very character, comically contradicting the therapist's statement and validating the patient's fear.

pennywise-in-sewer.name: pennywise-in-sewer

text_options.description: This text label, placed over the person diving into the sewer, identifies the individual or group who finds the offer in the top panel irresistible. It's often labeled "Me" or a specific demographic to show who is being tempted.

This text is placed over the storm drain where Pennywise is hiding. It represents the tempting offer or lure that Pennywise is using. The text is typically a niche interest, a desirable object, or a guilty pleasure that would entice the person labeled in the bottom panel.

pennywise-in-sewer.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format based on a scene from the 1990 horror miniseries "It." The top panel shows the menacing clown Pennywise peering from a storm drain, attempting to lure someone. The bottom panel, a separate image, shows a person enthusiastically diving headfirst into a sewer. The meme humorously subverts the horror context, where Pennywise's lure is something so desirable that the person eagerly dives in to get it, representing an overwhelming or obsessive desire for a particular interest or guilty pleasure.

My-precious-Gollum.name: My-precious-Gollum

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically identifies the person, group, or entity that is experiencing the intense desire. This label represents the 'Gollum' in the scenario, providing the subject for the obsession.
The top text box, placed near Gollum's hand and the ring, labels the object of intense desire. This text effectively replaces the One Ring, representing the 'precious' item that the subject covets.

My-precious-Gollum.image_description: This meme features the character Gollum from 'The Lord of the Rings' franchise, looking ecstatic and obsessed while holding up the One Ring. His crazed, joyful expression is central to the meme's use. The format is used to humorously depict an intense, almost unhealthy desire for something, echoing Gollum's famous line, "My Precious."

Czas-na-csa.name: Czas-na-csa

text_options.description: This is the punchline panel. The text here, originally "pora na CSa" (time for CS), reveals the distracting or "evil" activity the person has switched to after abandoning their responsibilities. It represents the outcome of the dark transformation shown in the previous panel.

This is one of the setup panels. Text in this area typically describes the wholesome or productive task the person is supposed to be doing, such as "Me studying for my exam." It establishes the initial, responsible state of the character.

This is the crucial transformation panel, visually represented by the color-inverted image. Text here often describes the internal monologue or the moment the person gives in to temptation, for example, "My inner demons calling me." It signifies the turning point from good to bad.

This is another setup panel, reinforcing the initial scene. Like the panel at index 1, text here would describe the productive activity, emphasizing the character's initial focus before being corrupted by the distraction.

Czas-na-csa.image_description: A four-panel meme depicting a young boy's transformation from a diligent student to a gamer. The first two panels show him studying, the third panel shows his face in a color-inverted negative, signifying a dark transformation or corruption. The final panel reveals the punchline: he has stopped studying to play the video game Counter-Strike, as indicated by the Polish text "pora na CSa" (time for CS). This meme format humorously portrays giving in to a tempting, often negatively stereotyped, distraction like gaming after a brief period of productive work.

Whatcha-Got-There.name: Whatcha-Got-There

text_options.description: This label is placed on Spencer, the character who is being questioned. Text here represents the person or entity trying to hide something, often a bad habit, a secret project, or a guilty pleasure, by offering a weak excuse.
This label is placed on the ostrich, the object being hidden. Text here represents the obvious, often problematic or embarrassing thing that the first person (Spencer) is trying to conceal.

This label is placed on Carly and Sam, the characters asking the question. Text here represents the person, group, or authority figure that is suspicious and questioning the first person's strange behavior.

Whatcha-Got-There.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the Nickelodeon TV show iCarly. In the top panel, Carly Shay and Sam Puckett look suspiciously at Carly's brother, Spencer Shay, asking, "Um...whatcha got there?". In the bottom panel, Spencer nervously holds a smoothie cup and replies, "A smoothie," while trying to hide a large ostrich behind his back. The meme is used to humorously depict someone trying to conceal something obvious and absurd with a flimsy and unconvincing excuse.

slap-that-button.name: slap-that-button

text_options.description: The blue button is labeled with a tempting, often humorous or relatable, action or choice. This text represents the impulsive decision or desirable option that is being eagerly selected.
The hand is labeled with the person, group, or entity making the impulsive choice. This text identifies who is enthusiastically 'smashing the button,' providing the subject for the meme's scenario.

slap-that-button.image_description: This meme, known as the 'Nut Button' or 'Slapping a Button,' depicts a hand about to slam a large blue button. It's used to represent an immediate, enthusiastic, or impulsive decision in response to a tempting offer or situation. The button is labeled with the desirable option, and the hand represents the person eagerly choosing it without a second thought. This format humorously highlights relatable urges, poor decisions, or exaggerated reactions.

Pablo-escobar-waiting-alone.name: Pablo-escobar-waiting-alone

text_options.description: The bottom area of the image is a common placement for a caption that describes the situation causing the character's feelings of waiting or contemplation. This text provides the context for the meme, making Escobar's pensive state relatable to a specific, often humorous or mundane, scenario.

The top portion of the image is a primary location for a text caption. This text sets up the entire premise of the meme, describing a scenario where the viewer is left waiting, feeling bored, or lost in thought, which is then visually represented by Pablo Escobar's vacant expression.

Pablo-escobar-waiting-alone.image_description: This meme, known as "Sad Pablo Escobar" or "Pablo Escobar Waiting," features actor Wagner Moura as the drug lord from the Netflix series "Narcos." The image shows Escobar sitting alone on a swing with a thousand-yard stare, looking pensive and dejected. It is widely used as a reaction image to express feelings of loneliness, boredom, or deep contemplation while waiting for something to happen, often in mundane or relatable situations.

They-call-me-007.name: They-call-me-007

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to the number '7' and serves as the punchline of the joke. It typically contains a description of a mundane or negative activity or trait that the user has done seven times, contrasting sharply with the heroic exploits expected of James Bond.
This text box corresponds to the second '0' in '007'. It continues the self-deprecating list, usually stating another thing the user has zero of, building on the joke established in the first line.
This text box corresponds to the first '0' in '007'. It's the first part of the punchline, where the user lists something they have zero of, beginning the subversion of the competent spy trope.

They-call-me-007.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white image of actor Daniel Craig as the sophisticated spy James Bond, with the text "They call me 007". The format subverts the cool persona of James Bond by reinterpreting "007" as a list of personal statistics. This meme is used for self-deprecating humor, contrasting the suave image with a list of mundane, embarrassing, or unimpressive personal traits.

I-think-i-forgot-something.name: I-think-i-forgot-something

text_options.description: This area labels the forgotten item, which is the punchline of the meme. In the original scene, this is the character Jake, who has been forgotten at his soccer game. In meme formats, this is replaced with text describing a very important task, person, or object that the user has neglected.

This box labels Alan Harper again, who represents the person who has forgotten something. His dialogue, "Yeah, you're right," signifies his acceptance of the bad advice and his decision to ignore the nagging feeling. In memes, this character is often labeled as 'Me' or a similar proxy for the user.

This box labels Charlie Harper, who acts as the dismissive voice or bad influence. His line, "If you forgot, then it wasn't important," convinces the first character to ignore their concern. In memes, this character is often labeled as a distraction, a bad habit, or a lazy part of one's brain.

This box labels the character Alan Harper, who represents the person with a nagging feeling they've forgotten something important. The original dialogue here is, "I think I forgot something." In memes, this character is typically labeled as 'Me' or someone responsible for a task.

I-think-i-forgot-something.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "I Think I Forgot Something," originates from the TV show "Two and a Half Men." It depicts Alan Harper telling his brother Charlie that he feels he's forgotten something, only for Charlie to dismiss it as unimportant. The final panel reveals the forgotten item is Alan's son, Jake, left stranded in the rain. The meme is used to humorously represent forgetting a crucial task, person, or responsibility, with the forgotten item being labeled over Jake.

Obi-Wan-Kenobi-Jedi-Mind-Trick.name: Obi-Wan-Kenobi-Jedi-Mind-Trick

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned near Obi-Wan's gesturing hand, delivers the punchline. This is the 'mind trick' itself, a statement that directly contradicts or dismisses the setup in the top text, often formatted as "These aren't the [X] you're looking for."
The top text sets up the scenario by stating an obvious fact, situation, or observation that the meme creator wishes to deny or downplay.

Obi-Wan-Kenobi-Jedi-Mind-Trick.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the character Obi-Wan Kenobi, played by Alec Guinness, from the original Star Wars film. In the scene, he is performing a "Jedi mind trick" to deceive Imperial Stormtroopers. The meme, often called "Jedi Mind Trick," is used to humorously portray an attempt to distract or mislead someone from an obvious truth, mirroring the original scene's dialogue, "These aren't the droids you're looking for."
Obi-Wan-Kenobi-Jedi-Mind-Trick.display_name: Obi Wan Kenobi Jedi Mind Trick

Sonic-Says.name: Sonic-Says

text_options.description: This area shows the loading bar from the original game screen. In the meme, it is typically left unedited, reinforcing the video game aesthetic, though sometimes the "LOADING" text is altered for an extra punchline.

This is the main text area where the meme's core message or punchline is placed. Following the prompt "SONIC SAYS...", users insert a statement that can range from genuine advice to absurd, controversial, or humorous opinions, creating a comedic juxtaposition with Sonic's wholesome persona.

Sonic-Says.image_description: The "Sonic Says" meme features Sonic the Hedgehog giving a thumbs-up next to a message box. Originating from a loading screen in a Sonic game, it parodies the public service announcement (PSA) segments from old cartoons. This format is used to present a piece of advice, a strong opinion, or a humorous, often absurd or controversial statement, attributing it to Sonic for comedic effect.

GALAXY-BRAIN.name: GALAXY-BRAIN

text_options.description: This is the final and bottom-most panel, corresponding to the image of a cosmic, enlightened being. The text here is the punchline, representing the most absurd, nonsensical, or ironically simple solution to a problem, framed as the highest level of thinking.

This is the third panel from the top, paired with the image of a brain glowing brightly and emitting light. The text here typically describes a more complex, clever, or seemingly superior idea compared to the ones above it, building towards the final punchline.

This is the second panel from the top, next to the brain with glowing synapses. The text here usually presents an idea that is slightly more advanced or preferable to the first one, showing a progression in thought.
This is the top-most panel, placed next to the image of a small, simple brain in an X-ray. The text here represents the most basic, conventional, or least desirable option or idea in the comparison.

GALAXY-BRAIN.image_description: This is the "Expanding Brain" or "Galaxy Brain" meme format, which consists of four vertical panels. Each panel on the right shows a progressively more enlightened or active state of consciousness, starting from a simple brain X-ray and culminating in a glowing, cosmic being. The meme is used to satirically compare different ideas or actions, with the most absurd or ironically brilliant concept placed at the bottom, corresponding to the highest state of enlightenment.

Kicking-out-Simpsons.name: Kicking-out-Simpsons

text_options.description: This label is placed on Barney, who has reappeared in the final panel. The text here represents the same problem or entity from the first panel, highlighting its persistent and unavoidable nature, serving as the punchline.
This label is on Barney as he is being thrown out by Moe. The text here identifies an annoying person, a persistent problem, or an undesirable idea that the subject (Moe) is trying to eliminate.
This label is on Moe, the one doing the throwing. The text here represents the person, group, or entity attempting to solve a problem or get rid of something they find undesirable.

Kicking-out-Simpsons.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Moe Throws Barney Out," originates from the animated TV show *The Simpsons*. It depicts the bartender Moe Szyslak forcefully ejecting his patron Barney Gumble from the bar, only for Barney to mysteriously reappear behind him in the final panel. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where someone gets rid of a problem, only for it to immediately and inexplicably return, representing persistent annoyances, recurring issues, or unwelcome ideas.

Knight-Protecting-Princess.name: Knight-Protecting-Princess

text_options.description: Text placed on the knight's large shield represents the person, action, or tool that is providing protection. This is the active defensive element in the meme, shielding the subject in box 1 from some form of harm or annoyance.

Text placed on the woman represents the person, thing, or idea being protected. This is the vulnerable or cherished subject that requires the defense provided by the entity labeled on the shield (box 0).

Knight-Protecting-Princess.image_description: This meme, known as "Knight Protecting Princess," features a digital painting of a knight in full armor using a large shield to protect a woman in a blue gown from an unseen threat, all while a crowd cheers in the background. The meme is used to illustrate a person, group, or concept (the knight/shield) defending something cherished or vulnerable (the princess) from attacks, criticism, or annoyances. The dynamic highlights a strong protective instinct, often in a relatable or humorous way.

Vanya-and-Five.name: Vanya-and-Five

text_options.description: This label identifies the first of two subjects being compared. The text here represents a person, group, or idea that is about to have a moment of recognition with the subject in the top panel.

This label identifies the second subject, which shares a surprising similarity or connection with the first subject in the bottom panel. The text here completes the parallel, creating the meme's punchline by highlighting the unexpected common ground between the two entities.

Vanya-and-Five.image_description: This two-panel meme, from the Netflix series 'The Umbrella Academy,' shows characters Vanya Hargreeves (top) and Number Five (bottom) looking at each other in surprise as they drive past one another in separate cars. The format is used to illustrate two different entities, ideas, or groups that have a brief moment of recognition or share a surprising commonality before continuing on their separate paths. It humorously highlights fleeting connections or unexpected similarities.

Bird-Box.name: Bird-Box

text_options.description: This area, covering the two blindfolded children, typically labels the problem, consequence, or responsibility that is being ignored. The children often represent the direct result or victims of the willful ignorance depicted.

Text placed here, above the main character, identifies the person, company, or entity that is doing the ignoring. This label represents the subject who is metaphorically "blindfolded" to the situation described elsewhere.

Bird-Box.image_description: This meme originates from the 2018 Netflix film "Bird Box," featuring a tense scene with a blindfolded Sandra Bullock and two children in a boat. In the movie, they must wear blindfolds to avoid seeing creatures that cause insanity and death. The meme uses this visual to represent willful ignorance, where a person or group deliberately ignores an obvious problem, danger, or inconvenient truth.

WHICH-SIDE-ARE-YOU-ON.name: WHICH-SIDE-ARE-YOU-ON

text_options.description: This text box is on the blue 'Crips' side of the image. It contains one of the two opposing choices in the meme's debate, representing the second option.
This text box is on the red 'Bloods' side of the image. It contains one of the two opposing choices in the meme's debate, representing the first option.

WHICH-SIDE-ARE-YOU-ON.image_description: This meme, known as 'Which Side Are You On?' or 'Bloods vs Crips,' presents a stark choice between two opposing sides, visually represented by figures associated with the rival American street gangs. The image is split vertically into red (Bloods) and blue (Crips) paisley-patterned halves. The format is used ironically to frame trivial or humorous debates as intense, serious conflicts, forcing the viewer to choose a side on a low-stakes issue.

Robert-Downey-Jrs-Comments.name: Robert-Downey-Jrs-Comments

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over Robert Downey Jr.'s chest, serves as the punchline. This is his direct response to the setup in the top text. The original and most famous text here is "I'm stuff," but it is often replaced with other absurd or self-defining statements, reinforced by his gesture.

The top text, placed above Robert Downey Jr.'s head, acts as the setup for the joke. It typically presents a statement or a question from another person or entity, creating a context for his nonsensical or literal response.

Robert-Downey-Jrs-Comments.image_description: A black and white image of actor Robert Downey Jr. wearing a suit and glasses, gesturing towards himself with a slightly surprised expression. This image is famously known as the "I'm Stuff" meme. The format typically involves a top caption setting up a scenario or question, followed by a bottom caption where Robert Downey Jr. delivers an absurd, literal, or tautological punchline from his perspective.

PTSD-dog.name: PTSD-dog

text_options.description: Text in this bottom section describes the past traumatic or intense event that the character is flashing back to. Placed over the war scene, it provides the context for the flashback, representing the source of the 'trauma'.

Text in this top section describes the present-day, often mundane or innocuous, trigger that caused the flashback. Placed over the dog's face, it represents the character's current situation and their internal reaction to the trigger.

PTSD-dog.image_description: This meme, known as "PTSD Dog" or "War Flashback Dog," features the face of a white dog with a startled, wide-eyed expression superimposed over a Vietnam War battle scene. The dog's eyes reflect helicopters, enhancing the sense of a traumatic memory. The meme is used to humorously depict someone having an intense flashback to a past stressful event, often triggered by something mundane in the present.

Drake-Hotline-approves.name: Drake-Hotline-approves

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Drake smiling and approving. It is used to label the preferred, superior, or desirable option in the comparison.
This text box is placed next to the image of Drake looking displeased and rejecting something. It is used to label the disliked, inferior, or undesirable option.

Drake-Hotline-approves.image_description: This is the 'Drake Hotline Bling' meme, a two-panel exploitable format featuring rapper Drake. The top panel shows Drake looking displeased and holding up a hand in rejection, while the bottom panel shows him smiling and pointing in approval. This meme is widely used to express a preference for one thing over another, contrasting an inferior or disliked option with a superior or liked one.

Overly-Attached-Girlfriend.name: Overly-Attached-Girlfriend

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This text reveals the girlfriend's obsessive, creepy, or possessive reaction to the situation established in the top text.
The top text in the image macro format. This line usually sets up a seemingly innocent situation or statement from the perspective of her partner, which she then misinterprets in a clingy way.

Overly-Attached-Girlfriend.image_description: This is the "Overly Attached Girlfriend" meme, featuring a young woman with a wide-eyed, intense stare and a forced, toothy smile directed at the camera. The character, Laina Morris, gained fame from a YouTube video, and her unsettling expression is used to humorously depict obsessive, clingy, and stalker-like behavior in a relationship. The meme typically follows a top-text/bottom-text format to frame a scenario and deliver a possessive punchline.

Drunk-Guy-Talking-To-Girl.name: Drunk-Guy-Talking-To-Girl

text_options.description: This label is placed on the woman (Anna Jay), who represents the uninterested listener. The text here identifies the person or group being subjected to the long-winded explanation, highlighting their boredom or confusion.

This label is on the man (John Silver), who represents the enthusiastic "explainer." Text here identifies the person or entity passionately explaining a topic, often one that is niche or uninteresting to the listener.

This large area at the top of the image is reserved for the topic of the explanation itself. The text here is typically a long, detailed, and often comically mundane or obscure monologue that the man is delivering to the woman.

Drunk-Guy-Talking-To-Girl.image_description: This meme, known as "Bro Explaining" or "Girl Listening to Bro Explain," features pro wrestlers John Silver and Anna Jay. Silver is depicted as passionately explaining something to a visibly unimpressed or bored Jay. The format is used to humorously illustrate situations where someone is over-enthusiastically explaining a niche, complex, or uninteresting topic to someone who clearly doesn't care.

Metronome.name: Metronome

text_options.description: This label is placed on the base of the metronome. It identifies the person, group, or entity that is being indecisive or hypocritical, acting as the subject of the meme.
This box, positioned on the right, contains one of the two conflicting ideas, opinions, or actions. It represents one extreme of the subject's wavering stance.

This box, positioned on the left, contains the second conflicting idea, opinion, or action, which is directly opposite to the one in the right box. The metronome swinging between these two boxes visualizes the subject's rapid and contradictory shifts.

Metronome.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Metronome,' features a metronome swinging rapidly back and forth. It is used to humorously illustrate a person, group, or entity quickly and repeatedly switching between two contradictory ideas, actions, or beliefs. The two opposing concepts are placed in the boxes above, while the subject doing the switching is labeled on the metronome itself, highlighting their indecisiveness or hypocrisy.

Good-then-bad.name: Good-then-bad

text_options.description: This text box, positioned next to the man's disappointed face, delivers the punchline. It reveals the negative reality, the unexpected twist, or the disappointing outcome that contrasts with the initial positive situation described above.

This text box, placed next to the smiling man, describes a positive scenario, a hopeful expectation, or a desirable outcome. It sets up the premise of the meme by establishing the reason for the initial happiness.

Good-then-bad.image_description: This meme, known as 'Disappointed Black Guy' or 'Smiling and Disappointed Black Guy', is a two-panel reaction image. The top panel shows a man smiling with excitement, representing a positive expectation or situation. The bottom panel shows the same man with a look of sudden disappointment, representing the negative or unexpected reality. The meme is used to express disappointment by contrasting a hopeful setup with a letdown.

DBZ-FUSION.name: DBZ-FUSION

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the fused character, Gotenks. It represents the final product or outcome of combining the two elements from the top panel, serving as the punchline of the meme.
This text box is placed over the character Trunks. It is used to label the second of two concepts, people, or items that are being combined or 'fused' together.
This text box is placed over the character Goten. It is used to label the first of two concepts, people, or items that are being combined or 'fused' together.

DBZ-FUSION.image_description: This meme format, known as the 'Fusion Dance,' originates from the anime series Dragon Ball Z. It depicts two characters, Goten and Trunks, performing a special dance to merge into a single, more powerful being called Gotenks. The meme is used to represent the combination of two different things (people, ideas, objects) to create a new, often superior or humorous, third entity.

This-Little-Manuever-is-Gonna-Cost-us-51.name: This-Little-Manuever-is-Gonna-Cost-us-51-Years

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the original quote: 'This little maneuver is gonna cost us 51 years.' It quantifies the disastrous and disproportionate cost of the action described in the top text. While the original line is often used, the '51 years' can be replaced with another significant but humorous cost relevant to the setup.

Located at the top of the image, this is the setup for the meme. The user adds text here to describe a seemingly small, insignificant, or quick action they took. This action, or 'little maneuver,' is then framed as the cause for the massive, negative consequence stated in the bottom text, creating a relatable and humorous scenario.

This-Little-Manuever-is-Gonna-Cost-us-51.image_description: This meme features a still of astronaut Cooper from the 2014 film 'Interstellar', looking stressed inside his spacecraft. The scene depicts the severe consequences of time dilation, where a brief action results in a massive loss of time. The meme format uses this to humorously exaggerate the negative, time-wasting outcomes of seemingly small or simple decisions.
This-Little-Manuever-is-Gonna-Cost-us-51.display_name: This Little Manuever is Gonna Cost us 51 Years

Drooling-Brainless-Idiot.name: Drooling-Brainless-Idiot

text_options.description: This bottom text box labels the person, group, or ideology being portrayed as the 'Brainlet'. It serves to identify the target of the mockery.

This top text box, positioned above the character's head, contains the foolish statement, simplistic argument, or flawed logic attributed to the 'Brainlet'. It represents the thought or opinion being ridiculed as unintelligent.

Drooling-Brainless-Idiot.image_description: This is the 'Brainlet' meme, a variation of the Wojak character, depicted as a crudely drawn figure with a very small, smooth brain, a smug expression, and a tear running down his face. The character's appearance is meant to symbolize low intelligence or a simplistic understanding of a topic. This meme is used to mock or ridicule an argument, opinion, or group by portraying them as intellectually inferior, often highlighting a Dunning-Kruger effect where someone is confidently incorrect.

Epic-Handshake-Three-Way.name: Epic-Handshake-Three-Way

text_options.description: Text placed over the clasped hands represents the common ground, shared belief, or point of agreement that unites the different parties. This is the punchline of the meme, revealing the surprising connection.
Text on this bicep identifies one of the distinct groups, individuals, or concepts involved in the agreement. It serves as one of the setup elements for the meme.
Text placed on this bicep labels another one of the groups or concepts. Along with the other arms, it helps establish the different parties that are finding common ground.
Text on this bicep identifies the final group or concept participating in the handshake. This completes the setup, showing all the parties involved in the unexpected alliance.

Epic-Handshake-Three-Way.image_description: The "Epic Handshake" meme features a close-up painting of three muscular arms from different individuals clasping hands in a powerful agreement. Originating from a scene in the movie "Predator," it's used to illustrate an unexpected alliance or a shared commonality between two or three distinct, and often conflicting, groups or ideas. The central handshake represents the surprising point of unity that brings them together.

Guy-getting-beat-up.name: Guy-getting-beat-up

text_options.description: This label identifies the second muscular character (purple) who joins the attack. It represents a second person, group, or concept that allies with the first to gang up on the target.
This label identifies the first muscular character (red) as he teams up with the second one. It represents the initial person or group that is provoked by or decides to attack the target.

This label is on the first muscular character (red) when he initially appears, looking provoked. This text represents the first entity that takes issue with the smaller character's statement or existence.

This label identifies the small, happy green character. This character represents the 'victim' of the meme—a person, idea, or group that says or does something innocent or controversial, which leads to them being attacked.

Located in the speech bubble of the small green character, this text represents the initial statement, opinion, or action that triggers the aggressive reaction from the two muscular figures. It is the catalyst for the conflict.

Guy-getting-beat-up.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, known as 'Two Guys Ganging Up On a Box' or 'Me Explaining to My Mom', shows a small, happy green character being violently beaten by two large, muscular figures. The first muscular character appears in response to the small one, then is joined by a second, and they attack together. The meme illustrates a situation where two powerful entities or groups unite to overwhelm a single, weaker target, often for a minor or controversial statement.

Spongegar.name: Spongegar

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below SpongeGar, typically labels the person or entity experiencing the panicked reaction. This is often a self-referential label like "Me" or a specific group, grounding the meme by identifying who is feeling overwhelmed.

The top text, placed above SpongeGar's head, describes the overwhelming or confusing situation that triggers the primal panic. This text sets up the context for the reaction, presenting the stimulus that causes the character to revert to a state of high alert.

Spongegar.image_description: This meme features a prehistoric version of SpongeBob SquarePants, often called "SpongeGar" or "Caveman SpongeBob." He is depicted hunched over with a prominent brow and a panicked, wide-eyed expression, suggesting a primal state of high alert or confusion. The meme is used to illustrate an intense, instinctual, or overwhelmed reaction to a sudden and stressful stimulus, contrasting a modern situation with a primitive response.

Nick-Young.name: Nick-Young

text_options.description: The bottom text box is typically used for the main caption that describes the confusing or illogical situation, statement, or action that elicits the confused reaction. This text provides the core context for the meme's punchline.
The top text box often serves as a title or a setup for the main caption below. It can introduce the subject or provide initial context before the confusing statement at the bottom is revealed.

Nick-Young.image_description: This meme, known as "Confused Nick Young" or "Question Mark Nick," features a still image of basketball player Nick Young with a perplexed expression and question marks surrounding his head. The image is taken from the web series "Thru The Lens" and captures his reaction to a comment from his mother. It is widely used to express confusion, bewilderment, or disbelief in response to a nonsensical, illogical, or surprising statement or situation.

drake-yes-no-reverse.name: drake-yes-no-reverse

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Drake looking displeased and holding up his hand to reject something. The text here represents the disliked, inferior, or incorrect option, which is being contrasted with the preferred option above.
This text box is placed next to the image of Drake looking pleased and pointing. The text here represents the preferred, superior, or correct option in the comparison being made.

drake-yes-no-reverse.image_description: This is the 'Drake Hotline Bling' meme, a two-panel reaction image featuring stills of the rapper Drake from his music video. In the top panel, Drake smiles and points approvingly, while in the bottom panel, he holds up his hand in a gesture of rejection and disgust. The meme is used to express a strong preference for one thing (top) over another, contrasting a desirable option with an undesirable one.

Professor-Farnsworth-Good-News-Everyone.name: Professor-Farnsworth-Good-News-Everyone

text_options.description: This is the punchline area, where the iconic quote "I don't want to live on this planet anymore" is placed. It serves as Professor Farnsworth's dramatic and exasperated reaction to the setup text above.
This top section is for the setup text. It typically describes a frustrating, illogical, or disappointing event, news headline, or social media post that prompts Farnsworth's extreme reaction.

Professor-Farnsworth-Good-News-Everyone.image_description: This meme features Professor Farnsworth from the animated series Futurama, looking exasperated with his hands up. The format is known as "I Don't Want to Live on This Planet Anymore," based on his famous quote from the show. It is used to express extreme frustration, disappointment, or disbelief in response to a foolish, absurd, or infuriating situation described in the text.

Ah-shit-here-we-go-again.name: Ah-shit-here-we-go-again

text_options.description: This area contains the dialogue subtitle, "Ah shit, here we go again." This text is the punchline and the core of the meme, expressing CJ's (and the user's) exasperation at having to repeat an experience.

This top section is where custom text is typically added to set up the context for the meme. The text placed here describes the recurring, undesirable situation that the user is reluctantly about to face, which prompts the reaction in the subtitle below.

Ah-shit-here-we-go-again.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the character Carl "CJ" Johnson from the video game *Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas*. The image captures the moment CJ returns to his old neighborhood, Grove Street, and utters the iconic line, "Ah shit, here we go again." The meme is widely used to express a feeling of weary resignation or frustration when faced with a familiar, often unpleasant or repetitive, situation that one must go through yet again.
Ah-shit-here-we-go-again.display_name: Ah shit here we go again

Car-turning.name: Car-turning

text_options.description: The car is labeled with the subject or person making the abrupt decision. This label clarifies who is choosing between the two options presented on the highway sign.
The exit ramp sign represents the impulsive, difficult, or more appealing last-minute choice. This is the option the car recklessly chooses, forming the punchline of the meme.
The sign for the straight path represents the sensible, responsible, or expected choice. This is the option that is being abandoned in favor of the more chaotic alternative on the right.

Car-turning.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Car Drifting an Exit Ramp" or "Highway Exit," illustrates making a sudden, impulsive, or difficult choice. The top panel displays a highway sign with two options, while the bottom panel shows a car recklessly swerving to take the exit ramp at the last second.
