The meme is used to contrast a sensible, planned-out decision (going straight) with a more chaotic, tempting, or last-minute alternative (taking the exit), with the car representing the person making the choice.

Leonardo-DiCaprio-throwing-Money.name: Leonardo-DiCaprio-throwing-Money

text_options.description: This bottom text box labels what the money being thrown represents. It's often something trivial, abundant, or ironically worthless, contrasting with the visual of throwing cash. For example, 'My one upvote' or 'Unsolicited advice'.
The top text box typically identifies the person, company, or entity that is doing the 'spending' or 'giving'. This sets up the context for the action depicted in the image.

Leonardo-DiCaprio-throwing-Money.image_description: This meme features actor Leonardo DiCaprio as Jordan Belfort in the film 'The Wolf of Wall Street', casually throwing money off a yacht. The image is used to humorously depict someone or something spending money extravagantly, wastefully, or with reckless abandon. It's often used sarcastically to represent giving away something of little value as if it were a grand gesture.

Pepe-holding-sign.name: Pepe-holding-sign

text_options.description: This is the customizable sign where the user places their text. The message written here is the core of the meme, typically a plea, a sad realization, a complaint, or a relatable frustration that is amplified by Pepe's pleading expression.

Pepe-holding-sign.image_description: This meme features a variation of Pepe the Frog, a popular internet character, with large, sad, and pleading eyes. The character, often referred to as "PepeHands" in streaming culture, is holding a blank sign above its head. This format is used to express a sad, desperate, or earnest opinion, complaint, or request, with the user adding their own text onto the sign to convey a relatable and often melancholic message.

single-worker-digging-hole.name: single-worker-digging-hole

text_options.description: This label is placed on the lone worker in the hole. The text here identifies the person, entity, or concept that is performing all the actual labor or carrying the entire burden of a task.

This label covers the large group of onlookers. The text here represents the supervisors, managers, clients, or teammates who are not contributing to the work but are merely observing, often creating a humorous or frustrating contrast with the person labeled at index 0.

single-worker-digging-hole.image_description: This meme, often called "One Guy Working, 8 Watching" or "Construction Workers Watching," depicts a single construction worker digging in a hole while a large group of other workers stand around observing him. The image is a popular exploitable format used to satirize inefficient management, bureaucracy, or imbalanced workloads in group projects. It humorously represents any situation where one person does all the work while many others idly supervise or offer unhelpful input.

Bugs-Bunny-No.name: Bugs-Bunny-No

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically the word "no". It is positioned near Bugs Bunny's mouth, making it appear as if he is uttering the word in direct, dismissive response to the text in the top box.
This top caption area is where the user adds the setup for the joke. It usually contains a question, a request, or a statement that will be firmly rejected by Bugs Bunny's response below.

Bugs-Bunny-No.image_description: This meme features a close-up of the cartoon character Bugs Bunny with a smug and dismissive expression. Known as the "Bugs Bunny 'No'" meme, it is used to humorously and emphatically reject a question, suggestion, or statement. The format typically involves a setup caption at the top, to which Bugs Bunny's deadpan "no" serves as the punchline, conveying a sense of finality and condescension.

smiling-dolphin.name: smiling-dolphin

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline or reaction. This text typically represents the internal thoughts or a quiet, awkward response of the person embodied by the porpoise, reacting to the situation described in the top text.

The top text of the meme, which sets up the context or scenario. This text usually describes a statement, question, or situation that would elicit an awkward or polite but confused reaction from someone.

smiling-dolphin.image_description: This meme features a close-up photograph of a finless porpoise underwater, looking directly at the camera with a subtle, ambiguous smile. The porpoise's smooth, rounded head and gentle expression give it an air of awkward politeness, similar to the well-known 'Polite Cat' meme. This image is typically used as a reaction meme to represent someone trying to remain composed, feign understanding, or be polite in a confusing, uncomfortable, or strange social situation.

I-have-failed-you.name: I-have-failed-you

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline, spoken by Dexter. The original line is "I have failed you," but it is frequently edited to a different verb to express the creator's feelings or actions towards the subject in box 1, such as "studied," "memed," or "simped for."

This is a placeholder for an image of a person, character, or object. It represents the subject of Dexter's (and the meme creator's) intense focus, admiration, or obsession, as described by the text in box 0.

I-have-failed-you.image_description: This meme, known as "Dexter in the Locker" or "I Have Failed You," originates from the animated series "Dexter's Laboratory." It depicts the main character, Dexter, looking up reverently at a picture inside his locker. The meme is used to express admiration, obsession, or sometimes failure towards a person, object, or concept placed in the image area, with the caption often being altered to fit the context.

Feels-Good-Man.name: Feels-Good-Man

text_options.description: This bottom text area often contains a caption that explicitly states the feeling, such as 'Feels good man' or 'MFW' (My Face When). It reinforces the emotion depicted in the image, acting as a direct label for the character's state of contentment.

The top text area is used to describe the scenario or action that leads to the feeling of satisfaction shown by the character. This text provides the context or the 'cause' for the blissful reaction, setting up the entire premise of the meme.

Feels-Good-Man.image_description: A black-and-white line drawing of a bald man, known as 'Feels Guy' or a variation of Wojak, with a blissful and content expression on his face. He is gently touching his cheeks with both hands, eyes closed in satisfaction. This meme is widely used to express a feeling of profound pleasure, relief, or contentment in response to a positive situation.

youtube-video-template.name: youtube-video-template

text_options.description: This text box is located where the upload date of a YouTube video is typically shown, right after the view count. It's used to add a secondary piece of information, often a humorous date or a short, punchy phrase that provides extra context to the main joke in the title.

This text box is placed over the video's title. This is where the main setup or punchline of the meme goes, describing the absurd or chaotic event that the distorted video is supposed to be depicting.

youtube-video-template.image_description: This meme format is a distorted screenshot of a YouTube video page, often referred to as a "deep-fried" or "nuked" meme. The video player section is intentionally corrupted with visual noise and color banding to represent something chaotic, loud, or nonsensical. This template is used to create fake, absurd video titles, with the distorted image representing the ridiculous content described in the text.

jesus-watcha-doin.name: jesus-watcha-doin

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically describes an action, thought, or situation that is being 'watched' by Jesus. This is the setup for the joke, often detailing something morally questionable, embarrassing, or sinful that the user has done or is thinking about doing.

The top text box serves as the punchline or reaction to the situation described below. It often represents a subsequent action or a direct consequence, implying that the person is now aware of being watched by Jesus. For example, if the bottom text describes a questionable internet search, the top text might read '[Deletes search history]'.

jesus-watcha-doin.image_description: This meme, known as 'Jesus is Watching You' or 'Peeking Jesus', features a cutout of a classical painting of Jesus Christ peeking into the frame from the left. It is a reaction image used to humorously suggest that Jesus is observing someone's actions, particularly those that are sinful, questionable, or embarrassing. The meme plays on the idea of divine judgment or surveillance over mundane, often online, activities, creating a comedic contrast.

Maslows-Hierarchy-of-Needs.name: Maslows-Hierarchy-of-Needs

text_options.description: The bottom and largest tier of the pyramid, representing the most fundamental requirement in the meme's context. The text here is the core of the joke, presenting a humorous or absurd item as the ultimate 'basic need'.
The second level from the bottom. The text here describes a need that is considered essential but only after the foundational need in box 0 has been met.
The middle tier of the pyramid. This level typically represents a 'psychological need' within the meme's humorous context, building upon the priorities established in the lower tiers.
The fourth tier, second from the top. The text here represents a higher-level desire or goal that becomes relevant once the more 'basic' needs below it are satisfied according to the meme's logic.
The top tier of the pyramid, representing 'self-fulfillment'. The text here is the pinnacle of the meme's hierarchy, the ultimate achievement or final goal in the specific, often comical, context.

Maslows-Hierarchy-of-Needs.image_description: This meme template features Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs, a five-tiered pyramid used in psychology to categorize human needs. In memes, the original labels are replaced to create a new, humorous hierarchy of priorities for a specific person, group, or situation. The humor often comes from placing a trivial or niche desire at the bottom as the most fundamental 'basic need,' subverting the original diagram's purpose.

yoda-smell.name: yoda-smell

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline or the core piece of wisdom. It completes the thought from the top text, always written in Yoda's characteristic inverted grammar to deliver the humorous or insightful conclusion.

The top text of the meme, which acts as the setup for the joke or statement. This line introduces a situation or concept, written in Yoda's signature inverted sentence structure to establish the context for the punchline below.

yoda-smell.image_description: This is an image macro meme featuring the character Yoda from the Star Wars franchise. Known for his wisdom and unique object-subject-verb speech pattern, the meme uses this format to deliver humorous or profound advice. Typically, the text is split into a setup and a punchline, both written in Yoda's distinctive syntax. The image of Yoda with his eyes closed and a serene expression reinforces the idea that he is imparting some form of deep knowledge or observation.

Smart-Guy.name: Smart-Guy

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline: the flawed, illogical, or comically simple "solution" to the problem. It aligns with the character's smug expression, highlighting the absurdity of the advice.
The top text box typically presents a problem, a challenge, or a situation that requires a solution. This sets up the premise for the flawed advice that follows.

Smart-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Roll Safe" or "Think About It," features actor Kayode Ewumi as the character Reece Simpson from the web series "Hood Documentary." The character is smiling knowingly and tapping his temple, conveying a sense of misplaced confidence. The meme is used to satirize poor decision-making and flawed logic by presenting a problem followed by a comically nonsensical or counterproductive solution, as if it were a stroke of genius.

Morgan-Freeman.name: Morgan-Freeman

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline or the profound 'truth.' This text is meant to be read in Morgan Freeman's voice, giving a mundane or humorous statement an air of deep wisdom and finality.
The top text area typically contains the first part of a statement or a setup for the punchline. It establishes the context or premise of the 'wise' observation to follow.

Morgan-Freeman.image_description: This meme features a black and white portrait of actor Morgan Freeman, known for his authoritative and calming voice, often used in narration or to portray wise characters. The image is used as a reaction or a statement format where Freeman's perceived wisdom lends weight to the text. The meme's humor often comes from presenting a mundane or silly observation as a profound truth, as if narrated by Freeman himself.

am-I-a-joke-to-you.name: am-I-a-joke-to-you

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the text "Am I a joke to you?". This text represents the subject's feeling of being overlooked or disrespected by the entity described in the top panel.

This top panel is where the user adds text to set up the context. It typically describes a person, group, or situation that is ignoring or showing disrespect towards the subject represented by the man in the bottom panel.

am-I-a-joke-to-you.image_description: This is the "Am I a joke to you?" reaction meme, which originates from a South African television show. It features a man with a deadpan, slightly pained expression, questioning whether he is being taken seriously. The meme is used to express feelings of being ignored, undervalued, or disrespected in a particular situation, with the top panel typically describing the person or entity doing the ignoring.
am-I-a-joke-to-you.display_name: am I a joke to you

Dog-on-fire.name: Dog-on-fire

text_options.description: This text label is placed on the dog, representing the person, group, or entity that is in a state of denial or calmly accepting a terrible situation. It identifies the subject who is pretending everything is fine.

This text label is placed at the top of the image, often describing the overwhelming problem, chaotic environment, or disaster that the subject (the dog) is ignoring. It sets the context for the "fire" or crisis.

Dog-on-fire.image_description: The "This is Fine" meme features an anthropomorphic dog wearing a bowler hat, sitting calmly at a table with a mug while the room is engulfed in flames. Originating from KC Green's webcomic "Gunshow," the image is a popular symbol for denial, willful ignorance, or maintaining a semblance of calm in a chaotic or disastrous situation. It's used to humorously comment on situations where a person or group is pretending everything is normal despite overwhelming problems.

Four-Naan-Jeremy-Four-Thats-insane.name: Four-Naan-Jeremy-Four-Thats-insane

text_options.description: The bottom text, typically placed over Mark's chest, represents his internal monologue or an awkward verbal response. This is the punchline of the meme, revealing a comically anxious, cynical, or over-analytical perspective on the situation described in the top text.

The top text sets up the external context, often a question, statement, or situation posed to the character. It serves as the premise that triggers the internal reaction or awkward response shown in the bottom text.

Four-Naan-Jeremy-Four-Thats-insane.image_description: This meme features Mark Corrigan from the British sitcom 'Peep Show,' looking concerned or surprised in a restaurant. Known for his anxious and cynical internal monologues, this image is used to represent a moment of sudden, unwelcome realization or overthinking. The format typically contrasts an external situation or question with Mark's internal, often bleak or socially awkward, response.
Four-Naan-Jeremy-Four-Thats-insane.display_name: Four Naan Jeremy Four Thats insane

Adolf-Hitler.name: Adolf-Hitler

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, often serving as the punchline or a direct label. This text typically contains a shocking, ironic, or paradoxical statement related to the setup in the top text, directly referencing Hitler or the concept of evil he represents.

The top text of the image macro, which sets up the premise of the joke or statement. It often poses a question or describes a situation that will be unexpectedly and darkly answered or commented on by the image of Hitler.

Adolf-Hitler.image_description: This meme features a black and white portrait of Adolf Hitler. The image is used in various meme formats, often as a symbol of ultimate evil or for shock value. The humor, which is typically dark and controversial, arises from juxtaposing this infamous historical figure with mundane, absurd, or paradoxical text. This creates a hyperbolic comparison or a shocking punchline.

Jay-jay-the-plane.name: Jay-jay-the-plane

text_options.description: This label is placed on Jay Jay the Jet Plane. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that has caused the chaos depicted in the background and is now nonchalantly moving on.
This label is placed on the explosion. The text here describes the problem, disaster, or chaotic situation that the entity labeled on the plane has created and is now leaving behind.

Jay-jay-the-plane.image_description: This meme, known as "Jay Jay the Jet Plane's 9/11," features the titular character from the children's show smiling cheerfully as he flies away from a massive explosion in a city. The humor comes from the stark contrast between the innocent, happy cartoon character and the destructive, chaotic background. The meme is used to represent someone who has caused a significant problem or disaster and is now leaving the scene, either oblivious to the consequences or smugly satisfied with their actions.

Oh-No-Black-Cat.name: Oh-No-Black-Cat

text_options.description: This area, located on the zoomed-in, startled face of the cat, is typically left blank. The cat's wide-eyed expression is the punchline itself, conveying a powerful non-verbal reaction of shock or realization. Adding text here is uncommon as it would detract from the visual humor.

The top panel serves as the setup for the meme. Text placed here describes a situation, a statement, or an action that seems innocuous at first but leads to the sudden, shocking realization depicted by the cat in the panel below. This text provides the crucial context for the punchline.

Oh-No-Black-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as the "Startled Cat" or sometimes "When the edibles kick in," is a two-panel image featuring a black cat. The top panel shows the cat looking off to the side, while the bottom panel is a blurry, zoomed-in shot of its face with wide, shocked eyes. The format is used to represent a sudden, delayed, and often intense realization or reaction to a preceding statement or event. It humorously captures the feeling of being hit by an unexpected thought or consequence.

Tornado-Guy.name: Tornado-Guy

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image labels the man in the foreground. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is either causing the problem (the tornado) or foolishly ignoring it while focusing on something trivial like taking a selfie.

The text over the tornado represents the impending disaster, a significant problem, or a negative consequence. This label defines the specific crisis or chaotic situation that the person in the foreground is either responsible for or oblivious to.

Tornado-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as 'Tornado Selfie' or 'Dude with Tornado,' features a man taking a selfie with a strained expression while a large tornado looms in the background. The format humorously depicts someone ignoring a massive, imminent problem to focus on themselves. It's often used to represent a person, group, or entity that is either oblivious to or the direct cause of a disastrous situation they are documenting.

Pinky-and-the-brain.name: Pinky-and-the-brain

text_options.description: The bottom panel contains the punchline, which is a simple, nonsensical, or comically literal answer. This text represents Pinky's response, which completely misses the point of the question and provides an absurd or humorous non-sequitur, creating the core humor of the meme.

The top panel is where the setup or a serious, often philosophical or complex question is placed. This text represents the kind of grand, world-domination-related query The Brain would pose to his simple-minded companion, Pinky.

Pinky-and-the-brain.image_description: This meme features the characters Pinky and the Brain from the animated series of the same name. The image depicts the tall, dim-witted Pinky looking confusedly at the short, genius mouse, The Brain, who appears deep in thought. The meme format juxtaposes a complex or serious question at the top with a simple, absurd, or unrelated answer at the bottom, reflecting the dynamic between the two characters. It is typically used to show a humorous misunderstanding or a comically simplistic perspective on a profound topic.

We-Have-A-Hulk.name: We-Have-A-Hulk

text_options.description: This area, overlaid on Tony Stark, contains the punchline of the meme. It's a short, simple, and powerful rebuttal that completely invalidates or surpasses the statement made in the top panel. Its placement on the unimpressed character emphasizes the effortless and decisive nature of the comeback.

This text box, placed over Loki, represents the setup of the meme. It typically contains a boastful claim, a complex argument, a list of advantages, or a threat. This text establishes an opponent's seemingly strong position that will be dismantled by the punchline in the panel below.

We-Have-A-Hulk.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "We Have a Hulk," originates from the 2012 Marvel film "The Avengers." The top panel shows the villain Loki delivering an arrogant monologue, while the bottom panel shows Tony Stark (Iron Man) looking unimpressed. The meme contrasts a lengthy, boastful, or threatening statement with a simple but overwhelmingly powerful counter-argument, mirroring the original dialogue where Loki's "I have an army" is met with Tony's "We have a Hulk."

We-did-it-Patrick-We-saved-the-City.name: We-did-it-Patrick-We-saved-the-City

text_options.description: This bottom text area serves as the punchline, typically containing the iconic quote "We saved the city!" or a similar self-congratulatory statement. This text, spoken by the characters, creates a stark, humorous contrast with the disastrous background, highlighting their cluelessness and misplaced pride.

The top text box sets up the context for the meme. It usually describes the situation or the entity that the characters (or the meme's subject) were supposed to fix or manage, which has now been ruined. This text establishes the initial problem that leads to the ironic failure depicted.

We-did-it-Patrick-We-saved-the-City.image_description: This meme, known as "We Saved the City," features SpongeBob SquarePants and Patrick Star standing cheerfully amidst the fiery destruction of their city, Bikini Bottom. The image is from an episode where they believe they've defeated a villain, but have actually destroyed the town in the process. It's used to satirize situations where someone claims a victory or success while being completely oblivious to the catastrophic failure or damage they've caused.
We-did-it-Patrick-We-saved-the-City.display_name: We did it Patrick We saved the City

Jump-on-Rake.name: Jump-on-Rake

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the bottom image of men skillfully using rakes like skateboards. The text here typically describes the surprisingly cool, successful, or impressive version of an action, contrasting with the clumsy version above. It represents the idealized outcome or the "reality" in an "Expectation vs. Reality" format.

This text box is placed over the top image of a stick figure getting hit by a rake. The text here usually describes the clumsy, self-defeating, or expectedly negative action or outcome. It sets up the failure or the "expectation" part of the meme's comparison.

Jump-on-Rake.image_description: This two-panel meme contrasts different outcomes of the same action, often involving a rake. The top panel depicts a generic 3D stick figure stepping on a rake and getting hit in the face, a classic trope for self-inflicted, foreseeable problems. The bottom panel shows several cartoon men skillfully grinding down stairs on rakes like skateboards. The meme is used to compare a clumsy, expected, or negative outcome (top) with a surprisingly cool, successful, or impressive one (bottom), often in an "Expectation vs. Reality" format.

Ant-and-Dec-laughing.name: Ant-and-Dec-laughing

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the audio equipment on the table. It typically contains the text describing the mischievous instruction, impulse, or external force that is causing the main action of the meme. It represents the 'cause' or the 'command' being issued.

This text box is placed over Ant and Dec, who are laughing. It represents the 'puppet masters' or the entity that is giving the instructions and enjoying the chaotic or humorous outcome. This text identifies the instigators of the situation.

Ant-and-Dec-laughing.image_description: This meme features British TV presenters Ant and Dec laughing hysterically. The image is from a segment on their show where they secretly give instructions to someone through an earpiece to create awkward and funny situations. The meme is used to depict a scenario where one entity (Ant and Dec) mischievously controls or influences another (the unseen subject), finding the chaotic results hilarious.

grabbing-ball.name: grabbing-ball

text_options.description: This text is on the yellow balloon in the second panel, which is now moving out of reach. It restates the goal from the first panel (index 2) to emphasize that it is now unattainable due to the obstacle.

This text labels the large pink character that is holding the main character back. It represents the obstacle, unexpected problem, or responsibility that prevents the person from achieving their goal.
This text is placed on the yellow balloon in the top panel. It describes a desirable goal, a hope, or something positive that the main character is happily pursuing.
This text labels the main character who is happily chasing the balloon. It typically represents the meme creator, a specific group, or 'me' in a relatable scenario.

grabbing-ball.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as 'Running Away Balloon' or 'Guy Held Back', illustrates a situation where a goal is thwarted by an unforeseen obstacle. The top panel shows a happy, generic character reaching for a yellow balloon, representing a desire or goal. In the bottom panel, the character is held back by a large pink figure, representing a problem or responsibility, causing the character to look on in distress as the balloon floats away.

Confused-Little-Girl.name: Confused-Little-Girl

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically represents the person or group reacting with Chloe's expression. It's often labeled with 'Me:' or a similar identifier to frame the reaction as the user's own, showing their personal judgment or confusion towards the situation described in the top text.

The text at the top of the image describes the situation, statement, or action that elicits Chloe's concerned and unimpressed reaction. This text provides the context or the stimulus that is being judged or questioned.

Confused-Little-Girl.image_description: This meme, known as "Side-Eyeing Chloe," features a young girl named Chloe in a car seat giving a concerned and judgmental look. The image is a screenshot from a viral video where she reacts unenthusiastically to a surprise trip to Disneyland. Her iconic expression is widely used as a reaction image to convey confusion, disapproval, or skepticism in response to something strange, cringeworthy, or questionable.

Why-you-no.name: Why-you-no

text_options.description: The bottom text area contains the punchline of the meme. It always begins with the iconic phrase 'Y U NO' (a deliberate misspelling of 'Why don't you') followed by the action the subject is failing to perform, encapsulating the user's exasperation.
The top text area is used to identify the subject or entity being addressed. This sets the stage for the frustrated question that follows, providing context for the complaint.

Why-you-no.image_description: This meme features the 'Y U NO Guy,' a popular character from the rage comic series. The character is depicted with a comically enraged and pleading expression, demanding to know why something isn't happening the way it should. The meme is used to express frustration or exasperation over a simple or logical action not being taken, framed as a direct question. The iconic, grammatically incorrect phrase 'Y U NO' is the cornerstone of this format.

Jack-Sparrow-you-have-heard-of-me.name: Jack-Sparrow-you-have-heard-of-me

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Captain Jack Sparrow. It contains the witty comeback or punchline that reframes the initial criticism. This text represents a clever or unexpected perspective that turns the insult into a point of pride, emphasizing that being known, even for failure, is a form of success.

This text box is placed over Commodore Norrington. It typically contains the setup for the meme, which is an insult, a criticism, or a declaration of someone's incompetence. The original line is, "You are without a doubt the worst pirate I've ever heard of."

Jack-Sparrow-you-have-heard-of-me.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the film "Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl." It features Commodore Norrington in the top panel confronting Captain Jack Sparrow in the bottom panel. The meme's format contrasts a statement of criticism or failure with a clever retort that reframes the situation positively, celebrating notoriety over competence. It's used to represent turning an insult on its head by pointing out that despite the criticism, one is still known or recognized.
Jack-Sparrow-you-have-heard-of-me.display_name: Jack Sparrow you have heard of me

I-Robot-Will-Smith.name: I-Robot-Will-Smith

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the robot, Sonny, in the middle panel. It contains the robot's response, which serves as the punchline. The text here is typically a surprisingly profound, witty, or unsettling statement that subverts expectations and triggers the contemplative reaction in the final panel.

This text box is positioned over Will Smith's character in the top panel. It represents the initial question or statement directed at the robot. This text sets up the premise for the robot's unexpected and thought-provoking reply.

I-Robot-Will-Smith.image_description: This three-panel meme features Detective Del Spooner (Will Smith) and the robot Sonny from the 2004 film "I, Robot". In the first panel, Spooner looks at Sonny with a skeptical or questioning expression. The second panel shows Sonny's neutral face, and the third shows Spooner looking down in deep, troubled thought. The meme format illustrates a dialogue where an initial question is met with an unexpectedly profound or disturbing answer, causing the questioner to have an existential crisis or moment of deep contemplation.

Jesse-WTF-are-you-talking-about.name: Jesse-WTF-are-you-talking-about

text_options.description: This is the final panel and the punchline, showing Walter White's silent, downward gaze. The text here typically represents the listener's final thought of confusion, despair, or a label for the person who is utterly baffled by the preceding explanation.
This panel shows Jesse looking down, continuing his monologue. The text here is part of Jesse's ongoing, convoluted explanation, often adding another strange detail to the story.
This panel shows an animated Jesse gesturing as he speaks. The text here is the core of his bizarre explanation, usually the most energetic or detailed part of his speech.
This panel shows Walter White listening with a concerned expression. The text here often represents a question or a label for the listener, setting up the context for Jesse's explanation.
This is the first panel of the sequence, showing Jesse Pinkman beginning to speak. The text here introduces the absurd or confusing topic that he is about to explain.

Jesse-WTF-are-you-talking-about.image_description: This multi-panel meme, known as "Jesse, What the F**k Are You Talking About?", features characters Jesse Pinkman and Walter White from the TV series Breaking Bad. The format depicts Jesse enthusiastically explaining something complex or nonsensical to a silent, increasingly concerned Walter. It's used to represent a situation where one person's explanation is so bizarre or convoluted that the listener is left in a state of stunned, horrified silence.
Jesse-WTF-are-you-talking-about.display_name: Jesse WTF are you talking about

Girl-crying-while-drawing.name: Girl-crying-while-drawing

text_options.description: Text in this bottom region typically describes the specific task, responsibility, or piece of information that is causing the overwhelming distress. It represents the direct source of the subject's frustration.
Text in this top region identifies the person, group, or entity experiencing the overwhelming emotion. This label provides the context for who is suffering from the problem described at the bottom.

Girl-crying-while-drawing.image_description: This meme features a stock photo of a young girl crying at a desk while holding a crayon, looking utterly overwhelmed. Known as "Crying Kid Coloring," it's used to express extreme frustration, sadness, or a sense of being burdened by a task or situation. The humor comes from applying this dramatic reaction to relatable, often adult, problems and responsibilities.

Buff-Doge-vs-Crying-Cheems.name: Buff-Doge-vs-Crying-Cheems

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Cheems, the weaker dog. It typically contains a label for the modern, inferior, or disappointing version of the subject being compared. This side of the meme represents the 'now' or the less desirable outcome.

This text box is placed over Swole Doge, the muscular dog. It usually contains a label for the past, superior, or idealized version of a subject. This side of the meme sets up the comparison by representing the 'then' or the powerful ideal.

Buff-Doge-vs-Crying-Cheems.image_description: This is the 'Swole Doge vs. Cheems' meme, a popular comparison format. On the left, a muscular, confident Shiba Inu known as Swole Doge represents a superior, glorious, or powerful past version of a subject. On the right, a small, sad, and pathetic-looking Shiba Inu named Cheems represents the inferior, disappointing, or weaker present-day counterpart. The meme humorously contrasts historical strength with modern weakness or vice versa.

worship-the-lord.name: worship-the-lord

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the group of smaller kneeling figures. It typically labels a group of peers, friends, or a collective entity that is also forced to submit alongside the main subject (labeled in box 1).

Positioned over the most prominent kneeling figure in the foreground, this text box usually represents the meme's creator or the main protagonist of the scenario, often labeled as 'Me'. This character is part of the group but is singled out to make the meme more personal and relatable.

This text box is placed on the chest of the giant, imposing statue. It represents the object of worship or the overwhelming force that everyone is bowing to. This could be a person, an institution, a difficult task, or an unpopular but unavoidable opinion.

worship-the-lord.image_description: This image is a panel from the popular webtoon 'Solo Leveling,' depicting the main character and others bowing before a massive, intimidating statue of a god-like king on a throne. The scene is set in a dark, cavernous hall, emphasizing the power disparity. As a meme, it's used to represent a group of people reluctantly submitting to, or worshipping, a powerful entity, an unpopular opinion, or an overwhelming force, often for humorous effect.

Guy-posing-in-front-of-grave.name: Guy-posing-in-front-of-grave

text_options.description: This text label is placed on Grant Gustin, who is smiling and flashing a peace sign. It represents the person, entity, or concept that is celebrating, thriving, or is responsible for the 'death' of the subject on the gravestone.
This text label is placed on the gravestone. It represents the person, idea, or thing that has failed, ended, been defeated, or made obsolete, much to the delight of the character labeled in box 0.

Guy-posing-in-front-of-grave.image_description: This meme, known as "Grant Gustin Next to Oliver Queen's Grave," originates from a behind-the-scenes photo from the TV show "Arrow." It features actor Grant Gustin (who plays The Flash) cheerfully posing with a peace sign next to the grave of the show's protagonist, Oliver Queen, while other characters mourn in the background. The stark contrast between the somber funeral and Gustin's happy demeanor is used to humorously depict someone celebrating or benefiting from the downfall, failure, or demise of something else.
Guy-posing-in-front-of-grave.display_name: Guy posing in front of grave

crying-boy-on-a-bench.name: crying-boy-on-a-bench

text_options.description: This text box is on the final panel, which shows the disappointing outcome or the 'consolation prize' that caused the sadness, serving as the punchline.
This text box is over Peter (Freddie Highmore), representing the recipient of the bad news, often labeled as 'Me' to show personal disappointment.
This text box is placed over J.M. Barrie (Johnny Depp), who represents the person or entity delivering bad news or a disappointing statement.

crying-boy-on-a-bench.image_description: This three-panel meme format originates from the 2004 film "Finding Neverland," featuring J.M. Barrie (Johnny Depp) and Peter Llewelyn Davies (Freddie Highmore). The meme depicts a conversation where Barrie delivers disappointing news, Peter reacts with sadness, and the final panel shows the sad outcome. It's used to humorously illustrate situations of letdown, harsh realities, or unfulfilled expectations.

Its-fine.name: Its-fine

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the dog character. It typically labels the person, group, or entity that is in denial or calmly accepting a disastrous situation. This represents the subject of the meme who is ignoring the problem.

Located at the top of the image, this text box is superimposed over the burning room. This area is used to label the overwhelming problem, disaster, or chaotic situation that the character (labeled in box 0) is ignoring.

Its-fine.image_description: This meme, known as 'This is Fine,' features an anthropomorphic dog wearing a hat and sitting at a table with a coffee mug while the room is engulfed in flames. The dog's calm, smiling demeanor in the face of disaster is used to represent denial, willful ignorance, or trying to maintain composure during a chaotic or catastrophic situation. It humorously captures a feeling of being overwhelmed but pretending everything is normal.

ANDY-DROPPING-WOODY.name: ANDY-DROPPING-WOODY

text_options.description: This text labels Andy, who represents the person or entity doing the abandoning. This label typically identifies the person or the new interest that is causing them to discard the old one.
This text labels Woody, the toy being dropped. It represents the object, hobby, or concept that is being abandoned or forgotten in favor of something new.

ANDY-DROPPING-WOODY.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Andy Dropping Woody' or 'I Don't Want to Play with You Anymore,' originates from the movie Toy Story. It depicts Andy, the boy, dropping his long-favored toy, Woody, symbolizing the act of abandoning something old for something new. The meme is used to humorously illustrate situations where a person, group, or trend quickly moves on from a previously cherished item, idea, or relationship.

Mr-T-Pity-The-Fool.name: Mr-T-Pity-The-Fool

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, often starting with or including Mr. T's famous catchphrase, "I pity the fool." This text delivers a judgment or a direct, often humorous, rebuke related to the setup in the top text, reinforced by his pointing gesture.
The top text of the meme, typically written in Impact font, sets up the scenario. It describes a person, action, or belief that the meme creator finds ridiculous or worthy of pity.

Mr-T-Pity-The-Fool.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor Mr. T, known for his tough-guy persona in shows like "The A-Team." He has an intense, stern expression and is pointing directly at the viewer, creating a confrontational feel. This image macro is famously used with his catchphrase, "I pity the fool," to call out or mock actions and statements considered foolish or illogical.

They-dont-know-.name: They-dont-know-

text_options.description: This area depicts the other partygoers who are happily socializing and dancing. They represent the oblivious crowd or the "they" in the meme's catchphrase. This section typically does not have text added, serving as the visual counterpoint to the isolated main character.

This text box is placed next to the isolated character and functions as their internal monologue or thought bubble. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is a secret, niche interest, or embarrassing fact that the character believes sets them apart from everyone else. The text here follows the setup phrase "They don't know..." to reveal the source of the character's alienation.

They-dont-know-.image_description: This meme, known as "They Don't Know" or "I Wish I Was At Home," features a Wojak character standing alone in the corner at a party, looking melancholic while others socialize. The character, often called the Loner, represents someone feeling socially anxious, introverted, or possessing a secret or niche knowledge unknown to the oblivious crowd. The format contrasts the character's internal monologue with the carefree party scene to humorous effect.

ANIME-BUTTERFLY-MEME.name: ANIME-BUTTERFLY-MEME

text_options.description: Text placed over the butterfly represents the object, action, or concept that is being misunderstood or mislabeled by the subject of the meme.
Text placed over the anime character identifies the person, group, or entity who is making the incorrect assumption or misinterpretation.

ANIME-BUTTERFLY-MEME.image_description: This meme, known as "Is this a pigeon?", originates from a scene in the 1990s anime "The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird." It features the protagonist, an android named Yutaro Katori, mistakenly identifying a butterfly as a pigeon due to his unfamiliarity with Earth's fauna. The format is widely used to humorously depict someone misinterpreting, mislabeling, or being confused about a person, object, or concept. It highlights a naive or incorrect assessment of a situation.

Hulk.name: Hulk

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It reveals the 'secret' or the constant state of being, completing the implied phrase "I'm always [X]..." This mirrors the original movie quote and delivers the humorous or relatable confession.

This top text box typically presents a question or a statement posed to the subject (Bruce Banner). It sets up the context for the punchline, often asking how he is able to do something or why he is a certain way.

Hulk.image_description: This meme features Bruce Banner (Mark Ruffalo) from the 2012 film "The Avengers," smirking amidst a scene of destruction. The format is based on his iconic line, "That's my secret, Cap. I'm always angry." It is used to humorously reveal a constant, underlying state, habit, or feeling as an explanation for a particular behavior or ability.

All-My-Homies-Love.name: All-My-Homies-Love

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image often serves as a secondary punchline or a label for the group itself. It adds another layer to the joke initiated by the top text, sometimes describing a specific member or the group's collective identity within the meme's context.

The text at the top of the image serves as the main caption, setting up the entire premise of the meme. It describes the activity or situation that "me and the boys" are about to engage in, creating a humorous contrast with their tough-looking appearance in the photo.

All-My-Homies-Love.image_description: This meme, often captioned "Me and the boys," features a black-and-white photograph of a group of young Black men posing with a tough demeanor inside what appears to be a store. The image is used to humorously represent a group of friends getting ready to do something together. The comedy arises from the contrast between their serious, 'gangster' appearance and the often mundane, nerdy, or silly activity described in the caption.

Paulo-Coelho.name: Paulo-Coelho

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a humorous or absurd statement that reframes or undermines the quote above. It is often formatted as an attribution to Paulo Coelho, completing the joke by contrasting his philosophical image with the silly text.

This top text box contains the setup for the joke. It usually features a quote that appears to be deep, inspirational, or philosophical, mimicking the style of Paulo Coelho's writing to set the reader's expectations.

Paulo-Coelho.image_description: This meme features a black and white portrait of the Brazilian author Paulo Coelho, known for his philosophical and inspirational works. The format is used for bait-and-switch jokes where a seemingly profound quote is presented, only to be followed by a humorous, mundane, or absurd punchline that subverts the initial statement. The humor derives from the contrast between Coelho's wise appearance and the often silly or unexpected text attributed to him.

Do-you-want-ants-archer.name: Do-you-want-ants-archer

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It typically reads, "Because that's how you get [X]," where [X] is the undesirable outcome mentioned in the top text.
The top text box is for the setup of the meme's catchphrase. It usually poses a rhetorical question in the format, "Do you want [X]?" where [X] is an undesirable outcome.

Do-you-want-ants-archer.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Sterling Archer, the main character from the animated series "Archer," looking directly at the viewer with a serious expression. The meme format is known as "Do you want ants? Because that's how you get ants," originating from a line in the show. It is used to sarcastically point out the obvious and often negative consequences of a particular action or statement, framing it as a cause-and-effect scenario.

yoda.name: yoda

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the first part of a sentence, typically the subject and object. This sets up the main idea or the premise of the statement.

The top text box contains the second part of the sentence, usually the verb or action. When read after the bottom text, it completes the thought in Yoda's signature inverted syntax, delivering the punchline or piece of wisdom.

yoda.image_description: This meme features the character Yoda from the Star Wars franchise, a wise Jedi Master known for his unique, inverted sentence structure. In the image, Yoda is depicted in a thoughtful pose, often with a finger raised as if imparting wisdom. The meme format splits a sentence into two parts, with the second half at the top and the first half at the bottom, mimicking Yoda's speech pattern to deliver humorous advice or commentary.

Well-Yes-But-Actually-No.name: Well-Yes-But-Actually-No

text_options.description: This text box, positioned directly above the image, typically contains the 'yes' part of the scenario—a statement that is technically true. It sets up the contradiction that the character's line, 'but actually no,' will resolve.

The top text box sets the context for the meme, usually by posing a question or describing a situation. This text prompts the nuanced, two-part answer that follows in the second text box and the image itself.

Well-Yes-But-Actually-No.image_description: This meme features the Pirate Captain from the Aardman Animations film "The Pirates! In an Adventure with Scientists!". The image captures him saying the iconic line, "Well yes, but actually no," which is used as a punchline to express a nuanced or contradictory answer. This format is perfect for situations that are technically true but practically false, or for giving a gentle but firm refusal to a question. The humor lies in the pedantic or roundabout way of saying "no".

Is-this-a-bird.name: Is-this-a-bird

text_options.description: This area, covering the anime character, is labeled with the person, group, or entity that is making an incorrect assumption or misidentification.
This area, located over the butterfly, is labeled with the actual object, concept, or situation that is being misunderstood or mislabeled by the character.

This area is where the punchline text is placed, representing the incorrect label or question. In the original scene, the subtitle here reads, "Is this a pigeon?", which serves as the template for the meme's humorous misidentification.

Is-this-a-bird.image_description: This meme, known as "Is This a Pigeon?", originates from a screenshot of the 1990s anime series The Brave Fighter of Sun Fighbird. It features the character Yutaro Katori, an android, looking at a butterfly and seemingly questioning what it is. The meme is used to humorously depict someone misinterpreting or mislabeling something due to ignorance, naivety, or a specific point of view.

Gabe---shut-up-about-the-sun.name: Gabe---shut-up-about-the-sun

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a forceful and angry dismissal of the statement above. It often directly quotes or paraphrases Gabe's famous line, "SHUT UP ABOUT THE SUN!", to convey extreme annoyance and a desire for the topic to be dropped.

The top text box serves as the setup, presenting a statement, opinion, or topic that the meme creator finds irritating or absurd. This text is the catalyst for Gabe's angry reaction depicted in the image.

Gabe---shut-up-about-the-sun.image_description: This meme features Gabe Lewis from the TV show "The Office" with a contorted, angry expression. Known as the "Shut up about the sun!" meme, it's used to express extreme frustration or forcefully dismiss an opinion or statement that the user finds annoying, over-discussed, or ridiculous. The character's intense and aggressive look perfectly complements the dismissive nature of the punchline.
Gabe---shut-up-about-the-sun.display_name: Gabe   shut up about the sun

Dumb-Wojak.name: Dumb-Wojak

text_options.description: This area often contains a label identifying the person or group being portrayed as the 'Brainlet'. This directly attributes the simplistic thinking to a specific target.

This caption area above the character's head contains the simplistic, foolish, or poorly-worded statement that is being mocked. It functions as a speech bubble or a title, presenting the 'low-IQ' take that the meme is ridiculing.

Dumb-Wojak.image_description: This meme features a crudely drawn Wojak character known as "Brainlet" or "Grug." The character has a deformed, small head, a vacant expression, and is often depicted drooling, symbolizing low intelligence or simplistic thinking. The meme is used to satirize or mock individuals or groups for holding what the creator perceives as foolish, primitive, or poorly-reasoned opinions. It's a reaction image or exploitable format used to portray an opponent's argument as intellectually inferior.

Every-day-I-wake-up.name: Every-day-I-wake-up

text_options.description: This area in the final panel, next to the action text "[crying]", is often used to label the person or entity represented by Adam Driver. It provides context for who is experiencing the emotional breakdown, solidifying the punchline of despair after the initial anger.

This text in the first panel sets up the premise of the meme. It describes the frustrating or anger-inducing situation that causes the character's outburst. The original line, "Every day I wake up...", is almost always replaced with a different statement that serves as the source of the frustration.

Every-day-I-wake-up.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Adam Driver Punching a Wall" or "Marriage Story Argument," originates from the 2019 film "Marriage Story." It depicts actor Adam Driver as his character Charlie Barber having an emotional breakdown. The sequence shows him yelling angrily, punching a wall in frustration, and finally collapsing into tears. The meme is used to express a progression from intense anger or frustration about a situation to overwhelming sadness and defeat.

Spongebob-box.name: Spongebob-box

text_options.description: This area inside the glowing briefcase is where the object of reverence is labeled. It's the punchline of the meme, revealing the item that is considered extremely valuable or important, often something mundane, niche, or silly for comedic effect.
The top text area provides the context or setup for the meme. It typically describes the person or entity (often represented by SpongeBob) who is presenting the precious item shown in the briefcase.

Spongebob-box.image_description: This meme features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series of the same name, holding open a briefcase from which a brilliant light emanates. The image is a parody of a famous scene from the movie Pulp Fiction. This format is used to humorously present something as incredibly precious, valuable, or sacred, with SpongeBob representing the person presenting the item with great reverence.

Holding-hands.name: Holding-hands

text_options.description: Placed over the clasped hands, this text represents the common ground, shared belief, or mutual interest that unites the two otherwise disparate entities. It serves as the punchline, revealing the surprising point of agreement.
This label, placed over the white arm (typically Arnold's), identifies the first of two groups, individuals, or concepts. It represents one side of the agreement or comparison.
This label, placed over the Black arm (typically Carl Weathers'), identifies the second group, individual, or concept. It represents the other, often contrasting, side of the agreement or comparison.

Holding-hands.image_description: The 'Epic Handshake' or 'Predator Handshake' meme is a painting depicting a muscular Black arm and a muscular white arm clasping hands. Originating from a scene in the 1987 film 'Predator' with characters played by Carl Weathers and Arnold Schwarzenegger, it symbolizes agreement or a shared characteristic between two different or opposing groups. The meme is used to highlight an unexpected common ground, with the two arms representing the groups and the handshake representing their point of unity.

Blank-Tombstone.name: Blank-Tombstone

text_options.description: This area at the base of the gravestone is typically used to display the 'lifespan' of the subject, often with a 'Born:' and 'Died:' date. These dates add a layer of specificity and mock formality to the joke, pinpointing the exact start and end of whatever is being mourned.

This is the main face of the gravestone where the primary text or epitaph is placed. It usually contains the name of the person, concept, or thing being declared 'dead,' often accompanied by a witty or ironic phrase about its demise. This text is the central punchline of the meme.

Blank-Tombstone.image_description: This meme, known as "Gravestone" or "RIP", features a blank headstone in a cemetery. It serves as an exploitable template for users to humorously declare something dead or over. The meme is used to satirically mourn the "death" of trends, ideas, hopes, or objects by adding a custom epitaph. This format often employs dark humor to comment on things that have failed, become obsolete, or ended abruptly.

Apu-takes-bullet.name: Apu-takes-bullet

text_options.description: Text placed on Apu, the character being shot, represents the person or concept that is being harmed, sacrificed, or is taking the blame for something.
Text placed on the robber represents the threat, problem, or antagonistic force that is causing the harm or creating the negative situation.
Text placed on the character hiding behind Apu represents the person, group, or idea that is being protected by or benefiting from the sacrifice of the entity labeled on Apu.

Apu-takes-bullet.image_description: This meme originates from an episode of 'The Simpsons' depicting a robbery at the Kwik-E-Mart. In the scene, Apu Nahasapeemapetilon is shot by a robber while another character hides behind him for protection. The format is used as an object-labeling meme to represent a situation where one entity (Apu) is sacrificed or takes damage to protect another (the hidden person) from a threat (the robber).

Bugs-bunny-I-wish-all-empty-template.name: Bugs-bunny-I-wish-all-empty-template

text_options.description: This text box contains the outcome or event being wished upon the group from the first box. It completes the phrase 'a very' with a description, which can be either genuinely pleasant (e.g., 'pleasant evening') or ironically unpleasant (e.g., 'stub your toe'), delivering the punchline of the meme.

This text box identifies the specific group of people being addressed by the meme. The user inserts a noun or phrase here (e.g., 'Virgos,' 'people who don't use their turn signals') to define the target of the wish.

Bugs-bunny-I-wish-all-empty-template.image_description: This meme features the Looney Tunes character Bugs Bunny dressed in a tuxedo with a smug expression. The format, "i wish all [group] a very [outcome]," is used to express a good-natured or, more commonly, a sarcastic or passive-aggressive wish towards a specific group of people. The formal, almost presidential tone set by Bugs Bunny's appearance creates a humorous contrast with the often niche or petty nature of the wish.
Bugs-bunny-I-wish-all-empty-template.display_name: Bugs bunny I wish all empty template

timmys-turner-dad.name: timmys-turner-dad

text_options.description: The text in the bottom panel is the punchline, typically reading "IF I HAD ONE!". This text, combined with the character's angry and frustrated expression, confirms the absence of the desired item from the top panel and delivers the core humor of the meme.

The text in the top panel describes the desired object, achievement, or situation that the meme creator wishes they had. It sets up the premise for the punchline in the bottom panel, representing an ideal but currently unattainable goal.

timmys-turner-dad.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "This Is Where I'd Put My Trophy... If I Had One!", features Timmy's Dad from the animated show "The Fairly OddParents". The top panel shows him proudly gesturing towards an empty pedestal, representing a desire or achievement. The bottom panel shows his expression shift to anger and frustration, signifying the disappointing reality of not having that thing. The meme is used to express relatable longing or frustration over something one lacks.

10-Guy.name: 10-Guy

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, serving as the punchline. This line reveals the absurd or comically incorrect conclusion to the thought started in the top text, encapsulating the 'stoner logic' that defines the meme's humor.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a scenario or begins a thought process. This text establishes the context for the nonsensical punchline that will follow at the bottom.

10-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "10 Guy" or "Stoner Stanley," features a young man with a dazed and intoxicated expression. The character is used to represent someone who is extremely high, on a scale of 1 to 10. The meme's humor comes from pairing this image with text that expresses a nonsensical, comically obvious, or logically flawed thought that might seem profound while under the influence.

Quit-Having-Fun.name: Quit-Having-Fun

text_options.description: This text box, located in the middle panel where the fedora guy is absent, describes the specific action that is considered the "wrong" way to have fun. This is the trigger for the character's anger, often highlighting a trivial or perfectly acceptable behavior that a gatekeeper would criticize (e.g., "Playing on easy mode").

This text box in the top panel sets the initial scene. It typically contains a neutral description of the activity the group is enjoying, providing the general context for the meme's punchline (e.g., "A group of friends playing a new RPG").

Quit-Having-Fun.image_description: This three-panel comic strip meme, known as "Quit Having Fun" or "Stop Having Fun Guy," features stick figures. In the first panel, a man in a fedora observes others playing a video game. In the second, he is gone, and in the third, he returns to angrily yell "QUIT HAVING FUN." The meme is used to satirize gatekeepers or killjoys who get angry when others enjoy a hobby or activity in a way they deem "incorrect" or suboptimal.

Blank-Starter-Pack.name: Blank-Starter-Pack

text_options.description: The punchline of the meme. This text reveals the absurd or humorous item that supposedly fits inside the car, completing the salesman's sentence from the previous panel.
The setup for the punchline. This panel typically contains the first part of the salesman's catchphrase, like 'This bad boy can fit so much...'.
This panel often contains dialogue from the car salesman, continuing his pitch. It builds momentum towards the main catchphrase.
This panel usually depicts the car salesman slapping the roof of the car. It's an action panel and often has no text.
The introductory text or setup for the entire meme. It often presents a question from a customer or a statement that prompts the salesman's pitch.

Blank-Starter-Pack.image_description: This is the 'Slaps Roof of Car' meme template, a five-panel comic featuring a car salesman. The salesman enthusiastically slaps the roof of a car while making an absurd claim about its capacity. The format is used to humorously suggest that an object or concept can contain an unexpectedly large or abstract amount of something, leading to a punchline.

Darth-Vader-Where-is-Padme.name: Darth-Vader-Where-is-Padme

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline. This text represents Darth Vader's iconic, drawn-out scream and is almost always written as 'NOOOOOOOOOOOO' or a similar expression of anguish, serving as the dramatic reaction to the setup in the top box.
The top text box sets up the scenario. It typically contains a question or statement that will elicit a negative or disappointing response, creating anticipation for the punchline.

Darth-Vader-Where-is-Padme.image_description: This meme features a still from the movie *Star Wars: Episode III – Revenge of the Sith*, showing the character Darth Vader. The scene captures the moment he learns of Padmé's death and lets out a long, anguished scream of 'Nooooooo!'. The meme is used to express extreme disappointment, denial, or despair in a melodramatic and humorous way, reacting to a negative statement or situation.

Naruto-Handshake-Meme-Template.name: Naruto-Handshake-Meme-Template

text_options.description: This label is placed on the weapon hidden behind Hashirama's back in the dark, red-tinted lower panel. The text here reveals the secret, treacherous plan or the true, often negative, intention that undermines the agreement shown above. It serves as the punchline, exposing the betrayal.

This label identifies Hashirama Senju, one of the two individuals shaking hands. The text here typically represents one of the parties involved in the agreement, often the one proposing the deal or appearing to be the more trustworthy figure, despite their hidden intentions.

This label points to Madara Uchiha, the other person in the handshake. The text here represents the second party in the agreement, who is either being deceived or is also part of the deceptive pact. Together with label 1, it sets up the context of the agreement.

Naruto-Handshake-Meme-Template.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as 'Madara and Hashirama Handshake' or 'Trust Issues,' originates from the anime Naruto Shippuden. The top panel shows rivals Madara Uchiha and Hashirama Senju shaking hands, symbolizing an agreement or truce. The bottom panel reveals one of them hiding a weapon behind their back, exposing a hidden, treacherous motive. The meme is used to illustrate situations where a seemingly friendly agreement masks a secret, often malicious, plan.

Yoda-Begun-The-Clone-War-Has.name: Yoda-Begun-The-Clone-War-Has

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the core message of the meme. It often starts with "There is another," revealing an alternative to the situation presented in the top text. The text here subverts expectations and is frequently written in Yoda's characteristic object-subject-verb syntax to complete the joke.

The top text box serves as the setup, presenting a statement, a problem, or a scenario that appears to have only one conclusion or a limited set of options. This text establishes the context that Yoda's wisdom in the bottom text will challenge or provide an alternative to.

Yoda-Begun-The-Clone-War-Has.image_description: This meme features a still image of the Star Wars character Yoda looking somber and contemplative. The format is typically used to present a situation or statement, followed by a profound or alternative perspective, often mimicking Yoda's unique speech pattern. Known as "There is another," the meme plays on Yoda's role as a wise master, offering an unexpected or alternative solution to a problem posed in the top text.
Yoda-Begun-The-Clone-War-Has.display_name: Yoda Begun The Clone War Has

Anakin-and-Padme.name: Anakin-and-Padme

text_options.description: This text is placed over the final panel showing Padmé's concerned expression. It is typically the exact same text as in the second panel (index 1), often a question like "...For the better, right?". The repetition, combined with her changed expression, creates the punchline, re-framing the optimistic question into one of dawning horror or disbelief in response to Anakin's unsettling stare in the third panel.

This text is placed over the second panel where Padmé is smiling. It represents her initial, positive, and slightly naive reaction to Anakin's first statement (from the first panel). This is often phrased as a hopeful question seeking confirmation, with the canonical line being "For the better, right?".

This text is placed over the first panel showing Anakin's neutral expression. It serves as the setup for the joke, representing a statement that seems positive or innocuous at first glance. For example, "I'm going to change the world."

Anakin-and-Padme.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "For the Better, Right?" or the "Anakin and Padmé" meme, originates from a scene in "Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones." It features Anakin Skywalker and Padmé Amidala during a picnic. The format illustrates a conversation where an initial positive statement from Anakin is met with a smile from Padmé, but a subsequent, more ominous stare from Anakin causes Padmé's expression to turn to one of concern. The meme is used to represent a situation that takes an unexpectedly dark or unsettling turn.

Angry-npc-wojak.name: Angry-npc-wojak

text_options.description: This text box contains the dialogue of the simple, white-outlined character. The statement is typically a question, opinion, or observation that is perceived as foolish, ignorant, or a common misconception by the NPC Wojak, serving as the catalyst for their eventual anger.

This text box, located above the NPC Wojak, usually contains a short, often dismissive or sarcastic internal thought or unspoken reply. It represents the NPC's initial, restrained reaction to the other character's statement, contrasting with the final panel's overt anger. In many variations, this box is left blank to emphasize the silent judgment.

Angry-npc-wojak.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, known as "NPC Wojak" or "I know, I know... But", depicts a simple white-outlined character speaking to a grey, expressionless character called NPC Wojak. The NPC Wojak maintains a blank stare for two panels before its face contorts into an angry expression in the final frame. The meme illustrates a situation where the NPC character is triggered into a rage by a naive, ignorant, or provocative statement made by the other character, representing a slow burn of frustration.

Dwight-Schrute.name: Dwight-Schrute

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Dwight's shirt, delivers the punchline. It's typically a simple, declarative statement of fact that is often obvious or humorously literal, directly addressing the setup in the top text. This text embodies Dwight's character trait of stating plain truths without social nuance.

The top text, positioned above Dwight's head, serves as the setup for the meme. It usually presents a question, a complex statement, or a scenario that seems to require a nuanced answer. This text establishes the context that the punchline will humorously subvert.

Dwight-Schrute.image_description: A still image of the character Dwight Schrute from the TV show 'The Office' staring directly at the camera with a serious, deadpan expression. This meme format, often called 'Dwight Schrute Facts,' is used to present a simple, often obvious, or blunt statement as a response to a preceding question or situation. The humor comes from the contrast between the setup and the overly literal, factual punchline, mirroring Dwight's personality.

We-Want-you.name: We-Want-you

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, located below Uncle Sam's pointing finger. This section typically contains the specific task, action, or group the viewer is being "recruited" for, often serving as the punchline to the setup in the top text.

The top text of the meme, positioned above Uncle Sam's head. This is the headline and almost always starts with "I WANT YOU," directly mimicking the original poster to set up a demand or call to action.

We-Want-you.image_description: This is the iconic "I Want You for U.S. Army" recruitment poster featuring Uncle Sam, a personification of the United States. In the image, Uncle Sam points directly at the viewer with a stern expression, making a direct appeal. As a meme, this format is used to make a humorous or emphatic call to action, replacing the original military recruitment text with a wide range of demands or requests.

Thor-is-he-though.name: Thor-is-he-though

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the punchline, which is a question casting doubt on the statement above. The classic text here is "Is he, though?" or a similar skeptical phrase that directly challenges the assertion in box 1, aligning with Thor's smug expression.

This top text box is where the initial statement or assertion is placed. It usually represents something said by the character Thor is looking at, often a boast or a confident claim that Thor's expression is reacting to and about to undermine.

Thor-is-he-though.image_description: This meme features the Marvel character Thor, played by Chris Hemsworth, from the movie "Thor: Ragnarok," giving a smug, knowing smile to another character whose back is turned. The format, known as "Is He, Though?", is used to express doubt or sarcastically question a statement. Thor's confident expression represents someone who knows a contrary truth or has inside information, undermining the assertion made by the other person.

Boy-and-girl-texting.name: Boy-and-girl-texting

text_options.description: This speech bubble belongs to the boy in the bottom panel. It typically contains the punchline of the meme: a very short, blunt, or low-effort response that hilariously contrasts with the long message sent by the girl.

This speech bubble belongs to the girl in the top panel. It is used for a long, detailed, or emotionally invested text message that sets up the expectation for a similarly thoughtful reply, which is then subverted by the response below.

Boy-and-girl-texting.image_description: This two-panel meme, often called "Couple Texting in Bed," shows a young woman and a young man smiling as they text each other at night. The format is used to humorously contrast communication styles or levels of investment in a conversation. Typically, one person sends a long, heartfelt, or detailed message, while the other gives a very short, simple, or anticlimactic reply, creating a comedic juxtaposition.

puppet-Monkey-looking-away.name: puppet-Monkey-looking-away

text_options.description: This text box, positioned at the bottom across both panels, typically describes an awkward situation, a direct accusation, or an uncomfortable truth. It acts as the setup, providing the context that causes the puppet's nervous reaction.

This text box, located at the top, usually identifies the person reacting to the situation described below, often labeled simply as 'Me:'. It frames the puppet's shifty-eyed glance as the personal reaction of the meme's creator, signifying their guilt or desire to avoid the topic.

puppet-Monkey-looking-away.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Awkward Look Monkey Puppet' or 'Monkey Puppet,' features a puppet character from a Japanese children's show. The first panel shows the puppet staring blankly, and the second captures it nervously darting its eyes to the side. The meme is used to humorously depict a person's guilt, anxiety, or awkwardness when caught in an uncomfortable or incriminating situation.

Help-Me-Obi-Wan-Youre-our-only-hope.name: Help-Me-Obi-Wan-Youre-our-only-hope

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is a variation of Princess Leia's famous line. It typically reads, "Help me, [X]. You're my only hope," where [X] is replaced by the person, object, or concept that is the supposed last resort for the problem described in the top text.
The top text box is used to set up a relatable or humorous problem. This text establishes the context of desperation, leading into the plea shown in the image and the bottom text.

Help-Me-Obi-Wan-Youre-our-only-hope.image_description: This meme features a still image of Princess Leia's holographic message from the film *Star Wars: A New Hope*. In the scene, she famously pleads, "Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi. You're my only hope." The meme uses this iconic moment of desperation to humorously frame a situation where the user feels they have only one last resort or solution to a problem.
Help-Me-Obi-Wan-Youre-our-only-hope.display_name: Help Me Obi Wan Youre our only hope

I-for-one-welcome-our-new-overlords.name: I-for-one-welcome-our-new-overlords

text_options.description: This bottom caption area typically contains the punchline, a variation of Kent Brockman's original quote, such as "I, for one, welcome our new [X] overlords." The '[X]' is replaced with the subject of the meme, which is the new dominant force being humorously accepted.

The text placed over Kent Brockman's head identifies the person or group who is feigning submission. This label is often "Me" or a specific group of people who are being affected by the new "overlord" mentioned in the bottom caption.

I-for-one-welcome-our-new-overlords.image_description: This meme features Kent Brockman, a news anchor from the animated series "The Simpsons." In this scene, he is reporting on what appears to be a space ant invasion, leading to his famous line, "I, for one, welcome our new insect overlords." The meme is used to sarcastically or humorously express submission to a new, powerful entity, trend, or authority figure, feigning acceptance of their dominance.
I-for-one-welcome-our-new-overlords.display_name: I for one welcome our new overlords

See-You-Again.name: See-You-Again

text_options.description: This text is placed on the bottom panel where the two cars are shown diverging on the road. It typically describes the overarching situation or the two distinct paths that are being taken, setting the stage for the comparison.

This label is placed over Paul Walker's character, Brian O'Conner. The text here represents one of the two entities that are parting ways, often the one perceived as taking a different or sometimes more sensible path compared to the other.

This label is placed over Vin Diesel's character, Dominic Toretto. The text here represents the second entity in the comparison, contrasting with the one associated with Paul Walker. It completes the pair of diverging concepts or individuals.

See-You-Again.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Paul Walker and Vin Diesel Parting Ways' or 'For Paul,' originates from the final scene of the movie 'Furious 7'. It depicts characters Brian O'Conner (Paul Walker) and Dominic Toretto (Vin Diesel) driving in separate cars and looking at each other before their paths diverge at a fork in the road. The meme uses this emotionally charged scene of farewell to humorously or poignantly represent two different people, ideas, or groups going their separate ways.

Lumbergh.name: Lumbergh

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline and the character's signature catchphrase, 'That would be great.' This phrase, placed at the end, delivers the passive-aggressive and condescending tone of the request made in the top text.
The top text sets up the meme by stating a passive-aggressive request or demand. It often starts with 'Yeah, if you could just...' to mimic the character's annoying and indirect way of giving orders.

Lumbergh.image_description: This meme features Bill Lumbergh, the condescending boss from the 1999 film 'Office Space'. In the image, he is standing in a cubicle farm, holding a coffee mug with a patronizing expression. The meme is used to make sarcastic or passive-aggressive requests, mimicking Lumbergh's management style. The format typically follows the phrasal template, 'Yeah, if you could just [do an undesirable task], that would be great.'

Dafuq-did-I-just-read.name: Dafuq-did-I-just-read
