text_options.description: This text overlay on the bottom panel serves as the punchline. It describes the shocking, disappointing, or disgusting information that causes the man's negative reaction, creating a humorous contrast with the setup in the top panel.

This text overlay on the top panel describes the initial situation, action, or piece of information that the person is considering or 'reading'. It sets up the context for the reaction shown in the bottom panel.

Dafuq-did-I-just-read.image_description: This two-panel meme features a portrait of 18th-century writer Samuel Johnson. In the top panel, he is shown reading a book with a look of concentration or mild confusion. In the bottom panel, he looks directly at the viewer with a wrinkled brow and an expression of disgust or disappointment. The meme is used to contrast an initial action or statement with a subsequent, unpleasant realization or outcome.

Manly-Handshake.name: Manly-Handshake

text_options.description: Located on the clasped hands, this central text box contains the punchline of the meme. It describes the shared belief, action, or characteristic that unites the two otherwise different parties shown.
This text box is placed over the character on the right, Alex Louis Armstrong. It is used to label the first of the two parties or groups that are forming an agreement.
This text box is placed over the character on the left, Sig Curtis. It is used to label the second party or group, which is often in contrast or opposition to the first one.

Manly-Handshake.image_description: This meme, known as 'Epic Handshake,' originates from the anime 'Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood' and features two very muscular characters, Alex Louis Armstrong and Sig Curtis, engaging in a powerful handshake. The intense, muscular greeting signifies a moment of mutual respect and agreement. Culturally, this format is used to represent two different, often opposing, groups or entities finding common ground on a specific topic, which is labeled over their clasped hands.

Obi-Wan-Kenobi.name: Obi-Wan-Kenobi

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is almost always a direct quote or a slight variation of Obi-Wan Kenobi's line: "Now that's a name I've not heard in a long, long time." This text directly reflects the character's expression of recognizing something from the distant past.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically presents a scenario or mentions a name, object, or concept that is considered old, obscure, or nostalgic, prompting the reaction from Obi-Wan.

Obi-Wan-Kenobi.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Obi-Wan Kenobi, played by Alec Guinness, from Star Wars: A New Hope. His expression is one of weary recognition and nostalgia. The meme is used to react to something old, forgotten, or from a long time ago, often a piece of pop culture, a trend, or a name that has resurfaced. The format typically pairs a prompt about a nostalgic topic with Obi-Wan's iconic line, "Now that's a name I've not heard in a long, long time."

CNN-Breaking-News-Anderson-Cooper.name: CNN-Breaking-News-Anderson-Cooper

text_options.description: This is the main news banner where the punchline of the meme is placed. Text here presents a funny, relatable, or ridiculous statement as if it were a legitimate and urgent news headline, directly playing on the "BREAKING NEWS" graphic to its left.

This area, placed over Anderson Cooper's head, is used to label the subject of the fake news. The text here often identifies a person, group, or entity that is either delivering, experiencing, or is the topic of the humorous headline in the banner below.

CNN-Breaking-News-Anderson-Cooper.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of CNN news anchor Anderson Cooper during a live broadcast. The format mimics a serious "Breaking News" segment, creating a template for users to insert their own humorous, absurd, or mundane text into the news banner. The humor arises from the contrast between the official, urgent presentation of a news broadcast and the trivial or silly nature of the user-generated headline.

Phoebe-teaching-Joey-in-Friends.name: Phoebe-teaching-Joey-in-Friends

text_options.description: The punchline of the meme. This text, spoken by Joey with a confident smile, is a completely incorrect and often absurd version of what he was just taught. Its nonsensical nature, contrasted with his confident expression, creates the humor.

This panel shows Joey concentrating intensely before his final, incorrect answer. The text here often represents his flawed thought process or a simple prompt from Phoebe, building anticipation for the punchline in the next panel.
Joey's repetition of the second part of the lesson. The text here is typically a correct repetition of the text in panel 5, showing that he is capable of following simple, individual steps.
Joey's repetition of the first part of the lesson. The text here is usually a correct repetition of the text in panel 7, establishing the premise that he is trying to learn.

Phoebe's final instruction, often combining all the previous parts into the complete, correct phrase. Her slightly exasperated expression contrasts with Joey's final, incorrect answer, highlighting the failure.
The second part of the concept Phoebe is teaching. This text builds on the first part from panel 7, continuing the step-by-step lesson.
The third and final part of Phoebe's lesson. This is usually the simplest component, which makes Joey's ultimate failure to grasp it even more humorous.
The first part of the lesson or concept that Phoebe is trying to teach Joey. It's the initial, simple step in the sequence.

Phoebe-teaching-Joey-in-Friends.image_description: This is a four-panel meme template known as "Phoebe Teaching Joey," originating from the TV show "Friends." It depicts Phoebe Buffay attempting to teach Joey Tribbiani a simple concept, breaking it down into parts. The format is used to humorously illustrate a situation where someone fails to grasp a basic idea despite clear instructions, delivering a comically incorrect and nonsensical answer with confidence for the punchline.

One-please.name: One-please

text_options.description: This label identifies the recipient of the transaction, represented by the small, expectant anime girl. This text typically names a person, company, or concept that demands resources, such as "My landlord," "Steam sales," or "Gacha games."

This text label is placed over the tray, representing the item after it has been given away. It often contains the same text as the label in the first panel to show the completion of the transaction, for instance, "My rent money" or "My entire wallet."

This label identifies the valuable item being held tightly in the clenched fist. It represents what the subject is reluctant to part with, commonly labeled as "My money," "My paycheck," or another prized possession.

One-please.image_description: This three-panel meme, originating from the anime "Wataten!: An Angel Flew Down to Me," humorously depicts a reluctant transaction. The first panel shows a clenched fist, symbolizing holding onto something valuable, which is then shown being given away by an open hand in the second panel. The final panel features the character Hana Shirosaki looking on expectantly, representing the recipient. The meme is widely used to illustrate situations of reluctantly giving up money or resources to entities like bills, video game sales, or other obligations.

Mean-Girls---Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-H.name: Mean-Girls---Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-Happen

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is Regina George's dismissive response. The canonical text is "Stop trying to make 'fetch' happen. It's not going to happen," but it is almost always adapted to reject the subject mentioned in the top text, such as "Stop trying to make [unpopular trend] happen."

The top text box is used to introduce the subject that is being rejected. This could be a person, a group, an idea, or a trend that the meme creator finds annoying or believes is being forced into popularity. It sets up the context for Regina's dismissive quote below.

Mean-Girls---Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-H.image_description: This is a meme template featuring the character Regina George from the 2004 movie "Mean Girls." In the image, Regina, wearing a Santa hat, looks directly at the viewer with a condescending and annoyed expression. This meme, known as "Stop Trying to Make Fetch Happen," is used to forcefully dismiss an idea, trend, or statement that someone is trying to popularize against others' will. The format humorously conveys strong disapproval or rejection.
Mean-Girls---Stop-Trying-to-Make-Fetch-H.display_name: Mean Girls   Stop Trying to Make Fetch Happen

Im-awake-but-at-what-cost.name: Im-awake-but-at-what-cost

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically contains the punchline or the cat's internal monologue. This text verbalizes the judgmental or disgusted reaction implied by the cat's face, often as a direct, unimpressed response to the setup text above.
The top text area is used to set up the scenario or present a statement that the cat is reacting to. This text provides the context for the cat's expression of disgust, disappointment, or judgment.

Im-awake-but-at-what-cost.image_description: This meme features a close-up of a white kitten with squinted, tired-looking eyes, giving it a judgmental or disgusted expression. Known as the 'Sleepy Cat' or 'Disgusted Cat,' it's used as a reaction image to express disappointment, disapproval, or being thoroughly unimpressed with a preceding statement or situation. The cat's subtle yet potent look of contempt makes it a versatile tool for conveying mild negative feelings online.
Im-awake-but-at-what-cost.display_name: Im awake but at what cost

Expanding-brain-3-panels.name: Expanding-brain-3-panels

text_options.description: This is the final panel, paired with the most illuminated brain. The text here is the punchline, presenting the most absurd, illogical, or comically enlightened idea in the sequence. It's meant to be a 'galaxy brain' take that is ironically portrayed as the highest level of intelligence.

This is the middle panel in the sequence, corresponding to a brain that is more illuminated than the first. The text here typically describes a more complex or alternative idea compared to the one in the top panel, representing a higher level of thought or a more nuanced perspective.

This is the top panel and the starting point of the meme. The text here usually describes a simple, common, or conventional idea or action. It corresponds to the image of the brain with the least amount of activity, setting the baseline for the intellectual escalation that follows.

Expanding-brain-3-panels.image_description: The "Expanding Brain" meme features a series of panels depicting a brain with progressively increasing levels of enlightenment, represented by glowing and radiating light. This format is used to satirically rank different ideas, actions, or concepts in a hierarchy. The sequence typically starts with a simple or conventional idea and escalates to increasingly absurd, nonsensical, or ironically profound alternatives, with the final, most illuminated brain representing the ultimate, often ridiculous, level of thinking.

laughing-hitler.name: laughing-hitler

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Hitler's torso, typically contains the punchline or the controversial statement. This is where the creator puts the 'evil' or questionable idea they are ironically endorsing, directly associating it with the infamous figure in the image.

The top text serves as the setup for the joke. It often poses a rhetorical question or states a premise that frames the subsequent punchline, such as 'If evil, why hot?' or a similar structure that creates an absurd justification for the controversial statement below.

laughing-hitler.image_description: This meme features a colorized, smiling portrait of Adolf Hitler. The format is often used for dark or edgy humor, typically following the phrasal template "If [X is bad], why [Y is good]?" or to frame a controversial opinion or action in a positive light. The humor arises from the extreme absurdity of positively framing one of history's most condemned figures, making it a vehicle for shocking or satirical punchlines.

Tell-me-the-truth-Im-ready-to-hear-it.name: Tell-me-the-truth-Im-ready-to-hear-it

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Mary Jane's crying face in the final panel. It typically labels the person or group who is upset or disillusioned by the 'truth' revealed in the panel above. For example, it might say 'Me,' 'Gamers,' or 'People who thought [common misconception].'

This text box is in the middle panel, representing Peter Parker's response. This is where the punchline of the meme goes. It contains the harsh, unpopular, or funny 'truth' that Mary Jane asked to hear, which directly causes her emotional reaction in the next panel.

Tell-me-the-truth-Im-ready-to-hear-it.image_description: This meme format originates from the 2002 film "Spider-Man," featuring Mary Jane Watson (Kirsten Dunst) and Peter Parker (Tobey Maguire). In the first panel, a tearful Mary Jane asks Peter to tell her the truth, bracing herself for it. The meme's humor comes from the second panel, where Peter delivers a harsh, funny, or inconvenient truth, leading to the third panel where Mary Jane is shown crying in response. It's used to express a "hard to swallow pill" or a disappointing realization.
Tell-me-the-truth-Im-ready-to-hear-it.display_name: Tell me the truth Im ready to hear it

Bird-Cracker.name: Bird-Cracker

text_options.description: This label identifies the subject of the meme, typically 'Me' or a specific person/group. This character is the one who has the dramatic change of heart, going from rejection to adoration.
This label identifies the object or concept being tried, which is the same as in the first panel. The subject is now reluctantly or aggressively sampling the thing they just rejected.
This label identifies the object, idea, or activity that the subject (the bird) is initially and aggressively rejecting. It represents something new or unwanted being offered.

Bird-Cracker.image_description: This four-panel comic, known as "Get That Thing Out Of My Face Bird" or "Chicken Thoughts Bird," shows a small blue bird angrily rejecting a cracker. In the following panels, the bird aggressively bites the cracker and then develops a blissful, starry-eyed expression, having clearly enjoyed it. The meme is used to humorously represent someone vehemently refusing something, only to immediately change their mind and love it after giving it a try.

Black-guy-disappearing.name: Black-guy-disappearing

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the man in the first panel. It typically contains a label identifying the person or entity who is reacting to the situation and wants to disappear.

Located at the top of the image, this text box describes the awkward, undesirable, or incriminating situation that prompts the character's desire to vanish. This text serves as the setup for the punchline, which is the visual act of disappearing.

Black-guy-disappearing.image_description: This is the "Disappearing Black Guy" or "Fading Away" meme, featuring a young Black man in a three-panel format. In the first panel, he looks back with an awkward or concerned expression; in the second, he begins to fade; and in the third, he has vanished completely. The meme is used to humorously represent a desire to escape or withdraw from an uncomfortable, awkward, or incriminating situation.

Meg-Family-Guy-Better-than-me.name: Meg-Family-Guy-Better-than-me

text_options.description: Text here is placed over Peter Griffin, the main character in the sophisticated group. This label typically represents the primary entity, company, or concept that is being challenged or is acting ignorant.
This label is on Lois Griffin, who is part of the dismissive group. Text here usually represents a secondary entity or concept that is aligned with the primary one (Peter).
This label is on Chris Griffin, the third member of the formal group. Text here represents another supporting entity, reinforcing the idea of a unified, out-of-touch bloc.

This text box is placed in the background, near the door where Meg enters. It often contains the setup for the punchline, representing the event or topic that is causing the disruption (e.g., "Ligma").

Text here is placed over Meg Griffin, who is portrayed as the frantic outsider. This is the punchline of the meme, typically a question or statement that highlights the ignorance of the group below (e.g., "Who the hell is Steve Jobs?").

Meg-Family-Guy-Better-than-me.image_description: This is a two-panel meme template from the animated sitcom "Family Guy," often called "Who the hell is Steve Jobs?" or "Peter Griffin Tuxedo." The bottom panel shows Peter, Lois, and Chris Griffin dressed in formal attire, looking smug and sophisticated. The top panel shows their daughter, Meg Griffin, bursting into the room with a concerned or urgent expression. The meme is used to contrast a group that is out of touch, dismissive, or represents an established power with an outsider bringing up a new, disruptive, or obvious topic.
Meg-Family-Guy-Better-than-me.display_name: Meg Family Guy Better than me

Reaction-Guys.name: Reaction-Guys

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the bottom panel, where the men are cheering wildly. The text here describes something exciting, desirable, or a superior version of a concept, eliciting the positive and enthusiastic reaction.

This text box is placed next to the top panel, where the men look bored. The text here typically describes something mundane, disappointing, or an inferior option, which corresponds to the men's unimpressed reaction.

Reaction-Guys.image_description: This is a two-panel reaction meme known as "Reaction Guys" or "Gaijin 4Koma." The top panel shows four men sitting side-by-side, looking stoic and unimpressed while watching something off-screen. The bottom panel depicts the same four men in a state of wild excitement, cheering, pointing, and celebrating enthusiastically. The meme format contrasts a mundane or undesirable subject (top) with an exciting or superior alternative (bottom), highlighting a strong preference for the latter.

Straining-kid.name: Straining-kid

text_options.description: This text label is placed over the straining man's body. It typically identifies the person or entity who is experiencing the intense internal struggle, setting up the subject of the meme (e.g., 'Me').

This caption, placed at the top of the image, describes the specific urge, thought, or action that the person is trying so hard to hold back. This text provides the context for the man's strain and serves as the punchline of the meme.

Straining-kid.image_description: This meme, known as "Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl" or "Straining Guy," features a young man in a classroom visibly struggling to contain himself, with veins bulging on his forehead and neck. The image perfectly captures a moment of intense internal struggle and the immense effort required to suppress a powerful urge or impulse. Culturally, it's used to humorously depict situations where someone is desperately trying not to say or do something, often something inappropriate or obvious, in a social setting.

Water-Dam-Meme.name: Water-Dam-Meme

text_options.description: The text in this box, placed over the town, typically represents the person, group, or situation that is being protected or is oblivious to the impending danger. It is the potential victim or the status quo that would be destroyed if the dam were to break.

This text box, positioned over the vast reservoir of water, identifies the overwhelming force, urge, emotion, or problem being held back. This is the source of the immense pressure that threatens to break through the dam.

Water-Dam-Meme.image_description: This meme, known as 'Dam Holding Back Water,' depicts a large dam precariously holding back a massive body of water, with a small town nestled peacefully below. The dam itself represents a single person, idea, or object exerting immense effort to restrain something powerful. This format is used to humorously illustrate situations of great internal or external pressure, where one thing is barely preventing a catastrophic or overwhelming outcome.

They-are-the-same-picture.name: They-are-the-same-picture

text_options.description: This box contains the second of two images or concepts that are being compared. The meme's punchline asserts that this item is identical to the one in the other box.
This box contains the first of two images or concepts that are being compared. The meme sets this up as distinct from the other item, only for Pam to declare them the same.

They-are-the-same-picture.image_description: This meme features Pam Beesly from the TV show *The Office*. In the top panel, someone off-screen asks her to find the differences between two pictures, with the subtitle "Corporate needs you to find the differences between this picture and this picture." In the bottom panel, Pam looks directly at the camera and states, "They're the same picture." The format is used to humorously claim that two seemingly different things are actually identical in nature or effect.

Trying-to-calculate-how-much-sleep-I-can.name: Trying-to-calculate-how-much-sleep-I-can-get

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region typically describes the confusing or complicated situation that the subject is trying to understand or solve. This text serves as the punchline or the core problem causing the mental gymnastics.

The text in this top region usually introduces the subject who is doing the intense thinking or calculation, often starting with "Me trying to..." or identifying a specific group. It sets up the context for the humorous overthinking depicted in the meme.

Trying-to-calculate-how-much-sleep-I-can.image_description: This meme, often called "Confused Math Lady" or "Zach Galifianakis Calculating," features a close-up of the actor Zach Galifianakis from the movie "The Hangover" looking perplexed. Floating mathematical equations are superimposed over his face, symbolizing intense mental calculation, overthinking, or confusion. The meme is typically used to humorously depict someone trying to solve a complex or nonsensical problem, often an everyday situation that is being overanalyzed.
Trying-to-calculate-how-much-sleep-I-can.display_name: Trying to calculate how much sleep I can get

Doomguy.name: Doomguy

text_options.description: This area, covering the horde of demons, represents the numerous, overwhelming, or difficult challenges, tasks, or opponents. The text here lists the problems or the group that the central figure is about to confront.

This label is placed on the Doom Slayer, the central protagonist. The text here identifies the single person, group, or concept that is bravely and aggressively facing the overwhelming odds represented by the demons below.

Doomguy.image_description: This meme features the cover art from the 2016 video game 'Doom,' depicting the protagonist known as the Doom Slayer or Doomguy. He stands defiantly in a hellish landscape, armed with a shotgun and surrounded by a massive horde of demons. The format is used to represent a single, powerful individual or entity facing an overwhelming number of challenges, problems, or opponents, often with a sense of righteous fury or determination.

neck-vein-guy.name: neck-vein-guy

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image usually identifies the person or entity that is doing the straining or holding back. It sets up the subject of the joke.

Positioned at the top, this text describes the action, urge, or thought that the subject (identified in box 0) is desperately trying to suppress. This caption provides the context for the intense struggle shown in the image.

neck-vein-guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Straining Guy" or "Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl in Class," features a young man with bulging veins on his forehead and neck, looking like he is under immense physical or mental pressure. The image perfectly captures a moment of intense internal struggle and immense effort to suppress an urge or hold back a comment. It's widely used to humorously represent situations that require extreme self-control.

Youre-laughing.name: Youre-laughing

text_options.description: This bottom text area is typically reserved for the punchline or the final, damning statement delivered by Murray Franklin. It often contains the iconic line from the movie, "You get what you f*cking deserve," or a variation that represents the negative consequence or harsh truth being delivered to the subject of the meme.

The top text box is used to set up the context of the meme. It usually describes an absurd, naive, or problematic statement or action made by a person or group, which Murray Franklin's character is reacting to with disbelief or judgment.

Youre-laughing.image_description: This meme features a still of Robert De Niro as the talk show host Murray Franklin from the 2019 film "Joker." Murray is shown with a serious, concerned, and slightly condescending expression, looking towards the Joker (off-screen). The meme is part of the "You Get What You F*cking Deserve" format, used to illustrate a situation where someone faces a just and often harsh consequence for their foolish or malicious actions, with Murray representing the voice of reason or judgment before the final outcome.

modi-congratulations-meme.name: modi-congratulations-meme

text_options.description: The bottom text box serves as the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a response attributed to Narendra Modi, often a catchphrase, a piece of simplistic advice, or a dismissive comment that humorously contrasts with the problem stated in the top text. This creates the comedic effect of a powerful leader giving an absurdly unhelpful or funny solution to a mundane problem.

The top text box is used to set up the joke by presenting a relatable problem, a question, or a frustrating scenario. This text establishes the context for the punchline that follows below, often describing a common everyday struggle or a difficult situation.

modi-congratulations-meme.image_description: This meme features a portrait of Narendra Modi, the Prime Minister of India, against a soft-focus background. The format is a two-panel macro, where text is added to the top and bottom to create a humorous scenario. Typically, a problem or situation is presented at the top, and Modi's image is used to deliver a funny, often simplistic or unrelated, punchline at the bottom, frequently using his popular catchphrases for satirical effect.

And-Then-He-Said.name: And-Then-He-Said

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the joke. It is typically a cynical, dismissive, or absurd statement, often starting with "And then I said..." This text is framed as the joke being told that caused the men to laugh, revealing a harsh or humorous truth that contrasts with the setup in the top box.

The top text box provides the setup for the meme's joke. It usually presents a naive question, a hopeful statement, or a common belief expressed by someone outside the laughing group. This text establishes the context that the men in the photo find amusingly out of touch.

And-Then-He-Said.image_description: This meme, known as "And Then I Said" or "Laughing Men," features a vintage photograph of several men in suits, including former U.S. President Ronald Reagan, sharing a moment of uproarious laughter. The format is typically used to create a two-part joke mocking naive beliefs or expectations. The image conveys a sense of cynical amusement from a powerful, in-the-know group at the expense of an unseen, gullible person.

Its-Free-Real-Estate.name: Its-Free-Real-Estate

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme, 'It's Free Real Estate'. This phrase is the reaction to the situation described in the top text, conveying an enthusiastic and opportunistic seizure of something for free.

This area above the man's head is where the setup text is placed. Users add a caption here describing a scenario, object, or space that is available to be taken, which then humorously justifies the 'It's Free Real Estate' reaction.

Its-Free-Real-Estate.image_description: This meme features actor Tim Heidecker from a sketch on the 'Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!'. With an intense and slightly unsettling smile, he enthusiastically declares 'It's Free Real Estate'. The meme is used to humorously describe a situation where someone can take advantage of an unclaimed or freely available resource, opportunity, or space, often in an absurd or opportunistic way.

Nah-yeah.name: Nah-yeah

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Drake smiling and pointing in approval. The text here represents the preferred, superior, or more desirable option in the comparison.
This text box is adjacent to the image of Drake looking displeased and holding up his hand in rejection. The text placed here represents the undesirable, inferior, or rejected option.

Nah-yeah.image_description: This is the "Drake Hotline Bling" meme, a two-panel reaction image featuring the rapper Drake. In the top panel, he looks displeased and gestures dismissively, indicating rejection. In the bottom panel, he smiles and points approvingly, signaling preference. This format is widely used to contrast two things, showing a clear preference for the second option over the first.

Nobody-Expects-the-Spanish-Inquisition-M.name: Nobody-Expects-the-Spanish-Inquisition-Monty-Python

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline. This is where the iconic phrase "NOBODY EXPECTS THE SPANISH INQUISITION!" or a variation of it is placed. It represents the sudden, unexpected event or entity that interrupts the setup described in the top text.

The top text, which provides the setup for the meme. It typically describes a normal, predictable, or mundane situation, conversation, or question. This text establishes a sense of normalcy that is about to be abruptly shattered by the punchline.

Nobody-Expects-the-Spanish-Inquisition-M.image_description: A still from a Monty Python sketch featuring three men dressed as cardinals of the Spanish Inquisition. This meme, known as "Nobody Expects the Spanish Inquisition," is used to represent a sudden, unexpected, and often absurd interruption to a situation. The humor comes from the abrupt appearance of the characters, mirroring their catchphrase and disrupting the flow of a conversation or event.
Nobody-Expects-the-Spanish-Inquisition-M.display_name: Nobody Expects the Spanish Inquisition Monty Python

What-the-hell-is-this.name: What-the-hell-is-this

text_options.description: This box is placed on the penguin. In the meme format, this character is labeled with the first of two concepts or entities that are being combined.
This box is on the elephant. This character is labeled with the second concept or entity that, when combined with the first (the penguin), produces an unexpected result.
This box is on the penguin-elephant hybrid creature. This character represents the strange, confusing, or undesirable outcome of combining the two elements labeled on the penguin and the elephant.

What-the-hell-is-this.image_description: This meme originates from a "Family Guy" scene depicting Noah on his ark. He looks with confusion and disgust at a bizarre hybrid creature, an elephant-penguin, standing next to its supposed parents, a regular penguin and an elephant, and asks, "What the hell is this?". The meme is used to express bewilderment or disapproval towards an unexpected, strange, or undesirable combination of two different things.

Headaches.name: Headaches

text_options.description: This area is the customizable punchline of the meme. Users insert text here to describe a specific, often trivial, but highly irritating situation, object, or concept that is the source of the overwhelming 'headache' depicted by the fully red head below it.

This is the title of the chart, originally reading "Types of Headaches." It sets up the premise of the meme. While often left as is, this text can sometimes be edited to better fit the specific context of the punchline, such as "Types of Pain" or "Reasons I'm Stressed."

Headaches.image_description: The "Types of Headaches" meme is an exploitable four-panel comic based on a medical diagram illustrating different headache types. The first three panels show medically recognized headaches like 'Migraine' and 'Stress' with specific areas of the head highlighted in red. The fourth panel, the punchline, shows a head completely engulfed in red, representing an overwhelming, all-consuming annoyance. This meme format is used to humorously complain about frustrating or nonsensical things by labeling them as the cause of this ultimate headache.

Men-Discussing-Men-Fighting.name: Men-Discussing-Men-Fighting

text_options.description: This label identifies the group that is portrayed as handling issues in a formal, organized, and non-confrontational manner. The text here typically describes a group perceived as more 'civilized' or bureaucratic, contrasting with the chaotic scene above.

This label identifies the group that is depicted as resolving conflicts in a chaotic, direct, and physical way. The text here usually names a group humorously stereotyped as being less sophisticated or more primal in their interactions, contrasting with the orderly meeting below.

Men-Discussing-Men-Fighting.image_description: This two-panel meme contrasts a chaotic, violent brawl with a formal, orderly meeting. The top image, from the film 'Green Street Hooligans', shows men physically fighting on a dirt ground, representing a direct and unsophisticated approach to conflict. The bottom image shows officials seated far apart at a large, circular table, symbolizing a diplomatic, bureaucratic, or passive-aggressive method. The meme is used to humorously compare how different groups (e.g., men vs. women, different professions) supposedly handle disagreements.

thank-you-for-changing-my-life.name: thank-you-for-changing-my-life

text_options.description: This text box is the punchline of the meme. It completes the sentence "i'm literally a..." with the name of a mundane, silly, or specific object, person, or concept that the girl is thanking. The humor derives from the contrast between the profound gratitude expressed and the triviality of the thing being thanked.

This large area at the top is typically used to display an image of the object or person being thanked. This visual element represents the speaker of the second line ("i'm literally a...") and provides the context for the punchline written in box 0.

thank-you-for-changing-my-life.image_description: This meme, known as "Thank You For Changing My Life," features a Trad Girl Wojak character expressing deep gratitude. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of her heartfelt thanks with the mundane or silly nature of the object she is thanking. This object, often depicted in the top panel, responds with "i'm literally a [object]," highlighting how trivial things can sometimes have a profound, albeit exaggerated, impact on our lives.
thank-you-for-changing-my-life.display_name: thank you for changing my life

Plane-flying-from-explosions.name: Plane-flying-from-explosions

text_options.description: Text placed over the exploding city typically describes the chaotic situation, the problem, or the negative consequences left behind by the person or entity represented by the plane.

Text placed over Jay Jay the Jet Plane identifies the person, group, or entity responsible for the chaos depicted below. This label represents the culprit who is shown as being smug, indifferent, or happy about the destruction they have caused.

Plane-flying-from-explosions.image_description: This meme features a photoshopped image of Jay Jay the Jet Plane, a cheerful character from a children's TV show, flying away from a massive explosion in a city with a smug smile. The stark contrast between the innocent character and the catastrophic background creates a dark humor. The meme is used to represent someone who has caused a significant problem or chaos and is now leaving the scene, completely unbothered or even pleased with the destructive outcome.

Third-World-Success-Kid.name: Third-World-Success-Kid

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline. It describes a small, often first-world-problem-style success or relief that humorously contrasts with the serious problem mentioned in the top text. The child's triumphant expression aligns with this statement of victory.

The top text, which acts as the setup for the joke. This line typically introduces a problem or a negative situation, often playing on stereotypes about life in developing countries, to create a context of hardship.

Third-World-Success-Kid.image_description: The 'Third World Success' meme, also known as 'Dancing African Kid', features a young Black child dancing enthusiastically on a dirt road with a wide smile. The meme is a two-part image macro that juxtaposes a stereotypical hardship associated with developing countries with a minor, often trivial, personal victory. The child's joyful expression perfectly captures the feeling of this small success, creating a humorous and relatable contrast.

Where-were-going-we-dont-need-roads.name: Where-were-going-we-dont-need-roads

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the characters in the car and serves as the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a modified version of Doc Brown's quote, replacing "roads" with another concept that is being disregarded (e.g., "Sleep? Where we're going, we don't need sleep.").

Located at the top of the image, this text box provides the setup or context for the punchline below. It often presents a statement or question that highlights the need for the very thing that will be dismissed in the punchline (e.g., "You should get some sleep before the big exam.").

Where-were-going-we-dont-need-roads.image_description: A still image from the movie "Back to the Future" featuring characters Marty McFly, Jennifer Parker, and Dr. Emmett "Doc" Brown inside the DeLorean time machine. Doc Brown, on the right wearing futuristic sunglasses, is about to travel to the future. The meme uses Doc's famous line, "Roads? Where we're going, we don't need roads," to humorously dismiss a conventional necessity in favor of a more ambitious or reckless goal.
Where-were-going-we-dont-need-roads.display_name: Where were going we dont need roads

Sitting-Wolf.name: Sitting-Wolf

text_options.description: The bottom text is the main punchline of the meme. It typically contains an overly dramatic, edgy, or nonsensical quote that is meant to sound profound but comes across as cringeworthy or silly, representing the 'deep thoughts' of the lone wolf.

The top text area usually serves as a setup or context for the punchline below. It often contains a simple prompt like 'Me when...' or 'Nobody:', framing the situation that supposedly leads to the wolf's profound (and ironic) realization.

Sitting-Wolf.image_description: This meme, often called 'Loner Wolf' or 'Sad Wolf', features a dramatic illustration of an anthropomorphic white wolf sitting pensively by a stormy sea. The image's serious and melancholic tone is typically used ironically to mock overly edgy, pseudo-profound, or 'alpha male' statements. The humor comes from the contrast between the dramatic artwork and the often cringeworthy or nonsensical text overlaid on it, satirizing people who identify with the 'lone wolf' archetype.

Woman-holding-man.name: Woman-holding-man

text_options.description: This label identifies the antagonist or the source of frustration. It's the person, concept, or situation that provokes the strong reaction from the character at index 1.
This label represents the protagonist or the meme creator, often labeled as 'Me.' This character is filled with rage and wants to confront or attack the entity labeled at index 0.

This label, placed on Kevin Hart, represents the restraining force. It could be a friend, a sense of responsibility, social norms, or any practical reason that prevents the character at index 1 from acting on their impulse.

Woman-holding-man.image_description: This meme, known as 'Kevin Hart Holding Woman Back,' originates from the parody TV show 'Real Husbands of Hollywood.' It features Kevin Hart restraining a woman (Tanee McCall) who is angrily trying to confront another woman. The meme is used to represent a strong urge to confront a problem or person, but being held back by a restraining force, such as reason, social norms, or a practical obstacle.

Cute-cat-hehe-and-not-hehe.name: Cute-cat-hehe-and-not-hehe

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the angry kitten ("not hehe"). It is used to label something the creator dislikes, disapproves of, or finds frustrating, representing the negative side of the comparison.
This text box is placed next to the happy kitten ("hehe"). It is used to label something the creator likes, approves of, or finds amusing, representing the positive or preferred option.

Cute-cat-hehe-and-not-hehe.image_description: This is a two-panel reaction meme featuring a small, white and grey kitten. In the top panel, the kitten has a cute, slightly smiling expression with the caption "hehe," indicating approval or amusement. In the bottom panel, the same kitten has an angry, scowling expression with the caption "not hehe," indicating disapproval or annoyance. The meme is used to contrast something positive or desirable with something negative or undesirable, similar to the Drakeposting format.
Cute-cat-hehe-and-not-hehe.display_name: Cute cat hehe and not hehe

Patrick-Star-and-Man-Ray.name: Patrick-Star-and-Man-Ray

text_options.description: This panel shows the character Man Ray initiating an action. Text here usually represents the person or entity giving a task or instruction.
This panel shows Patrick Star, who is about to receive the instruction. Text here represents the person or group who will misunderstand the task.
A continuation of the setup, showing Patrick receiving the wallet. This area is often unlabeled in the meme.
Man Ray's hopeful or expectant expression. Text here represents the initial assumption that the instruction was understood.
Patrick returning the wallet. Text here represents the incorrect action or misunderstanding of the person performing the task.
Man Ray's frustrated reaction. Text here represents the exasperation of the instructor upon seeing the failure.
Patrick's smug expression, oblivious to his mistake. Text here represents the cluelessness of the person who failed the task.

The punchline panel showing Patrick's ID. The name "PATRICK STAR" is typically replaced with a label for a person, group, or idea being mocked, implying their identity is the reason for their incompetence.

Patrick-Star-and-Man-Ray.image_description: This multi-panel meme, known as "Patrick's Wallet," originates from the show SpongeBob SquarePants. It depicts the villain Man Ray trying to teach the dim-witted Patrick Star how to be evil by having him steal his wallet, but Patrick keeps returning it, frustrating Man Ray. The format is used to represent a frustrating cycle where one party (Patrick) fails to understand a simple instruction from another (Man Ray), with the final panel revealing an identity card that serves as a punchline to explain the incompetence.

Red-String.name: Red-String

text_options.description: The text here typically labels the person Charlie is explaining his theory to, or represents a simple, often mundane, question or statement from a skeptical listener. This creates a humorous contrast with the frantic and complex explanation being delivered by Charlie.

This area is for the text representing Charlie's frantic, elaborate explanation. It's typically a long block of text detailing a complex conspiracy theory, a niche obsession, or an attempt to connect seemingly unrelated events, which is the core of the meme's humor.

Red-String.image_description: A man, Charlie Kelly from 'It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia,' stands wild-eyed before a 'conspiracy board' covered in documents connected by red string. He appears to be frantically explaining a complex theory, gesturing with a cigarette in hand. This meme format is used to humorously depict someone passionately explaining a convoluted idea, a wild conspiracy theory, or an obsession with a particular topic.

Bronze-Medal.name: Bronze-Medal

text_options.description: This area covers the final punchline panel, showing the athlete on the third-place podium. Text here typically describes the minor or mediocre achievement that is being celebrated with excessive pride, providing the context for the joke.

This box highlights the initial celebratory actions of the athlete receiving and biting his medal. Text placed here usually identifies the person or group who is celebrating disproportionately to their actual achievement, setting up the subject of the meme's punchline.

Bronze-Medal.image_description: This six-panel comic meme, known as '3rd Place Celebration' or 'Bronze Medalist,' illustrates an athlete celebrating his third-place finish with the fervor of a first-place champion. The first five panels show him receiving his medal, kissing a woman, and celebrating wildly, while the final panel reveals he is on the third-place podium, confusing the actual first and second-place winners. The meme is used to satirize over-the-top celebrations for minor achievements or to express ironic pride in a small personal victory.

Borat-i-go-to-america.name: Borat-i-go-to-america

text_options.description: This area, often covering Borat's body, is where the label for the person or entity reacting is placed. This text identifies who is having the overly enthusiastic response to the situation described in the top panel.
The top portion of the image is used to set up the context or describe a situation. The text here presents a scenario that serves as the premise for Borat's enthusiastic reaction below.

Borat-i-go-to-america.image_description: This meme features the character Borat Sagdiyev, played by Sacha Baron Cohen, from the 2006 mockumentary film "Borat." The image shows Borat in his supposed home village in Kazakhstan, looking ecstatic and shouting with joy. This format is typically used as a two-part reaction meme to express overwhelming or unexpected enthusiasm for a situation that might otherwise seem mundane or unexciting.

iceberg-levels-tiers.name: iceberg-levels-tiers

text_options.description: This is the final and deepest layer, often called the 'bottom of the iceberg' or 'the void'. Text here represents the most profound, esoteric, or reality-altering secrets of a topic, signifying a state of ultimate enlightenment or complete detachment from reality, as symbolized by the glowing cosmic being.

Located in the abyss below the iceberg, this level is for extremely obscure, bizarre, or nonsensical theories that are almost completely unknown. The corresponding image of a beluga whale adds a surreal and mysterious tone to the incomprehensible nature of the information found at this depth.

This layer, deep in the dark water, is for very obscure, often unsettling or conspiratorial information. Text here represents the 'point of no return' for someone researching a topic, where the knowledge becomes strange and potentially disturbing, reflected by the haggard character with glowing eyes.

Situated further down the submerged part of the iceberg, this text box is for niche facts and theories that are known only to a small, dedicated community. The information here is significantly more obscure than the levels above.

This section, well below the waterline, is for information that requires dedicated interest to discover. The text typically includes lesser-known facts, fan theories, or early lore, indicating a deeper dive into the subject matter, as the corresponding character becomes more unkempt.

This is the first layer submerged beneath the water's surface. Text here represents information that is not immediately obvious but is still relatively easy to find for those who are curious. It marks the transition from casual knowledge to more specialized information.

This box is placed on the visible tip of the iceberg. Text here represents the most common, widely-known, and surface-level information about a topic. It's what virtually everyone, including casual observers, would know.

Positioned in the sky above the iceberg, this is the highest and most superficial level. The text here represents the most basic, entry-level, or 'normie' understanding of a topic, often what someone might assume without any real knowledge.

iceberg-levels-tiers.image_description: This meme format, known as the "Iceberg Chart" or "Iceberg Tiers," illustrates a hierarchy of knowledge about a specific topic. The image displays an iceberg with multiple layers, from the sky above to the deep, dark ocean below, with corresponding characters on the right that degrade and then transcend. The top layers represent common, surface-level information, while deeper layers contain progressively more obscure, niche, or disturbing facts and theories, showing how one's understanding (and sanity) changes as they delve into a subject.

minions.name: minions

text_options.description: The bottom text box, placed below the Minion, typically contains the punchline or a concluding statement that complements the top text. It completes the joke or observation, following the classic top-text/bottom-text meme structure. For example, if the top text is a relatable problem, the bottom text might offer a humorous solution or reaction.

The top text box, positioned above the Minion's head, serves as the setup for the joke or the main statement of the meme. This text is usually a relatable observation, a complaint about daily life, or a general statement that the Minion's cheerful demeanor humorously contrasts or supports.

minions.image_description: This image features a Minion, a popular character from the 'Despicable Me' film series. Minion memes are a widespread internet phenomenon, often associated with content shared on Facebook by older demographics, sometimes referred to as 'boomer humor.' The meme format typically combines an image of a cheerful Minion with relatable, often simplistic or wholesome, text about everyday life, frustrations, or inspirational quotes.

startrek.name: startrek

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, serving as the punchline. The text here provides a frustrating, illogical, or absurd answer to the question or statement presented in the top panel. It aligns with Picard's exasperated gesture, emphasizing the ridiculousness of the response.

This is the top text area, which sets up the meme's premise. It typically contains a question or statement expressing disbelief or annoyance, often starting with phrases like 'Why the fuck...' or 'How come...' to highlight a frustrating or illogical situation.

startrek.image_description: This meme features Captain Jean-Luc Picard from 'Star Trek: The Next Generation,' played by Patrick Stewart, on the bridge of the USS Enterprise. With an exasperated expression and an open-handed gesture, he appears to be questioning something incredulously. Known as the 'Annoyed Picard' or 'Why The F*ck' meme, it's a two-panel format used to express frustration with illogical or annoying situations. The top panel poses a question about a perplexing scenario, and the bottom panel delivers a nonsensical or frustrating answer.

So-No-Head.name: So-No-Head

text_options.description: This label corresponds to the man who is walking and then tripping. The text here identifies the subject of the meme—the person, group, or entity that gets distracted and subsequently fails or suffers a setback.

This text label, positioned at the top, typically describes the distraction or the appealing but ultimately detrimental thing that captures the man's attention, causing him to trip. It represents the temptation that leads to the downfall.

So-No-Head.image_description: This two-panel meme format shows a man walking on a sidewalk while looking at his phone, and in the next panel, he is seen tripping and falling. This meme is a variation of the "Distracted Boyfriend" format, used to illustrate how a person or entity gets sidetracked by a distraction (the phone) and suffers an immediate, negative consequence (tripping). The format humorously depicts failure due to a lack of focus on a more important task.

trap-card.name: trap-card

text_options.description: This is the card's effect description box. In the meme, this area is used to explain the consequences or the details of the "trap" that has been sprung, often serving as the punchline that elaborates on the situation named at the top.
This is the card's name field. In the meme, this text is used to label the specific "trap" or clever plan that the opponent has just fallen for, setting the context for the punchline.

trap-card.image_description: This meme template features a blank Yu-Gi-Oh! Trap Card, recognizable by its distinct purple border and the text "[TRAP CARD]". Originating from the popular anime and card game, the phrase "You've activated my trap card!" is used when a character turns the tables on an opponent. In meme culture, this template is used to humorously declare that someone has fallen into a predictable situation or argument, with the user revealing their clever counter-move or observation.

I-didnt-hear-no-bell.name: I-didnt-hear-no-bell

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Randy Marsh's body and represents his defiant and often illogical response or outburst to the situation described above. It's the punchline of the meme, frequently using the original quote, "I thought this was America!", or a variation of it to express indignant surprise.

This text box is located at the top of the image and sets up the scenario. It typically describes a rule, a statement, or an action that the character (Randy) finds objectionable, prompting his aggressive reaction in the panel below.

I-didnt-hear-no-bell.image_description: This meme features Randy Marsh from the animated show South Park, looking disheveled and beaten up after a fight at a baseball game. The image captures his defiant and indignant expression, famously associated with his line, "I thought this was America!". This meme is used to express over-the-top outrage or disbelief when someone's perceived freedoms or expectations are challenged, often in a trivial or absurd context.

dad-legend.name: dad-legend

text_options.description: This speech bubble is associated with the young boy playing on the floor. The text here usually represents an even more simplistic, childish, or absurd question, adding another layer of humorous contrast to the father's serious demeanor and the daughter's main question.

This large text box, placed over the father, serves as the setup for the meme. It typically describes the father's significant accomplishments or the heavy responsibilities he has at a certain age, establishing him as a capable and mature adult from a previous generation (e.g., "My dad at my age: owned a house, had two kids").

This speech bubble, coming from the daughter, delivers the punchline of the meme. The text is a question that represents a modern, often trivial, "first-world problem" or a lack of basic skills, which contrasts humorously with the competence and serious responsibilities of the father established in box 1 (e.g., "Dad, how do I rotate a PDF?").

dad-legend.image_description: This meme format, known as "My Parents At Age 29" or "Dad, How Do I...", uses a vintage illustration of a seemingly stressed father with his two children to highlight a humorous generational gap. The meme contrasts the perceived significant accomplishments and responsibilities of the father's generation with the often trivial, modern-day problems or lack of basic life skills of the current generation, represented by the children. The humor comes from the stark difference between the father's situation and the questions his children ask.

Im-in-Danger--blank-place-above.name: Im-in-Danger--blank-place-above

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, the subtitle "(chuckles) I'm in danger." It represents the subject's delayed realization of the peril they are in, which is described in the top caption.

A blank caption area at the top of the image where users add text. This text sets up a scenario where a person or entity is blissfully unaware of an impending problem or danger, leading to the reaction shown by Ralph.

Im-in-Danger--blank-place-above.image_description: This meme features Ralph Wiggum from 'The Simpsons' sitting alone on a school bus. He has a look of dawning realization and says, "(chuckles) I'm in danger." The meme is used to humorously express the moment someone realizes they are in a precarious, awkward, or threatening situation, often one they have naively entered.
Im-in-Danger--blank-place-above.display_name: Im in Danger  blank place above

death-battle.name: death-battle

text_options.description: This text box is for the name of the second combatant, placed directly below their corresponding image on the right. It serves to identify one of the two opposing forces in the hypothetical 'Death Battle' scenario.

This text box is for the name of the first combatant, placed directly below their corresponding image on the left. It identifies the character or concept that will be pitted against the one on the right, setting up the 'versus' dynamic of the meme.

death-battle.image_description: This meme template originates from the popular web series 'Death Battle,' which pits fictional characters against each other in a fight to the death. The format features two empty frames side-by-side, separated by 'VS,' under the show's gritty, blood-splattered title. Users place images of two opposing characters or concepts into the frames and label them below to create hypothetical matchups for debate or comedic effect.

Noble.name: Noble

text_options.description: The bottom text describes the person, action, or opinion being judged by the figures in the image. It's the setup for the punchline, presenting something that the meme creator finds inferior, cringeworthy, or unsophisticated.

The top text, often optional, labels the group or entity that is doing the judging. This text identifies who the Volturi are representing in the context of the meme, such as "People who read the book" judging those who only saw the movie.

Noble.image_description: This meme features the Volturi, a coven of ancient and powerful vampires from the movie "The Twilight Saga: New Moon." The characters, Aro (center), Caius (left), and Marcus (right), are depicted looking down with a judgmental or condescending expression. The meme is used to represent a group or individual looking down on someone else's actions, choices, or tastes with an air of superiority and disapproval.

Soldiers-hold-up-society.name: Soldiers-hold-up-society

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the struggling soldiers. It labels the person, group, or concept that is making the sacrifice or doing the unappreciated hard work that supports the situation depicted above. This is the foundational element of the meme's comparison.

This text box is placed over the idyllic scene with the family. It labels the beneficiary, the positive outcome, or the seemingly effortless situation that is being supported by the group below. This text provides the crucial contrast to the sacrifice shown in the bottom half.

Soldiers-hold-up-society.image_description: This meme, often called "Society" or "Civilization is Held Up by Soldiers," is an illustration contrasting a peaceful, idyllic scene with the brutal reality supporting it. The top half shows a family enjoying a beautiful day on a grassy cliff, representing a positive outcome or a privileged group. The bottom half reveals that this cliff is being held up by a mass of struggling soldiers in a bloody battle, symbolizing the unseen sacrifice, hard work, or unpleasant foundation that makes the pleasant surface reality possible. The meme is used to highlight the unacknowledged efforts that support a seemingly effortless or positive situation.

Worst-mistake-of-my-life.name: Worst-mistake-of-my-life

text_options.description: Text in this area labels Peter Griffin, representing the person or entity trying to escape or avoid the thing chasing them.
Text here labels the biplane, symbolizing the overwhelming problem, persistent person, or unavoidable responsibility that is pursuing the subject labeled on Peter.

Worst-mistake-of-my-life.image_description: This meme features Peter Griffin from the animated show 'Family Guy' running frantically away from a biplane, which is a parody of a famous scene from the movie 'North by Northwest'. The format is used to represent a person (Peter) desperately trying to escape or avoid a persistent problem, person, or responsibility (the plane). The humor lies in the relatable feeling of being pursued by something overwhelming.

Distracted-boyfriend.name: Distracted-boyfriend

text_options.description: Text placed on the girlfriend in the light blue top represents the current, sensible, or responsible option that is being neglected. It's what the subject already has or should be focused on.

Text placed on the man represents the subject of the meme—the person, group, or entity being tempted or making a poor choice. This character connects the existing responsibility with the new temptation.
Text placed on the woman in the red dress represents the new, attractive, or distracting object of desire. This is the temptation that is leading the subject astray and often serves as the punchline.

Distracted-boyfriend.image_description: This is the "Distracted Boyfriend" meme, a popular stock photo showing a man in a plaid shirt looking admiringly at a passing woman in a red dress, while his own girlfriend looks at him in disgust. The man represents a person or entity, his girlfriend represents a current responsibility or choice, and the woman in red represents a new, tempting alternative. This meme format is used to humorously illustrate situations of temptation, disloyalty, or choosing a new, often worse, option over an existing one.

bart-hitting-homer-with-a-chair.name: bart-hitting-homer-with-a-chair

text_options.description: This text, placed on Bart Simpson, represents the disruptive force or sudden, unwelcome event. It is typically a piece of bad news, a sudden responsibility, or a negative realization that is about to shatter the peace.

This text, placed on Homer Simpson in the bath, represents a person, group, or concept in a state of blissful ignorance or contentment. They are completely unaware of the impending negative event represented by Bart.

bart-hitting-homer-with-a-chair.image_description: This meme, known as "Bart Hits Homer with a Chair," originates from the animated series The Simpsons. It depicts Bart Simpson menacingly holding a chair over his unsuspecting father, Homer, who is relaxing in a bathtub. The format is used to represent a peaceful or oblivious state (Homer) being abruptly and violently interrupted by an unexpected, often negative, event or realization (Bart with the chair).
bart-hitting-homer-with-a-chair.display_name: bart hitting homer with a chair

mr-krabs-money.name: mr-krabs-money

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the large pile of money. It typically labels the source of the profit, such as customers, a specific event, or a product that is being exploited for financial gain.

This text box is placed above Mr. Krabs and serves as the label for the greedy entity. This is where the name of the company, person, or group that is benefiting financially is written, casting them in the role of the money-obsessed Mr. Krabs.

mr-krabs-money.image_description: An image from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants depicting the character Mr. Krabs, a red crab, surrounded by a massive pile of money. He is holding up a single dollar bill with a greedy expression. This meme is used to represent a person, company, or entity that is profiting immensely, often at the expense of others, highlighting their greed and love for money.

Change-My-Mind-tilt-corrected.name: Change-My-Mind-tilt-corrected

text_options.description: This area contains the fixed, iconic phrase of the meme, "CHANGE MY MIND." This text serves as the punchline and a direct challenge to the viewer, inviting them to debate the statement presented above it. Its presence is essential for the meme's format and recognizable setup.

This is the main editable area of the meme template. Users insert a controversial, unpopular, or humorous opinion here. The statement is presented as a debatable topic, setting the stage for the challenge issued by the text below.

Change-My-Mind-tilt-corrected.image_description: This meme, known as "Steven Crowder's Change My Mind Campus Sign," features conservative commentator Steven Crowder sitting at a table outdoors with a sign inviting debate. The original sign had a controversial statement followed by the phrase "CHANGE MY MIND." The format is widely used as an exploitable template where users replace the original statement with their own controversial, humorous, or mundane opinions, challenging others to argue against them.

Dr-Evil-Quotes.name: Dr-Evil-Quotes

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which typically contains the punchline or the specific word or phrase that Dr. Evil is sarcastically quoting. This is the core of the joke, representing the dubious or ironic statement being highlighted.

The top text, which serves as the setup or provides context for the punchline below. It establishes the situation or the initial part of the statement that will be ironically completed or emphasized by the text in the bottom section.

Dr-Evil-Quotes.image_description: This meme features the character Dr. Evil from the Austin Powers film series, identifiable by his bald head, grey suit, and a scar over his right eye. He is making "air quotes" with both hands, a gesture used to express sarcasm, skepticism, or to quote something ironically. The meme format, known as "Dr. Evil Air Quotes," leverages this gesture to mock or cast doubt on a statement, idea, or claim by placing it within the quoted text.

Ryan-Beckford.name: Ryan-Beckford

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the toy laptop and the user's hands. It typically describes the simple, unimpressive, or mundane action that the person is performing, which serves as the setup for the joke. For example, 'Me after centering a div' or 'When I connect to the public Wi-Fi without the tutorial'.

This text box is positioned at the top of the image, over the Matrix-style code. It represents the punchline, describing the person's exaggerated sense of accomplishment or how they perceive themselves after performing the simple task mentioned below. It often labels the subject as a 'hacker' or a tech genius, creating a humorous contrast with the triviality of their actual action.

Ryan-Beckford.image_description: This meme, often called "Hackerman," features a young man with pink sunglasses smirking at a toy laptop against a background of green cascading code from the movie *The Matrix*. The image humorously juxtaposes the character's smug, expert-like expression and the high-tech background with the reality of performing a very simple or mundane computer task. It's used to poke fun at people who feel like master hackers after accomplishing a basic tech-related action, such as opening the inspect element tool in a browser or installing a program.

Orange-Jacket-Guy.name: Orange-Jacket-Guy

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the image of Drake smiling and pointing in approval. The text here represents the preferred, superior, or desired option in the comparison.
This text box is placed next to the image of Drake looking away with a gesture of rejection. The text here represents the disliked, inferior, or rejected option.

Orange-Jacket-Guy.image_description: This is the "Drakeposting" meme format, featuring two stills of the rapper Drake from his "Hotline Bling" music video. In the top panel, Drake looks displeased and holds up a hand in rejection, while in the bottom panel, he smiles and points in approval. The meme is used to show a strong preference for one thing (bottom) over another (top), creating a simple and widely understood visual for approval versus disapproval.

Look-Son.name: Look-Son

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the son. It represents the son's internal thoughts or a label for his perspective, which is typically something that shows his disinterest, a non-sequitur, or a completely different priority, contrasting sharply with what the father is pointing at.

This text box is placed in the area the father is pointing towards. It is used to label the object, person, or concept that the father is excitedly trying to show his son. This text establishes the setup for the meme's punchline.

Look-Son.image_description: This meme, known as "Father and Son" or "Dad Pointing," features a vintage black-and-white photo of a father enthusiastically pointing at something off-screen while his son looks on with a bored or unimpressed expression. The format is used to create a humorous contrast between the father's excitement for a particular subject and the son's completely unrelated, mundane, or indifferent thoughts. It often highlights generational gaps, differing interests, or a general disconnect between two perspectives.

Hitler-Downfall.name: Hitler-Downfall

text_options.description: This bottom area is where the fake subtitles are placed in the meme. The text here represents the core of the rant, expressing extreme frustration or disappointment about a specific, often trivial, topic. It serves as the punchline, detailing the specific grievance that triggers the outburst.

The top of the image is typically used for a title or a caption that sets up the context for the meme. This text introduces the situation or the subject that Hitler is about to become enraged over, providing the premise for the joke.

Hitler-Downfall.image_description: This meme features a still of actor Bruno Ganz as Adolf Hitler from the 2004 film 'Downfall' (Der Untergang). The image captures a moment of intense rage and frustration, with Hitler shouting and gesturing angrily. This scene is famously used in parody videos where the original German dialogue is replaced with humorous English subtitles about trivial, modern-day frustrations, creating a stark contrast between the dramatic visuals and the mundane topic of the rant.

Hide-the-pain-harold.name: Hide-the-pain-harold

text_options.description: The bottom panel shows Harold looking directly at the camera with his signature pained smile. The text here typically represents the punchline or the internal monologue of someone trying to pretend everything is okay after the event described in the top panel.

The top panel sets up the scenario. The text here usually describes a painful, awkward, or unfortunate situation. Harold is looking at his laptop, implying he has just encountered this information online.

Hide-the-pain-harold.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character known as 'Hide the Pain Harold,' an older man whose facial expression conveys suppressed pain and discomfort behind a forced smile. He is sitting at a desk with a laptop and a mug. The meme is used to represent situations where someone is trying to appear fine on the outside while dealing with internal suffering, awkwardness, or a distressing realization.

dave-chappelle-yall-got-any-more-of-crac.name: dave-chappelle-yall-got-any-more-of-crackhead

text_options.description: The bottom text, located below the image, serves as the punchline. It names the specific, often trivial or humorous, thing that the person is craving, creating a comedic contrast with the character's desperate appearance.
The top text, positioned above the image, sets up the joke. It typically reads, "Y'all got any more of that..." or a similar phrase, establishing the theme of intense need and addiction.

dave-chappelle-yall-got-any-more-of-crac.image_description: This meme features comedian Dave Chappelle as his character Tyrone Biggums from "Chappelle's Show." The character, a crack addict, is shown looking up with an expression of intense craving while scratching his neck. The meme format, known as "Y'all Got Any More of That," is used to humorously express a desperate desire or addiction to something, often mundane or non-addictive items like a TV show, a food, or a video game.
dave-chappelle-yall-got-any-more-of-crac.display_name: dave chappelle yall got any more of crackhead

Aliens-Guy.name: Aliens-Guy

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline of the meme. It almost invariably reads "Aliens," serving as the absurd and conspiratorial explanation for the situation described in the top text.
The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically poses a question about a mysterious or unexplainable event, which can range from a historical enigma to a mundane personal inconvenience.

Aliens-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Ancient Aliens" or "Giorgio A. Tsoukalos," features a still of the television personality from the History Channel show of the same name. He is depicted with wild hair and gesturing with his hands as if explaining a complex theory. The meme is used to humorously propose outlandish, pseudoscientific explanations for everyday or mysterious phenomena by attributing them to extraterrestrial involvement. The punchline is almost always a variation of "Aliens."

spongebob-panic-inside.name: spongebob-panic-inside

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, famously reading "Ight Imma Head Out" (a slang spelling of "Alright, I'm going to head out"). This phrase is the declaration of leaving the situation described in the top text box, directly corresponding to SpongeBob's action of getting up to leave.

The top text box is used to set up the context or describe the situation that the user wants to escape from. This text provides the reason for wanting to leave, making SpongeBob's subsequent action of "heading out" a relatable and humorous reaction.

spongebob-panic-inside.image_description: This meme, known as "Ight Imma Head Out" or "SpongeBob Fading," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series. He is shown getting up from his chair, with a transparent, faded overlay creating a motion blur effect as if he is disappearing. The meme is used to humorously express a desire to leave an awkward, uncomfortable, or undesirable situation.

Trumpet-Boy.name: Trumpet-Boy

text_options.description: The text here labels the 'Trumpet Boy'. It represents the person, group, or concept that is loudly, enthusiastically, and often annoyingly promoting something or making its presence known.
This text labels the annoyed girl. It represents the person, group, or entity that is being bothered by, trying to ignore, or is the unwilling audience of the subject labeled on the boy.

Trumpet-Boy.image_description: This meme, known as 'Trumpet Boy' or 'Following Trumpet Boy', shows a boy playing a trumpet while walking behind a girl who is covering her ears in annoyance. The meme is used to represent a dynamic where one entity (the boy) is obnoxiously and persistently promoting or doing something. The other entity (the girl) represents an unwilling, annoyed audience trying to ignore the first.

Eric-Andre-Let-Me-In-blank.name: Eric-Andre-Let-Me-In-blank

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the bottom panel where Eric Andre is screaming. The text here describes the negative, painful, or unexpected outcome of the situation set up in the top panel. It serves as the punchline, revealing the disastrous consequences of the initial desire.

This text box is on the top panel where Eric Andre is shouting at the gate. The text here typically labels the gate or the general scene with the name of a group, place, or situation that someone desperately wants to join or be a part of.

Eric-Andre-Let-Me-In-blank.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Let Me In," features comedian Eric Andre from "The Eric Andre Show." In the top panel, he desperately shouts at a closed gate, representing a strong desire to access or participate in something. The bottom panel shows him screaming in apparent agony, symbolizing the negative or painful consequences that result from either gaining that access or being rejected. The meme is typically used to illustrate situations where getting what you want leads to a disastrous outcome, or the attempt itself is painful.
Eric-Andre-Let-Me-In-blank.display_name: Eric Andre Let Me In blank

High-Expectations-Asian-Father.name: High-Expectations-Asian-Father

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline, representing the father's critical and unimpressed reaction to the achievement mentioned above. This text typically downplays the accomplishment and sets an even higher, often absurd, standard (e.g., "Why not A+?").

The top text box sets up the premise of the meme, usually stating an achievement or situation from the perspective of the child. This is often something that would be considered a major success by most standards (e.g., "Gets an A on test").

High-Expectations-Asian-Father.image_description: This meme is known as "High Expectations Asian Father," an advice animal image macro featuring a stern-looking older Asian man. The format is used to humorously portray the stereotype of a demanding parent who holds their children to impossibly high standards, particularly in academics and career choices. The humor arises from the contrast between a child's significant accomplishment and the father's unimpressed or critical response.

Pink-Blob-In-the-Box.name: Pink-Blob-In-the-Box

text_options.description: Located under the third panel, this text typically labels the pink blob itself. It represents the person, feeling, or habit that is being suppressed after a bad experience.

This label points to the hand pushing the blob. Text here identifies the negative experience, external force, or reason that causes the person to retreat and suppress the part of themselves that they let out.

Positioned under the second panel where the blob is emerging, this text describes the act of opening up or trying something new. It represents the moment of hope or exploration before the negative event occurs.
Located under the first panel, this text describes the initial state of the person or subject. It represents the comfort zone or the suppressed state before the attempt to change or open up.
