Pink-Blob-In-the-Box.image_description: A four-panel comic meme by artist Shen Comix (Owlturd) showing a cute pink blob being forced back into a box. The blob starts content in its box, emerges happily, is then violently shoved back in by a hand, and ends up back in the box with the caption 'NEVER AGAIN.' The meme illustrates the cycle of trying something new or opening up, having a negative experience, and retreating back into one's comfort zone, vowing not to repeat it.

Satisfaction.name: Satisfaction

text_options.description: The text in the bottom box typically describes the situation or action that is causing the immense feeling of satisfaction. This is the setup for the punchline, providing the context for the character's blissful reaction.

The text in the top box often serves as a title or a direct expression of the feeling, such as 'MFW' (My Face When) or a short phrase summarizing the context. It reinforces the emotion shown in the image, though this area is sometimes left blank.

Satisfaction.image_description: This meme, known as 'Feels Good Man' or simply 'Feels Good', is a simple line drawing of a bald man with a serene, blissful expression. He is touching his face with both hands, eyes closed, conveying a powerful sense of satisfaction, contentment, or relief. The meme is used to express a feeling of pure, unadulterated pleasure or perfection in response to a particular situation.

Regular-Show.name: Regular-Show

text_options.description: This label is placed on the flyer held by Mordecai. It represents a controversial opinion, a strong argument, or an unavoidable truth that is being forcefully presented to the other character.
This label is on the man in the suit lying on the ground. It represents the person, group, or entity that is ignoring or unwilling to accept the information presented on the flyer (label 0).

Regular-Show.image_description: This meme format, originating from the animated series 'Regular Show,' features characters Mordecai (a blue jay) and Rigby (a raccoon). In the first panel, Mordecai attempts to hand a flyer to a man in a suit who walks past, ignoring him. The second panel shows the man lying on the ground as Mordecai places the flyer on his chest. This meme is used to humorously depict someone forcefully imposing their opinion, argument, or unwanted information on an unwilling or oblivious person.

Its-a-trap.name: Its-a-trap

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the image, this text box contains the punchline, which is almost always the character's iconic quote, "IT'S A TRAP!". This text serves as the direct reaction to the setup described in the top text, revealing the hidden catch or danger.
Positioned at the top of the image, this text typically describes a situation or offer that seems appealing, innocent, or too good to be true. It serves as the setup for the punchline below.

Its-a-trap.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of Admiral Ackbar, a Mon Calamari character from the film Star Wars: Return of the Jedi. The image captures him in a moment of sudden, horrified realization inside a starship cockpit. This meme is famously known as "It's a Trap!" and is used to humorously warn others of a suspected trick, deception, or an undesirable situation that seems too good to be true.

Now-thats-a-name-I-havent-heard-since.name: Now-thats-a-name-I-havent-heard-since

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over Obi-Wan's chest, typically contains the punchline. It often directly quotes the line "Now that's a name I've not heard in a long time" or a variation of it, reacting to the subject mentioned in the top text.
The top text serves as the setup for the meme. It usually introduces a person, object, or concept from the past that has been largely forgotten, prompting Obi-Wan's nostalgic reaction.

Now-thats-a-name-I-havent-heard-since.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Obi-Wan Kenobi, played by Alec Guinness, from the original Star Wars trilogy. He has a pensive and distant look, recalling a memory. The meme, often captioned with his line "Now that's a name I've not heard in a long time," is used to express nostalgia or surprise when an old, once-popular topic, person, or thing is mentioned after a long period of obscurity.
Now-thats-a-name-I-havent-heard-since.display_name: Now thats a name I havent heard since

Anakin-Padme-Meme.name: Anakin-Padme-Meme

text_options.description: This panel contains Padmé's reaction to Anakin's stare or dark statement. The text is often a repetition of her earlier question but now filled with dawning horror or confusion, such as '...Right?'. Her expression of concern is the final punchline.

This panel is often left blank, as Anakin's silent, intense stare serves as the punchline or the unsettling clarification. Sometimes, it contains a short, blunt, or dark response that directly contradicts the optimism of the previous panel.
This panel shows Padmé's cheerful and optimistic response to the initial statement. The text here is often a question seeking positive confirmation, like the titular 'For the better, right?'.
This panel contains the initial statement or setup for the conversation, usually spoken by Anakin. It's a neutral or seemingly innocuous statement that prompts Padmé's response.

Anakin-Padme-Meme.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as 'For the Better, Right?', features Anakin Skywalker and Padmé Amidala from *Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones*. The format depicts a conversation where an optimistic statement is met with a deadpan, ominous clarification, causing a dramatic shift in mood from cheerful to concerned. This meme is widely used to highlight a grim or unsettling reality hidden behind a seemingly positive idea, playing on the dramatic irony of Anakin's eventual turn to the dark side.

Looks-Good-To-Me.name: Looks-Good-To-Me

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline, representing the out-of-touch person's awkward and failed attempt to use slang or relate to the group. It is often a variation of the iconic line from the scene, 'How do you do, fellow kids?'

The top text sets up the context, identifying the person or entity that is trying to fit in with a particular group or trend. It establishes who is making the awkward attempt to seem 'cool' or 'in the know'.

Looks-Good-To-Me.image_description: This meme, known as 'How Do You Do, Fellow Kids?', features actor Steve Buscemi from a scene in the TV show '30 Rock'. In the scene, his character is a private investigator awkwardly attempting to blend in with high school students. The meme is used to satirize or mock individuals, corporations, or older people who try to appear trendy, young, or part of a subculture they clearly don't understand, resulting in a cringeworthy failure.

sinking-skeleton.name: sinking-skeleton

text_options.description: Placed on the skeleton at the bottom of the water, this text represents something completely forgotten, obsolete, or long-abandoned. It is the final and most extreme stage of neglect in the meme's hierarchy.
This label is on the drowning child, representing an entity, task, or interest that is being actively neglected, struggling, or is in desperate need of attention while another is favored.

Positioned over the mother and the happy child she is holding, this text identifies the favored person, object, or concept that is receiving all the positive attention, causing the neglect of the others.

sinking-skeleton.image_description: This three-panel meme format illustrates a hierarchy of neglect and prioritization. The top panel shows a mother happily playing with one child while another struggles to stay afloat, representing a favored option and a neglected one. The bottom panel adds a skeleton sitting in a chair underwater, symbolizing something that has been completely forgotten or is long obsolete. The meme is used to humorously compare how attention is distributed between three different subjects, from being cherished to being ignored to being utterly abandoned.

Smash-Bros.name: Smash-Bros

text_options.description: This large, central area is a placeholder where an image of the subject of the meme is superimposed. This could be a person, an animal, an inanimate object, or an abstract concept that is being humorously introduced as a new 'challenger'.

This text box is where the name of the character or subject shown in area 0 is written. It completes the iconic phrase "... Joins the Battle!", solidifying the parody of a Super Smash Bros. character announcement.

Smash-Bros.image_description: This meme template originates from the character reveal splash screens in the Nintendo fighting game series, Super Smash Bros. The format, featuring an orange background and a black ink-like splash, announces a new character with the text "[Name] Joins the Battle!". Culturally, this meme is used to humorously announce the unexpected arrival or inclusion of a person, object, or concept into any given situation, treating it with the same dramatic weight as a new video game fighter.

Roblox-Error-Message.name: Roblox-Error-Message

text_options.description: This is the punchline or the response field. The text here is typically a short, direct, and often humorous or absurd answer to the setup in the panel above. Its position directly above the 'OK' button implies it's a final, unchangeable statement.
This is the setup panel of the meme. Text here usually poses a question, describes a situation, or makes a statement that sets the context for the punchline below.

Roblox-Error-Message.image_description: This meme format, often called "OK," features a simple, generic dialog box with two text fields and an "OK" button. It's used to create a simple cause-and-effect or question-and-answer joke. The top panel presents a situation, statement, or question, while the bottom panel delivers a blunt, often humorous or unexpected response, which the user is forced to accept by clicking "OK."

give-me.name: give-me

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the absurd, illogical, or outrageous statement that the character in the image is reacting to. It serves as the setup or the premise that prompts the incredulous response.

Located at the top, this text represents the voice of the man in the painting, expressing his disbelief and demanding an explanation. It often contains phrases like "Explain this," "Bro, are you serious?", or a direct question challenging the nonsensical statement presented below.

give-me.image_description: This meme, from the 1844 painting "The Village Politicians," features a man in historical attire pointing at his open palm with an expression of disbelief. Known as "Explain This" or "Bro, are you serious?", the meme is used to demand an explanation for a statement or situation that is absurd, illogical, or nonsensical. The man's gesture and expression perfectly capture the feeling of incredulity when confronted with something utterly baseless.

Confused-Travolta.name: Confused-Travolta

text_options.description: Text in the bottom region typically describes the action or situation that leads to the confusion. It sets the stage for why the subject (represented by Travolta) is bewildered, such as 'When I enter a room and forget why I came in' or 'Me looking for the motivation to start my work'.

Text placed in the top region often acts as a caption or a title for the scenario. It can be a direct question that prompts the confusion, like 'Where did everybody go?', or a statement that establishes the context for the bewilderment shown in the image.

Confused-Travolta.image_description: This meme, known as 'Confused Travolta' or 'Lost Travolta,' features actor John Travolta as his character Vincent Vega from the 1994 film Pulp Fiction. In the scene, he looks around a room with a bewildered and lost expression, shrugging with his hands out. The meme, often used as a GIF, perfectly captures a feeling of confusion, being lost, or searching for something that isn't there, making it a popular reaction to perplexing situations or questions.

Addicts-before-and-after.name: Addicts-before-and-after

text_options.description: This text box serves as the punchline of the meme. The user places the name of a hobby, activity, or interest here (e.g., "Gaming," "Anime," "Coffee"). This label humorously frames the chosen interest as an "addiction" that, unlike the real drugs in the other panels, leads to happiness and a positive transformation.

Addicts-before-and-after.image_description: This is a four-panel "Addicts Before and After" meme that contrasts the negative effects of hard drugs with a positive transformation. The first three panels show mugshots depicting the physical decline from cocaine, alcohol, and crack addiction. The fourth panel subverts this expectation by showing a young man going from a neutral expression to a wide, happy smile, creating a punchline. This format is used to humorously label a non-drug-related hobby or interest as a positive, all-consuming "addiction."

PlayStation-trophy.name: PlayStation-trophy

text_options.description: This text box is placed where the name of the earned trophy would typically appear. In the meme, this is the punchline, describing the mundane or silly "achievement" that is being ironically celebrated. For example, it might say "Managed to get out of bed" or "Said 'you too' to the waiter."

This area above the notification is used to provide context for the "achievement." It typically contains an image or text that sets up the joke, showing the situation that led to the trophy being awarded.

PlayStation-trophy.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the PlayStation trophy notification, which reads "You have earned a trophy!" This format is used to sarcastically award someone for a mundane, unimpressive, or sometimes negative real-life accomplishment. The humor lies in applying the concept of a video game achievement to everyday situations that are not actually praiseworthy, creating an ironic sense of accomplishment.

braveheart-freedom.name: braveheart-freedom

text_options.description: This is the bottom text box, serving as the punchline of the meme. It contains the defiant declaration, often a variation of '...but they'll never take our freedom!' The text here represents the core, unyielding principle or possession that the speaker refuses to give up, contrasting with what was stated in the top panel.

This is the top text box, which sets up the premise of the meme. The text here typically follows the format 'They may take our X...' or a similar phrase, establishing what is being conceded or lost. This sets the stage for the defiant punchline in the bottom panel.

braveheart-freedom.image_description: This meme features a still of William Wallace, played by Mel Gibson, from the movie Braveheart. He is depicted with blue war paint on his face, shouting defiantly while surrounded by his army. The meme format is typically used to express a bold, defiant statement that is often humorous or ironic, following the structure of his famous line, 'They may take our lives, but they'll never take our freedom!'

Dodge-chad-vs-virgin.name: Dodge-chad-vs-virgin

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to Cheems, the weaker character. It typically contains a label for the inferior or modern version of the subject being compared. The text often incorporates Cheems' characteristic speech impediment, where extra 'm's are added to words (e.g., "cheemsburger").

This text box is placed over Swole Doge, the strong character. It is used to label the superior, idealized, or past version of the subject in the comparison. This text sets up the powerful standard against which Cheems is unfavorably compared.

Dodge-chad-vs-virgin.image_description: This meme, known as "Swole Doge vs. Cheems," features a comparison between two Shiba Inu characters. On the left is Swole Doge, a muscular and confident dog representing a strong, idealized, or past version of a subject. On the right is Cheems, a small and pathetic-looking dog representing the weak, disappointing, or present-day version. The meme is typically used to humorously contrast a glorious "then" with a feeble "now," often commenting on generational differences or historical changes.

FLOODING-THUMBS-UP.name: FLOODING-THUMBS-UP

text_options.description: This text identifies the person or entity that is struggling or overwhelmed but trying to maintain a positive facade. It represents the subject who is metaphorically "drowning."

This text, placed on the solid ground above the water, represents the overwhelming problem, responsibility, or external force causing the person below to "drown." It is the source of the stress or failure.

FLOODING-THUMBS-UP.image_description: This meme, known as "Drowning Thumbs Up" or "Sinking Thumbs Up Guy," features a person submerged in murky water, giving two thumbs up. The image humorously contrasts a positive gesture with a dire situation. It's used to represent someone pretending everything is fine while being overwhelmed by problems, stress, or failure, often in contexts like work, school, or personal life.

Homer-Simpson-Drooling.name: Homer-Simpson-Drooling

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image, near Homer's body, is often left blank or used to label the person or entity experiencing the desire. Common text includes 'Me' or a description of a group, grounding the abstract craving in a specific subject.

This space above Homer's head is where the object of desire is placed. It can be text or an image of something highly coveted, such as delicious food, a new gadget, or an appealing concept, which serves as the trigger for Homer's intense reaction.

Homer-Simpson-Drooling.image_description: This meme features the character Homer Simpson from the animated series 'The Simpsons' with his head tilted back, drooling, and a look of intense longing on his face. This image is used as a reaction to express an overwhelming desire or craving for something. The meme format typically places the object of desire above Homer, making it appear as though he is looking up at it with extreme want.

RIP.name: RIP

text_options.description: This lower section of the tombstone typically contains the "cause of death" or the dates of existence for the subject named above. This text provides the punchline or the specific reason why the thing is now considered dead or irrelevant.

This top section of the tombstone is where the name of the person, concept, or object being declared "dead" is placed. It serves as the main subject of the joke, identifying what has supposedly met its end.

RIP.image_description: This meme features a cartoon illustration of a tombstone with "R.I.P." engraved on it, commonly known as the "RIP Gravestone" meme. The format is used to humorously or sarcastically declare something as obsolete, finished, or metaphorically "dead." Users edit text onto the tombstone to signify the end of a trend, a career, a hope, or any concept, making a satirical statement about its demise.

5-panel-gru-meme.name: 5-panel-gru-meme

text_options.description: The first step of Gru's plan. The text here introduces the initial action or goal, corresponding with Gru's excited and confident expression.
The second step of the plan. This text builds upon the first step, continuing the setup for the desired outcome.
The third step of the plan, which is usually the intended positive outcome. Gru looks very pleased with himself, indicating this is the part he's most proud of.
The unexpected negative consequence or realization. Gru looks back at his plan with confusion and dismay, as the text in this box reveals the flaw that undermines everything.

This is a repeat of the third step of the plan. The text here is identical to the text in box 2, but now it's viewed in light of the negative consequence from box 3, highlighting the irony and the flaw in the original plan.

5-panel-gru-meme.image_description: This is the "Gru's Plan" meme, featuring the character Gru from the animated film "Despicable Me." The five-panel format depicts Gru excitedly outlining a plan on a presentation board, only to realize a critical, unforeseen flaw. This meme is used to humorously illustrate situations where a seemingly good plan has an obvious but overlooked negative consequence.

Pimples-Zero.name: Pimples-Zero

text_options.description: This box is in the final panel, which serves as the punchline of the meme. The text in this panel is always "ZERO," acting as a definitive and humorous answer to the question or statement posed in the preceding panel (labeled 1). It emphatically states that the quantity or existence of the subject is absolutely none.

This large, blank panel is the customizable part of the meme where the user writes the setup. The text is typically a question or a statement about a concept, possession, or quality that the user humorously claims to lack, for example, "My motivation?" or "Money in my wallet?".

Pimples-Zero.image_description: This meme format, known as "Pimples? Zero," originates from a skincare advertisement featuring Filipino actress Marian Rivera. The six-panel comic shows her asking about common skin problems like "Pimples?" and "Blackheads?" and then answering "Zero" while holding the product. The final two panels are the template, where a user poses a new question in the fifth panel, only to be met with the emphatic "ZERO" in the final panel, humorously indicating a complete lack or absence of something.

Powerpuff-Girls-Creation.name: Powerpuff-Girls-Creation

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the panel where Professor Utonium accidentally adds "Chemical X." In the meme format, this label represents the final product or the punchline, showing the result of combining the three preceding ingredients with an unexpected fourth one.

This text box is placed over the panel illustrating "everything nice." It's used to label the third ingredient in the recipe, typically representing a wholesome, sweet, or positive quality of the final subject.
This text box is placed over the panel for "spice." It labels the second ingredient in the combination, often representing a feisty, edgy, or more intense characteristic of the subject.

This text box is placed over the panel where "sugar" is being added. It is used to label the first ingredient in the metaphorical recipe, usually representing a sweet, innocent, or fundamental quality.

Powerpuff-Girls-Creation.image_description: This four-panel meme originates from the opening sequence of the animated series "The Powerpuff Girls." It depicts Professor Utonium creating the perfect little girls by combining three ingredients: "sugar," "spice," and "everything nice." The format is used to list three components that combine to create a particular person, object, or concept, with the fourth panel representing an unexpected or accidental element that defines the final result.

Windows-Error-Message.name: Windows-Error-Message

text_options.description: This is the main body of the error message. The text here delivers the core punchline of the meme, describing the absurd or contradictory "error" that has occurred. It's the central part of the joke, often detailing a real-life problem or a funny observation in the language of a computer malfunction.

This is the title bar of the error window. The text here typically names the fictional program or process that has 'crashed', setting the context for the main error message. For example, it might say "Life.exe" or "Social_Skills.dll" to frame the joke.

Windows-Error-Message.image_description: This meme format features a customizable error message box from an older version of Microsoft Windows. The iconic design, with its gray background, red 'X' error icon, and a single "Ok" button, is used to frame humorous, absurd, or frustrating situations as technical failures. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of a computer error with real-life problems, creating a sense of relatable and inescapable absurdity.

old-man-yells-at-cloud.name: old-man-yells-at-cloud

text_options.description: This area shows the angry old man, Grampa Simpson. In the meme, this figure is often labeled to represent the person or group whose opinion is being ridiculed as outdated or out of touch.

This is the newspaper headline, "OLD MAN YELLS AT CLOUD." In meme variations, the word "CLOUD" is typically replaced with the specific topic of the person's complaint, framing it as something absurd and pointless to be angry about.

old-man-yells-at-cloud.image_description: This meme, known as "Old Man Yells at Cloud," originates from the animated series The Simpsons. It features a newspaper article showing the character Grampa Simpson angrily shaking his fist at a small cloud. The image is used to humorously mock and dismiss people who complain about trivial, modern, or inevitable things, portraying their anger as irrational and pointless.

clown-computer.name: clown-computer

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the clown's body and is used to label the person or group being depicted as foolish or making a mistake. It identifies the subject of the meme's ridicule.
Located at the top of the image, this text describes the foolish action, belief, or situation that makes the subject (labeled in box 0) a clown. It provides the context or the punchline for the joke.

clown-computer.image_description: This meme, often called 'Clown at Computer' or 'Clown in Office,' shows a person in a full clown costume sitting at a desk and using a computer. The juxtaposition of the absurd, colorful clown with the mundane office environment creates a humorous visual. It's used to represent someone feeling or looking foolish, incompetent, or out of place, especially when trying to perform a serious task or expressing a silly opinion online.

Persian-Cat-Room-Guardian.name: Persian-Cat-Room-Guardian

text_options.description: Located in the second panel, this text box contains the punchline, representing the creature's exasperated or bewildered response. It's usually a question like "What the fuck?" or "What do you mean?", which is amplified by the creature's dramatic, pleading pose in the close-up shot.

This text box is placed at the top of the first panel. It typically contains a statement, action, or quote from another person that serves as the setup for the meme. This text provides the context that elicits the creature's initial confused reaction.

Persian-Cat-Room-Guardian.image_description: This two-panel meme features a "Persian Cat Room Guardian," a white, fluffy taxidermy creature with human-like hands. The first panel shows the creature shrugging with a confused look, while the second panel is a close-up of it looking up with its hands raised in a pleading or questioning gesture. The meme is used to express confusion, frustration, or disbelief in response to a statement or situation, often formatted as a "WTF" reaction.

Open-the-gate-a-little.name: Open-the-gate-a-little

text_options.description: This text box, in the final panel, reveals a specific, redeeming, or intriguing detail that makes the previously rejected subject acceptable again. It's the punchline that justifies the compromise of opening the gate "a little," representing a nuanced or conflicted final opinion.

This text box, in the middle panel, introduces a negative or undesirable trait about the subject from the first panel. This new information causes the lookout's immediate panic and reversal, leading to the command to "CLOSE THE GATE!".

This text box, in the top panel, describes the initial object or person of interest that the lookout sees. It represents something wholly positive or desirable, prompting the enthusiastic command to "OPEN THE GATE!" and setting up the premise of the meme.

Open-the-gate-a-little.image_description: This meme, known as "Open the Gate," is a three-panel comic strip illustrating a rapid change of opinion. A castle lookout first spots something desirable and orders the gate opened, then sees a negative detail and orders it closed, and finally notices a redeeming quality and cautiously orders it opened "a little." The meme is used to humorously depict a situation where an initial positive impression is quickly ruined by a flaw, only to be partially salvaged by a specific, appealing aspect.

Lord-farquaad.name: Lord-farquaad

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, revealing the speaker's selfish indifference. It typically reads, "...but it's a sacrifice I am willing to make," or a variation that shows the speaker is perfectly fine with the negative outcome described in the top text, as it doesn't affect them.

The top text box sets up the scenario by describing a negative or dangerous situation that will affect a group of people. This is the first part of the quote, such as "Some of you may die," which establishes the high stakes for others.

Lord-farquaad.image_description: This meme features Lord Farquaad from the movie Shrek, pointing with a smug expression. The original line from the movie is, "Some of you may die, but it's a sacrifice I am willing to make." The meme is used to humorously portray a person or entity callously disregarding the well-being of others for their own gain or convenience, highlighting their selfish indifference to the consequences faced by others.

La-Roca-Ayer-Vino.name: La-Roca-Ayer-Vino

text_options.description: The bottom text box is for the punchline of the joke. This text often contains a pun related to Dwayne Johnson's nickname, 'The Rock,' providing a humorous and literal answer to the setup in the top text.
The top text box serves as the setup for the meme's joke. It usually presents a question or a scenario that leads into a pun involving the word 'rock'.

La-Roca-Ayer-Vino.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor Dwayne 'The Rock' Johnson, looking stoic and muscular with his arms crossed. His serious expression and powerful build are central to the image's use. The meme is typically used for puns involving his name, 'The Rock,' where the text plays on words to create a humorous and often literal interpretation.

Now-all-of-China-knows-youre-here.name: Now-all-of-China-knows-youre-here

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is the original quote from the movie: 'Now all of China knows you're here.' The word 'China' is often replaced with a different group or location (e.g., 'the whole office,' 'the internet') to fit the specific context of the embarrassing situation being described.

This area at the top of the image is used to describe the action or mistake that caused the unwanted attention. It often starts with 'Me:' followed by a description of an embarrassing act, setting up the punchline delivered by Captain Shang.

Now-all-of-China-knows-youre-here.image_description: This meme features Captain Li Shang from Disney's animated film 'Mulan' looking angrily at a large fire. The subtitle reads, 'Now all of China knows you're here.' The meme is used to humorously call out a person for making a clumsy or conspicuous mistake that draws unwanted attention from everyone, with Shang representing the person pointing out the blunder and the fire symbolizing the mistake itself.
Now-all-of-China-knows-youre-here.display_name: Now all of China knows youre here

Crying-Aya-Chad.name: Crying-Aya-Chad

text_options.description: This text box is placed under the 'Yes Chad' character. It typically contains a short, simple, and direct statement representing the 'enjoyer's' viewpoint, which is framed as the more sensible or superior opinion in the comparison.

This text box is positioned under the crying anime girl. It usually contains a long, rambling, or emotionally charged paragraph representing the 'fan's' perspective, which is portrayed as overly complex, irrational, or inferior.

Crying-Aya-Chad.image_description: This meme format, often a variation of "Fans vs. Enjoyers," juxtaposes two contrasting figures to compare different perspectives. On the left, a distraught, crying anime girl represents an overly emotional or frantic "fan" of a particular concept. On the right, the stoic and calm "Yes Chad" or "Nordic Gamer" Wojak represents a simple, confident "enjoyer" of an alternative concept, implying their choice is superior and less complicated.

Trump-McDonalds-Drive-thru.name: Trump-McDonalds-Drive-thru

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image typically contains the punchline or a statement attributed to Donald Trump. It often features a humorous or unexpected phrase that contrasts with his persona as a former president, completing the joke set up by the image and the top text.

This top section serves as the setup for the joke. Text here usually presents a question, a customer's order, or a statement that prompts a response from Trump in the drive-thru window, establishing the context for the punchline below.

Trump-McDonalds-Drive-thru.image_description: This meme features a photoshopped image of former US President Donald Trump working at a McDonald's drive-thru window. He is shown wearing an apron over his signature white shirt and red tie, waving to someone outside. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of a powerful world leader in a mundane, low-wage job, often used to joke about his post-presidency career or to create absurd scenarios.

Trump-interview.name: Trump-interview

text_options.description: This box is placed on the blank paper being presented. It is the focal point of the meme, where the user inserts a ridiculous, nonsensical, or obviously false statement, image, or "proof" that forms the basis of the joke.

This box covers the paper as Jonathan Swan examines it with a confused expression. The content from box 0 is often repeated here to emphasize that this is what Swan is reacting to. This panel visually connects the absurd premise with the beginning of the skeptical reaction.

This box is placed over Donald Trump as he hands the paper to Jonathan Swan. Text here labels Trump, representing the person, company, or entity confidently presenting the flawed or absurd information shown in box 0.

Trump-interview.image_description: This meme format, known as "Trump Shows Chart" or "Jonathan Swan Interview," originates from a 2020 Axios on HBO interview. It depicts former President Donald Trump presenting a document to journalist Jonathan Swan, who reacts with increasing confusion and disbelief across the panels. The meme is used to humorously illustrate someone presenting a nonsensical argument, flawed data, or an absurd idea, followed by a rational person's baffled reaction.

Star-Wars-No.name: Star-Wars-No

text_options.description: Text here typically labels the person or group receiving the bad news, mirroring Luke Skywalker's horrified reaction. It represents the recipient of the unwelcome information who is in a state of shock or denial.
This text box is for the shocking revelation or unpleasant truth, delivered by the authoritative figure of Darth Vader. This statement sets up the punchline by presenting a hard-to-accept fact.

Star-Wars-No.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the iconic "I am your father" scene in "Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back." The top panel features the villain Darth Vader, who delivers a shocking or unpleasant truth. The bottom panel shows the hero Luke Skywalker screaming in anguish, representing the horrified reaction to that truth. The meme is used to humorously convey a hard-to-swallow pill or an unwelcome revelation.

I-WANT-PICTURES-OF-SPIDERMAN.name: I-WANT-PICTURES-OF-SPIDERMAN

text_options.description: Text in this position labels J. Jonah Jameson, representing the person, group, or entity making a forceful and often comically intense demand.
Text placed here, typically over the background, identifies the object, person, or concept that is being demanded with great fervor. This is the target of the demand.

I-WANT-PICTURES-OF-SPIDERMAN.image_description: This meme features J. Jonah Jameson from the 1990s Spider-Man animated series, depicted in a fit of rage, slamming his fist on his desk. He is the editor-in-chief of the Daily Bugle, known for his obsession with getting photos of the titular hero. The meme is used to humorously express an intense, often unreasonable, demand for something specific, mirroring his iconic line, "Get me pictures of Spider-Man!"

Jessica-Jones-Death-Stare.name: Jessica-Jones-Death-Stare

text_options.description: Text here identifies the person or entity who is being bothered or is trying to ignore something. This is the main subject of the meme, represented by the annoyed Jessica Jones.

Text placed over Kilgrave represents the intrusive thought, annoying person, or persistent problem that is bothering the subject. His position behind Jessica visually reinforces the idea of something inescapable and looming.

Jessica-Jones-Death-Stare.image_description: This meme features Jessica Jones (played by Krysten Ritter) looking distressed while the villain Kilgrave (played by David Tennant) stands behind her with a smug, knowing look. The image is from the Marvel Netflix series 'Jessica Jones'. The meme format is used to illustrate a situation where an individual is being unpleasantly reminded of or confronted by a persistent, unwelcome thought, person, or obligation they are trying to ignore.

two-guys-on-a-bus.name: two-guys-on-a-bus

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the happy man looking at the sunny landscape. The text here typically describes a positive, fortunate, or desirable person, group, or situation, contrasting with the negative counterpart on the left.

This text box is placed over the sad man looking at the bleak rock face. The text here usually describes a negative, unfortunate, or undesirable person, group, or situation, serving as the pessimistic foil to the optimistic character on the right.

two-guys-on-a-bus.image_description: This meme, known as 'Two Guys on a Bus' or 'Two People on a Bus', is a cartoon depicting two men with contrasting experiences. On the left, a sad man looks out at a bleak, rocky wall, while on the right, a happy man looks at a sunny, pleasant landscape. The meme is used to represent duality, contrasting two different perspectives, outcomes, or situations, highlighting how attitude or circumstances can drastically alter one's experience.

A-Wizard-Is-Never-Late.name: A-Wizard-Is-Never-Late

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Gandalf's beard, serves as the punchline. It almost always contains the phrase 'I have no memory of this place' or a slight variation, directly quoting (or slightly misquoting) his line from the movie. This text expresses the user's complete confusion or forgetfulness in response to the situation described in the top text.

The top text, positioned above Gandalf's face on his hat, sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes a situation, a past event, or a piece of information that the user is expected to know or remember but doesn't, creating the context for their subsequent confusion.

A-Wizard-Is-Never-Late.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Gandalf the Grey from 'The Lord of the Rings' with a slightly perplexed expression. Known as 'Confused Gandalf' or 'I Have No Memory of This Place,' the meme is used to express confusion, forgetfulness, or being out of the loop regarding a specific event or topic. The format uses a phrasal template where a situation is presented, followed by the punchline expressing a total lack of memory, humorously adapting a scene from the film.

What-my-friends-think-I-do.name: What-my-friends-think-I-do

text_options.description: A caption for the bottom middle panel, typically forming part of the comic's punchline or concluding statement.
The caption for the final panel on the bottom right. This text delivers the punchline or shows the absurd consequence of the salesman's claim.
The caption for the bottom left panel. This text is part of the comic's conclusion, often leading into the final punchline.
The caption for the middle right panel. This is the second part of the salesman's dialogue, containing the exaggerated claim about what 'this bad boy can fit'.
The caption for the middle left panel. This is where the salesman's iconic line typically begins, often with the action text '*slaps roof of car*'.
A small, centrally located text box, often used for a sound effect like '*slap*' to emphasize the action in the first panel.
The title banner for the entire comic strip. This text sets the overall theme or introduces the subject of the meme.

What-my-friends-think-I-do.image_description: This is a blank template of the 'Slaps Roof of Car' meme. The meme is a multi-panel comic strip featuring a car salesman who makes an exaggerated claim about a car's capacity, famously starting with the line '*slaps roof of car* this bad boy can fit so much X in it.' It's used to humorously describe cramming an excessive or absurd amount of something into a container or situation.
What-my-friends-think-I-do.display_name: What my friends think I do

Grumpy-Cat-Birthday.name: Grumpy-Cat-Birthday

text_options.description: The text at the bottom, typically placed on the cake, serves as the punchline. It's a cynical, negative, or unenthusiastic statement that reflects Grumpy Cat's supposed feelings about the celebration, directly contrasting with the happy occasion.

The text at the top of the image acts as the setup for the joke. It usually describes a situation or makes a statement that is meant to be positive or cheerful, setting the context for Grumpy Cat's negative reaction in the punchline.

Grumpy-Cat-Birthday.image_description: This meme features the internet-famous "Grumpy Cat" (Tardar Sauce), a cat known for her permanently sullen facial expression. The image captures her at a birthday party, wearing a festive hat and sitting behind a cake, with a "Happy Birthday" banner in the background. The humor comes from the stark contrast between the celebratory atmosphere and the cat's perpetually unimpressed look, making it a popular format for expressing cynicism or displeasure about events that are supposed to be joyful.

RIP-headstone.name: RIP-headstone

text_options.description: This area on the base of the tombstone is typically used for the "birth" and "death" dates of the subject. Alternatively, it can contain a short, punchy phrase that explains the cause of death or the reason for the subject's obsolescence, providing context for the main joke.

This is the main epitaph area on the tombstone. The name of the person, object, or concept being declared "dead" is written here. This is the central focus of the meme, identifying the subject of the humorous eulogy.

RIP-headstone.image_description: This meme features a grey tombstone with "R.I.P" at the top, used to humorously declare something as "dead," obsolete, or no longer relevant. The format, known as the "R.I.P. Gravestone" or "Tombstone" meme, allows users to write the name of a person, trend, or object on the grave to signify its end. It's a versatile and straightforward way to comment on the fleeting nature of trends, technology, or cultural phenomena.

Plate-toss.name: Plate-toss

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or entity that is forcefully rejecting the offering. This is the same entity as in box 3, shown here in the act of dismissal.
This label identifies the offering itself, now in mid-air as it's being thrown away. The text here is typically identical to the text in box 4 to emphasize what is being rejected.
This label identifies the person or entity who made the offering, now looking dejected after the rejection. This is the same entity as in box 5, showing the consequence of the rejection.
This label identifies the recipient of the offering, who appears unimpressed or neutral before rejecting it in the second panel. This sets up the impending dismissal.
This label identifies the well-intentioned but ultimately unwanted offering, idea, or effort being presented. This is the central subject of the meme.
This label identifies the person or entity proudly presenting their creation or idea. This character represents the hopeful or earnest party before their efforts are rejected.

Plate-toss.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as "Mac's Famous Mac and Cheese," originates from the TV show 'It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia' and features characters Mac and Dennis Reynolds. In the top panel, Mac proudly serves Dennis a bowl of macaroni and cheese, which Dennis then throws against the wall in the bottom panel while Mac looks on, dejected. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where a person's earnest effort, gift, or idea is met with abrupt and harsh rejection or is completely disregarded.

Abe-Simpson-telling-stories.name: Abe-Simpson-telling-stories

text_options.description: This area, placed over the children, represents the modern concept, person, or thing that the storyteller is complaining about or misunderstanding. It serves as the punchline, contrasting with the long, nonsensical story above.

Text in this box, positioned over Grandpa Simpson, represents the long, rambling, and often nonsensical story or complaint from an older, out-of-touch perspective. This sets up the joke by mimicking a "back in my day" rant.

Abe-Simpson-telling-stories.image_description: This meme, known as "Grandpa Simpson Storytelling" or "Old Man Yells at Cloud," originates from the animated series The Simpsons. It features Abraham "Grandpa" Simpson telling a seemingly long and rambling story to a group of children, including his grandson Bart. The format is used to humorously depict someone complaining about modern trends or telling an irrelevant, out-of-touch story that makes no sense to a younger audience.

Refuses-to-elaborate-any-further.name: Refuses-to-elaborate-any-further

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the lower half of Gigachad's body. It typically contains the "chad" or superior response, a simple yet profound statement, or the punchline to the setup in the top panel. The text here represents the ultimate, correct, or most desirable answer or viewpoint.

This text box is at the top of the image, serving as the setup or context. It usually contains a question, a prompt, or a statement that the Gigachad image below is responding to. For example, it might ask a question like "What do you do when someone insults you?"

Refuses-to-elaborate-any-further.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white photograph of an extremely muscular and chiseled man known as "Gigachad" (a character based on photos of model Ernest Khalimov). He is depicted as the epitome of masculinity and perfection. The meme is typically used to represent an ideal, superior, or based opinion or action, often in response to a question or statement presented in the top panel.

Hydra.name: Hydra

text_options.description: This label is placed on the neck of the goofy, derpy-looking dragon head. The text here represents the punchline of the meme—the inferior, silly, or failed member of the group that contrasts sharply with the other two.

This label is on the neck of the central, serious-looking dragon head. The text here typically represents one of the competent, formidable, or standard examples in the comparison, helping to set up the expectation that the third head will subvert.

This label is on the neck of the leftmost, menacing dragon head. Similar to the central head, the text here describes a competent or serious element, reinforcing the pattern of quality that the goofy head's label will comically break.

Hydra.image_description: This meme, known as the 'Three-Headed Dragon' or 'King Ghidorah', features a cartoon of the three-headed monster from Godzilla. Two heads are depicted as menacing and serious, while the third head on the right is drawn in a goofy, derpy style with its tongue out. The meme is used to compare three related items, where two are competent or impressive, and the third is a comically inferior or absurd outlier, serving as the punchline.

You-took-everything-from-me---I-dont-eve.name: You-took-everything-from-me---I-dont-even-know-who-you-are

text_options.description: This label is placed on Thanos. Text here represents the person, company, or institution that is completely oblivious or indifferent to the other party's feelings or existence. This character's dismissive ignorance serves as the punchline, creating a humorous or relatable contrast with the emotional investment shown in the top panel.

This label is placed on Scarlet Witch. Text here represents an individual, group, or concept that is deeply invested, holds a strong grudge, or feels wronged by the entity in the bottom panel. This sets up the emotional core of the meme, highlighting a one-sided sense of history or importance.

You-took-everything-from-me---I-dont-eve.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from a scene in the film *Avengers: Endgame* where Scarlet Witch (Wanda Maximoff) confronts the villain Thanos. The top panel shows an emotional Scarlet Witch, representing someone with a deep-seated grievance, while the bottom panel shows a dismissive Thanos, representing an oblivious or uncaring party. The meme is used to humorously contrast a situation of intense personal investment or suffering with complete ignorance or indifference from the other side.
You-took-everything-from-me---I-dont-eve.display_name: You took everything from me   I dont even know who you are

Buddy-the-elf-excited.name: Buddy-the-elf-excited

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned near Buddy's clasped hands, typically contains the punchline or the specific object of excitement. It's often a single word or a short phrase written in all caps to match the character's shouting expression, for example, 'SANTA!' or 'FRIDAY!'.
The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It introduces a scenario or a statement that leads to the extreme excitement depicted by Buddy the Elf.

Buddy-the-elf-excited.image_description: This meme features Will Ferrell as Buddy the Elf from the movie 'Elf', looking ecstatically happy with wide eyes and an open mouth. The image captures a moment of pure, child-like excitement and is used to express overwhelming joy or anticipation. This meme format typically uses top and bottom text to describe a situation that would elicit such a gleeful reaction, often in an exaggerated or humorous way.

Hello-My-Name-Is.name: Hello-My-Name-Is

text_options.description: The blank white space is where the user writes the 'name' or the core content of the meme. This text serves as the punchline or the main identifier, defining the subject in a humorous, ironic, or self-deprecating manner. Its placement directly after 'my name is' gives the text the weight of a formal, yet often absurd, introduction.

Hello-My-Name-Is.image_description: This meme features a classic red and white 'Hello my name is' sticker, a common name tag used for introductions at events. As a meme template, it's used to label or introduce a person, an idea, or a relatable experience in a direct and often humorous way. The joke or statement is delivered by what is written in the blank space, effectively personifying a concept or making a self-deprecating comment.

Will-Smith-Slap.name: Will-Smith-Slap

text_options.description: Text placed over Will Smith represents the aggressor or the powerful, often unexpected, force that is causing a negative outcome. This label identifies the cause of the 'slap' in the meme's scenario.

Text placed over Chris Rock represents the victim or the recipient of the aggressive action. This label identifies the person, idea, or situation that is being negatively impacted or 'slapped' by the force represented by Will Smith.

Will-Smith-Slap.image_description: This meme captures the moment actor Will Smith slaps comedian Chris Rock on stage at the 94th Academy Awards. In meme culture, Will Smith represents an aggressive or overwhelming force, concept, or entity that suddenly and powerfully impacts another. Chris Rock, the recipient of the slap, represents the victim or an idea that is being unexpectedly and negatively affected, often to a comical or absurd degree.

Business-Handshake.name: Business-Handshake

text_options.description: This label is placed directly on the clasped hands, symbolizing the agreement itself. The text here is the punchline, revealing the surprising or ironic trait, belief, or action that the two parties have in common.
This label is placed on the arm on the right, representing one of the two parties in the agreement. The text typically identifies a group, person, or concept.
This label is placed on the arm on the left, representing the second party in the agreement. This group is often presented as being in opposition to or very different from the party on the right.

Business-Handshake.image_description: This meme, known as the "Handshake Agreement" or "Epic Handshake," features a stock image of two people in business suits shaking hands. It is used to illustrate an unexpected point of agreement or a shared characteristic between two otherwise disparate or opposing groups. The two arms represent the different parties, while the handshake itself represents their surprising common ground, often for comedic or satirical effect.

Surprised-Pikachu-High-Quality.name: Surprised-Pikachu-High-Quality

text_options.description: This area highlights Pikachu's shocked face, which is the punchline of the meme. Text is not typically placed here, as the facial expression itself conveys the entire reaction of feigned surprise. The face acts as the unspoken response to the setup text above.

This top section is where the setup text for the meme is placed. It typically describes a two-part scenario: first, an action taken by the user, and second, the obvious negative consequence of that action. For example, 'Me: *Does something with a clear, predictable outcome* / Also me when the predictable outcome happens:' followed by the image.

Surprised-Pikachu-High-Quality.image_description: This meme, known as "Surprised Pikachu," features the Pokémon character Pikachu with a wide-eyed, open-mouthed expression of shock. It is used as a reaction image to express feigned surprise at a completely predictable and often negative outcome of one's own actions. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of a foolish action and the subsequent, yet entirely foreseeable, consequence that the person pretends to be shocked by.

Never-again.name: Never-again

text_options.description: This text box, positioned under the panel where the blob is being forced back into the box, describes the negative experience or external force that causes the retreat. It's the punchline, explaining what went wrong and why the character is being forced back into their original state.

Located under the second panel where the blob is happily leaving its container, this text describes the act of trying something new or stepping out of a comfort zone. It represents the moment of optimism and the action that initiates the story.

This text box, under the first panel showing the happy blob in its box, describes the initial state of comfort, habit, or isolation. It labels the person's default, safe behavior before they decide to change.

Never-again.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, often called 'Blob in a Box' or 'Never Again,' features a cute pink blob character. The story shows the blob happily leaving its box, representing a comfort zone, only to be violently shoved back in by a hand, representing a negative experience. The final panel shows the blob back in its box with the text 'NEVER AGAIN,' humorously illustrating the feeling of trying something new (like socializing), having it go badly, and vowing to retreat to one's old, safe habits.

I-am-the-danger.name: I-am-the-danger

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline, which is a forceful and defiant confirmation of the statement in the top text. It often contains the original quote from the scene, "You're Goddamn Right," or a variation that fits the context, providing an aggressive and confident response.

The top text box sets up the meme by posing a question or making an accusation that the meme's creator intends to confirm emphatically. This text establishes the context that Walter White's intense expression is reacting to.

I-am-the-danger.image_description: This meme features a close-up of an intensely angry Walter White from the TV show Breaking Bad, during the iconic "Say My Name" scene. In this moment, he is shouting to assert his powerful and dangerous identity as the drug kingpin Heisenberg. The image is used as a reaction format to forcefully agree with, confirm, or defiantly own a statement made by someone else, mirroring the character's intense self-assurance.

Whose-Line-is-it-Anyway.name: Whose-Line-is-it-Anyway

text_options.description: The bottom text area serves as the punchline. It typically contains a nonsensical or contradictory statement that satirizes the setup provided in the top text, framing it as an absurd prompt in the show.

The top text area provides the setup or context for the meme. This is where the initial statement, claim, or situation is presented, which is then undermined or shown to be absurd by the punchline at the bottom.

Whose-Line-is-it-Anyway.image_description: This meme features Drew Carey, the host of the improv comedy show "Whose Line Is It Anyway?". He is pictured at his desk with the audience behind him, smiling towards the camera. The format is used to present a situation or statement that is absurd, contradictory, or hypocritical, framing it as a prompt for the show, often invoking the catchphrase "where everything's made up and the points don't matter."

Random-Bullshit-Go.name: Random-Bullshit-Go

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme, "RANDOM BULLSHIT GO!!!!". This phrase is the core of the joke, representing the chaotic and improvised action being taken by the character. It is almost never edited, as it defines the entire meme format.

This area is used to label the person, entity, or concept that is employing the chaotic "random bullshit" strategy. The text here provides the context for the meme, identifying who is taking the desperate, unplanned action depicted by Moon Knight.

Random-Bullshit-Go.image_description: This meme is a comic book panel of the Marvel superhero Moon Knight throwing a barrage of crescent-shaped darts. The image is captioned with the phrase "RANDOM BULLSHIT GO!!!!", humorously depicting a chaotic, unplanned, and desperate strategy. It's used to represent situations where someone resorts to throwing everything they have at a problem, hoping something will work, without a clear plan or finesse.

Oigan-y-el.name: Oigan-y-el

text_options.description: This text box, positioned over Morty's bed, delivers the punchline of the meme. It contains the harsh, embarrassing, or dreadful realization that causes Morty's distressed reaction, directly contrasting with the setup text above.

Located at the top of the image, this text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically describes a pleasant situation, a happy memory, or a seemingly good idea, creating an expectation that is about to be shattered.

Oigan-y-el.image_description: This meme features the character Morty Smith from the animated show "Rick and Morty" waking up in bed with a look of pure horror and distress. Known as the "Morty's Mind Blowers" or "Aw Jeez" meme, it's used to contrast an initial pleasant thought or memory with a sudden, jarring, and unpleasant realization. The format typically presents a positive setup that is immediately undercut by a harsh reality, perfectly captured by Morty's panicked expression.

Brokeback-Mountain.name: Brokeback-Mountain

text_options.description: This text label, placed over the characters' embrace, typically identifies the subject of the meme—the person who is unable to quit something. It is often simply labeled "Me" to make the meme relatable to the viewer, with the embrace symbolizing the strong, unbreakable attachment.

The text in this top position describes the object, habit, or concept that the subject finds impossible to quit. This sets up the premise of the meme, framing the item as an all-consuming, addictive force in the subject's life, creating a humorous contrast with the dramatic image.

Brokeback-Mountain.image_description: This meme features a still from the 2005 film "Brokeback Mountain," showing characters Jack Twist (Jake Gyllenhaal) and Ennis Del Mar (Heath Ledger) in an emotional embrace. The image is used to express an intense, often humorous, inability to give up a particular habit, interest, or object, referencing the famous line, "I wish I knew how to quit you." The meme's humor comes from applying this deep, emotional sentiment to trivial or relatable everyday struggles.

sun-tsu-fake-quote.name: sun-tsu-fake-quote

text_options.description: This area of the meme template contains the fixed attribution text '-sun tsu'. This attribution is crucial to the meme's format, as it falsely credits the quote in region 1 to the revered author of 'The Art of War', creating the central satirical joke.

This is the primary text area where the user-generated 'quote' is placed. The text is typically a humorous, absurd, or overly simplistic piece of advice presented as a profound strategic maxim from 'The Art of War'. The humor comes from attributing this mundane or silly statement to the great military strategist Sun Tzu.

sun-tsu-fake-quote.image_description: This meme format, often called 'Sun Tzu's Art of War,' features a statue of a Terracotta Warrior, commonly misidentified as the ancient Chinese general Sun Tzu. The meme humorously attributes absurd, obvious, or comically mundane advice to Sun Tzu, parodying the profound strategic wisdom found in his book, 'The Art of War.' The juxtaposition of the serious historical figure with trivial modern-day 'wisdom' creates a satirical effect, making it a popular format for witty observations.

Was-anybody-going-to-tell-me.name: Was-anybody-going-to-tell-me

text_options.description: This space is for a verb or action that completes the rhetorical question, describing how the speaker was supposed to have learned the information on their own. A common entry is 'figure that out,' emphasizing the feeling of being left in the dark.

This is the core of the meme where the user inserts the surprising fact, piece of common knowledge, or life hack they just discovered. The humor comes from the mundane or obvious nature of the information that the speaker was unaware of.

Was-anybody-going-to-tell-me.image_description: This two-panel meme features comedian Chris Fleming with a look of exasperated disbelief. Known as "Was Anybody Going to Tell Me," it's used to express frustration and surprise upon learning a piece of information that seems like common knowledge. The user fills in the blanks to convey their feeling of being the last to know something, questioning why no one had informed them sooner.
Was-anybody-going-to-tell-me.display_name: Was anybody going to tell me

It-is-time-to-go.name: It-is-time-to-go

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme. After the Grim Reaper says "NO," this space is used to reveal what the subject actually was, often a harsh, disappointing, or comically specific label that subverts the initial question.

This text box is where the user inserts the role or identity for which the character is seeking validation, completing the question "Was I a ___?". This sets up the expectation of a positive answer, which is then denied in the following panels.

It-is-time-to-go.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, known as "Was I a Good Boy?", depicts the Grim Reaper escorting a soul (represented by a halo) to the afterlife. The soul asks for validation about its life or role, questioning "Was I a good [X]?", only for the Reaper to bluntly reply, "NO." The meme's punchline is delivered in the final panel, where the Reaper reveals what the subject truly was, creating a humorous and often harsh subversion of expectations.

Peter-Parker-Reading-Book--Crying.name: Peter-Parker-Reading-Book--Crying

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the page Peter Parker is pointing to. It contains the punchline of the meme: a sad, disappointing, or inconvenient truth that causes his emotional reaction in the final panel.

This text box is on the cover of the book. It typically contains a title that establishes the context, such as 'The Big Book of Facts' or 'The Rulebook,' framing the content inside as an undeniable truth.

Peter-Parker-Reading-Book--Crying.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as 'Peter Parker Reading a Book,' originates from the 1967 Spider-Man animated series. It shows Peter Parker reading a book, pointing to a specific passage, and then looking up with tears in his eyes. The format is used to convey sadness or disappointment after discovering an inconvenient or upsetting fact, which is typically edited onto the book's page.

I-am-speed.name: I-am-speed

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, which is almost always Lightning McQueen's original quote, "I am speed." It represents the subject's overconfident or ironic declaration of their quickness in response to the situation described in the top text.

This area at the top of the image provides the setup for the joke. The text describes a scenario or action that the meme creator performs with great, often comical, speed or haste, setting the context for the punchline below.

I-am-speed.image_description: This meme features Lightning McQueen, the main character from the Disney/Pixar movie "Cars," on a racetrack with a confident expression. The image is taken from a scene where he famously says, "I am speed." The meme is used to humorously depict situations where someone does something very quickly, often with reckless abandon, inefficiency, or in a comically unimpressive context, contrasting the mundane action with McQueen's high-octane self-assurance.

i-know-kung-fu.name: i-know-kung-fu

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline or the profound realization. This is the "shower thought" or epiphany that reframes the setup from the top text, causing the mind-blown reaction mirrored by Neo's expression.
The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It usually presents a common situation, a seemingly simple question, or an everyday observation that will be examined from a new, surprising perspective.

i-know-kung-fu.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Neo (played by Keanu Reeves) from the movie "The Matrix," looking upwards with an expression of dawning realization and shock. The scene depicts the moment he awakens in the real world, unplugged from the simulated reality he believed was real. This image is used as a reaction meme to express a profound, often belated, or mind-blowing realization, similar to a "shower thought" that fundamentally changes one's perspective on a common situation.

Neuron-activation.name: Neuron-activation

text_options.description: This text box, labeled "Monkey sees action," is where the stimulus or cause is described. It represents the action, object, or situation that triggers a thought or desire in the subject.

This text box, labeled "Neuron activation," represents the resulting thought, urge, or response to the stimulus in box 0. The humor of the meme often comes from the direct, simple, or comically primal nature of this reaction.

Neuron-activation.image_description: This meme, known as "Neuron Activation" or "Monkey See Monkey Do," features a pensive-looking monkey with an exposed brain from a scientific diagram. The format illustrates a simple cause-and-effect or stimulus-response scenario. It's used to humorously depict a person having a sudden, often simplistic or primal, thought or urge after observing a particular action or situation.

Three-Buttons.name: Three-Buttons

text_options.description: An optional label placed on the sweating man, identifying the person, group, or entity facing the difficult choice presented by the buttons.
The text for the first button, representing one of the conflicting options in the dilemma. This is one of the core choices causing the character's stress.
The text for the second button, representing the other conflicting option. Together with the first button, it establishes the central conflict of the meme.
The text for an optional third button. While the classic format uses two choices, this allows for a more complex dilemma or a third, often absurd, alternative.

Three-Buttons.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as 'Daily Struggle' or 'Two Buttons,' depicts a character's intense indecision. The top panel shows a hand hovering over multiple buttons, each representing a different choice, while the bottom panel reveals a man sweating profusely with a stressed expression. The meme is used to humorously illustrate a difficult dilemma between two or more conflicting desires, duties, or options.

Joey-Repeat-After-Me.name: Joey-Repeat-After-Me

text_options.description: Joey's initial reaction. This text shows his enthusiastic agreement or understanding of the first simple point. He is smiling broadly.
Phoebe's first point. This text box introduces the initial, simple part of the explanation. She is smiling and confident.
Joey processing the information. His expression is more serious, indicating he's trying to follow the more complex part of the explanation.
Phoebe's second point. This text box adds a layer of complexity to the explanation, building on the first point.
Joey's confusion. His face shows clear confusion and difficulty in understanding the last piece of information.
Phoebe's third and final point. This box contains the most complex or nuanced part of the explanation.
Joey's incorrect punchline. This text box contains Joey's hilariously wrong interpretation of the entire explanation, delivered with misplaced confidence.
Phoebe's summary or question. This text often prompts Joey to repeat back what he has learned, representing the 'test' of his understanding.

Joey-Repeat-After-Me.image_description: This meme, known as 'Joey Teaching Phoebe' or 'Joey's Wrong Answer', features characters Phoebe Buffay and Joey Tribbiani from the TV show Friends. The four-panel format depicts Phoebe patiently explaining a concept step-by-step, while Joey's expression shifts from understanding to confusion, culminating in him confidently stating a completely incorrect conclusion. It's used to humorously illustrate misunderstandings of complex topics or instructions.

Tiny-piece-of-paper.name: Tiny-piece-of-paper

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the punchline, describing the tiny, insignificant, or confusing detail that the person is hyper-focusing on. It represents the object of intense scrutiny, which is often comically unimportant or difficult to understand, mirroring the character's expression.

The top text box is used to set up the context of the meme. It often describes a larger, more complex, or more important piece of information that is being ignored in favor of the tiny detail mentioned in the bottom text.

Tiny-piece-of-paper.image_description: This meme features actor Ken Jeong as the character Ben Chang from the TV show "Community." In the image, he is squinting intensely at a tiny piece of paper, conveying a sense of extreme difficulty in reading or understanding something. The meme, often called "Tiny Paper" or "Ken Jeong Squinting," is used to humorously represent situations where someone is struggling to comprehend something small, overly detailed, or nonsensical.

Steamboat-Willie.name: Steamboat-Willie

text_options.description: The bottom panel of the meme. This area typically contains text describing a negative consequence, an inconvenient truth, or a problem that is being willfully ignored by the person or entity represented by Mickey Mouse.

The top panel, located inside a large speech bubble coming from Mickey. This is where the initial, often naive or cheerful statement, action, or goal is placed. It sets up the ironic contrast with the text in the bottom panel.

Steamboat-Willie.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white still of Mickey Mouse from the 1928 animated short film "Steamboat Willie." In the image, Mickey is cheerfully piloting a steamboat, seemingly oblivious to his surroundings. The meme format typically contrasts Mickey's happy-go-lucky attitude with an impending or ongoing problem, often presented as text in two separate panels, one for the statement and one for the ignored consequence.

Gordon-Ramsay-Idiot-Sandwich.name: Gordon-Ramsay-Idiot-Sandwich

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the woman, Julie Chen, who is being called an "idiot sandwich." The text here identifies the person, group, or concept being insulted or labeled as incompetent, serving as the punchline of the meme.

This text box is placed over Gordon Ramsay, the figure of authority who is yelling. The text here typically represents the person or entity delivering the harsh criticism or asking the iconic question, "What are you?"

Gordon-Ramsay-Idiot-Sandwich.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Idiot Sandwich," originates from a parody sketch featuring celebrity chef Gordon Ramsay. In the top panel, Ramsay yells while holding two slices of bread on either side of a woman's head, and the bottom panel shows a close-up of her looking downcast. The meme is used to humorously call someone or something foolish or incompetent, with Ramsay representing the authority figure delivering the insult and the woman representing the target.

Beggar.name: Beggar

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned near the empty bowl, typically contains the punchline or the specific request. It often follows the format "Please sir, can I have some more [X]?", where [X] is the desired object or concept.
The top text sets up the context of the meme. It usually identifies the person, group, or entity that is making the desperate plea for more of something.

Beggar.image_description: This meme features a still of a young, gaunt Oliver Twist from the 1948 film, holding an empty bowl with a pleading expression. The scene famously depicts the orphan asking for more food, with the line, "Please, sir, I want some more." This image is used as a reaction meme to humorously beg for more of something, whether it's content, attention, or any other desired item, contrasting the original's desperation with a modern, often trivial, want.

skinner-pathetic.name: skinner-pathetic

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline and the core of the meme, the single word "Pathetic." This text is almost always present and unchanged, delivering the final judgment on the subject mentioned above.

Text placed in this region describes the person, group, or situation that is being judged as pathetic. As Skinner is looking down from this position, the text here represents the target of his (and the meme creator's) scorn.

skinner-pathetic.image_description: This meme features Principal Seymour Skinner from the animated series *The Simpsons*. In the scene, Skinner looks down with a smug, disdainful expression, judging something off-screen. The image is used as a reaction to express a feeling of superiority, contempt, or disappointment towards a person, action, or idea, labeling it as "pathetic."

Flynn-rider-swords.name: Flynn-rider-swords

text_options.description: This area, covering the multitude of swords, is used to label the group, community, or individuals who are vehemently opposing the opinion stated above. The sheer number of swords visually represents the overwhelming backlash or criticism.

Positioned over Flynn Rider's head, this text represents the unpopular, controversial, or 'hot take' opinion that the meme creator is expressing. Flynn's smug expression implies that the person holding this opinion is confident and unashamed, despite the negative reaction.

Flynn-rider-swords.image_description: This meme features the character Flynn Rider from the Disney movie 'Tangled', surrounded by numerous swords pointed threateningly at him. Despite the dangerous situation, Flynn wears a smug and unconcerned expression. The meme is used to represent someone confidently sharing a controversial or unpopular opinion, with the swords symbolizing the inevitable backlash, criticism, or disagreement from a large group of people.

Vein-forehead-guy.name: Vein-forehead-guy

text_options.description: This text box labels the person or entity experiencing the intense struggle. It identifies the subject who is trying to hold something back.
This text box, positioned above the subject's head, describes the urge, thought, or action that the person is desperately trying to suppress. It represents the source of the internal conflict.

Vein-forehead-guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl in Class" or "Straining Guy," features a high school student with bulging veins on his forehead, looking like he's under immense physical and mental pressure. He sits next to a girl who is looking away, oblivious to his struggle. The meme is used to humorously represent the intense internal effort required to suppress an urge, a thought, or a comment in a sensitive or inappropriate situation.

mexican-word-of-the-day.name: mexican-word-of-the-day

text_options.description: This bottom text area delivers the punchline of the joke. It typically contains a pun or a humorous phrase related to Mexican or Hispanic stereotypes, often a playful mispronunciation or a Spanish word that sounds like an English one. The man's laughing expression perfectly complements the delivery of this punchline.

This top text area serves as the setup for the joke in the classic advice animal format. It presents a situation, a question, or a statement that the bottom text will humorously resolve with a stereotype-based punchline.

mexican-word-of-the-day.image_description: This meme, known as 'Merry Mexican' or 'Sombrero Guy,' features a man with a mustache laughing heartily while wearing a very large sombrero. It's an advice animal-style image macro used to tell jokes based on stereotypes about Mexican culture, language, and food. The format typically involves a setup line at the top and a humorous, often pun-based, punchline at the bottom that plays on Spanish words or cultural references.

computer-nerd.name: computer-nerd

text_options.description: The bottom text contains the punchline, delivering the "butthurt" or overly pedantic response from the character. This text is meant to sound arrogant, dismissive, or excessively technical, reinforcing the stereotype of a socially inept expert who feels superior due to their niche knowledge.

The top text sets up the scenario or presents a general statement, often a popular opinion or a casual comment about a topic the character is passionate about. This line acts as the trigger for the character's reaction.
