computer-nerd.image_description: This meme, known as "Butthurt Dweller" or "Gamer," features a vintage photograph of a man at a computer, embodying the stereotype of an obsessive nerd or gamer. The image is used to mock people who get overly defensive or pedantic about their niche hobbies, especially in online discussions. The format follows the classic image macro style, with a setup line at the top and a punchline at the bottom that reflects the character's stereotypical condescending or socially awkward perspective.

angry-dog-meme.name: angry-dog-meme

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the smiling, pleasant-looking chihuahua. The text here represents the positive, desirable, or superior option in the comparison. It's the 'after' in a before-and-after scenario or the preferred outcome that contrasts with the negative subject in the other panel.

This text box is placed over the snarling, angry chihuahua. The text here represents the negative, aggressive, or undesirable element of the comparison. It's meant to be the 'before' or the problematic subject that is being contrasted with the more positive one on the right.

angry-dog-meme.image_description: This two-panel meme features a chihuahua with contrasting expressions. On the left, the dog is snarling and aggressive, while on the right, it appears calm and is smiling sweetly. This format, often called "Angry Chihuahua vs. Smiling Chihuahua," is used to compare two opposing things, situations, or states of mind. It effectively highlights a duality, such as a harsh reality versus an ideal outcome, or a person's different attitudes depending on the context.

Skeleton-Computer.name: Skeleton-Computer

text_options.description: The bottom text box, placed over the desk and computer, typically contains the caption describing the specific thing the person is waiting for. This text provides the context for the joke, setting up the punchline that the wait has been long enough for them to turn into a skeleton. For example, 'Waiting for the page to load' or 'Waiting for a reply'.

The top text box is a less common location for text in this meme format, but it can be used for a title or a setup phrase. It might contain a general statement like 'Still waiting for...' or 'Me when...', which introduces the specific context that is usually detailed in the bottom text. This follows the classic top-text/bottom-text meme structure.

Skeleton-Computer.image_description: This meme, known as 'Waiting Skeleton' or 'Still Waiting,' features a skeleton sitting patiently at a computer desk. The image humorously exaggerates the feeling of waiting for an extremely long time for something to happen, such as a slow download, a game release, or a response from someone. The punchline is that the user has been waiting so long they have literally wasted away.

I-am-the-Senate.name: I-am-the-Senate

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline of the meme, delivered from Palpatine's perspective. It reveals the ironic outcome of the situation presented in the top text, often starting with the word "Ironic" or quoting a line from the movie like "He could save others from death, but not himself."

The top text sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes a person, a power, or a situation that seems to have a certain capability or outcome, setting the stage for the ironic twist that follows.

I-am-the-Senate.image_description: This meme features Emperor Palpatine from Star Wars: Revenge of the Sith, also known as Darth Sidious. The image captures his smug, knowing expression as he recounts a story, and is famously used for the "Ironic" or "Tragedy of Darth Plagueis the Wise" meme format. The meme is used to point out ironic situations, where the top text describes a scenario and the bottom text, from Palpatine's perspective, reveals the ironic twist or outcome.

Dr-Evil-One-Million.name: Dr-Evil-One-Million

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a specific, often comically small, absurd, or ironic detail that contrasts with the grand statement made in the top text, completing the two-part joke structure.

The top text sets up the joke by presenting a grand, ambitious, or seemingly serious statement, plan, or demand. This text establishes the context for the punchline that will follow at the bottom of the image.

Dr-Evil-One-Million.image_description: This meme features the character Dr. Evil from the "Austin Powers" film series, known for his comically inept attempts at world domination. He is depicted with his pinky finger to his mouth, a signature gesture often preceding an evil plan or a demand. The meme format is typically used to present a grandiose or absurd idea, followed by a specific, often underwhelming or ironic, condition or detail, creating a humorous contrast.

Imma-Keep-It-Real-With-You-Chief.name: Imma-Keep-It-Real-With-You-Chief

text_options.description: This bottom text box is where the punchline or the 'real talk' is placed. It typically contains a negative opinion, a harsh truth, or a rejection, completing the phrase set up by the top text.

This top text, 'IMA KEEP IT REAL WIT U CHIEF!!', is the fixed setup for the meme. It establishes a tone of honest and direct communication, preparing the audience for the blunt statement that follows in the bottom text.

Imma-Keep-It-Real-With-You-Chief.image_description: This meme features Muppets characters Kermit the Frog and Pepe the King Prawn. Kermit appears to be delivering a hard truth to a shocked-looking Pepe, prefaced by the phrase at the top. This format is used to express a blunt, often negative, opinion or judgment about something, with the punchline placed at the bottom.
Imma-Keep-It-Real-With-You-Chief.display_name: Imma Keep It Real With You Chief

Are-you-two-friends.name: Are-you-two-friends

text_options.description: This label is placed over the character Harry Kim, who is smiling and answers 'Yes.' Text here represents the person, group, or concept that believes a friendly or positive relationship exists, often naively or optimistically.

This label is placed over the character Tuvok, who has a serious expression and answers 'No.' Text here represents the person, group, or concept that denies or rejects the relationship, creating the humorous conflict and punchline of the meme.

Are-you-two-friends.image_description: This meme format originates from a scene in the TV show Star Trek: Voyager, where the character Kes asks Tuvok and Harry Kim, 'Are you two friends?'. The humor comes from their conflicting responses, with the optimistic Harry Kim saying 'Yes' while the stoic Tuvok says 'No.' The meme is used to represent a one-sided relationship or a fundamental disagreement between two entities, where one party is enthusiastic about a connection that the other party completely rejects.

Heaven.name: Heaven

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the stairs is where the subject of the meme is placed. It's typically an image of a person, object, or idea that is being humorously depicted as 'dying' or 'ascending to heaven,' starting its journey upwards.

The text at the top, in the heavenly light, usually provides the context or punchline for why the subject is ascending. It often contains a caption explaining the reason for the subject's 'death' or departure, completing the joke.

Heaven.image_description: This meme, known as "Stairway to Heaven" or "Ascension," features a stock image of a cloudy staircase leading up to a bright, heavenly light in the sky. It is used to humorously depict the "death," obsolescence, or departure of a person, object, or concept. The subject is shown ascending the stairs, signifying it has passed on or is no longer relevant, often for a funny or trivial reason.

Liam-Neeson-Taken-2.name: Liam-Neeson-Taken-2

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the punchline. It typically completes the famous quote with a twist, such as "...I will find you, and I will [do something]." The final action is often altered for comedic effect, replacing the original's violent threat with a humorous or trivial consequence.

The top text, which sets up the premise of the meme. It usually starts with a variation of the original line, "I don't know who you are. I don't know what you want," to establish the context of addressing an unknown person or entity who has caused a problem.

Liam-Neeson-Taken-2.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of actor Liam Neeson as his character Bryan Mills from the 2008 film "Taken." In the scene, he is on the phone delivering a menacing monologue, famously threatening the person on the other end. The meme format, often called "I Will Find You," uses this image to express a comically intense determination to find someone or something, adapting the original threatening speech to more mundane or humorous situations.

I-am-the-captain-now.name: I-am-the-captain-now

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, typically the phrase 'I'm the captain now' or a variation of it. It is attributed to the new person in charge (Abduwali Muse) and signifies the completion of the power shift, creating the humorous climax of the meme.

This top text box is used to label the original authority figure or the established power dynamic, represented by Captain Phillips. It sets up the context for the reversal of roles that is about to happen. For example, it might label Captain Phillips as 'My parents' or 'The teacher'.

I-am-the-captain-now.image_description: This meme originates from the 2013 film 'Captain Phillips,' featuring the Somali pirate leader Abduwali Muse (played by Barkhad Abdi) confronting Captain Phillips (Tom Hanks). The iconic line, 'Look at me, I'm the captain now,' is used to humorously depict a sudden shift in power or a takeover of control in various situations. The meme format contrasts an established authority with the new, often unexpected, person or entity now in charge.

Girls-whispering.name: Girls-whispering

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline or the shocking secret itself. This text is what causes the surprised reaction from the listener (Emma Roberts), revealing the humorous or unexpected information that was whispered.

The top text box is used to set up the context of the meme. It often labels the person whispering (JoJo) or describes the general topic of the secret being shared, establishing the premise for the punchline that follows.

Girls-whispering.image_description: This meme, known as "JoJo and Emma Roberts Whispering," originates from the 2006 film 'Aquamarine'. It features singer JoJo whispering to actress Emma Roberts, who reacts with a shocked, open-mouthed expression. The format is used to humorously depict the sharing of a surprising, scandalous, or unexpected piece of information, with the text revealing the nature of the 'secret' being told.

laughing-kid.name: laughing-kid

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically contains a punchline or a label for the action being performed with great effort. It often describes the internal feeling or the result of the struggle mentioned in the top text, completing the joke by articulating the immense strain shown on the boy's face.
The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It describes the specific, often relatable and awkward, social situation that is causing the intense internal struggle depicted by the boy's face.

laughing-kid.image_description: This meme, known as 'Straining Kid' or 'Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl in Class,' features a young boy with a comically contorted and strained facial expression. The image is used to represent a moment of intense internal struggle or the immense effort required to suppress an urge, thought, or physical reaction. It's a classic image macro format used to humorously illustrate situations demanding extreme self-control, especially in socially awkward settings.

Soviet-Bugs-Bunny.name: Soviet-Bugs-Bunny

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline of the meme. It directly refutes the top text by changing the possessive pronoun from singular (e.g., "my") to plural ("our"), humorously imposing a communist ideal of shared ownership onto the object or concept mentioned above.
The top text sets up the joke by presenting a statement of personal ownership. It typically starts with "My..." followed by a noun, such as "My girlfriend," "My grades," or "My meme."

Soviet-Bugs-Bunny.image_description: This meme, known as "Communist Bugs Bunny" or the "Our Meme," features the Looney Tunes character Bugs Bunny with a smug expression against a background with the communist hammer and sickle symbol. The meme is used to humorously reframe a statement about personal possession into one of collective ownership, playing on stereotypes of communism. Typically, a user posts about "my" something, and another person responds with this image and the caption "our" something.

angry-turkish-man-playing-cards-meme.name: angry-turkish-man-playing-cards-meme

text_options.description: This label is placed over the cards already on the table. Text here typically describes the ongoing situation, the problem at hand, or the preceding points in an argument, setting the stage for the final, decisive action.
This label is on the man in the plaid shirt who is slamming the card. This character represents the person, group, or entity delivering the final, powerful statement or solution.

This label is on the card being slammed onto the table. The text here is the punchline, representing the ultimate, undeniable argument, the perfect solution, or the 'trump card' that decisively resolves the situation.

angry-turkish-man-playing-cards-meme.image_description: This meme, known as 'Man Slapping Card Down' or 'Card Slap,' shows a man in a plaid shirt forcefully slamming a playing card on a table during a game with others. The image conveys a sense of ultimate finality, conviction, and a decisive winning move. It is used to represent someone presenting an irrefutable argument, a perfect solution, or a 'trump card' that ends a discussion or solves a problem.
angry-turkish-man-playing-cards-meme.display_name: angry turkish man playing cards meme

Honey-wake-up.name: Honey-wake-up

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the sleeping woman. It contains her presumed internal monologue, which is almost always the phrase "He's probably thinking about other women..." or a close variation. This text serves as the setup for the meme's punchline by establishing a stereotypical, insecure assumption.

This text box is positioned over the awake man, representing his actual thoughts. This is the punchline of the meme, containing a statement that is completely unrelated to infidelity and is often absurd, technical, or focused on a niche hobby. The humor comes from the stark contrast between his innocent or nerdy thought and his partner's dramatic assumption.

Honey-wake-up.image_description: This meme, known as "I Bet He's Thinking About Other Women," features a stock photo of a couple in bed. A woman sleeps soundly while her male partner is awake, looking down with a thoughtful smile. The humor arises from a juxtaposition of their supposed thoughts: the woman assumes he's thinking about infidelity, while his actual thoughts are revealed to be about something mundane, nerdy, or completely random. This format plays on relationship stereotypes and subverts expectations for comedic effect.

Thumbs-Up-Rambo.name: Thumbs-Up-Rambo

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline, representing the person's forced positive reaction or attempt to downplay their suffering. This text aligns with Rambo's thumbs-up gesture, creating a stark, humorous contrast with his pained expression.
The top text box is used to establish the context of a difficult, painful, or unpleasant situation that the subject is enduring. This text explains why the character looks so distressed.

Thumbs-Up-Rambo.image_description: This meme features a still of Sylvester Stallone as John Rambo from the 2008 film 'Rambo'. He appears battered, covered in sweat and grime, with a pained expression, yet he is giving two thumbs up. The meme, often called 'Rambo Thumbs Up', humorously depicts someone pretending everything is okay or showing approval despite being in a clearly difficult, painful, or stressful situation.

Conspiracy-Keanu.name: Conspiracy-Keanu

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline or completes the thought started in the top text. This line solidifies the absurd or pseudo-profound nature of the question, justifying Keanu's shocked expression.
The top text sets up a hypothetical or conspiratorial question. It's the first part of a two-line phrase that leads to a surprising or mind-bending conclusion, often beginning with "What if...".

Conspiracy-Keanu.image_description: This meme, known as "Conspiracy Keanu" or "What If Keanu," features a still of a young Keanu Reeves from the 1989 film "Bill & Ted's Excellent Adventure." His wide-eyed and slightly bewildered expression captures a moment of sudden, profound, or often absurd realization. The format is typically used to pose pseudo-philosophical questions, shower thoughts, or humorous conspiracy theories, often starting with the phrase "What if...".

meme-man.name: meme-man

text_options.description: This bottom text area is the punchline of the meme. It contains a single, intentionally misspelled word that humorously represents the concept or action being depicted. For example, 'Stonks' for stocks, 'Helth' for health, or 'Shef' for chef. This misspelling is the core comedic element of the format.
The top text area typically describes a situation, action, or context that the meme is commenting on. This text sets up the punchline that appears at the bottom of the image.

meme-man.image_description: This image features the character known as 'Meme Man,' a poorly rendered 3D model of a bald, disembodied head. He is a central figure in surreal memes, most famously the 'Stonks' meme, which satirizes financial or business decisions. The format typically involves pairing Meme Man's blank, emotionless expression with deliberately misspelled words to create absurd or ironic commentary on a given topic.

Smithers-vs-Strippers.name: Smithers-vs-Strippers

text_options.description: This label is placed on one of the female dancers. The text here represents a popular, mainstream, or conventionally desirable option that is being ignored by the subject of the meme.
This label is on Waylon Smithers. The text here identifies the person or group who is ignoring the popular options in favor of their own specific, often niche, preference.
This label is placed on the second female dancer. Similar to the other dancer, the text here represents another aspect of the popular or obvious choice that is being disregarded.

Smithers-vs-Strippers.image_description: This meme, known as "Smithers' Choice," originates from an episode of The Simpsons. It depicts Waylon Smithers in a burlesque house, averting his gaze from two female dancers to look at something off-screen (implied to be a male dancer). The meme is used to contrast a mainstream or widely appealing option (the dancers) with a more niche or personal preference (what Smithers is looking at). Smithers represents the user who ignores the popular choice in favor of their own specific interest.

Blue-armor-guy.name: Blue-armor-guy

text_options.description: Located in the speech bubble of the giant protector, this text represents what the protector is saying or thinking. It's often a simple, reassuring, or nonchalant comment, highlighting how unaffected they are by the barrage of 'attacks'.

This label is placed on the small, unarmored character. It typically identifies the vulnerable person, group, or concept being protected, such as 'Me,' 'Junior developers,' or 'My last bit of motivation'.

This label is placed on the large, armored character. It identifies the powerful entity providing protection, such as 'My veteran teammate,' 'The project's robust error handling,' or 'My mom's unconditional support'.

Blue-armor-guy.image_description: This meme, from a comic by artist SrGrafo, depicts a giant, heavily armored character effortlessly deflecting a volley of arrows while a much smaller, unarmored character stands safely behind it. The giant character represents a powerful protector (e.g., a senior colleague, a strong argument), while the small character represents someone or something vulnerable being shielded. The meme is used to illustrate situations where a strong entity absorbs all the attacks, criticism, or problems (the arrows) for a weaker one.

Get-Better-Material-meme.name: Get-Better-Material-meme

text_options.description: This text, written on the notecard, reveals the source or reasoning behind the initial statement. It serves as the punchline, typically showing a flawed, weak, or ridiculous justification for why the "joke" failed.
This speech bubble contains the initial statement, opinion, or "joke" that the crow (representing the user) presents. It's the setup that is about to be rejected by the audience.

Get-Better-Material-meme.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, known as "Heckled Crow" or "Get Better Material," depicts a crow performing stand-up comedy. After telling a joke, the crow is booed by the audience and looks at its notecards in distress. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where an opinion or statement is poorly received, with the final panel revealing the flawed or unpopular source of that idea.

Here-Lies-X.name: Here-Lies-X

text_options.description: This top section of the tombstone typically contains an introductory phrase like "Here Lies" or "R.I.P." to set up the funereal context of the meme.

This is the main body of the tombstone where the punchline is placed. Users write the name of the person, object, or concept that has been lost or has failed, representing their 'dead' hopes and dreams.

Here-Lies-X.image_description: This meme features a tombstone from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants, originally inscribed with "Here Lies Squidward's Hopes and Dreams." The image is used to humorously mourn the loss or failure of something, such as a goal, an expectation, or a concept. Users edit the text on the gravestone to represent whatever has metaphorically "died," making it a versatile format for expressing disappointment and relatable failures.

Rick-and-Morty-Butter.name: Rick-and-Morty-Butter

text_options.description: In the bottom panel, this text box is placed over the dejected-looking robot. It typically contains the robot's reaction of despair, such as 'Oh my god,' which serves as the punchline to the meme, highlighting its existential crisis.

Located in the middle panel over the character Rick Sanchez, this text box contains the answer to the robot's question. This is typically a mundane, overly specific, or disappointing purpose that sets up the punchline.

In the top panel, this text box is placed over the robot as it looks up expectantly. This is where the initial question is placed, usually 'What is my purpose?', which establishes the premise of the meme.

Rick-and-Morty-Butter.image_description: A three-panel meme from the animated show 'Rick and Morty' known as 'What is my purpose?'. The first panel shows a small robot asking a question. The second panel shows its creator, Rick Sanchez, providing an answer. The final panel shows the robot looking down in despair. This meme format is used to humorously express an existential crisis or a feeling of uselessness after discovering one's purpose is mundane, trivial, or unfulfilling.

Emperor-Palpatine.name: Emperor-Palpatine

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, which is typically a variation of Emperor Palpatine's quote, such as "Good, good. Let the hate flow through you." This text represents the meme creator's gleeful and evil-sounding encouragement of the negative emotion or action described in the top text.

The top text box sets up the context for the meme. It usually describes a situation or a person's statement that is causing frustration, anger, or leading them to embrace a more cynical or 'evil' point of view.

Emperor-Palpatine.image_description: This meme features Emperor Palpatine from the Star Wars franchise, recognizable by his pale, wrinkled face, yellow eyes, and dark hooded robe, grinning menacingly. The image is a still from "Return of the Jedi" and is famously associated with his line encouraging Luke Skywalker to embrace his anger. Culturally, this meme is used to humorously express satisfaction or encouragement when someone else gives in to negative emotions like anger, frustration, or any 'dark side' temptation.

Aint-Nobody-Got-Time-For-That.name: Aint-Nobody-Got-Time-For-That

text_options.description: This is the punchline area, typically containing the iconic phrase "Ain't nobody got time for that." This text directly quotes Sweet Brown and delivers the core message of the meme, expressing that the situation described above is not worth the time or effort.
The top text sets up the scenario. This is where a user describes a frustrating, lengthy, or annoying task, situation, or statement that they are reacting to.

Aint-Nobody-Got-Time-For-That.image_description: This meme features Kimberly "Sweet Brown" Wilkins from a viral news interview where she dramatically described escaping an apartment fire. Known as the "Ain't Nobody Got Time for That" meme, her exasperated expression is used to convey a strong sense of dismissal towards a tedious, annoying, or time-consuming situation. The meme humorously rejects tasks or events that are deemed not worth the effort or time.
Aint-Nobody-Got-Time-For-That.display_name: Aint Nobody Got Time For That

Greta-Thunberg-how-dare-you.name: Greta-Thunberg-how-dare-you

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the punchline, which is most often the iconic phrase "How dare you?". This text directly voices the anger and accusation conveyed by Thunberg's expression, serving as the climax of the meme's joke.
The top text box is used to set up the scenario. It describes the person, action, or situation that is the target of the intense disapproval shown in the image, providing the context for the outrage.

Greta-Thunberg-how-dare-you.image_description: This meme features a close-up image of climate activist Greta Thunberg delivering an impassioned speech at the 2019 UN Climate Action Summit. Her face is contorted with an expression of intense anger and frustration, famously associated with her line, "How dare you?". The meme is used to express extreme disappointment or outrage, often in a hyperbolic or humorous way, by juxtaposing her serious expression with trivial, everyday annoyances.

BREAKING-NEWS.name: BREAKING-NEWS

text_options.description: The bottom text, located over the news desk, delivers the punchline from Ron Burgundy's perspective. It typically contains a phrase expressing disbelief, like 'I don't believe you,' or surprise at a rapid turn of events, such as 'Well, that escalated quickly,' reacting to the setup text above.

The top text, placed above Ron Burgundy's head, serves as the setup for the meme. This area usually contains a statement, quote, or description of a situation that is unbelievable, absurd, or has escalated dramatically, prompting the reaction in the bottom text.

BREAKING-NEWS.image_description: This meme features Ron Burgundy, the comically self-important news anchor from the film 'Anchorman: The Legend of Ron Burgundy,' played by Will Ferrell. He is depicted sitting at his news desk with a serious, deadpan expression, looking directly at the viewer. This format is popularly known as the 'I Don't Believe You' or 'That Escalated Quickly' meme, used to express skepticism towards an absurd claim or to comment on a situation that has intensified unexpectedly.

Sky-Sports-Breaking-News.name: Sky-Sports-Breaking-News

text_options.description: This is the main text area on the news ticker. It typically contains a description of an awkward, embarrassing, or cringeworthy action or statement. This text is the core of the joke, setting up the situation that elicits the contrasting reactions from the two anchors.

This smaller text box on the news ticker, to the left of the main one, usually identifies the person or group responsible for the action described in box 0. It acts as a label or a name tag, attributing the embarrassing behavior to a specific entity.

Sky-Sports-Breaking-News.image_description: This meme, often called "News Anchors Reaction" or "Trying to Hold a Fart," shows two Sky Sports News anchors, a man and a woman, at a desk. The man on the left has a pained or disappointed expression, while the woman on the right appears to be suppressing a laugh. The meme is used to represent an awkward or embarrassing situation where one person is struggling and the other is finding it humorous, with their contrasting reactions forming the basis of the joke.

Fun-Facts-with-Squidward.name: Fun-Facts-with-Squidward

text_options.description: This is the main content area of the meme where the user inserts the 'fun fact.' The text placed here is typically a grim, cynical, or uncomfortable statement that contrasts sharply with the cheerful heading, delivering the punchline of the meme.

Fun-Facts-with-Squidward.image_description: This meme, known as 'Fun Facts with Squidward,' features the character Squidward Tentacles from SpongeBob SquarePants with a smug, knowing expression. He appears to be sharing information in a large speech bubble. The format is used to present a depressing, inconvenient, or unsettling truth under the guise of a 'fun fact,' creating dark humor through the ironic contrast.

One-does-not-simply-blank.name: One-does-not-simply-blank

text_options.description: This is the bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It completes the phrase started in the top text, describing the action or task that is being presented as difficult or complex. For example, it could be the original "walk into Mordor" or a humorous alternative like "find a matching sock."

This is the top text, which sets up the meme's premise. It almost always contains the phrase "One does not simply," establishing the recognizable snowclone format of the meme before the punchline is delivered at the bottom.

One-does-not-simply-blank.image_description: This meme features a still image of the character Boromir, played by Sean Bean, from the film "The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring." In the scene, Boromir is explaining the immense difficulty of entering the enemy territory of Mordor. The meme format, known as "One Does Not Simply," adapts his famous line to humorously describe tasks that are more complicated or challenging than they appear on the surface.

Keep-my-wifes-name-out-of-your-mouth.name: Keep-my-wifes-name-out-of-your-mouth

text_options.description: This area, covering the lower part of the image including Will Smith and Lupita Nyong'o, typically labels the person or group (represented by Will Smith) whose opinion or mood is about to change drastically.

Text in this position, above Will Smith's head, usually describes the joke, comment, or situation that initially elicits the positive, laughing reaction from the subject. It sets up the context for the subsequent, often opposite, reaction.

Keep-my-wifes-name-out-of-your-mouth.image_description: This meme features actor Will Smith laughing enthusiastically in the audience at the 2022 Oscars, with actress Lupita Nyong'o looking on with a more serious expression beside him. This image captures the moment just before Will Smith went on stage to slap Chris Rock over a joke about his wife. The meme is typically used to represent an initial positive or amused reaction to something, which is then dramatically reversed, often by pairing this image with one of the subsequent slap.
Keep-my-wifes-name-out-of-your-mouth.display_name: Keep my wifes name out of your mouth

Expectation-vs-Reality.name: Expectation-vs-Reality

text_options.description: This box is in the "REALITY" row. It is a placeholder for text or an image that represents the actual, often disappointing or comically underwhelming, outcome of a situation. This serves as the punchline of the meme, creating a humorous contrast with the expectation set in the panel above.

This box is in the "EXPECTATION" row. It is a placeholder for text or an image depicting an idealized, desired, or anticipated scenario. This part of the meme sets up the joke by showing what someone hopes or expects will happen.

Expectation-vs-Reality.image_description: This is the "Expectation vs. Reality" meme template, a two-panel format used to humorously contrast an idealized situation with the actual, often disappointing, outcome. The top panel is labeled "EXPECTATION..." to set up a hopeful scenario, while the bottom panel, labeled "REALITY...", delivers the punchline by showing what actually happened. This format is widely used to express relatable frustrations, self-deprecating humor, and the gap between aspirations and the real world.

spongebob-worship.name: spongebob-worship

text_options.description: This label is placed directly on SpongeBob's body. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is completely exhausted or overwhelmed by a situation.

This label is placed in the empty space above and away from SpongeBob. The text here describes the task, event, or minor inconvenience that has caused the extreme state of exhaustion depicted, often something trivial for comedic effect.

spongebob-worship.image_description: This meme, known as "Exhausted SpongeBob" or "SpongeBob Lying on the Floor," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the eponymous animated series lying face-down on the ground, appearing completely drained and defeated. The image is used to humorously represent a state of utter exhaustion, being overwhelmed, or giving up after a strenuous or difficult task. The stark contrast between the cause and the resulting exhaustion creates the comedic effect.

newspaper.name: newspaper

text_options.description: This large, lower section is where the main image of the fake news story is placed. The image serves as the visual punchline or evidence for the headline written above. Its content is crucial for completing the joke, often by providing a literal, absurd, or unexpected illustration of the headline.

This upper section is designated for the main headline of the fake news article. Users typically write a sensational, funny, or ridiculous headline here to set up the premise of the meme. The text in this box is the setup for the visual punchline that will be placed in the area below.

newspaper.image_description: This meme template features the masthead of a fictional newspaper titled "DAILY NEWS". Below the masthead are two large blank sections, designed for a user-created headline and a corresponding image. The format parodies a traditional newspaper layout to create humorous, absurd, or satirical news stories. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the serious, official-looking format with often silly or unbelievable user-generated content.

News-Headline.name: News-Headline

text_options.description: This is the main punchline area, located in the news ticker banner at the bottom labeled 'BREAKING NEWS'. Users insert a fake, often absurd or funny, headline here to create a satirical news report.

This area, placed over Anderson Cooper's head, is not a standard part of the meme's text but can be used to label the subject of the fake news. Often, it's used to label Anderson Cooper himself or a group he is meant to represent in the context of the joke.

News-Headline.image_description: This meme template features CNN news anchor Anderson Cooper with a serious expression in front of a world map background. The format mimics a 'Breaking News' segment, creating a template for users to insert their own humorous or satirical headlines. The humor comes from the contrast between the official news presentation and the often absurd or mundane content of the user-generated text.

Licking-lips.name: Licking-lips

text_options.description: This text label identifies the person, group, or entity represented by the man in the yellow jacket. It's the subject who is eagerly and often greedily anticipating the situation described above.

This text describes the favorable situation, opportunity, or event that the person (labeled in box 0) is excitedly looking forward to. The man's gaze is directed towards this area, reinforcing the idea that this is the source of his anticipation.

Licking-lips.image_description: This meme, known as "Anthony Adams Rubbing Hands" or "Greedy Man Rubbing Hands," features former NFL player Anthony Adams in a bright yellow jacket, peeking from behind a tree. He has a sly, eager expression on his face while rubbing his hands together in anticipation. The meme is used to represent someone who is about to profit from or enjoy a particular situation, often in a mischievous or opportunistic way.

Soldier-jump-spetznaz.name: Soldier-jump-spetznaz

text_options.description: Text here labels the stoic, standing soldier. This represents a person, group, or concept that is either unaware of an impending event, focused on a task, or represents the status quo that is about to be disrupted.

Text over the jumping soldier identifies a chaotic, unexpected, or overwhelming force. This element is the punchline, representing the disruption or problem that is about to crash into the entity labeled on the standing soldier.

Soldier-jump-spetznaz.image_description: This meme, often called "Jumping Ugandan Soldier," features two soldiers against a grey sky. One soldier stands stoically in the foreground holding a rifle, while another soldier in camouflage jumps energetically in the background. The meme's humor comes from the juxtaposition of the calm, oblivious soldier and the chaotic, airborne one. It is typically used as an object-labeling macro to represent an unexpected or disruptive force (the jumping soldier) interrupting a person or situation (the standing soldier).

drake-meme.name: drake-meme

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to Drake's approving gesture. It contains the preferred, superior, or desired option that the meme creator is endorsing.
This text box is adjacent to Drake's gesture of rejection. It is used to label the undesirable, inferior, or disliked option that is being contrasted with the preferred choice below.

drake-meme.image_description: This is the "Drakeposting" or "Drake Hotline Bling" meme, featuring two stills of the rapper Drake from his "Hotline Bling" music video. In the top panel, Drake holds up his hand with a look of disapproval, while in the bottom panel, he smiles and points in approval. This popular reaction meme format is used to express preference by contrasting an undesirable option (top) with a more desirable one (bottom).

Wholesome-Protector.name: Wholesome-Protector

text_options.description: This speech bubble is for the heavily armored knight. Text placed here usually represents a calm, reassuring, or protective statement made by the protector, reinforcing their role in shielding the smaller character.

This label is placed on the small, unarmored character. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept being protected, often something new, innocent, or vulnerable that is being defended from harm.

This label is on the large, armored knight. The text here identifies the protector—a veteran, an established community, a strong brand, or any entity capable of withstanding attacks (represented by the arrows) on behalf of the weaker character.

Wholesome-Protector.image_description: This meme, from a comic by artist SrGrafo, depicts a massive, heavily armored knight shielding a small, defenseless character from a barrage of arrows. The knight, often referred to as the "tank," absorbs all the damage without flinching. The format is used to represent a powerful or experienced entity protecting a weaker, newer, or more vulnerable one from overwhelming threats, criticism, or difficulties.

uno-reverse-card.name: uno-reverse-card

text_options.description: This text label typically represents the person or entity who is now the target of the reversed action or statement. They are the one on the receiving end of the "no, you" comeback.

This text label usually represents the person or entity who initiated the original action, insult, or accusation that is about to be reversed. They are the one who is getting the "Uno reverse card" played on them.

uno-reverse-card.image_description: This is an image of a blue Uno Reverse card, a card from the popular game Uno. In meme culture, this card is used metaphorically to deflect an insult, accusation, or situation back onto the original person. It's a widely recognized symbol for the phrase "no, you" or for turning the tables on an opponent, often used as a comeback in online arguments.

Vein-popping-kid.name: Vein-popping-kid

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the straining student. It typically contains a label identifying the person or group who is struggling to hold something back, often starting with 'Me' or a specific noun. This label establishes the subject of the meme's joke.

Located in the upper portion of the image, this text box describes the action, urge, or statement that the person (labeled in box 0) is desperately trying to suppress. This text provides the crucial context for the student's intense expression, revealing the source of their internal conflict and creating the punchline.

Vein-popping-kid.image_description: This meme, known as 'Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl in Class' or 'Vein Popping Guy,' features a male student in a classroom straining intensely, with veins bulging on his forehead and neck. The image humorously represents an immense effort to suppress an urge, an opinion, or a comment in a social setting. Its versatility allows it to be used for any situation requiring extreme self-control, making the internal struggle visibly and comically apparent.

pepe-punch.name: pepe-punch

text_options.description: Text in the bottom half of the image usually describes the situation, place, or conversation that the character is dropping into. This text provides the context for the sudden arrival, representing the target of the intervention or the scenario being disrupted.

Text placed in the top half of the image typically describes the person, object, or concept that is 'dropping in.' This text acts as a label for the falling Pepe, establishing the powerful or absurd force that is about to enter the scene.

pepe-punch.image_description: This meme features a muscular, smug version of Pepe the Frog, often called GigaChad Pepe, falling through the air with motion blur. The image is used to represent a sudden and overwhelming arrival or intervention. It humorously depicts someone or something 'dropping in' on a situation with immense confidence or a powerful statement, often to disrupt or dominate it.

He-Man.name: He-Man

text_options.description: This text box is in the bottom panel where He-Man is leaving. It typically contains a short, often italicized action phrase describing the departure, such as "*leaves*" or "*disappears*". This text serves as the punchline, representing the user's immediate reaction to the situation presented in the top panel.

Located in the top panel, this text box sets up the premise of the meme. It usually describes an awkward social interaction, an uncomfortable statement, or a situation that would make someone want to leave immediately.

He-Man.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character He-Man from the 1980s cartoon "He-Man and the Masters of the Universe". In the top panel, He-Man looks forward with a concerned or serious expression, and in the bottom panel, he is shown turning away and leaving on a vehicle. The meme is used to humorously depict someone abruptly exiting an awkward, uncomfortable, or undesirable situation that is described in the top panel.

Oregon-trail.name: Oregon-trail

text_options.description: This bottom text box is the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a blunt statement of failure or a negative outcome, directly parodying the status updates from the game, such as the infamous "You have died of dysentery." The text here delivers the comical and often relatable bad news.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It usually describes an action, goal, or situation that the subject is attempting, setting the stage for the inevitable failure announced in the bottom text box. This text provides the context for the punchline.

Oregon-trail.image_description: This meme features a pixelated, green-on-black graphic of an ox pulling a covered wagon, a screenshot from the classic educational video game "The Oregon Trail." The game was known for its difficulty and the abrupt, often comical ways players could fail their journey. The meme format leverages this nostalgia to humorously convey failure, misfortune, or an unfortunate outcome, often mimicking the game's famous "You have died of dysentery" message.

Big-Brain-Wojak.name: Big-Brain-Wojak

text_options.description: This text box is located at the bottom of the image, near the base of the brain-chair. In the context of the 'Expanding Brain' meme format, this area typically contains the text for the final, most 'enlightened' or absurd stage of a thought process. Its position at the bottom of the ultimate panel reinforces its role as the conclusion or punchline of the entire sequence.

This text box covers the massive, oversized brain of the Wojak character. This space is used to label the peak intellectual or pseudo-intellectual concept in the meme's progression. The text here represents the final, most transcendent, or ridiculously over-the-top idea, corresponding to the visual of the 'galaxy brain' itself.

Big-Brain-Wojak.image_description: This meme features the 'Big Brain Wojak' or 'Galaxy Brain' character, a line drawing of a figure with an enormous, pulsating brain, sitting in a chair also made of brain matter while smoking a pipe. It is the final panel in the 'Expanding Brain' meme format, used to represent the ultimate, most profound, or often most absurd and ironic level of thought in a sequence. The meme satirizes intellectualism and overthinking, showing a progression from simple ideas to ridiculously complex or nonsensical ones.

Jackie-Chan-Confused.name: Jackie-Chan-Confused

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically contains the punchline or the specific statement, question, or situation that causes the confusion. This text is the core reason for the bewildered reaction depicted by Jackie Chan.

The top text area is used to set up the context or premise for the joke. It often presents a scenario or a piece of information that seems straightforward at first, leading into the confusing element described in the bottom text.

Jackie-Chan-Confused.image_description: This meme, known as "Jackie Chan Confused" or "My Brain is Full of F*ck," features the actor Jackie Chan with his hands on his head, expressing overwhelming confusion and frustration. His bewildered facial expression makes it a popular reaction image used to convey a state of being mind-blown, baffled, or unable to process illogical or nonsensical information. The meme perfectly captures the feeling of mental overload when confronted with a perplexing situation.

Bro-Not-Cool.name: Bro-Not-Cool

text_options.description: This label is on the disapproving friend. The text here represents the current responsibility, duty, or the sensible choice that is being ignored or betrayed.
This label is on the man who gets distracted. The text here typically represents the user or a subject who is tempted to abandon their responsibilities for something more appealing.
This label is on the woman walking by. The text here represents the new, alluring temptation or distraction that is causing the subject to stray from their original path or commitment.

Bro-Not-Cool.image_description: This two-panel meme, originating from a Gillette commercial, depicts a man being distracted by a passing woman, only to be confronted by his friend. The top panel shows the man (1) looking admiringly at the woman (2), while the bottom panel shows his friend (0) stopping him with a disapproving look. This format is used to illustrate someone being tempted by a new, often irresponsible, option while neglecting their current duties or responsibilities.

Woman-Holding-Kevin-Hart.name: Woman-Holding-Kevin-Hart

text_options.description: This label is placed on the woman being pointed at, who is the source of the conflict or provocation. The text here represents the problem, antagonist, or frustrating situation that elicits a strong, often aggressive, response.

This label is on the woman in the yellow dress who is being held back. This text typically represents the person or entity (often the meme creator) who is on the verge of an impulsive or irrational reaction to the provocation at index 0.

This label is on Kevin Hart, who is acting as the restraining force. The text here represents the person, idea, or circumstance that is preventing the impulsive action, such as a friend, logic, fear of consequences, or a sense of responsibility.

Woman-Holding-Kevin-Hart.image_description: This meme, known as "Kevin Hart Holding Woman Back," originates from the reality TV parody "Real Husbands of Hollywood." It depicts a tense scene where a woman in a yellow dress is being physically restrained by comedian Kevin Hart, preventing her from confronting another woman. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where an impulsive or aggressive reaction is being held in check by a restraining force, such as common sense, a friend, or a potential consequence.

Bonjour.name: Bonjour

text_options.description: This label is placed on or next to the polar bear. It represents the person, entity, or concept that is making a sudden and unexpected appearance, often something that was previously ignored or has returned.

This text at the top of the image sets the context or describes the person/situation that is about to be interrupted by the entity represented by the bear. It establishes the 'before' state, which the bear's arrival disrupts.

Bonjour.image_description: This meme, known as 'Bonjour Bear', features a polar bear peeking its head out of a hole in the snow with the word 'Bonjour' written below it. The image is used to represent the sudden and often unwelcome appearance of a person, problem, or idea into a situation. The friendly French greeting contrasts humorously with the often disruptive or surprising nature of the arrival, creating a sense of comedic timing.

Who-are-we.name: Who-are-we

text_options.description: The text in this bottom-right panel typically introduces a collective thought or reaction from the group, often serving as a counterpoint or a more subdued version of the idea presented on the left.
This bottom-left panel is the first part of a two- or three-part statement. It usually sets up the enthusiastic declaration made by the individual character.
The middle-right panel continues the collective thought from the panel below it. It builds upon the group's reaction or statement.
The middle-left panel continues the individual's enthusiastic statement, building momentum towards the final punchline in the top panel.
This top-right panel concludes the thought process or reaction of the group, often delivering the final part of their collective statement.
The top-left panel contains the punchline or the most exaggerated part of the individual's goal, typically following the "[Verb] all the [nouns]!" format.

Who-are-we.image_description: This is a six-panel meme format known as "All the Things" or "X all the Y," featuring a character from Allie Brosh's webcomic "Hyperbole and a Half." The panels on the left depict a single, hyper-enthusiastic character with a broom, while the panels on the right show a crowd of identical characters. The meme is used to express an overwhelming, often comically absurd, desire to do a large number of tasks or activities, contrasting an individual's manic ambition with a collective sentiment.

Tom-chasing-Harry-and-Ron-Weasly.name: Tom-chasing-Harry-and-Ron-Weasly

text_options.description: This label is placed on Tom, the cartoon cat, who is depicted as the menacing pursuer. The text here identifies the source of the panic or the problem that the other two characters are desperately trying to escape. This is often an everyday annoyance, a responsibility, or an abstract concept framed as a terrifying threat.

This label is on Ron Weasley, who is driving the car with a look of sheer panic. The text here typically represents one of the entities fleeing from the threat identified by label 0. It often works in conjunction with the label on Harry to represent a pair or a group.

This label is on Harry Potter, who is in the passenger seat looking equally terrified. The text here represents the second entity fleeing from the threat. Often, this is labeled as 'Me' or something that complements the label on Ron, creating a relatable scenario of two parties escaping a common problem.

Tom-chasing-Harry-and-Ron-Weasly.image_description: This meme is a crossover image combining a scene from *Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets* with the cartoon character Tom from *Tom and Jerry*. It shows a terrified Harry Potter and Ron Weasley in a car, seemingly being chased by a maniacally grinning Tom who is photoshopped into the rear view. The format is used to represent a situation where someone is frantically trying to escape from an unexpected, often trivial or absurd, problem or entity.
Tom-chasing-Harry-and-Ron-Weasly.display_name: Tom chasing Harry and Ron Weasly

anakin-and-obi-wan.name: anakin-and-obi-wan

text_options.description: This text box is placed on Anakin Skywalker. The text here represents the defiant, angry, or disappointing response from the person or entity being admonished. It serves as the punchline, often a variation of Anakin's line "I hate you!" or another statement that confirms the betrayal.

This text box is placed on Obi-Wan Kenobi. The text here represents the person or entity expressing a sense of betrayal or disappointment. It typically sets up the joke by stating a high expectation that was not met, often paraphrasing Obi-Wan's famous line, "You were the chosen one!"

anakin-and-obi-wan.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the dramatic lightsaber duel between Obi-Wan Kenobi (top) and Anakin Skywalker (bottom) in "Star Wars: Episode III – Revenge of the Sith." Obi-Wan looks distressed and is yelling, while Anakin is screaming in anger. The format is used to express deep disappointment or a sense of betrayal, where Obi-Wan represents the accuser with high expectations, and Anakin represents the one who has failed or defied those expectations.

A-ustedes-les-pagan.name: A-ustedes-les-pagan

text_options.description: The text at the bottom (index 0) is the punchline, delivered from the perspective of the confused character. It's often phrased as a question that reveals the speaker's surprise and naivety about the situation described in the top text, famously starting with 'Wait, you guys are...?'

The text at the top (index 1) sets up the scenario. It typically describes a group of people or a situation that the meme's subject (represented by Kenny) is observing, creating the context for their subsequent confused reaction.

A-ustedes-les-pagan.image_description: This meme features a still of actor Will Poulter as Kenny from the movie 'We're the Millers,' wearing a confused and incredulous expression. The format is typically used to express surprise or disbelief upon learning something that others already knew or were benefiting from. The classic punchline, 'Wait, you guys are getting paid?', perfectly captures the feeling of realizing you're at a disadvantage or have been left out of the loop.

hey-little-man-hows-it-goin.name: hey-little-man-hows-it-goin

text_options.description: This area on the character's chest reveals the punchline. In the original, it's a tape recorder, but in meme variations, it's replaced with a logo or symbol. This object represents the entity being mocked for providing a generic, pre-recorded, or disingenuous response, highlighting their lack of genuine engagement in the conversation.

This large, empty panel is intended to be filled with a long, detailed, or emotionally charged block of text. This text represents the ignored response from the person the main character is talking to. The contrast between this wall of text and the simple, dismissive reply in the final panel creates the meme's humor.

hey-little-man-hows-it-goin.image_description: This four-panel comic, known as "A True Conversationalist" or "Hey Little Man," depicts a crudely drawn character initiating a conversation. After asking "hows it goin?", the character ignores the other person's unseen response and replies with a simple "yea," revealing a tape recorder on their chest. The meme satirizes disingenuous interactions, where one party uses generic or automated replies, completely disregarding the other's input. The tape recorder is often replaced with logos or symbols to mock specific entities for their canned responses.
hey-little-man-hows-it-goin.display_name: hey little man hows it goin

Finally-inner-peace.name: Finally-inner-peace

text_options.description: The bottom text, which reads "Finally, inner peace," serves as the punchline. This phrase is the fixed part of the meme, expressing the ultimate feeling of contentment and relief that the character is experiencing.

The top text area is where the user provides the setup or context. This text describes the specific action, event, or realization that has led to the profound sense of peace, often highlighting a simple or humorous situation.

Finally-inner-peace.image_description: This meme features Master Oogway, the wise tortoise from the animated film "Kung Fu Panda," with a serene and content expression. The image captures a moment of profound peace and acceptance. This format is typically used to humorously express a feeling of immense relief or satisfaction after achieving a long-awaited, often mundane or relatable, goal.

Black-guy-confused.name: Black-guy-confused

text_options.description: The bottom text area. This caption typically describes the confusing situation, statement, or action that elicits the bewildered reaction from the subject. It often works in conjunction with the top caption to set up the joke.

The top text area. This caption usually presents the initial part of a confusing scenario or statement. It sets the context for the punchline or the source of confusion, which is often elaborated on in the bottom text.

Black-guy-confused.image_description: This meme, known as 'Confused Nick Young' or 'Question Mark Guy,' features basketball player Nick Young with a comically bewildered and questioning expression. The image, often edited to include floating question marks around his head, perfectly captures a moment of profound confusion or disbelief. It is widely used to react to nonsensical statements, illogical situations, or anything that makes one question reality.

Guy-pouring-olive-oil-on-the-salad.name: Guy-pouring-olive-oil-on-the-salad

text_options.description: This text labels the small salad, which represents the recipient of the excessive action. It's typically something simple, small, or a situation that is being overwhelmed or 'drowned' by the subject of the olive oil bottle.

This text is placed on the giant bottle of olive oil, representing the thing that is being applied in excessive, overwhelming quantities. This could be anything from a developer's unnecessary updates to a person's over-the-top compliments or a specific, niche interest.

This text labels the smiling man, who represents the person, group, or entity performing the excessive action. Their happy expression highlights a lack of awareness or a deliberate choice to go overboard, making them the agent of the overwhelming force.

Guy-pouring-olive-oil-on-the-salad.image_description: This meme features a stock photo of a smiling man pouring an absurdly large jug of olive oil onto a small salad. The image is used to represent someone enthusiastically applying an excessive or overwhelming amount of something to a situation or object that doesn't require it. The humor lies in the extreme disproportion between the action and its target, symbolizing over-the-top efforts, unwanted additions, or smothering affection.
Guy-pouring-olive-oil-on-the-salad.display_name: Guy pouring olive oil on the salad

Wants-to-know-your-location.name: Wants-to-know-your-location

text_options.description: This text box identifies the entity making the location request. It typically contains the word "Google" to match the search engine theme, but can be replaced with any name or character to customize the joke, representing the person or group that is searching.

This is the Google search bar where the user inputs a query. The text here sets up the premise of the joke, often being a search for a person, a hard-to-find object, or a concept, which then triggers the comically invasive location request below.

Wants-to-know-your-location.image_description: This meme format, known as "Google Wants to Know Your Location," humorously depicts the perceived intrusiveness of technology. It consists of two parts: a Google search bar with a specific query, and a browser pop-up below it asking for the user's location. The joke lies in the juxtaposition, suggesting that Google (or another entity) is taking the search query literally and is actively trying to find the person or thing in the physical world. This meme is used to comment on privacy concerns or to create absurd scenarios where a search becomes a real-life hunt.

Tom-and-Jerry-swordfight.name: Tom-and-Jerry-swordfight

text_options.description: This label identifies the third party, represented by Jerry the mouse. This entity is typically the cause of the conflict between the two characters in the top panel, often something seemingly small or innocent that has sparked a major dispute.
This label identifies one of the two conflicting parties, represented by Tom the cat. This entity is shown actively fighting with the other character.
This label identifies the second conflicting party, represented by Spike the dog. This entity is shown in direct opposition to the character labeled at index 1.

Tom-and-Jerry-swordfight.image_description: This two-panel meme from the cartoon 'Tom and Jerry' illustrates a conflict dynamic. The top panel shows Tom the cat and Spike the dog sword fighting, representing two powerful or opposing entities. The bottom panel shows Jerry the mouse with a shocked expression, representing a third, often smaller, party who is the cause of the conflict or is caught in the middle. The meme is used to humorously depict situations where two groups are fighting over or because of a third one.

Mr-Mackey.name: Mr-Mackey

text_options.description: The bottom text contains the punchline, which is a variation of Mr. Mackey's catchphrase. It often takes the form of '[The bad thing] is bad, m'kay?' to deliver a condescending or simplistic moral judgment on the action described in the top text.

The top text describes an action, belief, or situation that is generally considered negative, illegal, or socially unacceptable. This text serves as the setup, presenting the 'bad' thing that Mr. Mackey is reacting to.

Mr-Mackey.image_description: This meme features Mr. Mackey, a character from the animated show South Park, looking distressed. It's used to humorously condemn actions or behaviors that are considered wrong or inappropriate. The format typically presents a negative action followed by Mr. Mackey's catchphrase, 'M'kay,' framing it as a moral lesson.

Donkey-staring.name: Donkey-staring

text_options.description: The bottom text, typically a punchline or a reaction. This text often represents the meme creator's internal thought or a direct, often blunt or absurd, response to the situation established in the top text. Its placement at the bottom concludes the joke, with Donkey's stare emphasizing the statement.
The top text, which serves as the setup for the meme. It usually describes a scenario, a question, or a statement made by another person that the meme creator is reacting to.

Donkey-staring.image_description: This meme features a distorted, front-facing, close-up image of the character Donkey from the movie series "Shrek." His wide-eyed, blank stare directly at the viewer creates a sense of awkwardness or silent judgment. The meme is typically used as a reaction image to express confusion, disbelief, or a deadpan response to a preceding statement or situation, often in a two-panel text format.

grave-spongebob.name: grave-spongebob

text_options.description: This text is placed on the tombstone. It labels the hope, dream, plan, or expectation that has 'died' or failed, serving as the punchline of the meme. For example, 'My plans for the weekend' or 'My New Year's resolutions'.

This text is placed over Squidward. It identifies the person or group who is mourning the loss of the thing written on the tombstone. It is most commonly labeled 'Me' to make the meme relatable to the viewer's own disappointments.

grave-spongebob.image_description: A two-panel meme from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants, known as 'Squidward's Grave'. The top panel shows the character Squidward Tentacles kneeling sadly before a tombstone, holding a bouquet of flowers. The bottom panel is a close-up of the tombstone. This meme is used to humorously represent the death of hopes, dreams, or expectations, with Squidward representing the disappointed individual and the tombstone representing the failed concept.

Too-weak-Unlimited-Power.name: Too-weak-Unlimited-Power

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the image of Palpatine unleashing his full power. The text here represents the same entity from the top panel, but now revealing its true, powerful nature, creating a humorous contrast. This is the punchline of the meme.

This text box is placed over the image of Palpatine feigning weakness. The text here typically describes a person, group, or object that is pretending to be weak, helpless, or uninterested to set up the joke.

Too-weak-Unlimited-Power.image_description: This two-panel meme features Emperor Palpatine from Star Wars: Revenge of the Sith. In the top panel, he appears frail and defeated, with the caption "I'm too weak." In the bottom panel, he unleashes powerful Force lightning with a malevolent grin, captioned "Unlimited Power!". The meme is used to humorously contrast a feigned state of weakness or reluctance with a sudden, overwhelming display of strength, enthusiasm, or capability.

You-have-no-power-here.name: You-have-no-power-here

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, serving as the punchline. It typically contains the quote 'You have no power here' or a variation, representing the subject's dismissive and defiant response to the statement or authority mentioned in the top text.
This is the top text, which sets up the meme's premise. It usually presents a command, a rule, a warning, or a statement from an authority figure that the meme's creator wishes to mock or defy.

You-have-no-power-here.image_description: This meme features King Théoden from 'The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers' in a decrepit and weakened state while under Saruman's influence. He is shown slouched on his throne with a faint, mocking smile. The meme is used as a reaction image to dismiss an authority, rule, or statement, juxtaposing a command or declaration with Théoden's iconic, defiant line, 'You have no power here.' It humorously represents a situation where someone's perceived authority is completely irrelevant or ineffective.

Baby-Boss-Relaxed-Smug-Content.name: Baby-Boss-Relaxed-Smug-Content

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, identifying the person or entity feeling smug and satisfied. It often starts with 'Me:' or a similar label, directly linking the smug expression of the baby to the subject of the joke.

The top text box sets up the scenario or describes the action that leads to the feeling of satisfaction. This text provides the context for the baby's smug reaction, explaining what minor victory or clever maneuver has just occurred.

Baby-Boss-Relaxed-Smug-Content.image_description: This meme features a baby sitting in a high chair with a smug, self-satisfied expression and hands clasped behind its head. Known as 'Smug Baby' or 'Relaxed Baby,' the image conveys a feeling of accomplishment, cleverness, or being in control of a situation. It's typically used to humorously boast about a minor victory or a situation that turned out perfectly in one's favor, like a boss enjoying a well-executed plan.

Blank-Bingo.name: Blank-Bingo

text_options.description: This large area at the top of the card, containing the number 25, serves as a placeholder for the main title of the Bingo game. The title sets the theme, such as "Family Dinner Bingo" or "Bad Action Movie Bingo."

A placeholder square on the Bingo grid, intended to be replaced with a specific cliché or predictable event related to the card's theme.
This text, with overlapping numbers '2' and '6', is a placeholder for the title of the Bingo card. The title establishes the specific scenario or topic the meme is satirizing.

Blank-Bingo.image_description: This is a "Bingo Card" meme template, featuring a 5x5 grid with a central "Free!" space. The other squares are numbered placeholders, intended to be filled with common phrases, events, or tropes related to a specific topic. This format is used to satirize the predictability of certain situations, with users metaphorically shouting "Bingo!" when a line of these clichés is observed.

Political-compass.name: Political-compass

text_options.description: This text box is in the Libertarian Right (LibRight) quadrant. Text placed here typically represents or satirizes ideologies focused on free-market capitalism, minimal government, and individual liberties, often associated with stereotypes like anarcho-capitalism, gun ownership, and the phrase "don't tread on me."

This text box is in the Libertarian Left (LibLeft) quadrant. Content here usually represents or mocks ideologies centered on social justice, anti-authoritarianism, and progressive values. In memes, this quadrant is often stereotyped with topics like environmentalism, anarcho-communism, and identity politics.

This text box is in the Authoritarian Right (AuthRight) quadrant. Text in this area typically represents or satirizes ideologies that value tradition, authority, and nationalism. Common stereotypes used for humor include conservatism, monarchy, and religious fundamentalism.

This text box is in the Authoritarian Left (AuthLeft) quadrant. Text here generally represents or satirizes ideologies involving strong state control and a centrally planned economy. It is most commonly associated with stereotypes of communism and socialism, with jokes often referencing figures like Stalin or concepts like gulags and state-enforced equality.

Political-compass.image_description: This is the Political Compass meme, a four-quadrant chart that plots political ideologies along two axes: economic (left-right) and social (authoritarian-libertarian). The four quadrants are Authoritarian Left (red), Authoritarian Right (blue), Libertarian Left (green), and Libertarian Right (purple/yellow). The format is widely used to satirize political stereotypes by placing text, images, or Wojak characters representing each ideology within their respective quadrant.

Ronald-McDonald-Temp.name: Ronald-McDonald-Temp

text_options.description: This label is placed on Ronald McDonald's body and represents the person or entity making the urgent phone call. This is the protagonist of the meme, who is reacting with alarm or complaint to the situation described above.
Text placed in this top region describes the absurd, frustrating, or shocking event that has prompted the phone call. It serves as the catalyst for the reaction from the character labeled at index 0.

Ronald-McDonald-Temp.image_description: This meme features the fast-food mascot Ronald McDonald holding a phone receiver to his ear with a concerned or urgent expression. The image is used to represent someone making a frantic, absurd, or demanding complaint to an authority figure. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the normally cheerful character in a serious or confrontational situation, often used to express disbelief or the need for immediate intervention.

Matrix-Pills.name: Matrix-Pills

text_options.description: This area, over the hand holding the blue pill, represents the choice of blissful ignorance or the status quo. Text placed here describes the easier, more comfortable, or conventional option that allows one to remain in a state of unknowing.

This area, over the hand holding the red pill, represents the choice of accepting a difficult or life-changing truth. Text placed here describes the challenging, unconventional, or eye-opening option that leads to a deeper understanding of reality.

Matrix-Pills.image_description: This meme originates from a pivotal scene in the 1999 film "The Matrix," where the character Morpheus offers the protagonist, Neo, a choice between two pills. The red pill represents embracing a harsh, life-altering truth, while the blue pill symbolizes remaining in blissful ignorance. Culturally, this image is used as a metaphor to frame a difficult choice between two opposing options, often a challenging reality versus a comfortable falsehood.

Sad-Megamind.name: Sad-Megamind

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, typically a noun followed by a question mark. It represents the thing that the subject of the meme is supposedly lacking, for example, "Bitches?", "Maidens?", or any other desirable object or concept. This text completes the question started in the top box.

The top text box, placed on Megamind's large forehead, contains the setup for the joke. It almost always consists of the single word "No", which begins the question that is completed by the text at the bottom.

Sad-Megamind.image_description: This meme features a distorted, close-up image of the character Megamind from the 2010 animated film of the same name, looking down with a sad or judgmental expression. Known as the "No Bitches?" or "Megamind Peeking" meme, it is used to humorously question or point out a person's lack of something, whether it be romantic partners, skills, or possessions. The setup involves a question posed across the top and bottom of the image, creating a condescending punchline.

PEPPERIDGE-FARMS-REMEMBERS.name: PEPPERIDGE-FARMS-REMEMBERS

text_options.description: This area contains the fixed punchline of the meme, "PEPPERIDGE FARMS REMEMBERS." This text is the core of the meme's identity, delivering the judgmental or nostalgic final word that follows the setup text placed at the top of the image.

This top section is where the user adds text to set up the meme's joke. It typically describes a past event, a forgotten promise, or a simpler time, often starting with "Remember when...". This text provides the specific context for what "Pepperidge Farm remembers."

PEPPERIDGE-FARMS-REMEMBERS.image_description: This meme, known as "Pepperidge Farm Remembers," originates from a "Family Guy" parody of nostalgic commercials for the Pepperidge Farm brand. It features an elderly man in old-fashioned attire on a horse-drawn carriage, looking sternly at the viewer. The meme is used to express nostalgia or to sarcastically point out when someone has forgotten a past promise, a previous state of affairs, or how things used to be better. The format contrasts a past situation described in the top text with the unchanging, long memory of Pepperidge Farm.

staring-fish.name: staring-fish

text_options.description: The bottom text represents the punchline or the fish's direct, often awkward or confrontational, response to the situation described in the top text. It's the core of the joke, delivered with the intensity of the fish's stare.

The top text box establishes the context or setup for the meme. It typically describes a situation, a question posed to the viewer, or a statement made by someone else that warrants the fish's intense reaction.

staring-fish.image_description: This meme, known as "Staring Fish" or "Fish Looking at Camera," features a close-up, front-facing shot of a triggerfish underwater. Its intense, direct gaze is used to represent an awkward, blunt, or confrontational reaction to a preceding statement or situation. The meme follows a setup-punchline format, where the fish's stare embodies the directness of the punchline.

Randy-Marsh-computer.name: Randy-Marsh-computer

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically represents the person or entity reacting with shame or exhaustion. The text here often describes the user's state after witnessing or doing something questionable, aligning with Randy's defeated posture.

The top text box is used to label the cause of the reaction. This is where the meme creator places the name of the shocking, overwhelming, or embarrassing content they have just consumed, providing context for the scene.

Randy-Marsh-computer.image_description: This meme features the character Randy Marsh from the animated show South Park, sitting in front of a computer and covered in a white substance, which in the show is referred to as "ectoplasm." The scene depicts a moment of post-indulgence shame and exhaustion. This image is widely used to express feelings of guilt, disgust, or being caught in an embarrassing or questionable act, particularly after consuming a large amount of online content.

Jewish-guy.name: Jewish-guy

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, serving as the punchline. This text almost invariably delivers a joke based on antisemitic stereotypes, often related to greed, financial gain, or trickery. The man's welcoming, open-handed gesture is contextually re-framed by the text to appear as if he is making a sly deal or proposition.

The top text of the meme, which provides the setup for the joke. This text typically introduces a situation or poses a question that will be answered by the punchline below, setting the stage for a punchline based on a Jewish stereotype.

Jewish-guy.image_description: This meme, often referred to as the "Happy Merchant," features a smiling Jewish man in front of what appears to be the Western Wall. The image is used as a highly controversial and often antisemitic meme template to perpetuate stereotypes about Jewish people, particularly concerning money, business, and schemes. The format is a standard image macro, with a setup at the top and a punchline at the bottom that typically relies on these stereotypes.

Lisa-Simpson-Coffee-That-x-shit.name: Lisa-Simpson-Coffee-That-x-shit
