text_options.description: This label is placed on Lisa Simpson's face and arm. It represents the person, group, or entity that is smugly and eagerly receiving something. This is often labeled 'Me' or a specific type of person who enjoys absorbing the thing represented by the coffee.

This label is placed on the coffee pot. It represents the source or the concept being 'poured' into or absorbed by the person labeled at index 0. This could be anything from gossip and drama to specific information, ideologies, or content.

Lisa-Simpson-Coffee-That-x-shit.image_description: This meme features Lisa Simpson from 'The Simpsons' with a smug, knowing expression while holding a mug as coffee is poured into it. The format is used to represent someone eagerly and self-satisfyingly absorbing something, often information, drama, or a specific viewpoint. Lisa represents the recipient, while the coffee being poured symbolizes the concept she is consuming.
Lisa-Simpson-Coffee-That-x-shit.display_name: Lisa Simpson Coffee That x shit

panik-calm-panik.name: panik-calm-panik

text_options.description: This text box, located in the bottom panel next to the motion-blurred, panicking Meme Man, delivers the punchline. It introduces a new, often worse, problem or a negative consequence of the previous statement, creating a sudden twist that makes the situation more dire than the initial problem.

This text box is in the middle panel, corresponding to the serene "Kalm" image of Meme Man. It typically contains a statement that describes a solution, a positive realization, or a moment of relief that resolves the initial problem mentioned in the top panel.
This text box is in the top panel, alongside the first "Panik" image. It sets the scene by describing an initial stressful or problematic situation that causes the user to panic.

panik-calm-panik.image_description: This is the "Panik, Kalm, Panik" meme, a three-panel format featuring the surreal 3D character Meme Man. The meme illustrates a short narrative of escalating anxiety: a stressful situation causes panic, followed by a moment of relief when a solution appears, only for a new, often worse, realization to trigger even greater panic. The humor lies in the relatable rollercoaster of emotions and the absurd twist in the final panel.

I-choose-you.name: I-choose-you

text_options.description: This bottom text area reveals the 'chosen one' or the solution to the problem stated above. It functions as the punchline, often being an absurd, funny, or unexpected choice that Ash is 'summoning' with his Poké Ball to handle the situation.
The top text area is used to describe a problem, a challenge, or a situation that requires a specific response. This sets up the context for the punchline that follows below.

I-choose-you.image_description: This meme features Ash Ketchum from the Pokémon anime, dynamically throwing a Poké Ball. The image captures a moment of intense action, symbolizing the act of choosing or summoning something. It's famously used in the "Go! I choose you!" format, where a user presents a problem or situation and then 'chooses' a humorous or fitting person, object, or concept to deal with it.

Girlspaining.name: Girlspaining

text_options.description: This area is typically used to label the man's internal thoughts. The text here represents the simple, unrelated, or mundane thing he is thinking about, contrasting with the complex topic being explained to him. For example, it might say "I wonder if I left the stove on" or "She's cute but I can't hear a thing."

This area represents the long, passionate, and often niche explanation the woman is giving. The text here is usually a dense block of text detailing a complex topic, like the lore of a video game, a historical event, or a convoluted personal story, which serves to highlight the man's disinterest.

Girlspaining.image_description: This meme, known as "Girl Explaining" or "Bro Explaining," features a young woman with her mouth open, yelling into the ear of a young man who looks bored and disinterested. The setting appears to be a loud outdoor event like a music festival. The format humorously contrasts someone passionately explaining a niche or complex topic with the listener's complete lack of interest, who is often depicted as thinking about something mundane.

Pulp-Fiction-Say-What-One-More-Time.name: Pulp-Fiction-Say-What-One-More-Time

text_options.description: This area represents the target of the user's frustration or demand. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that is being aggressively questioned or commanded by the character Jules Winnfield.

This is the main caption area, where the user's aggressive question or demand is placed. The text here mimics Jules Winnfield's intense dialogue from the film, often phrased as a challenge or a final warning, to create the meme's punchline.

Pulp-Fiction-Say-What-One-More-Time.image_description: A still from the film 'Pulp Fiction' shows Jules Winnfield (Samuel L. Jackson) aggressively pointing a gun and yelling at another man. This meme, known as 'Say What Again,' is used to express extreme frustration or to make a forceful, often humorous, demand. The user embodies Jules's intimidating presence to emphasize their point or question.
Pulp-Fiction-Say-What-One-More-Time.display_name: Pulp Fiction Say What One More Time

Old-guy-pc.name: Old-guy-pc

text_options.description: This text box is in the bottom panel. It typically contains the punchline or the painful realization that results from the action described in the top panel. This text reveals the awkward or unfortunate truth, which is amplified by Harold's pained smile directed at the viewer.

This text box is in the top panel. It usually describes an initial action, thought, or situation that sets up the joke. This text represents the "before" or the facade of normalcy before the painful truth is revealed in the panel below.

Old-guy-pc.image_description: This is a two-panel meme featuring András Arató, better known as "Hide the Pain Harold." In both panels, he sits at a desk with a laptop, holding a mug. The top image shows him looking at the laptop, while the bottom shows him looking at the camera, both with his signature expression that seems to be a smile masking deep pain or discomfort. This format is used to contrast an initial action or thought with its painful or awkward consequence, representing someone trying to maintain composure despite internal suffering.

Mr-Incredible-Uncanny.name: Mr-Incredible-Uncanny

text_options.description: This text box is associated with the disturbed, black-and-white image of Mr. Incredible. The text here presents a horrifying, unsettling, or shocking realization that serves as the punchline, directly contrasting with the initial, more positive statement.

This text box is placed over the normal, smiling Mr. Incredible. It typically contains a positive, innocent, or seemingly harmless statement or scenario. This sets up the initial, pleasant context before the meme reveals a darker twist.

Mr-Incredible-Uncanny.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Traumatized Mr. Incredible" or "Mr. Incredible Becoming Uncanny," contrasts two versions of the character from Pixar's *The Incredibles*. On the left, a normal, smiling Mr. Incredible represents a positive or naive viewpoint. On the right, a distorted, black-and-white, and horrified version of him represents a disturbing or shocking realization. The meme is used to show a progression from a pleasant thought to a deeply unsettling one.

Tony-Stark-success.name: Tony-Stark-success

text_options.description: The bottom text box, positioned below Tony Stark, serves as the punchline. It describes the creation, achievement, or result being presented, which is usually something underwhelming, silly, or comically specific, creating a humorous juxtaposition with Stark's proud and dramatic presentation.
The top text box sets up the context of the meme. It typically identifies the person, group, or entity who is proudly presenting something, establishing the 'creator' in the scenario.

Tony-Stark-success.image_description: This meme features Tony Stark (played by Robert Downey Jr.) from the movie Iron Man 2, standing on a brightly lit stage in a tuxedo with his arms outstretched. Known as "Tony Stark's Presentation" or "I Present...", the image captures a moment of proud, almost arrogant, showmanship. The meme is typically used in a two-panel format to humorously present a creation or achievement that is often trivial, unimpressive, or absurd, contrasting with Stark's grandiose pose.

Dinkleberg-Blank.name: Dinkleberg-Blank

text_options.description: This bottom text box is for the punchline of the meme: "...IF I HAD ONE!" This part delivers the core of the joke, emphasizing the character's (and the user's) frustration and lack of the desired item.

The top text box is used for the setup of the meme. It typically contains a phrase like, "This is where I'd put my [desired object/achievement]...", which establishes what the user is lamenting not having.

Dinkleberg-Blank.image_description: This meme features an angry-looking Mr. Turner from the animated series 'The Fairly OddParents'. The image is taken from a scene where he yells, "This is where I'd put my trophy... IF I HAD ONE!" The meme is used to express extreme frustration and disappointment over not having something that one desires or feels they deserve.

gondor-calls-for-aid.name: gondor-calls-for-aid

text_options.description: This text box is placed over King Théoden. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is a dismissive and often illogical response or excuse to the statement made in the top panel. This text frequently follows the phrasal template "And where was [X] when [Y] happened?" to highlight hypocrisy or a refusal to cooperate.

This text box is placed over Aragorn. The text here sets up the meme's scenario, typically presenting a reasonable request, a call for help, or a logical argument that the user wants to see get unfairly dismissed.

gondor-calls-for-aid.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the film "The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers." The top panel features Aragorn earnestly making a point, while the bottom panel shows King Théoden of Rohan looking away with a dismissive expression. The meme is used to contrast a reasonable request or statement (Aragorn) with a weak, selfish, or whataboutist excuse for inaction (Théoden), often parodying Théoden's line, "Where was Gondor when the Westfold fell?"

Jordan-Peele-Sweating.name: Jordan-Peele-Sweating

text_options.description: The text at the bottom, though less common in this format, typically labels the person or entity experiencing the stress described in the top text. It explicitly identifies who is represented by the sweating character, often simply stating 'Me'.
The text at the top of the image describes the stressful or anxiety-inducing scenario. It sets the context for the character's nervous reaction, acting as the setup for the visual punchline.

Jordan-Peele-Sweating.image_description: This meme features comedian Jordan Peele from a 'Key & Peele' sketch, where he is sweating profusely and looking extremely nervous. Known as 'Sweating Jordan Peele' or 'Nervous Sweat,' it's used to humorously depict intense anxiety, stress, or fear in a high-pressure situation. The image perfectly captures the feeling of being on the spot, trying to make a difficult decision, or waiting for a dreaded outcome.

Robert-Downey-Jr-Annoyed.name: Robert-Downey-Jr-Annoyed

text_options.description: The bottom text box, positioned over Tony Stark's crossed arms, typically contains a label identifying the person or group who is reacting with annoyance. This text clarifies who is feeling the exasperation depicted by the eye-roll in response to the statement above.

The top text box contains the setup for the meme. It describes a statement, question, or situation that is meant to be perceived as foolish, annoying, or painfully obvious, thereby justifying Tony Stark's extreme eye-rolling reaction.

Robert-Downey-Jr-Annoyed.image_description: This meme features Robert Downey Jr. as Tony Stark from the Marvel movie 'The Avengers,' making an exaggerated, annoyed face with his eyes rolled back and arms crossed. Known as the 'Tony Stark Eye Roll' or 'Robert Downey Jr. Eye Roll,' this reaction image is used to express extreme exasperation, sarcasm, or disbelief in response to something perceived as incredibly stupid, obvious, or frustrating.

Chris-Farley-For-the-love-of-god.name: Chris-Farley-For-the-love-of-god

text_options.description: This text, placed at the bottom, typically describes a person, group, or a simple statement that triggers the extreme reaction from the character above. It sets up the context for the punchline.

This text, placed over Chris Farley's yelling face, represents the loud, emphatic, and often absurd warning or declaration he is shouting. This is the main punchline of the meme, conveying an over-the-top reaction to the situation described in the bottom text.

Chris-Farley-For-the-love-of-god.image_description: This meme features comedian Chris Farley as his Saturday Night Live character, Matt Foley, a comically intense motivational speaker. In the image, Foley is hunched over and yelling, a pose taken from his famous sketch where he warns teenagers they'll end up "living in a van down by the river." The meme is used to express an overly aggressive, loud, or passionate warning, often in response to a mundane or minor issue, highlighting a dramatic overreaction.
Chris-Farley-For-the-love-of-god.display_name: Chris Farley For the love of god

Goodfellas-Laugh.name: Goodfellas-Laugh

text_options.description: This bottom text box is where the punchline or the funny statement is placed. It's the direct cause of the uproarious laughter depicted in the image, delivering the core of the joke.
This top text box typically contains the setup or context for the joke. It describes a situation, a person, or a preceding statement that the characters in the meme are reacting to with laughter.

Goodfellas-Laugh.image_description: This meme features a still from the 1990 film *Goodfellas*, showing actor Ray Liotta and others laughing hysterically. Known as "Goodfellas Laughing" or "Ray Liotta Laughing," the image is used to react to a joke, a funny situation, or a statement that is found to be absurdly amusing. It perfectly captures the feeling of a group erupting in shared, unrestrained laughter.

Picard-Riker-listening-to-a-pun.name: Picard-Riker-listening-to-a-pun

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the bottom panel, which contains the punchline. The text here describes the disappointing, foolish, or cringeworthy outcome or statement that causes Commander Riker's facepalm reaction, creating a humorous contrast with the setup in the top panel.

This text box is positioned over the top panel, which serves as the setup for the meme. The text here typically introduces a normal situation, a serious question, or a hopeful statement, establishing the context before the disappointing punchline in the panel below.

Picard-Riker-listening-to-a-pun.image_description: This two-panel meme, often called 'Picard and Riker Facepalm' or 'Annoyed Picard,' originates from Star Trek: The Next Generation. It features Captain Jean-Luc Picard and Commander William Riker reacting to a situation. The top panel shows them with serious expressions, setting up a scenario, while the bottom panel shows Riker facepalming in exasperation as Picard looks on stoically. This format is used to express frustration, disappointment, or secondhand embarrassment in response to a foolish statement or a disappointing outcome.
Picard-Riker-listening-to-a-pun.display_name: Picard Riker listening to a pun

Crying-kid-with-gun.name: Crying-kid-with-gun

text_options.description: Text in this bottom section, placed over the handgun, describes the difficult, unpleasant, or destructive action that must be performed. It represents the "what" of the situation – the hard choice or task at hand.

Text in this top section, placed over the crying boy's face, identifies the person, entity, or group that is being forced to take the unpleasant action. This label represents the reluctant actor in the scenario.

Crying-kid-with-gun.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Crying Kid with a Gun," features a stock photo of a young boy in a red shirt crying while holding a handgun. The meme is used to represent a situation where someone is forced to do something they find emotionally difficult or painful, often an act of destruction or betrayal. The crying boy represents the reluctant individual, while the gun symbolizes the necessary but unpleasant action they must take.

crying-wojak-mask.name: crying-wojak-mask

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the crying Wojak face, representing the person's true, hidden feelings or the harsh reality of their situation. The text here reveals the internal pain, sadness, or frustration that contrasts with the outward appearance.

This text box is positioned over the smug mask, representing the public facade or the statement someone makes to appear calm, confident, or superior. The text here is what the person wants others to see or believe, hiding their true emotions.

crying-wojak-mask.image_description: This meme, known as "Wojak Mask" or "Crying Wojak Behind Mask," depicts a crying Wojak character hiding his face behind a smug, calm-looking mask. The stark contrast between the hidden emotion and the outward facade is the core of the meme. It is used to represent someone pretending to be fine, confident, or unaffected on the outside while secretly feeling sad, angry, or distressed.

What-Do-We-Want-3.name: What-Do-We-Want-3

text_options.description: This is the first panel in the 'reality' column on the right. Text here typically describes the initial, often boring or problematic, situation that sparks the ambitious plan in the adjacent panel (1).

This is the first panel in the 'expectation' column on the left. The text here usually states a grand, overly ambitious goal, often in the format 'X all the Y!', which is a reaction to the situation described in panel 0.

This is the middle panel on the right, continuing the 'reality' narrative. It usually describes an action taken by the character that deviates from the original plan, often a form of procrastination or a step that complicates things.

This is the middle panel on the left, continuing the 'expectation' or internal monologue. The text here often represents a new, revised, or equally ambitious thought that justifies the action in panel 2.
This is the final panel on the right, serving as the punchline. The text describes the ultimate, underwhelming result of the character's actions, showing the failure to achieve the original goal.

This is the final panel on the left, representing the peak of the character's ambition or the intended final step of the grand plan. It creates a stark and humorous contrast with the actual outcome in panel 4.

What-Do-We-Want-3.image_description: This is a six-panel comic meme featuring the 'All the Things' character, also known as Hyperbole and a Half. The left column depicts a single, manically energetic character with a broom, representing ambitious plans or intentions. The right column shows multiple, subdued, or sad versions of the same character, representing the mundane or disappointing reality. The meme's humor comes from contrasting the grand expectations (left) with the underwhelming outcome (right), often telling a short story of procrastination or failure.

Trust-Nobody-Not-Even-Yourself.name: Trust-Nobody-Not-Even-Yourself

text_options.description: This label identifies the betrayer or the agent of sabotage. In the context of the meme, this character is often labeled with the same entity as the victim to highlight the self-destructive nature of the action.

This label identifies the unsuspecting victim who is about to be betrayed. It is typically labeled with the same text as the person holding the gun (index 0) to create the punchline about self-sabotage.

This area at the top of the image is typically used for a caption that sets up the scenario or provides the overarching theme. It often contains a statement describing the self-defeating action or a variation of the phrase 'Trust Nobody, Not Even Yourself'.

Trust-Nobody-Not-Even-Yourself.image_description: This meme, known as "Trust Nobody, Not Even Yourself," features a person pointing a gun at the back of their own head, achieved through image editing. It visually represents the concept of self-sabotage, betrayal from an unexpected source, or being one's own worst enemy. The meme is used to humorously illustrate situations where an individual or group acts against their own interests.

Umbrella-Academy-Car.name: Umbrella-Academy-Car

text_options.description: This text is placed over Number Five, who has a shocked and alarmed expression. It represents the person or entity having a sudden, often negative, realization in response to the statement or action presented in the top panel. This is the punchline of the meme.

This text is placed over Vanya, who has a calm, neutral expression. It typically represents a person making an innocent statement, asking a question, or performing an action that inadvertently causes alarm or reveals a shocking truth to the other person. This text sets up the joke.

Umbrella-Academy-Car.image_description: A two-panel meme from the Netflix series "The Umbrella Academy," featuring characters Vanya (top) and Number Five (bottom) driving in separate cars. Vanya looks over with a neutral expression, while Number Five looks back with a shocked and alarmed expression. The format is used to contrast a calm or naive statement/action (Vanya) with a shocking or problematic realization or response (Five).

Sad-Pepe-Suicide.name: Sad-Pepe-Suicide

text_options.description: Text placed here typically represents the person or group reacting with despair. This is the subject of the meme who is metaphorically about to stick the fork in the outlet.

Text in this top panel describes the cause of the distress. It's the external event, statement, or situation that is so unbearable it provokes the extreme, self-destructive reaction from the character in the bottom panel.

Sad-Pepe-Suicide.image_description: This meme features a sad-looking Pepe the Frog, a popular and versatile internet character, squatting on the floor while holding a fork near an electrical outlet. The image humorously and hyperbolically represents a feeling of extreme despair, frustration, or a desire to give up in response to a negative or cringeworthy situation. It is often used to convey a reaction of "I can't take this anymore" in a darkly comedic way.

Power-Ranger-Teletubbies.name: Power-Ranger-Teletubbies

text_options.description: This area in the final panel often contains a caption summarizing the situation or the group's collective identity, though it is frequently left blank as the humor is conveyed through the labels on the hands.
This label is placed on the Teletubby's hand. It represents the punchline of the meme—the outlier, the absurd addition, or the unwelcome element that doesn't fit with the rest of the group.
This label is on one of the Power Rangers' hands, representing the final member of the cohesive group before the outlier joins. It's one of several related items being listed.
This label is on a Power Ranger's hand as it joins the huddle. It represents another item that belongs to the established, coherent group.
This label is on a Power Ranger's hand, continuing the team huddle. It represents a third item that fits logically with the others in the group.
This label is on the second Power Ranger's hand to join the huddle. It represents another item in a list of things that are similar or belong together.
This label is on the first Power Ranger's hand. It represents the first item in a list of related or compatible things, setting up the theme for the group.

Power-Ranger-Teletubbies.image_description: A multi-panel comic meme featuring the Power Rangers and a Teletubby. The first panels show the Power Rangers putting their hands together in a team huddle, but their effort is interrupted by Tinky Winky, the purple Teletubby, who cheerfully adds his hand. The final panel shows the Power Rangers looking annoyed and confused at the unexpected addition. This meme format is used to represent a cohesive group or list of related items being joined by an absurd or out-of-place outlier.

Marked-safe.name: Marked-safe

text_options.description: This bottom text box is for the undesirable thing, event, or person that the subject is 'safe' from. It serves as the punchline, humorously framing something trivial or annoying as a major disaster from which one needs protection.

This top text box typically identifies the person, place, or situation that is providing the 'safety' or is the desirable alternative. It sets up the context for the joke, contrasting with the 'threat' mentioned in the bottom box.

Marked-safe.image_description: The 'Marked Safe From' meme is a template that parodies Facebook's Safety Check feature. It features a blue flag icon and the text 'MARKED SAFE FROM' positioned between two customizable text areas. This format is used to humorously declare oneself safe from an undesirable or trivial situation, person, or event, often contrasting it with a more desirable alternative.

Opera.name: Opera

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image typically contains the second part of the announcement or the punchline. It often mirrors the top text, completing the phrase "And YOU get a [item]!" to emphasize that everyone is receiving the specified thing.
The text placed in this top box usually contains the first part of Oprah's famous giveaway line, such as "You get a [item]!". This text establishes what is being generously distributed to everyone.

Opera.image_description: This meme, known as "Oprah's You Get a Car," features a jubilant Oprah Winfrey in a red dress with her arms outstretched, holding a microphone. The image is from a famous episode of her talk show where she gave away cars to the entire audience. It is used to humorously express over-the-top generosity or the widespread distribution of something, whether desirable or not, to a group of people.

Last-Place-Douche-Bag.name: Last-Place-Douche-Bag

text_options.description: This area covers the entire winners' podium. Text here often labels the different tiers to create a hierarchy or ranking of related concepts, with the most superior at the top and the subject of ridicule at the very bottom, represented by the celebrating athlete.

A label is placed on the athlete's chest to identify the person, group, or concept being mocked. This text establishes the subject who is celebrating a minor or insignificant achievement with unwarranted enthusiasm.

Last-Place-Douche-Bag.image_description: This two-part meme format, often called "Bronze Medalist Celebration" or "First Place Celebration," depicts an athlete in a blue tracksuit wildly celebrating a low-ranking achievement. The top four panels show him receiving a medal, biting it, spraying champagne, and giving middle fingers. The final, wider panel reveals he is on the lowest step of a multi-tiered winners' podium, highlighting his misplaced and excessive pride. The meme is used to satirize someone or something celebrating a minor accomplishment as if it were a major victory.

Me-when-Im-in-a--competition-and-my-oppo.name: Me-when-Im-in-a--competition-and-my-opponent-is-

text_options.description: This text box identifies the opponent in the competition. The humor comes from this opponent being someone or something that is the epitome of the skill mentioned in the competition, making it an impossible challenge for the user (represented by Squidward).
This text box is where the user defines the type of competition they are in. It sets the context for the joke, which is completed by revealing the unbeatable opponent in the next line.

Me-when-Im-in-a--competition-and-my-oppo.image_description: This meme features a distorted, low-quality image of Squidward Tentacles from SpongeBob SquarePants looking stressed and wide-eyed. The text above sets up a hypothetical scenario: "when I'm in a [competition] and my opponent is [someone/something]". The meme is used to humorously express the feeling of being hopelessly outmatched when facing an opponent who is an expert or the very embodiment of the skill being competed in, leading to the user's inevitable and comical defeat.
Me-when-Im-in-a--competition-and-my-oppo.display_name: Me when Im in a  competition and my opponent is

Bugs-Bunny-King.name: Bugs-Bunny-King

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, representing the meme creator's supposedly superior or more enlightened perspective. It often contrasts with the statement in the top box, framing the creator as more intelligent or having better taste, complementing Bugs Bunny's smug expression.
The top text box establishes the premise of the meme. It typically describes a group of people, a common action, or a popular opinion that the meme's creator finds inferior or foolish.

Bugs-Bunny-King.image_description: This meme features the Looney Tunes character Bugs Bunny dressed in royal attire, including a purple robe and a gold crown, sitting on a throne. His expression is smug and condescending, with half-closed eyes and a slight smirk. Known as 'King Bugs Bunny' or 'Smug Bugs Bunny,' this reaction image is used to express a feeling of superiority or to dismiss someone else's opinion or preference as inferior.

Consuela.name: Consuela

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the punchline, which is almost always Consuela's catchphrase, 'No... no...'. It represents her simple, unwavering refusal to the request or statement presented in the top text.
The top text area is the setup for the joke. It typically contains a question, a command, or a statement from one party, which Consuela (representing the meme creator) will firmly reject.

Consuela.image_description: This meme features Consuela, the stoic housekeeper from the animated TV show 'Family Guy'. In the image, she is on the phone, looking unimpressed, which captures her typical demeanor. The meme format is used to humorously and stubbornly refuse a request or reject a statement, channeling her famous catchphrase, 'No... no...'. It's a popular reaction image for expressing a simple, non-negotiable denial.

23-wolves-laugh.name: 23-wolves-laugh

text_options.description: This label is placed on one of the two 'laughing' wolves. The text here typically represents one of two people or concepts that are part of a joke or a shared amusing experience, working in tandem with the text at index 2.

This label is on the central, serious-looking wolf. The text here represents the punchline of the meme—the unamused person, the voice of reason, or a mundane thought that contrasts sharply with the other two.

This label is on the second 'laughing' wolf. The text here represents the other person or concept involved in the joke or amusing situation, setting up the contrast for the unimpressed wolf in the middle.

23-wolves-laugh.image_description: This meme, known as 'Laughing Wolves' or 'Three Wolves,' features two white wolves with their mouths open in what appears to be laughter, flanking a third wolf with a serious, unimpressed expression. The format is used to contrast two people who find a situation funny or exciting with a third who is tired, annoyed, or has a completely different perspective. The humor arises from this relatable group dynamic, where one person acts as the straight man to their friends' antics.

i-am-spartacus.name: i-am-spartacus

text_options.description: This bottom caption typically represents the more experienced, weary, or knowledgeable individual (Spartacus). The text here sets up the correct or jaded perspective on the situation, which is then contrasted by the enthusiastic statement above.

This top caption represents the enthusiastic, naive, or newcomer's perspective (the shouting man). The text here is often a loud, incorrect, or overly eager statement that creates a humorous contrast with the more reserved character's viewpoint described in the bottom text.

i-am-spartacus.image_description: This meme originates from the 1960 film 'Spartacus' and features two characters with contrasting expressions. On the left, a man shouts with passionate defiance, while on the right, the main character Spartacus looks on with a weary, stoic expression. The meme is used to contrast an enthusiastic, often naive or incorrect, reaction (the shouting man) with a more experienced, jaded, or disapproving one (Spartacus) in response to a shared situation.

Tuna-the-dog-Phteven.name: Tuna-the-dog-Phteven

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This text is almost always written with a lisp, replacing 's' sounds with 'th' to mimic the dog's appearance (e.g., "Phteven" instead of "Stephen"). This punchline represents the awkward or silly response to the situation described in the top text.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a scenario or context. This text typically describes a situation where a person might feel awkward, anxious, or say something foolish.

Tuna-the-dog-Phteven.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Tuna, a Chiweenie dog with a pronounced overbite, known online as "Phteven" (a lisping pronunciation of "Stephen"). The dog's awkward, toothy grin and wide eyes, combined with a formal bow tie, create a humorous contrast. The meme is typically used to represent social awkwardness, cringeworthy situations, or someone trying too hard to be sophisticated and failing.

King-Ghidorah.name: King-Ghidorah

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the goofy, silly-looking dragon head on the right. It contains the punchline of the meme, representing the outlier, the failure, or the absurdly simple or dumb version of the concept established by the other two heads.

This text box corresponds to the central, most aggressive-looking dragon head. The text here represents a second serious, competent, or impressive example, reinforcing the pattern set by the first head and building up the contrast for the final punchline.

This text box is positioned over the serious dragon head on the left. The text here typically describes a competent, serious, or respectable example of a subject, setting up the comparison for the rest of the meme.

King-Ghidorah.image_description: This meme features a fan-art depiction of King Ghidorah, a three-headed dragon from the Godzilla franchise. Two of the heads are portrayed as menacing and serious, while the third head on the right is drawn in a goofy, cartoonish style with googly eyes. This format is used to compare three related items, where the first two are competent or serious, and the third (often called 'Kevin' by fans) is a comically inept or absurd outlier, serving as the punchline.

Good-Guy-Greg.name: Good-Guy-Greg

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, describing the unexpectedly kind, helpful, or considerate action that Good Guy Greg performs. This text completes the scenario set up by the top text and highlights his selfless nature.
The top text sets up a common social scenario or situation. It provides the context in which a person could act selfishly or neutrally, creating an expectation for the punchline.

Good-Guy-Greg.image_description: This is the "Good Guy Greg" meme, a classic image macro format featuring a slightly blurry photo of a smiling man with a cigarette or joint in his mouth. The character is portrayed as a kind, considerate, and selfless individual. The meme is used to highlight positive and thoughtful actions, often in everyday social situations, presenting a wholesome counterpoint to more negative character memes.

godfather.name: godfather

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which almost invariably contains the punchline and famous quote: 'Look how they massacred my boy.' This line directly expresses the user's profound disappointment and dismay at the perceived degradation of the subject.
The top text area, which serves as the setup for the punchline. This text typically describes the original, beloved subject or concept that is about to be shown in its 'massacred' or ruined state.

godfather.image_description: This meme features Marlon Brando as Don Vito Corleone from the 1972 film 'The Godfather'. The image captures a moment of solemn disappointment and is famously paired with the quote, 'Look how they massacred my boy.' It is used to express sadness or disgust when something cherished, like a movie, video game, or even a piece of food, has been ruined or poorly altered.

epic-hand-shake.name: epic-hand-shake

text_options.description: Text in this area typically labels the two muscular arms separately. Each arm represents a different group, person, or concept, often ones that are considered rivals or opposites. This sets up the premise of the meme by identifying the two unlikely allies.

Text placed over the clasped hands serves as the punchline. It describes the common belief, action, or characteristic that unites the two entities labeled on the arms below. This text reveals the surprising and often humorous point of agreement between the two.

epic-hand-shake.image_description: This meme, known as "Epic Handshake" or "Predator Handshake," is a still from the 1987 film Predator, featuring a muscular arm-wrestle-style handshake between characters Dutch (Arnold Schwarzenegger) and Dillon (Carl Weathers). The image symbolizes an unexpected agreement or shared characteristic between two otherwise disparate or opposing groups. Culturally, it's used to highlight surprising common ground, with the two arms representing the different factions and the clasped hands representing their point of unity.

Who-the-fk-starts-a-conversation-like-th.name: Who-the-fk-starts-a-conversation-like-that-I-just-sat-down

text_options.description: This text box, placed in the calm first panel, contains the absurd, inappropriate, or jarring statement that provokes Peter's outburst. It serves as the setup for the punchline, representing the conversation starter that is so out of place it warrants Peter's incredulous reaction.

Who-the-fk-starts-a-conversation-like-th.image_description: This two-panel meme from the animated show "Family Guy" features characters Glenn Quagmire and Peter Griffin at a bar. The top panel depicts a seemingly normal moment, which is then contrasted by the bottom panel where Peter angrily exclaims, "Who the fuck starts a conversation like that I just sat down!". This format is used to react to an abrupt, strange, or overly intense opening to a conversation, with the top panel setting up the bizarre statement and the bottom delivering the punchline reaction.
Who-the-fk-starts-a-conversation-like-th.display_name: Who the fk starts a conversation like that I just sat down

Tom-and-Spike-fighting.name: Tom-and-Spike-fighting

text_options.description: This label is placed over Jerry the mouse. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is benefiting from the conflict between the other two, or who may have secretly caused it. Jerry's smug expression is key to this role.
This label is on Tom the cat, who is engaged in a sword fight. The text here represents one of the two main conflicting parties in the scenario being depicted.
This label is on Spike the dog, who is fighting Tom. The text here represents the second conflicting party, the direct opponent of the entity labeled over Tom.

Tom-and-Spike-fighting.image_description: This three-panel meme from the cartoon 'Tom and Jerry' depicts a conflict and a beneficiary. The top panel shows Tom the cat and Spike the dog fighting with swords, representing two opposing forces. The bottom panel features Jerry the mouse with a smug, knowing expression, representing a third party who instigated the conflict or is benefiting from it while the others are distracted.

Skipping-steps.name: Skipping-steps

text_options.description: This label is on the lowest step the boy is on. It represents the starting point or the first action in an illogical sequence of events.
Placed on the next step up, this label marks the second stage in the convoluted process, building upon the initial strange action.
This label is on the third step in the sequence. It continues the narrative of the absurd progression, often representing a further complication or an unnecessary step.
Positioned on a higher step where the boy's hands are, this label signifies a more advanced stage in the unconventional process, leading toward the final goal at the top of the stairs.

Skipping-steps.image_description: This meme, known as 'Boy Crawling Up Stairs,' shows a young boy in a red shirt and cap ascending a staircase on all fours. The image humorously illustrates a situation where someone chooses a bizarre, convoluted, or inefficient method to accomplish a task or progress through stages. The individual steps are typically labeled to represent the illogical sequence of actions, highlighting the absurdity of the approach compared to a simpler, more direct way.

I-am-inevitable.name: I-am-inevitable

text_options.description: This is the original subtitle from the movie, 'I am inevitable.' It serves as the punchline of the meme, reinforcing the idea of an inescapable fate or a certain outcome presented by the label on Thanos.

This area is where a user-added label is placed to identify the 'inevitable' force or entity. This text recontextualizes Thanos's powerful statement to apply to a more mundane or humorous situation, such as 'Procrastination' or 'Monday morning'.

I-am-inevitable.image_description: This meme features the villain Thanos from the movie 'Avengers: Endgame' as he is about to snap his fingers and says his famous line, 'I am inevitable.' The image captures a moment of perceived ultimate victory and power. It is used to represent an unstoppable force, a certain doom, or an unavoidable outcome in a wide variety of humorous or relatable situations.

research-cat.name: research-cat

text_options.description: Text placed over the laptop keyboard typically represents what the cat is typing. This is often depicted as frantic, nonsensical keyboard mashing (e.g., 'asdfghjkl'), onomatopoeia for rapid typing, or a specific, often aggressive or witty, message to emphasize the cat's serious demeanor.

A caption is usually placed in this area above the cat's head to provide context for the scene. This text describes the situation that requires such intense focus, often in a relatable way, such as 'Me writing a 10-page essay the night before it's due' or 'Explaining my point in an online argument.'

research-cat.image_description: This meme features a cat wearing round glasses and a bow tie, sitting in front of a laptop with a serious expression. Often referred to as "Serious Cat" or "Typing Cat," this image is used to humorously represent intense focus, furious typing, or someone working diligently on a task. The humor comes from anthropomorphizing the cat into a studious or professional figure.

Angry-face.name: Angry-face

text_options.description: This text box is for the statement made by the conformist character. It typically contains a popular slogan, hashtag, or opinion related to a recent event or trend, often framed as a virtue signal. This phrase is the catalyst for the NPC Wojak's eventual anger.

This text box is typically used to label the NPC Wojak character. The text here represents the individual or group that is silently observing and disagreeing with the popular opinion presented in the adjacent panel. Often, this space is left blank to emphasize the character's role as a silent, stoic observer.

Angry-face.image_description: This four-panel comic meme features the NPC Wojak, a grey, emotionless character, encountering a simple, expressive character. The NPC Wojak, representing someone who thinks independently, observes the other character espousing a popular opinion. The meme culminates with the NPC Wojak becoming angry, satirizing the frustration with perceived social conformity and groupthink, often summarized as supporting "the current thing."

Sarcastic-spongebob.name: Sarcastic-spongebob

text_options.description: Text placed over SpongeBob represents the person or entity that is panicking, overreacting, or running away from something.
Text placed over Squidward in the background represents the mundane task, responsibility, or person that is causing the disproportionate panic in the subject represented by SpongeBob.

Sarcastic-spongebob.image_description: A meme featuring SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series of the same name. SpongeBob is in the foreground with a panicked, wide-eyed expression, seemingly running away. In the background, visible through a window, his neighbor Squidward Tentacles stands calmly. This meme format is used to represent an exaggerated reaction of fear or avoidance towards a simple, mundane, or harmless task, person, or responsibility.

excited.name: excited

text_options.description: This text is placed on the lower part of the image, over the man's torso. It typically contains the punchline or the excited reaction itself, often a simple, all-caps exclamation like 'OH MY GOD' or a description of the joyous feeling.

Positioned at the top of the image, this text serves as the setup or context. It describes a situation, event, or piece of news that would cause the extreme, positive reaction depicted by the character.

excited.image_description: A still image from the 2011 film 'Horrible Bosses' shows a man, played by P.J. Byrne, with his hands raised and mouth wide open in a scream of pure ecstasy. This meme, often called 'Ecstatic Guy' or 'Oh My God', is used as a reaction image to express overwhelming joy, excitement, or sometimes sarcastic enthusiasm. The format typically involves a top text setting up a positive scenario, with the image itself serving as the punchline.

Beavis--Butthead.name: Beavis--Butthead

text_options.description: The bottom text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a person, group, or a common, often less desirable, action or idea. This text is associated with both characters but primarily sets the stage for the contrast, often aligning with Butt-Head's oblivious nature.

The top text box delivers the punchline of the meme. It represents a superior, more clever, or niche alternative to what is described in the bottom text. This text aligns with Beavis's smug expression, signifying that this is the 'winning' or 'smarter' side of the comparison.

Beavis--Butthead.image_description: This meme features the animated characters Butt-Head (left) and Beavis (right) from the TV show "Beavis and Butt-Head". Butt-Head stares forward blankly, representing a simple or mainstream idea, while Beavis looks at him with a smug, knowing grin, representing a superior or more clever counterpoint. The format is used to create a humorous contrast between two subjects, with the one associated with Beavis being framed as the winner or more desirable option.

white-background.name: white-background

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which typically delivers the punchline or the main point of the meme. It concludes the thought or scenario introduced by the top text, often with a humorous, ironic, or relatable twist.

This is the top text area, used to set up the context or premise of the meme. The text here introduces a situation, a character's thought, or a general statement that the bottom text will then react to or complete.

white-background.image_description: This is a generic two-panel meme template, commonly known as the "Top Text, Bottom Text" format. It's one of the most foundational and classic meme structures, often associated with the "Advice Animal" style popular in the early 2010s. The format is simple: a top caption sets up a situation or statement, and a bottom caption provides a punchline, reaction, or consequence, with an image typically placed in the middle.

tired-cat.name: tired-cat

text_options.description: The bottom text area, labeled with index 0, provides the punchline or the reaction to the situation described in the top text. It often expresses the feeling of giving up, needing a break, or the state of being completely drained, mirroring the kitten's sleepy posture.

The top text area, labeled with index 1, sets up the scenario or describes the cause of the exhaustion. This text typically introduces a task, problem, or situation that is mentally or physically draining.

tired-cat.image_description: This meme features a small, sleepy tabby kitten resting its head on a computer keyboard, bathed in sunlight. The image conveys a strong sense of exhaustion, burnout, or the desire to procrastinate. This format is typically used as a reaction image to express feeling overwhelmed by work, school, or other responsibilities, using the kitten's adorable fatigue as a relatable stand-in for the user's own feelings.

Triggered-Liberal.name: Triggered-Liberal

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which typically delivers the punchline. This text describes the specific, often trivial, thing that supposedly caused the person's extreme reaction, acting as the 'trigger' in the meme's context.

The top text of the meme, which sets up the scenario. This text usually presents a statement, action, or general situation that the person in the image is reacting to, serving as the setup for the punchline at the bottom.

Triggered-Liberal.image_description: This meme, known as "Triggered" or "Screaming Feminist," features a person with glasses and short hair yelling with a wide-eyed, intense expression. The image is a still from a video of a protest and is used to mock people who are perceived as being easily offended or having an extreme, disproportionate reaction to a statement or event. It is typically used as an image macro where text describes a situation that "triggers" the person.

Nerd-emoji.name: Nerd-emoji

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is the pedantic correction or overly detailed explanation delivered by the "nerd." It directly refutes or elaborates on the statement in the top text, embodying the know-it-all persona of the emoji.

The top text box typically presents a statement, opinion, or common misconception that the "nerd" character is about to correct. This sets up the joke by providing the context for the pedantic response that follows.

Nerd-emoji.image_description: This meme features the "Nerd Face" emoji, a yellow smiley with large, black-rimmed glasses and prominent buck teeth. The emoji is used to represent a stereotypical nerd or know-it-all character. The meme format typically involves quoting a statement and then providing a pedantic, overly detailed, or condescending correction, often prefaced with a phrase like "Um, actually...". It's used to mock nitpicking and unsolicited corrections online.

Happy-Squirrel.name: Happy-Squirrel

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically sets up the context or describes the subject of the meme. It often represents a person or a group facing a challenge or a mundane situation, grounding the meme before the punchline.

Positioned at the top where the squirrel is looking, this text represents the glorious outcome, the object of praise, or the event that causes the dramatic reaction. It serves as the punchline, creating a humorous contrast with the setup text below.

Happy-Squirrel.image_description: This meme, often called 'Happy Squirrel' or 'Dramatic Squirrel,' features a squirrel standing on its hind legs with its arms raised towards the sky. The pose is highly expressive, conveying a sense of overwhelming joy, praise, relief, or sometimes sarcastic celebration. The meme is typically used in a two-part format to contrast a situation with a highly desired or positive outcome that elicits this dramatic reaction.

Blank-Comic-Panel-2x2.name: Blank-Comic-Panel-2x2

text_options.description: This is the fourth and final panel, located at the bottom right. In the "Loss" meme, this panel is the punchline, depicting one character standing and another lying down to represent the "|_" part of the iconic pattern, revealing the tragic or absurd conclusion.

This is the third panel, located at the bottom left. In the sequence of the "Loss" meme, this panel typically shows two standing characters, corresponding to the second "||" in the "| || || |_" pattern, continuing the narrative build-up.

This is the second panel, located at the top right. Following the first panel, this section usually depicts two standing characters, representing the first "||" in the "| || || |_" pattern of the "Loss" meme.

This is the first panel of the comic, located at the top left. In the context of the "Loss" meme, this panel sets the scene and typically features a single standing character, representing the initial "|" in the "| || || |_" pattern.

Blank-Comic-Panel-2x2.image_description: This is a blank four-panel comic template for the infamous "Loss" meme, also known as "Is this Loss?". Originating from a dramatic 2008 "Ctrl+Alt+Del" webcomic about a miscarriage, the meme has evolved into an abstract visual pattern (| || || |_) representing the positions of the characters in each panel. The format is used as an elaborate inside joke, where creators hide this minimalist pattern in various images, and the challenge for viewers is to recognize it.

Spongebob-money.name: Spongebob-money

text_options.description: This text, placed over SpongeBob's wallet in the bottom panel, describes a desirable but often unnecessary item or hobby that the user is extremely eager to spend money on. SpongeBob's manic expression and readiness to open his wallet correspond to this impulsive or passion-driven purchase.

Located in the top panel, this text describes a necessary, practical, or expensive item that the user is reluctant to pay for. SpongeBob's tired and bored expression reflects this feeling of obligation or financial drain.

Spongebob-money.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "SpongeBob's Wallet," contrasts spending habits using two different images of SpongeBob SquarePants. The top panel shows a tired and unimpressed SpongeBob, representing reluctance to spend money on necessary or expensive items. The bottom panel features a hyper-realistic, crazed, and excited SpongeBob eagerly opening his wallet, symbolizing an enthusiastic willingness to spend money on desirable, often frivolous, things. The meme humorously highlights selective or hypocritical financial priorities.

Dragon-Ball-opening.name: Dragon-Ball-opening

text_options.description: This text box is placed in the foreground, often over the white feather. It contains the punchline of the meme, revealing the trivial, absurd, or pun-based 'treasure' that was the object of the long search implied by the Dragon Balls.

This text box is placed over the collected Dragon Balls. It typically labels the collection itself, setting up the premise of a completed quest. The text here often re-contextualizes the Dragon Balls as some other set of collectible items to fit the meme's narrative.

Dragon-Ball-opening.image_description: This image is a still from the opening of the anime series Dragon Ball Z, showing all seven Dragon Balls gathered on a rocky landscape with a single white feather in the foreground. This scene is used in the 'Finally, After All These Years' meme format. The meme juxtaposes the epic feeling of completing a long quest (gathering the Dragon Balls) with a mundane, absurd, or pun-based punchline, representing the long-sought-after 'treasure'.

terminator-arnold-schwarzenegger.name: terminator-arnold-schwarzenegger

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline. It typically describes the meme creator or a subject acting with the same unstoppable determination as the Terminator, fulfilling the mission set up by the top text.

The top text, which sets up the premise or the 'mission' for the Terminator. This often describes a request, a promise, or a situation that the subject of the meme will later address with intense focus.

terminator-arnold-schwarzenegger.image_description: A close-up shot of Arnold Schwarzenegger as the T-800 from the 1984 film 'The Terminator'. He is wearing his iconic sunglasses and a black leather jacket, holding a large pistol with a determined and menacing expression. This image is used as a reaction meme to represent someone who is relentlessly focused on a task, often a mundane one, contrasting the character's serious demeanor with a trivial goal.

Proudness.name: Proudness

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the cringeworthy statement that elicits Michael Scott's pained reaction. It's the core of the joke, creating the awkward or uncomfortable situation that the meme is reacting to.
The top text box typically sets up the scenario or presents a question/statement from one party in a conversation. It provides the necessary context for the awkward punchline that follows below.

Proudness.image_description: This meme features Michael Scott from the TV show 'The Office' with a pained, forced smile, trying to suppress strong emotions. It's often called 'Michael Scott's Cringe' and is used to express secondhand embarrassment, awkwardness, or discomfort in response to a cringeworthy situation. The format typically presents a setup followed by an awkward punchline, with Michael's face representing the reaction to the punchline.

Could-you-not--for-5-MINUTES.name: Could-you-not--for-5-MINUTES

text_options.description: This text is placed on Shrek's annoyed face in the bottom panel. It typically labels the person or entity whose request for peace has just been violated, representing their exasperated reaction.

This label is placed on Donkey, who is seen in the background of the bottom panel. It identifies the person, group, or concept that is causing the disruption and ignoring the request made in the first panel.

This text is placed over the smiling Shrek in the top panel. It contains the initial, often desperate, plea for a brief moment of calm, famously phrased as "Can you [not do something], FOR FIVE MINUTES?" This sets up the comedic failure depicted in the panel below.

Could-you-not--for-5-MINUTES.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as "For Five Minutes," originates from the 2001 film "Shrek." The top panel shows the ogre Shrek smiling peacefully, while the bottom panel shows him looking exasperated at his companion, Donkey, in the background. The meme is used to express frustration when a brief period of peace or normalcy is immediately interrupted. Shrek represents someone making a simple request, while Donkey represents the person or thing that instantly foils it.

maury-povich.name: maury-povich

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which reveals the 'truth' and contradicts the statement above. It often starts with the classic phrase from the show, "The lie detector determined that was a lie," or a variation of it, delivering the humorous refutation.

The top text box is used to present a statement, quote, or claim that is about to be debunked. This text sets up the premise of the joke, presenting something that is widely believed, said, or hoped for, but will be proven false by the punchline.

maury-povich.image_description: This meme features Maury Povich, host of the talk show "Maury," looking down at a results card. The image is taken from his famous lie detector or paternity test segments. The meme format, known as "Maury Lie Detector," is used to humorously call out a false statement by presenting a claim and then revealing it to be a lie, mimicking the dramatic reveals on the show.

Calvin-Peeing.name: Calvin-Peeing

text_options.description: This area is where the target of disdain is placed. Text or a logo here represents the person, brand, sports team, or concept that the creator of the meme is expressing contempt for, as it's the object Calvin is urinating on.

This space on Calvin's shirt is used to identify the person or entity expressing the disdain. It often contains a logo or name of a rival to the target in box 0, framing the act as a statement of superiority or opposition.

Calvin-Peeing.image_description: This meme, known as 'Peeing Calvin' or 'Calvin Pissing', features a bootleg, black-and-white drawing of the character Calvin from the comic strip 'Calvin and Hobbes'. He is depicted with a mischievous grin while urinating on something off-screen. This image is famously used as a car decal to express contempt, defiance, or dislike for a particular rival brand, sports team, political figure, or concept.

Not-stonks.name: Not-stonks

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline "not stonks," a deliberate misspelling of "not stocks." This text is the core of the meme, explicitly stating that the situation has resulted in a loss. Its placement near the bottom, aligned with the downward-pointing arrow, reinforces the negative outcome.

This upper section of the image is part of the background, showing the stock market chart. In meme formats, this area is often used to add a caption describing the action or decision that led to the financial loss. The text here provides the context or the setup for the "not stonks" punchline below.

Not-stonks.image_description: This is the "Not Stonks" meme, a variation of the popular "Stonks" meme. It features Meme Man, a surreal, poorly-rendered 3D character, dressed in a business suit with his arms crossed. He stands in front of a stock market chart with a large arrow pointing downwards, symbolizing a financial loss or a poor decision. This meme is used to humorously comment on situations that result in failure, loss, or a bad outcome, contrasting with the original meme's theme of unexpected success.

Turn-up-the-volume.name: Turn-up-the-volume

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the person reacting emotionally. It typically describes the specific moment in the song or the particular lyric that triggers this intense reaction, serving as the punchline of the meme (e.g., "Me when the beat drops").

Located on the top panel over the volume knob, this text box is used to label the song, artist, or quote that the person is listening to. It sets up the context for why the volume is being turned up so dramatically.

Turn-up-the-volume.image_description: This two-panel meme, often called "Volume Up," expresses intense appreciation for a piece of music or a powerful statement. The top panel shows a hand turning a volume knob to the maximum, while the bottom panel features a person with headphones reacting with overwhelming emotion. The meme is used to highlight a song, lyric, or quote that is so good it demands to be heard at full volume, capturing the feeling of being deeply moved by audio content.

Calling-the-police.name: Calling-the-police

text_options.description: This bottom area is part of the reaction image. While often left blank, text here can sometimes specify who the man is calling (e.g., 'Hello, police?') to reinforce the punchline that he is reporting the offense described in the top text.

The text placed in the top section (index 1) describes a situation, action, or statement that is considered comically unacceptable, cringeworthy, or 'illegal' in a hyperbolic sense. This text serves as the setup for the joke, providing the reason for the man's disapproving phone call.

Calling-the-police.image_description: This meme, known as 'Martin' or 'Black Guy on the Phone,' features a man in a blue striped polo shirt talking on a cell phone with a serious, concerned expression. He looks directly at the viewer as if reporting something he has just witnessed. The meme is typically used to humorously express disapproval or outrage over a trivial, absurd, or cringeworthy situation by pretending to call the police or another authority figure.

Confucius-Says.name: Confucius-Says

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which serves as the punchline of the proverb. It typically contains the pun or the unexpected, often humorous or mundane, twist that subverts the expectation of ancient wisdom set up by the top text.

This is the top text, which acts as the setup for the joke. It usually begins with a phrase like "Confucius say..." or another statement that mimics the start of a wise aphorism, establishing the format.

Confucius-Says.image_description: This meme features a classical portrait of the Chinese philosopher Confucius, often referred to as "Confucius Say" or "Wise Confucius." The format is used to present a seemingly profound proverb that turns out to be a modern pun, a silly observation, or a double entendre. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the sage's serious and wise appearance with the often mundane or ridiculous nature of the text.

Police-Chasing-Guy.name: Police-Chasing-Guy

text_options.description: This label is placed on the man running away. It represents the person, group, or idea that has successfully provoked, outsmarted, or escaped from the entity represented by the chasing cop. This character is the triumphant protagonist of the meme's narrative.

This label is placed on the chasing riot police officer. It represents the authority figure, institution, or individual who has been angered, annoyed, or outwitted and is now giving chase in frustration. This character is the antagonist or the 'butthurt' party in the scenario.

Police-Chasing-Guy.image_description: This meme, often called 'Running Away From Cop' or 'Butthurt Smuggler,' depicts a man in a black beanie gleefully running away from a police officer in full riot gear. The image captures a dynamic of playful defiance or successful trolling. It's typically used to represent someone getting away with a mischievous or annoying act, leaving an authority figure or opponent frustrated and in pursuit.

Unhelpful-High-School-Teacher.name: Unhelpful-High-School-Teacher

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It typically contains the unhelpful, contradictory, or sarcastic part of the teacher's statement, revealing the absurdity of her advice or instructions.
The top text of the meme, which sets up the scenario. This line usually presents the beginning of a teacher's instruction, a question from a student, or a general classroom situation.

Unhelpful-High-School-Teacher.image_description: This meme, known as 'Unhelpful High School Teacher,' features a stock photo of a smiling woman in a classroom setting, standing in front of a chalkboard and a world map. Part of the classic 'Advice Animal' image macro series, it is used to satirize teachers who give contradictory, useless, or nonsensical advice. The humor arises from the contrast between her friendly appearance and the unhelpful or frustrating statement presented in the text.

Is-mayonnaise-an-instrument.name: Is-mayonnaise-an-instrument

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Patrick's trumpet and lower body. It contains the punchline of the meme: the absurd or foolish question that derails the conversation, replacing Patrick's original line, "Is mayonnaise an instrument?".

Positioned at the top of the image, this text box sets up the context for the meme. It typically describes a serious situation, a topic of discussion, or a question posed to a group, which is then interrupted by the nonsensical question in the box below.

Is-mayonnaise-an-instrument.image_description: This meme, known as "Is Mayonnaise an Instrument?", originates from the SpongeBob SquarePants episode "Band Geeks". It features the character Patrick Star, a pink starfish, holding a trumpet with a confused expression, alongside Sandy Cheeks and other characters in a band. The meme is used to represent someone asking a profoundly stupid, irrelevant, or nonsensical question in a serious context, highlighting their cluelessness.

Why-cant-you-just-be-normal-blank.name: Why-cant-you-just-be-normal-blank

text_options.description: The text here represents one of the two conflicting parties or viewpoints. Placed over the screaming child, it often embodies a more naive, demanding, or panicked perspective in a chaotic argument or situation.

This text represents the second party in the conflict, opposing the viewpoint in the bottom panel. Placed over the screaming mother, this label often represents a more authoritative, exasperated, or equally panicked counter-argument, completing the dynamic of a mutual shouting match.

Why-cant-you-just-be-normal-blank.image_description: This two-panel meme, taken from the horror film 'The Babadook,' shows a mother and her son screaming frantically inside a car. It is used to represent two opposing groups, ideas, or individuals who are in a state of mutual panic, intense disagreement, or shared distress over a common situation. The top panel (the mother) and the bottom panel (the son) are labeled with conflicting perspectives, visually depicting a chaotic argument or shared frustration where both sides are equally agitated.
Why-cant-you-just-be-normal-blank.display_name: Why cant you just be normal blank

Look-At-All-These.name: Look-At-All-These

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the field of flowers, sets up the premise of the joke. It typically describes a large quantity of something the user is ironically presenting, often starting with phrases like 'Look at all the...'.

The top text, positioned over the mountains and sky, delivers the punchline. This text reveals that the items mentioned in the bottom text are actually absent, empty, or non-existent, creating the meme's sarcastic and humorous effect.

Look-At-All-These.image_description: This meme features a still of Julie Andrews as Maria from the 1965 film 'The Sound of Music,' with her arms outstretched in a vast mountain meadow. The image is used sarcastically to gesture towards a large quantity of something, which is often revealed to be non-existent or undesirable. The meme's humor comes from the contrast between Maria's joyful, welcoming posture and the typically cynical or empty statement made by the text.

I-Too-Like-To-Live-Dangerously.name: I-Too-Like-To-Live-Dangerously

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, typically containing the exact phrase 'I also like to live dangerously.' This text is attributed to Austin Powers and reveals his comically low-stakes interpretation of the risky situation presented in the top text.
This is the setup text, usually describing a rule, warning, or a situation that implies some level of risk or defiance. It sets the stage for Austin Powers' humorous and anticlimactic response.

I-Too-Like-To-Live-Dangerously.image_description: A still image of the character Austin Powers from the movie series of the same name, smirking slightly. He is wearing a red velvet suit, a white frilly cravat, and black-rimmed glasses. This image is famously used in the 'I also like to live dangerously' meme format, which juxtaposes a statement about a risky or forbidden action with Austin's comically mundane act of rebellion.
I-Too-Like-To-Live-Dangerously.display_name: I Too Like To Live Dangerously

Oprah---you-get-a-car.name: Oprah---you-get-a-car

text_options.description: This area covers the audience. The text placed here typically identifies the group of people or things that are the recipients of Oprah's giveaway. It represents the 'everyone' in the meme's catchphrase.

Located at the top of the image, this is where the punchline text is placed. It describes the item or concept being generously distributed to everyone, often something humorous, absurd, or unexpected, replacing the original 'car'.

Oprah---you-get-a-car.image_description: This meme features Oprah Winfrey from a 2004 episode of her talk show where she famously gave away cars to her entire audience. In the image, she is wearing a red suit, pointing excitedly towards the audience with a microphone in hand. The meme, known as "Oprah's You Get a Car" or "Everybody Gets a Car," is used to express over-the-top generosity, often sarcastically, by showing Oprah giving something to everyone.

I-Guarantee-It.name: I-Guarantee-It

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a variation of the famous catchphrase, "I guarantee it." This text serves as a confident, and often ironic, assertion about the statement made in the top text.
The top text box sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a situation, action, or belief that will be followed by a guaranteed outcome in the bottom text.

I-Guarantee-It.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of George Zimmer, the founder of Men's Wearhouse, from a television commercial. He is known for his signature catchphrase, "You're going to like the way you look. I guarantee it." The meme format uses this image to make a confident, often humorous or ironic, guarantee about a particular situation or outcome, playing on the original ad's authoritative tone.

Do-You-Wanna-Build-A-Snowman.name: Do-You-Wanna-Build-A-Snowman

text_options.description: The text in this bottom position is the main punchline or the core statement of the meme. It's the part delivered with the smug confidence reflected in Anna's expression, completing the thought started in the top text box.

The text in the top box serves as the setup or the first part of a two-part sentence. It introduces the topic or question that the punchline in the bottom box will confidently address, setting the stage for the joke.

Do-You-Wanna-Build-A-Snowman.image_description: This meme features a still of a young, smug-looking Princess Anna from Disney's "Frozen." Her confident, almost mischievous expression is the core of the meme's humor. It's typically used to represent someone making a bold, sassy, or slightly absurd statement with unwavering self-assurance. The format often presents a two-part statement, with Anna's face acting as the visual punchline for the confident delivery.
Do-You-Wanna-Build-A-Snowman.display_name: Do You Wanna Build A Snowman

Groundskeeper-Willie-Natural-Enemies.name: Groundskeeper-Willie-Natural-Enemies

text_options.description: This is the first panel in the reaction sequence. The text here typically introduces the observer (the meme creator) who is just beginning to notice something they find questionable or annoying.
In the second panel, Willie's agitation increases. The text here describes the situation escalating or a more irritating detail coming to light, fueling the observer's annoyance.
Willie turns away in disgust. The text in this panel often represents the observer having seen enough and solidifying their negative opinion about the unfolding situation.
Willie clenches his fist in anger. The text here usually represents the "final straw" or the most infuriating aspect of the situation, pushing the observer to the brink of taking action.
Willie is now shouting, fully enraged. The text in this panel represents the peak of the observer's outrage or a declaration of their intent to intervene or confront the issue.

This final panel reveals the cause of Willie's anger. The text here identifies the person, group, or concept that the meme creator is criticizing. Principal Skinner and Mrs. Krabappel are often labeled to represent this source of frustration.

Groundskeeper-Willie-Natural-Enemies.image_description: This multi-panel meme, known as "Willie Hears Ya, Willie Don't Care" or "Groundskeeper Willie Watching," originates from the animated series The Simpsons. It depicts Groundskeeper Willie looking out a window with escalating anger, culminating in him bursting into Principal Skinner's office. The meme is used to express growing frustration and disapproval towards a person, event, or idea, with the final panel revealing the source of the annoyance.

Big-black-guy-big-dick.name: Big-black-guy-big-dick

text_options.description: Text placed here, at the bottom of the image, typically represents a person, group, or concept that is being confronted or overwhelmed by the entity described in the top text box. It is the unsuspecting or less powerful party in the scenario.

Text in this top position represents a powerful, dominant, or unexpectedly large force that is imposing itself upon the subject labeled in the bottom box. This label leverages the imposing figure of the man to create a humorous comparison of scale or power.

Big-black-guy-big-dick.image_description: This meme, known as "Barry Wood Sitting on a Bed" or simply "Wood Sitting on a Bed," features a screenshot of a muscular Black man with a bald head and tattoos sitting on the edge of a bed. The image is taken from an adult film but is used in a non-explicit, humorous context online. It is typically used as a bait-and-switch prank or a reaction image to represent something unexpectedly large, imposing, or overwhelming, often to humorous effect.

Vince-McMahon-5-tier.name: Vince-McMahon-5-tier

text_options.description: This bottom-most text box corresponds to the most extreme reaction from Vince McMahon, often edited with glowing red eyes. The text here represents the ultimate, god-tier, or most outrageously desirable option in the ranked list, serving as the punchline of the meme.

Paired with McMahon leaning back in pure ecstasy, this text box contains a fantastic or highly superior option. It is the second-to-last stage, representing something that is almost the best possible choice.
This text box is aligned with McMahon's expression of genuine excitement and approval. The text here describes a significantly better or more appealing option compared to the ones above it.
This text box corresponds to Vince McMahon's face showing initial, wide-eyed excitement. The text placed here is for an option that is a clear improvement over the baseline choice at the top.

This is the top-most text box, corresponding to Vince McMahon's most neutral or unimpressed expression. The text here typically describes the most basic, standard, or least desirable option in the series, setting the baseline for the escalating comparison.

Vince-McMahon-5-tier.image_description: This meme, known as "Vince McMahon Reaction" or "Expanding Brain McMahon", features a multi-panel sequence of former WWE CEO Vince McMahon. His expression escalates from mild interest to explosive, over-the-top excitement with each descending panel. The meme is used to create a ranked list, where each text label corresponds to an increasingly desirable, impressive, or superior concept, culminating in the final panel which represents the ultimate or most coveted choice.

Matt-Damon-gets-older.name: Matt-Damon-gets-older

text_options.description: The text in this top caption area sets up the entire joke. It typically contains a statement of fact that highlights the passage of time, such as 'The first Shrek movie came out over 20 years ago.' This piece of information acts as the trigger that causes the viewer (represented by Matt Damon) to feel suddenly and dramatically older.
