Matt-Damon-gets-older.image_description: This meme, known as 'Matt Damon Aging' or 'Matt Damon Getting Old,' originates from a scene in the 1998 film 'Saving Private Ryan.' The four-panel image shows a visual transition of the character, Private Ryan (played by Matt Damon), from a young soldier to a weathered old man. The meme is used to humorously express the feeling of aging rapidly upon realizing how much time has passed since a particular event, often a pop culture milestone.

We-Dont-Talk-about-Bruno.name: We-Dont-Talk-about-Bruno

text_options.description: This text box, positioned over Félix and Pepa's hands, typically identifies the person or entity doing the silencing. It represents the party that wants the other to stop talking to prevent a secret from being revealed or a situation from being made awkward.

This text box, located at the top of the image above the characters' heads, contains the statement of the person who is talking too much. This text sets up the context, representing the secret, over-explanation, or inappropriate comment that is about to be said.

We-Dont-Talk-about-Bruno.image_description: This meme features characters Félix and Pepa Madrigal from the Disney movie "Encanto". The image depicts Pepa silencing Félix by placing her finger on his lips as he looks on with a surprised or flustered expression. This format is typically used to represent a situation where one person is trying to stop another from revealing a secret, over-explaining something, or saying something inappropriate or incriminating.

Urinal-Guy-More-text-room.name: Urinal-Guy-More-text-room

text_options.description: This bottom panel serves as the punchline or reaction to the awkward situation above. It typically contains text or an image describing the negative or cringe-worthy outcome of the unwelcome interaction, representing the user's frustration or the consequence of the social boundary being crossed.

This area covers the first two panels, setting up the scenario. The man in the yellow hoodie is labeled as the user or something they are enjoying, while the man in the blue shirt, who is walking over to stand right next to him, is labeled as an annoying or intrusive person, company, or concept that is about to ruin the experience.

Urinal-Guy-More-text-room.image_description: This is a three-panel comic meme known as "Urinal Etiquette" or "Guy at Urinal." The first panel shows a man in a yellow hoodie using a urinal, while another man in a blue shirt walks past a row of empty urinals. The second panel shows the man in blue choosing the urinal directly next to the first man, violating an unwritten social rule. This meme is used to represent an annoying, intrusive, or unwelcome person, thing, or idea disrupting a peaceful or normal situation.

Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-3-panel.name: Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-3-panel

text_options.description: This text box is aligned with the most dapper version of Pooh, complete with a top hat and monocle. It is reserved for the most elaborate, verbose, or ironically high-class version of the concept, representing the ultimate level of sophistication or absurdity in the hierarchy.
This text box is placed next to Winnie the Pooh wearing a tuxedo. The text here represents a more refined, sophisticated, or preferable alternative to the concept in the top panel.
This text box corresponds to the regular, unimpressed Winnie the Pooh. It is used for the most basic, simple, or common version of a concept, serving as the baseline for the comparison.

Tuxedo-Winnie-the-Pooh-3-panel.image_description: This meme, known as "Tuxedo Winnie the Pooh" or "Pooh Fancy," features a three-panel progression of the character Winnie the Pooh becoming increasingly sophisticated in his attire and expression. The format is used to compare three related items, ideas, or phrases, ranking them from simple and common (top) to elegant and superior (bottom). The humor often comes from presenting an everyday concept in an absurdly formal or elaborate way in the final panel.

idiot-skull.name: idiot-skull

text_options.description: This text box highlights the watermark of the meme generator website, 'imgflip.com'. It is not a customizable part of the meme's content and is usually cropped out or ignored by viewers.

This is the punchline area of the meme. The text placed here identifies a group, opinion, or behavior that the meme creator considers primitive or unintelligent, corresponding to the less-evolved skull above it.

idiot-skull.image_description: This meme format, known as 'Different Skulls' or 'We Are All The Same', displays a grid of identical human skulls labeled with various human demographics (man, woman, black, white, etc.) to suggest that all people are fundamentally the same. The final image in the grid is a primitive, ape-like skull, which is contrasted with the others. This last skull is labeled with a group, belief, or behavior that the creator wishes to mock as being less evolved, unintelligent, or inferior, serving as the punchline.

squidward-poor.name: squidward-poor

text_options.description: This text at the bottom of the image typically identifies the person or entity that is in the desperate situation represented by Squidward. It often serves as the punchline, revealing who is "broke" or "begging."

This text, placed above Squidward, usually represents the plea or the context for the situation. It often contains a variation of the phrase "Spare change?" or describes the action or entity causing the financial distress.

squidward-poor.image_description: This meme features a destitute-looking Squidward Tentacles from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants, sitting in a cardboard box and holding a tin cup. The scene, from the episode "Can You Spare a Dime?", depicts Squidward as homeless and begging. Known as "Spare Change" or "Homeless Squidward," the meme is used to humorously express a state of financial hardship, desperation, or begging for something, often after making poor financial decisions.

Annoying.name: Annoying

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline or the reactor's internal thought. This text expresses frustration, disbelief, or a direct, exasperated response to the setup provided in the top box, aligning with Michael Scott's gesture.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It usually contains a statement, question, or description of an event that is considered foolish, illogical, or frustrating, prompting the facepalm reaction.

Annoying.image_description: This meme features Michael Scott, a character from the TV show 'The Office,' looking deeply frustrated and disappointed. He is pinching the bridge of his nose with his eyes closed, a gesture commonly known as a facepalm. The image is used as a reaction to express exasperation, disbelief, or annoyance at a foolish statement, action, or situation.

pouring-gas-on-fire.name: pouring-gas-on-fire

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the bonfire. It is used to label the initial problem, controversy, or chaotic situation that is already in progress.
This text box is placed over the red gasoline can. It labels the person, entity, or action that is exacerbating the existing problem, literally 'adding fuel to the fire'.

pouring-gas-on-fire.image_description: This meme, often called 'Adding Fuel to the Fire,' features a person pouring gasoline from a red can onto an already burning bonfire. It is a reaction image used to illustrate a person, group, or action that is making a bad or chaotic situation significantly worse. The fire symbolizes the existing problem, while the person pouring gasoline represents the catalyst that escalates the issue.

donald-trump.name: donald-trump

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image is where the punchline or rebuttal is typically placed in the two-panel meme format. It often features a screenshot of a Google search, a Wikipedia article, or a simple text reply that humorously contradicts or fact-checks the statement made in the top panel.

This top area is the primary location for the setup text of the meme. The text is usually a bold, often exaggerated or fabricated, statement or question posed as if Donald Trump is saying it. This statement serves as the premise that the second part of the meme will humorously undermine.

donald-trump.image_description: This meme features former U.S. President Donald Trump standing at a podium with his arms outstretched, set against a backdrop of American flags. The image is typically the first panel in a two-part format. It's used to set up a joke by pairing it with a caption that presents a boastful, questionable, or controversial statement attributed to Trump.

Spiderman-Computer-Desk.name: Spiderman-Computer-Desk

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline or the mundane reality. It's a response to the setup in the top panel, often describing an anticlimactic action, a feeling of being overwhelmed, or simple inaction, which contrasts humorously with the superhero image.

The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a situation, a task, or a question that implies a certain level of importance, urgency, or potential for action, creating an expectation for the viewer.

Spiderman-Computer-Desk.image_description: This meme, known as 'Spider-Man at Desk,' features a still from the 1960s Spider-Man animated series. The image shows Spider-Man sitting behind a desk in a plain office, creating a humorous juxtaposition of a superhero in a mundane, bureaucratic setting. The meme is used to express feelings of being overwhelmed, procrastinating, or dealing with ordinary tasks despite having the potential for more exciting things, often contrasting a grand idea with a simple, underwhelming reality.

Spongebob-shows-Patrick-Garbage.name: Spongebob-shows-Patrick-Garbage

text_options.description: This text labels the massive, overwhelming problem that has been dumped, representing the culmination of all the smaller issues shown in the previous panels.
This label identifies one of the attempts to hide or contain the problem, showing it being stored away out of sight.
This text describes an attempt to disguise or repurpose the problem, making it seem like something else entirely, like furniture.
This label highlights the sheer volume of the problem, showing it overflowing from a container, indicating it's unmanageable.
This text typically labels the initial, small-scale version of the problem or a specific instance of it that is causing frustration.
This label identifies the person or entity (represented by SpongeBob) who is actively trying to get rid of an unwanted problem or task (the trash).
This text labels the person or entity (represented by Patrick) who is ultimately and unexpectedly burdened by the problem that was disposed of by the first person.

Spongebob-shows-Patrick-Garbage.image_description: This multi-panel meme, known as "SpongeBob Dumping Trash," originates from the SpongeBob SquarePants episode "Snowball Effect." It depicts SpongeBob trying various methods to get rid of a large quantity of snowballs, ultimately dumping them in a massive pile. The final panel shows his friend Patrick Star, who has been affected by the dumped snowballs, looking annoyed. The meme is used to illustrate someone trying to offload a problem, task, or unwanted information onto someone else, only for it to come back and cause issues for that other person.

Jim-Office-Blinds.name: Jim-Office-Blinds

text_options.description: The bottom text identifies the observer, who is represented by Jim. This is typically labeled as "Me" or a specific person/group enjoying the spectacle described in the top text.
The top text sets the scene by describing the situation or event being observed. This is often a dramatic, awkward, or humorous scenario that the person represented by Jim is watching.

Jim-Office-Blinds.image_description: This meme features Jim Halpert from the TV show "The Office" peeking through window blinds with a subtle, amused smirk. The image captures a sense of voyeurism or watching drama unfold from a safe distance. It's commonly used to represent someone secretly observing an awkward, funny, or chaotic situation they are not directly involved in.

Man-triggered-at-school.name: Man-triggered-at-school

text_options.description: This label is placed on the straining young man and identifies the person or entity who is struggling to hold back an impulse or comment. It represents the subject of the meme who is experiencing the intense internal conflict.

This label, positioned in the background above the characters, describes the situation, person, or statement that is triggering the overwhelming urge. It provides the context for the struggle and explains why the person labeled in box 0 is straining so hard.

Man-triggered-at-school.image_description: The "Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl" or "Veins Popping Guy" meme features a young man in a classroom straining intensely, with veins bulging on his forehead and neck. He represents someone trying with extreme effort to suppress an urge, a comment, or an action in a socially awkward or inappropriate situation. This meme format is used to humorously depict internal struggles against saying or doing something, often something pedantic, obvious, or socially unacceptable.

Table-Flip-Guy.name: Table-Flip-Guy

text_options.description: Text in the bottom panel serves as a concluding statement or punchline. It often contains an expression of defeat, a final angry remark, or the popular kaomoji emoticon for table flipping: (╯°□°）╯︵ ┻━┻.
Text in the top panel sets up the context for the meme. It describes the frustrating event, comment, or situation that causes the character's intense anger and leads to them flipping the table.

Table-Flip-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Table Flip" or "Flipping Tables," is a classic rage comic character depicted as a stick figure violently flipping a table in anger. The image is a popular reaction used to express extreme frustration, rage, or the act of "rage quitting" in response to an infuriating situation. The simple, expressive drawing style is characteristic of early 2010s internet memes.

But-Not-because-Im-Black.name: But-Not-because-Im-Black

text_options.description: Located on the bottom-right panel where Will Smith is screaming, this text describes the most shocking, absurd, or undesirable option in the comparison. It serves as the punchline, representing the scenario that provokes the most extreme negative reaction.

Positioned on the bottom-left panel showing a concerned expression, this text typically describes a situation that is slightly worrying, questionable, or a step down from the ideal. It represents a less-than-optimal but not yet catastrophic scenario.

This text is on the top-right panel where Will Smith has a calm and neutral expression. It usually represents the best, most logical, or most desirable option among the choices presented. This panel often serves as the positive baseline for the comparison.

Placed on the top-left panel where Will Smith appears angry or is shouting, this text describes a frustrating or annoying, but not shocking, scenario. It represents a common or moderately negative option that elicits an angry response.

But-Not-because-Im-Black.image_description: This four-panel meme, featuring actor Will Smith as Agent J from *Men in Black 3*, showcases a progression of his facial expressions: angry, calm, concerned, and screaming. The format is used to humorously rank or compare different concepts, actions, or scenarios. Typically, the calm expression represents the ideal or preferred option, while the other expressions correspond to increasingly negative, absurd, or undesirable alternatives, culminating in the screaming face for the worst-case scenario.

No-Patrick.name: No-Patrick

text_options.description: This area, often placed over the instruments or the other characters, typically labels the person, group, or serious topic being addressed. It establishes the context that is about to be interrupted by a foolish question.

Positioned above Patrick's head, this is where the user places the absurd, off-topic, or silly question that mirrors the original line, "Is mayonnaise an instrument?" This text represents the clueless interjection that defines the meme.

No-Patrick.image_description: This is a screenshot from the Spongebob Squarepants episode "Band Geeks," featuring the character Patrick Star with his hand raised. The meme, known as "Is Mayonnaise an Instrument?", captures a moment where Patrick asks a profoundly stupid and off-topic question in a serious setting. It is used to represent someone making a foolish, irrelevant, or nonsensical contribution to a conversation, often to the exasperation of others.

Spiderman-Presentation.name: Spiderman-Presentation

text_options.description: This area covers the audience. Text placed here typically labels the group of people that the presenter (Spider-Man) is trying to convince or who might disagree with the opinion being presented. This sets up the context for the argument on the screen.

This is the main content area on the projector screen. Text here represents the core argument, controversial opinion, or 'hot take' that Spider-Man is presenting. It's the punchline of the meme, where the user inserts their own passionate belief.

Spiderman-Presentation.image_description: This meme, known as "Spider-Man's Presentation," features a person in a Spider-Man costume standing on a stage and giving a presentation to an audience. The format is used to present a strong, often niche or controversial, opinion on the projector screen as if it were a formal lecture. The humor arises from the absurdity of a superhero earnestly presenting a personal 'hot take' or a detailed argument to a captive audience, making it a popular template for sharing opinions online.

Spongebob---I-Dont-Need-It-by-Henry-C.name: Spongebob---I-Dont-Need-It-by-Henry-C

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the final panel where SpongeBob is screaming. It typically describes the person or entity that is loudly and outwardly proclaiming their resistance to the temptation, representing the climax of their denial.

Positioned over an extreme close-up of SpongeBob's dehydrated, bloodshot eyes, this text represents the intense internal monologue of the person struggling. It often contains a desperate, repeated phrase of denial, like "I don't need it... I definitely don't need it," highlighting the peak of their internal suffering.

This text box is on the panel showing SpongeBob beginning to shrivel. It usually represents a continuation of the internal struggle, where the resolve is clearly weakening. The text here might be a simple, strained statement of denial.

Located over the glass of water that SpongeBob is staring at, this text box labels the object of temptation. It clearly defines the thing that the subject of the meme desperately wants but is trying to resist.

Spongebob---I-Dont-Need-It-by-Henry-C.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "I Don't Need It" or "SpongeBob Resisting Temptation," originates from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants. It depicts SpongeBob progressively dehydrating and becoming more frantic as he tries to resist a glass of water. The meme is used to humorously illustrate a desperate internal struggle to resist a strong temptation or desire, with the subject's resolve weakening over time.
Spongebob---I-Dont-Need-It-by-Henry-C.display_name: Spongebob   I Dont Need It by Henry C

TIGHTEN-MEGAMIND-THERE-IS-NO-EASTER-BUNN.name: TIGHTEN-MEGAMIND-THERE-IS-NO-EASTER-BUNNY

text_options.description: This is the core punchline of the meme. The user inserts a word or phrase to complete the sentence "and there is no...", humorously declaring that this concept is as fictional as the Easter Bunny or the Tooth Fairy.
This space is often used for an optional caption to provide context for the meme. It typically sets up a scenario or identifies the speaker, framing the subsequent dramatic denial for comedic effect.

TIGHTEN-MEGAMIND-THERE-IS-NO-EASTER-BUNN.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Tighten from the animated film Megamind. In the top panel, he looks distressed while shouting, with subtitles reading, "There is no Easter Bunny, there is no Tooth Fairy,". In the bottom panel, his expression shifts to a crazed, menacing smile as the subtitle continues, "and there is no". This format is used to humorously or sardonically deny the existence of something by equating it with well-known childhood myths, with the punchline being the user-added text.
TIGHTEN-MEGAMIND-THERE-IS-NO-EASTER-BUNN.display_name: TIGHTEN MEGAMIND THERE IS NO EASTER BUNNY

Old-lady-at-computer-finds-the-Internet.name: Old-lady-at-computer-finds-the-Internet

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, revealing the shocking, confusing, or unexpected information that the grandma is reacting to. This text is what causes the depicted expression of bewilderment and completes the joke.
The top text sets up the scenario. It typically describes an action, such as a search query or a question, that leads to the surprising discovery, providing the context for the grandma's reaction.

Old-lady-at-computer-finds-the-Internet.image_description: This meme, known as 'Grandma Finds the Internet' or 'Internet Grandma,' features an elderly woman squinting at a laptop screen with a look of confusion and surprise. The image is a reaction macro used to express shock, disbelief, or being overwhelmed by something seen online. It often portrays a generational gap or a newcomer's naive discovery of the internet's more bizarre corners.
Old-lady-at-computer-finds-the-Internet.display_name: Old lady at computer finds the Internet

Batman-dont-leave-me.name: Batman-dont-leave-me

text_options.description: This area, featuring Batman's crying face and the dialogue "DON'T LEAVE ME!!", represents the person or entity experiencing a profound, often comically exaggerated, sense of loss. The text placed here identifies the subject who is sad about the departure of the person or thing labeled in the top panel.

This section, showing Batman pleading with the ghostly figures of his parents, is typically labeled with the person, object, or concept that is leaving or being lost. The original dialogue "NO. NO, STAY WITH ME!" establishes this area as the source of Batman's (and the meme creator's) grief.

Batman-dont-leave-me.image_description: This two-panel comic meme shows the DC superhero Batman grieving the ghostly apparitions of his deceased parents. In the first panel, he begs them to stay, while the second panel is a close-up of him crying in anguish. The meme, known as "Batman Crying" or "Batman's Parents Dying," is used to express exaggerated sadness, desperation, and attachment when something cherished is being lost or taken away, often in a humorous or relatable context.

Bonk.name: Bonk

text_options.description: This label is placed on Cheems, the dog being hit. The text here identifies the person, group, or idea being punished or corrected for being undesirable, often for being 'horny' or cringe.

This label is placed on the larger dog wielding the bat. The text here identifies the entity doing the punishing or correcting, representing the community, a specific person, or a concept enforcing a norm.

This area is typically where the onomatopoeia "BONK" is written, representing the action of hitting. In meme variations, this text can be replaced to describe the reason for the punishment, such as "Go to Horny Jail."

Bonk.image_description: This is the "Cheems Bonk" or "Go to Horny Jail" meme, featuring two Shiba Inu dog characters. A larger, stronger dog (often representing a corrective force) is hitting a smaller, sad-looking dog named Cheems on the head with a baseball bat. This meme is used as a reaction to express humorous disapproval, often to punish someone for being overly sexual (horny), cringe, or expressing a foolish opinion, metaphorically sending them to "horny jail."

Gordon-Ramsay-some-good-food.name: Gordon-Ramsay-some-good-food

text_options.description: This top section is a blank space for user-added text. The text here typically describes a scenario or a series of negative experiences that makes Gordon Ramsay's eventual satisfaction more impactful. It sets up the context for his relief, establishing what he was enduring before finally finding something good.

Gordon-Ramsay-some-good-food.image_description: This meme features a close-up of celebrity chef Gordon Ramsay looking relieved and satisfied. The image is a screencap from one of his shows, with subtitles that read "delicious. Finally, some good fucking food." Known for his harsh criticism, this rare moment of approval is used to express immense satisfaction or relief after experiencing a series of subpar or disappointing things. The "food" is often a metaphor for any kind of content, product, or experience that is of high quality.

Bobby-Hill-Kids-No-Watermark.name: Bobby-Hill-Kids-No-Watermark

text_options.description: This area represents the group of people ('those kids') who are the subject of the insult or harsh truth presented in the top panel. Text here often labels the group to provide context for the joke.

This space is for the main text of the meme. It contains an insulting statement, a controversial opinion, or a harsh truth directed at the group of people shown in the bottom panel. This text serves as the setup for the punchline 'If those kids could read they'd be very upset.'

Bobby-Hill-Kids-No-Watermark.image_description: This two-panel meme from the animated show 'King of the Hill' features Bobby Hill pointing at a sign in the top panel. The bottom panel shows a group of students, with the caption 'If those kids could read they'd be very upset.' The format is used to mock a particular group by placing an insulting statement or a harsh truth on the sign, implying the group is too ignorant or oblivious to understand and be offended by it.

Spiderman-Hospital.name: Spiderman-Hospital

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the lower half of the bed, identifies the subject who is feeling defeated or exhausted. This is the punchline, often starting with "Me:" or naming a group, connecting them to the feeling of being worn out by the situation described in the top text.

The top text describes a challenging, demanding, or overwhelming action, event, or statement. This text serves as the setup, providing the context or reason for Spider-Man's (and by extension, the meme creator's) exhausted state.

Spiderman-Hospital.image_description: This meme, known as "Spider-Man in Hospital Bed" or "Sick Spider-Man," originates from the 1960s Spider-Man animated series. It depicts the superhero in his full suit, looking dejected and weak while lying in a hospital bed. The meme humorously contrasts the character's usual strength with a moment of vulnerability, used to represent feeling defeated, exhausted, or overwhelmed after a difficult or draining experience.

kahn.name: kahn

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom, near Kirk's open mouth, identifies the target of the rage. It typically contains a single word or name, often in all caps, replacing the original "KHAN!" to represent what the user is metaphorically screaming about.
The top text box provides the context or setup for the outburst. It usually describes the frustrating scenario or action that has provoked the intense reaction shown in the image.

kahn.image_description: This meme, known as "Screaming Kirk" or "KHAAAN!", features a close-up of Captain James T. Kirk (played by William Shatner) from the film *Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan*. The image captures a moment of intense rage and frustration as he screams the name of his nemesis, Khan. It is used to express extreme, often comically exaggerated, anger or frustration towards a person, situation, or minor inconvenience.

Money-Money.name: Money-Money

text_options.description: This bottom text box identifies the person or entity doing the spending. It's the punchline of the meme, often labeled 'Me' or another subject, who is acting out the scene of lavishly throwing money around.

This top text box sets up the context or reason for the spending spree. It typically describes the situation, such as 'after getting paid' or 'when my favorite item goes on sale,' providing the justification for the character's excited financial splurge.

Money-Money.image_description: This meme features the character The Mask, played by Jim Carrey, from the 1994 film of the same name, ecstatically fanning out wads of cash. The image captures a moment of exuberant and often reckless spending. It's typically used to humorously depict someone spending money lavishly on something they desire, whether the amount is objectively large or comically small.

Comprehending-Joey.name: Comprehending-Joey

text_options.description: This text box corresponds with Joey's shocked expression. The text here introduces the punchline—a sudden, unpleasant realization, a negative consequence, or a shocking fact that completely reverses the positive sentiment established in the top panel.

This text box is placed next to the image of Joey looking smug and pleased. The text here typically describes a positive situation, a seemingly good idea, or an agreeable statement that sets up the premise of the joke.

Comprehending-Joey.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Joey's Delayed Reaction" or "Smug Joey / Shocked Joey," features the character Joey Tribbiani from the TV show Friends. In the top panel, Joey has a smug, self-satisfied expression, which contrasts with his wide-eyed, shocked look in the bottom panel. The format is used to illustrate a situation where an initial positive or agreeable thought is immediately followed by a shocking or horrifying realization, causing a drastic change in perspective.

Kramer-whats-going-on-in-there.name: Kramer-whats-going-on-in-there

text_options.description: This label is placed on Kramer. In the meme's context, this text identifies the person, group, or entity responsible for or involved in the chaotic situation depicted in the middle panel.

This central black box is the core of the meme, where a user inserts an image or text describing a bizarre, chaotic, or unexpected event. This content serves as the answer to Jerry's question, "what's going on in there?", and is the setup for the punchline delivered by Kramer's reaction.

Kramer-whats-going-on-in-there.image_description: This meme format, known as "Kramer, What's Going On In There?", originates from a scene in the TV show Seinfeld. In the top panel, Jerry Seinfeld asks his neighbor Kramer about a strange red light coming from his apartment. The bottom panel shows Kramer's startled reaction, confirming something unusual is happening. The meme is used to express bewilderment or concern about a chaotic or bizarre situation, which is typically depicted in the blank middle panel.
Kramer-whats-going-on-in-there.display_name: Kramer whats going on in there

Well-That-Escalated-Quickly.name: Well-That-Escalated-Quickly

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, which is almost always the direct quote 'I DON'T BELIEVE YOU' from the movie scene. This text directly expresses the skepticism and disbelief conveyed by Ron Burgundy's expression towards the statement in the top panel.
The top text box presents a statement, claim, or scenario that is considered unbelievable, far-fetched, or suspicious. This text sets up the punchline delivered in the bottom panel.

Well-That-Escalated-Quickly.image_description: This meme features Ron Burgundy from the movie 'Anchorman,' played by Will Ferrell, sitting at his desk with a smug, disbelieving look while holding a beer. The image captures a moment of skepticism and is widely used as a reaction to express doubt or disbelief towards a statement or claim. The format typically pairs a questionable assertion with Burgundy's iconic line, "I don't believe you."

Spongebob-chicken.name: Spongebob-chicken

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region describes the frantic action or the person reacting in panic. It acts as the punchline, representing the user's over-the-top response to the situation described in the top text box.
The text in this top region sets up the scenario or provides the context that causes SpongeBob's panicked reaction. This is the trigger or the source of the anxiety that the meme is conveying.

Spongebob-chicken.image_description: This meme, known as "Panicked SpongeBob" or "SpongeBob Running," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants with a wide-eyed, frantic expression as if he's running away in terror. The image is from the SpongeBob episode "Nature Pants" and is used to represent an extreme, humorous, or panicked reaction to a situation. The meme is typically a two-part format where a statement is made, and SpongeBob's image represents the chaotic response.

Leonardo-Dicaprio-Wolf-Of-Wall-Street.name: Leonardo-Dicaprio-Wolf-Of-Wall-Street

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the image of DiCaprio laughing uncontrollably. It typically contains the punchline, an absurd or cynical response that reveals the true, often chaotic, reality, directly contrasting with the setup in the top panel.

This text box is located in the top panel where DiCaprio has a calm, slightly smug smile. It's used for a setup, often a naive question, an innocent statement, or a plan that seems reasonable on the surface, which is then subverted by the bottom panel.

Leonardo-Dicaprio-Wolf-Of-Wall-Street.image_description: This two-panel meme features actor Leonardo DiCaprio as Jordan Belfort in the film "The Wolf of Wall Street." The top panel shows him smiling calmly, while the bottom panel captures him laughing hysterically. The format is used to contrast a naive statement or question in the top panel with a cynical, absurd, or unexpected reality in the bottom panel, with the laughter highlighting the ridiculousness of the initial premise.
Leonardo-Dicaprio-Wolf-Of-Wall-Street.display_name: Leonardo Dicaprio Wolf Of Wall Street

When-X-just-right.name: When-X-just-right

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, describing the perfectly satisfying result or feeling that prompts Pacha's 'just right' gesture. It's the resolution to the setup in the top text.
This top text box sets up the scenario or describes an action. It's the first part of the joke, establishing the context for the perfect outcome that follows.

When-X-just-right.image_description: This meme features the character Pacha from Disney's 'The Emperor's New Groove' making a perfect 'OK' hand gesture with a satisfied expression. Known as 'Pacha OK' or 'When the sun hits that ridge just right,' it's used to express a feeling of perfect satisfaction or when something aligns flawlessly. The meme sets up a scenario and then reveals the perfectly fitting or satisfying outcome.

Tom-Cruise-laugh.name: Tom-Cruise-laugh

text_options.description: This area contains the main subject, Tom Cruise, laughing. In a meme format, text here would typically label the person or entity who is reacting with intense amusement. This represents the 'actor' or the user's perspective.

This upper section, often used for context, would contain text describing the situation, statement, or event that is being laughed at. It sets up the punchline for which the laughing Tom Cruise image is the reaction.

Tom-Cruise-laugh.image_description: This reaction meme, known as "Laughing Tom Cruise," features actor Tom Cruise laughing with an intense, almost maniacal expression. The image is a still from a 2006 video interview about Scientology, where his behavior was widely seen as bizarre. The meme is used to express extreme, unrestrained, or even inappropriate amusement, often conveying schadenfreude or finding humor in a dark or absurd situation.

Angry-NPC-Meme.name: Angry-NPC-Meme

text_options.description: This text box is for a statement made by the simple, white-drawn character. It typically contains an opinion, question, or fact that challenges a popular or mainstream belief. This statement serves as the trigger for the NPC Wojak's angry reaction, highlighting the meme's theme of intolerance towards non-conformist thought.

This text box is positioned above the NPC Wojak. It is often left blank, as the focus is on the character's reaction rather than their words. When text is included, it might label the NPC (e.g., "Society") or represent a mainstream, conformist thought that is about to be challenged by the other character.

Angry-NPC-Meme.image_description: This is a four-panel comic meme featuring the NPC Wojak character, a grey, expressionless figure representing people who supposedly can't think for themselves. In the first panel, the NPC Wojak is shown opposite a crudely drawn character. The meme's progression shows the NPC Wojak becoming enraged in the final panel after hearing the other character's statement. This format is used to satirize people who are perceived to blindly follow mainstream opinions or trends (the "current thing") and react with hostility to any dissenting viewpoint.

Jerry-Maguire-you-had-me-at-hello.name: Jerry-Maguire-you-had-me-at-hello

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the character's face, delivers the punchline or the disappointing reality. This text contrasts with the setup in the top panel, creating the humor or relatable sadness of the meme. The character's expression is a direct reaction to this letdown.
The top text, placed above the character's head, serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a positive scenario, a hopeful thought, or an exciting expectation.

Jerry-Maguire-you-had-me-at-hello.image_description: This meme features a still of actress Renée Zellweger from the film "Jerry Maguire," looking visibly sad and disappointed. The format is used to express a feeling of being let down or crestfallen. Typically, the meme sets up a positive or hopeful expectation in the top text, only to reveal a disappointing or anticlimactic reality in the bottom text, with Zellweger's expression serving as the reaction.
Jerry-Maguire-you-had-me-at-hello.display_name: Jerry Maguire you had me at hello

Spongebob-My-Eyes.name: Spongebob-My-Eyes

text_options.description: This text, placed at the bottom, typically labels the person or entity experiencing the overwhelming situation. It represents the subject of the meme who is having the extreme reaction shown by the fish.

The text at the top of the image describes the cause of the stress or overstimulation. This caption sets the context, explaining what specific event or stimulus is leading to the fish's panicked reaction.

Spongebob-My-Eyes.image_description: This meme features a pink fish character from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants, looking extremely stressed and overstimulated. The fish has wide, bloodshot eyes with smoke rising from them and a screaming, open mouth, conveying a state of sensory overload or intense panic. This image is used as a reaction meme to humorously represent feeling overwhelmed by a situation, whether it's too much information, social interaction, or any other intense stimulus.

Man-holding-sign.name: Man-holding-sign

text_options.description: This area represents the crowd or the general public. In the meme, this group is often labeled as the target of the message on the sign or people who hold an opposing, mainstream view, providing context for the protester's statement.

This is the blank sign, the central element of the meme. Users edit this space to add a statement, opinion, or complaint, which serves as the punchline. The text is typically a relatable, everyday grievance or a humorous take on a social norm.

Man-holding-sign.image_description: This meme, known as "Protester with a Sign" or "Dude with Sign," features a young man holding a blank sign amidst a crowd at a protest. The format is an exploitable, where users add their own text to the sign to voice humorous, relatable, or mundane opinions as if they were serious protest causes. The humor comes from the contrast between the formal protest setting and the often trivial nature of the message on the sign.

Pokemon-Battle.name: Pokemon-Battle

text_options.description: This large text box at the bottom of the screen delivers the punchline of the meme. In the game, this area displays battle actions and dialogue. In the meme, it contains a statement or describes an action that reveals the overwhelming power imbalance between the two opponents, often to a humorous or shocking effect.

This status bar, typically representing the player's Pokémon, is used to label the weaker, less experienced, or outmatched party in the scenario. The low level ('Lv.') often shown next to the name emphasizes their vulnerability.

This status bar represents the opponent Pokémon and is used to label the overwhelmingly stronger, more experienced, or superior force in the confrontation. This entity is positioned to easily defeat the one labeled in box 1.

Pokemon-Battle.image_description: This meme format uses a screenshot of a battle screen from a Pokémon video game, likely from the Nintendo DS era. The template shows the health bars and names of two opposing Pokémon, along with a large text box at the bottom. It's used to depict a lopsided confrontation or an unfair fight, where one entity is vastly more powerful, experienced, or prepared than the other.

Homer-Bar.name: Homer-Bar

text_options.description: This label is placed on Homer Simpson. The text here identifies the subject of the meme—the person, company, or idea that is completely out of place or trying to awkwardly fit in with a group they don't belong to.

This label is placed over the crowd of women in the background. The text here represents the specific group, community, or demographic that the subject (labeled 0) is trying to appeal to or is uncomfortably situated within, highlighting the social disconnect.

Homer-Bar.image_description: A still from the animated series *The Simpsons* showing the character Homer Simpson sitting alone and looking out of place at a bar. In the background, a large crowd of women is socializing, creating a stark contrast. This meme format, known as 'Homer Simpson in a Lesbian Bar,' is used to represent a person, brand, or entity that is awkwardly and obviously out of its element, often trying to pander to a group it doesn't understand.

Yeah-if-you-could.name: Yeah-if-you-could

text_options.description: This is the bottom text and the punchline of the meme. It almost always reads "That'd be great" or a slight variation, completing the passive-aggressive request started in the top text. This phrase is the character's signature sign-off, making the request sound non-negotiable despite its polite framing.

This is the top text, which sets up the sarcastic request. It typically starts with "Yeah, if you could just..." followed by an annoying or unreasonable task. This line directly quotes the character's condescending way of speaking in the movie, establishing the meme's tone.

Yeah-if-you-could.image_description: This meme features Bill Lumbergh, the condescending boss from the 1999 film "Office Space," standing in an office environment holding a mug. He is wearing a light blue shirt, a patterned tie, and red suspenders. The meme is used to make a passive-aggressive or sarcastic request, mimicking Lumbergh's famous line. It's a popular way to complain about annoying tasks or management requests in a humorous way.

cast-it-into-the-fire.name: cast-it-into-the-fire

text_options.description: This label is placed on Isildur's face. The text here represents the person or entity who stubbornly refuses to follow good advice or a command, representing the user or a relatable figure making a poor but tempting choice.
This label is placed on Elrond's face. The text here represents the voice of reason, a person giving advice, or an internal thought (e.g., 'my brain') urging the protagonist to do the sensible thing.
This label is placed on the One Ring. The text here represents the tempting but ultimately bad idea, object, or habit that the protagonist (Isildur) cannot bring themselves to abandon or destroy.

cast-it-into-the-fire.image_description: This meme is a three-panel image from the movie "The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring." The top panel shows the One Ring, the middle panel shows Elrond yelling "Cast it into the fire! Destroy it!", and the bottom panel shows Isildur defiantly saying "No." The format is used to represent a conflict between a rational suggestion and a tempting, often irrational, refusal to follow it.

hello-person-from.name: hello-person-from

text_options.description: The second word of the punchline phrase in the top-right panel. In the classic format, this is the word "side," completing the phrase "the other side."
The first part of the punchline phrase in the top-right panel. This text, combined with the text in box 0, forms the response. Typically, this is "the other" to form the iconic lyric.
The second word of the setup phrase in the top-left panel. This text identifies the location, group, or perspective of the first character, setting up the joke.
The first word of the setup phrase in the top-left panel. This text, along with the text in box 2, establishes the context for the first character's greeting.

hello-person-from.image_description: This is a four-panel comic template for the "Hello from the Other Side" meme. The meme is a reference to the opening lyrics of Adele's song "Hello." The format typically features a character in the top-left panel saying "Hello from [a specific group or place]," and a character from an opposing or contrasting group in the top-right panel responding, "Hello from the other side." The meme is used to highlight rivalries, differences, or humorous juxtapositions between two subjects.

Meme-Stealing-License.name: Meme-Stealing-License

text_options.description: This text box corresponds to the "Occupation" field on the license. Users typically fill this with a humorous, self-aware job title related to meme culture, such as "Professional Meme Thief," "Shitposter," or "Content Reappropriator," to reinforce the joke of the license.

This text box is for the "Joined" date, mimicking a profile on a social media platform or forum. This field is often filled with a funny or nonsensical date, like "Since the dawn of the internet," to add to the comedic and unofficial nature of the license.

This text box represents the "Level" field, borrowing from video game or forum terminology. It's used to humorously rank the user's skill in meme stealing, often with an exaggeratedly high number or a funny title like "Grandmaster" or "Over 9000."

This text box is for the "Gender" field. It is often filled with a joke answer or another meme reference (e.g., "Attack Helicopter") rather than a serious identifier, contributing to the overall absurdity of the fake license.

This text box is for the "Name" field on the license. It is typically customized with the user's online username, a funny fake name, or a title like "The Meme Bandit," personalizing the joke for whoever is posting the image.

Meme-Stealing-License.image_description: This meme depicts a fake "Official Meme Stealing License," formatted like an ID card with a blank space for a photo and fields for personal details. It's a meta-joke within internet culture, used humorously to justify or admit to reposting someone else's meme without credit. Posting this license is a playful, non-confrontational way to engage with the common online practice of sharing and circulating content.

Woosh-cat.name: Woosh-cat

text_options.description: This bottom caption identifies the person or entity making the failed attempt. It typically sets up the joke with a phrase like 'Me trying to explain...' or simply labels the cat as the person in question (e.g., 'My brain').

This text is placed over the chaotic scribble and describes the complex subject or task being poorly executed. This could be anything from 'quantum physics' to 'my code,' visually labeling the confusing mess as the outcome of the attempt.

Woosh-cat.image_description: This meme, often called 'Wizard Cat' or 'Magic Cat', shows a cat with glowing eyes wearing a party hat as a wizard's hat and holding a crudely drawn wand. The cat appears to be casting a spell, which results in a chaotic, colorful crayon scribble. The humor comes from the contrast between the cat's serious attempt at magic and the nonsensical, childish outcome. It's used to represent someone trying to explain a complex topic or perform a technical task but producing a confusing, disorganized, or incorrect result.

Inigo-Montoya.name: Inigo-Montoya

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, typically reading, 'I do not think it means what you think it means.' This text serves as the direct correction or clarification of the word or phrase mentioned in the top text, completing the famous quote.
The top text sets up the meme by quoting a word or phrase that is being misused. It's the first part of the character's well-known line, often starting with 'You keep using that word...'

Inigo-Montoya.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Inigo Montoya from the 1987 film 'The Princess Bride,' looking intently at the viewer. The image is famously used for the 'You Keep Using That Word' meme format, which calls out the misuse or misunderstanding of a word, concept, or phrase. The meme's tone is often pedantic or corrective, leveraging the character's articulate and determined personality.

Laughing-Villains.name: Laughing-Villains

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It reveals a surprisingly or ridiculously small number that contrasts sharply with the expectation set by the top text. This anticlimactic reveal is the source of the humor, mirroring Dr. Evil's original "one million dollars" demand.
The top text box sets up the scenario by posing a question or making a statement that implies a large or significant number is forthcoming. This text builds anticipation for the punchline.

Laughing-Villains.image_description: This meme features the character Dr. Evil from the movie "Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery," flanked by his laughing henchmen. The scene depicts the moment Dr. Evil makes a comically low ransom demand, causing his own team to erupt in laughter. The meme is used to mock situations where a proposed number, price, or quantity is absurdly or disappointingly small, creating an anticlimactic and humorous effect.

Spongebob-yeet.name: Spongebob-yeet

text_options.description: This box is placed over the fire where the paper is burning. This area represents the final, decisive rejection of the idea from the paper. While often left blank, text placed here might label the fire as "the trash" or "hell" to emphasize that the discarded opinion is worthless or evil.

This box is placed over the paper as SpongeBob reads it with a look of disgust. The text here is typically the same as in the first panel, reinforcing the undesirable content that is causing his negative reaction. It's the moment of judgment before the final action.

This area, on the paper SpongeBob holds up initially, introduces the subject matter. Text here presents the idea, opinion, or statement that is about to be evaluated and ultimately rejected. It serves as the setup for the meme's punchline.

Spongebob-yeet.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "SpongeBob Burning Paper," features SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series. He is shown looking at a piece of paper, then scowling at it, and finally tossing it into a fire with a cheerful expression. The meme is used to humorously express strong disagreement with or rejection of an idea, opinion, or piece of information, signifying that it is worthless and deserves to be destroyed.

Why-are-you-gay.name: Why-are-you-gay

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the direct question. The original text is "why are you gay?", but it is frequently edited to question a different, often trivial or absurd, action or characteristic, making the interviewer's serious demeanor comical.

This area at the top is used to provide context or a setup for the punchline below. It typically describes a scenario, action, or statement made by a person or group, which then prompts the blunt question from the interviewer. This text establishes the behavior that is being questioned.

Why-are-you-gay.image_description: This meme, known as "Why Are You Gay?", originates from a Ugandan TV interview where an interviewer bluntly asks an activist this question. The image features the interviewer on the right looking seriously at the interviewee on the left. The meme is used as a reaction or template to humorously and directly question someone's actions, choices, or preferences, often by replacing the word "gay" with another adjective or verb to fit the context.

Dog-in-burning-house.name: Dog-in-burning-house

text_options.description: Text placed over the dog represents the person, group, or entity that is in denial or calmly accepting a terrible situation. This is the central character of the meme, who is pretending everything is okay despite the surrounding chaos.

Text placed over the fire and burning room describes the overwhelming problem, crisis, or disaster that the main character is ignoring. This area provides the context for the chaotic situation that makes the dog's calm reaction absurd and humorous.

Dog-in-burning-house.image_description: This is a two-panel comic strip featuring an anthropomorphic dog, known as the "This is Fine" dog, sitting in a room that is engulfed in flames. Despite the clear danger, the dog is smiling calmly and holding a mug, famously saying "This is fine." The meme is used to represent a state of denial, willful ignorance, or extreme composure when faced with a disastrous or chaotic situation, humorously highlighting a person's attempt to carry on as if nothing is wrong.

one-million-dollars.name: one-million-dollars

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, containing the punchline. This is where the specific, often comically large or absurd, demand is stated, mimicking Dr. Evil's iconic ransom requests. It frequently includes phrases like "One Million Dollars" or other exaggerated sums to create a humorous effect.

The top text of the meme, which sets up the context or identifies the person or entity making the demand. This text establishes the scenario for Dr. Evil's punchline, often describing a situation where someone is asking for something in a comically serious or villainous way.

one-million-dollars.image_description: This meme features Dr. Evil, the antagonist from the Austin Powers film series, holding his pinky finger to his lips with a scheming expression. The image is a reaction macro used to humorously express an exorbitant or comically specific demand, often for money. It directly references his iconic scene where he demands a ransom of "one million dollars," which at the time was considered a paltry sum for a supervillain.

tom-the-cat-shooting-himself.name: tom-the-cat-shooting-himself

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the shotgun that Tom is holding. It typically labels the initial action, plan, or entity that is the cause of the self-sabotage. This is the 'weapon' that is supposed to affect an external target.

This text box is positioned above Tom's head, in the path of the backfiring shot. It represents the negative, unintended consequence or the person/thing that is ironically harmed by the action described in box 0. It visualizes the 'backfire' effect.

tom-the-cat-shooting-himself.image_description: This meme, known as "Trust Nobody, Not Even Yourself" or "Tom Shoots Himself," features Tom the cat from the cartoon "Tom and Jerry." Tom is depicted gleefully holding a double-barreled shotgun whose barrels are bent backwards, pointing directly at his own head as it fires. The image is used to represent situations of self-sabotage, where an action or plan backfires spectacularly, causing harm to the originator.

Car-Salesman-Slaps-Hood.name: Car-Salesman-Slaps-Hood

text_options.description: This text box is used to label the object, person, or concept that the salesman is presenting. The salesman's hand gestures directly towards this area, identifying it as the subject of his sales pitch.

This area contains the punchline, which is the salesman's dialogue. It typically follows the format "*slaps [object from box 0]* this bad boy can fit so much [absurd or funny thing] in it," making an exaggerated claim about the subject's capacity.

Car-Salesman-Slaps-Hood.image_description: This is the "Slaps Roof of Car" meme, featuring an illustration of a car salesman enthusiastically gesturing towards a blank space while talking to a potential customer. The salesman presents an object or concept, and the humor comes from the exaggerated or absurd claim he makes about its capacity or function. The meme follows the phrasal template "*slaps [object]* this bad boy can fit so much [something] in it."

Archer.name: Archer

text_options.description: This is the bottom text and the punchline of the meme. It completes the phrase started at the top, typically reading, "Because that's how you get [X]," where [X] is the same undesirable outcome mentioned in the top text. This line confirms the inevitable consequence of the initial action.

This is the top text that sets up the meme's premise. It poses a rhetorical question, usually in the format, "Do you want [X]?" where [X] is an undesirable thing or situation. This text introduces the cause or action that will lead to a predictable result.

Archer.image_description: This meme features the character Sterling Archer from the animated series 'Archer', looking seriously at the viewer. The format is known as "Do You Want Ants? Because That's How You Get Ants," derived from a line in the show. It's used to sarcastically point out the obvious and often negative consequences of a particular action or situation, functioning as a rhetorical question to highlight a predictable outcome.

All-your-base.name: All-your-base

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline or the specific, often absurd, consequence of the situation. It completes the thought started in the top text, revealing the "paradox" or dramatic outcome in a humorous way, contrasting with the character's serious expression.

The text in this top position typically introduces a grand, philosophical statement or the first half of a quote from the game. It serves as the setup, establishing a tone of dramatic importance before the punchline is delivered at the bottom.

All-your-base.image_description: This meme features a pixelated portrait of Kain, the protagonist from the video game series *Legacy of Kain*. The format, known as "Kain's Monologue" or "History Abhors a Paradox," is used to humorously overstate the dramatic consequences of a seemingly minor action or choice. The meme juxtaposes Kain's serious, philosophical demeanor with mundane or absurd situations, creating a sense of ironic melodrama.

If-I-Had-One.name: If-I-Had-One

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always the phrase "IF I HAD ONE!". This text completes the setup from the top panel, delivering the joke and expressing the character's frustration about lacking the desired item.

Text placed here describes the desired object, achievement, or situation that the meme creator wishes they had. This serves as the setup for the punchline, representing the metaphorical "trophy" that is missing.

If-I-Had-One.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Denzel Crocker from the animated series "The Fairly OddParents." In the top panel, he is smiling and proudly gesturing towards an empty display stand. In the bottom panel, his expression shifts to one of rage and despair. Known as the "This is where I'd put my trophy... IF I HAD ONE!" meme, it's used to express frustration and disappointment over not having something that is desired or expected.

Evil-Plotting-Raccoon.name: Evil-Plotting-Raccoon

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the raccoon's paws, typically delivers the punchline by revealing the specific evil or cunning thought or action. This is the humorous payoff that explains what the raccoon is plotting.
The top text sets up a scenario or context that presents an opportunity for mischief or a devious plan. It's the premise that justifies the raccoon's scheming expression.

Evil-Plotting-Raccoon.image_description: This meme, often called 'Evil Raccoon' or 'Scheming Raccoon,' features a raccoon rubbing its paws together with a mischievous and plotting expression. The pose is reminiscent of a classic cartoon villain contemplating a devious plan. The meme is used to humorously express malevolent, cunning, or mischievous thoughts and intentions, which are often for petty or silly reasons.

Jackie-Chan-WTF.name: Jackie-Chan-WTF

text_options.description: The bottom text area, often used for a punchline or a direct expression of confusion like "WTF?". In many variations of this meme, this space is left blank, allowing the expressive image itself to serve as the entire reaction.
The top text area is used to describe a confusing, illogical, or mind-boggling situation or statement. This text sets up the context that causes the bewildered reaction depicted in the image.

Jackie-Chan-WTF.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white rage comic style drawing of actor Jackie Chan, known as the "Jackie Chan WTF" or "My Brain is Full of Fuck" meme. The image depicts him with his hands on his head, wearing an expression of extreme confusion and disbelief. It is used as a reaction image to express bewilderment, frustration, or shock in response to something illogical, nonsensical, or overwhelmingly complex.

spongebob-imagination.name: spongebob-imagination

text_options.description: The bottom text box is used to state a mundane, disappointing, or contrary reality. This text serves as the punchline, contrasting sharply with the imaginative or idealistic concept presented by SpongeBob and the top text.

The top text box, positioned above the rainbow, typically contains the word "Imagination" or describes a fantastical, unrealistic, or overly optimistic idea. This sets up the joke by framing the subject as a product of pure fantasy.

spongebob-imagination.image_description: This meme features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series of the same name, standing with his hands outstretched and a joyful expression. A sparkling rainbow arches over his head, originating from his hands. This image, often referred to as the "Imagination SpongeBob" meme, is taken from the episode "Idiot Box." It is typically used to sarcastically mock an idea or statement by juxtaposing a fantastical or unrealistic concept (represented by the rainbow) with a mundane or contrary reality.

Kids-Afraid-of-Rabbit.name: Kids-Afraid-of-Rabbit

text_options.description: This text labels the rabbit, which represents the source of the fear. It is typically something harmless, mundane, or even positive that the subject of the meme is irrationally afraid of, such as 'commitment,' 'a stable job,' or 'positive feedback.'

This text labels the crying boy and his sister, representing the person or group having an exaggerated and fearful reaction. It is almost always labeled 'Me' or a specific demographic to identify who is overreacting to the object labeled on the rabbit.

Kids-Afraid-of-Rabbit.image_description: This meme, often called 'Kids Scared of Rabbit,' features a young boy crying hysterically while his older sister holds him back from a small black rabbit. The image captures a moment of irrational fear and overreaction to a harmless subject. It is typically used to represent someone being terrified of something benign, mundane, or even beneficial, creating a humorous contrast between the perceived threat and the extreme reaction.

Over-Your-Head.name: Over-Your-Head

text_options.description: This text labels the character. It typically represents a person, group, or entity that is blissfully or willfully ignoring an obvious problem or warning sign.
This text labels the object flying past the character's head. It represents the obvious problem, red flag, or piece of information that is being ignored by the character.

Over-Your-Head.image_description: This meme, often called "Thing Flying Past Head" or "Ignoring a Red Flag," originates from a webcomic by SrGrafo. It features a simple, serene-looking cartoon character who remains completely unfazed as an object flies rapidly past their head. The meme is used to represent someone willfully or naively ignoring an obvious problem, warning sign, or piece of information. The character represents the person doing the ignoring, while the flying object symbolizes the red flag or issue being disregarded.

They-hated-Jesus-meme.name: They-hated-Jesus-meme

text_options.description: This caption originally reads "They hated Jesus because He told them the truth." In the meme, the name "Jesus" is often replaced by the name of the person or entity delivering the unpopular opinion in box 1, framing them as a truth-teller who is being unfairly rejected.

This speech bubble, originating from an unseen speaker (implied to be Jesus), is where the meme creator places their controversial or hard-to-swallow opinion. This statement is presented as the "truth" that the angry crowd below is rejecting.

They-hated-Jesus-meme.image_description: This meme, known as "They Hated Jesus Because He Told Them the Truth," originates from a Christian comic book. It depicts an angry crowd reacting negatively to a message, with a caption from Galatians 4:16. The meme is used to present a controversial or unpopular opinion, which the user frames as an inconvenient truth that others reject, often for humorous or trivial subjects.

Arnold-Schwarzenegger-Mr-Bean.name: Arnold-Schwarzenegger-Mr-Bean

text_options.description: This label identifies the powerful, skilled, or serious entity. It represents the 'workhorse' or the capable tool in the scenario, such as a highly skilled professional, a powerful computer, or a complex piece of software.

This label identifies the user or the purpose for which the powerful entity is being used. It typically represents someone or something seemingly simple, clueless, or trivial that is in control, creating a humorous contrast with the entity labeled '0'.

Arnold-Schwarzenegger-Mr-Bean.image_description: This photoshopped meme features two iconic characters: Arnold Schwarzenegger as the formidable Terminator and Rowan Atkinson as the bumbling Mr. Bean. The Terminator, a powerful cyborg, is depicted carrying Mr. Bean, who is casually sitting in an armchair on his shoulder. This absurd juxtaposition is used to represent a powerful, complex, or skilled entity being controlled or used by a much simpler, sillier, or less competent one for a trivial purpose.

Tier-List.name: Tier-List

text_options.description: This is the "F" tier row, the lowest possible rank. Items placed here are considered the absolute worst, failures, or completely undesirable within the context of the ranking.
This is the "E" tier row, representing a very low rank. Items in this row are considered bad or significantly below average, but perhaps not the absolute worst.
This is the "D" tier row, for items that are below average or mediocre. Things placed here are generally not recommended or are seen as having significant flaws.
This is the "C" tier row, which typically represents the average or middle-of-the-road items. They are considered decent or acceptable, but not particularly special or noteworthy.
This is the "B" tier row, for items that are good or above average. These are solid choices that are generally well-regarded but fall short of being the best.
This is the "A" tier row, representing a high rank. Items placed here are considered excellent, top-quality, and highly recommended, just shy of the absolute pinnacle.

This is the "S" tier row, the highest possible rank. The "S" often stands for "Super" or "Special," and this row is reserved for items deemed god-tier, flawless, or the undisputed best in their category.

Tier-List.image_description: This is a blank "Tier List" meme template, a popular format for ranking items, characters, or concepts. The list features a vertical column of colored boxes on the left labeled with letters S, A, B, C, D, E, and F, which represent hierarchical ranks from best (S-tier) to worst (F-tier). Next to each rank is a large, empty horizontal row where users place images or text to categorize them according to their personal or community-based valuation.

Comic-Book-Guy.name: Comic-Book-Guy

text_options.description: This area on Comic Book Guy's torso is typically labeled with the person, group, or entity who is expressing the harsh judgment. For example, it might be labeled "Me," "Critics," or a specific fandom to identify the source of the disappointment.

This space above the character's head contains the punchline, which follows the format "Worst. [Subject]. Ever." The subject is whatever the meme creator finds disappointing or terrible. This text directly quotes the character's famous catchphrase, delivering the core of the joke.

Comic-Book-Guy.image_description: This meme features the character Comic Book Guy from the animated TV show The Simpsons. He is depicted with a look of disgust and disappointment, which is central to the meme's theme. The format is famously known as "Worst. [X]. Ever.", derived from his catchphrase. It's used to hyperbolically express extreme dissatisfaction or criticism towards a particular subject, often related to pop culture, but applicable to any disappointing situation.

Loading-cat.name: Loading-cat

text_options.description: The bottom text typically presents a statement, question, or situation that is confusing, complex, or unexpected, causing the subject to pause and process. This is the catalyst for the 'buffering' reaction depicted by the cat.

The top text usually identifies the person or entity experiencing the confusion, often labeled as 'Me:' or a similar identifier. This text provides the context for who is having the slow mental processing moment.

Loading-cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Loading Cat" or "Buffering Cat," features a cat looking down with a spinning loading icon on its forehead. The image humorously represents a moment of confusion, slow processing, or a delayed reaction. It's used to illustrate someone trying to understand a complex question, a surprising statement, or a sudden realization dawning on them.

Expanding-Brain-5-Panel.name: Expanding-Brain-5-Panel

text_options.description: This bottom-most text box corresponds to the image of a transcendent, meditating figure, representing the ultimate level of enlightenment. The text here is the punchline, presenting the most absurd, nonsensical, or ironically profound idea in the sequence.

This text box is paired with the iconic "galaxy brain" image, where the brain is glowing and emitting light. The text here usually introduces a significant leap in logic, presenting an overly complex or ridiculous idea that satirizes "big brain" thinking.

This text box is placed next to the third brain image, which is glowing brightly. The text here typically represents a more sophisticated or seemingly intelligent option compared to the ones above it, continuing the logical progression before the meme turns ironic.

This text box corresponds to the second image from the top, showing a brain with some glowing synapses. The text here represents a slightly more advanced or nuanced idea than the first, building on the established hierarchy.

This top-most text box is paired with the image of a small, simple brain in an X-ray. The text here represents the most basic, conventional, or common idea or action, serving as the starting point for the meme's escalating scale.

Expanding-Brain-5-Panel.image_description: This is the "Expanding Brain" or "Galaxy Brain" meme format, which uses a series of images depicting increasing levels of consciousness or intelligence. The meme satirically ranks concepts or actions, with the progression moving from a simple, normal idea to increasingly absurd, nonsensical, or ironically brilliant ones. The final, most "enlightened" stage typically represents the most ridiculous or unexpected take, making it a tool for ironic commentary.

BABY-CRYING.name: BABY-CRYING

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which serves as the punchline. It completes the thought started in the top text by revealing the trivial 'first world problem' that is causing the exaggerated distress, such as '...BUT THE REMOTE IS ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE COUCH'.

The top text of the image macro, which sets up the scenario. This line typically introduces a situation or desire that will be comically undermined by the punchline at the bottom, for example, 'I HATE IT WHEN...'

BABY-CRYING.image_description: This meme, known as 'First World Problems,' features a stock photo of a baby crying with a distressed expression. The format is a classic image macro used to express frustration over trivial inconveniences experienced by people in privileged, developed nations. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the baby's intense sorrow with a caption detailing a minor issue, such as slow internet or a forgotten password, ironically framing it as a major catastrophe.

Picard-Wtf.name: Picard-Wtf

text_options.description: The text at the bottom is the punchline of the meme. It specifies the particular person, object, or action that is the source of the frustration mentioned in the top line. Its placement at the bottom, directly in front of Picard's gesturing hand, emphasizes it as the target of his annoyance.

The text at the top serves as the setup, posing a question or making a statement that expresses frustration or disbelief. It often begins with an expletive phrase like "Why the fuck..." or "What the fuck..." to establish a tone of exasperation.

Picard-Wtf.image_description: This meme features Captain Jean-Luc Picard from Star Trek: The Next Generation, with his hand raised in a gesture of exasperation. Known as "Annoyed Picard" or "Why the fuck...", the meme is used to express frustration or disbelief at a particular situation, action, or idea. The format typically poses a rhetorical question in the top line, followed by the specific, illogical subject of the complaint in the bottom line.

Annoyed-face.name: Annoyed-face

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the boy's chest, typically describes the internal struggle, the embarrassing secret, or the uncomfortable thought the person is trying to suppress. This caption reveals the true source of the awkwardness that is causing the strained expression.

The top text, placed above the boy's head, sets up the external social context or the situation that is causing the internal conflict. It describes the scenario in which the person must maintain their composure.

Annoyed-face.image_description: This meme, known as "Awkward Smile Kid" or "Trying to Hold a Fart Next to a Cute Girl in Class," features a school portrait of a young boy with a very strained and uncomfortable smile. His expression perfectly captures a moment of intense internal struggle while trying to maintain a calm and normal exterior. The meme is used to represent situations where someone is hiding extreme discomfort, anxiety, or a secret in a social setting, pretending that everything is okay.

Aww-did-someone-get-addicted-to-crack.name: Aww-did-someone-get-addicted-to-crack

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It typically describes the trivial, ironic, or self-inflicted problem that the characters are pretending to be upset about.
The top text of the meme, which provides the setup. This text usually describes an action, choice, or situation that directly leads to the minor inconvenience or "problem" stated in the bottom text.

Aww-did-someone-get-addicted-to-crack.image_description: This meme features Charlie Kelly and Mac from the TV show "It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia" pretending to cry in an exaggerated, insincere manner. Known as "Professional Whiners" or "Hired Mourners," the image is used to sarcastically mock complaints about trivial, self-inflicted, or "first-world" problems. The over-the-top fake crying highlights the absurdity and lack of genuine distress regarding the issue being complained about.
Aww-did-someone-get-addicted-to-crack.display_name: Aww did someone get addicted to crack

Hey-you-going-to-sleep.name: Hey-you-going-to-sleep

text_options.description: This box highlights the person in bed, now with wide, startled eyes, unable to sleep. This area shows the reaction to the brain's intrusive thought, serving as the visual punchline of the meme. No text is typically placed here.

This is a blank speech bubble for the brain in the third panel. This is the customizable part of the meme where users insert an intrusive thought, an embarrassing memory, a cringey moment, or a stressful question that prevents the person from sleeping.

Hey-you-going-to-sleep.image_description: This is a four-panel comic meme known as "Brain, Go to Sleep" or "Hey you goin' to sleep?". The meme illustrates the common experience of one's own brain bringing up intrusive, embarrassing, or anxiety-inducing thoughts right before sleep. In the first two panels, a person tells their personified brain they are going to sleep, and in the final panel, they are wide-eyed and awake, disturbed by the thought the brain introduces in the third panel.

Blank-Cereal-Guy.name: Blank-Cereal-Guy

text_options.description: This text box is in the bottom-left panel. It typically contains the punchline or the most shocking piece of information that causes the Cereal Guy's exaggerated reaction. It follows the setup in the panel above (index 2).

This text box is in the top-right panel, over the calm Cereal Guy. It usually represents the character's initial, unsuspecting thought or a neutral statement, establishing the 'before' state prior to the shocking reveal.

This text box is in the top-left panel. It serves as the setup, presenting the first part of a statement or an initial image that the Cereal Guy is observing. It leads into the punchline in the panel below (index 0).

Blank-Cereal-Guy.image_description: This is the 'Cereal Guy Spit Take' rage comic meme. The four-panel format shows a stick figure character, Cereal Guy, calmly eating cereal in the top-right panel. He then reads or sees something in the left-hand panels, causing him to spit out his cereal in a dramatic, shocked reaction in the bottom-right panel. The meme is used to express exaggerated surprise, disbelief, or disgust in response to a preceding statement or image.

Gina-Linetti.name: Gina-Linetti
