text_options.description: This label is placed on Gina Linetti. The text here represents the person or entity who is blissfully or intentionally ignoring a chaotic situation or pressing issue.
This label is placed on the chaotic scene in the background. The text here describes the problem, responsibility, or chaotic event that is being ignored by the person in the foreground.

Gina-Linetti.image_description: This meme features Gina Linetti from the TV show Brooklyn Nine-Nine, who is peacefully listening to music on her headphones in the foreground, completely oblivious to a chaotic brawl happening among her police colleagues in the background. The stark contrast between her calm demeanor and the surrounding turmoil is the core of the joke. This format is used to represent someone willfully ignoring their responsibilities, problems, or any form of chaos and drama in their life.

Dumpster-Fire.name: Dumpster-Fire

text_options.description: Text placed on the dumpster itself identifies the subject that is considered a complete mess or a failure. This could be a person, a company, a project, a year (e.g., '2020'), or even the user's own life.

Text placed over the flames often describes the specific problem, event, or cause of the chaos that is consuming the subject labeled on the dumpster. It adds context to why the situation is a 'dumpster fire'.

Dumpster-Fire.image_description: The 'Dumpster Fire' meme shows a photograph of a large green dumpster with intense flames and smoke billowing out of it. This image is the literal representation of the popular idiom 'a dumpster fire,' which is used to describe a situation that is chaotically disastrous and hopelessly out of control. The meme is typically used to label a person, event, or entity as a complete and utter failure or a catastrophic mess.

Guy-checks-out-red-dress-girl.name: Guy-checks-out-red-dress-girl

text_options.description: This label is placed on the girlfriend, who represents the current, sensible, or obligatory option that is being neglected. The text here signifies a commitment, responsibility, or the status quo that the subject (the boyfriend) is supposed to be focused on.

This label is placed on the man, who represents the subject of the meme. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is making a choice or being distracted from their current commitment in favor of a new temptation.

This label is placed on the woman in the red dress, who represents the new, attractive, or distracting alternative. The text here signifies the temptation, new trend, or appealing option that is drawing the subject's attention away from their responsibilities.

Guy-checks-out-red-dress-girl.image_description: This meme, known as "Distracted Boyfriend," features a man in a plaid shirt looking admiringly at another woman in a red dress, while his girlfriend looks on with an expression of shock and disgust. The three figures are typically labeled to represent a person or entity (the man) being tempted by a new, appealing option (the woman in red) over their current responsibility or commitment (the girlfriend). The format is widely used to humorously depict infidelity, poor choices, or shifting priorities.
Guy-checks-out-red-dress-girl.display_name: Guy checks out red dress girl

Yugioh-card-draw.name: Yugioh-card-draw

text_options.description: The text here, on Yugi's card, represents the superior counter-argument or winning move. This is the punchline that completely invalidates or outclasses the statement in the first panel, leading to Kaiba's defeated reaction.
The text here, placed on Kaiba's card, represents the initial, often inferior or flawed, statement, argument, or plan. It serves as the setup for the meme's punchline.

Yugioh-card-draw.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Kaiba's Defeat" or "Yugi's Legendary Move," originates from the anime *Yu-Gi-Oh!*. It depicts a duel where the rival, Seto Kaiba, makes a move, only to be countered by the protagonist, Yami Yugi, with a far superior play. Kaiba's final shocked expression signifies his utter defeat, making the format perfect for showing a weak argument or action being overwhelmingly trumped by a clever or powerful counter-argument.

Fairly-odd-parents.name: Fairly-odd-parents

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the angry face of Timmy's Dad in the bottom panel. It contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always the phrase "...IF I HAD ONE!" This text conveys the frustration and reveals the reality that the item mentioned in the top panel is missing.

Located in the top panel, this text box describes the desired object, achievement, or situation that the user wishes they possessed. It sets up the joke by showing Timmy's Dad proudly presenting the place where this hypothetical item would go, creating an expectation that is subverted in the second panel.

Fairly-odd-parents.image_description: This two-panel meme features Timmy's Dad from the animated show 'The Fairly OddParents,' in a scene that has become the "This Is Where I'd Put My Trophy... If I Had One!" format. In the top panel, he proudly gestures to an empty pedestal, representing a desired object or achievement. The bottom panel shows his expression shifting to intense anger and frustration, delivering the punchline. The meme is used to express bitter disappointment or lament the absence of something one desires.

shrek-five-minutes.name: shrek-five-minutes

text_options.description: This text box is on the bottom panel, representing Donkey's plea or the person/thing making a request. The text here is typically the question or statement that challenges the initial stance shown in the top panel, often framed in a cute, persistent, or desperate way to elicit a change of heart.

This text box is on the top panel, representing Shrek's initial, often negative, stance or a general rule. The text here sets up the conflict by establishing a firm position that is about to be challenged by the text in the bottom panel.

shrek-five-minutes.image_description: This two-panel meme features Shrek and Donkey from the movie "Shrek." In the top panel, Shrek has a stern, contemplative expression. In the bottom panel, he looks down at Donkey, who is looking up at him pleadingly. The meme format is used to depict a situation where someone initially resistant or hesitant (Shrek) is about to give in to a persistent request (from Donkey), often with a sense of reluctant acceptance.

borat.name: borat

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically describes the situation, object, or person that is being enthusiastically approved of. It sets up the context for the punchline.

The top text box almost always contains Borat's iconic catchphrase, "Very Nice!" or a variation of it. This text serves as the punchline, delivering the enthusiastic and often sarcastic approval that defines the meme.

borat.image_description: This meme features the character Borat Sagdiyev, portrayed by Sacha Baron Cohen, from the 2006 film "Borat." He is shown wearing a grey suit, sporting his signature mustache, and giving two enthusiastic thumbs up with a wide, slightly manic grin. The meme is famously associated with his catchphrase "Very nice!" and is used to express strong, often ironic or sarcastic, approval of a situation or statement.

Heavy-Breathing-Cat.name: Heavy-Breathing-Cat

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, almost always containing the phrase "(heavy breathing)" or a variation. Placed at the bottom, it acts as a caption for the cat's expression, verbalizing the intense internal reaction of desire or anticipation. The parentheses suggest it's an action or a thought, completing the joke.

The top text area is optional but commonly used to provide context. It describes the situation or the object of desire that is causing the intense reaction depicted by the cat. For example, it might read "When I see pizza" or "New game trailer drops," setting up the scenario for the punchline below.

Heavy-Breathing-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Heavy Breathing Cat," features a close-up of a cat with wide, intense eyes. It is used to express extreme anticipation, desire, or excitement for something, often to a comical or obsessive degree. The cat's focused expression perfectly captures the feeling of being overwhelmed by want, commonly in reaction to seeing desirable things like food, new products, or attractive people.

Happy-Picard.name: Happy-Picard

text_options.description: The bottom text provides the punchline or the satisfying resolution to the setup above. This text reveals the positive outcome or clever solution that justifies Picard's triumphant expression, completing the joke.

The top text sets up a scenario, often posing a question or describing a situation that seems problematic or confusing. A common format starts with 'Why the fuck...' to express initial bewilderment before the satisfying answer is given below.

Happy-Picard.image_description: This meme features Captain Jean-Luc Picard from Star Trek: The Next Generation, looking extremely pleased and clenching his fists in a triumphant gesture. Known as 'Happy Picard' or 'Triumphant Picard,' this image is used to express immense joy, satisfaction, or a successful outcome. The meme format typically involves a two-part text structure where a problem or question is posed, and the resolution is a source of great delight, mirroring Picard's expression.

Homer-Simpson-in-Bush---Large.name: Homer-Simpson-in-Bush---Large

text_options.description: Text in this bottom section typically describes the awkward situation, uncomfortable fact, or undesirable outcome that the subject (labeled in box 1) is trying to escape from. Homer's disappearance into the bushes visually represents the retreat from whatever is described here.
Text in this top section labels Homer Simpson, representing a person, group, or entity. This sets up the character who will then awkwardly retreat from the situation described in the bottom panel.

Homer-Simpson-in-Bush---Large.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Homer Backs into Bushes," originates from an episode of The Simpsons. It depicts the character Homer Simpson awkwardly and slowly retreating backward until he is completely engulfed by a large green hedge. The meme is widely used to humorously illustrate a desire to disappear from an embarrassing, awkward, or uncomfortable situation, often after saying or doing something regrettable.

fastest-thing-possible.name: fastest-thing-possible

text_options.description: This is the label for the fourth panel, corresponding to the fastest item. It typically contains the same text as the panel above it (index 1) or a shortened version, naming the subject of the punchline to match the format of the other panels.

This is the customizable punchline area of the meme. Users insert text here to describe the thing they are comically claiming is the fastest on Earth, faster than a cheetah, an airplane, and even the speed of light.

fastest-thing-possible.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, titled "The Fastest Things On Earth," establishes a pattern of increasing speed by showing a cheetah, an airplane, and the speed of light, each with a corresponding speed bar. The final panel is left blank for customization, with its speed bar completely full and glowing red, indicating a speed that humorously surpasses the speed of light. The meme is used to exaggerate the velocity of any given action, reaction, or phenomenon for comedic effect.

mom-throwing-baby.name: mom-throwing-baby

text_options.description: Text placed on the woman represents the person, group, or entity that is abandoning or getting rid of something. This character is the actor in the meme's scenario.
Text placed on the baby represents the responsibility, problem, or object that is being abandoned or "yeeted." This is the thing being discarded by the person labeled in box 0.

mom-throwing-baby.image_description: This meme, often called "Woman Throwing a Baby" or "Yeet Baby," features a cartoon illustration of a woman enthusiastically throwing a baby into the air. The woman represents a person or entity, while the baby symbolizes a responsibility, problem, or unwanted item. The meme is used to humorously depict the act of abandoning or getting rid of something with force and disregard, a concept popularly known as "yeeting."

spongebob-magic.name: spongebob-magic

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or the core concept being mockingly presented. This text is often a mundane, absurd, or sarcastic statement that is framed as something magical or profound by SpongeBob's 'imagination' gesture.

The top text box typically contains the word 'Imagination,' directly referencing the scene from the show. It acts as a title or a label for the concept being presented below, setting the sarcastic tone of the meme.

spongebob-magic.image_description: A still image from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants featuring the main character, SpongeBob, with his hands outstretched creating a rainbow. This meme, known as 'Imagination SpongeBob' or 'Spongebob's Imagination', is used to sarcastically present an idea or concept. The rainbow gesture, originally representing the power of imagination, is repurposed to mockingly highlight a mundane, silly, or obvious statement.

Presidential-Alert.name: Presidential-Alert

text_options.description: This area at the very bottom of the image, over the phone's app dock, is not part of the original notification. In memes, this space is sometimes used for a secondary caption, a watermark, or a social media handle to credit the creator, separate from the main punchline within the alert itself.

This is the main body of the notification and the central location for the meme's punchline. The text here is edited to be a funny, absurd, or attention-grabbing message that is framed as an urgent national announcement, creating the core comedic element of the meme.

Presidential-Alert.image_description: This meme format, known as "Presidential Alert," features a close-up of a smartphone screen displaying an emergency notification. Originating from a 2018 U.S. national wireless alert system test, the meme replaces the official message with a humorous, absurd, or urgent personal announcement. The humor derives from the contrast between the serious, unblockable nature of a presidential alert and the often trivial or ridiculous custom text, making it a template for making a loud, unignorable statement.

Sixth-Sense.name: Sixth-Sense

text_options.description: This is the punchline, typically completing the phrase from the top text. It reveals the specific thing that is seen everywhere, such as "[X] people" or simply "[X] everywhere," creating a humorous or relatable complaint about its ubiquity.
This top text box sets up the joke, often starting with "I see..." to mimic the original line from the movie. It introduces the general category or subject of the observation.

Sixth-Sense.image_description: This meme features a close-up of a fearful-looking Cole Sear (Haley Joel Osment) from the 1999 film "The Sixth Sense." The original, iconic line is "I see dead people," which is parodied in the meme format. This template is used to express the overwhelming and often annoying prevalence of a certain trend, topic, or type of person by replacing "dead people" with something else.

Good-Morning-Vietnam.name: Good-Morning-Vietnam

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It replaces the word "Vietnam" from the original movie quote to specify the target of the enthusiastic greeting, often a group of people, a place, or a concept relevant to a current event or inside joke.

This top text box contains the setup for the announcement, typically starting with "Gooooood morning" or a similar exclamatory greeting. It mimics the iconic radio sign-on from the movie, establishing the loud and energetic tone of the meme.

Good-Morning-Vietnam.image_description: This meme features actor Robin Williams as Adrian Cronauer from the film "Good Morning, Vietnam," enthusiastically shouting into a microphone. The image is used as a two-panel exploitable meme format to make a loud, often humorous announcement. The top text sets up the greeting, while the bottom text reveals the subject or audience, replacing the original "Vietnam" with a new punchline.

Sure-Jan.name: Sure-Jan

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the girl's simplistic, often nonsensical, or comically incorrect explanation or response. The text here is meant to be a punchline that contrasts sharply with the topic in the top box, leveraging her smug expression for comedic effect.

The top text box introduces a complex, confusing, or absurd topic, often framed as a question or statement from another person (frequently a man trying to explain something). This text sets up the joke by presenting a problem that seems to require a detailed answer.

Sure-Jan.image_description: This meme, known as 'Girl Explaining' or 'Smug Girl Explaining,' features a young blonde girl (Chloe from the Disney show 'Good Luck Charlie') with a smug, knowing smirk. The format is typically used to contrast a complex, confusing, or serious topic with a simplistic, comically incorrect, or dismissive explanation. The humor arises from the girl's confident expression as she delivers her simple 'explanation' to a complicated problem.

ha-gay.name: ha-gay

text_options.description: This bottom text area is often left blank, as the visual reaction of the other students serves as the punchline. When text is present, it might provide a label for the unimpressed audience or a quiet, contrasting reaction to the yelling.

The top text box contains the statement being yelled by Señor Chang. This text represents a loud, often obnoxious or obvious opinion, a controversial take, or a simple observation delivered with unwarranted intensity, setting up the meme's central joke.

ha-gay.image_description: This meme features Señor Chang from the TV show 'Community' yelling with his hands cupped around his mouth in a classroom, while other students look on with annoyed or indifferent expressions. The format is used to represent someone loudly and obnoxiously proclaiming an opinion, often one that is obvious, controversial, or unwelcome. The humor comes from the contrast between the loud proclamation and the silent disapproval of the audience.

Damn-I-kinda-dont-meme.name: Damn-I-kinda-dont-meme

text_options.description: This text box is at the bottom of the image and contains the punchline. It typically holds the phrase "don't care" or a similar dismissive statement, which delivers the humorous and indifferent conclusion to the setup phrase at the top.

This text box is positioned to complete the sentence starting with "Damn.... I kinda". The text here sets up the joke by stating what the person is supposedly contemplating, creating a contrast with the eventual punchline of indifference.

Damn-I-kinda-dont-meme.image_description: This meme, known as "Confused Black Boy" or "Damn... I kinda don't care," features a young Black boy with a puzzled yet smug expression, scratching his head. The image is typically paired with text that feigns consideration before bluntly expressing indifference. This format is used to humorously dismiss a topic, opinion, or situation, conveying a sassy lack of concern.

Fist-pump-baby.name: Fist-pump-baby

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which reveals the successful outcome or the punchline. This text completes the setup from the top, describing the small victory that warrants the baby's triumphant expression.

The top text of the meme, which sets up a situation or challenge. It typically describes a scenario where failure or a negative outcome is expected, creating anticipation for the successful resolution below.

Fist-pump-baby.image_description: The "Success Kid" meme features a toddler on a beach with a determined expression, clenching a fistful of sand. This iconic image is used to express a feeling of victory or relief in everyday situations. Typically, the text describes a scenario that could have gone wrong but ended up being a small, personal win, making it a universally relatable symbol for minor triumphs.

Cabin-the-the-woods.name: Cabin-the-the-woods

text_options.description: This section covers the bottom portion of the whiteboard list. In the meme format, this area continues the list of overwhelming options from above, often culminating in a punchline or a particularly absurd or mundane item that contrasts with the others. The original's crossed-out "RONALD THE INTERN" is often replaced with a similarly humorous failed or discarded option relevant to the meme's context.

This section covers the top portion of the whiteboard. In memes, this area is filled with a long, often overwhelming, list of user-defined items. These items typically represent various challenges, problems, anxieties, or absurd choices, setting the stage for the meme's central joke about being faced with a plethora of bad options.

Cabin-the-the-woods.image_description: This meme originates from the 2012 horror-comedy film "The Cabin in the Woods." The image shows a man in an office setting standing in front of a large whiteboard covered with a list of various monsters and horrific entities. This scene is used as an exploitable template where the list on the whiteboard is replaced with a long list of problems, anxieties, bad choices, or any overwhelming set of options, humorously framing them as bets in a morbid office pool.

Congratulations-you-are-being-rescued-pl.name: Congratulations-you-are-being-rescued-please-do-not-resist

text_options.description: This label is placed on Jyn Erso, who is lying on the ground. The text here represents the person, group, or idea that is the unwilling recipient of the forceful 'help' or 'rescue' from the entity labeled as 1.
This label is placed on the droid K-2SO. The text here represents the entity imposing its will on the other character, framing a forceful or unwanted action as a benevolent 'rescue'.

Congratulations-you-are-being-rescued-pl.image_description: This is a three-panel meme from the Star Wars movie 'Rogue One,' featuring the droid K-2SO and the character Jyn Erso. K-2SO announces he is rescuing Jyn, who appears apprehensive, and then tells her not to resist. The meme is used to satirize situations where a person or entity is forced into an unwelcome situation under the pretense that it is for their own good, highlighting the irony of a forceful or unwanted 'rescue.'
Congratulations-you-are-being-rescued-pl.display_name: Congratulations you are being rescued please do not resist

Crusader-knight-with-M60-Machine-Gun.name: Crusader-knight-with-M60-Machine-Gun

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically identifies the target of the 'crusade.' It labels the person, group, idea, or territory that the meme creator humorously suggests needs to be conquered, purged, or reclaimed with extreme prejudice.

The top text area sets up the scenario or provides the crusader's motivation. It often contains a phrase that triggers the aggressive reaction, such as 'When you hear [target] needs liberating' or a quote expressing the zealous intent, framing the subsequent action.

Crusader-knight-with-M60-Machine-Gun.image_description: This meme, often called 'Crusader with an M60' or 'Deus Vult,' features a person in full medieval crusader armor, including a great helm and chainmail, incongruously holding a modern M60 machine gun. The humor stems from this anachronism, blending historical religious zeal with contemporary overwhelming firepower. It's typically used to express an exaggerated, often ironic, desire to 'reclaim' or 'purge' something, applying the concept of a holy crusade to modern, often trivial, subjects.
Crusader-knight-with-M60-Machine-Gun.display_name: Crusader knight with M60 Machine Gun

Abuelo-Simpson.name: Abuelo-Simpson

text_options.description: This bottom text box is used to label the "cloud," which is the object of Grandpa's irrational anger. It represents the modern trend, new technology, person, or idea that the subject of the meme is complaining about.

This top text box identifies the "old man" doing the yelling. It labels the person, group, or entity that is being portrayed as out of touch and complaining about the subject labeled in the bottom box.

Abuelo-Simpson.image_description: This meme, known as "Old Man Yells at Cloud," features the character Abraham "Grandpa" Simpson from the animated series "The Simpsons." In the image, Grandpa Simpson is sitting at a desk, angrily shaking his fist and shouting. The meme is used to humorously mock people who are perceived as being out of touch, complaining about modern trends, or holding outdated, reactionary opinions, symbolizing a futile rage against things they don't understand.

Raise-your-hand-if-you-have-ever-been-pe.name: Raise-your-hand-if-you-have-ever-been-personally-victimized-by-R

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the teacher figure who is addressing the students. It contains the setup of the meme, typically a question or statement that prompts a reaction from the group.

This box covers the audience of students, all with their hands raised. This area represents the unanimous, affirmative response to the question posed in box 0. Text is not usually placed here, as the visual of everyone agreeing serves as the punchline.

Raise-your-hand-if-you-have-ever-been-pe.image_description: This meme originates from the 2004 film 'Mean Girls' and depicts a school assembly scene where a teacher asks a question to a large group of female students. The students unanimously raise their hands in response, creating a powerful visual of agreement. The format is used to pose a relatable or humorous question to which a specific group would overwhelmingly agree, with the raised hands signifying a collective 'yes' or shared experience.
Raise-your-hand-if-you-have-ever-been-pe.display_name: Raise your hand if you have ever been personally victimized by R

Doge-bonk.name: Doge-bonk

text_options.description: This bottom area is typically used to label the two characters. The dog on the left (Swole Doge) is labeled as the entity doing the punishing (e.g., "Me"), while the dog on the right (Cheems) is labeled as the person or group being punished for their transgression.

The top text box serves as the main caption, setting up the context for the meme. It usually describes the undesirable or "horny" action or statement that prompted the "bonk," providing the reason for the punishment.

Doge-bonk.image_description: This meme, known as "Bonk" or "Go to Horny Jail," features a large, muscular Shiba Inu (Swole Doge) hitting a smaller, sad-looking Shiba Inu (Cheems) on the head with a baseball bat, accompanied by the onomatopoeia "BONK." It is widely used as a reaction image to humorously punish or reprimand someone for expressing overly sexual or "horny" thoughts online. The act of "bonking" metaphorically sends the offender to "horny jail."

Insanity-Wolf.name: Insanity-Wolf

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This area contains the dangerously insane, violent, or sociopathic 'advice' that Insanity Wolf offers in response to the situation described in the top text.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a relatable situation or problem. This text establishes the context for the absurdly terrible advice that will follow in the bottom text.

Insanity-Wolf.image_description: This meme, known as "Insanity Wolf," features the head of a snarling black wolf with red eyes against a dark, grainy, geometric background. It's part of the "advice animal" image macro series and is used to give terrible, insane, or dangerously extreme advice. The humor comes from the shocking and sociopathic nature of the suggestions, which are presented as a dark parody of motivational posters.

Spongebob-Chocolate.name: Spongebob-Chocolate

text_options.description: The text in this bottom section typically labels the person or entity experiencing the extreme reaction. It often says 'Me:' to make the meme relatable, identifying the user with the overwhelmed fish character.
The text placed here, at the top of the image, describes the situation, person, or thought that is causing the intense stress, frustration, or agitation depicted by the character.

Spongebob-Chocolate.image_description: This meme features a fish character from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants looking extremely stressed and sleep-deprived, with wide, bloodshot eyes and a clenched fist. The character's agitated expression is used to represent intense frustration, anxiety, or the physical feeling of being overstimulated or overwhelmed. This image perfectly captures the feeling of being on the edge due to a difficult or annoying situation.

Star-Trek-Kirk-Khan.name: Star-Trek-Kirk-Khan

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline, representing Kirk's scream. This text replaces the original 'KHAN!' with the name of the person, object, or concept that is the source of the user's frustration, often written in all caps for emphasis.
The top text sets up the context for Kirk's rage. It usually describes a situation or a statement that would provoke an extremely frustrated reaction.

Star-Trek-Kirk-Khan.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Captain Kirk from 'Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan' screaming in anguish and rage. The image captures a moment of intense emotion, making it a popular reaction image. It is typically used to express extreme frustration or hatred towards a specific person, entity, or situation, whose name is often used as the punchline.

Terminator-Robot-T-800.name: Terminator-Robot-T-800

text_options.description: This text, placed over the Terminator's body, delivers the punchline. It identifies the person or group reacting to the setup in an overly dramatic, prepared, or serious way, humorously equating them with the battle-ready robot.
The text in this top section sets up the premise of the meme. It usually describes a simple, everyday situation or statement that will provoke an unexpectedly intense reaction.

Terminator-Robot-T-800.image_description: This meme features a close-up of a T-800 Endoskeleton from the "Terminator" film series, characterized by its metallic skull and glowing red eyes. The image portrays an intimidating, heavily armed robot ready for battle, often used to represent an overly serious or intense preparation for a mundane situation. The format typically contrasts a simple scenario (described in the top text) with this dramatic reaction, creating a humorous exaggeration of someone's response to a minor inconvenience or task.

Capitalist-and-communist.name: Capitalist-and-communist

text_options.description: This text box is the punchline, placed next to the 'Communist' Bugs Bunny. It reframes the text from the top panel to reflect collective ownership, typically by changing a singular possessive pronoun like 'my' or 'your' to the plural 'our'.

This text box serves as the setup, positioned next to the 'Capitalist' Bugs Bunny. The text here usually establishes a concept of individual ownership or a personal statement, often using words like 'I', 'my', or 'your'.

Capitalist-and-communist.image_description: This meme, known as "Communist Bugs Bunny" or "Our Meme," features a two-panel format with the cartoon character Bugs Bunny. The top panel depicts him with an American flag overlay, representing individualism or capitalism, while the bottom panel shows him with a Soviet hammer and sickle, representing collectivism or communism. The meme is used to humorously reframe something initially presented as personal or belonging to one person (e.g., "my stuff") into something shared by a group (e.g., "our stuff").

Powder-that-makes-you-say-yes.name: Powder-that-makes-you-say-yes

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the document Plastic Man is reading. It contains the stimulus or the shocking information that causes his extreme reaction. This is the setup for the punchline.

Located in the speech bubble, this text represents Plastic Man's verbal reaction to what he has just read. It typically contains an expression of disbelief, a question, or a statement of shock that complements the visual.

Powder-that-makes-you-say-yes.image_description: This meme features a comic book panel of the DC superhero Plastic Man, looking utterly shocked with his jaw dropped while reading a document. The image is used to represent an extreme, exaggerated reaction of disbelief, horror, or being overwhelmed by some piece of information. The humor comes from the over-the-top visual response to the text presented.
Powder-that-makes-you-say-yes.display_name: Powder that makes you say yes

confused-screaming.name: confused-screaming

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, a closed-caption style text reading "*Confused screaming*". It explicitly labels the action and emotion of the character, serving as the reaction to the setup provided in the top text. This text is fundamental to the meme's identity and is rarely changed.

This top caption area is where the setup for the meme is placed. The text here describes a confusing, contradictory, or overwhelming scenario that causes the user to react with the "confused screaming" depicted in the image below.

confused-screaming.image_description: This meme, known as "Confused Screaming," features a screenshot of internet personality Joji, from his time as the character Filthy Frank. The image captures him with a look of utter panic and confusion, mouth agape in a scream. It's a popular reaction image used to express a state of bewilderment, internal conflict, or being overwhelmed by a bizarre or nonsensical situation.

Professor-X.name: Professor-X

text_options.description: This bottom caption typically identifies the person or entity exerting the mental effort. It sets up the context for who is concentrating so intensely.

This top caption, placed over Professor X's head, represents the specific thought, command, or desire being mentally projected. It's the punchline that reveals what the intense concentration is focused on, often something relatable or trivial.

Professor-X.image_description: This meme features Professor X from the 90s X-Men animated series, looking strained with his hands on his temples as red psychic energy waves emanate from his head. The image captures a moment of intense mental effort or concentration. It is typically used to humorously depict someone trying to mentally will something to happen, prevent an undesirable outcome, or struggling with a powerful, often mundane, thought.

the-more-you-know.name: the-more-you-know

text_options.description: The bottom text box is typically used for a concluding statement or a punchline that complements the information presented at the top. It can also be left blank, as the image itself often serves as the punchline, implying the phrase "The More You Know."

The top text box is where the main piece of information or the setup for the joke is placed. This text presents a fact, a realization, or an observation that is often trivial, obvious, or humorous, setting the stage for the PSA-style conclusion.

the-more-you-know.image_description: This meme features the iconic logo from the NBC public service announcement (PSA) series, "The More You Know." The image shows the 3D text "The More You Know" flying through a starry space background, trailed by a bright yellow star with a rainbow-colored tail. The meme is used to sarcastically or genuinely share a piece of information, a newfound realization, or a trivial fact, mimicking the educational and wholesome tone of the original PSAs.

show-me-the-real.name: show-me-the-real

text_options.description: This bottom panel is the punchline. The text here represents the ultimate, most authentic, or "perfect" version of the subject, corresponding to Magneto's most intense expression of approval. It's the final reveal in the hierarchical comparison.

The text in this middle panel typically describes an improved or more desirable version of the item mentioned in the top panel. It acts as a step up in the hierarchy, building towards the final reveal in the bottom panel.

This top panel serves as the setup for the meme. The text here introduces the initial, often common or less-desirable, version of the subject being compared. It establishes the baseline for the progression that follows.

show-me-the-real.image_description: This is a three-panel meme featuring the character Erik Lehnsherr (Magneto), played by Michael Fassbender, from the film "X-Men: First Class." The format, often called "Perfection" or "I Said The Real...", is used to show a hierarchical progression of a concept. Each panel presents a version of something, with the bottom panel revealing the ultimate, most authentic, or "perfect" version, corresponding to Magneto's increasingly intense and approving expression.

Chris-Pratt---Too-Afraid-to-Ask.name: Chris-Pratt---Too-Afraid-to-Ask

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always a variation of '...and at this point I'm too afraid to ask.' This phrase captures the core sentiment of the meme: the social awkwardness and fear of admitting one's lack of knowledge about a seemingly common topic.

This top text box sets up the premise of the meme. It typically contains a statement of ignorance, such as 'I don't know what [popular thing] is' or 'I missed the part where everyone learned about [topic].' This text establishes the subject that the person is too afraid to inquire about.

Chris-Pratt---Too-Afraid-to-Ask.image_description: This meme features Andy Dwyer, a character played by Chris Pratt in the TV show 'Parks and Recreation', looking confused and slightly concerned. The image is from a scene where he admits to not knowing what something is. This meme, known as 'Afraid to Ask Andy', is used to humorously confess ignorance about a popular topic or trend that the user feels they should already know but is too embarrassed to ask about.
Chris-Pratt---Too-Afraid-to-Ask.display_name: Chris Pratt   Too Afraid to Ask

blinking-guy-vertical-blank.name: blinking-guy-vertical-blank

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to the final panel, where the man has completed his blink and is staring again. It typically contains the shocking, absurd, or unbelievable statement that causes the double-take reaction, serving as the punchline of the meme.

This text box is next to the first panel, showing the man's initial neutral expression. It usually presents the initial context or a seemingly normal statement that sets up the punchline which will follow.

blinking-guy-vertical-blank.image_description: The 'Blinking White Guy' meme is a three-panel reaction image featuring Drew Scanlon. The first panel shows his neutral, slightly confused face, the second shows him blinking, and the third returns to the initial expression, creating the effect of a double-take. This sequence is used to express disbelief, shock, or confusion in response to a surprising or absurd statement or situation.

Master-Oogway.name: Master-Oogway

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the main punchline or quote attributed to Master Oogway. It's typically either a declaration of departure (e.g., "My time has come") or a humorous, pseudo-profound piece of advice that plays on his wise persona.

This top text area provides the context or setup for the punchline below. It usually describes an awkward or undesirable situation that prompts the reaction in the bottom text. In the 'fake quote' variation of the meme, this area is often left blank.

Master-Oogway.image_description: This meme features Master Oogway, the wise old tortoise from the movie 'Kung Fu Panda', smiling serenely with a finger raised against a starry night sky. The image is associated with his profound quotes, most notably "My time has come" and "There are no accidents." The format is used to either humorously announce one's departure from a situation or to share fake, often funny, 'wise' advice.

Memes-Poop-Jurassic-Park.name: Memes-Poop-Jurassic-Park

text_options.description: Text placed over the giant pile of droppings represents the thing being criticized or dismissed. This is the subject that the meme creator considers to be a "big pile of shit," such as a bad argument, a terrible movie, a political statement, or a flimsy excuse.

Text placed over Dr. Ian Malcolm and the background identifies the person, group, or entity reacting to the subject with disdain. This label represents the observer who is unimpressed and sees the subject for the nonsense it is.

Memes-Poop-Jurassic-Park.image_description: This meme features a still image of Dr. Ian Malcolm (played by Jeff Goldblum) from the 1993 film Jurassic Park, standing next to a massive pile of dinosaur droppings. The scene is famously accompanied by his line, "That is one big pile of shit." As a meme, it is used as a reaction to express strong disapproval, disbelief, or to call out something as nonsensical, false, or of extremely poor quality.

Sad-Spongebob.name: Sad-Spongebob

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically sets up the scenario or identifies the person or group feeling sad. It provides the context for the emotional reaction depicted, often describing a hopeful or neutral situation before the disappointment occurs.

The top text area usually contains the punchline or the specific cause of the sadness. This text reveals the disappointing outcome or statement that leads to SpongeBob's heartbroken expression, completing the joke.

Sad-Spongebob.image_description: This meme features a close-up of the cartoon character SpongeBob SquarePants looking utterly heartbroken. His eyes are large, detailed, and filled with tears, and a single teardrop is rolling down his cheek, conveying extreme sadness or disappointment. This image, known as "Sad SpongeBob" or "Crying SpongeBob," is a popular reaction meme used to humorously express feelings of being let down, sad, or devastated over a relatable situation.

Spongebob-Coffee.name: Spongebob-Coffee

text_options.description: This bottom text box represents the internal monologue or anxious thoughts of the person depicted by SpongeBob. It's the punchline of the meme, revealing an over-the-top, worried, or overly analytical response to the situation set up by the top text.
The top text box provides the context or setup for the meme. It usually contains a simple question, statement, or action from another person that triggers SpongeBob's anxious reaction.

Spongebob-Coffee.image_description: This meme, known as "Anxious SpongeBob" or "SpongeBob Waiting," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the eponymous animated series. He is depicted sitting alone in a diner with a worried and pensive expression, staring into the distance. The empty setting emphasizes his isolation and anxiety, making the meme perfect for representing situations of overthinking, social anxiety, or nervously waiting for a response or event.

Black-woman-squinting.name: Black-woman-squinting

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the bottom of the image, representing the person or entity who is squinting. It typically labels the subject of the meme, such as 'Me,' 'My mom,' or any group, to establish the perspective of who is trying to understand something.

Located in the upper part of the image, this text box describes the confusing, unbelievable, or hard-to-see thing that the subject is squinting at. This text serves as the punchline, revealing the source of the subject's intense concentration or disbelief.

Black-woman-squinting.image_description: The 'Squinting Woman' meme features a photo of internet personality Kayla Nicole Jones bending over with her hands on her knees, squinting intensely as if trying to see something far away or unclear. This image is used to humorously represent moments of confusion, disbelief, or intense scrutiny when trying to understand something perplexing or hard to believe. The meme's format typically involves labeling the woman as the subject and the background as the confusing object of her focus.

My-death-was-greatly-exaggerated.name: My-death-was-greatly-exaggerated

text_options.description: This label is placed on Metro Man, who is smugly announcing his return. The text here represents a person, concept, or thing that was thought to be gone, defeated, or irrelevant but has made an unexpected and impactful comeback.

This label is placed on the shocked character, Titan. The text here represents the person, group, or entity that is surprised and often dismayed to see the return of the subject labeled in the bottom panel, having previously written it off.

My-death-was-greatly-exaggerated.image_description: This two-panel meme originates from the animated film *Megamind* (2010). The top panel shows the character Titan looking shocked, with the subtitle "Oh, I... I thought you were dead." The bottom panel features the superhero Metro Man confidently stating, "My death was... greatly exaggerated." This format is used to humorously depict the unexpected return of something (a person, trend, or concept) that was widely believed to be gone, obsolete, or defeated, much to the surprise of others.

Depends-on-the-context.name: Depends-on-the-context

text_options.description: This is the third and final part of the Doctor's explanation. The text here is typically the punchline or the most intense, detailed point of the monologue, corresponding with his emphatic, hands-up gesture.
This is the second part of the Doctor's explanation. The text here continues to build upon the initial statement, adding more complexity or detail to the topic being passionately discussed.
This is the first part of the Doctor's explanation. The text in this box introduces the topic that the character is about to explain in great detail, setting up the long-winded monologue.

This box is placed over Clara Oswald, the listener. The text here represents the simple, often unimpressed or unrelated, response to the Doctor's lengthy explanation, creating the meme's humorous contrast.

Depends-on-the-context.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "The Doctor Explaining," features the Twelfth Doctor from the TV show *Doctor Who* passionately explaining a topic across three panels to his companion, Clara Oswald. The final panel shows Clara's unimpressed or confused reaction. The meme is used to contrast a long, detailed, and often niche explanation with a simple, dismissive, or clueless response from the listener, humorously depicting over-explanation or 'mansplaining'.

fast-and-furious-7-final-scene.name: fast-and-furious-7-final-scene

text_options.description: This text label is placed over Dominic Toretto's car. It represents one of the two entities in the meme that are separating or diverging from each other.
This text label is placed over Brian O'Conner's car as it takes the diverging path. It represents the second entity that is parting ways, visually emphasizing the act of separation.

fast-and-furious-7-final-scene.image_description: This meme originates from the final scene of the movie "Furious 7," showing Dominic Toretto (Vin Diesel) and Brian O'Conner (Paul Walker) driving their separate ways. The scene is a poignant tribute to the late actor Paul Walker, symbolizing a final farewell. The meme is used to represent two people, groups, or concepts that were once aligned but are now parting ways, often with a sense of nostalgia or bittersweet separation.

Goku-Staring.name: Goku-Staring

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It typically reads, "But can he beat Goku tho?" This question serves to humorously dismiss the power of the character described in the top text, reinforcing Goku's iconic status as an unbeatable figure in power-scaling debates.

The top text box is the setup for the joke. It usually describes an incredibly powerful character or entity from another fictional universe, often listing their immense, world-destroying abilities to establish them as a seemingly unbeatable force.

Goku-Staring.image_description: This meme features a shadowed, serious-looking image of Goku in his Super Saiyan form from the anime series Dragon Ball Z. Known as the "Can he beat Goku though?" meme, it is used to humorously and often ironically end debates about the power of any fictional character. The format presents an incredibly powerful character and then juxtaposes their abilities with the simple question of whether they could defeat Goku, who is treated as the ultimate benchmark of strength.

Patrick-Scientist-vs-Nail.name: Patrick-Scientist-vs-Nail

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the image of Patrick with a board nailed to his head. It typically contains a description of a simple, incorrect, or foolish action or concept, which is being contrasted with the more sophisticated idea in the other panel.

This text box corresponds to the image of 'Scientist Patrick.' The text here usually describes a complex, intelligent, or proper way of doing something, serving as the superior half of the comparison.

Patrick-Scientist-vs-Nail.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Patrick Star from SpongeBob SquarePants to create a comparison. On the left, 'Scientist Patrick' is shown in a lab coat looking intently into a microscope, representing a sophisticated, complex, or intelligent approach. On the right, a clueless-looking Patrick is depicted with a board nailed to his head, representing a simplistic, foolish, or incorrect approach. The meme is used to contrast two different methods, ideas, or situations, often to humorously highlight a downgrade or a misunderstanding.

yo-dawg-i-heard-you-like.name: yo-dawg-i-heard-you-like

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which contains the punchline of the meme. It completes the recursive phrase started in the top text, explaining the absurd modification, such as "...so I put a car in your car so you can drive while you drive."

This is the top text area, which sets up the premise of the meme. The text here almost always starts with the phrase "Yo dawg, I herd you like..." followed by a noun or concept that will be the subject of the recursive joke.

yo-dawg-i-heard-you-like.image_description: This image features rapper Xzibit, host of the TV show "Pimp My Ride," in a meme format known as "Yo Dawg" or "Xzibit Heard You Like." The meme parodies the show's premise of adding extravagant customizations to cars by using a recursive phrasal template. It's typically used to describe putting a thing inside the same or a similar thing, often to an absurd degree, following the structure: "Yo dawg, I herd you like X, so I put an X in your Y so you can [verb] while you [verb]."
yo-dawg-i-heard-you-like.display_name: yo dawg i heard you like

Venn-diagram.name: Venn-diagram

text_options.description: Located in the central intersection of the two circles, this text box contains the punchline of the meme—the surprising or humorous trait that both groups share.

Positioned directly below the central text box (0) within the overlapping area, this space is also used for the shared characteristic. It often complements or continues the text from box 0, especially if the shared trait is a longer phrase.
This text box is within the right circle's exclusive area. It describes a characteristic or item that is unique to the group or concept represented by the right circle.
This text box is within the left circle's exclusive area. It describes a characteristic or item that is unique to the group or concept represented by the left circle.
Located in the lower part of the right circle's unique section, this box lists another trait specific to the right-side group, further distinguishing it from the left.
Located in the lower part of the left circle's unique section, this box lists another trait specific to the left-side group, further distinguishing it from the right.

Spanning the top of the diagram, this area is typically used to label the two groups being compared. The text on the left corresponds to the left circle, and the text on the right corresponds to the right circle, setting up the entire comparison.

Venn-diagram.image_description: This is a Venn diagram meme template, featuring two overlapping circles used to compare two different subjects. The non-overlapping sections of the circles are labeled with the unique characteristics of each subject. The central, overlapping section contains the punchline, highlighting a surprising or humorous trait that the two seemingly disparate subjects share.

I-was-there.name: I-was-there

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline or main caption. In its most popular format, this is where the phrase "Alright then, keep your secrets" is placed. The text here capitalizes on Elrond's serious expression to deliver the core joke, often a reaction to the setup in the top text.

The top text, which sets up the scenario or context for the meme. It typically presents a question or a situation where someone is being secretive, prompting the reaction from Elrond in the bottom text.

I-was-there.image_description: This meme features a close-up of the character Elrond from the movie "The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring." Elrond has a stern, knowing, and slightly disapproving expression on his face. This image is famously used for the "Alright then, keep your secrets" meme, which humorously portrays a reaction to someone being evasive or secretive. The format leverages Elrond's serious demeanor to express mild, feigned frustration or to deliver a deadpan, authoritative statement.

Allow-us-to-introduce-ourselves.name: Allow-us-to-introduce-ourselves

text_options.description: This is the fixed caption from the original scene, reading "Allow us to introduce ourselves,". It acts as the punchline, giving a voice to the characters who represent the disruptive element being introduced in response to the text above. This text is almost never altered in the meme format.

This is the setup for the meme, where the user places text describing a situation, statement, or belief. This text creates an expectation that is then immediately subverted or challenged by the characters in the image below. For example, it might state a problem for which there seems to be no solution, or a plan that seems foolproof.

Allow-us-to-introduce-ourselves.image_description: This meme, known as "Allow Us to Introduce Ourselves," features three anthropomorphic vegetable characters from the animated Christian children's show, VeggieTales. With smug and confident expressions, they stare forward as if addressing the viewer. The meme is used to humorously introduce an unexpected, often unwelcome, group or concept that suddenly appears to challenge or disrupt a preceding statement or situation. The top text sets up a scenario, and the image serves as the punchline, representing the unforeseen force.

x-when-x-walks-in.name: x-when-x-walks-in

text_options.description: This bottom text box is placed over Vince McMahon's chest and microphone. It typically contains the final, undesirable, or shocking statement that causes his horrified reaction. This text serves as the punchline of the meme.

The top text box provides the context or setup for the reaction. It usually describes a situation or a question, leading to the shocking answer or outcome presented in the bottom text box, which elicits McMahon's expression.

x-when-x-walks-in.image_description: This meme features a still image of WWE chairman Vince McMahon looking utterly shocked and horrified. It is the final panel of the multi-panel "Vince McMahon Reaction" or "Mr. McMahon Reaction" meme, where he reacts with increasing excitement to a series of items, only to be disgusted by the last one. This single panel is used to express extreme disappointment, shock, or disgust in response to an undesirable statement or outcome.

Angry-Tom-Reading-Book.name: Angry-Tom-Reading-Book

text_options.description: This is the main body of the page where the core text of the meme is placed. This text describes a plan, a statement, or a set of instructions that is the direct cause of Tom's anger in the second panel. It's typically something that is flawed, frustrating, or leads to an unexpectedly terrible outcome.

Located at the top of the page, this area functions as the title or header for the text below. It often reads something like "The Plan" or "The Rules," providing context and setting up the expectation for the infuriating content that follows in box 0.

Angry-Tom-Reading-Book.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Angry Tom Reading a Book" or "Tom's Plan," features Tom the cat from the classic cartoon "Tom and Jerry." The top panel is a close-up of a book, and the bottom panel shows Tom looking absolutely furious—red-faced with smoke coming off his head—after reading it. The meme is used to express intense anger or frustration upon discovering some unwelcome or absurd information, with the text in the book being the direct cause of the outrage.

Would-you-rather.name: Would-you-rather

text_options.description: The text in the red panel on the right represents the second, alternative option. This choice is typically presented as the less desirable, more chaotic, or negative consequence, creating the central conflict or humor of the meme.

The text in the blue panel on the left represents the first option in the dilemma. This choice is often portrayed as the more desirable, logical, or positive of the two, contrasting with the option in the red panel.

Would-you-rather.image_description: This is a "Would You Rather" meme template, which presents a binary choice between two options. The format consists of a blue panel on the left and a red panel on the right, separated by the word "or," under the prompt "Would you rather...". This template is used to pose humorous, difficult, or absurd dilemmas by placing contrasting choices in each panel, forcing the viewer to make a decision.

My-Time-Has-Come.name: My-Time-Has-Come

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, "My time has come," taken directly from the movie scene. It conveys a sense of calm acceptance of fate, which becomes humorous when juxtaposed with the mundane or silly situation described above it.

This top text area is where the user sets up the scenario. It typically describes a relatable, often slightly unfortunate or awkward situation that prompts the dramatic reaction of "My time has come." The humor comes from applying Oogway's profound acceptance of death to an everyday inconvenience.

My-Time-Has-Come.image_description: This meme features Master Oogway, the wise tortoise from the animated film "Kung Fu Panda." The image captures the poignant moment of his peaceful passing, where he says, "My time has come" before dissolving into peach blossoms. Culturally, this meme is used humorously to express a dramatic sense of finality, resignation, or an impending, often trivial, "end" to a situation.

Permission-Bane.name: Permission-Bane

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains Bane's response. It typically features a famous, dramatic, or slightly altered quote from the character, such as 'You merely adopted the dark; I was born in it, molded by it.' The text here is meant to sound profound and intimidating, creating a humorous contrast with the simpler text above.
This top text box represents a question or statement directed at Bane by an unseen person. It's usually a simple or mundane prompt that sets up Bane's overly dramatic reply in the bottom text box.

Permission-Bane.image_description: This meme features the character Bane from the 2012 film 'The Dark Knight Rises,' identifiable by his menacing mask. The image captures a dark, intense close-up of Bane, often used in a two-part dialogue format. This meme format, known as 'Bane's Monologue' or 'You Merely Adopted the Dark,' contrasts a simple question or statement with Bane's overly dramatic and philosophical response, creating a humorous effect through his intimidating persona.

STONKS-without-STONKS.name: STONKS-without-STONKS

text_options.description: This is the primary text location for the meme, placed at the bottom. It typically features a single, intentionally misspelled word that labels the absurd or illogical action being satirized. The classic text is "Stonks" (a misspelling of stocks), but it is often replaced with other misspelled words like "Helth" or "Tek" to fit the context of the joke, serving as the punchline.

This area at the top of the image is part of the background graphic. In the standard format of the "Stonks" meme, this section is intentionally left blank. The visual focus is meant to be on Meme Man and the single-word punchline at the bottom.

STONKS-without-STONKS.image_description: This is the "Stonks" meme, featuring a surreal, poorly-rendered 3D character known as Meme Man. He is depicted in a business suit with arms crossed, standing confidently in front of a rising stock market chart, indicated by a large orange arrow pointing upwards. The meme is used ironically to satirize poor financial decisions, flawed business logic, or any action that is foolishly perceived as a success. The humor derives from the contrast between the confident presentation and the nonsensical situation typically described by the text.

Nobody-is-born-cool.name: Nobody-is-born-cool

text_options.description: This area on the car's sun visor is the customizable punchline of the meme. Users place an image or text here to represent the person, group, or concept they believe is the exception to the rule, i.e., someone or something that was 'born cool.' The reveal in this panel, followed by Hoss's approving look, validates the subject's coolness.

Nobody-is-born-cool.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Nobody Is Born Cool," features the character Hoss Delgado from the animated series "The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy." In the sequence, Hoss makes the general statement that coolness is not an innate quality, but then immediately makes an exception. He pulls down his car's sun visor to reveal a person, object, or concept that he considers to be the sole exception, looking smugly at the viewer. This format is used to praise or show admiration for something the meme creator deems inherently and undeniably cool.

Signature-Look-of-superiority.name: Signature-Look-of-superiority

text_options.description: This area, placed over Count Dooku's torso, contains the punchline of the meme. The text here describes the 'superior' choice, action, or preference that the meme creator smugly endorses, contrasting with the 'inferior' option presented above.

This top panel is the setup for the meme. The text placed here describes a common, mainstream, or what the creator considers an 'inferior' choice or opinion, which will then be looked down upon by the 'superior' choice in the panel below.

Signature-Look-of-superiority.image_description: This meme, known as "Signature Look of Superiority" or "Count Dooku Looking Superior," features a picture of the Star Wars character Count Dooku from a visual dictionary. An arrow points to his smug, condescending expression with the caption "Signature look of superiority." The meme is typically used in a two-panel format to compare two things, with the user expressing a smug preference for the second, supposedly superior option, aligning themselves with Dooku's expression.

VAR-Video-Assistant-Referee.name: VAR-Video-Assistant-Referee

text_options.description: This text box covers the crowd of spectators. In the meme, this group is labeled to represent the people anxiously awaiting or reacting to the 'official' decision shown on the screen, such as 'My family watching me decide what to eat'.

This large blank area on the screen is the core of the meme. Text placed here represents the controversial topic or question being 'officially' judged, which serves as the punchline. For example, 'Is a hotdog a sandwich?'

VAR-Video-Assistant-Referee.image_description: This meme shows a large screen in a football (soccer) stadium displaying the text 'DECISION' and the 'VAR' (Video Assistant Referee) logo to a crowd of spectators. The format is used to humorously frame a subjective opinion, a personal choice, or a trivial matter as a high-stakes, official ruling being reviewed. The humor comes from applying the intense scrutiny of a sports replay to everyday situations.

Business-Cat.name: Business-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, labeled with index 0, delivers the punchline of the meme. It contrasts the professional setup from the top text by revealing a purely feline instinct or behavior, creating the humor through the unexpected juxtaposition.

The top text, labeled with index 1, sets up a professional or office-related scenario. This line typically uses corporate jargon or describes a task given by a boss, establishing the 'business' part of the 'Business Cat' persona.

Business-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as 'Business Cat,' features a black cat wearing a shirt collar and tie against a colorful pinwheel background. It's a classic 'Advice Animal' image macro that humorously blends corporate workplace scenarios with feline instincts and behaviors. The format typically uses a setup line at the top and a cat-related punchline at the bottom, creating a funny juxtaposition between professional life and animal nature.

What-are-you-in-for.name: What-are-you-in-for

text_options.description: This speech bubble contains the punchline, spoken by the smaller, unassuming inmate. The text here is an unexpectedly intimidating, clever, or horrifying response that frightens the larger inmate away, subverting the audience's expectations.

This speech bubble contains the setup for the joke, spoken by the large, tough-looking inmate. The text is typically a boast, a question establishing dominance, or an inquiry like "What are you in for?", which sets the stage for the smaller inmate's surprising reply.

What-are-you-in-for.image_description: This three-panel comic meme, often called "What are you in for?", depicts a large, intimidating prisoner speaking to a smaller, nerdy-looking one. After the smaller inmate replies, the final panel shows him sitting alone, implying his response was so shocking or terrifying that the larger inmate fled. The meme is used to subvert expectations, where a seemingly harmless entity reveals itself to be far more dangerous or powerful than a visibly threatening one.

Woman-yelling-at-cat.name: Woman-yelling-at-cat

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the confused cat, Smudge. The text here represents the calm, often witty or literal, response to the accusation from the yelling woman. It serves as the punchline, with the cat's bewildered expression perfectly complementing a retort that highlights the absurdity of the situation.

This text box is positioned over the yelling woman, Taylor Armstrong. The text here typically represents an angry, emotional, or irrational accusation or complaint. This sets up the conflict of the meme, establishing the emotional outburst that the cat will react to.

Woman-yelling-at-cat.image_description: This is the "Woman Yelling at a Cat" meme, a two-panel image that juxtaposes two unrelated pictures to create a humorous scenario. The left panel features a distraught Taylor Armstrong from "The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills" crying and pointing, while the right panel shows a confused-looking white cat named Smudge sitting at a dinner table. The meme is used to represent a confrontation where one person makes an emotional or irrational accusation (the woman), and the other person responds with a calm, confused, or witty retort (the cat).

1990s-First-World-Problems.name: 1990s-First-World-Problems

text_options.description: The bottom text, which is optional but often used. It typically delivers the punchline or specifies the trivial problem causing the dramatic sadness, completing the setup from the top text.
The top text, which sets up the context or describes a situation. This text establishes the scenario that leads to the exaggerated emotional breakdown depicted in the image.

1990s-First-World-Problems.image_description: This meme, known as "Crying Dawson" or "Dawson's Crying Face," features actor James Van Der Beek as the character Dawson Leery from the 90s TV show Dawson's Creek. The image captures an intensely emotional, crying expression that has been repurposed to humorously represent an over-the-top, melodramatic reaction to a minor inconvenience or a "first world problem." Its cultural use lies in exaggerating sadness for comedic effect, making light of trivial disappointments.

Donal-Trump-Birthday.name: Donal-Trump-Birthday

text_options.description: This bottom section serves as the setup for the meme. It typically introduces a general concept, a group of people, or a statement that will be commented on or exemplified by the text above.

Located at the top where Trump is pointing, this section contains the punchline. The text here presents a specific, often superior or more extreme, example related to the setup in the bottom text, completing the joke.

Donal-Trump-Birthday.image_description: This meme features former U.S. President Donald Trump pointing upwards with a confident expression. It's a two-part format where the bottom text introduces a topic or a group, and the top text, where Trump is pointing, presents a superior, funnier, or more specific example of that topic. The meme is versatile and used for humorous comparisons, social commentary, and political satire.

Ill-Have-You-Know-Spongebob.name: Ill-Have-You-Know-Spongebob

text_options.description: This area, placed over SpongeBob's body, contains the specific, often humorous or overly detailed, answer or example. Its placement on the character associates the text with his smug, 'I know the perfect example for this' expression.

The top panel of the meme, located above SpongeBob's head where he is pointing. This text box establishes the premise, posing a general question, statement, or broad category that the bottom text will provide a specific example for.

Ill-Have-You-Know-Spongebob.image_description: This meme, known as "SpongeBob Pointing Up," features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series of the same name. He has a smug, knowing expression while pointing his index finger upwards, as if presenting a key piece of information. The format is typically used as a two-panel meme where the top text presents a general category or question, and the bottom text, superimposed over SpongeBob, provides a very specific, often comically niche or relatable, example.

michael-jackson-eating-popcorn.name: michael-jackson-eating-popcorn

text_options.description: The text in this bottom region typically identifies the person or group who is passively and entertainingly observing the situation. This is the 'spectator' of the drama.
The text at the top of the image describes the dramatic event, argument, or chaotic situation that is being watched. It sets the context for the 'show' that the person below is enjoying.

michael-jackson-eating-popcorn.image_description: This meme features a still image of pop icon Michael Jackson from his 1982 music video "Thriller," showing him eating popcorn in a movie theater with an amused and engrossed expression. It is widely used as a reaction image to represent someone eagerly watching drama, arguments, or chaos unfold, particularly in online discussions. The act of eating popcorn symbolizes the enjoyment of being a spectator to an entertaining conflict from a safe distance.

Freezing-cold.name: Freezing-cold

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over Jack's frozen body, typically identifies the person or group experiencing the long wait or cold. This caption serves as the punchline, directly relating the user's relatable experience to the extreme situation shown in the image.
The top text of the image macro sets up the scenario. It describes the situation or action that is causing the long, 'freezing' wait, providing the context for the punchline below.

Freezing-cold.image_description: This meme features a still image of the character Jack Torrance, played by Jack Nicholson, frozen to death in the snow from the final scene of the 1980 horror film 'The Shining'. The image is widely used to humorously exaggerate feelings of being extremely cold, waiting for a very long time, or being ignored (e.g., 'left on read'). The frozen, lifeless expression of the character is key to the meme's comedic effect in mundane situations.

Its-Finally-Over.name: Its-Finally-Over

text_options.description: The bottom text contains the punchline, almost always a variation of the quote 'It's over. It's done.' This text represents the speaker's (Frodo's) exhausted but relieved declaration that a difficult task is finally complete.

The top text sets up the context for the relief. It typically describes a challenging or lengthy situation that has just ended, such as finishing a difficult project, a long work week, or a stressful exam.

Its-Finally-Over.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Frodo Baggins from 'The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King,' looking exhausted and battered inside Mount Doom. The scene captures the moment after the One Ring has been destroyed, with Frodo's face conveying immense relief and weariness. This format is used to express profound relief and finality after completing a long, arduous, or stressful task, often with the punchline 'It's over. It's done.'

CNN-Wolf-of-Fake-News-Fanfiction.name: CNN-Wolf-of-Fake-News-Fanfiction

text_options.description: This is the main text area, located in the lower-third news banner. Users insert their own custom "breaking news" headline here, which serves as the punchline of the meme. The text is typically something mundane, personal, or funny, contrasting sharply with the serious news format.

This label is placed over Wolf Blitzer's chest. It is typically used to identify the person or entity making the announcement in the news banner. Often, this is labeled "Me" to signify that the user is the one delivering their own personal "breaking news."

CNN-Wolf-of-Fake-News-Fanfiction.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of CNN news anchor Wolf Blitzer in the "Situation Room" during a "BREAKING NEWS" segment. The format is used to humorously announce trivial, personal, or absurd information as if it were major news. The contrast between the serious news presentation and the often mundane or silly user-provided text creates the comedic effect. This template allows users to frame their personal updates or jokes with an air of unearned importance.
CNN-Wolf-of-Fake-News-Fanfiction.display_name: CNN Wolf of Fake News Fanfiction

Finally-A-worthy-opponent.name: Finally-A-worthy-opponent

text_options.description: This label identifies the 'opponent' that Tai Lung is addressing in the second panel. The text here represents the person, object, or concept that is considered a worthy match for the subject in the first panel, completing the setup for their 'legendary battle'.
This label is placed over Tai Lung's chest and identifies the first subject or the 'challenger'. The text here represents the entity that has finally found its equal or a formidable challenge.

This top caption area provides the overarching context or setup for the entire meme. The text here establishes the scenario that leads to the two subjects being pitted against each other as worthy opponents.

Finally-A-worthy-opponent.image_description: This two-panel meme features Tai Lung, the snow leopard antagonist from the animated film *Kung Fu Panda*. In the top panel, he looks intensely at an unseen foe, with the caption "Finally! A worthy opponent!" and in the bottom panel, he bows respectfully, saying, "Our battle will be legendary!". The meme is used to express excitement, often ironically, about finding a suitable rival or an equal match, especially in mundane, absurd, or niche contexts.

Arrested-Development-how-much-would-a-ba.name: Arrested-Development-how-much-would-a-banana-cost

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is the absurdly high price estimate. In the original quote, this is "ten dollars?" This text completes the setup from the top box, delivering the humorous and out-of-touch part of the statement.

The top text box contains the setup for the joke, typically a question or statement that shows a person's ignorance about the price of a common item. This text is placed over Lucille's face to attribute the out-of-touch sentiment to her character.

Arrested-Development-how-much-would-a-ba.image_description: This meme features Lucille Bluth from the TV show "Arrested Development" speaking condescendingly to her son Michael. The scene is famous for her line, "I mean, it's one banana, Michael. What could it cost, ten dollars?", which reveals her complete detachment from the financial reality of ordinary people. The format is used to mock statements that are wildly out of touch with the actual cost of goods or services, highlighting a person's cluelessness and privilege.
Arrested-Development-how-much-would-a-ba.display_name: Arrested Development how much would a banana cost

Praise-Squirrel.name: Praise-Squirrel

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image, near the squirrel's feet, typically describes the initial situation, a problem, or an action taken. This sets up the context for the celebration depicted by the squirrel.

The text at the top, where the squirrel is looking and reaching, serves as the punchline. It describes the positive, often surprisingly good, outcome or result of the situation mentioned at the bottom, which is the cause of the squirrel's exultation.

Praise-Squirrel.image_description: This meme, often called "Happy Squirrel" or "Dramatic Squirrel," features a squirrel standing on its hind legs with its arms raised towards the sky in a triumphant or worshipful pose. The image is used to express overwhelming joy, relief, or celebration in response to a positive event or outcome. The format typically presents a situation or action at the bottom and the glorious result at the top, with the squirrel acting as the celebratory link between the two.

I-find-your-lack-of-faith-disturbing.name: I-find-your-lack-of-faith-disturbing

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Admiral Motti, the character being choked. The text here represents an opinion, statement, or belief that the meme creator finds foolish, naive, or disagreeable. It serves as the setup, presenting the 'lack of faith' that will be criticized by the text above.

This text box is placed over Darth Vader, the figure of authority and power. The text here delivers the punchline, which is typically a variation of the quote "I find your lack of [X] disturbing." The variable [X] is replaced with a word relevant to the setup in box 0, expressing strong disapproval in an intimidating yet comical manner.
