I-find-your-lack-of-faith-disturbing.image_description: This meme, known as "Darth Vader Choke" or "I Find Your Lack of Faith Disturbing," originates from the film "Star Wars: A New Hope." It depicts the iconic villain Darth Vader using the Force to choke Admiral Motti for questioning his power. The format is used to humorously express strong disagreement or disappointment, with Vader representing the user's opinion and the choked officer representing a contrary or foolish statement.
I-find-your-lack-of-faith-disturbing.display_name: I find your lack of faith disturbing

nooo-haha-go-brrr.name: nooo-haha-go-brrr

text_options.description: This text box is under the calm "30-Year-Old Boomer" Wojak. It typically contains a very short, simple, and often traditional or common-sense response. This text serves as the punchline, humorously undermining the complex or emotional statement made by the character on the left.

This text box is positioned under the crying Wojak. The text here usually represents a long-winded, emotional, or overly intellectual argument that is being mocked. It sets up the joke by presenting the viewpoint that will be contrasted and dismissed by the character on the right.

nooo-haha-go-brrr.image_description: This meme, known as "Crying Wojak vs. 30-Year-Old Boomer," juxtaposes two Wojak characters to contrast different perspectives. On the left, a crying and angry Wojak (often called a Soyjak), wearing a yellow and black bowtie, represents a modern, often complex or emotionally charged viewpoint. On the right, a calm, weathered Wojak known as the "30-Year-Old Boomer" represents a simpler, more traditional, or experienced perspective. The meme is used to mock the first viewpoint as overly complicated or foolish by contrasting it with the simple, direct logic of the second.

Yuu-buys-a-cookie.name: Yuu-buys-a-cookie

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the final panel, this area often contains a caption or subtitle that delivers the punchline, summarizing the disappointing outcome or the context of the empty promise.
This label is placed on Hoshino Hana, who represents the person, group, or audience that is expecting something and is met with disappointment. She is the recipient of the empty offer.

This label identifies Matsumoto Kōko, the character who confidently presents the empty tray. She represents the person, organization, or entity that fails to deliver on a promise or presents something that doesn't exist.
Text placed over the empty tray explicitly names the thing that is missing or was promised but not delivered. This is the core subject of the meme's joke.

Yuu-buys-a-cookie.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Koko's Empty Tray," originates from the anime series "Wataten!: An Angel Flew Down to Me." It features the character Matsumoto Kōko presenting a wooden tray, first with a closed fist, then with an open hand revealing it's empty, and finally showing it to another character, Hoshino Hana. The format is used to humorously depict a situation where something is promised or expected but is ultimately nonexistent or undelivered, with Kōko as the provider and Hana as the disappointed recipient.

may-i-please-get-a-crumb.name: may-i-please-get-a-crumb

text_options.description: This bottom text area represents the small, disappointing, or insignificant reward, outcome, or recognition received. It's the punchline that contrasts with the effort described in the top text, aligning with the beggar character who is receiving something.

The top text area describes the person, group, or entity that is giving a lot, making a huge effort, or is generally powerful and wealthy. This text sets up the expectation of a significant exchange or outcome.

may-i-please-get-a-crumb.image_description: This meme features a still of Robin Hood from the 1973 Disney animated film, disguised as a blind, poor fox. He wears a tattered cloak, a hat, and dark sunglasses while holding out a cup, looking dejected. The meme is used to humorously depict a situation where a significant effort or contribution results in a very small or disappointing reward, highlighting a feeling of being underappreciated or receiving a pittance.
may-i-please-get-a-crumb.display_name: may i please get a crumb

no-i-dont-think-i-will.name: no-i-dont-think-i-will

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the original subtitle from the movie: "No... No I don't think I will." It serves as the fixed response to the user-provided text in the top panel, signifying a firm refusal.

This top section is where the user adds a prompt, suggestion, or command. This text sets up the context for Captain America's refusal, creating the joke by contrasting the expectation with his unwillingness to comply.

no-i-dont-think-i-will.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of an elderly Steve Rogers, also known as Captain America, from the film 'Avengers: Endgame'. With a calm and slightly weary expression, he delivers the line, "No... No I don't think I will." The meme is used as a reaction image to express a polite but firm refusal to do something that is suggested, expected, or demanded, often in a humorous or defiant context.
no-i-dont-think-i-will.display_name: no i dont think i will

Lois-Griffin-Family-Guy.name: Lois-Griffin-Family-Guy

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to Lois in the bottom panel where the crowd is cheering enthusiastically. It contains the punchline of the meme: a simplistic, controversial, or populist statement that unexpectedly wins over the audience, contrasting sharply with the first statement.

This text box is positioned next to Lois in the top panel where the audience appears bored and unresponsive. This area is used for the setup of the meme, typically containing a well-reasoned, complex, or unpopular opinion that fails to impress the crowd.

Lois-Griffin-Family-Guy.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Lois Griffin's Speech," originates from the animated show Family Guy. It features the character Lois Griffin at a podium, first speaking to a bored, silent audience, and then, in the second set of panels, to a wildly cheering and applauding crowd. The meme is used to contrast a reasonable, nuanced, or unpopular statement that gets no reaction with a simplistic, controversial, or populist statement that elicits widespread approval, often satirizing mob mentality or public opinion.

Rich-men-laughing.name: Rich-men-laughing

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline of the joke. It's typically a cynical, out-of-touch, or absurd statement, often starting with 'And then I said...', which is presented as the reason for the politicians' laughter. This text delivers the core satirical message of the meme.

The top text sets up the joke or scenario. It usually describes a situation or a question posed by a less powerful group (e.g., students, employees, the general public) to the figures of authority depicted in the image. This text provides the context that makes the punchline at the bottom impactful.

Rich-men-laughing.image_description: This meme, often called 'And Then I Said' or 'Laughing Politicians,' features a photograph of several men in suits, including former U.S. Presidents Ronald Reagan and George H.W. Bush, sharing a boisterous laugh. The format typically involves a setup line at the top, followed by a punchline at the bottom. The punchline is a statement that makes their laughter appear cynical, arrogant, or dismissive of a particular group or issue, creating a satirical commentary on politics, corporate culture, or societal problems.

Persian-Cat-Room-Guardian-Single.name: Persian-Cat-Room-Guardian-Single

text_options.description: This bottom area is less frequently used for text. When it is, it might label the creature or provide a secondary punchline, but often this space is left blank as the humor is carried by the top text and the image itself.

The text in this top region sets up the entire premise of the meme. It typically describes a strange, confusing, or absurd situation that prompts the creature's bewildered reaction. The user places a statement here that they find baffling or questionable.

Persian-Cat-Room-Guardian-Single.image_description: This meme features a 'Persian Cat Room Guardian,' a white, fluffy, taxidermy-like doll with a cat-like face, blue eyes, and human-like hands. The creature sits on a box with a confused or questioning expression, gesturing outwards as if asking "what is this?". This image is widely used as a reaction meme to express profound confusion, bewilderment, or disgust in response to a strange or unexpected situation.

Story-Time-Jesus.name: Story-Time-Jesus

text_options.description: This label is placed over the crowd of listeners at the bottom. It identifies the specific person, group, or entity that humorously misinterprets or takes Jesus's general statement personally, forming the punchline of the meme.
This text box is positioned above Jesus and contains the general, often philosophical or metaphorical, statement he is making to the crowd. This statement serves as the setup for the joke.

Story-Time-Jesus.image_description: This meme features a religious painting of Jesus Christ speaking to a crowd of followers. The format, often called "And I took that personally," juxtaposes a general statement made by Jesus with a specific person or group in the crowd who misinterprets it literally or applies it to themselves in a humorous way. The humor arises from the contrast between the broad, often profound, teaching and the specific, mundane, or absurd reaction of an individual listener.

Winter-is-coming.name: Winter-is-coming

text_options.description: The bottom text area, which contains the punchline of the meme. The text here almost always begins with the phrase 'One does not simply...' followed by a restatement of the action from the top line, humorously emphasizing its difficulty or complexity.
The top text area, which serves as the setup for the meme. The text here typically describes a goal or action that someone might naively assume is easy to accomplish.

Winter-is-coming.image_description: This meme features the character Ned Stark, played by Sean Bean, from the HBO series 'Game of Thrones'. Known as the 'One Does Not Simply' or 'Brace Yourselves' meme, it is used to express that a task is much more difficult or complex than it appears. The format consists of a two-part caption, where the top line presents a seemingly simple goal and the bottom line refutes its simplicity with the iconic catchphrase.

Interrupting-bird.name: Interrupting-bird

text_options.description: This box highlights the small bird's face in the final panel. This panel contains no text and serves as the punchline, conveying the silent frustration and annoyance of being interrupted and ignored.

This large speech bubble belongs to the interrupting crow. The text placed here is typically a loud, simplistic, or aggressive opinion that completely overshadows what the small bird was trying to say.
This box highlights the small bird in the second panel, who is in the middle of making its point. It represents the person with a nuanced take before they are interrupted.
This is the speech bubble for the small bird in the second panel. The text here continues the nuanced or thoughtful statement that was started in the first panel, just before the interruption occurs.
This is the speech bubble for the small bird in the first panel. The text here introduces a nuanced or thoughtful idea, setting up the joke where it will be completely ignored and shouted down.

Interrupting-bird.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, known as "Annoyed Bird" or "Crow and Bird," features a small bird attempting to make a point, only to be loudly interrupted by a large, obnoxious crow. The final panel shows the small bird's silent, annoyed expression. The meme is used to represent situations where a nuanced or thoughtful opinion is drowned out by a loud, simplistic, or aggressive counterpoint.

Stewie-Wheres-My-Money.name: Stewie-Wheres-My-Money

text_options.description: This text label, placed at the bottom over Brian and the lower part of Stewie, identifies the person, group, or entity being aggressively confronted or from whom something is owed.

The top text label represents the aggressive demand or the person making the demand. It's often phrased as a question demanding something that is overdue or owed, reflecting Stewie's role as the aggressor in the scene.

Stewie-Wheres-My-Money.image_description: This meme features Stewie Griffin, a baby, violently confronting Brian, the family dog, from the animated show "Family Guy". Stewie looks angry and is pulling Brian's ear, who appears beaten and distressed. The meme, often captioned with a variation of "Where's my money?", is used to humorously depict a situation where someone is aggressively and desperately demanding something they are owed from another person or entity.

no-russian.name: no-russian

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the screen, where the original subtitle 'Makarov: Remember - no Russian' is located, is used for the meme's punchline. The text here is typically an absurd or specific instruction that the group must follow, setting the premise for their 'mission'. It's the core of the joke, replacing the grim original line with something humorous or relatable.

The top section of the image is often used to add a title or context that describes the group or the situation they are entering. This text works with the punchline in box 0 to create the full joke. For example, it might say 'Me and the boys on our way to...' to set up the scenario.

no-russian.image_description: This meme originates from the controversial 'No Russian' mission in the video game Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2. It depicts the antagonist, Vladimir Makarov, and his team in an elevator just before committing a terrorist attack at an airport. The format is used to represent a group preparing for a coordinated, often absurd or controversial, action, with the dialogue being the key punchline. The tense atmosphere and serious expressions of the characters create a humorous contrast with the often trivial tasks described in the meme text.

blue-background.name: blue-background

text_options.description: The bottom panel of the meme. This area contains the punchline, the answer to the question posed above, or the contrasting element in a comparison, often with a humorous or ironic twist.
The top panel of the meme. This area is used for the setup, presenting a question, statement, or the first part of a comparison.

blue-background.image_description: This meme template features the iconic textured blue background from the game show 'Jeopardy!'. It is a simple two-panel format used for comparisons or to present a setup and a punchline. The top panel typically introduces a situation or statement, while the bottom panel delivers a humorous or ironic response, often framed as a definitive 'answer' in the style of the game show.

Sigma-Male.name: Sigma-Male

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the "Chad" statement. It represents GigaChad's assertive action or belief, which is framed as the superior or correct viewpoint in the context of the meme.

The top text box typically provides the setup or context for the meme. It often contains a question, a scenario, or a prompt that the bottom text responds to, such as the classic "Why yes, I [do something], how could you tell?" format.

Sigma-Male.image_description: This meme features the character known as "GigaChad," a black-and-white photograph of an extremely muscular and chiseled man. GigaChad represents an idealized, hyper-masculine archetype, embodying confidence and superiority. The meme is typically used to express a strong, often contrarian or assertive opinion, presenting it as the correct or most based take on a subject.

Im-doing-my-part.name: Im-doing-my-part

text_options.description: This text box contains the punchline of the meme, "I'm doing my part!". It is the original subtitle from the movie scene and is almost always kept intact. It represents the enthusiastic but often trivial contribution being made by the person or group identified in the top text.

This text box at the top of the image is used to describe a large-scale problem, a collective effort, or a situation requiring significant action. The text placed here sets up the context, making the minor contribution mentioned in the punchline appear comically insufficient or misguided.

Im-doing-my-part.image_description: This meme originates from a satirical propaganda scene in the 1997 film Starship Troopers, where a soldier enthusiastically declares, "I'm doing my part!". The image is used to sarcastically portray someone making a minimal, often insignificant or performative, contribution to a large-scale problem or collective effort. The character's earnest expression contrasts humorously with the triviality of the action being described by the meme's author.

Blankie-the-Shocked-Dog.name: Blankie-the-Shocked-Dog

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which serves as the punchline. It reveals the actual, often shocking or inappropriate, thing that was said or done, which starkly contrasts with the initial misunderstanding described in the top text. This revelation is the cause of the dog's horrified expression, completing the joke about the awkward moment of realization.

This is the top text, which sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes what the subject (represented by the dog) initially thought they heard or understood in a conversation. This text is usually an innocent or mundane interpretation of a phrase.

Blankie-the-Shocked-Dog.image_description: This meme, often called "Misunderstanding Dog" or "Awkward Moment Dog," features a close-up photo of a boxer dog with a shocked and wide-eyed expression. The dog's face conveys a sudden, horrifying realization. This image is typically used in a two-part caption format to illustrate a social situation where someone mishears something, leading to an awkward or embarrassing moment once they realize the truth.

Squid-Game-Two-Buttons.name: Squid-Game-Two-Buttons

text_options.description: This label identifies the person or entity facing the difficult choice shown in the top panel. It's typically labeled with 'Me' or a specific group to represent who is struggling with the decision.

This text box is placed over the red button with an 'X', symbolizing one of the two choices. This option is often the more tempting, easier, or immediately gratifying one, but ultimately the 'wrong' or less responsible path.

This text box is placed over the green button with an 'O', representing the second choice in the dilemma. This option is typically the more responsible, difficult, or correct path that requires discipline or sacrifice.

Squid-Game-Two-Buttons.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the Netflix series 'Squid Game', featuring the character Oh Il-nam (Player 001). The top panel shows a hand hovering between a red 'X' button and a green 'O' button, representing a difficult choice or dilemma. The bottom panel shows Oh Il-nam looking sad and conflicted, personifying the individual burdened by the decision. This meme is used to express the struggle of choosing between two conflicting options, often one being desirable but irresponsible and the other being responsible but undesirable.

Kevin-James.name: Kevin-James

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image typically describes the action or situation that the subject has just caused or participated in. This is the setup or the "cause" that leads to the sheepish reaction depicted by Kevin James's expression.

The text at the top of the image usually describes the person's reaction or current state after performing the action mentioned at the bottom. It often starts with a phrase like "Me after..." and frames the entire scenario from the perspective of the person feeling sheepish or smug, representing the "effect."

Kevin-James.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor Kevin James, likely from the sitcom "The King of Queens," shrugging with his hands in his pockets and a mischievous, sheepish smirk. The image, often called the "Kevin James Smirking" meme, went viral as a reaction image to represent a feeling of awkwardness, mild guilt, or cheeky confidence after doing something questionable. It's typically used in a two-panel format where the text describes a relatable, often humorous, scenario leading to this specific expression.

pie-chart-yes-but-in-yellow.name: pie-chart-yes-but-in-yellow

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image is often used for a caption or title that sets up the context for the pie chart. The text here typically poses a question or states a scenario that the chart humorously answers, establishing the premise for the joke.

This box at the top of the image serves as the title or main question that the pie chart is supposed to be visualizing. The text placed here provides the context for the chart's absurd data, framing the joke for the viewer.

pie-chart-yes-but-in-yellow.image_description: This meme features a pie chart with two categories: a large blue section labeled "yes" and a smaller yellow section labeled "yes but in yellow." The humor lies in the redundant and nonsensical data representation, where both options signify agreement, with the only difference being a superficial quality. It's used to satirize situations where distinctions are meaningless or to show overwhelming consensus on a topic in a funny, absurd way.
pie-chart-yes-but-in-yellow.display_name: pie chart yes but in yellow

really-fat-guy-on-computer.name: really-fat-guy-on-computer

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline of the meme. It often provides context that attributes the top text to the man in the image, for example, by saying '...he typed' or describing the situation, which creates the humorous contrast.

The top text box is used to set up the joke, usually with a quote that is overly aggressive, pedantic, or self-important, typical of online arguments. This text represents the comment being made by the stereotypical internet user depicted.

really-fat-guy-on-computer.image_description: This meme, often called 'Internet Husband' or 'Butthurt Dweller,' features a large, shirtless man smiling while typing at an old computer. The image is used to stereotype an overly-invested, argumentative, or self-important internet user, often found in forums or comment sections. The humor comes from juxtaposing a serious or aggressive online comment with the visual of the person supposedly writing it, implying they are a 'nerd' or 'no-life' individual.

Megamind-Peeking.name: Megamind-Peeking

text_options.description: This is the location for the punchline, typically a question formatted as "No [plural noun]?". The most famous example is "No bitches?", but it can be adapted to any subject to mock the viewer for not having something. Its placement at the bottom allows the viewer to first process Megamind's expression before reading the comedic insult.

This area covers Megamind's famously large forehead. In this meme format, this space is almost always left blank. The vast, empty forehead emphasizes the character's exaggerated features and focuses all the attention on his eyes and the punchline below.

Megamind-Peeking.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Megamind, the titular character from the 2010 animated film, peering down with a sad and judgmental expression. Known as the "No Bitches?" or "Megamind Peeking" meme, it is used to humorously question or mock the viewer for lacking something desirable, such as romantic partners, skills, or possessions. The humor stems from the condescending yet pitiful look on Megamind's face, making the viewer feel playfully called out.

Picard-Four-Lights.name: Picard-Four-Lights

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over Picard's shouting mouth, serves as the punchline. It contains the core of the frustrated exclamation, directly answering or reacting to the setup in the top text. This text embodies the raw anger and exasperation conveyed by Picard's expression.

The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically poses a question or describes a situation that is illogical, annoying, or infuriating, prompting Picard's angry reaction. This text establishes the context for the frustration.

Picard-Four-Lights.image_description: This meme features Captain Jean-Luc Picard from Star Trek: The Next Generation shouting with an expression of intense frustration and anger. The image is a reaction macro used to express extreme exasperation or disbelief in response to a frustrating situation or statement. It's often formatted as a rhetorical question starting with "Why the f***..." or a similar setup, with Picard's shout representing the peak of annoyance.

same-spider-man-7.name: same-spider-man-7

text_options.description: Text placed here labels one of the many individuals, groups, or concepts involved in the mutual accusation or ironic comparison. It represents one of the parties in the standoff.
This text box identifies another party in the conflict. Its placement contributes to the visual representation of a circular argument or widespread blame.
Text in this central foreground position labels a key participant in the multi-faceted conflict. This character is both pointing and being pointed at, central to the confusion.
This label identifies another participant in the blame game. Its position in the middle of the group reinforces the idea that everyone is equally involved or at fault.
This text box labels another entity, adding to the overall scene of chaos and finger-pointing. It helps represent a situation with many similar or culpable parties.
Text here identifies yet another party in the standoff. Like the others, it represents a person or idea that is identical to, or in conflict with, the rest.
This label is placed on another Spider-Man to represent an additional group or person in the circular argument, adding to the complexity and humor of the situation.

same-spider-man-7.image_description: This meme, known as "Spider-Man Pointing at Spider-Man," originates from a 1967 animated series and depicts multiple Spider-Men pointing at one another. It's used to humorously illustrate situations where multiple parties are blaming each other, being hypocritical, or are unexpectedly identical. The format highlights the irony and absurdity of a standoff where everyone is equally at fault or the same. This expanded version with numerous Spider-Men allows for more complex scenarios of widespread, mutual accusation.

Walking-Dead-Zombie.name: Walking-Dead-Zombie

text_options.description: The text at index 0, located at the bottom of the image over the zombie's body, represents the negative, disappointing, or 'after' state in the comparison. This is the punchline of the meme, contrasting with the more positive setup in the top panel. Its placement on the grotesque zombie reinforces the undesirable nature of the outcome.

The text at index 1, placed at the top of the image, describes the positive expectation, the 'before' state, or the setup for the comparison. This text establishes the initial, often desirable, scenario that will be contrasted with the grim reality represented by the zombie and the text at the bottom.

Walking-Dead-Zombie.image_description: This meme features the 'Bicycle Girl' walker from the TV show *The Walking Dead*, a decaying zombie crawling on the grass. The image is used as a two-panel comparison format. Typically, the top part represents a positive or expected situation, while the bottom part, featuring the zombie, represents a negative, disappointing, or grim reality, creating a humorous or relatable contrast.

Reverse-kalm-panik.name: Reverse-kalm-panik

text_options.description: This text box, opposite the final 'Kalm' image, describes the resolution or a new piece of information that alleviates the panic from the previous panel. It provides the final twist that makes the situation okay again, bringing the narrative to a humorous and satisfying close.

This text box, next to the 'Panik' image, introduces a sudden problem or a stressful realization that disrupts the initial calm. This is the core of the conflict in the meme's narrative, creating a moment of high tension and anxiety.

This text box, located at the top next to the first 'Kalm' image, sets up the initial scenario. It describes a seemingly positive or normal situation, establishing a baseline of peace and security before the conflict is introduced.

Reverse-kalm-panik.image_description: This is the "Kalm, Panik, Kalm" meme, which features the surreal character Meme Man in a three-panel format. The meme illustrates a sequence of reactions to a situation: first, a sense of calm, followed by a sudden moment of panic, and finally a return to calm upon a new realization. It's a popular format for telling short, relatable stories about anxiety and relief, with the humor stemming from the abrupt emotional shifts and the intentionally misspelled words.

Impractical-Jokers.name: Impractical-Jokers

text_options.description: This text box is the punchline of the meme. It describes the unexpected, embarrassing, or hilarious consequence of the action or statement introduced in the top panel, explaining why the characters are laughing uncontrollably.

This text box contains the setup for the joke. It typically describes a plan, a statement, or a situation that seems neutral or straightforward on its own, setting the stage for the chaotic outcome shown below.

Impractical-Jokers.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the American hidden camera reality show "Impractical Jokers." The top panel shows three of the show's stars (from left to right: Brian "Q" Quinn, Sal Vulcano, and Joe Gatto) standing calmly. The bottom panel depicts Sal and Joe collapsing in uncontrollable laughter. The meme is used to contrast a setup or statement in the top panel with an absurd or hilarious outcome in the bottom panel, with the laughter representing an extreme reaction to the situation.

Ceiling-Cat.name: Ceiling-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text box, often used for the punchline in classic meme formats. In the Ceiling Cat meme, this area typically contains a judgmental or observational comment from the cat's perspective, often written in 'lolspeak' (e.g., 'I see what u did thar').

The top text box, which usually provides context or a setup line. For the Ceiling Cat meme, this text often introduces the subject of the cat's observation or a general statement about its omnipresence, such as 'Ceiling Cat is watching you.'

Ceiling-Cat.image_description: The "Ceiling Cat" meme features a ginger cat peering down through a hole in a ceiling. Originating from the early days of internet memes, Ceiling Cat is portrayed as an all-seeing, god-like figure, often used to humorously imply surveillance or judgment. This iconic image is a cornerstone of LOLcat culture and is typically captioned with text mimicking the cat's perspective.

Boy-holding-his-breath.name: Boy-holding-his-breath

text_options.description: This area, covering the straining man's body, is used to label the person or group that is struggling to hold something back. It identifies the protagonist of the scenario who is under immense pressure.

Located on the whiteboard in the background, this space is used to describe the powerful urge, thought, or action that the person labeled in box 0 is desperately trying to suppress. It represents the source of the internal conflict causing the strain.

Boy-holding-his-breath.image_description: This meme, known as 'Veins Guy' or 'Trying to Hold a Fart,' shows a male student in a classroom straining intensely, with veins bulging on his forehead and neck. The image humorously depicts a moment of extreme internal struggle and the immense effort to suppress an overwhelming urge, thought, or comment. It's widely used to represent situations where someone is trying desperately to maintain composure under pressure.

Itd-Be-A-Lot-Cooler-If-You-Did.name: Itd-Be-A-Lot-Cooler-If-You-Did

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always the quote, "It'd be a lot cooler if you did." This text is positioned over Matthew McConaughey's character, attributing the persuasive and slightly condescending line to him.
The top text box typically sets up the scenario. It usually describes an action someone is not doing or a statement someone has made that the meme creator finds uncool or wants to challenge.

Itd-Be-A-Lot-Cooler-If-You-Did.image_description: This meme features a still of Matthew McConaughey as David Wooderson in the 1993 film "Dazed and Confused." In the scene, Wooderson, an older man who still hangs out with high schoolers, tries to persuade a younger character to join a party. The meme format uses his line, "It'd be a lot cooler if you did," to express a condescending or persuasive suggestion that someone should do something to be considered 'cool'.
Itd-Be-A-Lot-Cooler-If-You-Did.display_name: Itd Be A Lot Cooler If You Did

Abbacchio-Joins-the-Kicking.name: Abbacchio-Joins-the-Kicking

text_options.description: This text is placed on Abbacchio as he sips wine, representing the person or entity that is initially aloof, disapproving, or makes a statement contrary to the action they will later join. It sets up the ironic reversal in the final panel.

This label is on the person lying on the ground, representing the target of the group's collective scorn or attack. This is typically an unpopular opinion, a disliked concept, or a person being 'ratioed' online.

This text is placed over Abbacchio in the first panel, who is looking down at the target. He represents the main character of the meme's narrative: the one who is initially hesitant or judgmental before ultimately joining the others.

This label is on Narancia Ghirga, one of the two characters initially poised to attack the target. He represents one of the initial members of the group or one of the first opinions against the target.
This label is on Guido Mista, the other character ready to attack the target from the start. Along with Narancia, he represents the initial group or force acting against the subject on the ground.

Abbacchio-Joins-the-Kicking.image_description: This three-panel meme from 'JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Golden Wind' depicts characters Leone Abbacchio, Guido Mista, and Narancia Ghirga. The format shows Abbacchio initially looking on disapprovingly while Mista and Narancia stand over a defeated enemy, then calmly sipping wine, before joining them in violently kicking the person on the ground. This meme is used to show someone who at first seems indifferent or against an idea, but then enthusiastically joins in, often to gang up on an unpopular opinion or target.

Darth-Vader---Come-to-the-Dark-Side.name: Darth-Vader---Come-to-the-Dark-Side

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It typically features a variation of Darth Vader's famous quote, 'I find your lack of faith disturbing.' The phrase is altered to humorously or sarcastically respond to the statement placed in the top text box.

The top text box is used to set up the joke. It contains a statement, opinion, or quote that the meme creator finds foolish, naive, or disagreeable, prompting Darth Vader's disapproving reaction in the punchline below.

Darth-Vader---Come-to-the-Dark-Side.image_description: This meme features the character Darth Vader from the Star Wars franchise, specifically from the film 'The Empire Strikes Back'. In the image, Vader stands before a vast wall of lights, raising his hand in his iconic Force-choke gesture. The meme format, known as 'I Find Your Lack of Faith Disturbing,' is used to express disapproval or disagreement with a statement, often in a sarcastic or humorous way. The top text presents a statement the creator finds objectionable, and the bottom text delivers a witty, altered version of Vader's famous quote as a punchline.
Darth-Vader---Come-to-the-Dark-Side.display_name: Darth Vader   Come to the Dark Side

The-What.name: The-What

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, which reads "The WHAT". This text is an integral part of the reaction image, conveying a sense of escalating confusion and shock in response to the content presented in the top panel.

This top panel is the setup for the meme. Users place text or an image here that is intended to be confusing, nonsensical, or shocking, which then prompts the bewildered "The WHAT" reaction in the panel below.

The-What.image_description: This meme, often called "The WHAT" or "Confused Math Lady," features Brazilian actress Renata Sorrah as her character Nazaré Tedesco. The format consists of two panels: the top panel presents a confusing, shocking, or nonsensical statement or image. The bottom panel shows the reaction, transitioning from a polite smile with the word "The" to an extreme, wide-eyed close-up with the word "WHAT," expressing intense confusion and disbelief.

comparison-table.name: comparison-table

text_options.description: This is the second and final panel of the punchline. The text here completes the simple phrase started in the previous panel, delivering the humorous and anticlimactic resolution to the 'difficult' task mentioned in the setup.

This is the first of two bottom panels that form the punchline. The text here begins a simple phrase that directly contradicts the complex setup in the (unseen) top panel, setting up the final word in the next box.

comparison-table.image_description: This meme format, known as 'One Does Not Simply Walk into Mordor,' originates from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring.' It features the character Boromir, played by Sean Bean, making a solemn declaration about the difficulty of a task. The meme humorously juxtaposes this serious tone by applying the phrase 'One does not simply...' to mundane or everyday challenges, with the bottom two panels providing a simple, often sarcastic, punchline.

dont-look-at-them-Ricky.name: dont-look-at-them-Ricky

text_options.description: This is the speech bubble for the flamboyant man, delivering the punchline of the meme. The text here is a confident, often fabulous, declaration that subverts the mother's earlier dismissal. It reveals he is the very thing the son desired, but in a superior or unexpected form.

This speech bubble contains the mother's shocked reaction in the final panel. The text is typically a short exclamation of surprise or disbelief, such as "What?!", in response to the flamboyant man's statement.

This is the mother's speech bubble in the second panel, showing her annoyed response to her son. The text here is typically a dismissive refusal, often using the "we have [something similar] at home" trope to deny the son's request and set up the punchline.
This speech bubble belongs to the son in the first panel. The text here represents a request made to his mother, usually asking to get something or go somewhere, which initiates the meme's narrative.

dont-look-at-them-Ricky.image_description: This three-panel comic from "Extra Fabulous Comics" shows a mother and her son encountering a flamboyant man. The son points and asks for something, the mother dismisses the request, but is then shocked when the man reveals he is that very thing, or something even better. This meme format, known as "I Am the Manager," is used to subvert expectations, where a seemingly lesser option turns out to be surprisingly superior or perfect.

J-Jonah-Jameson-Spiderman.name: J-Jonah-Jameson-Spiderman

text_options.description: This text box is placed over J. Jonah Jameson. It typically labels the person, group, or entity that is laughing at or mocking the subject described in the top text box.

Located in the upper portion of the image, this text box describes the person, situation, or statement that is being laughed at. It serves as the setup or punchline that elicits the derisive laughter from the character below.

J-Jonah-Jameson-Spiderman.image_description: This meme features J. Jonah Jameson, the editor-in-chief from the 1960s Spider-Man animated series, laughing hysterically at his desk with a cigar in his mouth. Known as "J. Jonah Jameson Laughing," the image is used to express derisive laughter, mockery, or amusement at someone else's statement, failure, or misfortune. The meme typically labels Jameson as the one laughing and the space above him as the subject being ridiculed.

Shia-labeouf-JUST-DO-IT.name: Shia-labeouf-JUST-DO-IT

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically contains the punchline or the specific action the viewer is being urged to take. It often describes a task, a dream, or a simple decision that someone is hesitating over, which Shia LaBeouf's intense encouragement is directed towards.

The top text area usually sets up the context or presents a problem or procrastination scenario. This text provides the reason for Shia LaBeouf's intense motivational intervention, framing the situation that requires the 'Just Do It' attitude.

Shia-labeouf-JUST-DO-IT.image_description: This meme features actor Shia LaBeouf in a still from his intensely motivational 'Just Do It' speech, which originated from an art school project. He is depicted in a crouched, aggressive pose against a green screen, shouting with a passionate expression. The meme is widely used to humorously or earnestly encourage someone to stop procrastinating and take action on a goal, dream, or simple task, with the green screen background making it a highly versatile and exploitable format.

Dinosaurs-meteor.name: Dinosaurs-meteor

text_options.description: This text label is placed over the dinosaurs on the ground. It represents a person, group, company, or idea that is oblivious to an impending threat or about to be rendered obsolete.

This text label is placed on the meteor streaking across the sky. It represents the overwhelming, often unforeseen, force, event, or disruptive innovation that will cause the downfall of the entity labeled on the dinosaurs.

Dinosaurs-meteor.image_description: This meme, known as "Dinosaur Meteor" or "Dinosaur Extinction," depicts a group of dinosaurs, including a T-Rex and a Triceratops, in a prehistoric setting. Unbeknownst to them, a massive meteor is hurtling towards Earth, symbolizing an impending and unavoidable catastrophe. The meme is used to represent an entity, concept, or group that is blissfully unaware of an imminent, overwhelming threat or a disruptive change that will make them obsolete.

comic-book-guy-worst-ever.name: comic-book-guy-worst-ever

text_options.description: This area, placed over the keyboard, contains the critical or negative comment being typed. It's the punchline of the meme, often a hyperbolic and dismissive statement that reveals the commenter's cynical or gatekeeping attitude.

This label, placed over Comic Book Guy's head, identifies the person or group being satirized. It sets the context by naming the type of fan or online user (e.g., "Film Bros," "Gamers," "Redditors") who is making the overly critical statement.

comic-book-guy-worst-ever.image_description: This meme features the character Comic Book Guy from the animated series "The Simpsons." He is depicted sitting at his computer, sipping a drink, with a scowl on his face, embodying the stereotypical image of a nerdy, condescending, and overly critical internet commenter. The meme is used to mock people who make dismissive, gatekeeping, or sarcastically negative pronouncements online, often using his catchphrase format, "Worst. [Thing]. Ever."

Skeleton-at-deskcomputerwork.name: Skeleton-at-deskcomputerwork

text_options.description: This text box is located at the bottom of the image, often functioning as the punchline. It typically describes the specific thing the person was waiting for, which caused them to turn into a skeleton. For example, "Waiting for the game to load."

This text box at the top of the image usually provides the setup or context for the joke. It might describe the initial action or state of the person before the long wait began, such as "Me, sitting down to play a quick game before bed."

Skeleton-at-deskcomputerwork.image_description: The "Waiting Skeleton" meme features a full-size human skeleton sitting patiently at an office desk in front of a computer, wearing a headset. This image is used to humorously exaggerate the experience of waiting for an extremely long time for something to happen, to the point of dying and decomposing. It's a popular reaction image to express impatience with slow downloads, long-awaited game releases, or any situation involving a lengthy delay.

Sean-Bean-Lord-Of-The-Rings.name: Sean-Bean-Lord-Of-The-Rings

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It describes the action or task that is being presented as deceptively difficult, completing the phrase started in the top text. For example, in the original context, this text would read '...walk into Mordor.'

This top text box contains the setup phrase for the meme, which is almost always 'One does not simply...'. This text establishes the well-known catchphrase and sets up the punchline that follows in the bottom text box.

Sean-Bean-Lord-Of-The-Rings.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of the character Boromir, played by Sean Bean, from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring.' The image captures him at the Council of Elrond, looking serious and making a hand gesture while explaining a difficult concept. This format, known as 'One Does Not Simply,' is used to humorously point out that a seemingly straightforward task is actually much more complex or difficult than it appears.
Sean-Bean-Lord-Of-The-Rings.display_name: Sean Bean Lord Of The Rings

Karen.name: Karen

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline of the meme. It almost invariably contains the signature phrase 'I'd like to speak to your manager' or a variation of it, representing the ultimate expression of the 'Karen' stereotype's entitlement and desire to escalate a situation.

The top text box is used to set up the scenario. It typically contains a statement of complaint, a perceived slight, or an unreasonable demand made by the 'Karen' character, establishing the context for her entitled reaction.

Karen.image_description: This image shows a woman in profile with a distinctive blonde and brown spiky haircut and sunglasses, which has become the visual representation of the 'Karen' stereotype. 'Karen' is a pejorative term for an entitled or demanding middle-aged white woman. The meme is used to satirize people who exhibit privileged and obnoxious behavior, often culminating in the demand to 'speak to the manager'.

Lion-King-Rafiki-Simba.name: Lion-King-Rafiki-Simba

text_options.description: Text placed over Rafiki identifies the person or entity performing the action. This is the subject who is either proudly presenting or forcefully discarding the object represented by Simba.

Text placed over or near Simba represents the object, person, or concept being presented or discarded. This is the central focus or punchline of the meme, receiving the action from the character labeled as Rafiki.

Lion-King-Rafiki-Simba.image_description: This meme features a scene from Disney's 'The Lion King' where the mandrill Rafiki holds up the lion cub Simba on Pride Rock. In its meme format, this image is used in two primary ways: either to show someone proudly presenting something they cherish (labeling Rafiki as the presenter and Simba as the object), or more commonly, to humorously depict someone forcefully discarding something, often with the caption 'Yeet'. The latter subverts the original wholesome context for comedic effect, representing the act of getting rid of something with great enthusiasm.

Meet-the-Blank.name: Meet-the-Blank

text_options.description: Located on the bottom right, this is the lower line of the two-line copyright text. In the original, it says 'ALL RIGHTS RESERVED'. In memes, this text is often edited to add a secondary joke or a humorous credit related to the meme's subject.

Positioned on the bottom right, just above index 0, this is the top line of the copyright text. Originally, it reads 'COPYRIGHT © 2007 VALVE CORPORATION'. Meme creators frequently alter this line for comedic effect, replacing the official credit with something absurd or relevant to the meme's content.

This is the main, central text area where the title of the video or meme is displayed in large, bold letters. In the original 'Meet the Team' videos, it would name the character class (e.g., 'MEET THE SPY'). In the meme format, this is the punchline, replaced with 'MEET THE [SUBJECT]' to frame the subject in the context of the game.

This small area in the upper left corner is typically empty in the original title cards. In meme edits, it can be used to place a small logo, icon, or a short piece of text that adds an extra layer of context or humor to the main title.

Meet-the-Blank.image_description: This image is the iconic title card from the video game Team Fortress 2, used in the "Meet the Team" character introduction videos. The meme format, "Meet the [X]", uses this title card, often with its accompanying theme music, to humorously introduce a person, object, or concept as if they were a character class from the game. It serves as a punchline or an identifier, signaling that the preceding content is related to or has the chaotic, quirky energy of Team Fortress 2.

Leonardo-dicaprio-django-laugh.name: Leonardo-dicaprio-django-laugh

text_options.description: This area labels the person or entity, represented by Leonardo DiCaprio's character, who is reacting with smug laughter. It identifies the subject finding the situation described above humorous or pathetic.

The top caption area sets up the context or premise. The text here describes a situation, statement, or action that is perceived as naive, foolish, or absurd, thereby provoking the condescending laughter from the character below.

Leonardo-dicaprio-django-laugh.image_description: This meme features a still of Leonardo DiCaprio as the character Calvin Candie in the 2012 film "Django Unchained." In the scene, he is laughing hysterically and condescendingly while holding a drink. Known as "Laughing Leo" or "Django Laughing," the meme is used as a reaction image to express smug amusement, schadenfreude, or a patronizing laugh at someone else's expense or a ridiculous situation.

Kid-Named.name: Kid-Named

text_options.description: The bottom text region, located below the character's chin. This area typically contains the punchline or a simple, often absurd, response that contrasts with the setup text at the top. The humor comes from the deadpan delivery implied by Mike's expression.

The top text region, positioned above the character's head. This is where the setup for the joke is placed. It usually describes a situation, a question, or a statement that is often naive, foolish, or sets up an expectation that will be subverted.

Kid-Named.image_description: This meme features a close-up, intensely lit portrait of the character Mike Ehrmantraut from the TV shows Breaking Bad and Better Call Saul. Known for his stoic, no-nonsense demeanor, his deadpan and slightly weary expression is the core of the meme. The format typically uses this image as a reaction to a preceding statement or scenario, creating a humorous anticlimax or highlighting the absurdity of the setup. It's often used in a two-panel format where the top text presents a situation and Mike's face serves as the silent, judgmental punchline.

stop-trying-to-make-X-happen.name: stop-trying-to-make-X-happen

text_options.description: This is the punchline, typically a variation of Regina George's line. It often starts with phrases like "So you're telling me..." or "So you think..." to rephrase the setup text in a condescending or challenging manner, capturing the character's incredulous tone.
This is the setup text, which presents a statement, a situation, or a belief. It provides the context for Regina's sarcastic or questioning response in the bottom text.

stop-trying-to-make-X-happen.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Regina George, played by Rachel McAdams, from the 2004 film 'Mean Girls'. In the scene, she condescendingly asks, "So you agree? You think you're really pretty?" The meme format uses this image to sarcastically or incredulously question a statement or belief, rephrasing it in a challenging way.
stop-trying-to-make-X-happen.display_name: stop trying to make X happen

Spongebob-vs-Squidward-Alarm-Clocks.name: Spongebob-vs-Squidward-Alarm-Clocks

text_options.description: This label is placed over the wall of numerous alarm clocks. It represents the overwhelming, numerous, or powerful force, problem, or group in the comparison.
This label identifies Squidward, who is associated with the massive number of clocks. He represents the entity that is overly prepared, has a significant advantage, or is part of the larger group.
This label is on the single alarm clock held by SpongeBob. It represents the singular, often insufficient, or simple tool, idea, or effort being compared against the larger force.
This label identifies SpongeBob, who is holding the single clock. He represents the individual, the underdog, or the entity making a simple or naive attempt against a much larger challenge.

Spongebob-vs-Squidward-Alarm-Clocks.image_description: This two-panel meme from SpongeBob SquarePants contrasts a simple effort with an overwhelming one. In the top panel, an angry SpongeBob holds a single alarm clock, while the bottom panel shows a smug Squidward in front of a massive wall of alarm clocks. The format is used to compare a singular entity or simple solution against a much larger, more numerous, or complex opponent or problem.

Double-d-facts-book.name: Double-d-facts-book

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the open page of the book in the bottom panel. It contains the punchline of the meme: an unwelcome, inconvenient, or harsh truth that contradicts the statement presented in the top panel. Double D's annoyed expression as he reads reinforces the negative nature of this "fact."

This area, covering the book cover in the top panel, introduces the topic or popular belief that the meme is about to challenge. While the original book says "FACTS," this space is often edited to present a specific statement or idea that Double D seems enthusiastic about, setting up the subversion in the panel below.

Double-d-facts-book.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Double D's Facts Book," features the character Edd (Double D) from the cartoon "Ed, Edd n Eddy." In the top panel, he excitedly presents a book labeled "FACTS," representing a popular idea or belief. The bottom panel shows him reading the book with a look of disgust, revealing an unpleasant or inconvenient truth. The meme is used to contrast a common opinion with a harsh, contradictory fact.

Is-Four-A-Lot.name: Is-Four-A-Lot

text_options.description: This is the third and final part of the Doctor's explanation. The text here represents the climax of the long-winded explanation, often being the most technical, absurd, or convoluted statement, matching his intense, wide-eyed expression.
This is the second part of the Doctor's explanation. The text here continues to build on the initial point, adding more complexity or detail as the explanation becomes more elaborate and passionate.
This is the first part of the Doctor's explanation. The text here introduces the topic or the beginning of a long, complex explanation for what is usually a simple concept.

This text is placed over Clara Oswald, who looks unimpressed or confused. It typically contains the simple question or concept that prompted the long explanation, or it labels Clara as the person receiving the explanation, serving as the punchline.

Is-Four-A-Lot.image_description: This four-panel meme format, known as "Doctor Who Explains" or "Peter Capaldi Explains," originates from the TV series *Doctor Who*. It features the Twelfth Doctor (Peter Capaldi) passionately explaining something over three panels with escalating intensity, followed by a final panel of his companion, Clara Oswald (Jenna Coleman), looking unimpressed or confused. The meme is used to humorously illustrate someone giving a long, convoluted explanation for a simple concept or enthusiastically detailing a niche interest to an indifferent audience.

Dekh-raha-hai-na-binod.name: Dekh-raha-hai-na-binod

text_options.description: This text box is on the bottom panel where Prahlad is smiling deviously. The text here reveals the user's true, often selfish or humorous, underlying motive. It serves as the punchline, creating a comedic contrast with the statement made in the top panel.

This text box is on the top panel where Prahlad is speaking. The text here typically represents a formal, noble, or publicly acceptable statement or reason for doing something. It sets up the joke by presenting a facade of sincerity.

Dekh-raha-hai-na-binod.image_description: This two-panel meme features the character Prahlad Pandey from the Indian web series *Panchayat*. The top panel shows him making a seemingly serious or official statement, while the bottom panel shows him smiling slyly and rubbing his hands, revealing his true, often mischievous or self-serving, intention to another person. The meme is used to humorously contrast what someone says publicly with what they are actually thinking or planning, highlighting hypocrisy or a hidden agenda.

Drake-meme-3-panels.name: Drake-meme-3-panels

text_options.description: This bottom text box aligns with Drake's approving gesture. It contains the punchline of the meme—the preferred, superior, or 'galaxy brain' option that the creator is endorsing.

This middle text box corresponds to Drake's second disapproving gesture. The text here usually presents an option that is slightly better or more complex than the first, but is still ultimately rejected in favor of the final choice.
This top text box is placed next to Drake's first gesture of disapproval. It typically contains the most basic, common, or least desirable option in the comparison, which is being rejected.

Drake-meme-3-panels.image_description: This is an expanded three-panel version of the 'Drake Hotline Bling' meme, often used in a style similar to the 'Expanding Brain' meme. It features the rapper Drake in three rows: the top two show him with a gesture of disapproval, while the bottom one shows him smiling and pointing in approval. The format is used to create a hierarchy of preferences, rejecting the top two options to endorse the bottom one as a superior, more enlightened, or ironically clever choice.

Let-the-hate-flow-through-you.name: Let-the-hate-flow-through-you

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline. This area typically contains a quote expressing evil encouragement or satisfaction, such as 'Good, good. Let the hate flow through you' or a thematic variation. It represents the voice of Palpatine reacting to the situation described in the top text.

The top text, used to set up the context for the meme. This text describes a situation where someone is expressing anger, frustration, or succumbing to a negative impulse, which the meme creator finds amusingly evil.

Let-the-hate-flow-through-you.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Emperor Palpatine from Star Wars, grinning menacingly in his dark, hooded robe. The character, also known as Darth Sidious, is the embodiment of evil and manipulation in the series. This image is used to express sinister satisfaction or encouragement when someone gives in to anger, frustration, or a temptation, often referencing his famous line, 'Good, good. Let the hate flow through you.'
Let-the-hate-flow-through-you.display_name: Let the hate flow through you

This-Morgan-Freeman.name: This-Morgan-Freeman

text_options.description: The text in the bottom section typically contains the punchline or a reinforcing phrase. The most common text here is "He's right, you know," which validates the statement made in the top section and gives the meme its name.

The top section is where the main text of the meme is placed. This text presents a statement of fact, a profound observation, or an undeniable truth that the creator wants to emphasize, using Morgan Freeman's authoritative image to support it.

This-Morgan-Freeman.image_description: This meme features a close-up of actor Morgan Freeman looking thoughtful while holding up his index finger, as if making a profound point. Known for his authoritative voice and roles, Freeman's image lends credibility and weight to the statement presented. The meme, often called "He's Right, You Know," is used to share a surprising, insightful, or undeniable truth that the audience is meant to agree with.

Joker-Its-simple-we-kill-the-batman.name: Joker-Its-simple-we-kill-the-batman

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is a cynical, overly dramatic, or philosophical reaction to the setup above. It famously reads "WE LIVE IN A SOCIETY," but can be any statement that frames the initial minor issue as a profound symptom of a broken world, embodying the Joker's nihilistic persona.

The text at the top sets up a scenario or describes a common social convention. This is often a minor grievance, a personal pet peeve, or an observation about people's behavior that the meme's author finds illogical or annoying.

Joker-Its-simple-we-kill-the-batman.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Heath Ledger's Joker from the film "The Dark Knight," known for his chaotic and anti-establishment philosophy. The format is used to express cynical or edgy commentary on societal norms, often in an exaggerated or ironic way. The meme juxtaposes a mundane frustration with a grandiose, philosophical complaint about the state of the world, famously encapsulated by the phrase "We live in a society."
Joker-Its-simple-we-kill-the-batman.display_name: Joker Its simple we kill the batman

Donald-Trump-Birthday.name: Donald-Trump-Birthday

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, positioned below the podium. This is the punchline, representing Donald Trump's direct response or accusation. Capitalizing on his pointing gesture, this text often singles out the viewer (e.g., 'You') or a specific group to answer the question or complete the scenario set up by the top text.

The top text of the meme, placed above Donald Trump's head. This text serves as the setup, typically posing a question, describing a problem, or identifying a need to find a responsible party (e.g., 'Who is responsible for my problems?').

Donald-Trump-Birthday.image_description: This meme features a photograph of former U.S. President Donald Trump pointing directly at the camera with a serious expression while speaking at a podium. The image is a classic top-text, bottom-text meme format where Trump's pointing gesture is used to directly address or accuse the viewer. Typically, the top text poses a question or describes a situation, and the bottom text provides a direct, often humorous or blunt, answer as if spoken by Trump, implicating the reader.

Big-Willy-Wonka-Tell-Me-Again.name: Big-Willy-Wonka-Tell-Me-Again

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the sarcastic punchline. It's a condescending question or statement that directly mocks the setup in the top text, often beginning with phrases like "Oh, you must be..." or "Please, tell me more about..." to match Wonka's patronizing expression.

The top text sets up the joke by presenting a statement, often something someone has said that is perceived as naive, arrogant, or obvious. This line serves as the target for the condescending commentary that follows.

Big-Willy-Wonka-Tell-Me-Again.image_description: This meme, known as "Condescending Wonka" or "Creepy Wonka," features a still of actor Gene Wilder as Willy Wonka from the 1971 film "Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory." The image captures Wonka with a patronizing, insincere smile while resting his head on his hand. This meme is used to sarcastically or condescendingly respond to a statement someone has made, feigning interest before delivering a belittling punchline.
Big-Willy-Wonka-Tell-Me-Again.display_name: Big Willy Wonka Tell Me Again

Rick-and-Carl-Long.name: Rick-and-Carl-Long

text_options.description: A label identifying the unimpressed listener, typically representing Carl's role in the meme. This person is the target of the bad joke.
The first part of the joke's setup, spoken by Rick. This begins the multi-panel dad joke.
A label for the listener, same as index 0, showing their continued lack of amusement as the joke progresses.
The second part of the joke's setup, continuing from the previous panel to build up to the punchline.
Another label for the listener, same as the previous ones, positioned just before the punchline is revealed.
The punchline of the joke, which is always a terrible pun that justifies Carl's deadpan reaction and Rick's subsequent breakdown.
The final label for the listener, showing their ultimate disappointment or stoic expression after hearing the full joke.
Rick's over-the-top, often pained reaction to his own joke, frequently written as a sound effect like '(crying)' or '(wheezing)'. This highlights the cringeworthy nature of the pun.

Rick-and-Carl-Long.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as 'Rick Grimes' Dad Joke' or 'Carl!', originates from the TV show 'The Walking Dead' and features Rick Grimes telling a joke to his son, Carl. The format is read from bottom to top, with Rick setting up a terrible pun over the first few panels. The punchline is delivered in the second-to-last panel, followed by Rick breaking down in laughter or tears in the final panel while Carl remains stoic and unimpressed, representing the audience's reaction to a bad 'dad joke'.

Bycicle.name: Bycicle

text_options.description: This text is placed over the man who has fallen off his bike. It represents the negative outcome, the complaint, or the person/thing being blamed for the problem that the subject created for themselves. This is the punchline of the meme, highlighting the hypocrisy or foolishness of the situation.

This text is placed on the stick that the man is inserting into his bike's wheel. It represents the self-destructive action, decision, or policy that directly causes the problem. It is the act of self-sabotage itself.

This text is placed over the man happily riding his bike in the first panel. It typically describes a positive situation, a stated goal, or an initial opinion. This sets up the context before the act of self-sabotage occurs.

Bycicle.image_description: The "Bike Fall" meme, also known as "Bicycle Fall" or "Man putting a stick in his own bike," is a three-panel comic strip illustrating self-sabotage. In the first panel, a man happily rides a bicycle. In the second, he deliberately shoves a stick into the front wheel of his own bike. The final panel shows him crashed on the ground, looking pained. The meme is used to humorously point out situations where someone creates their own problem and then complains about or blames others for the negative consequences.

Nick-Cage-and-Pedro-pascal.name: Nick-Cage-and-Pedro-pascal

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the smiling Pedro Pascal. It typically describes a person, entity, or situation that is happy, carefree, or blissfully unaware of the negative reality represented by the other panel.

This text box is placed over the concerned Nicolas Cage. It represents a person, entity, or situation that is serious, worried, or burdened by a problem, directly contrasting with the happy perspective in the other panel.

Nick-Cage-and-Pedro-pascal.image_description: This two-panel meme features actors Nicolas Cage and Pedro Pascal from the film 'The Unbearable Weight of Massive Talent'. On the left, Nicolas Cage has a concerned and intense expression, while on the right, Pedro Pascal is smiling happily. The meme is used to contrast two opposing perspectives, emotions, or situations, where Cage represents a negative or serious viewpoint and Pascal represents a positive, carefree, or ignorant one.

Emergency-Alert.name: Emergency-Alert

text_options.description: This is the main body of the alert, where the punchline or core message is placed. The text here is the 'emergency' itself, which is usually an exaggerated opinion, a funny declaration, or a personal announcement presented with mock gravity.

This smaller box at the top serves as the title or header for the alert. It typically contains a capitalized phrase that sets the context, such as 'PRESIDENTIAL ALERT,' 'NATIONAL ALERT,' or a more customized, humorous label that introduces the sender or subject of the main message.

Emergency-Alert.image_description: This meme format is a template based on a smartphone's 'EMERGENCY ALERTS' notification, which gained popularity after a nationwide test of the US Presidential Alert system. The meme is used to make a dramatic, urgent, or humorous announcement about a topic that is often trivial or personal. The humor arises from the contrast between the serious, official-looking alert format and the typically mundane or absurd content of the message.

How-to-recognize-a-stroke.name: How-to-recognize-a-stroke

text_options.description: This area, positioned as a speech bubble in the final panel labeled "Incoherent speech," contains the punchline of the meme. The text placed here is typically a nonsensical phrase, a garbled sentence, a misquoted lyric, or text from another meme that sounds like gibberish. Its purpose is to be a humorous example of incoherent speech, contrasting with the serious medical information in the preceding panels.

How-to-recognize-a-stroke.image_description: This meme is a four-panel comic that parodies a medical infographic on how to recognize a stroke. The first three panels illustrate genuine symptoms like a twisted mouth and arm paralysis, setting a serious tone. The fourth panel, labeled "Incoherent speech," is the punchline, where an absurd or nonsensical phrase is inserted, humorously framing it as a symptom of a stroke. The meme's humor derives from the juxtaposition of the serious medical guide format with a ridiculous or out-of-context quote.

the-daily-struggle.name: the-daily-struggle

text_options.description: Text placed on the man's chest identifies the person or entity facing the dilemma. This label, often 'Me' or a specific group, provides context for who is struggling with the choice shown in the top panel.

Text is placed on the two white labels above the buttons, each representing one of the two conflicting options. These labels define the core dilemma of the meme, setting up the difficult choice that causes the man's distress.

the-daily-struggle.image_description: This two-panel comic meme, known as 'Daily Struggle' or 'Two Buttons,' depicts a cartoon man sweating profusely as he agonizes over a difficult choice. The top panel shows a hand hovering between two red buttons, each representing an option, while the bottom panel shows the man's stressed and anxious face. The meme is used to humorously illustrate a dilemma between two conflicting ideas, desires, or courses of action, exaggerating the difficulty of the decision.

Communist-cat.name: Communist-cat

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, located at the bottom. It typically contains a "corrected" version of the top text, replacing a singular possessive pronoun (like "my" or "your") with "our" to enforce the joke about collective ownership. For example, if the top text is "My meme," this text would be "*Our meme," with the asterisk often used to signify a correction.

This is the setup text, located at the top of the image. It usually presents a statement of individual ownership or possession. For example, it might say "My food," "Your phone," or "My girlfriend," setting up the object or concept that will be humorously claimed as collective property in the punchline below.

Communist-cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Communist Cat" or "Our Cat," features a close-up of a serious-looking cat against a red-tinted background with the Soviet Union's hammer and sickle symbol. The meme humorously applies the communist principle of collective ownership to everyday situations. It is typically used as a reaction to someone claiming personal possession of something, reframing it as belonging to everyone by changing "my" or "your" to "our."

death-note-blank.name: death-note-blank

text_options.description: This larger text area is where the name of the person, object, or concept that the meme creator wishes to eliminate is placed. It serves as the main subject of the meme's joke, representing the target being written into the Death Note.

Positioned directly where the pen is writing, this space is typically used for a secondary punchline or a specific detail related to the main target in box 0. It often functions as the 'cause of death' or adds a layer of specificity to the joke.

death-note-blank.image_description: This meme originates from the anime series 'Death Note', showing a close-up of a hand writing in a notebook with a fountain pen. The scene depicts the main character, Light Yagami, using the Death Note, a supernatural book that causes the death of anyone whose name is written inside. This format is used to humorously express a strong desire to eliminate or get rid of a person, trend, or concept by metaphorically 'writing their name' in the book.

Simpsons-Truth-Lionel-Hutz.name: Simpsons-Truth-Lionel-Hutz

text_options.description: This text, placed on the binder in front of the smiling character, typically labels the person or entity for whom the subject is feigning happiness. This is often a customer, boss, or social obligation that requires a polite, cheerful exterior.

This text, positioned above the annoyed character, describes the situation or thought that causes the genuine negative reaction. It sets the context for the disappointment or frustration that the character is trying to hide with a fake smile in the second panel.

Simpsons-Truth-Lionel-Hutz.image_description: This two-panel meme from The Simpsons features the Squeaky-Voiced Teen. In the first panel, he looks annoyed and disappointed, representing a genuine internal reaction. In the second panel, he forces a wide, cheerful smile, representing the fake, positive exterior one must present. The meme is used to contrast one's true feelings with the polite or professional facade required in a situation, often in a customer service context.

mouse-entering-and-leaving.name: mouse-entering-and-leaving

text_options.description: This text box is on the bottom panel where the character is retreating. It typically contains the punchline, which is the reason for the sudden reversal or abandonment of the initial statement. This text represents the inconvenient truth, the negative consequence, or the daunting reality that causes the person to change their mind.

This text box is on the top panel where the character is confidently moving forward. It is used for the initial bold statement, boast, or ambitious plan. This text sets up the user's confident but ultimately misguided intention before the reversal in the next panel.

mouse-entering-and-leaving.image_description: This two-panel meme format features a cartoon character from the show CatDog. In the top panel, the character confidently walks forward, away from a door, as if leading the way. In the bottom panel, he has abruptly turned around and is walking back towards the door. This meme is used to represent making a bold statement or plan, and then immediately retracting it or backing down after realizing the negative consequences or difficulties involved.

you-like-krabby-patties.name: you-like-krabby-patties

text_options.description: This text box, located at the bottom of the image, typically contains the setup for the joke. It often presents a question, a statement from another person, or a situation that SpongeBob (representing the meme creator) is reacting to.

This text box at the top represents the punchline or the smug individual's perspective. It describes the action or thought that causes the smug expression, directly responding to the text in box 0. For example, if box 0 says "My mom asking where the cookies went," box 1 might say "Me, with cookie crumbs all over my face:".

you-like-krabby-patties.image_description: A still image of SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series of the same name, wearing his Krusty Krab hat with a very smug, self-satisfied, and mischievous expression on his face. This meme, often called "Smug SpongeBob," is used to represent a person who is overly proud or confident about a situation, often in a humorous or slightly antagonistic way. It's typically used as a reaction image to convey a sense of knowing something others don't or having just done something clever or sneaky.

Will-Ferrell-Beer-Meme.name: Will-Ferrell-Beer-Meme

text_options.description: The bottom text, labeled with index 0, typically delivers the punchline or the disappointing outcome that causes the frustration. It explains the specific reason for the failed celebration or anticlimax set up by the top text.

The top text, labeled with index 1, sets up the initial expectation or scenario. This text describes something that should have been positive, exciting, or celebratory, creating a contrast with the disappointing reality shown in the image and explained in the bottom text.

Will-Ferrell-Beer-Meme.image_description: This meme features actor Will Ferrell with a deadpan, disappointed expression while crushing a beer can, causing it to spray everywhere. The image originates from a Bud Light commercial and is used to convey a sense of anticlimax, failed celebration, or frustration. The humor lies in the contrast between the act of opening a beer, typically a happy occasion, and Ferrell's somber reaction, symbolizing a ruined moment.

Blank-Pokemon-Card.name: Blank-Pokemon-Card

text_options.description: Located at the bottom right, this small area is typically used for a humorous credit, a punchline, or a witty side comment. In an actual Pokémon card, this section contains illustrator and set information, but in the meme, it serves as a space for an extra joke.

This large text box is for describing the subject's 'attacks' or 'abilities.' This is the core of the meme, where creators write funny or satirical descriptions of the subject's actions or characteristics, mimicking the style of the actual trading card game.

Positioned at the top of the card, this is where the name of the 'Pokémon' is placed. In the meme, this text establishes the subject of the card, which can be a person, an object, or a concept, setting the stage for the rest of the joke.
