Blank-Pokemon-Card.image_description: This meme template is a blank, Fire-type 'Basic' Pokémon trading card from the Pokémon franchise. The format is used to humorously present a person, object, or concept as if it were a Pokémon. Users insert an image into the main frame and add custom text for the name, attacks, and other stats to create a parody or a creative description.

bus-wankers.name: bus-wankers

text_options.description: This area, covering the car and its occupants, typically labels the person or entity doing the shouting. This is often labeled "Me" or a specific group, representing the source of the obnoxious opinion or insult.

Positioned above the car and in the background, this text box identifies the target of the insult being shouted. In the original scene, Jay yells "Bus wankers!" at people waiting for a bus, so this text is replaced with the name of a group or idea that the meme creator wishes to mock.

bus-wankers.image_description: This meme, known as "Inbetweeners Bus Wanker," originates from the British sitcom "The Inbetweeners." It features the character Jay Cartwright obnoxiously leaning out of a small yellow car to shout an insult, while his friends Simon and Will sit inside looking embarrassed or indifferent. The meme is used to represent someone loudly and crudely insulting a group or concept, contrasting the shouter's aggression with the silent disapproval or apathy of their peers.

Captain-America-Elevator-Fight.name: Captain-America-Elevator-Fight

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Captain America's face as he delivers the punchline of a joke. The text here is almost always a bad pun that relates to the setup in the first panel.

This box is on the face of Hydra agent Jasper Sitwell, who is looking at Captain America with a serious, unimpressed expression. He represents the audience reacting to the joke before the 'violent' reaction in the final panel. This area is often left blank, as his expression speaks for itself.
This text box is placed over Captain America in the first panel of the meme. The text here serves as the setup for the joke or pun that will be delivered in the next panel.

Captain-America-Elevator-Fight.image_description: This meme, known as "Captain America Elevator Fight Dad Joke," originates from a tense scene in the film *Captain America: The Winter Soldier*. The three-panel format depicts Captain America (Steve Rogers) in an elevator with several hostile Hydra agents. The meme humorously recontextualizes this scene as Captain America telling a terrible pun or a dad joke, with the subsequent fight in the third panel representing the violent and negative reaction from his audience.

Where-is.name: Where-is

text_options.description: This text box is in the final panel, next to the boy who is now addressing the viewer. The text here typically labels the viewer or the person being subjected to the fate of going to Brazil, serving as the punchline of the meme.

This text box is in the middle panel, where the boy points to Brazil on the map. The text here labels the undesirable, chaotic, or unexpected outcome, which is the core joke of the "You're going to Brazil" format.

This text box is in the top panel, which sets up the meme's premise. The text here usually represents a normal, desirable, or expected place or situation, which is then contrasted with the undesirable outcome in the next panel.

Where-is.image_description: This is a three-panel meme format known as "You're Going to Brazil." The first panel typically shows a desirable location or concept, often represented by a finger with a country's flag pointing to a map. The second panel abruptly switches to a young boy in a suit pointing to Brazil on a world map, representing an undesirable or chaotic alternative. The final panel shows the boy looking directly at the viewer with his hand on his chest, as if to say "you," confirming the viewer is the one being sent to Brazil.

I-Know-That-Feel-Bro.name: I-Know-That-Feel-Bro

text_options.description: This area typically contains labels for the two figures. The Wojak character is often labeled as 'me' or a specific group, while the faceless character is labeled with the problem, person, or concept they are embracing, which is the source of the shared feeling.

The top caption sets the scene or provides the overarching context for the meme. It usually describes a painful, ironic, or relatable situation that causes the two entities below to find common ground and share a moment of understanding.

I-Know-That-Feel-Bro.image_description: This meme, known as 'I Know That Feel Bro' or the Wojak Hug, features the Wojak (or Feels Guy) character embracing a faceless figure. The Wojak's melancholic expression conveys a sense of shared understanding and empathy for a difficult or relatable situation. The meme is used to express solidarity in the face of a common struggle, often with a bittersweet or ironic tone.

ight-imma-head-out-blank.name: ight-imma-head-out-blank

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically contains the punchline or reaction. In the context of the full "Ight Imma Head Out" meme, this is where that exact phrase would go, signifying the character's decision to leave. When used as a single panel, this text often represents SpongeBob's internal monologue or a caption summarizing his bored or contemplative state.

The top text area is used to establish the context or setup for SpongeBob's reaction. It usually describes a situation, a statement, or a scenario that is boring, awkward, or undesirable, prompting the feeling of wanting to leave or the contemplative expression shown in the image.

ight-imma-head-out-blank.image_description: This meme features SpongeBob SquarePants sitting in his armchair with a tired, bored, and contemplative expression. The image is a reaction shot, often used to convey a feeling of being done with a situation, deep in thought, or simply unimpressed. It is famously the first panel of the "Ight Imma Head Out" meme, where the subsequent panel shows him getting up to leave, making it perfect for expressing a desire to exit an awkward or uninteresting scenario.

Breaking-Bad---Say-My-Name.name: Breaking-Bad---Say-My-Name

text_options.description: This area, over Walter White's silent, smiling face, is typically left blank. The absence of text is the punchline, as his expression alone confirms that the outcome is not 'for the better', creating a sense of dread or dark humor.

Text in this box represents a hopeful, yet naive, clarifying question from the person reacting to the initial statement. It's almost always a variation of the phrase 'For the better, right?', seeking reassurance that the preceding statement will have a positive outcome.

This text box contains the initial statement or announcement that sets up the entire meme. It's usually a seemingly neutral or ambiguous declaration of a change or action, which prompts the concerned question in the next panel.

Breaking-Bad---Say-My-Name.image_description: A three-panel meme format from the TV show Breaking Bad, often called 'For the Better, Right?'. It depicts a tense conversation in the desert between protagonist Walter White and another character. The sequence shows Walter making a statement, the other character looking concerned and asking a clarifying question, and finally a silent, smiling close-up of Walter. The meme is used to represent a situation where a change is announced, and the silent, smug reaction in the final panel implies the change will have a negative or ironic outcome for the person asking.

WHAT-HOW.name: WHAT-HOW

text_options.description: The bottom panel represents the object of disapproval or rejection. Text placed here describes an idea, action, or item that is considered inferior, undesirable, or the 'wrong' way to do something.
The top panel represents the object of approval or preference. Text here describes the superior, preferred, or 'correct' alternative to the option in the bottom panel.

WHAT-HOW.image_description: This is a minimalist, abstract version of the 'Drakeposting' or 'Drake Hotline Bling' meme format. The template consists of two panels against a black background, representing Drake's disapproval (bottom) and approval (top). This format is used to express a preference for one thing over another, with the less desirable option in the bottom panel and the more desirable one in the top.

Jeffrey-Dahmer-tv.name: Jeffrey-Dahmer-tv

text_options.description: This text box labels the person or people being shown something, often representing the user's friends or an unsuspecting audience. Their label here highlights their role as the reluctant or unimpressed viewers of whatever the meme creator is enthusiastically presenting.

This text box represents the person who is enthusiastically showing something to others. It is typically labeled "Me" or a similar first-person identifier, establishing the meme creator as the one with the niche or intense interest they are eager to share.

Jeffrey-Dahmer-tv.image_description: This meme features a still image of actor Evan Peters as Jeffrey Dahmer from the Netflix series "Dahmer – Monster: The Jeffrey Dahmer Story." In the scene, Dahmer stands next to a vintage television in a dimly lit room, appearing to present something on the screen. The meme, often captioned "Me showing my friends," is used to humorously depict someone passionately sharing their niche or intense interests (like a favorite movie, song, or video) with an unwilling or uncomfortable audience, leveraging the unsettling context of the original character.

Gay-Unicorn.name: Gay-Unicorn

text_options.description: This bottom text area serves as the punchline, revealing the unexpectedly intense or aggressive reality. It directly corresponds to the image of the muscular unicorn, subverting the expectation set by the text in the top panel.

The top text area sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a person, thing, or situation in a way that makes it sound gentle, harmless, or cute, creating an expectation that will be humorously contradicted by the image and text below.

Gay-Unicorn.image_description: This meme, often called "Muscular Unicorn" or "Unicorn Man," features a muscular man in a pink and purple unicorn costume, striking a serious pose. The humor comes from the stark contrast between the tough, hyper-masculine figure and the whimsical, fantastical nature of the unicorn costume. It is typically used in a two-panel format to subvert expectations, where the first part describes something seemingly gentle or innocent, and the second part reveals its unexpectedly intense or aggressive reality, represented by this image.

stoned-guy.name: stoned-guy

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline of the meme. It contains the absurd, illogical, or hilariously simple conclusion to the thought started in the top text, representing the 'stoner thought' itself.
The top text serves as the setup for the joke. It typically introduces a situation, a question, or the beginning of a thought process that will be completed in a nonsensical way by the bottom text.

stoned-guy.image_description: This meme, known as "10 Guy" or "Stoner Stanley," features a young man with a dazed and intoxicated expression. The image is used as an image macro to convey nonsensical, illogical, or comically simple thoughts one might have while under the influence, particularly of marijuana. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of a seemingly profound or serious thought process with a ridiculously simple or incorrect conclusion, perfectly encapsulated by the subject's high-as-a-kite look.

Christopher-Walken-Fever.name: Christopher-Walken-Fever

text_options.description: The bottom text panel contains the punchline, a direct quote or parody of Christopher Walken's line from the sketch. It typically follows the template: "I got a fever... and the only prescription is more [X]," where [X] is the desired element that resolves the setup in the top panel.

The top text panel serves as the setup for the meme. It usually presents a situation, a problem, or a statement that is lacking a certain element, prompting Walken's 'prescription' in the panel below.

Christopher-Walken-Fever.image_description: This meme features actor Christopher Walken in the iconic "More Cowbell" sketch from Saturday Night Live. In the sketch, he plays music producer Bruce Dickinson who famously says, "I got a fever, and the only prescription is more cowbell." The meme format uses this image to express an intense need or desire for something by replacing "cowbell" with another word or concept, creating a two-part setup and punchline.

Bob-Ross-Meme.name: Bob-Ross-Meme

text_options.description: This text box, located at the bottom of the image, typically describes the initial mistake, failure, or unintended action. It serves as the setup for the meme's punchline.

This text box is placed over the finished, beautiful painting. It describes the positive and often unexpected outcome of the mistake mentioned below, representing the 'happy little accident' and delivering the punchline of the meme.

Bob-Ross-Meme.image_description: This meme features the beloved painter and television host Bob Ross, famous for his show 'The Joy of Painting.' In the image, he is smiling while holding a palette and brush next to a finished landscape painting. This format is known as the 'Happy Little Accidents' meme, used to reframe a mistake or negative event as an unexpected positive outcome, just as Ross would turn a painting error into a 'happy little tree.'

Chemistry-Cat.name: Chemistry-Cat

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image typically contains the punchline of a science-themed joke or pun. Its placement at the bottom provides a classic setup-punchline structure, concluding the joke started at the top or implied by the image itself.

Located at the top of the image over the chalkboard, this section is where the setup for a joke or a question is usually placed. The scientific formulas in the background reinforce the context, making this the ideal spot for the first part of a science pun.

Chemistry-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Chemistry Cat" or "Science Cat," features a white cat dressed as a professor with glasses and a bow tie in a chemistry lab. The cat sits in front of a chalkboard filled with humorous, nonsensical chemical formulas involving mice and cheese. This image is used to deliver science-related puns and jokes, with the cat's serious expression creating a humorous contrast with the often silly punchlines.

I-need-you.name: I-need-you

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below Uncle Sam's pointing finger, delivers the specific demand or punchline. It completes the phrase from the top text, specifying what the viewer is being 'recruited' or asked to do, which is often a mundane, silly, or ironic task.

The top text, located above Uncle Sam's head, typically sets up the call to action. It often starts with 'I WANT YOU' or a similar phrase that directly addresses the viewer, establishing the demanding tone of the meme.

I-need-you.image_description: This meme features the iconic American propaganda figure, Uncle Sam, from a World War I recruitment poster. He points directly at the viewer with a stern and commanding expression. The original 'I Want YOU for U.S. Army' slogan is adapted into a versatile meme format, used to make a direct, often humorous or satirical, call to action or demand.

Average-BLANK-Fan-VS-Average-BLANK-Enjoy.name: Average-BLANK-Fan-VS-Average-BLANK-Enjoyer

text_options.description: This text box is for the subject that is considered superior or more sophisticated. It is associated with the 'enjoyer,' a character depicted as a calm, confident, and physically ideal man known as GigaChad.
This text box is for the subject that is considered inferior or mainstream. It is associated with the 'fan,' a character depicted as an over-excited or unrefined person, often a Soyjak.

Average-BLANK-Fan-VS-Average-BLANK-Enjoy.image_description: This is the "Average Fan vs. Average Enjoyer" meme format, which uses a two-panel comparison to express a preferential opinion. On the left, an agitated man (often a variation of Soyjak) represents the "fan" of an allegedly inferior subject. On the right, a calm, muscular man (GigaChad) represents the "enjoyer" of a supposedly superior subject, framing the creator's preference as the more sophisticated choice.
Average-BLANK-Fan-VS-Average-BLANK-Enjoy.display_name: Average BLANK Fan VS Average BLANK Enjoyer

evil-genius-racoon.name: evil-genius-racoon

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the raccoon's body, typically reveals the punchline or the mischievous plan itself. It's the 'evil' thought or action that the raccoon is plotting in response to the setup in the top text.
The top text, positioned above the raccoon's head, sets up the context or situation that prompts the scheming behavior. It describes an opportunity or a scenario ripe for a clever or mischievous act.

evil-genius-racoon.image_description: This meme, known as 'Scheming Raccoon' or 'Evil Raccoon,' features a raccoon with a mischievous grin, rubbing its paws together. The animal's posture and expression perfectly capture a sense of plotting or devising a cunning plan. This image is used to humorously represent someone's internal monologue when they come up with a clever, selfish, or slightly wicked idea.

Skeptical-Baby.name: Skeptical-Baby

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over the baby's chest, typically contains the punchline or the specific part of a statement that is being questioned. It's the core of the skeptical reaction, often phrased as a doubtful question or a direct challenge to the setup text at the top.

The top text, placed above the baby's head, sets up the premise of the meme. It usually presents a statement, promise, or explanation that is perceived as dubious or hard to believe, prompting the baby's skeptical reaction.

Skeptical-Baby.image_description: The "Skeptical Baby" meme features a close-up photo of a baby with a furrowed brow, a raised eyebrow, and a sideways glance, conveying a strong sense of doubt and suspicion. This reaction image is used to question the logic or truthfulness of a statement. The humor comes from attributing such a complex, cynical expression to an innocent-looking baby, making it a perfect vehicle for expressing disbelief or calling out questionable claims.

Samuel-L-Jackson.name: Samuel-L-Jackson

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, typically stating the character's famous line, "I'm getting too old for this shit," or a variation of it. This text directly voices the exasperation and weariness shown on the character's face, concluding the meme's sentiment.

The top text box provides the context or setup for the meme. It describes the frustrating, confusing, or exhausting situation that is causing the character's reaction, effectively setting the stage for the punchline below.

Samuel-L-Jackson.image_description: This meme features actor Danny Glover as Roger Murtaugh in the film series "Lethal Weapon," looking weary and exasperated. Known as the "I'm Too Old For This Shit" meme, it is used to express frustration, exhaustion, or a feeling of being overwhelmed by a situation. The character's tired expression perfectly captures the sentiment of being done with a particular trend, event, or piece of nonsense, making it a popular reaction image for feeling out of touch or simply burnt out.

I-Wonder-What-Hes-Thinking.name: I-Wonder-What-Hes-Thinking

text_options.description: This lower region of the image, covering the couple under the covers, is typically left blank. It serves to establish the intimate bedroom setting, which provides the context for the woman's suspicions. Text is not usually placed here in this meme format.

This upper area is where the core text of the meme is placed, usually as two distinct thought bubbles. The text over the woman on the left expresses a serious suspicion (e.g., 'He's probably thinking about other women'). The text over the man on the right provides the punchline by revealing his actual, comically trivial or nerdy thoughts (e.g., 'Why do they call it an oven when you of in the cold food of out hot eat the food?').

I-Wonder-What-Hes-Thinking.image_description: This meme, known as 'Man Thinking in Bed' or 'He's Probably Thinking About Other Women', features a stock photo of a couple in bed. The woman looks suspiciously at her partner, who is awake and staring into the distance with a preoccupied expression. The humor comes from the contrast between the woman's assumed serious concern (usually about infidelity) and the man's actual inner monologue, which is revealed to be about something completely unrelated, mundane, or nerdy.

Unsheathing-Sword.name: Unsheathing-Sword

text_options.description: This area on the fully unsheathed katana represents the final, unrestrained, and often lengthy response. Text here is typically a detailed rant, a multi-paragraph rebuttal, or an aggressive counter-argument to the initial provocative statement, signifying that the user has unleashed their full opinion.

On the slightly drawn blade, this text represents the initial, restrained reaction or warning. It's usually a short, sharp phrase like 'Excuse me?' or a pointed question, indicating that the initial statement has been noticed and is being challenged, but the full response is still being held back.

This top panel is the setup for the meme. The text placed here is the trigger or catalyst—typically a controversial opinion, a 'hot take,' or a statement intended to provoke a strong reaction from the person represented by the sword-wielder.

Unsheathing-Sword.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as 'Unsheathing the Katana' or 'Master's Teachings,' originates from the anime Bleach. It depicts a katana being slightly drawn from its sheath and then fully unsheathed. The meme illustrates an escalating reaction, where a provocative statement leads to a restrained warning, followed by a full-blown, often aggressive response, symbolizing someone preparing to unleash a lengthy argument or rebuttal online.

UNO-Draw-The-Whole-Deck.name: UNO-Draw-The-Whole-Deck

text_options.description: This area of the Uno card contains the text for the extreme penalty, in this case, "Draw the whole deck." This is the consequence that the person in the meme chooses to accept, emphasizing their strong aversion to the alternative action presented in the top panel.

This is the primary editable area where the meme creator places text describing a highly undesirable action or statement. The humor of the meme relies on this action being so repulsive that the person in the right panel would rather draw an entire deck of cards than comply with it.

UNO-Draw-The-Whole-Deck.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Uno Draw 25' or 'Draw the whole deck,' presents a difficult choice. The left panel shows a custom Uno card offering two options, while the right panel shows a person who has chosen the second, more arduous option: drawing a massive number of cards. The meme is used to humorously illustrate an extreme refusal to do something by showing a preference for an absurdly punishing alternative.

write-that-down.name: write-that-down

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, containing the iconic quote "Write that down, write that down!". It represents the reaction to the observation, conveying an urgent and often humorous desire to record the information just witnessed.

This top text area is used to describe the person, group, or situation that is being observed by SpongeBob. The text placed here sets up the context for the meme, presenting the action or idea that is considered so noteworthy or clever that it must be written down.

write-that-down.image_description: This meme features SpongeBob SquarePants looking intently through binoculars while his friend Patrick Star stands ready with a notepad, seemingly about to jot down notes. Originating from the show SpongeBob SquarePants, this format is used to humorously highlight a clever idea, a useful piece of information, or a surprising observation that is worth remembering. SpongeBob represents someone discovering something profound or noteworthy, while Patrick is poised to record this newfound wisdom.

how-i-sleep-homer-simpson.name: how-i-sleep-homer-simpson

text_options.description: This text label is placed over Homer's body, identifying the person or group that is peacefully and ignorantly sleeping. It often says 'Me' or another identifier for the subject who is avoiding the problem.

Positioned at the top of the image, this text describes the pressing issue, responsibility, or chaotic situation that is being ignored by the sleeping person. The humor comes from the stark contrast between the serious problem described here and Homer's peaceful state.

how-i-sleep-homer-simpson.image_description: This meme, known as 'Homer Simpson Sleeping' or 'Homer in Bed,' features the character Homer Simpson from 'The Simpsons' sleeping soundly and peacefully. He is tucked into a purple blanket, looking completely content and untroubled. The meme is used to humorously depict a person or entity blissfully ignoring a major problem, responsibility, or chaotic situation, highlighting the contrast between their tranquility and the severity of the issue.

Impossibru-Guy-Original.name: Impossibru-Guy-Original

text_options.description: The bottom text area is typically used for the punchline or the user's dismissive response. This text directly expresses the contempt or disbelief shown by the face, often with a sarcastic or blunt retort like "B*tch, please" or a statement pointing out the obvious flaw in the setup text.

The top text area sets up the meme by presenting a statement, question, or scenario that the user finds foolish, naive, or worthy of ridicule. This provides the context for the dismissive reaction embodied by Yao Ming's face.

Impossibru-Guy-Original.image_description: This meme features a photo of retired basketball player Yao Ming making a contorted, strained face during a press conference. Known as the "B*tch Please" or "Yao Ming Face," this image is used to convey a strong sense of dismissal, disbelief, or contempt towards a preceding statement. It functions as a classic reaction face to express that something is incredibly stupid or obvious, effectively shutting down a conversation.

Troll-Face.name: Troll-Face

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline or the reveal of the troll. This text explains the prank, the misleading outcome, or the mischievous intent behind the setup presented in the top text.

The top text of the meme, which typically sets up a scenario or poses a question. This text is designed to be the 'bait,' luring the reader into a false sense of security or a specific line of thinking before the troll is revealed.

Troll-Face.image_description: This image features the 'Trollface,' a character from the rage comic series popular in the early 2010s. The crudely drawn black-and-white face has a massive, mischievous grin, signifying an internet troll or the act of 'trolling.' This meme is used to represent someone who has successfully played a prank, made a deliberately provocative statement, or tricked someone online for their own amusement.

We-Will-Rebuild.name: We-Will-Rebuild

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, representing the disappointing or chaotic reality. This text works in conjunction with the image of the fallen chair to signify failure or things going wrong, creating a humorous juxtaposition with the setup text at the top.

The top text sets up a scenario, often describing a plan, expectation, or a positive state. It establishes the 'before' or the ideal situation that is about to be contrasted by the image and the bottom text.

We-Will-Rebuild.image_description: This meme, known as 'Fallen Chair' or 'My Hopes and Dreams,' depicts a serene backyard scene with a plastic patio set where one chair has dramatically fallen over. The image is used to represent failure, disappointment, or plans going awry. The fallen chair symbolizes the catastrophic or unexpected outcome in contrast to the otherwise calm setting, often representing a person's plans versus reality.

Jack-Nicholson-The-Shining-Snow.name: Jack-Nicholson-The-Shining-Snow

text_options.description: This text box labels Jack Torrance, the subject of the meme. It typically contains a label like 'Me' or describes the person/entity that is enduring the long wait or cold, acting as the punchline to the setup in the top text.
The top text box provides the context or setup for the joke. It usually describes a scenario or a promise that leads to a long, frustrating wait, setting up the punchline below.

Jack-Nicholson-The-Shining-Snow.image_description: This meme features Jack Torrance (played by Jack Nicholson) frozen to death in the snow, a famous scene from the 1980 horror film 'The Shining'. The image is used to humorously represent situations of waiting for an extremely long time, feeling very cold, or being ignored and left out. The frozen, desperate expression on Jack's face perfectly captures the feeling of being stuck in an unpleasant or prolonged situation.

Frustrated-Boromir.name: Frustrated-Boromir

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This line describes the action or task that is surprisingly difficult, completing the phrase started in the top text. For example, '...get just one snack from the kitchen.'
The top text of the meme, which is almost always the setup phrase 'One does not simply'. This text establishes the recognizable format of the meme, referencing the original quote from the movie.

Frustrated-Boromir.image_description: This meme features the character Boromir, played by Sean Bean, from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring.' The image captures a moment of weary gravity from the Council of Elrond scene. Known as the 'One Does Not Simply' meme, it is used to humorously emphasize the unexpected difficulty or complexity of a seemingly simple task, parodying Boromir's famous line, 'One does not simply walk into Mordor.'

Sudden-Clarity-Clarence.name: Sudden-Clarity-Clarence

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image delivers the epiphany or the "sudden clarity" moment. This is the punchline of the meme, revealing a simple, often humorous, but surprisingly insightful observation that reframes the idea presented in the top text.

The text at the top of the image serves as the setup for the punchline. It usually presents a common situation, a well-known concept, or a seemingly simple premise that the viewer takes for granted, establishing the context for the realization.

Sudden-Clarity-Clarence.image_description: This meme, known as "Sudden Clarity Clarence," features a young man at a crowded party with a look of profound realization on his face. The image captures a moment of unexpected epiphany amidst a chaotic environment. It is typically used to share "shower thoughts" or simple, yet mind-blowing, realizations about everyday life, with the top text setting up a common idea and the bottom text delivering the surprising insight.

Michael-Jackson-Popcorn.name: Michael-Jackson-Popcorn

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Michael Jackson's body and typically labels the person or group who is enjoying the drama. Common labels include "Me," "The internet," or any other entity that is observing the situation with amusement.
This top text box provides the context for the drama being observed. It describes the argument, fight, or chaotic situation that Michael Jackson (representing the viewer) is watching so intently.

Michael-Jackson-Popcorn.image_description: This meme features a still image of Michael Jackson eating popcorn while watching a movie in his 1983 music video for "Thriller". The image is widely used as a reaction GIF or meme to represent someone eagerly and entertainingly watching drama, arguments, or chaos unfold, particularly online. It perfectly captures the feeling of being a spectator to a conflict, enjoying the spectacle from a safe distance.

Chuck-Norris-Approves.name: Chuck-Norris-Approves

text_options.description: The bottom text, often positioned near his nameplate, typically serves as the punchline or the main part of the "Chuck Norris fact." It delivers the core exaggerated claim about his god-like power or abilities, concluding the joke set up by the top text.

The top text area is used for the setup or the beginning of a "Chuck Norris fact." This text introduces a scenario or a concept that will be comically resolved by highlighting Chuck Norris's supposed omnipotence in the bottom text.

Chuck-Norris-Approves.image_description: This meme features actor and martial artist Chuck Norris giving a thumbs-up, and is the visual basis for the "Chuck Norris facts" internet phenomenon. These "facts" are satirical, hyperbolic claims about Norris's toughness, masculinity, and superhuman abilities, presented as absolute truths. The meme format uses this image as a backdrop for these absurd statements, with his confident and approving gesture adding to the humor.

Baby-Godfather.name: Baby-Godfather

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline or the core statement. This text typically contains the "offer," the command, or the witty remark that solidifies the baby's boss-like persona, often directly referencing "The Godfather" with phrases like "I'm gonna make him an offer he can't refuse."

The top text of the meme, used to set up the situation or pose a question. This line establishes the context for the baby's authoritative response, creating a scenario where a boss-like figure is needed to take control.

Baby-Godfather.image_description: This meme, often called "Baby Godfather" or "Tuxedo Baby," features a baby in a full black tuxedo with a bow tie, looking off to the side with a serious, plotting expression while pointing downwards. The image humorously juxtaposes the baby's innocent appearance with the demeanor of a powerful mob boss, reminiscent of characters from "The Godfather" film. It's typically used to make a demand, present an ultimatum, or make a clever, authoritative statement in a funny, non-threatening way.

Good-Guy-Putin.name: Good-Guy-Putin

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline or the main command of the meme. This text is emphasized by Putin's pointing gesture and often uses an authoritative tone or a humorous, stereotypical Russian phrasing to make a point.
The top text area typically contains the setup for the joke or statement. It presents a scenario, a question, or a general observation that the bottom text will react to or provide a punchline for.

Good-Guy-Putin.image_description: This meme features Russian President Vladimir Putin at a press conference, pointing forward with a pen and a serious expression. The image is used as a reaction macro to make a declarative, often humorous or ironic, statement. The format typically involves a setup in the top text and a punchline or command in the bottom text, emphasized by Putin's authoritative gesture.

Peter-Parker-Cry.name: Peter-Parker-Cry

text_options.description: This text box is placed over J. Jonah Jameson's explosive laughter. It contains the punchline, which is a direct and mocking dismissal of Peter's idea from box 2. Often, it's simply the sound of laughter or a sarcastic question like 'You're serious?'.

This text box aligns with J. Jonah Jameson's pensive expression as he seemingly considers Peter's statement. The text here, if present, is usually a short phrase like 'You're serious?' or 'Let me get this straight...' to emphasize his brief moment of contemplation before the laughter.
This text box is for Peter Parker's response. It contains the central idea, suggestion, or statement that will be the subject of ridicule. This text is often something earnest, naive, or hopeful.
This text box corresponds to J. Jonah Jameson's initial dialogue. It typically contains a question or prompt that sets up the conversation, asking Peter Parker for his idea or opinion.

Peter-Parker-Cry.image_description: This multi-panel meme format originates from the Sam Raimi 'Spider-Man' films, featuring J. Jonah Jameson and Peter Parker. It illustrates a scenario where a person (Peter Parker) presents an idea or statement, which is initially considered and then met with hysterical laughter and ridicule by another (J. Jonah Jameson). The final panel, showing a crying Peter Parker, represents the devastating emotional impact of this rejection, making the meme perfect for mocking naive or absurd proposals.

Angry-Toddler.name: Angry-Toddler

text_options.description: Positioned at the bottom of the image, this text typically represents the girl's internal monologue, a witty comeback, or the mischievous action she is about to take. Its placement near her clenched fist reinforces the sense of determination or satisfaction conveyed by her expression.

Located at the top of the image, this text describes a preceding event, a statement by another person, or a situation that provokes the girl's reaction. It sets up the context for her smug or annoyed expression.

Angry-Toddler.image_description: This black and white photo features a young girl with a mischievous and determined expression, looking sideways with a pursed-lip frown. Often referred to as 'Side-eyeing girl' or 'Pouty girl', her clenched fist and side-glance are used to convey feelings of petty revenge, smug satisfaction, or plotting something devious. The meme typically contrasts a situation described in the top text with the girl's silent, judgmental, or triumphant reaction.

Batman-Smiles.name: Batman-Smiles

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the image of Batman smiling. It describes the preferred, superior, or more satisfying option that elicits the character's subtle approval, forming the punchline of the meme.

This text box corresponds to the top panel where Batman has a serious expression. The text here typically describes a conventional, expected, or less appealing scenario that sets up the contrast for the second panel.

Batman-Smiles.image_description: This two-panel meme features Michael Keaton as Batman, showing a contrast in his expression. The top image displays a serious, stoic Batman, while the bottom image shows him with a slight, knowing smirk. The format is used to compare two things, with the serious expression representing a standard or undesirable option and the smiling expression representing a preferred, clever, or more satisfying alternative.

Smilin-Biden.name: Smilin-Biden

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline or the main statement. This text often represents what Joe Biden is 'saying' or thinking, directly responding to the setup in the top text. Its placement at the bottom, combined with his pointing gesture, makes it feel like a direct, conclusive, and often humorous remark to the viewer.

The top text of the meme, which typically provides the setup or context for the joke. This line introduces a situation, a question, or a general observation that Joe Biden's expression and the bottom text will then react to. It establishes the premise that the punchline will pay off.

Smilin-Biden.image_description: This meme features a photo of Joe Biden, often referred to as 'Uncle Joe' or 'Diamond Joe,' smiling warmly and pointing directly at the viewer. The gesture and expression create a friendly, approving, and confident tone, as if he's affirming something or sharing an inside joke. This image is widely used as a reaction image or in a top-text, bottom-text format to express agreement, make a relatable point, or deliver a lighthearted punchline.

Hey-Internet.name: Hey-Internet

text_options.description: Positioned over the stampeding horde of monsters, this label identifies the collective group or community that shares the intense desire. It broadens the joke from an individual's reaction to a massive, frenzied response from a specific fanbase or demographic.
This text box is placed over the main monstrous character's face. It typically contains a label for the person or entity experiencing this intense desire, acting as the meme's central punchline.

This area, above the excited simple character, is where the object of desire is named. It's the catalyst for the entire comic's reaction, often something niche, specific, or seemingly mundane that unexpectedly inspires a powerful craving.

Hey-Internet.image_description: This multi-panel rage comic meme depicts an extreme and monstrous desire for an item. The first panel shows a simple character excitedly pointing at something, which then triggers a transformation into a hyper-detailed, grotesque creature in the second panel, symbolizing intense want. The final panel shows a horde of these monsters stampeding, representing a whole community sharing this overwhelming desire. The meme is used to humorously exaggerate a strong craving for a product, idea, or piece of media.

RPG-Fan.name: RPG-Fan

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image, near the character's hands on the keyboard, describes an incredibly difficult, complex, or time-consuming task that the person is willing to do, usually within a video game or other niche hobby. This text highlights the character's intense focus and dedication to their virtual pursuits, serving as the punchline that contrasts with the simple task mentioned at the top.

The text at the top of the image typically describes a simple, mundane, or necessary real-life task that the character is avoiding or finds too challenging. This sets up the premise of the meme, contrasting the person's perceived laziness or incompetence in daily life with their dedication to gaming.

RPG-Fan.image_description: This meme features a character from the animated show South Park, from the episode "Make Love, Not Warcraft." The character, an overweight man with glasses and messy hair, is shown sitting intently at his computer in a cluttered room, representing the stereotype of a hardcore, "no-life" gamer. The meme is typically used in a two-panel format to contrast a simple real-life task that is being avoided with a far more complex or time-consuming achievement in a video game. It humorously highlights skewed priorities and dedication to virtual worlds over reality.

Dad-Joke-Dog.name: Dad-Joke-Dog

text_options.description: This text, located in the middle panel, provides the punchline to the joke. The dog's shifty, sideways glance in this panel perfectly complements the delivery of a cheesy or awkward punchline, setting up the final reaction shot.

This text, placed in the top panel, serves as the setup for a pun or dad joke. The dog is shown leaning towards the baby, as if whispering the first part of the joke, initiating the conversational format of the meme.

Dad-Joke-Dog.image_description: This three-panel meme, known as "Pun Dog" or "Dad Joke Dog," depicts a dog telling a joke to an unimpressed baby. The first panel shows the dog leaning in to tell the joke, the second shows the dog looking away after the punchline, and the third shows the dog's innocent expression and the baby's deadpan reaction. The format is used to deliver cheesy puns and dad jokes, with the baby's expression representing the audience's groan-worthy reaction.

LIGAF.name: LIGAF

text_options.description: The text in this bottom section represents the calm, indifferent, or even triumphant individual or entity amidst chaos. This is typically the punchline, often labeled as "me," showing the person who is either responsible for or enjoying the chaotic situation described above.

The text in this top section sets up the scenario by describing a chaotic, problematic, or disastrous situation. This text represents the external turmoil or the suffering of others that the person in the meme is ignoring.

LIGAF.image_description: This meme, known as "Man Sitting by Fire" or "Bonfire Guy," shows a man with a mustache sitting calmly with a drink in front of a roaring bonfire in a snowy environment. The meme is used to represent a person who is either the cause of a chaotic situation or is completely unbothered by it. The humor derives from the contrast between the man's serene demeanor and the surrounding chaos, which is described in the text overlays.

I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing-Dog.name: I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing-Dog

text_options.description: This is the punchline area. The text here reveals the subject's complete lack of knowledge, with the classic phrase being 'I Have No Idea What I'm Doing'. It's placed at the bottom to deliver the humorous conclusion to the scenario set up by the top text.

This is the setup text. It typically describes a complex or professional situation that the subject has been placed in, creating an expectation of competence. For example, 'I'm a chemistry major now' or 'They asked me to debug the code'.

I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing-Dog.image_description: This meme, known as 'I Have No Idea What I'm Doing' or 'Science Dog,' features a golden retriever wearing safety goggles in a laboratory setting. The image humorously captures the feeling of being completely unqualified or clueless about a task, despite appearing to be engaged in it. The dog's cheerful but vacant expression perfectly contrasts with the serious scientific environment, making it a relatable symbol for impostor syndrome or navigating unfamiliar situations.
I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing-Dog.display_name: I Have No Idea What I Am Doing Dog

Internet-Explorer.name: Internet-Explorer

text_options.description: The bottom text represents the punchline or the slow response from Internet Explorer. It typically contains a statement about an event or trend that is extremely old news, delivered as if it's a recent discovery, highlighting the browser's perceived slowness.

The top text serves as the setup or prompt for the meme. It often poses a question or describes a situation to which Internet Explorer is reacting, setting the stage for the delayed and outdated punchline below.

Internet-Explorer.image_description: This meme features the logo for the Internet Explorer web browser, a blue 'e' with a gold ring. It is widely used to symbolize slowness, being outdated, or being late to a trend, referencing the browser's historical reputation for poor performance. The humor comes from applying this concept of being comically behind the times to various situations, people, or news.

You-The-Real-MVP.name: You-The-Real-MVP

text_options.description: This bottom text box identifies the person, group, or object being praised. It serves as the subject of the meme, naming who 'the real MVP' is in a particular scenario.

This top text box contains the message of gratitude, often directly quoting or paraphrasing the famous line, 'You the real MVP'. It explains why the subject mentioned at the bottom is being appreciated.

You-The-Real-MVP.image_description: This meme features NBA player Kevin Durant looking emotional during his 2014 MVP acceptance speech, where he famously thanked his mother, calling her 'the real MVP'. The image is used to express sincere gratitude and appreciation, often towards unsung heroes or for everyday acts of kindness. While typically heartfelt, it can also be used sarcastically to thank someone for something trivial or unhelpful.

Pissed-Off-Obama.name: Pissed-Off-Obama

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed near Obama's pointing finger to reinforce the gesture. This is the punchline of the meme, directly addressing or accusing the viewer in response to the setup in the top text.
The top text, located above Obama's head. This area typically contains the setup for the joke, often a question or a statement describing a scenario (e.g., 'Who is awesome?').

Pissed-Off-Obama.image_description: This meme features a close-up image of former U.S. President Barack Obama pointing directly at the viewer with a serious, focused expression. The meme is typically used in a two-panel format to directly accuse or call out the reader in a humorous way. The setup is presented in the top text, and the pointing gesture combined with the bottom text delivers the punchline, implicating the viewer.

OMG-Cat.name: OMG-Cat

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, typically used for the punchline or the shocking revelation that causes the cat's surprised reaction. The text here delivers the unexpected twist or surprising information that justifies the cat's expression.
This is the top text area, which sets up the context or initial situation for the meme. It's the first part of the joke or statement, leading to the punchline at the bottom.

OMG-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as "Surprised Cat" or "Gasping Cat," features a close-up image of a white and grey cat with wide, startled eyes and its mouth agape in a gasp. The cat's expression of pure shock or disbelief is the central focus of the meme. It's commonly used as a reaction image to express astonishment, being caught off guard, or hearing something unbelievable.

I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing.name: I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It almost universally reads "I have no idea what I'm doing" or a close variation, revealing the subject's true incompetence and creating the humor.

The top text of the meme, which sets up the scenario. This text typically describes a situation that requires specialized skills or knowledge, placing the subject (the dog) in a position of responsibility they are not equipped for.

I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing.image_description: This meme, often called "I Have No Idea What I'm Doing" dog, features a Siberian Husky sitting upright in a chair at a computer desk, with its paws on the keyboard. The dog's intense, focused expression humorously contrasts with the absurdity of the situation. The meme is used to represent someone who is placed in a complex or high-stakes situation where they are completely unqualified but are trying to look competent.
I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-Am-Doing.display_name: I Have No Idea What I Am Doing

Warning-Sign.name: Warning-Sign

text_options.description: This is the bottom panel of the warning sign, which serves as the punchline. The text here describes the often absurd, disproportionate, or nonsensical consequence or "penalty" for the action mentioned in the panel above. The humor is derived from the contrast between the serious warning format and the ridiculous outcome.

This is the top panel directly under the "Warning" header, used to set up the joke. The text here typically describes a specific action, situation, or statement that the sign is warning against. It establishes the context or the "cause" for the humorous consequence that follows in the panel below.

Warning-Sign.image_description: This is a customizable warning sign meme template. The format mimics a standard yellow and black hazard sign with a red "Warning" label at the top. The meme's humor comes from the user-defined text in the two panels below, creating a cause-and-effect joke. Typically, the top panel describes a mundane action or situation, while the bottom panel presents an absurd, exaggerated, or ironic consequence.

Bad-Luck-Bear.name: Bad-Luck-Bear

text_options.description: The bottom text box is the primary location for the meme's caption. The text here typically describes what the bear is waiting for, providing the specific context for its patient and thoughtful pose. This punchline is what makes the meme relatable, connecting the bear's situation to a common human experience of anticipation.

The top text box serves as a potential setup or title for the meme. While less common for this specific format, which often relies on a single bottom caption, text here would establish the general situation or scenario. For example, it might state a broad condition, with the bottom text providing the specific, often humorous, outcome or object of waiting.

Bad-Luck-Bear.image_description: This meme, often called "Waiting Bear" or "Picnic Bear," features a large black bear sitting patiently at a picnic table with a contemplative expression. The bear's human-like posture creates a humorous and relatable image. The meme is typically used to express a feeling of waiting, anticipation, or patience for something to happen, often in a slightly lonely or pensive context.

Vladimir-Putin.name: Vladimir-Putin

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which serves as the punchline of the meme. It contains the absurd or illogical conclusion to the setup presented in the top text. The text here often relates to Putin's gesture of measuring something small, reinforcing the simplistic or flawed nature of the 'advice' being given.

This is the top text area, which sets up the premise or question for the meme. It's the first part of a two-part statement, often beginning with a phrase like "You see, Ivan..." to frame the subsequent text as a piece of advice or explanation.

Vladimir-Putin.image_description: This meme features Russian President Vladimir Putin sitting at a desk, gesturing with his hands as if explaining something simple or small. The format is commonly known as "You See, Ivan" or "Putin Explains." It's typically used to present a piece of flawed, absurd, or comically simplistic logic as a serious explanation, often playing on Russian stereotypes for humorous effect.

Kim-Jong-Un-Sad.name: Kim-Jong-Un-Sad

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline. It describes the disappointing reality or the negative outcome that crushes the hope established in the top text, thus justifying Kim Jong Un's exaggerated expression of sorrow.

The top text area sets up the scenario by describing a positive expectation or a hopeful situation. This text establishes what the user wanted to happen, creating a contrast with the disappointing outcome.

Kim-Jong-Un-Sad.image_description: This meme features a still image of North Korean leader Kim Jong Un crying, taken from footage of his father's funeral. The image is used as a reaction to express exaggerated sadness or disappointment over trivial or relatable first-world problems. The humor comes from the dramatic display of emotion being applied to mundane situations.

Yo-Mamas-So-Fat.name: Yo-Mamas-So-Fat

text_options.description: This is the reaction part of the meme, showing the boy spitting milk. It functions as the visual punchline. Text is rarely placed here, as the image itself conveys the strong reaction to the content presented in the panel above.

This top panel serves as the setup for the meme. It is almost always replaced with a different image, a surprising text post, or a shocking headline that is meant to cause the reaction seen below. The content here provides the context that makes the boy's spit-take funny.

Yo-Mamas-So-Fat.image_description: This meme, known as "Milk Spit" or "Cereal Guy Spit Take," shows a young boy dramatically spitting a mouthful of milk across a table in surprise. It is a classic reaction image used to express shock, disbelief, or disgust in response to some preceding content. The meme is typically used in a two-panel format, with the top panel containing the surprising stimulus and the bottom panel showing this explosive reaction.

Computer-Guy.name: Computer-Guy

text_options.description: This area, typically placed over the computer screen, shows the content that the character is reacting to. This is the catalyst for the meme, often depicting something strange, cringeworthy, or something a parent would find questionable on their child's computer.

The top caption area sets the scene or provides context for the character's action. It usually describes what the character is doing or thinking, for example, "Sees son's search history," establishing the premise for his intense reaction.

Computer-Guy.image_description: This meme, often called "Stare Dad" or "Computer Reaction Guy," features a simple line-drawn character with a goatee staring intently and with disapproval at a computer monitor. It's the first panel of a multi-panel comic, setting up a reaction to something seen online. The meme is used to express shock, confusion, or disapproval towards online content, with the character's intense gaze representing the user's strong reaction before they confront someone about it in a subsequent panel.

Ron-Swanson.name: Ron-Swanson

text_options.description: The text in the bottom box represents Ron Swanson's direct and often curt response or punchline. It's his answer to the question or statement posed in the top text, reflecting his minimalist and traditionalist character. Common responses are simple, like 'No,' or a short, declarative statement.

The text in the top box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically contains a question, a modern concept, or a statement that Ron Swanson's character would find ridiculous, unnecessary, or contemptible. This text prompts his deadpan reaction in the bottom panel.

Ron-Swanson.image_description: This meme features Ron Swanson, a character from the TV show 'Parks and Recreation,' known for his deadpan humor and libertarian views. He stares intently at the viewer with a serious, unimpressed expression. The format is typically used to present a question or statement at the top, to which Ron Swanson provides a blunt, dismissive, or comically simplistic answer at the bottom, reflecting his staunch, no-nonsense personality.

Monkey-Business.name: Monkey-Business

text_options.description: This area, covering the gorilla and the desk, typically represents the subject of the meme. The text here is often self-referential, like "Me" or "My brain," identifying the person who feels out of their depth or comically inept.

The text in this upper region provides the context or the challenge that the subject is facing. It usually describes the complex task, situation, or piece of information that is causing the confusion, for example, "trying to understand a new software" or "when someone explains crypto to me."

Monkey-Business.image_description: This meme features a gorilla in a yellow polo shirt sitting in an office cubicle, intently focused on a laptop. The image humorously represents someone feeling primitive, confused, or incompetent when faced with a modern or complex task, particularly in a work or tech-related context. It's often used to express a feeling of not knowing what one is doing, akin to an ape trying to use a computer.

Babushkas-On-Facebook.name: Babushkas-On-Facebook

text_options.description: Text in this area, placed over the laptop, describes the subject matter the women are looking at. This is the setup of the meme, presenting a piece of online content, a modern trend, or a concept that would be unfamiliar or shocking to an older, more traditional group.

Text placed over the women represents their collective reaction, thought, or comment. This serves as the punchline, typically expressing a humorous misunderstanding, naive question, or old-fashioned judgment about the content shown on the laptop in box 0.

Babushkas-On-Facebook.image_description: This meme, often called "Babushkas on the Internet" or "Russian Grannies," features four elderly women in traditional headscarves gathered around a laptop outdoors. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of these traditional figures with modern technology. The meme is used to represent people who are new to, or out of touch with, the internet, social media, or contemporary trends, often reacting with confusion, curiosity, or outdated judgment.

Socially-Awkward-Awesome-Penguin.name: Socially-Awkward-Awesome-Penguin

text_options.description: Located in the bottom red section, this text describes the socially awkward, embarrassing, or failed part of the situation. It serves as the punchline, undermining the initial success described in the top text and creating a relatable moment of social failure.

Positioned in the top blue section, this text describes a socially successful, cool, or confident action. This part of the meme sets up the "socially awesome" scenario, establishing a positive social context before the awkward twist.

Socially-Awkward-Awesome-Penguin.image_description: This meme is known as "Socially Awesome/Awkward Penguin." It features a penguin against a background split into a blue top half and a red bottom half. The format is used to describe a two-part social situation: the top describes a socially successful or "awesome" moment, while the bottom describes a subsequent socially awkward or embarrassing action. The humor arises from the relatable contrast between a moment of confidence and the cringeworthy follow-up.

Interupting-Kanye.name: Interupting-Kanye

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline of the meme. This is where Kanye West's interjection is written, stating what he believes is superior to the topic mentioned above, completing his famous line '...had one of the best videos of all time!'

The top text box sets up the premise of the meme. It represents the original statement or topic being discussed, corresponding to Taylor Swift's acceptance speech, which is about to be interrupted by Kanye's opinion.

Interupting-Kanye.image_description: This meme captures the infamous moment from the 2009 MTV VMAs where Kanye West interrupts Taylor Swift's acceptance speech. Known as 'Kanye Interrupts' or 'Imma let you finish,' the format is used to humorously interject with a strong, often unsolicited, opinion or preference. Kanye represents the interruption, while Taylor symbolizes the original topic being overshadowed.

Deadpool-Surprised.name: Deadpool-Surprised

text_options.description: This bottom caption area typically identifies the person or group making the obvious statement. It sets up the context for Deadpool's sarcastic reaction.

The top text box contains the actual statement or action that is supposedly shocking. This text is the punchline, representing something incredibly obvious or predictable that prompts Deadpool's mock surprise.

Deadpool-Surprised.image_description: This meme features the Marvel character Deadpool holding his hands to his face in a gesture of exaggerated, sarcastic shock. The image is a still from the movie "Deadpool" and captures the character's signature fourth-wall-breaking and meta-humor. It is typically used as a reaction image to express feigned surprise at an obvious statement, a predictable outcome, or something that is not shocking at all.

Burn-Kitty.name: Burn-Kitty

text_options.description: This is the bottom text location, acting as the punchline. The text here represents Grumpy Cat's cynical or negative commentary on the situation established by the top text, directly reflecting her famously unimpressed demeanor.
This is the top text location, which sets up the context for the meme. The text here typically describes a situation, event, or a statement that Grumpy Cat is reacting to with displeasure or apathy.

Burn-Kitty.image_description: This meme features the internet-famous "Grumpy Cat" (Tardar Sauce) photoshopped in front of a burning house. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the chaotic, destructive scene with the cat's iconic, perpetually unimpressed facial expression. This format is used to express extreme apathy, cynicism, or a dark sense of satisfaction in response to a disastrous or annoying situation, often implying the subject is unbothered by or even caused the chaos.

Evil-Cows.name: Evil-Cows

text_options.description: Text in this bottom section labels the cows. It typically represents the person, group, or entity that is calmly and blissfully ignoring the major problem depicted in the background. Common labels include "Me," "My company," or any subject that is remaining oblivious to a crisis.

Text placed over the fire at the top of the image describes the disaster, chaos, or overwhelming problem being ignored. This could be anything from "My responsibilities" and "Final exams" to broader issues like "The economy" or "2020," providing the context for the cows' absurd calmness.

Evil-Cows.image_description: This meme features two cows standing calmly in a grassy field while a large, raging fire burns in the background. The stark contrast between the serene cows and the chaotic fire creates a humorous and absurd visual. The meme is used to represent a state of denial, apathy, or being completely unfazed by a surrounding crisis or overwhelming problem.

You-Dont-Say.name: You-Dont-Say

text_options.description: This area covers the lower part of the character's drawing. In a multi-panel version of this meme, the preceding panel, which sets up the joke, would be located here or above the image. That panel typically contains an obvious statement or question that the 'You Don't Say?' face is sarcastically reacting to.

This is the punchline of the meme, containing the text 'YOU DON'T SAY?'. This sarcastic rhetorical question is the core of the meme's identity, used to express feigned surprise in response to a blatantly obvious statement.

You-Dont-Say.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white rage comic drawing of actor Nicolas Cage from the film 'Vampire's Kiss,' known as the 'You Don't Say?' face. The character has a wide-eyed, incredulous expression. It's used as a sarcastic reaction to an extremely obvious statement, feigning surprise to mock the person who said it.

Chuck-Norris-With-Guns.name: Chuck-Norris-With-Guns

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It completes the hyperbolic "fact" started in the top text, delivering the humorous and absurd conclusion about Chuck Norris's supposed abilities or actions.

The top text of the meme, which functions as the setup for a "Chuck Norris Fact." This line typically introduces a premise or begins a statement that will be resolved with an absurdly exaggerated punchline at the bottom.

Chuck-Norris-With-Guns.image_description: This meme features a promotional shot of actor Chuck Norris holding two guns against a red and blue starburst background, a common format for early 2000s "Advice Animal" memes. Known as "Chuck Norris Facts," the meme humorously attributes superhuman, god-like, or absurdly masculine feats to the actor, parodying the tough-guy persona he cultivated in action films. The format is used to create hyperbolic statements about his strength, invincibility, and overall manliness, presenting them as factual statements.

NPC.name: NPC

text_options.description: Text in this lower position typically serves as a label for the NPC character. It might identify the specific person, group, or ideology being mocked, for example, 'The Media' or 'Average Twitter User'.

Located over the character's head, this text represents the NPC's internal monologue or 'programming.' It usually contains a simplistic, repetitive, or popular catchphrase that the meme creator is criticizing as unthinking, thereby reinforcing the idea that the character is not capable of original thought.

NPC.image_description: This meme features the NPC Wojak, a grey, expressionless character derived from the original Wojak. The term 'NPC' (Non-Player Character) is used to satirize people who allegedly lack independent thought and simply repeat mainstream talking points, as if following a script. The meme is frequently used in online political discourse to dismiss opposing viewpoints as unoriginal and conformist.

DJ-Pauly-D.name: DJ-Pauly-D

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Pauly D's lower body and extended hand. It typically labels the person or group who is expressing strong rejection or disgust, often starting with "Me:" to personalize the reaction.
Located at the top of the image, this text describes the undesirable thing, concept, or situation that is causing the horrified reaction and being metaphorically pushed away.

DJ-Pauly-D.image_description: This meme features Pauly D from the reality TV show "Jersey Shore" looking horrified with wide eyes and an open mouth. He is extending his hand forward as if to forcefully push something away in disgust. The meme, often called "Pauly D Scared," is used to express strong aversion or rejection towards an idea, person, or situation.

1950s-Middle-Finger.name: 1950s-Middle-Finger

text_options.description: The bottom text typically delivers the punchline, often a blunt or sarcastic response that verbally reinforces the obscene gesture shown in the image.
The top text sets up the context or describes a situation, person, or idea that the meme creator wishes to express contempt or defiance towards.

1950s-Middle-Finger.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white, retro-style illustration of a smiling man in a suit giving the middle finger. The character, often seen as a generic 1950s-era figure, combines a cheerful demeanor with an obscene gesture. This creates a sarcastic and defiant tone, making it a popular reaction image to express contempt, disagreement, or a blunt 'fuck you' to a preceding statement or situation.

Castaway-Fire.name: Castaway-Fire

text_options.description: This bottom text, placed over the fire and stick, describes the triumphant creation or the successful outcome of the struggle. It represents the 'fire' that the user has created, which is often a simple but hard-won achievement, completing the punchline of the meme.

The top text sets up the context of the meme, typically describing a long and arduous struggle or a challenging situation the user has faced. This text establishes the effort and difficulty that makes the final achievement, shown in the image, so significant.

Castaway-Fire.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of Tom Hanks as Chuck Noland in the 2000 film 'Cast Away'. The image captures the iconic moment when, after much struggle, he successfully creates fire, shouting in triumph. The meme is used to express immense pride and excitement over accomplishing a difficult task, often one that seems simple to others, like fixing a bug in code or assembling furniture correctly.

Sexy-Railroad-Spiderman.name: Sexy-Railroad-Spiderman

text_options.description: This text box, located at the bottom of the image, typically represents the person or entity being tempted or lured. This subject is looking up at the tempting offer represented by Spider-Man and the text above.
This text box, positioned at the top, describes the tempting object, action, or idea. Spider-Man's alluring pose personifies this temptation, making it the 'bait' for the subject below.

Sexy-Railroad-Spiderman.image_description: This meme, known as 'Seductive Spider-Man' or 'Sexy Spider-Man,' originates from the 1960s Spider-Man animated series. It features the superhero lying in a comically suggestive pose on train tracks, looking back at the viewer. The meme is used to humorously depict a person, object, or concept trying to tempt or lure someone into doing something, often something they know they shouldn't.

Eye-Of-Sauron.name: Eye-Of-Sauron

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It describes the action or task that is supposedly simple but is, in fact, very difficult, complicated, or impossible, completing the phrase from the top text.
The top text of the meme, which sets up the joke. It almost always begins with the phrase "One does not simply..." to introduce a seemingly straightforward task.

Eye-Of-Sauron.image_description: This is the "One Does Not Simply Walk into Mordor" meme, featuring a still from "The Lord of the Rings" of the Eye of Sauron over its tower in Mordor. The meme is based on a line spoken by the character Boromir and is used to humorously point out that a task is much more difficult or complex than it sounds. The ominous imagery of Mordor serves as a visual metaphor for the perceived difficulty of the task mentioned in the text.

Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Black.name: Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Black

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the second part of the phrase, often starting with 'AND'. It serves as the punchline or completes the instruction from the top box (e.g., 'AND CARRY ON'), delivering the core message of the parody.

This top text box typically contains the first part of the phrase, usually starting with 'KEEP' followed by a verb or adjective (e.g., 'KEEP CALM'). It sets up the main instruction or theme of the meme.

Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Black.image_description: This meme format is a parody of the iconic British "Keep Calm and Carry On" World War II propaganda poster. It features a stylized Tudor Crown above two lines of text on a plain background. The format is used to create humorous or motivational slogans by replacing the original text, often maintaining the "Keep [X] and [Y]" structure to give mock-serious advice.
Keep-Calm-And-Carry-On-Black.display_name: Keep Calm And Carry On Black

Actual-Advice-Mallard.name: Actual-Advice-Mallard

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which provides the actual piece of advice or the solution to the problem. This line completes the thought started in the top text and delivers the useful tip that is the core of the meme.
The top text of the meme, which typically sets up a common situation, problem, or context. This line serves as the premise for the helpful advice that will follow in the bottom text.

Actual-Advice-Mallard.image_description: This meme is known as "Actual Advice Mallard". It features a photograph of a male mallard duck swimming calmly in the water. Unlike many other "advice animal" memes that offer sarcastic or bad advice, this format is used to provide genuine, practical, and helpful life tips or hacks. The duck's serene appearance lends a sense of wisdom and sincerity to the advice given.

Mario-Hammer-Smash.name: Mario-Hammer-Smash

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the point of impact for Mario's hammer. It is used to label the thing being smashed, which could be an idea, a person, a trend, or an object that the meme creator dislikes or wants to see eliminated.

Located at the top of the image, this text box typically labels Mario himself. The text here identifies the person, entity, or force that is performing the act of smashing, providing the context for who is taking the decisive action.

Mario-Hammer-Smash.image_description: This meme features the character Mario, in the art style of the "Paper Mario" video game series, about to smash something with a large wooden hammer. The image is used to represent a person, group, or concept forcefully rejecting, destroying, or putting an end to something else. The powerful, decisive action of the hammer smash makes it a popular format for expressing strong disapproval or for depicting the 'banning' of certain content or ideas.

Scary-Harry.name: Scary-Harry

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically identifies the person, group, or entity experiencing the intense negative reaction depicted by Harry. It labels the subject who is suffering or in agony.

The top text box provides the context or describes the action/event that causes the extreme pain, frustration, or regret. It sets up the scenario to which the subject in the bottom text is reacting so strongly.

Scary-Harry.image_description: This meme features a still of the character Harry Dunne (played by Jeff Daniels) from the movie "Dumb and Dumber." In the scene, his tongue is stuck to a frozen pole, causing him to scream in agony with his eyes rolled back. The image is used as a reaction meme to express extreme pain, frustration, regret, or a visceral negative response to a situation.

Confused-Lebowski.name: Confused-Lebowski

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which contains the punchline or the specific grievance. This text completes the question started at the top, stating the action or belief that the user finds baffling or annoying.
The top text of the meme, which almost always reads "Am I the only one around here". This text serves as the setup for the user's rhetorical question or complaint.

Confused-Lebowski.image_description: This meme features Jeffrey "The Dude" Lebowski from the film 'The Big Lebowski,' looking slightly exasperated. The format is known as "Am I The Only One Around Here" and is used to express a personal opinion, complaint, or observation that the user feels is unique to them, often in a frustrated or rhetorical manner. The Dude's laid-back yet bewildered persona makes him the perfect vehicle for questioning seemingly absurd or annoying common behaviors.

Guinness-World-Record.name: Guinness-World-Record

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the words 'WORLD RECORDS'. In the meme format, this is where the specific, often absurd or humorous, achievement is described. This text serves as the punchline, defining the ridiculous 'record' being awarded.

This text box covers the word 'GUINNESS' at the top of the logo. In the meme, this space is typically edited to name the person, group, or entity that is supposedly receiving the fake world record. It identifies the subject of the joke or sarcastic praise.

Guinness-World-Record.image_description: This is the logo for Guinness World Records, an organization that catalogs and verifies world records. In meme culture, this logo is used as an exploitable template to create fake, humorous awards for absurd or mundane achievements. The meme format involves editing the text on the logo to sarcastically recognize a person or thing for an extreme, often negative or silly, 'world record,' lending a mock sense of officiality to the joke.

Michael-Phelps-Death-Stare.name: Michael-Phelps-Death-Stare

text_options.description: This text, placed over Michael Phelps, represents the person or entity feeling intense anger, focus, or annoyance. It is the protagonist of the meme, often labeled as "me" or a specific group reacting to a frustrating stimulus.

This area, positioned away from Phelps, typically describes the source of his frustration or the rival causing his intense reaction. It represents the antagonist or the annoying situation that the subject (Phelps) is mentally preparing to confront or is being irritated by.

Michael-Phelps-Death-Stare.image_description: The "Phelps Face" or "Angry Michael Phelps" meme features a close-up of American Olympic swimmer Michael Phelps looking intensely angry and focused. Captured at the 2016 Rio Olympics before a race, he is wearing a dark hooded jacket with headphones on, scowling at a rival off-screen. This meme is used to represent feelings of intense annoyance, silent rage, or extreme concentration in response to a frustrating person or situation.

Question-Rage-Face.name: Question-Rage-Face

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the face, typically contains the punchline 'I LIED' in a bold, impactful font. This text directly contradicts the setup text at the top, delivering the meme's core joke and revealing the speaker's true, deceptive intentions, which are mirrored in the character's smug expression.
