The top text, placed above the character's head, sets up the premise of the joke. It usually contains a statement, promise, or claim that seems sincere or plausible on its own, creating an expectation that will be subverted by the punchline below.

Question-Rage-Face.image_description: This meme features a black and white line drawing of a rage comic face known as the 'I Lied' face or 'Me Gusta Creepy'. The character has a smug, mischievous expression with shifty eyes looking up and to the side, and a curled, knowing smirk. This image is used to humorously admit to a lie, often in a two-part format where an initial statement is revealed to be false, conveying a sense of self-satisfied deception.

First-World-Problems-Cat.name: First-World-Problems-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over the cat's body, delivers the punchline. It describes the trivial 'first world problem' or minor inconvenience that makes the situation described in the top text frustrating, creating a humorous contrast amplified by the cat's sad expression.

The top text of the meme, located in the upper portion of the image, serves as the setup. It typically describes a generally positive or modern-day situation that will be humorously undermined by the text below.

First-World-Problems-Cat.image_description: This meme is known as "First World Problems Cat" or "Sad Cat." It features a fluffy white cat with striking blue eyes and a melancholic expression, resting its head. The meme is used to humorously complain about trivial, minor inconveniences experienced by people in wealthy, developed countries, contrasting a generally good situation with a petty frustration.

Chill-Out-Lemur.name: Chill-Out-Lemur

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline by providing a paranoid, conspiratorial, or deeply suspicious interpretation of the setup from the top text. It captures the lemur's "sudden realization" moment, turning an innocent situation into something alarming.
The top text sets up the joke by presenting a seemingly normal situation, statement, or observation. This line acts as the premise that will be twisted into a paranoid conclusion in the bottom text.

Chill-Out-Lemur.image_description: This meme, known as "Paranoid Lemur" or "Conspiracy Lemur," features a ring-tailed lemur with wide, intense eyes and a hand held up in a halting gesture. The image is used to express sudden paranoid thoughts, conspiracy theories, or unsettling realizations. The format typically presents a normal situation in the top text, followed by a suspicious or conspiratorial interpretation in the bottom text, mirroring the lemur's alarmed expression.

Mad-Money-Jim-Cramer.name: Mad-Money-Jim-Cramer

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the specific, often absurd or funny, example that Cramer is emphatically highlighting. His pointing gesture and direct gaze are aimed towards this area, making it the focal point of the meme's declaration.

The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically introduces a broad category, a group of people, or a general statement, providing the context for the specific punchline that Cramer is "identifying" below.

Mad-Money-Jim-Cramer.image_description: This meme features TV personality Jim Cramer, host of the financial show "Mad Money," emphatically pointing while on set. The image is used as a two-panel exploitable format to make a declarative statement, often with an ironic or humorous tone. The setup is presented at the top, and Cramer points to the punchline or specific example at the bottom, creating a comedic effect through his intense expression.

Ryan-Gosling.name: Ryan-Gosling

text_options.description: This text box, located on the lower part of the image, contains the main body of the message. It's the sweet, thoughtful, or humorous phrase that follows the 'Hey Girl' opener, delivering the punchline that characterizes Gosling as the ideal partner.

Positioned at the top of the image, this is where the iconic opening phrase 'Hey Girl' is typically placed. This text serves as the setup, immediately identifying the meme format and addressing the viewer in a familiar, intimate tone.

Ryan-Gosling.image_description: This image features a portrait of actor Ryan Gosling and is the basis for the 'Hey Girl' meme. The meme humorously casts Gosling as the perfect, sensitive, and feminist boyfriend. It's used by pairing his image with text that begins with 'Hey Girl,' followed by a thoughtful, supportive, or romantic phrase, creating a parody of the ideal partner.

Bear-Grylls.name: Bear-Grylls

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, often containing the punchline or the phrase "Improvise. Adapt. Overcome." It presents an extreme, clever, or absurd solution to the problem stated in the top text, mimicking Bear Grylls' survivalist mentality.

The top text of the meme, which sets up the scenario by describing a problem, challenge, or inconvenient situation. This text serves as the premise for the humorous and often extreme solution that follows below.

Bear-Grylls.image_description: This meme features a close-up of British survivalist Bear Grylls in a snowy mountain environment, looking determined. Known as the "Improvise. Adapt. Overcome." meme, it humorously juxtaposes a challenging or inconvenient situation with an absurdly extreme or clever solution. The format typically uses a top text to describe the problem and a bottom text to present the unconventional solution, parodying Grylls' extreme survival tactics from his show "Man vs. Wild".

Unpopular-Opinion-Puffin.name: Unpopular-Opinion-Puffin

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which contains the main part or punchline of the unpopular opinion. It completes the statement started in the top text, delivering the supposedly controversial viewpoint.
The top text, which sets up the meme by introducing the unpopular opinion. This line often directly states the opinion or begins a sentence that is completed by the bottom text.

Unpopular-Opinion-Puffin.image_description: This meme, known as "Unpopular Opinion Puffin," features an Atlantic puffin standing on a grassy patch. The puffin's confident, strutting pose is used to humorously deliver an opinion that is presented as unpopular or controversial. Culturally, the meme is often used ironically, with the stated "unpopular opinion" actually being a widely held belief or common sense.

But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business-Neutral.name: But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business-Neutral

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the punchline and the name of the meme format: "But that's none of my business." This phrase is used to cap off the observation made in the top text, adding a layer of sarcasm and feigned indifference to the pointed comment.

The top text box is used to state a critical or shady observation about a person, group, or situation. This sets up the passive-aggressive tone of the meme, which is then concluded by the punchline at the bottom.

But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business-Neutral.image_description: This meme features the famous Muppet character, Kermit the Frog, sipping from a glass of tea with a knowing, slightly smug expression. Originating from a Lipton tea commercial, the image is famously used for the "But That's None of My Business" meme format. It's used to make a passive-aggressive or sarcastic observation about a situation or someone's behavior, followed by the titular phrase to feign indifference and detachment from the drama.
But-Thats-None-Of-My-Business-Neutral.display_name: But Thats None Of My Business Neutral

Chuck-Norris-Guns.name: Chuck-Norris-Guns

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which delivers the punchline or the second half of the 'Chuck Norris fact.' It completes the hyperbolic statement initiated by the top text, solidifying the joke about his legendary toughness.
This is the top text area in a typical two-part meme format. It presents the first half or the setup of a 'Chuck Norris fact,' an exaggerated claim about his superhuman abilities.

Chuck-Norris-Guns.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor Chuck Norris in an action pose, dual-wielding Uzi submachine guns. The image is the visual basis for the 'Chuck Norris Facts' meme, a popular trend from the mid-2000s. These 'facts' are satirical, hyperbolic statements that exaggerate his toughness, strength, and masculinity, often presenting him as an invincible, god-like figure.

Overly-Manly-Man.name: Overly-Manly-Man

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image contains the punchline. It presents the "overly manly" response or solution to the setup introduced in the top text, delivering the core humor of the meme through its exaggerated machismo.

The top part of the image serves as the setup for the joke. This text typically describes a common problem, an everyday complaint, or a situation that would normally require a practical or sensitive response, setting the stage for the hyper-masculine punchline below.

Overly-Manly-Man.image_description: This meme, known as "Overly Manly Man," features a vintage, black-and-white photograph of a shirtless, mustachioed man in a boxing stance. The character, identified as 19th-century boxer Mike Conley, embodies an exaggerated, almost cartoonish form of masculinity. The meme format uses a two-part caption to juxtapose a common problem or complaint with an absurdly tough, stoic, or impossible solution, parodying traditional macho stereotypes.

OMG-Karen.name: OMG-Karen

text_options.description: The bottom text represents the confused or nonsensical reply from the character. It's often a question that reveals a complete misunderstanding of the topic presented in the top text, highlighting the speaker's cluelessness. A classic line used here is a misattributed quote from another scene, "So you agree? You think you're really pretty?", which perfectly captures the non-sequitur nature of the meme.

The top text sets up the joke by presenting a statement, a question, or a situation. This text is typically something that the meme's subject (Karen) is supposed to be reacting to with confusion. It could be a complex idea, a piece of trivia, or a social observation that she fails to grasp.

OMG-Karen.image_description: This meme features a still image of the character Karen Smith (played by Amanda Seyfried) from the 2004 film "Mean Girls." She has a wide-eyed, confused, and slightly vacant expression, which is central to the meme's humor. The meme is used to portray a person who is comically clueless, misunderstanding a concept, or responding to a statement with a complete non-sequitur. It leverages Karen's character archetype as the "dumb blonde" to create humorous scenarios of misinterpretation or feigned ignorance.

Advice-Dog.name: Advice-Dog

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline of the meme. This is the "advice" part, which is typically terrible, absurd, or socially unacceptable, creating a humorous contrast with the wholesome image of the puppy.
The top text serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a situation, a problem, or a general premise to which the bad advice in the bottom text will apply.

Advice-Dog.image_description: This meme, known as "Advice Dog," is one of the original "advice animal" image macros. It features the head of a smiling puppy against a vibrant, rainbow-colored wheel background. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the cute, innocent-looking dog with the comically bad, nonsensical, or unethical advice presented in the text. This format established the classic top-text/bottom-text setup that became a staple for countless other advice animal memes.

Sigmund-Freud.name: Sigmund-Freud

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, typically a quote attributed to Freud. It serves as the reaction to the setup in the top panel, often providing a humorous psychoanalytic interpretation or an ironic dismissal of overthinking, such as the classic "Sometimes a cigar is just a cigar."

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It usually presents a statement, an image, or a scenario that is intentionally ambiguous or suggestive, inviting a Freudian or psychoanalytic interpretation from the viewer.

Sigmund-Freud.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white portrait of Sigmund Freud, the founder of psychoanalysis, looking thoughtfully at the viewer while holding a cigar. The meme format typically presents a situation or statement that could be interpreted through a psychoanalytic lens, often involving subconscious desires or phallic symbols. The punchline then either provides a stereotypical Freudian analysis or, more commonly, ironically dismisses the over-analysis with the famous (though likely apocryphal) quote, "Sometimes a cigar is just a cigar."

Officer-Cartman.name: Officer-Cartman

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over Cartman's body, serves as the punchline. It typically contains the character's iconic catchphrase, "Respect my authoritah!" or a variation, representing the subject's disproportionate and authoritarian reaction to the situation described in the top text.

The top text, placed above Cartman's head, sets up the scenario. It usually describes a situation where a person is given a minor amount of power or responsibility, setting the stage for their subsequent abuse of that authority.

Officer-Cartman.image_description: This meme features the character Eric Cartman from the animated series South Park, dressed as a police officer and holding a nightstick. Known as "Respect My Authoritah," the image is taken from an episode where Cartman abuses his newfound power. The meme is used to mock or satirize individuals who are on a power trip, being overly bossy, or demanding respect in a childish and unwarranted manner.

George-Washington.name: George-Washington

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which typically serves as the punchline or the main statement. It contrasts with the historical image of George Washington to create humor.
The top text of the image macro, which functions as the setup for the joke or the first part of a statement. It establishes the context for the punchline below.

George-Washington.image_description: This meme features a formal portrait of George Washington, the first President of the United States. This image is used as a classic top-text, bottom-text image macro. The humor comes from the anachronism of pairing the stately, historical figure with modern, often mundane or absurd commentary, as if he is offering his opinion on contemporary life.

Psy-Horse-Dance.name: Psy-Horse-Dance

text_options.description: The bottom panel of the meme. This space is used for the rejected, less desirable, or mundane option. Psy's energetic dancing pose, with his leg kicked out, is often interpreted as him moving away from or dismissing the text in this box.

The top panel of the meme. This area is designated for the preferred, superior, or more exciting option. Psy's pose, with his arms crossed as if holding the reins of a horse, directs attention towards this text, indicating his approval or choice.

Psy-Horse-Dance.image_description: This meme features a still image of South Korean musician Psy performing his iconic horse-riding dance from the 2012 music video for "Gangnam Style." Psy is dressed in a black suit and sunglasses in a horse stable, mid-dance. The format is a two-panel vertical comparison, similar to the Drakeposting meme, used to show preference for one thing over another.

Patrick-Says.name: Patrick-Says

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the image, this text serves as the punchline. It contains the absurd, irrelevant, or comically stupid question that Patrick is asking, which contrasts sharply with the context set up by the top text.

Positioned at the top, this text establishes the context or setup for the joke. It typically describes a situation where serious or intelligent questions are expected, such as a classroom lecture or a formal presentation, thereby setting the stage for the humorous punchline below.

Patrick-Says.image_description: This meme features Patrick Star from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants, raising his hand with a wide-eyed, vacant expression as if to ask a question. Known as "Is Mayonnaise an Instrument?" or "Raising Hand Patrick," the meme humorously portrays someone asking a profoundly foolish, irrelevant, or nonsensical question in a serious context. The format contrasts a formal setting with Patrick's comically simple-minded inquiry, highlighting a moment of cluelessness.

Chocolate-Spongebob.name: Chocolate-Spongebob

text_options.description: Located on the screaming mouth of Fred the Fish in the final panel, this text represents the climax of the negative reaction. It's typically an exclamation of pure horror, pain, or disgust in response to what is being presented.
This text labels SpongeBob and Patrick, who are happily presenting their item. They represent the person, group, or company enthusiastically offering something that will be poorly received.

Placed on Fred the Fish's annoyed face in the second panel, this text identifies the person or group who is the unwilling recipient of the presentation. Their initial unimpressed expression foreshadows their later horrified reaction.
This label is placed on the stack of papers or items SpongeBob is holding. It describes the object, idea, or creation that is being presented, which is the source of Fred's distress.

Positioned in the background of the first panel, this text often sets the scene or provides overarching context for the interaction. It can label the setting, the event, or a general concept that frames the entire meme.

Chocolate-Spongebob.image_description: This meme format, known as "What I Learned in Boating School Is," originates from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants. It features SpongeBob and Patrick enthusiastically presenting something to an annoyed fish character, Fred, whose reaction escalates to screaming in horror. The meme is used to contrast an unwanted or terrible idea/object presented with pride against an observer's overwhelmingly negative reaction.

Super-Cool-Ski-Instructor.name: Super-Cool-Ski-Instructor

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, located at the bottom of the image. It almost invariably contains the catchphrase, "you're gonna have a bad time," which serves as the negative consequence for the action described in the top text.

This is the setup text, placed at the top of the image. It typically describes a specific, often foolish or difficult action, usually starting with "If you..." to set up the conditional warning delivered by the ski instructor.

Super-Cool-Ski-Instructor.image_description: This meme, known as "You're Gonna Have a Bad Time" or "South Park Ski Instructor," features the character Thumper from the animated show South Park. He is a ski instructor with a distressed expression, standing in a snowy mountain landscape. The format is used as a conditional warning: an action described in the top text will inevitably lead to the negative outcome stated in the bottom text, which is almost always the catchphrase "you're gonna have a bad time."

Spiderman-Laugh.name: Spiderman-Laugh

text_options.description: This text box is placed next to J. Jonah Jameson, who is laughing uncontrollably. The text here is the punchline, typically representing the sound of laughter (e.g., "*laughs*") or a final, mocking dismissal of the idea presented earlier.

Located next to Jameson's contemplative face in the third panel, this text represents a moment of pause or a question that feigns consideration before the final rejection. In the original scene, he asks, "You serious?", and this text often reflects that beat, building suspense for the punchline.

This text box corresponds to Peter Parker's earnest expression. It contains the central proposition, request, or statement of the meme, which is often naive, hopeful, or outlandish from the perspective of the character represented by Jameson.

Positioned next to J. Jonah Jameson in the first panel, this text sets up the scenario. It's usually a question or statement from Jameson that prompts the proposal from the other person (represented by Peter Parker).

Spiderman-Laugh.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "J. Jonah Jameson Laughing," features J. Jonah Jameson and Peter Parker from the Sam Raimi "Spider-Man" films. The sequence shows Jameson listening to a proposal from Peter, seemingly considering it, and then bursting into hysterical laughter. The meme is used to humorously reject or mock a suggestion, idea, or statement that is perceived as absurd, naive, or ridiculous.

Ugly-Twins.name: Ugly-Twins

text_options.description: The bottom text, acting as the punchline. This caption typically names the crude, unrefined, or low-quality subject of the joke, contrasting with the setup in the top text.

The top text, which serves as the setup for the joke. This caption usually introduces a concept, question, or situation that the bottom text will answer or comment on in a crude or unsophisticated manner.

Ugly-Twins.image_description: This meme features two men with visibly poor dental health, smiling widely. They are often stereotyped as "Gopniks," a subculture in Russia and other post-Soviet countries. The image is used to represent something crude, low-quality, unsophisticated, or stereotypically Eastern European, often in a self-deprecating or ironically celebratory way.

Hohoho.name: Hohoho

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image typically describes the cause or provocation that leads to Santa's aggressive reaction. It sets up the joke by presenting a scenario that is antithetical to the Christmas spirit, such as someone being naughty or disbelieving in Santa.

The text at the top of the image serves as the punchline, representing Santa's extreme and violent response to the provocation mentioned in the bottom text. This text often contains a direct, threatening quote or action, subverting the traditional image of a kind and forgiving Santa Claus.

Hohoho.image_description: This meme features a person dressed as Santa Claus wearing a military tactical vest and firing a heavy machine gun from a fortified position. The humor stems from the juxtaposition of the traditionally jolly, peaceful figure of Santa with a violent, militaristic action. This format is typically used to represent a normally benevolent entity taking an unexpectedly aggressive or extreme stance in response to a provocation, often related to holiday themes.

Neil-deGrasse-Tyson.name: Neil-deGrasse-Tyson

text_options.description: The text in the bottom box is the punchline of the meme. It almost universally reads, "Watch out, we got a badass over here," delivering the sarcastic response to the statement presented at the top.

The text in the top box sets up the joke by presenting a statement or action that is meant to be perceived as tough, impressive, or rebellious. This is the content that the meme's sarcastic punchline will target.

Neil-deGrasse-Tyson.image_description: This meme, known as "Watch Out, We Got a Badass Over Here" or the Neil deGrasse Tyson reaction, features a black-and-white rage comic drawing of the astrophysicist. The character is depicted with a dismissive expression and hands raised in a sarcastic gesture of mock surrender or awe. It's used to sarcastically mock someone who is bragging, making an empty threat, or trying to act tough. The overall tone is condescending and belittling towards the subject's perceived self-importance.

Weird-Stuff-I-Do-Potoo.name: Weird-Stuff-I-Do-Potoo

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the bird's eyes, serves as the punchline. It describes the specific situation or context that triggers the awkward realization, connecting the weird habit from the top text to a moment of social panic or self-consciousness, which is reflected in the bird's wide-eyed stare.
The top text, placed above the bird's eyes, sets up the scenario. It typically describes a strange, quirky, or socially awkward habit, thought, or action that the creator secretly does.

Weird-Stuff-I-Do-Potoo.image_description: This meme, known as 'Weird Stuff I Do Potoo' or 'Awkward Moment Potoo,' features a close-up of a Potoo bird with large, startled-looking yellow eyes against a black background. The bird's shocked expression is used to represent a moment of sudden, awkward realization. The meme format typically describes a strange personal habit or thought, followed by the specific situation that makes the person realize how weird their action is, creating a relatable and humorous scenario.

Laughing-Goat.name: Laughing-Goat

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed over the goat's neck and chest, delivers the punchline of the joke. This is almost always a pun that relates to the setup text at the top, completing the joke format.
The top text, positioned in the sky area above the goat, presents the setup for a pun or a dad joke. It's the first part of a two-line joke structure.

Laughing-Goat.image_description: This meme, known as "Pun Goat" or "Laughing Goat," features a close-up photograph of a white mountain goat with its head tilted back, mouth open, and eyes squinted, giving it the appearance of laughing heartily. The image is a classic advice animal-style macro used to tell cheesy jokes or puns. The meme's humor comes from pairing a two-part pun with the goat's seemingly amused expression.

Angry-Bride.name: Angry-Bride

text_options.description: This text box covers the lower half of the image. This is an unconventional placement for text in this meme format, which typically labels the characters directly. If text were placed here, it would likely serve as a caption for the entire scene, describing the underlying situation or context for the conflict happening above.

This text box spans the upper half of the image, covering the bride (aggressor) and the groom (victim). Text here labels the two opposing forces. The bride is typically labeled with an intrusive thought, a bad habit, or an external force, while the groom represents the person, plan, or positive situation being ruined by that force.

Angry-Bride.image_description: A stock photo of a bride in her wedding dress punching the groom, who recoils from the blow, in a birch forest. This meme, known as "Bride Punching Groom" or "Angry Bride," visualizes a forceful and unexpected rejection of a situation, person, or idea. It's often used to represent a conflict where one party violently opposes something they are supposed to embrace, contrasting the expectation of a happy wedding with sudden violence.

Talk-To-Spongebob.name: Talk-To-Spongebob

text_options.description: This text is placed in the bottom panel where Squidward is leaning back in a relaxed, smug pose. It represents the punchline of the meme: a much simpler, lazier, or more desirable alternative to the suggestion in the top panel. The contrast between the two statements creates the humor.

This text is located in the top panel where Squidward is enthusiastically whispering to SpongeBob. It typically describes a complex, difficult, or conventional course of action. This text serves as the setup for the punchline that will appear in the panel below.

Talk-To-Spongebob.image_description: This two-panel meme format, known as "Squidward's Lounge Chair," originates from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants. It features Squidward Tentacles eagerly proposing an idea to a skeptical SpongeBob in the top panel, and then leaning back smugly in the bottom panel. The meme contrasts a difficult, complicated, or proper way of doing something (top) with a much simpler, lazier, or more appealing alternative (bottom), with Squidward representing the person making the suggestions.

Robots.name: Robots

text_options.description: The bottom caption area that contains the collective, unanimous response of the robots. This is typically a simple, affirmative word like 'Yes' or 'Correct', signifying total agreement and reinforcing the hive-mind nature of the meme.
The top caption area where a user places a statement, question, or controversial opinion. This text sets up the premise for the group's unified reaction.

Robots.image_description: This meme features a group of identical, white humanoid robots from the 2004 film 'I, Robot'. The main robot in the foreground has a slight, knowing smile, representing a collective or hive-mind. This two-panel format is used to present an opinion or statement in the top text, followed by a simple, unanimous agreement from the group in the bottom text, often highlighting a shared belief within a specific community.

Cool-Obama.name: Cool-Obama

text_options.description: The bottom text, often a punchline, typically contains a phrase of approval like "Not bad." This text gives voice to Obama's expression, confirming his positive reaction to the situation described in the top text.
The top text sets up the scenario or presents a statement to which Obama is reacting. This is the context that warrants his look of impressed approval.

Cool-Obama.image_description: This meme features a photograph of former U.S. President Barack Obama smiling, wearing sunglasses, and pointing forward while holding his tie. Known as the "Not Bad Obama" or "Obama Pointing" meme, it's used as a reaction image to express approval, acknowledgement, or impressed surprise. The overall tone is one of cool, casual affirmation, often in response to a clever or relatable statement.

Hipster-Barista.name: Hipster-Barista

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline from the perspective of the Hipster Barista. It's a condescending or dismissive statement about the mainstream topic mentioned in the top text, reinforcing the stereotype of a pretentious hipster.
The top text sets up the joke by introducing a mainstream or popular topic, such as a band, movie, or trend. This serves as the subject for the hipster's subsequent criticism.

Hipster-Barista.image_description: This meme, known as "Hipster Barista," features a man with glasses, a scarf, and tattoos, embodying the hipster stereotype. The format is used to satirize pretentiousness and the tendency to dislike things for being popular. The meme typically presents a mainstream topic, followed by a condescending punchline from the hipster's perspective, often claiming to have liked it "before it was cool."

Stop-Cop.name: Stop-Cop

text_options.description: This area is typically the second panel of the meme, located below the police officer. The text here serves as the punchline, describing the action, person, or situation that is being stopped or 'arrested' by the figure in the top panel. It often depicts something humorous, relatable, or absurd.

This area covers the police officer, who acts as the setup for the joke. The text placed here describes the person, entity, or concept that is intervening or stopping the action described in the bottom panel. It represents the authority or the reason for the halt.

Stop-Cop.image_description: This meme features a stock photo of a man in a police officer costume holding up his hand in a 'stop' gesture. It is the top panel of a two-panel format, representing an authority figure or an entity intervening or putting a halt to something. This format is used to humorously depict a cause-and-effect scenario, where the officer represents the 'cause' of stopping the action described in the bottom panel.

Baby-Insanity-Wolf.name: Baby-Insanity-Wolf

text_options.description: This bottom text box, placed near the howling pup, contains the punchline. It's a response to the setup text above, but is usually something mundane, silly, or childish, comically contrasting with the pup's seemingly majestic howl.

This top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically contains a serious, dramatic, or epic statement, question, or call to action, setting a grand tone that will be subverted by the punchline.

Baby-Insanity-Wolf.image_description: This meme features a small, cute wolf pup sitting in a field of flowers, looking up with its mouth open as if howling. The format is a two-part joke, contrasting a setup with a punchline. The top text presents a grand statement or call, while the bottom text, representing the pup's "howl," delivers a comically mundane, childish, or silly response, creating humor through juxtaposition.

Scrooge-McDuck.name: Scrooge-McDuck

text_options.description: This area, placed over the vast pile of gold, typically contains text describing the person or entity experiencing this feeling of wealth. It often starts with "Me:" or a similar label, directly connecting the user to the opulent scene.

Located at the top of the image, this space is used for a caption that explains the cause of the newfound "wealth." This text sets up the joke by describing the often mundane or minor event that triggered the exaggerated feeling of opulence, such as "Getting paid" or "Finding a dollar on the ground."

Scrooge-McDuck.image_description: This meme features the cartoon character Scrooge McDuck, known for his extreme wealth, lounging happily in his vault filled with gold coins and money. The image is a popular reaction meme used to humorously express a feeling of immense wealth, luxury, or having an abundance of something. It's often used to exaggerate the value of a small gain, contrasting a minor achievement with the over-the-top depiction of riches.

Take-A-Seat-Cat.name: Take-A-Seat-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text area delivers the punchline of the meme. It contains the sudden, declarative realization or ambitious thought, famously starting with the phrase 'I should...' The classic example is 'I should buy a boat,' which gives the meme its name.

The top text area sets the scene or provides the context for the cat's epiphany. It usually describes a mundane situation or a thought process that leads to the grand realization stated in the bottom text.

Take-A-Seat-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as 'I Should Buy a Boat Cat' or 'Sophisticated Cat,' features a tabby cat sitting at a table with its paws neatly folded, appearing deep in thought. The cat's serious and contemplative expression gives it a human-like quality, as if it has just had a profound realization. This format is used to express sudden, often comically ambitious or out-of-place epiphanies, contrasting a mundane setting with a grand idea.

Socially-Awkward-Penguin.name: Socially-Awkward-Penguin

text_options.description: The text in the bottom box, placed over the darker blue background, describes the 'socially awkward' part of the scenario. This is the punchline, revealing how the initially successful situation described in the top text turned into an embarrassing, cringeworthy, or failed social interaction.

The text in the top box, placed over the lighter blue background, sets up the 'socially awesome' part of the situation. It typically describes an action or event where the protagonist is confident, successful, or cool in a social setting, creating an expectation of a positive outcome.

Socially-Awkward-Penguin.image_description: This meme is the 'Socially Awesome/Awkward Penguin,' a classic advice animal format featuring a penguin on a blue, radially-burst background. The format contrasts two related social scenarios: the top half describes a 'socially awesome' or successful situation, while the bottom half describes a 'socially awkward' or failing outcome of the same situation. This juxtaposition creates a relatable and humorous take on everyday social anxieties and mishaps.

Grumpy-Cat-Star-Wars.name: Grumpy-Cat-Star-Wars

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which serves as the punchline. This text typically delivers a grumpy, negative, or cynical statement that reflects the combined persona of Grumpy Cat and Darth Vader.
The top text of the image macro, which provides the setup or the first part of a statement. It establishes the context for the grumpy punchline that follows at the bottom.

Grumpy-Cat-Star-Wars.image_description: This meme is a photoshop mashup featuring the face of the internet celebrity Grumpy Cat (Tardar Sauce) inside the helmet of the Star Wars character Darth Vader. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the powerful, menacing villain with the cat's perpetually unimpressed and cynical expression. This image is typically used as an image macro to express negative, cynical, or grumpy sentiments, often with a Star Wars-related theme.

Alright-Gentlemen-We-Need-A-New-Idea.name: Alright-Gentlemen-We-Need-A-New-Idea

text_options.description: This box contains the punchline of the meme. The text here is an absurd, controversial, or terrible idea that causes the shocked and angry reaction from the other characters in the adjacent panel. The humor relies on the extremity of this suggestion, which is implied to be the reason the speaker is thrown from the window.

Located in the middle-left panel, this box contains the first, often sensible or ignored, idea. This text serves as a foil to the final suggestion, setting up a normal expectation before the punchline is delivered in the panel below.

This box is part of the first panel, alongside the boss figure who is speaking. It contains the setup for the meme, establishing a problem or a topic for which suggestions are needed, often mirroring the original text, "Alright gentlemen, we need a new idea."

Alright-Gentlemen-We-Need-A-New-Idea.image_description: This meme, known as "Boardroom Suggestion," is a multi-panel comic depicting a business meeting. A boss asks for ideas, and an employee offers suggestions; the final one is so outrageous that the employee is implicitly thrown out of a window by his horrified colleagues. The format is used to present a controversial or unpopular opinion as the final suggestion, leading to the extreme reaction for comedic effect.
Alright-Gentlemen-We-Need-A-New-Idea.display_name: Alright Gentlemen We Need A New Idea

Depressed-Cat.name: Depressed-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, located in region 0, delivers the punchline of the meme. It reveals the trivial, insignificant reason for the "suffering," completing the "first world problem" complaint. This text contrasts with the cat's dramatic sadness, creating the core humor of the meme.

The top text, placed in region 1, introduces the setup for the "first world problem." It usually describes a desire, a situation, or an action that seems perfectly fine on the surface. This line sets the stage for the punchline that will follow at the bottom.

Depressed-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as "First World Problems Cat" or "Sad Cat," features a close-up of a tabby cat with a sorrowful and contemplative expression. The image is used as a classic two-line image macro to humorously express trivial or minor inconveniences as if they were major tragedies. The humor arises from the dramatic contrast between the cat's sad face and the pettiness of the problem being described.

Sad-Spiderman.name: Sad-Spiderman

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically describes an action, plan, or expectation the user had. This serves as the setup for the meme, outlining a goal or a desired scenario.

The top text box delivers the punchline, revealing the disappointing or frustrating outcome that foils the plan described in the bottom text. Its position above Spider-Man's head emphasizes the weight of the failure or sad realization.

Sad-Spiderman.image_description: This meme features a comic book panel of the superhero Spider-Man, looking dejected and defeated. He is hunched over with his head in his hand, a classic pose of despair or frustration. The meme, often called "Sad Spider-Man" or "Depressed Spider-Man," is used to express disappointment, failure, or sadness over a situation, often in a humorous or relatable way.

Young-Cardi-B.name: Young-Cardi-B

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. It contains the statement that the child (Cardi B) is supposedly relaying from her mother, often a humorous, petty, or childish observation or demand.

This is the setup text, typically reading 'My momma said' or a similar phrase. It establishes the premise that the girl is confidently repeating something she heard from her mother, setting the stage for the punchline below.

Young-Cardi-B.image_description: This meme features a childhood photo of rapper Cardi B, known as the 'My Momma Said' meme. The image shows a young Cardi B with a sassy expression, hand on her hip, as if she's about to tattle or confidently relay something an adult told her. This format is used to express humorous, petty, or childishly assertive statements, framed as if they are being repeated verbatim from one's mother.

Chainsaw-Bear.name: Chainsaw-Bear

text_options.description: Located in the bottom black bar, this text serves as the punchline or the demotivating caption. It's typically a cynical, sarcastic, or absurd statement that subverts the expectation set by the title and the image, completing the joke. For example, it might say, 'Your argument is invalid' or 'Because sometimes, nature needs a little help being red in tooth and claw.'

Positioned in the top black bar, this text is the title of the demotivational poster. It's usually a single, often profound-sounding word (like 'AMBITION' or 'ENVIRONMENTALISM') that frames the absurd image in a serious context, setting up the punchline below.

Chainsaw-Bear.image_description: This meme features a photoshopped image of a polar bear standing on its hind legs while holding a yellow chainsaw. The background is a barren, rocky landscape, adding to the surreal nature of the scene. This image is typically used in a demotivational poster format to convey absurdity, chaotic energy, or a nonsensical threat, deriving humor from the unexpected and menacing combination of a wild animal with a power tool.

Challenge-Accepted-Rage-Face.name: Challenge-Accepted-Rage-Face

text_options.description: The bottom text area, which serves as the punchline. In this meme format, this space almost always contains the phrase 'Challenge Accepted,' representing the character's bold response to the situation presented in the top text.

The top text area, which establishes the context or setup for the meme. This text describes the difficult or absurd challenge that the character is about to undertake, prompting their determined reaction.

Challenge-Accepted-Rage-Face.image_description: This meme features the 'Challenge Accepted' rage comic character, a crudely drawn stick figure with a smug, determined expression and crossed arms. It is used to express a confident and often audacious acceptance of a difficult, absurd, or seemingly impossible task. The meme's humor comes from the character's overconfident reaction to a daunting situation described in the text.

Derp.name: Derp

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which serves as the punchline. This line contains the foolish, ignorant, or nonsensical statement or action that embodies the "derp" moment, directly corresponding to the character's expression.
The top text of the image macro, which sets up the context or scenario. This text typically describes a situation or poses a question that leads to the foolish outcome presented in the bottom text.

Derp.image_description: This is a classic "rage comic" character known as "Derp" or "Derpina" when female. The crudely drawn, black-and-white face features a vacant, cross-eyed expression and a simple smile, visually representing foolishness, ignorance, or a moment of stupidity. This meme is typically used as a reaction image or in the final panel of a comic to signify a silly or nonsensical action or statement, often as a self-deprecating punchline.

The-Most-Interesting-Cat-In-The-World.name: The-Most-Interesting-Cat-In-The-World

text_options.description: The bottom text, in region 0, delivers the punchline. It completes the phrase started at the top with '...but when I do, [I do something specific or exaggerated],' providing the humorous twist that makes the meme relatable, often from a cat's point of view.

The top text, placed in region 1, serves as the setup for the joke. It follows the format 'I don't always [do a common activity]...', establishing a premise that will be humorously resolved by the bottom text.

The-Most-Interesting-Cat-In-The-World.image_description: This meme, known as 'The Most Interesting Cat in the World,' features a tabby cat lounging confidently on a cat tree. It's a parody of the 'Most Interesting Man in the World' from Dos Equis beer commercials, mimicking his suave demeanor. The format is used to make humorous boasts from a cat's perspective, typically following the snowclone 'I don't always [X], but when I do, [Y]' to comment on feline behaviors.
The-Most-Interesting-Cat-In-The-World.display_name: The Most Interesting Cat In The World

Successful-Black-Man.name: Successful-Black-Man

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It completes the phrase from the top text in an unexpected and positive way, subverting the initial stereotypical implication and revealing the man to be successful and respectable.

The top text of the meme, which acts as the setup or 'bait'. This line presents a phrase that, when read alone, appears to conform to a negative racial stereotype about Black men, creating an expectation that the bottom text will subvert.

Successful-Black-Man.image_description: This is the 'Successful Black Man' meme, an advice animal-style image macro. It features a stock photo of a well-dressed Black man against a brown color wheel background, looking directly at the camera with a serious expression. The meme operates on a bait-and-switch format, where the top text introduces a phrase that plays on negative racial stereotypes. The bottom text then subverts this expectation with a positive, successful, or wholesome conclusion, challenging the viewer's initial assumptions.

Minor-Mistake-Marvin.name: Minor-Mistake-Marvin

text_options.description: The bottom text, often starting with "Me:" or identifying a specific person/group. This caption frames the boy's expression as the reaction of the specified subject to the situation described in the top text.
The top text, which sets up the scenario. This caption usually describes an action, statement, or situation that elicits the awkward or judgmental reaction from the person depicted.

Minor-Mistake-Marvin.image_description: This meme features a young boy with a tense, awkward expression, looking slightly to the side. Known as "Awkward Black Boy" or used interchangeably with the "Awkward Look Monkey Puppet," it represents a reaction of silent judgment, suspicion, or discomfort. The meme is typically used to convey a personal, internal reaction to a strange or questionable statement or situation.

Angry-Dumbledore.name: Angry-Dumbledore

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains Dumbledore's dialogue, which is the punchline of the meme. It's typically an aggressive, all-caps question or statement that represents the overly intense reaction, often a variation of the famous line 'HARRY, DID YOU PUT YOUR NAME IN THE GOBLET OF FIRE?!'

The top text box sets up the scenario for Dumbledore's outburst. It often describes a situation or a person's action that will elicit the comically intense response shown in the image and written in the bottom text.

Angry-Dumbledore.image_description: This meme features a scene from the film *Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire* where Albus Dumbledore aggressively confronts Harry Potter. Known as 'Dumbledore Asked Calmly,' the meme humorously contrasts the movie's intense portrayal with the book's description of Dumbledore asking 'calmly.' It is used to represent an over-the-top, agitated, or comically aggressive reaction to a situation.

Bad-Joke-Eel.name: Bad-Joke-Eel

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the intentionally bad or cringeworthy punchline to the setup in the top text. The humor of the meme comes from how unfunny or nonsensical this punchline is.
The top text of the meme, which serves as the setup for a joke or pun. It's typically a question or the beginning of a statement that leads the audience to expect a normal punchline.

Bad-Joke-Eel.image_description: This meme, known as "Bad Joke Eel," features a close-up photograph of a moray eel with a goofy, wide-eyed expression. It belongs to the "advice animal" macro-image genre. The format is used to tell terrible jokes or puns, where the top line sets up a standard joke, and the bottom line delivers an intentionally cringeworthy or nonsensical punchline, with the eel's expression humorously underscoring the awkwardness.

Chuck-Norris-Phone.name: Chuck-Norris-Phone

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically contains the punchline or the main body of the "Chuck Norris Fact." This is where the hyperbolic statement about his impossible strength or abilities is placed, completing the joke set up by the top text or standing on its own as the entire meme.

The top text area is often used for the setup of a two-part "Chuck Norris Fact." It presents the first half of the joke or a general statement that the bottom text will absurdly resolve, establishing the context for the punchline.

Chuck-Norris-Phone.image_description: This meme features American actor and martial artist Chuck Norris looking serious while on the phone. It's a cornerstone of the "Chuck Norris Facts" meme, which consists of satirical, hyperbolic statements about his toughness, strength, and masculinity. The image is used as a backdrop for these facts, with his intense expression adding to the humor of the absurd claims being made about him.

Crying-Because-Of-Cute.name: Crying-Because-Of-Cute

text_options.description: The bottom text, labeled with index 0, delivers the punchline or the specific reason for the intense despair. It directly contradicts or shatters the hope established in the top text, causing the character's emotional breakdown.
The top text, labeled with index 1, sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes a situation, hope, or expectation that will be tragically or disappointingly crushed by the bottom text.

Crying-Because-Of-Cute.image_description: This meme features a rage comic character, often called 'Ultimate Cry' or 'Crying Peter Parker,' expressing overwhelming sadness and despair. The character has wide, bloodshot eyes with tears streaming down its face while holding its hands over its mouth in shock. This image macro is used to humorously exaggerate feelings of intense disappointment, frustration, or sadness in response to a given situation.

Futurama-Zoidberg.name: Futurama-Zoidberg

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is almost invariably "AND YOU SHOULD FEEL BAD." This phrase completes the snowclone and expresses a comically harsh judgment on the subject mentioned in the top text, leveraging Zoidberg's sad expression to create a sense of pathetic disappointment.

The top text sets up the premise by identifying something the creator finds subpar or disagreeable. It typically follows the format "YOUR [NOUN] IS BAD", where the noun is the subject of criticism (e.g., "YOUR MEME IS BAD", "YOUR OPINION IS BAD"). This line establishes the target of the humorous insult.

Futurama-Zoidberg.image_description: This meme features Dr. Zoidberg, a red, lobster-like alien from the animated series Futurama, looking dejected. The format is a two-panel macro known as "Your Meme is Bad and You Should Feel Bad" or simply "Sad Zoidberg". It's used to humorously criticize or dismiss someone's idea, creation, or opinion by stating that it's bad and they should feel ashamed of it.

Youre-Too-Slow-Sonic.name: Youre-Too-Slow-Sonic

text_options.description: The bottom text, which serves as the punchline of the meme. This text typically contains a shocking, edgy, or humorous statement that directly contradicts or subverts the expectation set up by the top text.
The top text, which acts as the setup for the joke. This line usually presents a conventional piece of advice or a seemingly innocent statement, mimicking the tone of a public service announcement.

Youre-Too-Slow-Sonic.image_description: This meme features the video game character Sonic the Hedgehog in a classic top-text, bottom-text format. The meme parodies the "Sonic Says" public service announcement segments from the 1990s cartoon "Adventures of Sonic the Hedgehog." It works by presenting a seemingly normal or wholesome statement at the top, which is then subverted by an edgy, absurd, or humorous punchline at the bottom, creating a comedic contrast.

Blank-Blue-Background.name: Blank-Blue-Background

text_options.description: The bottom text, marked by index 0, delivers the punchline of the meme. It's the reaction, consequence, or ironic "advice" that plays off the setup provided in the top text, completing the two-part joke.
The top text, marked by index 1, serves as the setup for the joke. This line typically introduces a scenario, a statement, or a general situation that establishes the context for the punchline below.

Blank-Blue-Background.image_description: This image shows the classic blue color wheel background used for "Advice Animal" style memes, which were highly popular in the early 2010s. The format consists of this radial background, a central image of a character (the "animal"), and text at the top and bottom. The meme is used to convey a relatable or humorous situation through a two-part joke structure, with the text reflecting the specific persona of the character.

Obama-No-Listen.name: Obama-No-Listen

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline of the meme. It almost invariably contains the phrase "Thanks, Obama" or a variation, sarcastically placing blame on him for the situation described in the top text.
The top text box sets up the joke by describing a frustrating, inconvenient, or negative situation. This is typically a mundane, everyday problem that is clearly not the fault of a president.

Obama-No-Listen.image_description: This meme features former U.S. President Barack Obama at a podium with a knowing expression, holding a hand to his ear. Known as the "Thanks, Obama" meme, it is used to sarcastically blame Obama for any minor, everyday inconvenience or personal problem. The humor stems from the absurdity of attributing trivial issues to a world leader, parodying political scapegoating.

Captain-Hindsight.name: Captain-Hindsight

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains Captain Hindsight's unhelpful, after-the-fact advice. It's the punchline of the meme, stating the obvious solution to the problem mentioned in the top text, often starting with phrases like "You should have..." or "If you didn't want X, you shouldn't have done Y."

The top text box establishes the context or the problem that has already happened. This is typically a statement of regret, a complaint, or a description of a negative outcome that prompts Captain Hindsight's appearance.

Captain-Hindsight.image_description: This meme features Captain Hindsight, a superhero character from the animated series South Park. He is depicted with a serious expression, pointing upwards as if delivering a profound statement after a disaster has occurred. The meme is used to sarcastically offer obvious advice or point out what someone should have done to prevent a problem they are now complaining about, highlighting the uselessness of such hindsight.

Joker-Rainbow-Hands.name: Joker-Rainbow-Hands

text_options.description: The bottom text describes a simple, often logical or innocuous action taken by the protagonist. This serves as the setup or the 'cause' that triggers the disproportionate reaction detailed in the top text.

The top text, placed over the sarcastic rainbow, describes the chaotic, illogical, and over-the-top reaction from 'everybody' or a group of people. This is the punchline, emphasizing the absurdity of the public's response to the simple action mentioned below.

Joker-Rainbow-Hands.image_description: This meme, known as "Joker Mind Loss" or "And Everybody Loses Their Minds," features Heath Ledger's Joker from 'The Dark Knight' in an interrogation room. A rainbow is photoshopped between his outstretched hands, creating an ironic and nonchalant tone. The meme contrasts a simple, often reasonable, action or statement with an unexpectedly chaotic and widespread negative reaction from society or a specific group, highlighting the absurdity of the overreaction.

Super-Birthday-Squirrel.name: Super-Birthday-Squirrel

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image typically serves as the punchline or a caption that describes the lonely or awkward situation from the subject's perspective. It often contains a self-deprecating comment about the solitary celebration, for example, 'When you throw a party and you're the only one who shows up.'

The text at the top of the image usually provides the setup or context for the scenario. It describes the event or expectation that leads to the lonely outcome depicted, creating an ironic contrast with the image and the punchline below.

Super-Birthday-Squirrel.image_description: This meme, known as 'Party Squirrel' or 'Birthday Squirrel,' features a squirrel sitting alone in the grass while wearing a festive party hat. The image evokes a sense of awkward, lonely, or low-key celebration, blending cuteness with a touch of melancholy. It is commonly used as a reaction image to express feelings of being left out, celebrating alone (especially on a birthday), or being the only one to participate in something.

Malicious-Advice-Mallard.name: Malicious-Advice-Mallard

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the duck, delivers the 'actual advice.' This line provides a sincere and practical solution, tip, or piece of wisdom related to the situation described in the top line, fulfilling the meme's purpose.

The top text, located above the duck, typically introduces a common problem, a relatable life situation, or a question. This line sets the context, preparing the viewer for the helpful advice that will follow below.

Malicious-Advice-Mallard.image_description: This meme, known as 'Actual Advice Mallard,' features a photograph of a male mallard duck swimming calmly in the water. Unlike many 'advice animal' memes that offer sarcastic or poor advice, this format is used to provide genuine, practical, and helpful tips. The meme follows a simple two-line setup where a problem is presented, followed by a useful solution, making it a source of sincere guidance on the internet.

Eminem.name: Eminem

text_options.description: This area is the punchline of the meme and is almost always replaced by an image of an object, not text. The humor comes from making it appear as if Eminem is earnestly presenting this object, which is often something funny, absurd, or unexpected in response to the setup text at the top.

The top text box serves as the setup or caption for the meme. It typically contains a statement, question, or scenario that provides context for the punchline revealed in the bottom half of the image.

Eminem.image_description: This meme features a serious portrait of the rapper Eminem, who is looking intently at the viewer with his hand over his chest. The format is a popular exploitable template where the lower portion of the image is edited to show Eminem holding or presenting an object. The humor arises from the contrast between Eminem's intense expression and the often absurd or mundane object he is 'presenting' as the punchline.

Sergeant-Hartmann.name: Sergeant-Hartmann

text_options.description: The bottom text box delivers the punchline, representing Gunnery Sergeant Hartman's loud, aggressive, and often expletive-filled reaction. This text is written from his perspective, directly addressing the situation described in the top text with a commanding or insulting tone.
The top text box establishes the context or setup for the meme. It usually describes a frustrating situation, a foolish action, or a question that provokes the sergeant's wrathful response.

Sergeant-Hartmann.image_description: This meme features Gunnery Sergeant Hartman from the 1987 film 'Full Metal Jacket,' portrayed by R. Lee Ermey. The image captures him aggressively pointing and shouting, a defining characteristic of his role as a harsh drill instructor. This format is typically used to express extreme anger, make a forceful demand, or yell at someone for a perceived mistake, with the text mimicking Hartman's intense and often profane speech.

Penguin-Gang.name: Penguin-Gang

text_options.description: The bottom text area, which is less frequently used in this format. When present, it typically contains a punchline, a concluding thought, or an additional detail that adds context to the situation described in the top text.

The top text, which sets up the scenario. It almost always begins with 'Me and the boys' followed by a description of the group's shared activity or destination, such as 'Me and the boys on our way to get beans'.

Penguin-Gang.image_description: This meme features a group of rockhopper penguins standing together, serving as a wholesome or alternative version of the 'Me and the Boys' meme format. The penguins' serious and slightly grumpy expressions create a humorous contrast with the text. The meme is used to depict the user and their friends embarking on a shared, often mundane or silly, activity.

Suspicious-Cat.name: Suspicious-Cat

text_options.description: This is the location for the bottom text, which acts as the punchline. The text here represents the cat's deadpan, cynical, or judgmental reaction to the setup provided in the top text, deriving its humor from the cat's serious expression.
This is the location for the top text, which sets up the premise or situation for the meme. It's the first part of the joke, establishing a context that the cat will then react to in the bottom text.

Suspicious-Cat.image_description: This meme, often in the "advice animal" style, features a close-up of a tortoiseshell cat with a stern, unimpressed expression. The format uses a top-text/bottom-text overlay to create a joke. The humor comes from pairing a setup line with the cat's seemingly judgmental or serious reaction as the punchline, often conveying cynicism or disapproval.

No-Bullshit-Business-Baby.name: No-Bullshit-Business-Baby

text_options.description: This text box is located at the bottom of the image. It typically contains a punchline or a statement that grounds the scene in a childish reality, directly contrasting with the serious nature of the phone call implied by the top text. For example, it might describe a simple, kid-related problem or desire.

Positioned at the top of the image, this text box contains the dialogue of the serious phone call the baby appears to be on. The text is usually something a high-powered professional, like a stockbroker or executive, would say, setting up the humorous premise of the meme.

No-Bullshit-Business-Baby.image_description: This meme, known as 'Business Baby' or 'Baby on the Phone,' features a toddler in a high chair holding a toy phone to his ear with a serious, concerned expression. The humor arises from the juxtaposition of the baby's adult-like demeanor with his mundane, childish setting of eating cereal. This format is typically used to represent someone handling a very serious or stressful phone call, often about business or finance, creating a comedic contrast with the visual.

Bitch-Please.name: Bitch-Please

text_options.description: The bottom text area typically contains the punchline or the reaction phrase. Classically, this is where the phrase "Bitch Please" is written, giving the meme one of its names. It serves to explicitly state the dismissive and condescending attitude conveyed by the laughing face.

The top text area is used to set up the joke by presenting a statement, question, or scenario that the meme creator finds ridiculous or foolish. This text provides the context for the dismissive reaction embodied by the Yao Ming face below it.

Bitch-Please.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white rage comic drawing of former NBA player Yao Ming laughing heartily. Known as the "Yao Ming Face" or "Bitch Please" meme, the image is taken from a 2009 press conference. The face's dismissive and contemptuous expression is used to react to a statement or situation that is considered naive, stupid, or worthy of ridicule. It conveys a sense of superiority and amusement at someone else's expense.

Bazooka-Squirrel.name: Bazooka-Squirrel

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically sets up the scenario by describing the initial action or provocation that elicits the extreme response. This is the "cause" part of the cause-and-effect joke.

The top text box contains the punchline, which is the squirrel's over-the-top reaction or threat. This text represents the disproportionate and aggressive "effect" to the cause mentioned in the bottom text.

Bazooka-Squirrel.image_description: This meme, often called "Bazooka Squirrel" or "Commando Squirrel," features a ground squirrel wearing a military helmet and holding a rocket launcher. The humor comes from the absurdity of a small, typically harmless animal being armed for serious combat. The meme is used to represent an unexpectedly extreme, aggressive, or disproportionate reaction to a situation, often a minor annoyance or provocation.

Internet-Guide.name: Internet-Guide

text_options.description: The bottom text, located here, serves as the punchline. It contains the overly dramatic, angry, or condescending reaction of the character, highlighting the perceived absurdity of their 'butthurt' response to the situation described in the top text.

The top text, placed in this area, establishes the premise of the meme. It usually describes a simple, common, or innocuous action or statement that the 'Butthurt Dweller' character will then overreact to.

Internet-Guide.image_description: This meme, known as 'Butthurt Dweller' or 'Gamer,' features a retro photograph of a man with glasses and a mustache sitting at a vintage computer setup. The character embodies the stereotype of an obsessive, basement-dwelling nerd from the 1980s or 90s. The meme format is used to satirize individuals who have overly intense, angry, or gatekeeping reactions to trivial matters within their hobbies, contrasting a simple premise with a disproportionately aggressive punchline.

Unicorn-MAN.name: Unicorn-MAN

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the internal monologue of the subject. It typically starts with "They don't know..." followed by a niche interest, a secret, or an accomplishment that the other party-goers are unaware of, highlighting the character's inner world and feelings of being misunderstood.

The top text box sets the external context, usually describing the social situation from the subject's perspective, such as "Me at the party." This text establishes the setting where the character feels out of place, creating a contrast with their internal thoughts expressed in the bottom text.

Unicorn-MAN.image_description: This meme, often called "They Don't Know" or "I Wish I Was at Home," features a muscular man in a vibrant, punk-rock unicorn costume at what appears to be a party. His serious, introspective expression contrasts sharply with his festive attire, creating a humorous disconnect. The format is used to represent someone at a social event who is internally preoccupied with a niche hobby or a desire to be elsewhere, feeling socially isolated despite being surrounded by people.

Short-Satisfaction-VS-Truth.name: Short-Satisfaction-VS-Truth

text_options.description: The text in the bottom panel describes the awkward, uncomfortable, or cringeworthy event that ruins the positive situation from the top panel. This text serves as the punchline, and its content is meant to evoke the uncomfortable feeling reflected in the seal's wide-eyed stare.
The text in the top panel sets up the meme by describing a positive, wholesome, or satisfying situation. This corresponds to the content and blissful expression of the 'Satisfied Seal' image.

Short-Satisfaction-VS-Truth.image_description: This two-panel meme contrasts the 'Satisfied Seal' (top) with the 'Awkward Look Seal' (bottom). The top image shows a seal with a blissful expression, while the bottom shows a seal with a wide-eyed, uncomfortable stare. The format is used to describe a situation that starts out pleasant or satisfying but is immediately followed by an awkward, cringeworthy, or uncomfortable realization or event.

Spiderman-Camera.name: Spiderman-Camera

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically describes the person, group, or specific action that is being 'caught' by Spider-Man. It provides the context for the punchline, identifying who is being exposed or what embarrassing thing they have done.

The top text box usually contains the punchline, most commonly the phrase "Caught in 4K" or a similar expression like "Screenshot." This text directly communicates the idea of capturing irrefutable digital evidence of someone's actions or words.

Spiderman-Camera.image_description: This meme features a still image of Spider-Man from the 1960s animated TV series, where he is holding a camera and pointing it directly at the viewer as if taking a picture. The meme is popularly known as "Caught in 4K" and is used as a reaction image to call someone out for saying or doing something contradictory, hypocritical, or embarrassing online. The act of Spider-Man taking a photo symbolizes capturing evidence of the person's questionable behavior for everyone to see.

Chubby-Bubbles-Girl.name: Chubby-Bubbles-Girl

text_options.description: This text label is placed over the running girl. It typically represents the person, group, or entity that is hastily trying to escape a situation. The girl's action of running away is central to the meme's punchline.

Located in the background area the girl is running from, this text describes the cause of her flight. It represents the problem, awkward situation, responsibility, or person that the subject (the girl) is desperately trying to get away from.

Chubby-Bubbles-Girl.image_description: This meme, known as 'Chubby Bubbles Girl' or 'Little Girl Running,' features a toddler in a yellow jacket running away with a bubble wand. Her wide-eyed, urgent expression as she looks back creates a humorous image of frantic escape. The meme is typically used to represent someone making a hasty retreat from an awkward situation, a responsibility, or the consequences of their own actions.

Condescending-Goku.name: Condescending-Goku

text_options.description: The text in this bottom section represents the superior, 'cool,' or 'drip' option. It's the punchline of the meme, directly contrasting with the text above and aligning with Goku's smug and confident expression.

The text placed in the top section describes a conventional, less desirable, or 'cringe' option. It serves as the setup for the comparison, representing the inferior choice that will be contrasted with the 'drip' alternative below.

Condescending-Goku.image_description: This meme, known as 'Drip Goku' or 'Goku Drip,' features the character Goku from Dragon Ball Z wearing a suit with a smug, self-satisfied expression. The format is used for comparisons, contrasting a mundane or inferior option (top text) with a superior, more stylish, or 'cooler' alternative (bottom text) represented by Goku's confident demeanor. It humorously highlights the perceived superiority of one choice, action, or entity over another.

Mega-Rage-Face.name: Mega-Rage-Face

text_options.description: This bottom text box is for the punchline, representing the character's enraged reaction. It almost universally contains a variation of the elongated expletive "FUUUUUUUUUUUU-", which is the signature catchphrase of this specific rage face.

The top text box sets up the scenario. It typically describes a frustrating or annoying situation that causes the character to fly into a rage, leading to the reaction depicted in the image and the bottom text.

Mega-Rage-Face.image_description: This meme features a close-up of a Rage Comic character known as the "Rage Guy" or "FU Guy". The black-and-white, highly-stylized face is contorted in extreme anger, with bared teeth and glowing red eyes, expressing intense frustration or rage. This image is typically used as the punchline panel in a multi-panel comic, reacting to an annoying, frustrating, or infuriating situation described in the preceding panels or text.

TED.name: TED

text_options.description: This area, positioned over Ted's body, is typically left blank. The absence of text is crucial to the meme's format, as it emphasizes that Ted's silent, judgmental stare is the entire reaction to the statement above.

The top text box is the setup of the meme. It usually contains a quote, a description of an action, or a statement that is considered cringeworthy, stupid, or disappointing, which in turn elicits Ted's silent disapproval.

TED.image_description: This meme features Ted, the sentient, foul-mouthed teddy bear from the movie "Ted", staring directly at the viewer with a deadpan, unimpressed expression. The image is used as a reaction to express silent judgment, disappointment, or disapproval towards a preceding statement or action. The humor lies in Ted's stoic, judgmental gaze serving as the punchline, implying that the initial statement is too foolish to even warrant a verbal response.

Evil-Otter.name: Evil-Otter

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It reveals the mischievous or devious thought/plan that the 'scheming otter' is concocting, directly corresponding to the situation set up by the top text.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a scenario or situation. This text provides the context for the otter's mischievous expression and subsequent punchline.

Evil-Otter.image_description: This meme features an otter with a devious expression, rubbing its paws together in a classic villainous pose. Known as 'Scheming Otter' or 'Conspiracy Otter,' the image humorously portrays someone hatching a mischievous or slightly malevolent plan. The format typically uses a top and bottom text to set up a situation and then reveal the otter's comically sinister intention.

No-I-Cant-Obama.name: No-I-Cant-Obama

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline, representing Obama's direct response to the situation described above. This text is often a command or a statement of concern, such as "Stay right where you are," framed as if he is speaking on the phone to address the problem.

The top text box sets up the joke by describing a problematic, absurd, or foolish scenario. This text introduces the cause for Obama's concerned reaction, establishing the context for the punchline below.

No-I-Cant-Obama.image_description: This meme, often called "Stressed Obama" or "Obama on the Phone," features a photograph of former U.S. President Barack Obama looking concerned while on a phone call. The image is used as a reaction format to express alarm, stress, or the need for a serious intervention in response to a foolish or problematic situation. The humor comes from contrasting a trivial problem with the gravitas of a presidential-level reaction.

Zombie-Overly-Attached-Girlfriend.name: Zombie-Overly-Attached-Girlfriend

text_options.description: The bottom text box is where the punchline or the main statement of the meme is placed. This text typically represents a creepy, obsessive, or overly possessive thought or action from the perspective of the 'Overly Attached Girlfriend,' which is made humorous by her intense expression.

The top text box is often used for a setup or introductory phrase that provides context for the punchline at the bottom. It might describe a normal situation to which the 'Overly Attached Girlfriend' has an extreme reaction, setting the stage for the joke.

Zombie-Overly-Attached-Girlfriend.image_description: This meme, known as "Overly Attached Girlfriend," features a young woman with dark eye makeup, wide, staring eyes, and an unnervingly large smile, creating an intense and unsettling expression. The image originates from a YouTube video by Laina Morris, where she performed a parody of a Justin Bieber song with clingy lyrics. The meme is used to humorously represent obsessive, possessive, or stalker-like behavior in a relationship, with captions describing exaggeratedly clingy actions.

Blank-Comic-Panel-2x1.name: Blank-Comic-Panel-2x1

text_options.description: This text box is on the right panel and introduces the "Average Enjoyer," the superior or preferred subject of the comparison. The text typically labels a person who appreciates a more niche, refined, or 'based' thing, which the meme creator champions.

Located on the left panel, this text box introduces the "Average Fan," representing the inferior or mainstream subject in the comparison. The text here describes a person who likes something that the meme creator considers cringe, overly popular, or less sophisticated.

Blank-Comic-Panel-2x1.image_description: This is a blank two-panel meme template known as "Average Fan vs. Average Enjoyer". The format is used to humorously contrast two opposing subjects, presenting one as inferior (the "fan" on the left) and the other as superior (the "enjoyer" on the right). Typically, the left panel features a scrawny, unimpressive character, while the right panel shows a muscular, confident figure, often referred to as a "Gigachad". This meme is used to express a strong, often ironically exaggerated, preference for one thing over another.

If-You-Know-What-I-Mean-Bean.name: If-You-Know-What-I-Mean-Bean

text_options.description: The bottom text, which is the punchline of the meme. This caption almost universally reads "If you know what I mean," directly stating the suggestive nature implied by the character's expression and completing the double entendre set up by the top text.

The top text, which serves as the setup for the joke. This area typically contains a statement that is innocent on the surface but can be interpreted with a sexual or mischievous double meaning, providing the context for Mr. Bean's suggestive reaction.

If-You-Know-What-I-Mean-Bean.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white rage comic style drawing of the character Mr. Bean, portrayed by Rowan Atkinson, with a smug and suggestive facial expression. Known as the "If You Know What I Mean" meme, it is used as a reaction image to add a sexual innuendo or double entendre to a preceding statement. The character's knowing smirk is key to implying a hidden, often risqué, meaning behind an otherwise innocent phrase.
If-You-Know-What-I-Mean-Bean.display_name: If You Know What I Mean Bean

Trailer-Park-Boys-Bubbles.name: Trailer-Park-Boys-Bubbles

text_options.description: The bottom text, often a single, capitalized word like "DECENT!", serves as the punchline.
