It represents Bubbles' enthusiastic and often over-the-top approval of the situation described in the top text. Its placement at the bottom provides a climatic, exclamatory end to the meme.

The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a situation, an object, or an event that the creator finds exceptionally cool, impressive, or desirable, prompting Bubbles' strong reaction.

Trailer-Park-Boys-Bubbles.image_description: This meme features the character Bubbles from the Canadian TV show "Trailer Park Boys," recognizable by his thick glasses and plaid shirt. He stands in a trailer park with a look of intense surprise or excitement. The format is used to express an overwhelmingly positive and often comically intense reaction to a situation or object. The top text sets up a scenario, and the bottom text delivers an emphatic, one-word punchline of approval.

Corona.name: Corona

text_options.description: This bottom section typically contains the punchline of the meme, often presented as a fake news headline, a search result, or a caption. It's where the explicit, humorous connection between Corona beer and the coronavirus is made, delivering the core joke of the format.

The top section of the image is used to set up the context for the joke. This area often contains a title, a fake news banner (e.g., 'BREAKING NEWS'), a social media handle, or the beginning of a search query, framing the absurd punchline that follows below.

Corona.image_description: This meme features a bottle of Corona Extra beer, which became a viral subject of jokes and misinformation during the early stages of the COVID-19 pandemic. The humor arises from the coincidental shared name between the popular Mexican lager and the coronavirus. The meme is typically used to create fake news headlines, search queries, or other humorous content that absurdly links drinking the beer to contracting the virus, highlighting public confusion and the spread of misinformation online.

Steve-Jobs.name: Steve-Jobs

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over Jobs's torso, contains the punchline. It describes the absurd or comically simple 'invention' that Jobs has supposedly created to solve the problem mentioned in the top text. His pointing gesture makes it seem like he is presenting this very solution.

The top text, placed above Steve Jobs's head, sets up the premise of the meme. It typically describes a common problem, an annoyance, or a situation that needs a solution, creating the context for Jobs's 'invention'.

Steve-Jobs.image_description: This meme features a photo of Apple co-founder Steve Jobs smiling and pointing directly at the camera. He is depicted as the inventor of humorous or absurd concepts that solve everyday problems in a ridiculous way. The meme format typically presents a problem in the top text and Jobs's supposed over-the-top or nonsensical solution in the bottom text, playing on his reputation as a revolutionary innovator.

Google-Chrome.name: Google-Chrome

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. The text here reveals the true subject, often something like 'Google Chrome with 2 tabs open' or 'My RAM,' humorously equating the browser's resource usage to the powerful entity described above.

This is the setup text. It typically describes a powerful, all-consuming force or entity, such as 'A supermassive black hole' or 'The devourer of worlds,' to create a dramatic premise for the punchline.

Google-Chrome.image_description: This meme features the old Google Chrome logo, which is widely known for its high RAM consumption. The format is a two-part comparison that humorously exaggerates this characteristic. It typically contrasts a powerful, all-consuming entity with Chrome, suggesting the browser is even more demanding on system resources.

Chuck-Norris-Flex.name: Chuck-Norris-Flex

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the punchline of the 'Chuck Norris Fact'. It completes the setup from the top text with an absurdly exaggerated statement of his power, for example, '...he pushes the Earth down.'
The top text of the meme, which sets up the 'Chuck Norris Fact'. This line introduces a common concept or action, for example, 'Chuck Norris doesn't do push-ups...'

Chuck-Norris-Flex.image_description: This meme features a promotional photo of actor and martial artist Chuck Norris looking tough and ready for action. It's the basis for the 'Chuck Norris Facts' meme, an internet phenomenon where users create satirical, hyperbolic statements about his supposed superhuman strength, durability, and masculinity. The humor lies in the absurd and impossible nature of these 'facts,' which have cemented his image as an icon of ultimate toughness in internet culture.

Forever-Alone.name: Forever-Alone

text_options.description: This area, covering the two bottom panels, typically contains text that sets up the context for the meme. It describes a specific, often relatable, situation that causes the feeling of loneliness or prolonged waiting, acting as the premise for the punchline.

This area is the top panel, which serves as a close-up reaction shot. It is often left blank, as Pablo Escobar's sad and contemplative expression is the punchline. When text is present, it's usually a very short internal monologue that reinforces the feeling of waiting or disappointment.

Forever-Alone.image_description: A three-panel meme known as "Sad Pablo Escobar" or "Waiting Pablo Escobar," featuring actor Wagner Moura as the character from the TV series "Narcos." The images depict him looking pensive, dejected, and alone in different settings, such as sitting on a swing, at a table, and standing by an empty pool. The meme is widely used to humorously express feelings of sadness, loneliness, or boredom while waiting for something to happen.

Batman-And-Superman.name: Batman-And-Superman

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the characters, serves as the punchline or rebuttal. It's typically a cynical, blunt, or harsh statement, often attributed to the grim and realistic Batman, that shatters the notion presented in the top text.
The top text is the setup for the joke. It usually presents a naive, idealistic, or sometimes obvious question or statement, setting up the expectation that will be subverted by the text below.

Batman-And-Superman.image_description: This meme features an animated still of DC superheroes Superman and Batman sitting together. Superman, holding a steaming mug, has a weary and unimpressed expression, while Batman is mostly in shadow beside him. The format is used for a two-part dialogue where an initial statement is met with a harsh, cynical, or blunt rebuttal. Superman's face perfectly captures the reaction to hearing an unwelcome or sobering truth.

Obama.name: Obama

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, typically used for the punchline of the meme. In this format, the text here is often an absurd, nonsensical, or edgy statement that contrasts sharply with the formal image of Obama, creating the core comedic effect.

This is the top text area, which functions as the setup for the joke. The text here usually introduces a scenario or a question that the bottom text will answer in an unexpected or humorous way, following the classic impact font meme format.

Obama.image_description: This meme features a portrait of the 44th U.S. President, Barack Obama, smiling confidently with his arms crossed against a backdrop of a waving American flag. The image is often used in ironic or surreal memes, where absurd, nonsensical, or edgy captions are juxtaposed with his formal and presidential demeanor. The humor stems from this contrast, treating Obama as a cool, authoritative figure delivering a completely unexpected or bizarre message.

Father-Ted.name: Father-Ted

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is typically a weak, unconvincing excuse or a confused reaction from the character. A famous example from the show used here is, "That money was just resting in my account," perfectly capturing the meme's theme of making flimsy justifications.

The top text sets up the scenario, often posing an accusation or a difficult question to the subject represented by Father Ted. This text establishes the context for the humorous excuse or reaction that follows.

Father-Ted.image_description: This meme features a still of Father Ted Crilly from the Irish sitcom "Father Ted," looking exasperated and slightly shifty. The character is known for getting into absurd situations and making poor excuses. The meme is used to represent someone making a flimsy or ridiculous justification for their actions, or to express bewilderment at a chaotic situation, often with a humorous or sarcastic tone.

Grumpy-Cat-Halloween.name: Grumpy-Cat-Halloween

text_options.description: The bottom text, labeled with index 0, delivers the punchline from Grumpy Cat's perspective. It's a negative, sarcastic, or dismissive response that humorously contradicts or undermines the positive setup presented in the top text.
The top text, labeled with index 1, typically sets up a scenario or presents a common saying that is usually viewed positively. This text serves as the premise for the cynical punchline that follows.

Grumpy-Cat-Halloween.image_description: This meme features the internet-famous "Grumpy Cat," a feline named Tardar Sauce known for her permanently scowling expression. The image is used as an image macro to convey cynicism, annoyance, or a pessimistic viewpoint. The humor arises from juxtaposing a typically positive or cheerful situation with the cat's comically unimpressed and negative reaction.

Bill-Nye-The-Science-Guy.name: Bill-Nye-The-Science-Guy

text_options.description: The bottom text, labeled with index 0, typically represents the punchline or the internal monologue of Bill Nye. It expresses the overwhelming, confusing, or existentially dreadful thought that results from the statement presented at the top of the image.

The top text, labeled with index 1, serves as the setup for the meme. It usually presents a statement, a question, or a scenario that is confusing, paradoxical, or nonsensical, prompting the distressed reaction from Bill Nye.

Bill-Nye-The-Science-Guy.image_description: This meme features Bill Nye, the host of the children's science show "Bill Nye the Science Guy," looking distressed with a hand on his head and a wide-eyed expression of shock. The image is a reaction meme used to convey a sense of bewilderment, existential crisis, or being overwhelmed by a complex or nonsensical idea. The humor stems from the contrast between his persona as a knowledgeable science educator and his apparent mental breakdown in the face of a confusing concept.

Alien-Meeting-Suggestion.name: Alien-Meeting-Suggestion

text_options.description: This text box contains the logical, simple, or common-sense suggestion that contrasts with the previous two. The alien's bored expression highlights the obviousness of his solution, which is ultimately rejected, forming the punchline of the meme.

This speech bubble is for the second suggestion, which typically agrees with or builds upon the first flawed idea. The smiling alien represents the groupthink mentality, reinforcing the popular but incorrect opinion.

This speech bubble contains the first suggestion, which is usually a bad, overly complex, or nonsensical idea. The alien's enthusiastic, finger-pointing pose emphasizes the confident delivery of this flawed proposal.

This text box, spoken by the presenter in the first panel, sets the topic for the meeting. It introduces the problem or question that the other aliens will then attempt to solve with their suggestions.

Alien-Meeting-Suggestion.image_description: This three-panel comic meme, often called "Boardroom Suggestion" or "Alien Suggestion," shows a group of aliens in a meeting. Typically, the first two aliens propose absurd or overly complicated solutions to a problem. A third, unimpressed alien then offers a simple, logical solution, which results in him being thrown out of their spaceship in the final panel. The meme is used to satirize situations where a sensible idea is rejected in favor of popular but flawed alternatives.

Alarm-Clock.name: Alarm-Clock

text_options.description: This text box, located at the bottom of the image, represents the 'sleeping' or unenlightened state. The text placed here describes a common, basic, or undesirable idea or action that serves as the setup for the comparison.

This text box, positioned at the top, represents the 'woke' or enlightened state. The text here presents the superior, more nuanced, or preferred alternative to the idea in the bottom box, completing the 'waking up' metaphor.

Alarm-Clock.image_description: This meme features a classic twin-bell alarm clock, used as a two-panel exploitable format to contrast two different ideas or states of being. The format plays on the concept of 'waking up' or becoming 'woke' to a new reality or superior concept. Typically, the bottom panel represents an initial, less-informed, or undesirable state ('asleep'), while the top panel represents the enlightened, preferred, or 'woke' state.

Okay-Truck.name: Okay-Truck

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image, near the ground, typically describes the cause or setup for the reaction. This is the statement, situation, or event that prompts the overwhelming feeling expressed by the truck.

The text at the top of the image, in the sky, represents the punchline or the truck's reaction. It's often written in all caps to signify screaming or a powerful, often nonsensical, emotional outburst in response to the text at the bottom.

Okay-Truck.image_description: This meme features a white cab-over truck with its cab tilted forward, which is anthropomorphized to look like a head thrown back in a scream of agony, frustration, or disbelief. The image is used as a reaction meme to express an overwhelming or intense emotional response to a preceding statement or situation. The format splits the image into two parts: the setup at the bottom and the screamed reaction at the top.

Redditors-Wife.name: Redditors-Wife

text_options.description: This text is placed over the man and his computer, representing what he is engrossed in or saying. It's typically a mundane, nerdy, or absurdly specific comment related to gaming, internet forums, or a niche hobby, creating a humorous contrast with the woman's apparent distress.

This text is positioned at the top, near the concerned woman, and represents her internal thoughts or what she might be saying. It usually expresses a serious worry, a deep emotional concern about their relationship, or a significant life issue that her partner is ignoring.

Redditors-Wife.image_description: This meme, known as "Internet Husband" or "Redditor's Wife," depicts a man intensely focused on his computer while a woman stands behind him looking sad and neglected. The format humorously contrasts the man's trivial or obsessive online activities with the woman's serious, unspoken concerns. This highlights a disconnect in their relationship, where online life overshadows real-world intimacy and problems.

TSA-Douche.name: TSA-Douche

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the agent's body and hands. It typically contains the punchline, describing the specific, often personal or trivial, thing being intensely scrutinized or judged.

Located at the top of the image, this text box sets up the context for the meme. It usually describes the person or situation that is about to be subjected to the intrusive 'inspection' detailed in the bottom text.

TSA-Douche.image_description: This meme features a man in a TSA-style uniform with a serious expression, pulling on a latex glove. The image is a still from a satirical video by The Onion about overly intrusive airport security pat-downs. It is used to humorously represent an unwanted, overly thorough, or uncomfortable examination of someone's choices, interests, or personal life. The TSA agent represents the person or entity doing the intrusive scrutinizing.

Thats-Just-Something-X-Say.name: Thats-Just-Something-X-Say

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the bottom panel where Jim Carrey has a forced, pained smile. The text here represents the character's reluctant or dishonest response to the prompt in the top panel. It's the punchline, highlighting the discomfort of telling a lie or a sugar-coated truth.

This text box is in the top panel, where Jim Carrey's character looks distressed. The text here typically represents a question or statement from another person (often his son) that forces the character to confront an unpleasant reality, setting up the joke.

Thats-Just-Something-X-Say.image_description: This two-panel meme features actor Jim Carrey as Fletcher Reede from the 1997 movie "Liar Liar." In the top panel, he looks pained while talking to his son, and in the bottom panel, he forces a wide, uncomfortable smile. The meme illustrates the internal conflict between wanting to say a harsh truth and having to say something socially acceptable or positive, with the pained expression revealing the true feelings.

Slenderman.name: Slenderman

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which typically contains the punchline or the unexpected, often dark or absurd, outcome of the situation described in the top text. It completes the joke by leveraging Slender Man's intimidating and mysterious presence.
This is the top text area, which usually sets up a scenario or poses a question. This text establishes the context for the punchline that follows at the bottom of the image.

Slenderman.image_description: This meme features the fictional supernatural character Slender Man, a tall, thin, faceless figure in a black suit with tentacles emerging from his back. Originating from a creepypasta internet meme, Slender Man is depicted in a dark, eerie setting, creating a sense of horror and mystery. The image is typically used as a two-panel macro meme with top and bottom text to create jokes, often with a dark, absurd, or unexpected punchline related to something scary, unwanted, or that appears suddenly.

Cereal-Guy-Spitting.name: Cereal-Guy-Spitting

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed below the character, delivers the punchline. It contains the shocking, unbelievable, or absurd piece of information that causes the character's spit-take reaction.
The top text sets up the scenario, often describing a mundane action like reading the news or browsing the internet. This text establishes the context for the surprising revelation that follows.

Cereal-Guy-Spitting.image_description: The "Cereal Guy" meme features a crudely drawn stick figure character at a table, spitting out a mouthful of cereal in a dramatic spit-take. This character is a classic from the rage comic era of the early 2010s. The meme is used to express extreme surprise, shock, or disbelief in reaction to something the character has just read or seen, typically online or in the news.

Travelonshark.name: Travelonshark

text_options.description: This text box labels the great white shark. It represents a large, impending, and often unavoidable problem, threat, or antagonist in a given scenario.

This text box labels the seal, which is positioned directly above the shark's open mouth. It represents the unsuspecting victim or a positive concept that is about to be metaphorically 'eaten' or destroyed by the problem labeled on the shark.

Travelonshark.image_description: This meme, known as "Shark Attacking Seal" or "Great White Shark," shows a dramatic photo of a shark breaching the water to catch a seal. In this object-labeling format, the shark represents a sudden, overwhelming problem or antagonist. The seal symbolizes the unsuspecting victim or a positive situation about to be ruined, creating a humorous depiction of unavoidable negative events.

Snape.name: Snape

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is the exaggerated and dramatic reaction. It often takes the form of "My [noun]..." or a statement of overwhelming defeat, directly responding to the setup text above and mirroring Snape's dramatic posture.

The top text box provides the setup or context for the meme. It usually describes a simple action, statement, or question that prompts the overly dramatic reaction depicted in the image and written in the text below.

Snape.image_description: This meme features the character Severus Snape from the Harry Potter series, looking distressed as he falls backward against a window. The image is used as a reaction format to express an overly dramatic or exaggerated negative response to a preceding statement or situation. The humor comes from pairing a mundane scenario with Snape's theatrical demise.

Dumb-Blonde.name: Dumb-Blonde

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, delivering the punchline. This text typically contains a cliché, self-absorbed, or mundane statement that characterizes the "Annoying Facebook Girl" persona, completing the joke set up by the top text.
The top text of the image macro, which sets up the scenario. This line usually describes a situation or action that the "Annoying Facebook Girl" is involved in.

Dumb-Blonde.image_description: This is the "Annoying Facebook Girl" meme, an image macro from the Advice Animals series. It features a young woman with blonde hair posing in front of a colorful, psychedelic starburst background. The meme is used to satirize and mock stereotypical, attention-seeking, or vapid posts and behaviors commonly seen on social media, particularly Facebook.

LOL-Guy.name: LOL-Guy

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, typically written in Impact font. This section delivers the punchline or the specific detail that causes the extreme reaction shown by the face, completing the joke set up by the top text.
The top text of the meme, usually in Impact font. This text sets up the scenario or describes a general situation that will lead to the intense emotional reaction depicted in the image.

LOL-Guy.image_description: This meme features a classic "Rage Face" character, a staple of early 2010s internet rage comics, depicted with a comically exaggerated expression of overwhelming frustration, shock, or rage. The simple black-and-white drawing shows a face with wide, frantic eyes and a gaping mouth full of sharp teeth, capturing a moment of intense emotional outburst. This image is typically used to humorously represent an over-the-top reaction to a relatable, everyday annoyance or a surprising discovery.

Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket.name: Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket

text_options.description: This label is placed on the Chum Bucket, which represents the inferior, less desirable, or knock-off option in the comparison. Text here is the punchline, naming the thing that is being mocked or presented as the worse alternative.
This label is placed on or near the Krusty Krab sign, representing the superior, popular, or original subject of the comparison. Text here sets up the joke by naming the 'good' or preferred option.

Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Krusty Krab vs. Chum Bucket," originates from the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants. It contrasts the successful Krusty Krab restaurant (top panel) with its perpetually failing competitor, the Chum Bucket (bottom panel). The format is used to compare a superior, popular, or original entity with an inferior, unpopular, or knock-off version, highlighting a significant gap in quality or desirability.

Surpised-Frodo.name: Surpised-Frodo

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline of the meme, almost always containing the phrase "Alright then, keep your secrets." This text represents the speaker's sarcastic or resigned reaction to being denied information, directly quoting Frodo's line from the film.

The top text sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes a situation where the user asks a question or tries to get information from someone or something, only to receive a vague, unhelpful, or secretive response.

Surpised-Frodo.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Frodo Baggins from "The Lord of the Rings," looking slightly confused and concerned. Known as the "Alright Then, Keep Your Secrets" meme, it's used to express mild frustration or amusement when someone is being evasive or won't share information. The format sets up a scenario where information is requested, followed by Frodo's iconic, resigned response.

Joe-Biden.name: Joe-Biden

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over Biden's suit, typically contains the punchline or the main statement of the meme. It concludes the setup from the top text, delivering the humorous or satirical point, often describing a comically negative or absurd consequence.

The top text serves as the setup or introduction for the meme's joke. It often establishes the premise, such as starting with a phrase like "In Joe Biden's America..." or beginning a folksy anecdote that is concluded by the bottom text.

Joe-Biden.image_description: This meme features a formal portrait of U.S. President Joe Biden smiling. The image is used in a top-text, bottom-text format to create humorous and often absurd scenarios. These memes either satirize political discourse by presenting exaggerated dystopian futures under his presidency or portray him as a folksy, sometimes out-of-touch character telling a rambling story.

I-Will-Find-You-And-Kill-You.name: I-Will-Find-You-And-Kill-You

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline and the threat. It's the conclusion of the famous monologue, typically paraphrasing the line, 'but I will find you, and I will kill you.' The final action is often humorously altered to fit the specific, often trivial, context established in the top text.

The top text serves as the setup, establishing the context or identifying the anonymous person or group the user is addressing. It often begins with a variation of the line, 'I don't know who you are,' to set a serious tone before the punchline.

I-Will-Find-You-And-Kill-You.image_description: This meme features a dramatically lit, intense close-up of actor Liam Neeson from his role as Bryan Mills in the 2008 film 'Taken'. Known as the 'I Will Find You' or 'Taken' meme, it leverages his character's threatening monologue to express a determined, often humorously exaggerated, promise to find someone or something. The humor arises from applying this intense threat to mundane or trivial situations.
I-Will-Find-You-And-Kill-You.display_name: I Will Find You And Kill You

Cute-Puppies.name: Cute-Puppies

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which typically serves as the punchline or the main point of the meme. It completes the thought or joke started by the top text.
The top text of the image macro, which usually provides the setup or context for the meme. It's the first part of a two-line joke or statement.

Cute-Puppies.image_description: This meme features two adorable husky puppies sitting on hay, with one appearing to kiss the other on the snout. The image is overwhelmingly cute and is used to express feelings of love, affection, and wholesomeness. It's often used as a reaction image or in memes to represent something sweet, innocent, or a heartwarming interaction.

Super-Kami-Guru-Allows-This.name: Super-Kami-Guru-Allows-This

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. It reveals Guru's supposed last words, which are intentionally anticlimactic, trivial, or nonsensical, subverting the serious tone established by the setup text.

The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically establishes the dramatic context, with text suggesting Guru is about to impart crucial, final wisdom or a warning, building anticipation for the punchline.

Super-Kami-Guru-Allows-This.image_description: This meme features Grand Elder Guru from the anime series Dragon Ball Z, appearing to be on his deathbed and struggling to speak. The format, known as "Guru's Final Words," creates a setup where he is about to reveal a profound secret or give a serious warning. However, the punchline subverts this expectation with a mundane, humorous, or absurd statement, making it a classic bait-and-switch meme.

Annoying-Facebook-Girl.name: Annoying-Facebook-Girl

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the punchline. This text typically represents a stereotypical, attention-seeking, or cringeworthy comment, status update, or photo caption that the 'Annoying Facebook Girl' would post.
The top text, which sets up the scenario. It usually describes a situation or context related to a social media post, setting the stage for the punchline below.

Annoying-Facebook-Girl.image_description: This is the 'Annoying Facebook Girl' meme, an advice animal image macro. It features a young woman with a goofy expression against a blue and white starburst background. The meme is used to satirize people who post attention-seeking, cliché, or cringeworthy content on social media platforms like Facebook. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of a common social media scenario (top text) with a self-absorbed or vapid punchline (bottom text).

Socially-Awesome-Penguin.name: Socially-Awesome-Penguin

text_options.description: The bottom text, located in the lower red section, serves as the punchline. It describes the awkward, embarrassing, or socially inept action or response to the situation established in the top text, delivering the core humor of the meme.
The top text, located in the upper red section, sets up a common social scenario or interaction. This text provides the context for the awkwardness that will follow in the bottom text.

Socially-Awesome-Penguin.image_description: This is the "Socially Awkward Penguin" meme, a classic "Advice Animal" image macro. It features an Adelie penguin walking with a slightly clumsy posture against a red, radially-sectioned background. The meme is used to humorously describe relatable, embarrassing, or clumsy moments in everyday social situations from a first-person perspective.

Happy-Guy-Rage-Face.name: Happy-Guy-Rage-Face

text_options.description: The bottom text provides the resolution or the event that triggers the overwhelming happiness. This punchline is the reason for the character's joyful tears, completing the narrative of a desire being fulfilled.
The top text sets up a scenario or expresses a long-held desire or struggle. It establishes the context for the emotional release that follows.

Happy-Guy-Rage-Face.image_description: This meme features a classic rage comic character known as the 'Happy Crying Face' or 'Crying with Joy' face. The character is depicted with a wide, toothy grin while simultaneously shedding tears, representing an overwhelming sense of happiness, relief, or satisfaction. This meme is typically used to express extreme joy over a long-awaited or highly desired outcome, where the emotion is so intense it brings one to tears.

Relaxed-Office-Guy.name: Relaxed-Office-Guy

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically contains the punchline of the meme, which is often the phrase "Like a Boss." It can also describe the confident or defiant action taken in response to the setup in the top text. Its position at the bottom provides a concluding statement to the scenario.

The top text box is used to set up the scenario, usually by describing a command, request, or situation given to the subject. This text provides the context for the subsequent action, which is then framed as being performed "like a boss."

Relaxed-Office-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "The Boss" or "Like a Boss," features a man in an office setting confidently leaning back in his chair with his feet on the desk. The image originates from The Lonely Island's song "Like a Boss" and is used to humorously depict someone performing an action with extreme confidence, authority, or nonchalance. The format typically involves a two-part caption describing a mundane task followed by the declaration that it was done "like a boss."

Original-Stoner-Dog.name: Original-Stoner-Dog

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the pun or dad joke. It is spatially associated with the smiling dog, who is positioned as the one telling the joke, making the grin appear as if it's reacting to its own cleverness.
The top text box is used for the setup of the joke or pun. It establishes the context or question that the punchline in the bottom box will answer, following a classic two-line joke structure.

Original-Stoner-Dog.image_description: This meme, often called "Pun Dog" or "Smiling Husky," features two husky-like dogs in a snowy landscape. The dog on the right has a wide, cheesy grin, while the dog on the left looks away with a serious expression. The format is used for dad jokes and puns, where the smiling dog delivers the punchline, and the other dog represents the unamused reaction of the audience.

Police-Officer-Testifying.name: Police-Officer-Testifying

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image contains the punchline or the officer's response. The text here is framed as his testimony, providing a humorous, absurd, or unexpected answer to the setup presented in the top text box.

The top text box, positioned above the officer's head, sets up the joke. It typically contains a question, a hypothetical scenario, or a statement that the officer is about to respond to in his "testimony."

Police-Officer-Testifying.image_description: This meme features a still image of former UC Davis police officer John Pike testifying in court, who is more widely known as the "Pepper Spray Cop." The image shows him in uniform, speaking into a microphone with a serious, deadpan expression. This format is typically used as a two-part Q&A, where a question or scenario is presented, and the officer provides an absurd, funny, or unexpected "expert" opinion as the punchline, contrasting his authoritative appearance with trivial or nonsensical topics.

The-Rock-It-Doesnt-Matter.name: The-Rock-It-Doesnt-Matter

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the more intense image of The Rock. It contains the punchline, representing the superior, more exciting, or escalated version of the concept introduced in the top panel.

This text box is placed over the calmer image of The Rock. It typically contains a standard, mundane, or less impressive idea or phrase, setting up the comparison for the punchline in the panel below.

The-Rock-It-Doesnt-Matter.image_description: This two-panel meme features actor and former wrestler Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson. The top panel shows him with a calm, inquisitive expression, while the bottom panel captures him in a much more intense, yelling pose. This format, often called "The Rock Driving" or "The Rock Reaction," is used to contrast a simple or standard idea with a more exciting, amplified, or superior version of it.

Dr-Evil.name: Dr-Evil

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is often a specific, comically small, or absurd demand. This is famously where phrases like 'ONE MILLION DOLLARS' are placed, meant to be read in Dr. Evil's distinctive voice.
The top text area sets up the premise or context for the meme. It often introduces a situation or a demand in a grandiose or villainous tone, preparing the reader for the punchline.

Dr-Evil.image_description: This meme features Dr. Evil, the antagonist from the Austin Powers film series, in his iconic pose with his pinky finger to his mouth. The image is used to make comically evil plans, sarcastic demands, or to quote his famous lines, particularly his demand for "one million dollars". The humor comes from the character's over-the-top yet often underwhelming villainy, making it perfect for expressing petty or absurdly grand schemes.

You-Get-An-X-And-You-Get-An-X.name: You-Get-An-X-And-You-Get-An-X

text_options.description: This area, placed over Oprah's lower half, contains the punchline of the meme. It typically features the phrase "You get a [noun]! And you get a [noun]!" or a similar variation, identifying the item or concept being generously (or sarcastically) distributed to everyone.
This top text box provides the context or setup for the meme. It usually identifies the person, entity, or situation that is doing the 'giving,' setting the stage for the punchline below.

You-Get-An-X-And-You-Get-An-X.image_description: This meme features a photo of talk show host Oprah Winfrey looking ecstatic with her arms outstretched to an audience. The image is from a famous 2004 episode of The Oprah Winfrey Show where she gave every audience member a new car, exclaiming "You get a car! And you get a car! Everybody gets a car!". The meme, known as "Oprah's You Get a Car" or "Everybody Gets a Car," is used to express over-the-top generosity or to hyperbolically state that everyone in a group is receiving the same thing, whether it's good or bad.
You-Get-An-X-And-You-Get-An-X.display_name: You Get An X And You Get An X

PTSD-Clarinet-Boy.name: PTSD-Clarinet-Boy

text_options.description: Text placed here, over the main, somber-looking boy, typically describes the present-day situation or a question that triggers the flashback. This sets up the context for the memory.

Text in this upper section, overlaying the ghostly, superimposed image, represents the past event or memory itself. This is the punchline, often a short, impactful phrase describing a traumatic or embarrassing moment that is now haunting the person.

PTSD-Clarinet-Boy.image_description: The "PTSD Clarinet Boy" or "Flashback Clarinet Boy" meme features a double-exposure school portrait from the 1980s or 90s. The main image is a close-up of a boy in a marching band uniform with a somber, distant expression, while a smaller, full-body image of him smiling and holding a clarinet is superimposed over his head. This visual setup is used to represent a person having a flashback to a past event, often a cringeworthy or comically trivial one, which is haunting them in the present.

Intelligent-Dog.name: Intelligent-Dog

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which serves as the punchline. It completes the hipster statement from the top text, usually by naming something obscure or claiming to have liked something 'before it was cool,' reinforcing the meme's satirical take on hipster culture.

The top text of the image macro. This area typically contains the setup for the joke, often starting a pretentious or obscure statement characteristic of the 'hipster' persona, such as 'I liked...' or 'You've probably never heard of...'.

Intelligent-Dog.image_description: This meme, known as "Hipster Dog" or "Hipster Pup," features a small white dog wearing large black-framed glasses and a plaid scarf, embodying a stereotypical hipster. The image is used as a macro to make ironic and pretentious statements, often claiming to have liked something "before it was cool." The dog's serious and slightly judgmental expression perfectly complements the satirical captions mocking hipster culture.

Brian-Williams-Was-There.name: Brian-Williams-Was-There

text_options.description: The text at the bottom, labeled with index 0, serves as the punchline and is often formatted to look like a news chyron. This text presents an absurd, boastful, or completely fabricated claim that wildly exaggerates the situation described in the top text, mimicking the 'misremembered' stories for which Brian Williams became known.
The text at the top of the image, labeled with index 1, sets up a mundane or relatable scenario. It's the first part of the joke, establishing a normal context that the punchline will wildly distort.

Brian-Williams-Was-There.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of news anchor Brian Williams looking serious at his news desk, a format often called 'Brian Williams Misremembers'. It originates from a controversy where Williams was found to have exaggerated his reporting experiences. The meme is typically used to tell a two-part joke: the top text describes a mundane situation, while the bottom text, formatted like a news chyron, presents an absurdly false and self-aggrandizing claim about that situation, humorously mimicking Williams' tendency to fabricate stories.

Storytelling-Grandpa.name: Storytelling-Grandpa

text_options.description: This text is placed on the open book itself. It contains the main punchline of the meme, revealing the shocking, absurd, or inappropriate content of the story the grandfather is supposedly reading to the children.

A top caption is often placed here to set up the joke. This text typically introduces the theme or title of the outrageous story that will be revealed on the book in box 0, providing context for the punchline.

Storytelling-Grandpa.image_description: This meme format, known as "Story Time with Grandpa" or "Grandpa Reading to Grandchildren," uses a wholesome stock image of an elderly man joyfully reading a book to two young girls. The humor comes from subverting this innocent scene by adding outrageous or inappropriate text to the book and as a caption. The meme portrays the grandfather as sharing some wild, absurd, or dark story, with the children reacting with glee, creating a stark and funny contrast.

Okay-Guy-Rage-Face2.name: Okay-Guy-Rage-Face2

text_options.description: The bottom text typically contains the punchline, which is almost always a simple, resigned "Okay." This text represents the character's reluctant acceptance of the unfortunate situation described in the top text, perfectly matching the facial expression.
The top text sets up a scenario that is disappointing, inconvenient, or generally negative for the subject. This text establishes the context for the character's resigned reaction.

Okay-Guy-Rage-Face2.image_description: This meme features the "Okay Guy," a character from the rage comic series. The black-and-white drawing shows a face with a resigned and slightly downtrodden expression, symbolizing reluctant acceptance. This meme is used to portray a situation where someone agrees to something undesirable or disappointing because they feel they have no other choice. The humor comes from the relatable feeling of begrudgingly accepting an unfortunate outcome.

Unwanted-House-Guest.name: Unwanted-House-Guest

text_options.description: The bottom text typically delivers the punchline or the disturbing piece of information that causes the horrified reaction. This is the core of the meme, revealing the unsettling truth or event that leads to the character's depicted state of shock and insanity.

The top text usually sets up the context or presents a seemingly normal or innocent premise. This setup creates a stark contrast with the disturbing punchline below, amplifying the shock value and the horror of the character's reaction.

Unwanted-House-Guest.image_description: This meme features a horrifying, hand-drawn character with wide, staring eyes and a grotesque, toothy grin, often seen as a variation of a Wojak. The image is used as an extreme reaction to convey profound shock, trauma, or a descent into madness. It represents a state of being deeply unsettled or having witnessed something terrible, often in response to a disturbing realization or piece of information.

Grumpy-Cat-Christmas.name: Grumpy-Cat-Christmas

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, typically serving as the punchline. It delivers a cynical, negative, or grumpy statement that reflects the cat's expression and subverts the festive theme or the setup from the top text.

The top text, which usually sets up the joke by stating a typically cheerful or positive holiday-related sentiment. This creates a contrast with Grumpy Cat's expression and the punchline at the bottom.

Grumpy-Cat-Christmas.image_description: This meme features the internet-famous feline Tardar Sauce, better known as "Grumpy Cat," wearing a Santa hat. Her permanently unimpressed and scowling expression provides a humorous contrast to the festive holiday attire. The meme is typically used to express cynicism, annoyance, or a lack of enthusiasm for things that are generally considered cheerful, especially Christmas and the holiday season.

Samuel-Jackson-Glance.name: Samuel-Jackson-Glance

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline, delivering an aggressive and exasperated response. It often contains a variation of Jules' famous line from the movie, such as "SAY '[word]' AGAIN. I DARE YOU," where '[word]' is replaced by a frustrating term from the setup text above.

The top text sets up the premise of the meme. It typically contains a statement, question, or quote that is confusing, poorly worded, or nonsensical, provoking the intense reaction depicted in the image.

Samuel-Jackson-Glance.image_description: A close-up screenshot of Samuel L. Jackson as Jules Winnfield from the 1994 film Pulp Fiction. He has an intense, wide-eyed, and confrontational expression, with his mouth open as if shouting. This image is used as a reaction meme to express extreme frustration, disbelief, or to aggressively demand clarification in response to a confusing or nonsensical statement.

Subtle-Pickup-Liner.name: Subtle-Pickup-Liner

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is always comically bad, illogical, or nonsensical advice. This text is the core of the joke, creating humor through its absurdity in response to the setup at the top.
The top text sets up a scenario or poses a problem for which advice is sought. It establishes the context for the terrible advice that will follow.

Subtle-Pickup-Liner.image_description: This is the 'Advice God' or 'Indian Advice Guy' meme, an Advice Animal image macro. It features a young man with glasses and a sweater, smiling and pointing confidently at the viewer against a colorful pinwheel background. The meme's humor comes from the stark contrast between his self-assured pose and the terrible, nonsensical, or comically bad advice provided in the text captions.

Monkey-OOH.name: Monkey-OOH

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, representing the orangutan's simple-minded or primal reaction. This text is often a short, grammatically incorrect, or nonsensical phrase (e.g., 'where banana,' 'uh oh stinky') that humorously contrasts with the situation presented in the top text.
The top text sets up the context or scenario for the meme. It usually describes a situation, a thought, or a question that prompts the orangutan's simplistic reaction.

Monkey-OOH.image_description: This meme, often called 'Le Monke,' features a close-up photograph of an orangutan looking up with its mouth open in an expression of awe, surprise, or simple-mindedness. It is part of the 'return to monke' meme trend, which humorously glorifies a simpler, more primitive existence over the complexities of modern life. The meme typically contrasts a complex situation or statement with a simplistic, primal, or nonsensical reaction from the orangutan.

Rasta-Science-Teacher.name: Rasta-Science-Teacher

text_options.description: The text at the bottom of the image is the punchline that subverts the stereotype established by the top text. It completes the sentence in an unexpected, positive, and often wholesome or professional way, revealing the man to be successful and responsible.

The text at the top of the image serves as the setup for the joke. It's the first half of a sentence designed to lead the audience toward a negative racial stereotype, playing on the man's appearance.

Rasta-Science-Teacher.image_description: This meme, known as "Successful Black Man," features a man with dreadlocks and a rasta-colored hat in a classroom setting. The format uses a two-part caption to subvert racial stereotypes. The top line of text creates a misleading, often stereotypical, expectation based on his appearance, which is then humorously contradicted by the wholesome or successful conclusion in the bottom line.

Paranoid-Parrot.name: Paranoid-Parrot

text_options.description: The bottom text, acting as the punchline, describes the paranoid or anxious reaction to the situation set up in the top text. This is where the irrational fear is explicitly stated, creating the humor of the meme.
The top text sets up a common, everyday scenario or action. This line serves as the premise for the paranoid thought that follows.

Paranoid-Parrot.image_description: This is the 'Paranoid Parrot' meme, an advice animal image macro featuring a close-up of a blue hyacinth macaw looking nervously over its shoulder. The meme is used to express irrational fears, social anxiety, and paranoid thoughts related to everyday situations. The format consists of a top caption describing a mundane event, followed by a bottom caption revealing an anxious or over-the-top worry about that event.

Sad-Cat.name: Sad-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, labeled with index 0, typically contains the punchline or the main request of the meme. This text is often phrased from the kitten's perspective, leveraging its cute and pleading expression to make the statement more endearing or persuasive.

The top text, labeled with index 1, usually serves as the setup or provides context for the meme. It establishes the situation that the bottom text will complete or react to, setting the stage for the kitten's 'plea' or statement.

Sad-Cat.image_description: This meme features an adorable, small grey and white tabby kitten sitting on a fluffy white blanket. The kitten is looking upwards with large, innocent, and pleading eyes, evoking a sense of cuteness and vulnerability. This image is a classic example of a wholesome or "lolcat" style meme, typically used to make a cute request, express a naive thought, or create a humorous contrast between the innocent visual and the accompanying text.

Turkey.name: Turkey

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image typically contains text that labels the main subject, often representing a simple or foundational concept. In the context of a comparison meme, it might be the 'before' state or the less impressive element.

Positioned over the turkey's impressive fanned tail feathers, this text usually represents an upgraded, more complex, or showy version of the concept labeled at the bottom. It leverages the visual of the turkey's display to signify expansion, showing off, or a final, more elaborate form.

Turkey.image_description: This image features a male turkey with its tail feathers fully fanned out in a classic display of plumage. While not a specific named meme format, this stock image is frequently used in memes and social media posts, especially around the Thanksgiving holiday in the United States. It's often used to personify the turkey, making jokes about its impending doom or to represent the holiday itself. The format often contrasts the impressive appearance with a less glamorous reality.

Blank-Colored-Background.name: Blank-Colored-Background

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which serves as the punchline of the meme. It typically contains terrible, nonsensical, or comically simplistic advice that subverts the setup presented in the top text.
This is the top text, which serves as the setup for the meme. It usually introduces a situation, a problem, or the beginning of a piece of advice, setting the context for the punchline below.

Blank-Colored-Background.image_description: This image is the iconic, brightly colored radial background from the 'Advice Dog' meme, one of the earliest and most influential 'Advice Animal' formats. The meme typically features a picture of a dog's head in the center, offering nonsensical or terrible advice. The format consists of a top-line setup and a bottom-line punchline, a structure that has been adapted for countless other character-based memes.

Priority-Peter.name: Priority-Peter

text_options.description: This text box covers the boy and his calculator. The text placed here represents his internal monologue or the task he is focused on, serving as the punchline. It highlights his nerdy preoccupation, which is comically out of place in the social setting, such as "I should buy a calculator" or a complex math problem.

This area covers the women and the vacation-like background. Text here typically labels the distracting social element that the boy is ignoring. It often simply says "Girls" or describes the appealing situation, like "Spring Break," to establish the context and emphasize the boy's obliviousness.

Priority-Peter.image_description: This meme, often called "Nerdy Guy with Girls" or "I Should Buy a Calculator," features a young man with glasses intently focused on a calculator while surrounded by several women in bikinis on a sunny deck. The humor stems from the stark contrast between the socially desirable setting and the boy's complete absorption in a mundane, intellectual task. It's used to represent prioritizing a specific, often nerdy, interest over a more conventionally appealing or distracting situation.

Hedonism-Bot.name: Hedonism-Bot

text_options.description: Text in this lower region typically describes the specific, often excessive or strange, action or belief that the user is unapologetically indulging in. This is the core statement of the meme, detailing the 'guilty pleasure' itself.

The top text box usually contains the setup or the direct quote from the scene, "I apologize for nothing!" This phrase establishes the defiant and self-satisfied tone of the meme, framing the action described below as something the user is proud of.

Hedonism-Bot.image_description: This meme features Hedonismbot, a golden, decadent robot character from the animated TV show "Futurama." He is depicted lounging luxuriously while being fed grapes, wearing a look of mild distress or overstimulation. The meme, often called "I Apologize for Nothing," is used to humorously and unapologetically express enjoyment of a guilty pleasure, an unconventional opinion, or an excessive act, completely disregarding any potential judgment from others.

First-World-Stoner-Problems.name: First-World-Stoner-Problems

text_options.description: Text in the bottom panel typically describes the aftermath or the feeling of reflection after the event in the top panel. This is the 'contemplation' or 'coping' phase, often expressing exhaustion, regret, or the simple need for a moment of peace after chaos.

Text in the top panel describes a stressful, chaotic, or overwhelming situation that the subject is rushing through. This represents the frantic action or the source of the stress that leads to the state of contemplation in the bottom panel.

First-World-Stoner-Problems.image_description: This two-panel meme features James Franco as the character Saul Silver from the movie "Pineapple Express." The top panel shows him frantically eating a burrito on a swing set, while the bottom panel depicts him calmly smoking a cigarette in the same spot. The meme contrasts a stressful, overwhelming, or rushed action with the subsequent moment of quiet contemplation, exhaustion, or regret. It's often used to illustrate the feeling of needing a break to process a difficult or chaotic experience that just occurred.

Ghetto-Jesus.name: Ghetto-Jesus

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, delivering the unexpected and often aggressive action taken by Jesus. This text directly contrasts the setup in the top caption, revealing the 'unholy' or extreme solution, which is the core of the meme's humor.

The top text, placed above Jesus's head, sets up a scenario or problem. This text typically describes a situation where a gentle, forgiving, or conventional response would be expected, creating the premise for the subsequent punchline.

Ghetto-Jesus.image_description: This meme features an illustration of a figure resembling Jesus Christ, often called 'Buddy Christ,' holding a pistol and a bottle of wine. The image humorously subverts the traditional peaceful depiction of Jesus, portraying him as ready for aggressive action. It is typically used as a reaction image to represent an unexpectedly extreme, violent, or 'unholy' solution to a problem, contrasting a gentle setup with a harsh punchline.

Hipster-Ariel.name: Hipster-Ariel

text_options.description: This is the bottom text and serves as the punchline. It typically contains Ariel's complaint about how the subject mentioned in the top text has become too mainstream, popular, or "sold out," thereby ruining it for her.
This is the top text, which sets up the joke. It usually describes something that Ariel once liked or an opinion she held, often something obscure or niche.

Hipster-Ariel.image_description: This meme, known as "Hipster Ariel" or "Hipster Mermaid," features a still of Ariel from Disney's "The Little Mermaid" edited to wear large, black-rimmed glasses. Her expression is one of disgust and disappointment. The meme is used to satirize hipster culture, with text expressing a condescending attitude towards anything that has become mainstream or popular, often using the cliché "I liked it before it was cool."

V-For-Vendetta.name: V-For-Vendetta

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline or the core declaration of the meme. It typically contains a defiant, rebellious, or threatening statement that embodies the 'hacker' persona, such as 'We are Anonymous. We are Legion. Expect us.' This text completes the setup from the top caption.

The top text sets up the context or presents the target of the meme's message. It introduces a situation, an entity, or a belief that the character is about to challenge or act against, establishing a serious or dramatic tone.

V-For-Vendetta.image_description: This meme features the character V from the film 'V for Vendetta', recognizable by the Guy Fawkes mask, black hat, and crossed daggers. The image has been widely adopted as a symbol for the hacktivist group Anonymous and is used to represent hackers, internet activists, or individuals making bold, often edgy, anti-establishment statements. The meme typically follows a top-text, bottom-text format to make a dramatic declaration or threat, often related to internet culture or social justice.

Homophobic-Seal.name: Homophobic-Seal

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It describes the awkward or embarrassing outcome of the situation set up in the top text, making the scenario relatable and humorous in a cringeworthy way.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a common or relatable social situation. This text establishes the context for the awkward punchline that follows below.

Homophobic-Seal.image_description: This meme, known as the "Awkward Look Seal" or "Socially Awkward Seal," features a cartoon seal glancing sideways with an uncomfortable and embarrassed expression. The format is used to describe relatable, socially awkward situations. The top text typically sets up a common social scenario, while the bottom text reveals the cringeworthy or awkward outcome, with the seal's expression perfectly capturing the feeling of that moment.

Bart-Simpson-Peeking.name: Bart-Simpson-Peeking

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the second of two contrasting options. This option is often portrayed as the more chaotic, fun, or unconventional choice, which Bart's mischievous expression seems to favor.

The top text box presents the first of two choices in this comparison format. This option is usually the more conventional, straightforward, or socially acceptable one, setting up the contrast with the alternative presented below.

Bart-Simpson-Peeking.image_description: This meme features Bart Simpson from 'The Simpsons' mischievously peeking from the side of a blue background, which serves as a template for a two-option comparison. It's a variation of the 'Lisa Simpson's Presentation' format, where the two text boxes are used to present contrasting ideas, choices, or scenarios. Bart's presence adds a layer of playful judgment or observation to the choice being presented.

Mother-Of-God.name: Mother-Of-God

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme, which almost always reads "MOTHER OF GOD." It vocalizes the character's intense reaction of shock and awe to the situation described in the top text.
This top text box is the setup for the meme. It typically describes a situation, an observation, or a realization that is so incredible or mind-blowing that it provokes the "Mother of God" reaction.

Mother-Of-God.image_description: This meme, known as "Mother of God," features a black-and-white rage comic character with a look of intense shock and awe, taking off his sunglasses. It is used as a reaction image to express overwhelming amazement, disbelief, or being impressed by something extraordinary or massive. The top text sets up a scenario, and the image with its catchphrase at the bottom serves as the punchline.

So-God-Made-A-Farmer.name: So-God-Made-A-Farmer

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline and the name of the meme: "It ain't much, but it's honest work." This phrase provides the context for the image, framing the action described in the top text as a source of humble pride and integrity.

The top text box is used to describe a simple, mundane, or difficult task that the meme creator has completed. This text sets up the scenario, which is then validated by the punchline below, highlighting the effort and earnestness behind the action.

So-God-Made-A-Farmer.image_description: This meme, known as "It Ain't Much, But It's Honest Work," features a black-and-white photograph of an elderly farmer or cowboy leaning on a fence with a sincere, weathered expression. The image is used to express a sense of pride and satisfaction in performing a task that may seem small, insignificant, or laborious to others. It celebrates the value of hard work and humility, often in a wholesome or self-deprecating context.

Barney-Stinson-Win.name: Barney-Stinson-Win

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline. It represents Barney's enthusiastic, often illogical or hilariously extreme answer to the setup in the top panel, aligning with his excited expression and thumbs-up gesture.
This top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically contains a question, a statement, or a scenario posed to Barney, prompting his reaction in the panel below.

Barney-Stinson-Win.image_description: This meme features the character Barney Stinson from the sitcom 'How I Met Your Mother', played by Neil Patrick Harris. He is shown in a bar with a wide, excited smile, giving two thumbs up. The meme is a two-panel format used to present a question or scenario followed by an enthusiastic, often absurd or comically over-the-top answer, reflecting Barney's larger-than-life personality.

Darth-Maul.name: Darth-Maul

text_options.description: The text in this bottom section delivers the punchline of the meme. It often completes a phrase started in the top section, creating a pun or a humorous, literal interpretation that contrasts with Darth Maul's serious demeanor.
The text in this top section serves as the setup for the joke. It typically contains the first part of a phrase, a question, or a statement that the bottom text will respond to or complete.

Darth-Maul.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Darth Maul, a villain from 'Star Wars: The Phantom Menace,' known for his intimidating appearance with red and black facial markings and horns. The image is typically used as a two-part reaction format, split horizontally. The meme's humor often derives from puns or wordplay, where the top half sets up a phrase and the bottom half delivers a punchline, with Maul's intense expression adding a layer of comedic seriousness.

Life-Sucks.name: Life-Sucks

text_options.description: This area, covering the defeated Finn and the concerned Jake, represents the person or people who have been exhausted by the situation. Text here typically labels the subject, such as 'Me and the boys' or 'My last two brain cells,' to identify who has suffered.

Positioned at the top, this text describes the arduous task or frustrating experience that caused the characters' state of exhaustion. This text serves as the punchline, revealing the seemingly simple but actually draining activity, like 'trying to fold a fitted sheet' or 'playing one round of League of Legends'.

Life-Sucks.image_description: This meme, from the 'Adventure Time' episode 'Fionna and Cake,' depicts Fionna and Jake sitting dejectedly in the rain while Finn lies defeated on the ground. The image conveys a sense of exhaustion, burnout, and emotional drainage after a difficult or frustrating experience. It's typically used as a reaction to a prompt asking what someone has been doing, with the image serving as a visual representation of their struggle.

Gangnam-Style-PSY.name: Gangnam-Style-PSY

text_options.description: Located at the bottom of the image, this text typically describes the action or cause of the chaos. It sets up the scenario, often detailing something irresponsible or disruptive that the subject (represented by Psy) has just done before walking away.

Positioned at the top over the explosion, this text describes the disastrous consequence or the chaotic situation being left behind. The explosion visually reinforces the text, representing the mess that the subject is coolly ignoring.

Gangnam-Style-PSY.image_description: This meme features a still from the music video for "Gangnam Style" by South Korean artist Psy. In the image, Psy, dressed in a blue tuxedo and sunglasses, walks calmly and confidently towards the camera while a massive explosion erupts behind him. The meme is used to represent someone nonchalantly ignoring or walking away from a chaotic, disastrous, or problematic situation, often one they themselves have caused. The humor lies in the contrast between Psy's cool demeanor and the destructive background.

Zuckerberg.name: Zuckerberg

text_options.description: This text is placed over the smiling, more expressive image of Mark Zuckerberg. It represents the positive, desirable, or superior outcome in the comparison. The text here is the punchline, contrasting with the text in the top panel to create a humorous before-and-after effect or to show a clear preference.

This text is positioned over the serious, emotionless image of a younger Mark Zuckerberg. It typically describes a negative, boring, or inferior situation or entity. This sets up the joke by establishing the less desirable half of the comparison.

Zuckerberg.image_description: This is a two-panel meme format featuring images of Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg. The top panel shows a younger, serious-looking Zuckerberg, often perceived as robotic or emotionless. The bottom panel shows a more recent photo of him smiling warmly. This meme is used to contrast a negative, undesirable, or inferior state (top) with a positive, desirable, or superior state (bottom), often showing a glow-up or a preferred choice.

Metal-Jesus.name: Metal-Jesus

text_options.description: The bottom text provides Jesus's humorous, anachronistic, or 'cool' response, which serves as the punchline and is reinforced by his 'rock on' gesture.
The top text sets up a scenario or question, often from the perspective of someone speaking to Jesus or about a religious concept.

Metal-Jesus.image_description: This meme, known as 'Rock On Jesus' or 'Heavy Metal Jesus,' features a photoshopped image of Jesus Christ making a 'rock on' hand gesture. The humor comes from the anachronistic and irreverent juxtaposition of a major religious figure with a symbol of rock and roll culture. It is typically used as a two-panel image macro to express cool approval or deliver a humorous, modern punchline from a divine perspective.

Zombie-Bad-Luck-Brian.name: Zombie-Bad-Luck-Brian

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which delivers the punchline. This is typically a terrible pun or a groan-worthy play on words that completes the setup from the top text.
The top text of the meme, which provides the setup for a joke. It's usually a question or the first part of a statement that leads into the punny punchline at the bottom.

Zombie-Bad-Luck-Brian.image_description: This meme, known as "Bad Joke Zombie" or "Pun Zombie," features a young man with zombie makeup, including pale skin, white eyes, and facial sores, smiling at the camera. He is dressed in a blue collared shirt and a red plaid sweater vest. The image originates from a news report featuring Jonathan Ware, who became famous as the "I Like Turtles Kid." The meme format uses this image for telling terrible puns or dad jokes, with the setup at the top and the punchline at the bottom.

Marvel-Civil-War-2.name: Marvel-Civil-War-2

text_options.description: This text is placed over the "Captain America: Civil War" movie title. It serves as the punchline, revealing the trivial or silly topic that has caused the major disagreement between the two sides represented by the characters above. For example, it might say "The correct way to hang toilet paper."

This area is over Tony Stark's face. Text here would represent one side of the argument, often the initial statement or controversial opinion that sparks the conflict. Captain America's panel below would represent the opposing viewpoint.

Marvel-Civil-War-2.image_description: This three-panel meme originates from the movie "Captain America: Civil War," featuring a tense confrontation between Tony Stark (Iron Man) and Steve Rogers (Captain America). The format is used to humorously frame a trivial or mundane disagreement as a massive, world-altering conflict, with the two heroes representing the opposing sides. The punchline, revealing the low-stakes nature of the argument, is typically placed over the movie's title card in the bottom panel.

Mitch-McConnell.name: Mitch-McConnell

text_options.description: The bottom caption of the meme. This text typically delivers the punchline, the preferred option, or a direct, often blunt, statement that concludes or contrasts with the setup in the top panel.
The top caption of the meme, which serves as the setup or the first part of a two-part statement. It introduces a topic or a general idea that is then commented on or contrasted by the bottom text.

Mitch-McConnell.image_description: This meme features a photograph of U.S. Senator Mitch McConnell speaking and gesturing with his index finger raised. The image is used as a two-panel macro format, with text placed at the top and bottom. This template is typically used to present two contrasting or related statements, with the bottom text often serving as a punchline or a more direct, sometimes absurd, conclusion to the setup provided by the top text.

Photogenic-College-Football-Player.name: Photogenic-College-Football-Player

text_options.description: This label is placed over the pile of tackled football players on the ground. Text here represents the obstacles, problems, responsibilities, or opponents that have been easily defeated or ignored by the entity labeled on the standing player.

This label is placed over the victorious football player who is standing over the pile of tackled opponents. Text here represents the person, idea, or entity that is effortlessly succeeding, dodging, or overcoming the challenges represented by the players on the ground.

Photogenic-College-Football-Player.image_description: This meme features a photograph from a football game where one player in a dark blue jersey stands tall and unscathed over a pile of tackled players in yellow jerseys. The standing player's confident expression contrasts with the defeated posture of the players on the ground. This visual is used to represent a person or entity effortlessly overcoming, avoiding, or ignoring a multitude of problems, responsibilities, or opponents.

Gasp-Rage-Face.name: Gasp-Rage-Face

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which typically delivers the punchline or the specific, horrifying detail that causes the character's reaction. It reveals the shocking information that the setup in the top text was leading to.
The top text, which sets up the context or scenario for the meme. It presents a situation or statement that seems normal at first but leads to the shocking reveal in the bottom text.

Gasp-Rage-Face.image_description: This meme features a crudely drawn, black-and-white rage comic character known as the "Horrified Face" or "Gasping Face". The character has wide, bloodshot eyes and an open mouth, conveying a sense of extreme shock, disgust, or a terrifying realization. This image is used as a reaction to something deeply unsettling, unexpected, or cringeworthy, often serving as the punchline in a multi-panel comic or as a standalone reaction image.

Morgan-Freeman-Good-Luck.name: Morgan-Freeman-Good-Luck

text_options.description: This text box is in the third panel, where Lucius Fox is smiling knowingly. It delivers the punchline or the clever revelation of the meme, completing the narrative and explaining why the character in the final panel is defeated.

Located in the second panel, this text box builds upon the initial setup from the first panel. It adds a piece of information that starts to hint at the twist or punchline, corresponding to Lucius Fox's slightly more engaged expression as he processes the situation.

This text box corresponds to the first panel where Lucius Fox looks pensive. It typically contains the setup or the beginning of a statement, introducing the context for the joke or scenario that will unfold.

Morgan-Freeman-Good-Luck.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Morgan Freeman's Realization" or "Lucius Fox Explaining," originates from the film "The Dark Knight." It depicts Lucius Fox (Morgan Freeman) gradually understanding a situation, his expression shifting from pensive to a knowing smile. The final panel shows a defeated-looking character, Thomas Schiff, representing the person being outsmarted or the butt of the joke. The meme is used to illustrate a slow burn realization leading to a clever or humorous conclusion.

Professor-Oak.name: Professor-Oak

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, delivering Professor Oak's authoritative and prohibitive statement. It often directly quotes or paraphrases his lines from the Pokémon games, such as "There's a time and place for everything, but not now!" or "You can't use that here," to shut down the action described in the top text.
The top text sets up the scenario by describing an action or behavior that is contextually inappropriate or forbidden. This text establishes the premise that Professor Oak will then comment on.

Professor-Oak.image_description: This is an Advice Animal-style meme featuring Professor Oak from the Pokémon franchise. The image shows his stern, disapproving face against a red and blue radial background. This meme, often called "Professor Oak" or "You Can't Use That Here," is used to authoritatively forbid an action or point out that something is inappropriate for the current situation. It plays on his in-game dialogue where he prevents the player from doing certain things, like riding a bike indoors.

2nd-Term-Obama.name: 2nd-Term-Obama

text_options.description: This bottom text box is the punchline of the meme. In the classic "What is Obama's Last Name?" format, this space would contain a single, absurd word presented as the answer. The text here subverts expectations by providing a funny, incorrect, or surreal response to the setup question above.

The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically contains a nonsensical or rhetorical question. The most famous use of this meme format has the text "What is Obama's last name?" here, setting up the absurd punchline that follows below.

2nd-Term-Obama.image_description: This meme features a photo of former U.S. President Barack Obama smiling smugly and clapping behind a podium. The image is used as an exploitable template, often for absurdist or anti-humor jokes. The most popular variant is the "What is Obama's Last Name?" meme, where a nonsensical question is posed at the top, and an equally nonsensical answer is provided at the bottom, creating a surreal punchline.

Dating-Site-Murderer.name: Dating-Site-Murderer

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It contains an absurdly aggressive, violent, or hyper-masculine response to the situation set up in the top text, creating the meme's humor through exaggeration.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a scenario or problem. This text typically describes an everyday situation or a common complaint that the 'Overly Manly Man' character will then react to.

Dating-Site-Murderer.image_description: This meme, known as "Dating Site Murderer" or "Overly Manly Man," features an intensely lit, close-up photograph of a bearded man staring seriously into the camera. The character is portrayed as an archetype of extreme, almost comical masculinity. The meme format is typically used as an advice animal, where the top text presents a situation and the bottom text provides an absurdly aggressive, violent, or hyper-masculine solution, satirizing tough-guy stereotypes.

Engineering-Professor.name: Engineering-Professor

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the whiteboard is where the simple, often absurd or funny, conclusion or statement is placed. It serves as the punchline, contrasting sharply with the complex 'proof' written above it.

This section at the top of the whiteboard is used for the complex, detailed, and often nonsensical explanation or 'proof.' The text here leverages the visual clutter of the diagrams to represent an overly elaborate and convoluted argument for the simple conclusion below.

Engineering-Professor.image_description: This meme, often called "Engineering Professor" or "Explaining," features a smiling, confident man standing in front of a whiteboard covered in complex equations and diagrams. The format is used to humorously contrast an overly complicated, often nonsensical, explanation with a very simple or absurd conclusion. It satirizes overthinking, creating convoluted justifications for simple ideas, or presenting pseudo-intellectual arguments.

Eighties-Teen.name: Eighties-Teen

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. It describes the unfortunate, embarrassing, or disastrous outcome that contrasts with the setup in the top text, defining the 'bad luck' aspect of the character.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a scenario. This line typically describes an action or situation that the subject is attempting, often with the intention of being successful or cool.

Eighties-Teen.image_description: This is the "Bad Luck Brian" meme, an image macro featuring a retro yearbook-style photo of a young man with braces and a mullet, smiling awkwardly in a snowy setting. The meme is used to tell stories of unfortunate, embarrassing, or ironic events.
