Derpina.image_description: This is a 2D drawing of the 'Meme Man' character, famous from the 'Stonks' meme. The image is split into two parts, the head and the face, to create a contrast. This format is used to juxtapose a simple or nonsensical idea presented outwardly (the face) with the complex, chaotic, or absurdly over-engineered thought process behind it (the head).

Scrooge-McDuck-2.name: Scrooge-McDuck-2

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the bottom of the image, often labeling the coins Scrooge is holding. It contains the punchline, revealing the specific, often humorous or relatable, item that the meme creator is hoarding or cherishing.

Located at the top of the image, this text box provides the setup or context for the meme. It typically contains a question or a statement from another person that prompts the hoarding behavior depicted below (e.g., 'What do you do with all your money?').

Scrooge-McDuck-2.image_description: This meme features the Disney character Scrooge McDuck, known for his extreme wealth and love for money. In the image, he is sitting at a desk, surrounded by bags of money, lovingly caressing a stack of gold coins. The meme is used to humorously represent someone hoarding or cherishing a large quantity of something, often a mundane or niche item, instead of actual money.

Since-When-Were-You-Under-The-Impression.name: Since-When-Were-You-Under-The-Impression

text_options.description: This area shows the body of the character, Sōsuke Aizen. This part of the image is typically not edited and serves to establish the character's smug and authoritative presence, which is central to the meme's tone.

This section contains the speech bubbles that deliver the meme's punchline. The bubble on the right contains the fixed setup phrase, "SINCE WHEN WERE YOU UNDER THE IMPRESSION THAT...". The empty speech bubble on the left is where the user inserts the surprising or contradictory statement that completes the sentence and subverts the initial premise of the meme.

Since-When-Were-You-Under-The-Impression.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white manga panel of Sōsuke Aizen from the anime series *Bleach*. Aizen has a smug, condescending look on his face as he delivers his iconic line, "Since when were you under the impression that...?" The meme is used to subvert expectations or reveal a shocking truth, where the user presents a situation and then uses Aizen's line to reveal that the reality was completely different from what was perceived, often in a triumphant or trolling manner.
Since-When-Were-You-Under-The-Impression.display_name: Since When Were You Under The Impression

Sheltering-Suburban-Mom.name: Sheltering-Suburban-Mom

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, often revealing the mother's hypocritical behavior, a double standard, or an overly cautious and misguided solution that contradicts the setup in the top text.

The top text sets up the scenario, typically stating a rule the mother imposes on her children, a concern she has, or a general belief she holds, often related to safety, technology, or social issues.

Sheltering-Suburban-Mom.image_description: This meme, known as "Sheltering Suburban Mom" or "Suburban Mom," is an Advice Animal-style image macro. It features a smiling, middle-aged woman in a black tracksuit against a color wheel background. The meme is used to satirize the stereotype of a well-meaning but often hypocritical, naive, or overprotective suburban mother. The humor arises from the contrast between her wholesome appearance and the often contradictory or out-of-touch statements attributed to her.

The-Bobs.name: The-Bobs

text_options.description: The bottom text represents the person, group, or concept being questioned. It typically contains a statement or description of a role or action that sounds convoluted, unnecessary, or absurd, setting up the punchline.

The top text delivers the punchline, representing the skeptical perspective of the consultants. It's usually a question or statement that highlights the pointlessness of the subject described in the bottom text, often a variation of the famous line, "So what would you say... you do here?"

The-Bobs.image_description: This meme features a screenshot from the 1999 film "Office Space" showing two consultants, Bob Slydell and Bob Porter (known as "The Bobs"), interviewing an employee. The man on the left is earnestly explaining something, while the man on the right listens with a skeptical and unimpressed expression. The meme, often captioned with the line "What would you say you do here?", is used to question the purpose or value of a job, role, or concept that seems redundant, nonsensical, or useless.

Jammin-Baby.name: Jammin-Baby

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, specifying the exact song, artist, or musical moment that is causing the baby's ecstatic reaction, providing context for the intense joy.
The top text sets up the scenario, often a general statement about listening to music or a specific situation that the punchline will relate to.

Jammin-Baby.image_description: This meme, known as 'Baby with Headphones' or 'Ecstatic Baby,' features a baby in a car seat with a blissful expression while wearing large headphones. It's used to represent the pure, overwhelming joy and satisfaction of listening to a favorite song or a particularly good part of a track. The meme perfectly captures the feeling of being completely absorbed and delighted by music.

Foul-Bachelorette-Frog.name: Foul-Bachelorette-Frog

text_options.description: The bottom text, serving as the punchline. This line reveals the lazy, gross, or socially unacceptable solution to the problem presented in the top text, embodying the 'foul' nature of the bachelor frog.
The top text, which sets up the scenario. This line typically describes a common household problem, a social situation, or a personal hygiene issue.

Foul-Bachelorette-Frog.image_description: This is an "Advice Animal" meme known as "Foul Bachelor Frog." It features a close-up image of a green tree frog with large red eyes against a purple and pink color wheel background. The meme is used to humorously describe lazy, unhygienic, or socially questionable habits and shortcuts, typically associated with single men living alone. The format consists of a setup line at the top and a punchline at the bottom detailing the "foul" behavior.

Tough-Guy-Wanna-Be.name: Tough-Guy-Wanna-Be

text_options.description: The bottom text box completes the setup caption started at the top. A classic example is 'I bet he's thinking about other women,' which establishes a stereotypical expectation that will be subverted by the man's actual, unrelated thoughts in the second panel of the meme.
The top text box is the first part of a caption that sets up the joke. It typically represents the incorrect assumption of an observer, often a romantic partner, based on the man's tough appearance.

Tough-Guy-Wanna-Be.image_description: This meme, known as 'Tough Guy Entrance' or 'I Bet He's Thinking About Other Women,' features a close-up of a man with a stereotypical 'biker' or 'tough guy' appearance. The format typically contrasts his rugged exterior with an unexpected, often mundane or wholesome, internal monologue. It's used to subvert expectations and play on the trope of men having simple or predictable thoughts.

Obama-Cowboy-Hat.name: Obama-Cowboy-Hat

text_options.description: This area is at the bottom of the image. In this meme format, the image itself acts as the punchline or reaction, so this space is often left blank. If text were added, it would be a caption that reinforces the cool or smooth action depicted, acting as a bottom-text punchline.

This top section is where the setup text for the meme is placed. It typically describes a situation or scenario to which the image of Obama tipping his hat serves as a cool, confident, or humorous response.

Obama-Cowboy-Hat.image_description: This meme, known as 'Cowboy Obama' or 'Obama Tipping Hat,' features a photograph of former U.S. President Barack Obama wearing a black cowboy hat and tipping it with a slight smile. The image is used as a reaction to convey a smooth, cool, or impressive entrance or exit. It's often the bottom panel in a two-panel meme, serving as a nonverbal punchline to a setup text placed above it, signifying a confident and stylish action.

Angry-Koala.name: Angry-Koala

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, often a blunt or aggressive statement that contradicts the setup in the top text. This text represents the harsh reality or the unexpected, negative outcome, delivered from the perspective of the menacing koala.

The top text typically presents a common misconception, a naive belief, or an expectation of something being cute, harmless, or positive. This line sets up the joke by establishing a contrast with the angry image.

Angry-Koala.image_description: This meme features a close-up photograph of a soaking wet koala with a fierce, aggressive expression, its mouth open as if snarling. Known as the "Wet Koala" or "Angry Koala," the image subverts the typical perception of koalas as cute and cuddly creatures. The meme is used to represent something that is expected to be harmless or pleasant but turns out to be unexpectedly menacing, dangerous, or unpleasant.

Crosseyed-Goku.name: Crosseyed-Goku

text_options.description: This is the bottom text area, which serves as the punchline. It typically contains a loud, screamed response to the setup text above, often represented by a long string of the letter 'A' or an emphatic, all-caps statement. This text directly visualizes the sound of Goku's yell.

This is the top text area, used for the setup of the meme. The text here describes a situation, often a minor annoyance, a relatable frustration, or a question that prompts the intense reaction depicted by Goku.

Crosseyed-Goku.image_description: This meme features the character Goku from the anime series Dragon Ball Z, captured mid-scream with an intense and angry expression. The image is used as a reaction macro to express extreme frustration, rage, or excitement in an exaggerated manner. Typically, the meme follows a two-part structure where a setup is presented, followed by a loud, screamed punchline that aligns with Goku's powerful yell.

Confession-Kid.name: Confession-Kid

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline by stating the trivial, minor inconvenience that is causing the exaggerated distress. This text is crucial for the meme's humor, as it contrasts the seemingly serious emotion in the image with a petty complaint.
The top text sets up the scenario, often describing a situation or desire that leads to the insignificant problem revealed in the bottom text. It provides the context for the "first world problem."

Confession-Kid.image_description: This meme, known as "First World Problems," features a young boy covering his face with his hand as if crying. The image is used to satirically frame trivial inconveniences or frustrations experienced by people in wealthy, developed countries as major hardships. The humor arises from the dramatic, distressed posture juxtaposed with a petty complaint, highlighting the privileged nature of the problem.

Will-Ferrell.name: Will-Ferrell

text_options.description: This text is placed at the bottom, corresponding with the serious portrait of Will Ferrell. It typically describes a person's outward appearance, a stated intention, or a seemingly normal situation, setting up the contrast for the punchline.

This text is placed at the top, corresponding with the goofy, smiling portrait of Will Ferrell. It serves as the punchline, revealing the person's true, hidden, or more chaotic inner thoughts that contradict the serious statement below.

Will-Ferrell.image_description: This meme features a composite image of actor Will Ferrell in a style reminiscent of a school portrait. In the foreground, he has a serious, deadpan expression, while a larger, faded image of him with a goofy, smiling expression looms in the background. The format is used to contrast a person's calm or serious exterior with their true, often chaotic or silly, inner thoughts or feelings.

Overly-Suave-IT-Guy.name: Overly-Suave-IT-Guy

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, revealing the character's simple, often incorrect, or comically basic solution to the problem stated above. This text highlights his unwarranted confidence and is key to the meme's humor.
The top text sets up the scenario, usually presenting a problem or a request from a client or boss. This text establishes the challenge that the overconfident character is about to tackle.

Overly-Suave-IT-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Overconfident IT Guy" or "Web Designer," features a stock photo of a young man in a suit sitting confidently with a laptop. The meme satirizes individuals, often in technical fields, who are smugly proud of accomplishing a very simple or misguided task. It typically follows a two-line format where a request is made, and the character provides an overly simplistic or naive solution, highlighting a Dunning-Kruger-like effect.

Duck-Face-Chicks.name: Duck-Face-Chicks

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which serves as the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a foolish, vapid, or hilariously incorrect statement attributed to the women, playing into the stereotype of them being unintelligent. The humor comes from the absurd nature of the response in contrast to the setup text above.

This is the top text, which sets up the joke. It usually poses a question or presents a scenario intended to elicit a response from the women in the image. The setup is crafted to make the subsequent punchline at the bottom seem even more comically ignorant or out of touch.

Duck-Face-Chicks.image_description: This meme features a photo of two women, often referred to as the "Bimbo Twins" or "Silicone Sisters," known for their exaggerated and extensive cosmetic surgery, particularly their extremely large lips. The image is used to represent a stereotypical "bimbo" persona, characterized by perceived vanity and a lack of intelligence. The meme format typically involves a setup and a punchline, where the women are depicted as giving a comically shallow, nonsensical, or ignorant response to a question or situation.

Kyon-Face-Palm.name: Kyon-Face-Palm

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the specific, often foolish or frustrating, statement that directly causes the facepalm reaction. It represents the final straw or the core reason for the character's exasperation, completing the setup from the top text.
The top text box is used to establish the context or setup for the meme. It typically describes a situation, a question, or a statement made by another person that the meme creator is reacting to.

Kyon-Face-Palm.image_description: This meme features the character Kyon from the anime series "The Melancholy of Haruhi Suzumiya" in a state of exasperation, performing a facepalm. Known as the "Anime Facepalm" or "Kyon's Facepalm," it is a popular reaction image used to express frustration, disappointment, or disbelief in response to something perceived as foolish or illogical. The meme typically follows a two-part structure where a situation is presented, followed by a statement or action that elicits the facepalm reaction.

Fast-Furious-Johnny-Tran.name: Fast-Furious-Johnny-Tran

text_options.description: The bottom text, often prefixed with 'Me:', serves as the punchline or the reaction. It describes the confident or show-off action taken by the subject in response to the setup in the top text, perfectly captured by Takashi's smug grin.

The top text sets up the scenario or presents a challenge. This text provides the context for the character's confident reaction, often describing a situation that calls for a specific, skillful, or audacious response.

Fast-Furious-Johnny-Tran.image_description: This is a still image of the character Takashi, also known as the Drift King (D.K.), from the movie 'The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift'. He is shown smiling confidently, almost smugly, from the driver's seat of his car. The meme is used as a reaction image to represent someone who is about to do something skillful, impressive, or reckless, often in response to a prompt or challenge.

Kim-Jong-Il-Y-U-No.name: Kim-Jong-Il-Y-U-No

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the angry reaction. The text here is typically written in an aggressive or frustrated tone, often in all caps, to match the character's enraged expression and clenched fists.

The top text box is used for the setup of the joke. It describes a situation, statement, or action that is meant to be frustrating, annoying, or anger-inducing, providing context for the reaction below.

Kim-Jong-Il-Y-U-No.image_description: This meme features a caricature of Mahathir Mohamad, the former Prime Minister of Malaysia, with an intensely angry facial expression and a crudely drawn stick-figure body with clenched fists. Known as "Angry Mahathir," this meme is used to express extreme frustration, rage, or annoyance towards a particular situation. The format is typically a two-part setup where the top text describes an action or statement, and the bottom text delivers an aggressive or exasperated reaction.
Kim-Jong-Il-Y-U-No.display_name: Kim Jong Il Y U No

Seriously-Face.name: Seriously-Face

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, often serving as the punchline. This area typically contains a rhetorical question or an exclamation that voices the character's disbelief, such as "REALLY?" or "ARE YOU SERIOUS?", directly articulating the sentiment of the facial expression.

The top text of the meme, which sets up the scenario. This text usually describes an action, statement, or situation that is foolish, illogical, or facepalm-worthy, prompting the incredulous reaction from the character below.

Seriously-Face.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white rage comic character known as "Are You Serious Face" or "Really?" guy. The character is a drawing of a man with a mustache and goatee, looking sideways with a condescending and utterly unimpressed expression. This image is used as a reaction to express disbelief, exasperation, or annoyance at a statement or situation that is perceived as incredibly stupid, obvious, or nonsensical.

Bubba-And-Barack.name: Bubba-And-Barack

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image typically contains text that sets up the scenario or provides the overarching context for the meme. It describes the situation or problem that both figures are involved in, creating the foundation for the contrasting reactions shown above.

This top section is used to label the two figures, Bill Clinton and Barack Obama, to represent two opposing ideas, groups, or attitudes. The text over the enthusiastic Clinton represents the carefree, often problematic party, while the text over the exasperated Obama represents the party that has to deal with the consequences or has a more serious outlook.

Bubba-And-Barack.image_description: This meme features former US Presidents Bill Clinton and Barack Obama in the White House press room. Clinton is depicted making a cheerful, grand entrance, while Obama stands at a podium looking stressed and exasperated. The format contrasts a carefree or troublemaking entity (Clinton) with a serious, burdened one that has to deal with the consequences (Obama). It's often used to compare two different approaches, generations, or situations in a humorous way.

Scumbag-Minecraft.name: Scumbag-Minecraft

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned below the Creeper's face, typically delivers the punchline or the negative consequence. It represents the "explosion" or the disastrous result of the situation introduced in the top text, completing the meme's narrative of sudden, unexpected failure or destruction.

The top text, placed above the Creeper's face, serves as the setup for the meme. It usually describes a person, object, or situation that is being approached or considered, setting the stage for an unfortunate and sudden turn of events, much like encountering a Creeper in the game.

Scumbag-Minecraft.image_description: This image features the pixelated face of a Creeper, a hostile mob from the video game Minecraft. Creepers are infamous for silently approaching players and exploding, making them a cultural symbol of impending doom, sudden danger, or an unexpected problem. This image is typically used in a top-text, bottom-text meme format to represent a situation that seems manageable at first but leads to a disastrous outcome.

Overjoyed.name: Overjoyed

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image, showing the beach and ocean, is the area that is typically altered or replaced. An absurd element, like an explosion, a historical scene, or a mythical creature, is photoshopped here to create the unbelievable scenario that the meme's caption refers to.

This top area, located in the sky, is the standard placement for the meme's punchline. The text, typically reading "Haters will say it's fake" or a variation, is placed here to sarcastically challenge the obvious artificiality of the edited image below.

Overjoyed.image_description: This image shows the silhouette of a person jumping exuberantly on a beach at sunset. It is the template for the "Haters Will Say It's Fake" or "Haters Will Say It's Photoshopped" meme. In this format, the jumping person is edited into an absurd, impossible, or humorous situation, with the text ironically defending the image's authenticity against imagined critics.

Baby-Cry.name: Baby-Cry

text_options.description: This text, placed over the toddler's stressed expression, represents the punchline or reaction. It typically conveys a feeling of disbelief, stress, or cringe in response to the situation described in the top panel.

This text, positioned over the toddler's confused, side-eyeing expression, sets up the meme's premise. It usually describes a confusing, illogical, or questionable statement or action that has just occurred.

Baby-Cry.image_description: This two-panel meme, often called "Confused Little Girl" or "Stressed Toddler," features a young child reacting to something. In the top panel, the child looks to the side with a confused and slightly angry expression. In the bottom panel, the child looks forward with a pained, stressed grimace. The meme is used to contrast a confusing or absurd statement (top) with a stressed or negative reaction to it (bottom).

Blue-Futurama-Fry.name: Blue-Futurama-Fry

text_options.description: The bottom text, which completes the thought started at the top. It typically begins with "or just..." and presents the second, often more cynical or suspicious, possibility that Fry is considering.
The top text, which sets up the premise of the meme. It usually starts with the phrase "Not sure if..." followed by the first part of a dilemma or a genuine observation.

Blue-Futurama-Fry.image_description: This meme features the character Philip J. Fry from the animated TV show Futurama, shown with a suspicious, squinting expression. Known as the "Not Sure If Fry" or "Futurama Fry" meme, it is used to express an internal conflict or uncertainty between two possibilities. The format humorously contrasts a genuine question with a more cynical or paranoid alternative, perfectly capturing a moment of indecision.

Big-Bird-And-Mitt-Romney.name: Big-Bird-And-Mitt-Romney

text_options.description: This text box is placed at the bottom of the image, near Mitt Romney. It is used to label Romney as the antagonist, a threat, or a negative force that is about to harm or destroy the entity represented by Big Bird.
This text box is placed over Big Bird's head. It is used to label Big Bird as something innocent, cherished, or vulnerable that is being threatened by the entity labeled over Mitt Romney.

Big-Bird-And-Mitt-Romney.image_description: This meme features the Sesame Street character Big Bird standing next to politician Mitt Romney, who has his arm around the large yellow bird. The image originates from a 2012 U.S. presidential debate where Romney mentioned cutting funding for PBS, the channel that airs Sesame Street, while also stating "I love Big Bird." This created a viral moment, and the image is now used as an object-labeling meme to represent a powerful or menacing entity (Romney) threatening something innocent, beloved, or vulnerable (Big Bird).

Good-Guy-Socially-Awkward-Penguin.name: Good-Guy-Socially-Awkward-Penguin

text_options.description: Located on the bottom panel, this text describes the socially awkward, embarrassing, or negative action that serves as the punchline. It contrasts with the top text to reveal the failure or cringeworthy conclusion to the social scenario.
Positioned on the top 'Socially Awesome Penguin' panel, this text sets up the scenario by describing a socially successful, cool, or confident action. It represents the positive start to the story.

Good-Guy-Socially-Awkward-Penguin.image_description: This is a two-panel advice animal meme format, combining the 'Socially Awesome Penguin' on top with the body of 'Scumbag Steve' on the bottom. This structure is typically used to narrate a two-part social interaction. The top panel describes a situation that starts out successfully or confidently, while the bottom panel delivers a punchline that reveals a subsequent socially awkward, embarrassing, or negative outcome, creating a humorous and relatable contrast.

Beyonce-Knowles-Superbowl-Face.name: Beyonce-Knowles-Superbowl-Face

text_options.description: The text in this bottom section delivers the punchline, which is often a mundane or relatable outcome that contrasts humorously with the intense effort depicted above. It completes the joke by revealing the anticlimactic result of the struggle described in the top text.

The text in this top section typically describes a challenging situation or an action requiring immense strength and concentration. It sets up the scenario, leveraging Beyoncé's fierce expression and powerful upper body to represent the peak of exertion or focus.

Beyonce-Knowles-Superbowl-Face.image_description: This meme, known as "Unflattering Beyoncé" or "Strong Beyoncé," features a photo of the singer during her 2013 Super Bowl halftime performance. The image captures her in a powerful, muscular pose with an intense facial expression, which famously became a meme after her publicist's attempts to remove it from the internet backfired. It's typically used as a two-panel macro to humorously depict intense effort or struggle, often with a mundane or anticlimactic punchline.

Gangnam-Style2.name: Gangnam-Style2

text_options.description: The bottom panel, labeled with index 0, delivers the punchline of the meme. The text here presents an exciting, absurd, or highly specific alternative to the situation described in the top panel. This text is aligned with Psy's enthusiastic expression, representing the user's strong preference for this option.

The top panel, labeled with index 1, serves as the setup for the meme. The text here describes a normal, boring, or generally disliked situation or action. This creates a baseline that contrasts sharply with the energetic punchline below.

Gangnam-Style2.image_description: This meme features a still of South Korean artist Psy from his viral 2012 music video "Gangnam Style." In the image, Psy is enthusiastically shouting on a party bus, surrounded by other people. The format is typically used as a two-panel reaction meme to contrast a mundane or undesirable option with an exciting, over-the-top, or preferable alternative, represented by Psy's energetic reaction.

Deadpool-Pick-Up-Lines.name: Deadpool-Pick-Up-Lines

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Deadpool's lower torso and crotch. It represents the foundation, the underlying support, or the surprising driving force behind the subject labeled on the head. The humor often comes from this label being something unexpected, mundane, or crude that supports a more complex or noble concept above.

This text box is placed over Deadpool's head and upper chest. It represents the main subject, person, or concept that is being supported or 'carried' by the entity labeled below. This is the setup for the joke, which is paid off by the label at index 0.

Deadpool-Pick-Up-Lines.image_description: This meme features the Marvel Comics anti-hero Deadpool standing in a confident pose against a red and white rising sun background. The image is used as a two-part object-labeling meme to represent a relationship of support. Typically, one entity is labeled on Deadpool's head, and the entity that is unexpectedly or humorously supporting it is labeled on his lower body. The humor derives from the often absurd or ironic connection between the two labeled subjects, reflecting Deadpool's irreverent personality.

CURLEY.name: CURLEY

text_options.description: This bottom section contains the punchline or reaction. It typically features one of Curly Howard's famous catchphrases like "Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk!", "Woob-woob-woob!", or another nonsensical, foolish, or comically simplistic response to the text in the top panel.
The top section of the meme serves as the setup. Text here usually presents a question, a statement, or a scenario that prompts the silly or nonsensical reaction from Curly in the panel below.

CURLEY.image_description: This meme features a black-and-white photo of Curly Howard from the classic comedy trio, The Three Stooges, making a goofy expression. The image is typically used as a two-part reaction meme where a statement or question is presented, followed by a nonsensical or foolish response, often one of Curly's signature catchphrases. This format is used to humorously express confusion, provide a silly answer, or react absurdly to a situation.

Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket-Blank.name: Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket-Blank

text_options.description: Text labeling the Chum Bucket represents the inferior, unpopular, or less desirable option in the comparison. In the show, this restaurant is a complete failure, so the label here signifies something negative or a 'knock-off' version of the superior item.

Text labeling the Krusty Krab's sign represents the superior, popular, or preferred option. As the main and successful restaurant in the series, it stands for the 'original' or 'better' choice in the meme's comparison.

Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket-Blank.image_description: This two-panel meme format originates from the cartoon SpongeBob SquarePants, contrasting the successful Krusty Krab restaurant with the perpetually failing Chum Bucket. The Krusty Krab represents a popular, superior, or desirable option, while the Chum Bucket symbolizes an unpopular, inferior, or neglected alternative. This template is widely used to humorously compare two opposing concepts, products, or ideas, highlighting the vast difference in their quality or reception.
Krusty-Krab-Vs-Chum-Bucket-Blank.display_name: Krusty Krab Vs Chum Bucket Blank

Success-Kid-Girl.name: Success-Kid-Girl

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, revealing the successful or fortunate result of the situation described above. This text aligns directly with the child's triumphant expression, signifying the 'success' in 'Success Kid'.
The top text describes the setup or a challenging situation. It sets the context for the eventual, often unexpected, positive outcome that will be revealed in the bottom text.

Success-Kid-Girl.image_description: This meme, known as 'Success Kid,' features a toddler in pink pajamas with a determined and triumphant expression, clenching their fist in a celebratory gesture. The image perfectly captures the feeling of a small, personal victory or an unexpected win. It's used to humorously celebrate minor successes and relatable moments of good fortune, often in a two-line setup/punchline format.

Jersey-Santa.name: Jersey-Santa

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline of the meme. It typically contains a phrase related to bodybuilding, fitness, or getting "gains," which humorously contrasts with the Christmas-themed setup in the top text.
The top text serves as the setup for the joke, usually introducing a common Christmas-related theme, phrase, or tradition (e.g., "He's making a list").

Jersey-Santa.image_description: This meme, known as "Bodybuilder Santa" or "Swole Santa," is an Advice Animal-style image macro. It features a cartoon depiction of a very muscular Santa Claus flexing his bicep against a red and white radial background. The humor comes from the juxtaposition of the traditionally jolly, plump Christmas figure with the hyper-masculine, fitness-obsessed persona of a bodybuilder. The meme is used to make jokes about fitness, "gains" (muscle growth), and diet, often by rephrasing Christmas traditions in workout terminology.

Self-Loathing-Otter.name: Self-Loathing-Otter

text_options.description: This area, covering the watermelon and the otter's paws, is labeled with the source of the intense emotional reaction. It represents the object, activity, or concept that is so good or overwhelming that it brings the subject to tears of joy or intense satisfaction.

This label is placed on the otter's head, representing the person or group experiencing the overwhelming emotion. The text here identifies the subject who is reacting so intensely to the thing labeled below.

Self-Loathing-Otter.image_description: This meme features a close-up photograph of a giant otter eating a slice of watermelon with a very intense, almost pained or tearful expression. The otter's eyes are squinted, and its mouth is open, mid-bite, conveying a sense of overwhelming emotion. This image is used as a reaction meme to express intense feelings, often of joy, satisfaction, or being emotionally overwhelmed by something positive, similar to "tears of joy."

Downcast-Dark-Souls.name: Downcast-Dark-Souls

text_options.description: This text, positioned at the bottom of the image, serves as the punchline. It describes the surprisingly simple or mundane thing that defeats the powerful entity described in the top panel, creating a humorous anticlimax.
This text, located at the top of the image, describes a powerful, formidable, or seemingly unbeatable person, object, or concept. It sets up the knight as a symbol of strength and resilience.

Downcast-Dark-Souls.image_description: This meme features a weary, battle-worn knight in full armor from the video game Dark Souls, resting in a dark environment. The knight, often representing a powerful entity, a difficult challenge, or a well-defended concept, sits solemnly with arrows stuck in his shield. The format is used to create a humorous contrast between this formidable figure and an unexpectedly simple or mundane thing that can defeat or bypass it.

McKayla-Maroney-Not-Impressed2.name: McKayla-Maroney-Not-Impressed2

text_options.description: The bottom text box typically contains the punchline or a dismissive statement that reflects Maroney's unimpressed expression. It serves as the direct reaction to the situation presented in the top text.

The top text box sets up the scenario for the meme. It usually describes an event, achievement, or statement that is supposed to be impressive or exciting, creating a contrast with Maroney's unimpressed reaction.

McKayla-Maroney-Not-Impressed2.image_description: This meme, known as "McKayla Maroney is Not Impressed," features the American gymnast on the podium at the 2012 London Olympics. Her distinct sideways smirk and scowl, captured after she won a silver medal instead of the expected gold, became a viral symbol of disappointment and being underwhelmed. The image is used as a reaction to express that something supposedly impressive fails to impress the viewer.

Pink-Escalade.name: Pink-Escalade

text_options.description: This label is placed on the pink Cadillac Escalade. The text here represents the person, group, or idea that is being portrayed as flashy, over-the-top, or comically out of place.

This label is placed on the Target store in the background. The text here represents the mundane context, the 'straight man' in the joke, or the ordinary situation that makes the subject labeled on the car seem so absurd.

Pink-Escalade.image_description: This meme features a flashy, bright pink Cadillac Escalade SUV parked in front of a Target store. The humor arises from the stark contrast between the extravagant, attention-grabbing vehicle and the mundane, everyday setting of a Target parking lot. It is typically used to represent someone or something that is being overly dramatic, extra, or trying to appear high-status in a completely ordinary situation.

Men-Laughing.name: Men-Laughing

text_options.description: This bottom section contains the punchline of the meme. The text here typically begins with the phrase "And then I said..." followed by a ridiculous, false, or patronizing promise that the powerful figures are supposedly laughing at having made.

The top section of the image serves as the setup for the joke. The text placed here usually represents a question, concern, or statement from a naive or earnest individual (e.g., a citizen, employee, or customer) directed at the powerful figures.

Men-Laughing.image_description: This meme, known as "And Then I Said" or "Laughing Senators," features a photo of several older men in suits laughing heartily. The image is used as a two-part exploitable template to satirize powerful entities like politicians, corporations, or authority figures. The setup involves a naive question or statement from the public, followed by a cynical and dismissive punchline from the powerful group, highlighting their perceived hypocrisy and disregard for the common person.

Brian-Williams-Was-There-3.name: Brian-Williams-Was-There-3

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains the punchline of the meme. It features Brian Williams's supposed quote, which is an exaggerated, dramatic, or completely fabricated memory of the mundane event described in the top text. The humor relies on this text being an over-the-top and unbelievable embellishment.

The top text area sets up the joke by describing a simple, everyday event or asking a question. This text represents the mundane reality that Brian Williams will later "misremember" in a grandiose fashion in the bottom text.

Brian-Williams-Was-There-3.image_description: This meme features a photo of former NBC news anchor Brian Williams looking seriously at the camera. Known as the "Brian Williams Misremembers" or "Brian Williams Remembers" meme, it plays on a real-life controversy where he was found to have exaggerated his reporting experiences. The format typically presents a mundane event in the top text, followed by Williams's absurdly dramatic and fabricated recollection of it in the bottom text, creating a humorous contrast.

Lethal-Weapon-Danny-Glover.name: Lethal-Weapon-Danny-Glover

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline, typically the iconic phrase "I'm getting too old for this shit" or a variation of it. This text directly voices the exasperation and weariness shown on the character's face, reacting to the context provided by the top text.

The top text sets up the context or describes a frustrating, tiring, or absurd situation that prompts the character's reaction. This text establishes the scenario that makes the person feel overwhelmed or too old to deal with it.

Lethal-Weapon-Danny-Glover.image_description: This meme features actor Danny Glover as Roger Murtaugh from the 'Lethal Weapon' film series, looking weary and exasperated. The image is famously associated with his line, "I'm getting too old for this shit." It's used to express frustration, burnout, or a feeling of being overwhelmed by a situation, particularly one that feels repetitive, juvenile, or nonsensical.

I-Lied-2.name: I-Lied-2

text_options.description: The bottom text, often simply the phrase "Me Gusta" (Spanish for "I like it"), serves as the punchline. It directly voices the character's creepy satisfaction with the situation described in the top text, solidifying the meme's theme of finding pleasure in the bizarre.

The top text sets up the scenario for the meme. It typically describes an action, thought, or situation that is socially awkward, strange, or even gross, providing the context for the character's unusual reaction.

I-Lied-2.image_description: This meme features the "Me Gusta" face, a character from the classic rage comic series. The image shows a large, round, blueish head with a wide, toothy, and unsettling grin, conveying a sense of disturbed or perverse pleasure. This meme is used to express enjoyment of something that is typically considered strange, awkward, or disgusting, capturing a feeling of guilty or weird satisfaction.

Contradictory-Chris.name: Contradictory-Chris

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This line describes the selfish, rude, or inconsiderate action that Scumbag Steve commits, contrasting with the social expectation set up in the top line.
The top text of the meme, which sets up a relatable social situation or scenario. This line establishes the context for the scumbag behavior that will be revealed in the bottom text.

Contradictory-Chris.image_description: This is the "Scumbag Steve" meme, a classic Advice Animal image macro from the early 2010s. It features a photo of a young man in a puffy jacket smirking against a brown and green starburst background. The character, Scumbag Steve, is an archetype of a selfish, inconsiderate, and mooching person. The meme is used to call out unethical or annoying social behaviors, with the top text setting up a scenario and the bottom text revealing the selfish act.

CASHWAG-Crew.name: CASHWAG-Crew

text_options.description: This bottom text area typically contains the punchline of the meme, describing the specific action or destination of the group. It often presents a mundane or silly activity (e.g., "going to get beans at 3 AM") which creates a humorous contrast with the characters' serious and tough appearance.

The top text box is used for the setup of the meme, establishing the context. It commonly uses the phrasal template "Me and the boys..." to introduce the group and the scenario they are in, setting the stage for the punchline in the bottom text.

CASHWAG-Crew.image_description: This meme features a fan art of Pokémon from the Pikachu evolutionary line, including Pichu, Pikachu, and Raichu, depicted as a cool and intimidating gang or squad. The characters are styled with serious expressions and accessories like sunglasses and jackets, giving them a tough demeanor. This image is typically used in the "Me and the Boys" format to humorously represent a group of friends uniting for a specific, often mundane or silly, purpose, contrasting with their formidable appearance.

Innocent-Sasha.name: Innocent-Sasha

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image contains the punchline, representing the smug girl's condescending or pseudo-intellectual response. The text here is the core of the joke, meant to sound profound but is often just convoluted or nonsensical, highlighting her pretentious character.

The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It typically contains a simple statement, a question posed to the character, or a description of a common situation. This text provides the context for the smug and overly analytical response that follows below.

Innocent-Sasha.image_description: This meme, known as "The Girl You Wish You Hadn't Started a Conversation With at a Party" or "Smug Girl," features a character from a Saturday Night Live sketch. The woman's smug and condescending expression is central to the meme's humor. It's used to mock pseudo-intellectuals or people who offer unsolicited, overly complicated, or self-righteous opinions on simple topics. The format typically presents a statement or question, followed by the character's pretentious and often nonsensical response.

Oh-My-God-Orange.name: Oh-My-God-Orange

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over the lower part of the face, delivers the punchline or the mind-blowing revelation. This is the information that causes the look of awe or shock on Dave's face, completing the setup from the top text.

The top text, placed across the forehead and eyes, sets up the context or premise for the meme. It often describes a common situation, a question, or a statement that will be challenged or expanded upon by the bottom text.

Oh-My-God-Orange.image_description: This meme features a close-up of astronaut Dave Bowman from the film '2001: A Space Odyssey' during the psychedelic Stargate sequence. His wide-eyed, awestruck expression is used to represent a moment of profound realization, having one's mind blown, or witnessing something incredible and incomprehensible. The meme format typically uses a top and bottom text to set up a situation and then deliver a surprising or mind-altering punchline.

Gangster-Baby.name: Gangster-Baby

text_options.description: Text placed here, often over the baby's body, represents the person or entity feeling exhausted or unimpressed. This label identifies the subject who is reacting to the situation.

Text in this upper region describes the context or the specific event that has caused the feeling of exhaustion or disappointment. It sets up the scenario to which the baby's expression is the punchline.

Gangster-Baby.image_description: This meme features a baby, often mistaken for a young XXXTentacion, sitting in a car seat with a very tired, unimpressed, and weary expression. The baby's face conveys a sense of being completely over a situation, as if they've just endured a long and draining experience. This image is used to humorously represent feelings of exhaustion, disappointment, or being fed up with something or someone.

Unhappy-Baby.name: Unhappy-Baby

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, revealing the trivial "first world problem" that is causing the exaggerated distress. This text completes the joke by stating the minor inconvenience, which is comically disproportionate to the baby's crying.

The top text sets up the scenario, often describing a situation of comfort or privilege. It serves as the first half of the complaint, establishing the context for the minor problem that will be revealed below.

Unhappy-Baby.image_description: This meme, known as "First World Problems" or "Crying Baby," features a stock photo of a baby crying hysterically. The image is used to humorously complain about trivial inconveniences experienced by people in wealthy, developed nations. The humor arises from the stark contrast between the baby's intense emotional distress and the minor, often absurd, problem being described.

Alan-Greenspan.name: Alan-Greenspan

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This text typically contains a blunt, overly simplistic, or nonsensical solution to the problem or situation established in the top text. Its placement at the bottom delivers the final, humorous blow.
The top text of the meme, which sets up the premise or joke. This text usually describes a complex modern problem, a complaint, or a question that the figure in the image is about to address.

Alan-Greenspan.image_description: This meme features a photo of Alan Greenspan, former Chair of the Federal Reserve, speaking authoritatively and pointing his finger. The format is a classic top-text, bottom-text macro used to deliver comically simplistic, out-of-touch, or absurd advice. The humor arises from the contrast between the serious, expert-looking figure and the nonsensical or overly blunt statement he makes.

Dat-Boi.name: Dat-Boi

text_options.description: This bottom text box is for the punchline or reaction to Dat Boi's arrival. The classic text here is 'o shit waddup!', expressing surprise and excitement, completing the iconic catchphrase of the meme.
The top text box serves as the setup for the meme. It traditionally contains the announcement 'here come dat boi', introducing the character and setting the stage for the punchline below.

Dat-Boi.image_description: This meme, known as 'Dat Boi,' features a 3D-rendered green frog riding a unicycle. It became a viral internet phenomenon in 2016, celebrated for its surreal and nonsensical humor. The meme is typically used to announce the arrival of someone or something in an unexpected and amusing way, often accompanied by its signature catchphrase.

Fabulous-Frank-And-His-Snake.name: Fabulous-Frank-And-His-Snake

text_options.description: This bottom panel contains the punchline, revealing the awkward or unimpressive reality. It contrasts with the setup in the top panel, delivering the self-deprecating or cringeworthy outcome that the image itself embodies.

The top panel of the meme is used to set up an expectation or describe a situation where someone is trying to appear cool, edgy, or impressive. This text establishes the 'what I think I look like' or 'the plan' part of the joke.

Fabulous-Frank-And-His-Snake.image_description: This meme, often called 'Awkward Photoshoot Snake Guy', features a person with long hair and glam-rock attire smiling intensely while holding a large python. The image's cringeworthy and try-hard aesthetic is central to its use. The meme typically contrasts an expectation of being cool, tough, or impressive with an awkward or embarrassing reality.

Annoying-Childhood-Friend.name: Annoying-Childhood-Friend

text_options.description: The bottom text, representing the punchline delivered by the 'Annoying Childhood Friend'. This text is a pedantic, overly literal, or unnecessarily scientific correction to the statement made in the top text. A classic example is, "Actually, quantum mechanics forbids this," which highlights the character's socially unaware, know-it-all nature.
The top text, which sets up the scenario. It's typically a common phrase, a hypothetical question, or a statement made by another person that the 'Annoying Childhood Friend' is about to correct.

Annoying-Childhood-Friend.image_description: This is the "Annoying Childhood Friend" meme, featuring a stock photo of a young boy smiling smugly at the camera from a low angle. The character represents a stereotypical know-it-all or pedant who enjoys correcting others with overly technical or literal information. The meme is used to satirize people who offer unsolicited, often irrelevant corrections in social situations, ruining the fun or flow of a conversation.

Chester-The-Cat.name: Chester-The-Cat

text_options.description: The bottom text, placed below the cat, serves as the punchline. It describes the cat's (or the subject's) state of inaction or relaxation, often with a simple word like 'Chillin'' or a phrase describing a trivial activity, creating a humorous contrast with the responsibility mentioned in the top text.
The top text, positioned above the cat, sets up the context for the meme. It typically describes a pressing situation, a responsibility, or a problem that the subject should be addressing.

Chester-The-Cat.image_description: This meme, known as 'Chilling Cat' or 'Cat Sitting Like a Human,' features an orange cat sitting on a bed in a slumped, human-like posture. The cat's relaxed and unbothered expression is used to represent procrastination, indifference, or simply relaxing when one should be doing something else. It typically follows a top-text/bottom-text format where a responsibility is stated, and the cat's state of 'chilling' is the punchline.

Sweaty-Concentrated-Rage-Face.name: Sweaty-Concentrated-Rage-Face

text_options.description: Text in this bottom region typically represents the character's internal monologue or the horrifying realization that causes the panic. It's the punchline that reveals the specific reason for their extreme stress, often a thought like 'I forgot to do the homework'.

Text placed at the top of the head usually sets up the external situation or event that triggers the character's anxiety. This provides the context for the panic, such as 'When the teacher says she's collecting the homework'.

Sweaty-Concentrated-Rage-Face.image_description: This image features a classic rage comic character known as the 'Oh Crap' or 'Sweating' face. The crudely drawn, black-and-white face is shown sweating profusely with wide, panicked eyes, expressing intense anxiety or a sudden, dreadful realization. This meme is used as a reaction to a high-stakes or stressful situation, often as the final panel in a comic where the character understands they are in deep trouble.

Fk-Yeah.name: Fk-Yeah

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned over the character's body. This is the punchline, typically expressing the character's defiant acceptance of the challenge stated in the top text, such as 'Challenge Accepted' or a description of their determined action.
The top text, placed above the character's head. This section sets up the meme by presenting a difficult, impossible, or absurd challenge or statement.

Fk-Yeah.image_description: This image features a rage comic character known as the 'Determined' or 'Challenge Accepted' face. The character is a simple stick figure with a grimacing, upward-looking expression and a single tear, signifying a difficult or painful struggle they are resolved to overcome. This meme is used to express a defiant acceptance of a difficult, absurd, or impossible task, often with a humorous or self-deprecating tone.

He-Will-Never-Get-A-Girlfriend.name: He-Will-Never-Get-A-Girlfriend

text_options.description: This area depicts the "Cereal Guy" character, who is reacting with shock and disbelief by spitting out his cereal. In the full meme format, this character is reacting to a subsequent image that contradicts the statement in the speech bubble. His over-the-top reaction is the comedic core of the meme.

This speech bubble contains the canonical phrase "He will never have a Girlfriend." This text serves as the setup, representing a condescending or judgmental prediction about someone. The humor of the meme format comes from this prediction being proven spectacularly wrong.

He-Will-Never-Get-A-Girlfriend.image_description: This meme features the rage comic character known as "Cereal Guy" spitting out his cereal in shock. A speech bubble above him contains a dismissive statement, setting up a punchline. The meme, titled "He will never have a Girlfriend," is typically used as the first panel in a two-part format to express disbelief when someone unexpectedly achieves something, often finding a romantic partner, thus proving the initial judgment wrong.
He-Will-Never-Get-A-Girlfriend.display_name: He Will Never Get A Girlfriend

Grumpy-Cat-Top-Hat.name: Grumpy-Cat-Top-Hat

text_options.description: This is the bottom text, which serves as the punchline. It contains a negative, cynical, or sarcastic response to the setup in the top text, directly reflecting Grumpy Cat's perpetually unimpressed expression. A common and classic punchline for this meme is simply the word "NO."

This is the top text, which sets up the premise of the joke. It usually describes a situation, event, or feeling that is generally considered positive, fun, or exciting, creating a stark contrast with the grumpy punchline that follows.

Grumpy-Cat-Top-Hat.image_description: This meme features Tardar Sauce, the cat famously known as "Grumpy Cat," photoshopped to wear a top hat and a monocle. Her naturally perpetual frown, combined with the aristocratic accessories and a dramatic, sun-rayed background, creates a comically disdainful and unimpressed character. The meme is used to express cynicism, annoyance, or a negative opinion about a typically positive or mundane situation, with the cat's expression delivering the punchline.

Minegishi-Minami.name: Minegishi-Minami

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, describing the overwhelming task, piece of information, or stressful situation that is causing the girl's panicked reaction.
This top text box provides the setup or context for the meme. It often contains a question, a statement, or a prompt that leads to the overwhelming conclusion described in the bottom text.

Minegishi-Minami.image_description: This meme, often called "Stressed Japanese Girl," features a member of the J-pop group Angerme with a look of intense distress and overload. She has her hands on her head and a panicked expression, capturing a feeling of being completely overwhelmed. The meme is typically used to represent situations of extreme stress, anxiety, or information overload, such as facing a daunting task, a difficult exam, or a flood of notifications.

Admiral-Ackbar-Relationship-Expert.name: Admiral-Ackbar-Relationship-Expert

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is almost always the character's famous quote, "IT'S A TRAP!". This text reveals the hidden danger or deception in the scenario presented at the top, creating the core humor of the meme.
The top text sets up a scenario or describes a situation that appears tempting, normal, or too good to be true. This line serves as the premise that will be subverted by the punchline below.

Admiral-Ackbar-Relationship-Expert.image_description: This meme features a headshot of Admiral Ackbar, a fish-like alien character from the Star Wars franchise, set against a red and maroon starburst background. Known as the "It's a Trap!" meme, it leverages Ackbar's iconic line from the film "Return of the Jedi." The format is used to humorously warn that a seemingly appealing or innocent situation is actually a trick, a deception, or has a hidden negative consequence.

Are-Your-Parents-Brother-And-Sister.name: Are-Your-Parents-Brother-And-Sister

text_options.description: The bottom text box, positioned over the man's lap, contains the punchline or reaction. This text verbalizes the man's disgusted expression, often with a question like "What is this?" or a statement of confusion, directly responding to the setup.

The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a bizarre, unpleasant, or confusing situation, object, or statement that elicits the man's disgusted reaction in the image below.

Are-Your-Parents-Brother-And-Sister.image_description: This meme, known as "What is this?" or "Disgusted Guy," features a man with a repulsed and confused expression looking at the camera. He is sitting outside at night, holding a small object on a stick. The image is used as a reaction to something strange, undesirable, or confusing, perfectly capturing a moment of disgust and bewilderment.
Are-Your-Parents-Brother-And-Sister.display_name: Are Your Parents Brother And Sister

Tom-Hardy-.name: Tom-Hardy-

text_options.description: This bottom caption describes the item, idea, or person that the user prefers. It represents the 'I like this' part of the meme, often highlighting a simpler, more personal, or unconventional choice that is favored over a more popular or objectively 'better' alternative.

The top text sets up the context or scenario for the meme. It often introduces a situation or a category from which a choice is being made, providing the setup for the preference stated in the bottom caption.

Tom-Hardy-.image_description: A close-up of actor Tom Hardy as Forrest Bondurant from the film 'Lawless', wearing a fedora and looking intently to the side with a serious, almost disapproving expression. This image is the second panel of the 'This is brilliant, but I like this' meme format, where this panel represents the preferred, often simpler or more personal, choice. On its own, the image is used to express a strong, unwavering preference or a simple, direct statement.

Im-Curious-Nappa.name: Im-Curious-Nappa

text_options.description: The bottom text is the punchline of the meme. It typically exclaims "IT'S OVER [A LARGE NUMBER]!" to express shock at the quantity mentioned in the setup text. The original and most famous line is "IT'S OVER 9000!", but this number is often customized to fit the specific context of the meme.

The top text sets up the joke by asking a question or making a statement that involves a numerical value. For example, it might ask, "What is his power level?" or "How many unread emails do you have?", creating the context for the exaggerated response below.

Im-Curious-Nappa.image_description: This image is from the anime Dragon Ball Z and features the character Nappa looking shocked and angry while wearing a scouter over his left eye. This scene is closely associated with the famous "It's Over 9000!" meme, which is used to express extreme surprise or disbelief at a number or quantity that is unexpectedly and overwhelmingly large. The meme format typically involves a question or statement about a value, followed by the punchline revealing that the value is far greater than anticipated.

Onde.name: Onde

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline or the shocking revelation. It's a statement that drastically contrasts with the setup in the top text, causing the horrified reaction depicted in the image. The humor relies on this text being unexpected, bizarre, or disturbing.
This top text box provides the setup for the joke. It usually describes a seemingly normal or mundane situation, setting the context for the punchline that follows below.

Onde.image_description: This meme, often called "Staring Man" or "Old Man Staring," features a close-up of an elderly man with wide, bulging eyes and an open mouth, conveying a look of intense shock or horror. It's a reaction image used in a two-panel format to express disbelief or being startled by an unexpected and often disturbing revelation. The humor comes from the extreme reaction to the punchline presented in the text.

Nailed-It.name: Nailed-It

text_options.description: This text box is at the bottom of the image, often on the boat or near the crashing person. It typically contains the punchline or the disastrous outcome that subverts the initial plan mentioned at the top. This text represents the "reality" or the failure.

Located in the sky area at the top, this text box is used for the setup of the meme. It describes a plan, a goal, or an optimistic expectation. This text sets the stage for the humorous failure depicted below.

Nailed-It.image_description: This meme, known as "Wakeboarding Fail," shows a person dramatically wiping out while wakeboarding, with their legs and board in the air and their head submerged. The image humorously contrasts an initial plan or expectation with a disastrous outcome. It's a classic "plan vs. reality" or "expectation vs. reality" format where the setup leads to an inevitable and comical failure.

Saw-Fulla.name: Saw-Fulla

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, almost always starting with a variation of Jigsaw's catchphrase, "I want to play a game." It reveals the specific, often trivial or annoying, prank that the user wants to initiate, contrasting with the serious tone of the character.

The top text sets up the context or scenario for the meme. It usually describes a situation that gives the user an opportunity to play a prank or be slightly mischievous, leading into the punchline below.

Saw-Fulla.image_description: This meme features a close-up of John Kramer, also known as Jigsaw, the antagonist from the 'Saw' horror film series, staring intensely. Known for his line "I want to play a game," the meme subverts his menacing persona for humorous effect. It's typically used to frame a petty prank or a slightly mischievous act as a high-stakes "game."

Brian-Griffin.name: Brian-Griffin

text_options.description: Located at the bottom, this text acts as a news ticker or subtitle, delivering the main punchline of the meme. It represents Brian's sarcastic, witty, or absurd commentary on the topic established by the text in box 1.

Positioned at the top of the image, this text typically serves as a headline, a news channel name, or the subject of the 'report.' It sets up the context or premise for the joke or commentary that Brian delivers in the text at the bottom (box 0).

Brian-Griffin.image_description: This meme features Brian Griffin, the anthropomorphic dog from the animated show "Family Guy," sitting in a chair with a smug, presentational pose. The format mimics a news report where Brian offers a sarcastic, humorous, or often absurd commentary on a given topic. It's used to mock news headlines, express a cynical opinion, or deliver a punchline in a news-like format.

Close-Enough.name: Close-Enough

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline and the name of the meme, "CLOSE ENOUGH." This text is almost always present and conveys the core message of accepting a less-than-perfect but satisfactory result.

This top text area is typically used to describe a situation or action that leads to the imperfect outcome. It sets up the context for the punchline, explaining what the person was trying to do before settling for a 'close enough' result.

Close-Enough.image_description: This is a rage comic meme known as "Close Enough." It features a crudely drawn stick figure with a smug and satisfied expression, despite a situation not going perfectly. The meme is used to express satisfaction with a mediocre or imperfect outcome, celebrating the idea that a result is good enough, even if it's not ideal. It's often used to humorously portray laziness or cutting corners.

Hawkward.name: Hawkward

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or the surprising outcome. It reveals an unexpected twist, a contradictory fact, or an absurd result that contrasts with the setup in the top panel, causing the hawk's shocked reaction.
The top text box serves as the setup for the joke. It typically describes a situation, an action, or a statement that seems normal or has a clear expectation associated with it.
