Cereal-Guy.image_description: This is a two-panel meme template featuring the rage comic character known as "Cereal Guy." In the top panel, Cereal Guy makes a dismissive or negative prediction about someone or something, often based on an early, unimpressive appearance. The bottom panel shows him reacting with a shocked "spit take," spitting out his cereal after seeing a later, much more impressive version of the same subject. The meme is used to highlight surprising transformations, "glow-ups," or ironic outcomes that defy initial expectations.

Bad-Wife-Worse-Mom.name: Bad-Wife-Worse-Mom

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or reaction. This text is typically a very short, often single-word, formal response like 'Sir,' 'Ma'am,' or a phrase like 'The audacity.' This terse, judgmental reply humorously contrasts with the outrageous statement presented in the top text box.

The top text box provides the setup for the meme. It contains a statement, quote, or description of an action that is meant to be perceived as shocking, inappropriate, or utterly absurd, thereby eliciting the horrified reaction from Queen Gorgo.

Bad-Wife-Worse-Mom.image_description: This meme features a still of Queen Gorgo from the movie '300', played by Lena Headey. She has a look of intense concern, shock, and disbelief. The format is used as a reaction image to express judgment or horror towards an absurd, offensive, or cringeworthy statement. The meme's humor comes from her serious, dramatic expression being applied to mundane or ridiculous situations.

Rob-In-The-Hood.name: Rob-In-The-Hood

text_options.description: This label is placed on Robin Hood's body and typically identifies the person, group, or entity experiencing the feeling of satisfaction.
This text, positioned above Robin Hood's head, describes the ideal situation, event, or condition that is causing the subject's blissful contentment.

Rob-In-The-Hood.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Robin Hood from the 1973 Disney animated film, depicted as an anthropomorphic fox. He is shown with a blissful, contented expression, smiling with his eyes closed, conveying a sense of perfect satisfaction. The meme is used to represent a feeling of pure happiness or when a situation turns out exactly as one hoped, often in a wholesome or gratifying way.

Overly-Attached-Father.name: Overly-Attached-Father

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline of the meme, which is the threat or consequence. It's a parody of the iconic line from the movie, "I will look for you, I will find you, and I will kill you," but adapted to the specific, often trivial, situation mentioned in the top text.

The top text sets up the scenario by describing an action or person that has provoked the meme's creator. It often begins with a variation of "I don't know who you are," directly quoting the movie to establish the threatening but comical tone.

Overly-Attached-Father.image_description: This meme features actor Liam Neeson pointing at the viewer with a serious expression, a pose that references his character Bryan Mills from the action film "Taken." The image is used as a reaction macro to express a humorous or exaggerated threat in response to an annoyance. The format typically follows the structure of his famous monologue from the film, where he threatens his daughter's kidnappers.

Hot-Caleb.name: Hot-Caleb

text_options.description: This bottom section contains the punchline, which is almost invariably the phrase "well that's a bit sad innit". This text serves as a dismissive and anticlimactic response to the statement presented in the top panel, providing the core humor of the meme.

The top panel of the meme, acting as the setup. This area typically features a quote, a screenshot of a social media post, or a statement where someone is bragging, seeking validation, or sharing something they believe is cool, but which comes across as cringeworthy or pathetic.

Hot-Caleb.image_description: This meme, known as "Well That's a Bit Sad" or "Sad Cunt," features a young man in a grey shirt and tie posing awkwardly. The image is typically used in a two-panel format to express a deflating or judgmental reaction to a preceding statement. The man's earnest yet slightly melancholic expression enhances the meme's punchline, which dismisses someone's attempt to be impressive as pathetic or sad.

Hora-Extra.name: Hora-Extra

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the pile of money. The text here typically represents the financial aspect, the reward, or the outcome of a situation. It's the "money" part of the "time is money" equation.

This text box is placed at the top, near the alarm clock. The text here usually represents the time, effort, or action required to achieve the outcome described in the bottom text. It's the "time" part of the "time is money" equation.

Hora-Extra.image_description: This stock image shows a classic twin-bell alarm clock resting on a large pile of hundred-dollar bills, visually representing the idiom "time is money." In memes, this image is used to illustrate a trade-off or direct relationship between two concepts. The two labels typically represent the time/effort invested and the monetary/tangible reward gained, often in a humorous or relatable context.

Bad-Luck-Hannah.name: Bad-Luck-Hannah

text_options.description: The bottom text of the image macro, which completes the thought started in the top text. It typically names a very common or mainstream hobby or interest, such as "and I play video games." The mundanity of the complete statement is key to the meme's humor, as it contrasts with the exaggerated reaction it supposedly elicits.

The top text of the image macro, which serves as the setup for the meme. This text usually begins a statement declaring a simple fact or preference, often starting with "I'm a girl..." or "I like..." to introduce the subject.

Bad-Luck-Hannah.image_description: This meme, known as "I'm a girl" or "A Girl Worth Fighting For," features a selfie of a young woman with glasses. It's typically used as the top panel in a two-panel reaction format. The meme humorously satirizes online interactions by pairing a simple statement about a common interest (e.g., liking video games) with a second image showing an overwhelmingly enthusiastic reaction, often from a large group of men.

Criana.name: Criana

text_options.description: The bottom text, positioned near the baby's lower body, serves as the punchline. It contains the skeptical thought, question, or realization that casts doubt on the initial statement from the top text. This text directly voices the baby's suspicious expression.
The top text, placed above the baby's head, sets up the scenario or presents a statement. This is the premise that the baby's expression is reacting to, which will be questioned by the bottom text.

Criana.image_description: This meme, known as "Skeptical Baby" or "Suspicious Baby," features a toddler with a pouty, frowning expression, looking upwards with suspicion. The image is used to express doubt or question the logic of a statement or situation. The format typically presents a premise followed by a skeptical thought that reveals a contradiction or absurdity, perfectly captured by the baby's dubious look.

Asshole-Ref.name: Asshole-Ref

text_options.description: This area, covering the soccer player and the referee, is typically labeled with the name of a person, group, or entity that is being subjected to an overwhelming number of rules, criticisms, or penalties. This is the main subject of the meme's joke.

Positioned above the main action, this text box usually identifies the source of the overwhelming criticism or the authority figure imposing the rules. It represents the person, institution, or concept that is 'punishing' the subject labeled in box 0.

Asshole-Ref.image_description: A meme template showing a soccer referee holding up a large handful of red and yellow cards towards a player, Miroslav Klose, who looks on with a resigned expression. This exaggerated scene is used to humorously depict someone being overwhelmed with an excessive number of punishments, criticisms, or rules all at once. The referee represents the punishing authority, while the player represents the person or entity receiving the overwhelming negative feedback.

Romney.name: Romney

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. The text here is the surprising, funny, or absurd statement that supposedly caused the girl's shocked reaction, subverting the expectation set by the top text.
This is the setup text for the meme. It typically poses a question or makes a statement that creates a normal expectation, setting the stage for the unexpected punchline below.

Romney.image_description: This meme, often called "Mitt Romney's Awkward Moment" or "Shocked Girl," features American politician Mitt Romney interacting with a young girl who has a comically shocked or amazed expression. The image is used as a two-part joke format, where a setup line is presented, followed by an unexpected, absurd, or cringeworthy punchline that supposedly caused the girl's extreme reaction. The humor comes from the bait-and-switch nature of the text overlay.

Frustrating-Mom.name: Frustrating-Mom

text_options.description: This text is placed at the bottom of the image, often over the daughter. It represents the person, object, or concept that is neglected, criticized, or less favored in the comparison.

This text is placed at the top of the image, covering the mother and the son. It represents the person, object, or concept that is praised, preferred, and receives all the positive attention, contrasting with the entity at the bottom.

Frustrating-Mom.image_description: This meme, known as "The Favorite Child" or "Mom's Favorite," features a stock photo of a mother baking with her two children. The girl points at her brother, who gives a thumbs-up, while the mother looks on with an excited expression. The format is used to humorously contrast two entities, where the one associated with the mother and son is clearly favored over the one associated with the daughter.

Modern-Warfare-3.name: Modern-Warfare-3

text_options.description: This area contains the original 'Call of Duty MW3' logo from the promotional art. While it's part of the source image, it grounds the meme in the context of a first-person shooter game, reinforcing the theme of combat and serious preparation.

This is the top caption area, typically used to set up the scenario. The text here usually describes a situation that triggers the extreme reaction embodied by the soldier, such as a bullying incident or a moment of final-straw frustration, often in the context of dark humor.

Modern-Warfare-3.image_description: This meme features a promotional image of a soldier from the video game 'Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 3'. The soldier is depicted in full combat gear with a serious, focused expression, ready for action. This image is commonly used in edgy memes, often starting with the phrase 'When the quiet kid...', to humorously or darkly represent someone preparing for a serious or extreme confrontation after being provoked.

Jim-Lehrer-The-Man.name: Jim-Lehrer-The-Man

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline. It often reads 'Unsolved Mysteries' or a humorous variation, acting as a dramatic conclusion to the trivial problem presented in the top text, mimicking the show's tone.
The top text box sets up the premise of the meme. It describes a confusing, contradictory, or unexplainable situation that serves as the 'mystery' for Robert Stack to present.

Jim-Lehrer-The-Man.image_description: This meme features Robert Stack, the host of the TV show 'Unsolved Mysteries,' looking serious and gesturing as if presenting a case. The format is used to humorously frame everyday puzzles or absurd situations as profound, unsolved cases. The top text describes a confusing scenario, and the bottom text delivers a punchline, often a variation of the show's title, to create a sense of mock-dramatic mystery.

Wrong-Number-Rita.name: Wrong-Number-Rita

text_options.description: The bottom text is the primary punchline. It's typically a completely random or nonsensical statement that has no connection to the image of licking an orange, creating humor through its sheer absurdity and irrelevance.

The top text, often used as a setup, provides a context or statement that is made humorous or bizarre by the image and the bottom text. It can establish a premise that the rest of the meme playfully ignores or subverts.

Wrong-Number-Rita.image_description: The 'I Lick the Orange' meme, also known as 'Annoying Facebook Girl,' features a person licking an orange with a vacant expression. This image is a classic example of early internet absurdism and random humor. It's typically used to represent pointless, attention-seeking, or bizarre actions, often paired with a completely unrelated caption to enhance the nonsensical nature of the scene.

Brian-Wilson-Vs-ZZ-Top.name: Brian-Wilson-Vs-ZZ-Top

text_options.description: This text, placed over the members of ZZ Top, represents the superior, ultimate, or "final boss" version in the comparison. It's the punchline that one-ups the subject in the top panel, highlighting their legendary status in the world of beards.

Text in this position, over baseball player Brian Wilson, introduces the initial subject of comparison. This label typically represents the standard or "player" version of something that is impressive on its own but is about to be outdone by the subject in the panel below.

Brian-Wilson-Vs-ZZ-Top.image_description: This two-panel meme contrasts baseball pitcher Brian Wilson, known for his impressive black beard, with the rock band ZZ Top, famous for their legendary, much longer beards. The meme format is used for comparison, presenting something impressive (Wilson) followed by a superior or more extreme version of the same thing (ZZ Top). It humorously illustrates a hierarchy or an escalation, similar to the "You vs. The Guy She Tells You Not to Worry About" trope.

Hardworking-Guy.name: Hardworking-Guy

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image typically contains a caption identifying the observer, often starting with 'Me:'. This text establishes the perspective of the person who is doing the intense staring.

This top section of the image contains a caption describing the person or action being watched. This text provides the context for the observer's intense focus, completing the humorous and relatable scenario.

Hardworking-Guy.image_description: This meme, often known as 'Creepy Hector,' features a man in a light blue polo shirt sitting at a desk and smiling knowingly at the camera. The meme is used to represent a person who is intensely, and often creepily, observing someone else in a relatable social situation. The humor comes from pairing the man's sly expression with a caption describing an everyday scenario of silent judgment or observation.

Efrain-Juarez.name: Efrain-Juarez

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the punchline of the meme. It's where the incredibly obvious or redundant statement is written, presented as if it were a shocking or profound discovery.

The scoreboard area is often edited to provide context or a setup for the obvious statement below. It can be a question that the punchline answers, or a label identifying the person making the obvious statement (e.g., "Captain Obvious").

Efrain-Juarez.image_description: This meme, known as "Captain Obvious" or "Capitán Óbvio," features Colombian soccer player Aquivaldo Mosquera looking shocked with his hand over his mouth. The image is taken from a soccer match and captures a moment of surprise. The meme is used to sarcastically point out something that is incredibly self-evident, with the player's expression representing a feigned shock at the obvious "revelation."

Memeo.name: Memeo

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline or the second, more stressful situation. This text escalates the problem presented in the top text, justifying the man's extreme expression of panic.
The top text box sets up the meme by presenting an initial stressful or challenging scenario. This text serves as the premise that will be intensified by the bottom text.

Memeo.image_description: This meme, known as "Stressed Out Guy" or "Tensed Guy," features a man with a comically terrified expression against a backdrop of a lightning storm. The image is used to represent an extreme reaction of stress, panic, or shock. It's typically a two-part macro where two related, compounding stressful situations are described, with the man's face serving as the reaction to the overwhelming combination.

Superior-Wadsworth.name: Superior-Wadsworth

text_options.description: This bottom text box, placed over the gun, typically contains the punchline or the hidden threat. It represents the "or else" part of a seemingly polite request, revealing the true, forceful nature of the situation.

The top text box is used for a seemingly polite or innocent statement or request. This sets up the premise of a normal interaction, which is then subverted by the character's threatening posture and the text in the bottom box.

Superior-Wadsworth.image_description: This meme features actor Tim Curry as Wadsworth the butler from the 1985 film "Clue." He is smiling warmly at the viewer while pointing a small pistol, creating a humorous contrast between a polite demeanor and an underlying threat. The meme is used to represent situations where a friendly request or statement is backed by a non-negotiable, often sinister, ultimatum.

Brian-Burke-On-The-Phone.name: Brian-Burke-On-The-Phone

text_options.description: This bottom caption often describes the person or group who is confused, such as 'My dad when...' or 'Me trying to understand...'. It provides the perspective of the person reacting to the confusing subject matter mentioned in the top text.

The top text box typically contains the source of confusion. This is often a modern slang term, a confusing text message, a new social media trend, or any concept that would be unfamiliar to an older person, setting up the punchline.

Brian-Burke-On-The-Phone.image_description: This meme features a close-up of Brian Burke, a hockey executive, squinting at his phone with a look of confusion. Known as the 'Confused Old Man' or 'Old Man Using Phone' meme, it humorously portrays the perceived difficulty older generations have with modern technology or youth culture. The format typically contrasts a confusing modern concept or slang term with the man's bewildered expression, representing a generational gap in understanding.

Pickup-Professor.name: Pickup-Professor

text_options.description: This bottom section of the image is where the punchline of the joke is placed. The text here is typically a pun, often related to chemistry or science, that serves as the answer to the setup presented in the top panel.
The top part of the image serves as the setup for the meme. Text here usually poses a question or presents the first half of a statement that will be completed by a pun in the bottom panel.

Pickup-Professor.image_description: This meme, often called "Chemistry Cat" or "Science Major," features a stock photo of a male and female scientist in a lab. The woman holds up a test tube with a mischievous expression, while the man looks down at the various beakers on the table. The meme is typically used as a two-panel format to tell science-related puns or dad jokes, with the setup at the top and the punchline at the bottom, as if the joke is the result of their chemical experiment.

Insanity-Puppy.name: Insanity-Puppy

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the pun or joke. Placed over the intense, close-up stare of the husky, this text delivers the comedic, often cringeworthy, conclusion to the setup in the top panel.
The text in the top panel is the setup for a pun. It's usually a question or the first part of a statement that establishes the context for the wordplay that follows in the second panel.

Insanity-Puppy.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as "Pun Dog" or "Bad Pun Dog," features a Siberian Husky puppy. The top panel shows the puppy sitting and looking away, which serves as the setup for a joke. The bottom panel is a close-up of the dog's face staring intently at the viewer, delivering the punchline. This format is used to tell simple puns or "dad jokes," with the dog's final expression humorously representing the awkward pause after a bad joke.

Scumbag-Redditor.name: Scumbag-Redditor

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which serves as the punchline. This text describes the selfish, unethical, or inconsiderate action that contradicts the setup presented in the top text, revealing the character's 'scumbag' nature.

The top text of the meme, which sets up a situation or context. It often describes a promise, a social norm, or a seemingly positive statement that the 'scumbag' character will then subvert in the bottom text.

Scumbag-Redditor.image_description: This is the 'Scumbag Steve' meme, featuring the Reddit mascot, Snoo, wearing the characteristic brown plaid scumbag hat. This variation is often called 'Scumbag Redditor.' The meme is used to call out selfish, hypocritical, or annoying behavior, particularly within the context of the Reddit community. It's a two-part image macro where the top text sets up a scenario, and the bottom text reveals the 'scumbag' action or punchline.

Friend-Zone-Fiona.name: Friend-Zone-Fiona

text_options.description: The bottom text serves as the punchline, delivering the woman's clueless or dismissive response. This text typically highlights the platonic nature of their relationship, effectively putting the man in the "friend zone" (e.g., "You're like a brother to me").
The top text sets up the joke by describing an action or statement from a man who is trying to express romantic feelings for the woman. It establishes the context for the inevitable rejection.

Friend-Zone-Fiona.image_description: This meme, known as "Friendzone Fiona" or "Laughing Woman," features a stock photo of a blonde woman laughing. It is an advice animal-style image macro used to represent a woman who obliviously rejects a man's romantic advances. The format involves a setup line at the top describing a man's romantic gesture, followed by a punchline at the bottom with the woman's response that places him in the "friend zone."

Crazy-Girlfriend-Praying-Mantis.name: Crazy-Girlfriend-Praying-Mantis

text_options.description: The bottom text box, typically on the blue background section, delivers the punchline or the outcome of the social situation. It contrasts with the setup in the top text. For example, if the top described a socially awesome action, the bottom would reveal an awkward consequence, or vice versa, creating the core humor of the meme.

The top text box, typically on the red or, in this case, cyan background section, sets up a social scenario. This line describes the initial action or situation, which is either socially awkward or socially awesome, setting the stage for the contrasting outcome described in the bottom text.

Crazy-Girlfriend-Praying-Mantis.image_description: This is a variation of the "Socially Awkward/Awesome Penguin" advice animal meme format, featuring the head of a green praying mantis instead of the typical penguin. The background is a color wheel split into eight wedges of alternating blue and cyan. The meme's structure contrasts a social situation (top text) with its outcome (bottom text), creating humor from the juxtaposition of awkwardness and success.

Helpful-Tyler-Durden.name: Helpful-Tyler-Durden

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is almost always a variation of 'You do not talk about [subject]'. The humor comes from the contradiction of stating a rule about secrecy while simultaneously breaking it.
The top text sets up the meme, typically starting with 'The first rule of [subject] is...'. The subject can be anything from a real-life group to a fictional concept or an inside joke.

Helpful-Tyler-Durden.image_description: This is an Advice Animal-style meme featuring the character Tyler Durden from the movie 'Fight Club'. Known as 'The First Rule of Fight Club', the meme plays on the film's iconic line about not talking about the secret club. It is used ironically to introduce a topic or inside joke by stating that the first rule is not to talk about it, thus immediately breaking the rule.

Family-Tech-Support-Guy.name: Family-Tech-Support-Guy

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the punchline, which is the character's hypocritical, entitled, or comically angry response to the situation described above. This text is the core of the meme, showcasing the "butthurt" reaction that gives the character his name.

The top text sets up a scenario, often a common or reasonable situation in video games, online forums, or social interactions. This text serves as the premise that will trigger the character's unreasonable reaction in the bottom text.

Family-Tech-Support-Guy.image_description: This meme, known as "Butthurt Dweller" or "Gamer," features a young man with a sullen expression against a black, white, and grey starburst background. It's an advice animal-style image macro used to satirize stereotypical, entitled, or easily offended internet users, particularly within gaming culture. The format uses a top-down setup and punchline to highlight hypocritical or overly dramatic complaints about trivial matters.

Who-Would-Win.name: Who-Would-Win

text_options.description: This box on the right is typically used to introduce the second contender, who is often portrayed as an underdog or a seemingly weaker opponent. The text or image placed here describes a character, object, or concept that has a specific, often overlooked, advantage that makes it the surprise winner in the matchup.

This box on the left is for the first contender in the matchup. This side usually represents a powerful, formidable, or overwhelmingly large force, such as an army, a god-like character, or a massive number of something. This sets up the expectation that this contender should easily win, which the meme then subverts.

Who-Would-Win.image_description: This is the "Who Would Win?" meme template, a popular exploitable format used for humorous comparisons. The image is divided into two sides, posing a hypothetical battle between two opposing subjects. The humor typically arises from an ironic or unexpected outcome where a seemingly weaker or absurd character on one side would logically defeat a powerful opponent on the other.

Are-they-in-the-room-with-us-right-now.name: Are-they-in-the-room-with-us-right-now

text_options.description: This area at the bottom of the image is used to label the two individuals. The detective on the left typically represents an authority figure, a group, or a concept that is questioning or judging. The suspect on the right represents the person or idea being scrutinized, often portrayed as guilty, weird, or in a vulnerable position.

Text placed in this upper region provides the context for the confrontation. It usually describes the specific situation, action, or belief that is the subject of the 'interrogation' between the two parties labeled below.

Are-they-in-the-room-with-us-right-now.image_description: This meme originates from a police interrogation video of Nikolas Cruz, the Parkland school shooter. The image depicts a detective (left) questioning Cruz (right), who is wearing a hospital gown. The meme is used to represent a serious, awkward, or judgmental confrontation where one party is being questioned or scrutinized by another, often for a mistake, a strange habit, or a controversial opinion.
Are-they-in-the-room-with-us-right-now.display_name: Are they in the room with us right now

cross-eyed-spongebob.name: cross-eyed-spongebob

text_options.description: Text placed on the right page of the book. This area represents one of two conflicting options, ideas, or pieces of information that are causing the dilemma.
Text placed on the left page of the book. This area represents the second conflicting option, which is juxtaposed with the text on the right page to create the central conflict of the meme.
Text positioned above SpongeBob's head. This label identifies the person, group, or entity that is struggling with the difficult choice presented on the two pages of the book.

cross-eyed-spongebob.image_description: This meme features the character SpongeBob SquarePants from the eponymous TV show, looking intensely stressed while reading a book with two open pages. Known as "SpongeBob Reading Two Pages" or "SpongeBob's Tough Decision," the format illustrates a difficult choice or the struggle to reconcile two conflicting ideas. The two pages of the book represent the opposing options, while SpongeBob represents the person or entity agonizing over the decision.

Hes-probably-thinking-about-girls.name: Hes-probably-thinking-about-girls

text_options.description: This area represents the man's actual thoughts and serves as the punchline of the meme. The text here is typically a mundane, silly, or deeply philosophical question that is completely unrelated to the relationship, subverting the expectation set by the woman's suspicion.

This area represents the woman's internal monologue, often framed as a thought bubble. The text here almost invariably expresses her suspicion, such as, "He's probably thinking about other women." This line acts as the setup for the joke.

Hes-probably-thinking-about-girls.image_description: This meme, known as "Man Thinking in Bed" or sometimes "Distracted Boyfriend in Bed," features a stock photo of a couple lying in bed, turned away from each other. The woman looks upset and suspicious, while the man stares into the distance, seemingly lost in thought. The humor arises from the contrast between what the woman assumes he's thinking (usually about infidelity) and the actual, often trivial, absurd, or nerdy thought that occupies his mind.

and-I-took-that-personally.name: and-I-took-that-personally

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, the direct quote from Michael Jordan: '...and I took that personally'. This text is almost always present and serves as the reaction to the setup text placed at the top of the image. It conveys a sense of intense, often comically disproportionate, personal investment in the preceding statement or event.

This top section is where the user adds custom text to set up the joke. The text typically describes a mundane action, a neutral statement, or a minor slight from someone else. This setup provides the context for Michael Jordan's (and by extension, the meme creator's) exaggerated and personal reaction.

and-I-took-that-personally.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of basketball legend Michael Jordan from the documentary 'The Last Dance'. In the scene, Jordan is explaining how he would use perceived slights from opponents as motivation. The meme format uses this intense reaction, summed up by the quote '...and I took that personally,' to humorously describe taking a minor or imagined offense as a deep personal challenge, showcasing a petty or overly competitive response to a trivial situation.

Funeral.name: Funeral

text_options.description: This text box is placed over Grant Gustin's body. The text here represents the person, entity, or concept that is benefiting from, celebrating, or is indifferent to the demise of the subject on the gravestone. This is the 'winner' or the triumphant party in the meme's narrative.

This text box is placed on Oliver Queen's gravestone. The text here represents the person, idea, or thing that has been defeated, replaced, or has failed. It is the subject of the other character's cheerful pose, representing the 'loser' or the obsolete concept in the meme's context.

Funeral.image_description: This meme, known as "Grant Gustin Next to Oliver Queen's Grave," features actor Grant Gustin (who plays The Flash) cheerfully posing with a peace sign next to the tombstone of Oliver Queen (The Green Arrow). The image is a behind-the-scenes photo from the TV show "Arrow." The meme's humor derives from the stark contrast between the somber setting of a grave and Gustin's happy demeanor, making it perfect for situations where someone is thriving or celebrating the downfall, failure, or obsolescence of something else.

Chill-guy.name: Chill-guy

text_options.description: The text here, located at the bottom of the image, typically labels the capybara. It often identifies the person or group exhibiting the calm and unbothered attitude, such as 'Me' or a specific name, setting the stage for who is reacting.

The text in this top section describes the situation or event that the capybara is nonchalantly reacting to. This is the setup, often detailing a chaotic, important, or dramatic scenario, which contrasts humorously with the character's relaxed expression.

Chill-guy.image_description: This meme features a cartoon capybara standing calmly in a field during a golden sunset. The character, known for its chill and unbothered demeanor, is often associated with the song 'After Party' by Don Toliver and the phrase 'Ok I pull up'. The meme is used to represent someone remaining cool, collected, and unfazed by a situation, often one that might normally cause stress or excitement.

I-do-ONE-Push-Up.name: I-do-ONE-Push-Up

text_options.description: This area contains the punchline of the meme, which is almost always static. The muscular character says, '...I DO ONE PUSH-UP,' and the other character reacts with 'JESUS CHRIST.' This fixed text provides the punchline that is contextualized by the user-edited text in the other box.

This is the customizable part of the meme, where the user inserts a phrase describing a very common or frequently recurring event. The original text here is 'EVERY TIME,' which is completed by the user's text to set up the joke about the event's high frequency.

I-do-ONE-Push-Up.image_description: This four-panel comic meme, known as 'I Do One Push-Up,' features a scrawny character asking an incredibly muscular character for their workout secret. The muscular figure reveals they do one push-up every time a specific event occurs. The humor comes from the implication that this event happens with such absurd frequency that it leads to a superhuman physique, making it a popular format to complain about or highlight recurring annoyances or common situations.

No-yes-lady.name: No-yes-lady

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the image of the woman looking intrigued and contemplative. The text here typically describes an alternative, often unconventional or strange idea, that is surprisingly found to be acceptable or even appealing compared to the first option.

This text box is positioned above the image of the woman making a disgusted face. The text here usually describes a concept, action, or thing that is met with strong disapproval or rejection, setting up the contrast for the second panel.

No-yes-lady.image_description: This two-panel meme features internet personality Brittany Broski, famously known as the "Kombucha Girl," reacting to trying kombucha. The left panel shows her with a face of disgust and revulsion, while the right panel captures a moment of reconsideration and intrigue. This format is used to contrast a strong initial dislike for something with a subsequent, unexpected approval or interest in an alternative, often highlighting a surprising preference.

Looks-like-meats-back-on-the-menu-boys.name: Looks-like-meats-back-on-the-menu-boys

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image contains the punchline, which is a modified version of the original movie quote. It typically reads, 'Looks like [X]'s back on the menu, boys!', where '[X]' is the thing that has made a comeback.

This label is placed over the Uruk-hai to identify the person or group who is excited about the return of the item mentioned in the punchline. It provides context by specifying who is making the declaration.

Looks-like-meats-back-on-the-menu-boys.image_description: This meme features a screenshot of an Uruk-hai from the film 'The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers'. In the original scene, the character famously declares, 'Looks like meat's back on the menu, boys!'. This format is used to humorously announce the return of something that has been absent or unavailable, with the word 'meat' being replaced by the returning item, concept, or activity.
Looks-like-meats-back-on-the-menu-boys.display_name: Looks like meats back on the menu boys

You-made-thisI-made-this.name: You-made-thisI-made-this

text_options.description: A label for the plagiarist or thief in the final panel, who is now falsely claiming credit for the creation.
A label for the stolen idea, content, or product, now in the possession of the plagiarist who claims to have made it.
A label for the character who is stealing the creation, shown in the middle panel as they walk away with it.
A label for the creation itself as it is being taken by the second character in the middle panel.
A label for the character who will become the plagiarist, shown here in the first panel innocently observing the original creation.
A label for the original creation, idea, or piece of content being proudly presented by its actual creator.
A label for the original creator of the work, who is proudly presenting their creation in the first panel.

You-made-thisI-made-this.image_description: This meme, known as "I Made This," is a three-panel comic strip illustrating plagiarism or intellectual property theft. In the first panel, a proud creator shows their work to another character, who then takes it in the second panel. In the final panel, the second character shamelessly claims the creation as their own, saying "I made this." This format is widely used to criticize individuals, companies, or groups for stealing ideas, content, or work from others and passing it off as original.

Born-Died-Welcome-Back.name: Born-Died-Welcome-Back

text_options.description: This text box, positioned next to "welcome back," contains the name of the person, object, or concept that has made a return. It serves as the punchline, identifying the subject of the meme's narrative of disappearance and reappearance.
Located next to the word "Born," this text box is where the date, event, or cause of the subject's reappearance or "rebirth" is placed. It marks the moment of the comeback.

Positioned next to the word "Died," this text box is filled with the date, event, or reason for the subject's initial disappearance or decline in relevance. It establishes the first part of the meme's timeline.

Born-Died-Welcome-Back.image_description: This is the "Welcome Back" meme template, which is used to humorously comment on the return or resurgence of a person, trend, or concept. The format mimics an informational display, showing when something "Died" (became irrelevant or disappeared) and when it was "Born" again (made a comeback). The punchline is delivered at the bottom, identifying the subject being welcomed back after its revival.

Ermahgerd-Berks.name: Ermahgerd-Berks

text_options.description: The bottom section of the image provides the punchline or the specific object of excitement. The text here names what the person is so thrilled about, also in the phonetic 'Ermahgerd' style, such as 'GERSBERMS' (Goosebumps) or 'BERKS' (books).

The top section of the image serves as the setup or exclamation. Text placed here is typically an excited phrase written in the meme's characteristic phonetic style, like 'ERMAHGERD' (Oh my god), establishing the tone of intense enthusiasm.

Ermahgerd-Berks.image_description: This meme, known as 'Ermahgerd' or 'Gersberms,' features a photograph of a young woman with an exaggeratedly excited expression while holding several 'Goosebumps' books. The humor comes from the phonetic spelling of words to mimic speech with a retainer, such as 'ermahgerd' for 'oh my god.' It is used to express overwhelming, often nerdy, excitement for something, frequently with a nostalgic 90s reference.

Squidward-Spare-Change.name: Squidward-Spare-Change

text_options.description: This text box at the bottom of the image typically identifies the person, group, or entity that the user is begging from. It sets up the target of the plea, representing who has the resources or power to grant the request.

The top text box is used to state what is being begged for. This is often something mundane, modern, or humorous, creating a comedic contrast with Squidward's desperate appearance. For example, it could be a plea for money, video game items, or social media engagement.

Squidward-Spare-Change.image_description: This meme, known as 'Spare Change' or 'Homeless Squidward,' features the character Squidward Tentacles from SpongeBob SquarePants looking destitute. He is sitting in a cardboard box, wearing tattered clothes and holding out a tin cup, appearing to beg. The meme is used to humorously express a desperate need or plea for something, often money, favors, or trivial items, by juxtaposing Squidward's pathetic state with the nature of the request.

Confession-Bear.name: Confession-Bear

text_options.description: The bottom text delivers the core of the confession or the punchline. It reveals the secret, unpopular opinion, or taboo act, completing the thought started in the top text.
The top text sets up the confession. It typically provides the context or the beginning of a statement that will be concluded with the actual confession in the bottom text.

Confession-Bear.image_description: This meme, known as "Confession Bear," features a Malayan sun bear leaning on a log with a pensive or guilty expression. The image is used as a macro for people to anonymously admit to secrets, controversial opinions, or taboo behaviors they wouldn't share publicly. The bear's somber face is meant to reflect the weight of the confession being made.

We-are-the-millers.name: We-are-the-millers

text_options.description: This is the punchline of the meme. The text here, placed over Kenny Rossmore (Will Poulter), is typically a question like "Wait, you guys are getting paid?" or a variation. It reveals this character's complete ignorance or exclusion from the situation the others are discussing, creating a comedic and relatable moment of realizing one is far worse off than their peers.

This text, over Casey Mathis (Emma Roberts), represents the third part of the setup. It typically expresses a complaint or a situation that is worse than the previous two panels, continuing the downward progression and setting the stage for the final punchline.

This text, over Rose O'Reilly (Jennifer Aniston), is the second part of the setup. It usually presents a situation or complaint that is a step down from the first panel, showing a less favorable outcome and escalating the comparison.

This is the first panel in the meme's narrative progression, placed over David Clark (Jason Sudeikis). The text here establishes the topic of comparison, often representing the best-case scenario or a complaint from a position of relative advantage that the other characters will then react to.

We-are-the-millers.image_description: This is a four-panel meme format known as "We're the Millers" or "You Guys Are Getting Paid?", featuring four characters from the 2013 film of the same name. The meme illustrates a conversation where three individuals compare their situations or achievements regarding a specific topic, with each one being progressively worse off. The final panel delivers the punchline, where the fourth character, with a look of genuine confusion, reveals they are not even participating in the activity, making their situation the most disadvantageous and humorous.

the-office-bankruptcy.name: the-office-bankruptcy

text_options.description: This bottom text box typically contains the direct quote from the scene, 'NO! GOD! PLEASE! NO! NO! NO! NOOOOOO!'. It functions as the punchline, verbalizing the intense negative reaction shown by Michael Scott. This text explicitly states the feeling of despair and rejection in response to the situation described in the top text.

This top text box is used to set up the context or premise that elicits Michael's extreme reaction. It usually describes an unwanted event, a terrible realization, or a disappointing statement. This text provides the reason for the frustration and sets the stage for the punchline.

the-office-bankruptcy.image_description: This meme features Michael Scott from the TV show 'The Office' shouting with a look of anguish and denial. The original scene shows his reaction to the return of his nemesis, Toby Flenderson. The image is widely used to express extreme frustration, disappointment, or vehement rejection of an undesirable situation or piece of news.

Are-you-winning-son-blank-template.name: Are-you-winning-son-blank-template

text_options.description: This bottom text area is optional and often used for labels to identify the characters, such as 'Dad' and 'Son', or to add a caption that provides extra context or a meta-joke.
This text box contains the father's dialogue, which is almost always the titular question, 'Are ya winning, son?'. This innocent and supportive question serves as the setup for the meme's punchline.

Are-you-winning-son-blank-template.image_description: This is the 'Are ya winning, son?' meme, a two-panel comic format featuring crudely drawn stick figures. The image shows the first panel where a father figure, depicted with a hat and pipe, walks into his son's room. The son is sitting at a computer with headphones on, seemingly engrossed in a game or other online activity. This setup is used to contrast the father's wholesome, out-of-touch question with the son's often strange, explicit, or niche online behavior, which is revealed in the second panel as the punchline.
Are-you-winning-son-blank-template.display_name: Are you winning son blank template

For-Christmas-I-Want-a-Dragon.name: For-Christmas-I-Want-a-Dragon

text_options.description: This small area on the girl's shirt in the final panel is often used to place a logo or symbol. This symbol typically represents the subject of the second, more "unrealistic" request that the user adds in the third panel, providing extra visual context for the punchline.

This blank panel is the main customizable part of the meme. Users insert text here representing the girl's second wish, which is intended to be far more unrealistic or absurd than her initial request for a dragon. The humor relies on this new request being so outlandish that Santa prefers the original 'impossible' wish.

For-Christmas-I-Want-a-Dragon.image_description: This is a four-panel comic meme known as "What Color Do You Want Your Dragon" or "Santa Be Realistic". It features a little girl asking Santa Claus for a dragon, to which he replies, "Be realistic." The third panel is left blank for users to insert a new, even more unrealistic request. In the final panel, Santa gives up and asks what color dragon she wants, implying the second request was far more impossible than the first, causing the girl to cry. The meme is used to humorously compare two things, framing the second as absurdly difficult or unattainable.
For-Christmas-I-Want-a-Dragon.display_name: For Christmas I Want a Dragon

I-hate-the-Antichrist.name: I-hate-the-Antichrist

text_options.description: This text box is placed in the first panel and represents the dialogue or statement of the UN soldiers. It typically contains a naive, bureaucratic, or sinister-sounding command or declaration, setting them up as an unwelcome authoritarian force.

This text box, positioned above the armed Trollface character, contains their defiant and often unhinged response. It serves as the punchline, frequently featuring phrases like 'I HATE THE ANTICHRIST' or other paranoid, anti-establishment statements, highlighting the character's extreme opposition.

I-hate-the-Antichrist.image_description: This meme, often associated with 'schizoposting' and the phrase 'I hate the antichrist,' depicts two shocked UN soldiers, represented by Wojak-like faces with UN helmets, discovering an armed, insane-looking Trollface character holding a shotgun. The format humorously contrasts a seemingly official or naive entity (the UN) with a chaotic, dangerous, and often conspiratorially-minded individual. It's typically used to express anti-authoritarian sentiments or to parody conspiracy theories in an absurd manner.

I-just-think-theyre-neat.name: I-just-think-theyre-neat

text_options.description: The text here labels the potato Marge is holding. It represents the object, hobby, or concept that the meme creator genuinely likes for simple, unexplainable reasons.
This text box, placed in the background near Marge's head, typically labels the person or group (representing Marge) who holds the simple, positive opinion about the object in box 0.

I-just-think-theyre-neat.image_description: This meme features Marge Simpson from the animated TV show 'The Simpsons' holding a potato with a pleasant smile, with the caption 'I just think they're neat.' The format is used to express a simple, unadulterated liking for something without needing a deeper justification, often for niche interests or hobbies. It conveys a wholesome and straightforward appreciation for an object or idea.

dj-khaled-suffering-from-success-meme.name: dj-khaled-suffering-from-success-meme

text_options.description: This area contains the original text from the album cover: "DJ KHALED SUFFERING FROM SUCCESS." This text is the title of the meme and establishes the core concept of having problems due to one's own achievements or abundance. It is usually left unedited.

This is the primary location for user-added text, which serves as the punchline. The text placed here describes a specific, often trivial, problem or complaint that is a direct consequence of being successful, wealthy, or skilled, creating the ironic humor of the meme.

dj-khaled-suffering-from-success-meme.image_description: The "Suffering from Success" meme features the album art for DJ Khaled's 2013 album of the same name. The black and white image shows DJ Khaled looking down with a pained expression, his head in his hand, while adorned with extravagant jewelry like large rings, bracelets, and chains. The meme is used ironically to describe trivial "first-world problems" or minor inconveniences that arise from having too much of a good thing, creating a humorous humblebrag.
dj-khaled-suffering-from-success-meme.display_name: dj khaled suffering from success meme

Soldier-not-protecting-child.name: Soldier-not-protecting-child

text_options.description: This label is placed on the sleeping person in the bed. It represents the individual, group, or concept that is being protected. This entity is often depicted as innocent, vulnerable, or oblivious to the dangers being shielded from them.

This label is placed on the rain of weapons (knives, grenades, bullets). It represents the various threats, criticisms, negative comments, or dangers that are being directed at the sleeping person. These are the negative forces that the protector is intercepting.

This label is placed on the soldier. It represents the protector, the person, group, or entity that is taking on the burden of defending the sleeping person from the incoming threats. This character embodies sacrifice and protection.

Soldier-not-protecting-child.image_description: This meme, known as "Soldier Protecting Sleeping Person," features a cartoon soldier in camouflage kneeling with arms outstretched to shield a sleeping person in a bed. A barrage of weapons, including knives, grenades, and bullets, rains down from the upper right, but the soldier intercepts them. The meme is used to represent a person, group, or entity (the soldier) defending something or someone they care about (the sleeping person) from various threats, criticisms, or negative influences (the weapons).

We-dont-do-that-here.name: We-dont-do-that-here

text_options.description: This text is the punchline of the meme, quoting T'Challa's line from the movie: "We don't do that here." It is almost always present and unchanged, delivering the firm rejection of the action described above.

This area is where the meme creator adds a caption describing an action, suggestion, or behavior that is being rejected. This text provides the context or setup for T'Challa's disapproving response below.

We-dont-do-that-here.image_description: This meme features a still of King T'Challa (Black Panther) from the Marvel film *Avengers: Infinity War*. In the scene, he firmly tells Bruce Banner, "We don't do that here," rejecting a suggestion. The meme is widely used to express disapproval or rejection of an action, belief, or behavior that goes against the norms or rules of a particular group or community.

Guy-tapping-head.name: Guy-tapping-head

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline, which is a terrible or nonsensical 'solution' to the problem stated above. The man's gesture of pointing to his head is spatially linked to this text, implying this is the 'smart' thought he's having.
This top text box typically describes a problem, a negative situation, or a condition that someone wants to avoid. It sets up the premise for the flawed logic that follows.

Guy-tapping-head.image_description: This meme, known as 'Roll Safe' or 'Think About It,' features a screenshot of actor Kayode Ewumi as Reece Simpson from the web series 'Hood Documentary.' The image shows him smiling confidently while tapping his temple, suggesting he has a brilliant idea. The meme is used to humorously present terrible, illogical, or counter-intuitive advice as if it were a clever life hack, creating a sarcastic tone.

Yu-Gi-Oh.name: Yu-Gi-Oh

text_options.description: This text box is placed on the cards Kaiba holds in the third panel, revealing his hand. This area typically contains the punchline or the reason for Kaiba's defeat, showing a weakness, a flaw, or a pathetic reality that undermines his initial confident statement from the first panel.

This text box is placed on the card Seto Kaiba is confidently playing in the first panel. Text here represents the initial, often arrogant or overconfident, statement, argument, or plan that is about to be countered and proven wrong.

Yu-Gi-Oh.image_description: This four-panel meme, known as "Kaiba's Defeat," originates from the anime series Yu-Gi-Oh!. It depicts a duel where Seto Kaiba confidently presents a card, only to be countered by his rival, Yami Yugi, leading to Kaiba's shocked and defeated reaction in the final panel. The meme is used to illustrate a situation where an argument or point is presented with confidence but is swiftly and decisively refuted, resulting in a comical failure.

spongebob-wanna-see-me-do-it-again.name: spongebob-wanna-see-me-do-it-again

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme, which is typically the phrase "Aight Imma Head Out" or a variation. It represents the speaker's (personified by SpongeBob) decision to leave the situation described in the top text.

The top text box is used to set up the scenario. It describes an awkward, uncomfortable, or strange situation that would prompt someone to want to leave, providing the context for SpongeBob's departure.

spongebob-wanna-see-me-do-it-again.image_description: This meme, known as "Aight Imma Head Out," features SpongeBob SquarePants from the animated series of the same name. In the image, SpongeBob is standing up, looking determined and ready to leave, often interpreted as a reaction to an awkward or undesirable situation. The meme is used to humorously express a desire to exit a conversation, event, or any uncomfortable scenario.
spongebob-wanna-see-me-do-it-again.display_name: spongebob wanna see me do it again

Why-would-X-do-this.name: Why-would-X-do-this

text_options.description: This text, spanning the bottom panel, represents the punchline. It's typically a question or statement from the perpetrator (Eric Andre) feigning ignorance or blaming an external party for the problem they just created, often phrased as 'Why would X do this?'
This label is placed on Eric Andre as he is shooting. The text here identifies the person, group, or entity that is actively causing a problem or performing a destructive action.
This label is placed on Hannibal Buress, the victim. The text here represents the person, concept, or thing that is negatively impacted or 'killed' by the actions of the entity labeled in box 1.

Why-would-X-do-this.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Who Killed Hannibal?' or 'Eric Andre Shooting Hannibal Buress,' originates from 'The Eric Andre Show.' In the top panel, host Eric Andre shoots his co-host Hannibal Buress. In the bottom panel, Andre turns to the camera with a shocked expression, as if questioning who is responsible. The meme is used to represent a person or entity causing a problem and then hypocritically blaming others or feigning ignorance about its cause.

Young-Thug-and-Lil-Durk-troubleshooting.name: Young-Thug-and-Lil-Durk-troubleshooting

text_options.description: This label is placed on Young Thug, who represents the person, entity, or complex concept being explained. This is the 'teacher' or the source of the confusing information, presented as confident and knowledgeable.

This label is placed on Lil Durk and the others, who represent the confused audience or 'students'. Their expressions of intense concentration and bewilderment signify their struggle to understand the difficult or absurd information being presented by entity 0.

Young-Thug-and-Lil-Durk-troubleshooting.image_description: This meme features rappers Young Thug and Lil Durk in a recording studio. Young Thug is standing and intently showing something on a computer screen to a seated and bewildered-looking Lil Durk. The format is used to humorously depict a situation where an expert or someone with complex knowledge is explaining something to a novice who is struggling to comprehend it.
Young-Thug-and-Lil-Durk-troubleshooting.display_name: Young Thug and Lil Durk troubleshooting

Im-gonna-say-it.name: Im-gonna-say-it

text_options.description: The punchline of the meme is placed here, often phrased as a question starting with "Wait, you guys are getting...?" This text reveals the speaker's surprising and less fortunate situation compared to others, forming the core of the joke.
A top caption that sets the context for the meme. It usually describes a general situation or topic that the characters are discussing, leading up to the final punchline.

Im-gonna-say-it.image_description: This meme features a young man in a yellow shirt and glasses pointing forward with a look of surprised realization. Known as "Wait, You Guys Are Getting Paid?", it originates from a classroom video. The meme is used to express shock and dismay upon discovering that others are receiving a benefit, reward, or positive experience that the speaker is not, highlighting a disparity or a personal disadvantage in a humorous way.

angry-chihuahua-happy-chihuahua.name: angry-chihuahua-happy-chihuahua

text_options.description: This text box is placed above the smiling chihuahua. It describes the positive or favorable situation that elicits a calm and happy reaction, creating a humorous contrast with the other panel.

This text box is positioned over the angry, snarling chihuahua. The text here typically describes a negative, frustrating, or undesirable scenario that causes the aggressive reaction shown in the image below it.

angry-chihuahua-happy-chihuahua.image_description: This two-panel meme, known as 'Angry and Smiling Chihuahua', contrasts two opposing reactions from the same dog. On the left, a chihuahua snarls aggressively, while on the right, it appears calm and content with a slight smile. The meme is used to humorously compare a person's behavior or feelings in two different situations, highlighting a dramatic shift in attitude.

The-Simpsons-Ralph-Wiggum-Picking-His-No.name: The-Simpsons-Ralph-Wiggum-Picking-His-Nose

text_options.description: The bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme. This is where the foolish, naive, or nonsensical statement is placed, representing the simple-minded perspective of the person personified by Ralph.

The top text box provides the setup or context for the joke. It usually describes a situation, poses a question, or presents a complex topic that the punchline below will naively or foolishly address.

The-Simpsons-Ralph-Wiggum-Picking-His-No.image_description: This meme features Ralph Wiggum, a character from the animated series The Simpsons, known for his simple-minded and naive nature. In the image, he is depicted picking his nose with a clueless expression, a pose that encapsulates his personality. This format is typically used to represent a person or group making a foolish, simplistic, or blissfully unaware statement in response to a more complex situation or question.
The-Simpsons-Ralph-Wiggum-Picking-His-No.display_name: The Simpsons Ralph Wiggum Picking His Nose

Eddie-Murphy-thinking.name: Eddie-Murphy-thinking

text_options.description: This bottom text box contains the punchline of the meme: the flawed, illogical, or comically poor advice. It's positioned to align with the character's expression of self-satisfaction, delivering the "brilliant" solution to the problem stated above.
The top text box sets up the premise or describes a problem. This text establishes the context for the terrible advice that follows, creating the setup for the joke.

Eddie-Murphy-thinking.image_description: This meme, known as "Roll Safe" or "Think About It," features actor Kayode Ewumi as the character Reece Simpson from the web series "Hood Documentary." The image captures him smiling knowingly while tapping his temple, a gesture suggesting a brilliant thought. The meme is used to humorously present flawed logic or terrible advice as if it were a stroke of genius, typically by proposing a nonsensical solution to a problem.

Sponge-Finna-Commit-Muder.name: Sponge-Finna-Commit-Muder

text_options.description: Paired with the ultimate, glowing, and enraged muscular SpongeBob, this bottom-most text box contains the final and most powerful, enlightened, or absurdly extreme option. It serves as the punchline and represents the pinnacle of the escalation.
This text box corresponds to the third panel, showing a very muscular SpongeBob. The text here represents a significantly stronger, more effective, or superior option compared to the ones above it.

Next to a determined-looking SpongeBob wearing a sweatband, this text box describes the second level in the hierarchy. It typically represents an option that is an improvement or a more serious version of the initial state.

This top-most text box is aligned with the normal, happy SpongeBob. It is used to label the most basic, weakest, or most common state or idea in the comparison, setting the baseline for the escalation.

Sponge-Finna-Commit-Muder.image_description: This is a four-panel meme format featuring the character SpongeBob SquarePants in escalating stages of strength and intensity. Starting from his normal, cheerful self, he becomes progressively more muscular and powerful, culminating in a glowing, enraged, super-buff form. The meme is used to rank concepts, actions, or entities in an ascending order of power, absurdity, or desirability, with each panel representing a higher level of enlightenment or effectiveness.

Steve-Harvey-Laughing-Serious.name: Steve-Harvey-Laughing-Serious

text_options.description: This text box is placed over the shocked and distressed Steve Harvey. The text here represents the negative outcome, the harsh reality, or the unexpected consequence that follows the initial statement. It serves as the punchline, contrasting sharply with the text on the laughing image.

This text box is over the laughing Steve Harvey. The text here typically describes an initial action, a confident statement, or a positive expectation. This sets up the joke, representing the "before" state or the cause that leads to the shocking result depicted on the right.

Steve-Harvey-Laughing-Serious.image_description: This meme features two contrasting images of comedian and TV host Steve Harvey, taken from the show "Family Feud." On the left, he is laughing heartily, while on the right, he appears shocked and distressed. The format is used to contrast an initial, often naive or positive statement (the laughing side) with a subsequent, harsh, or unexpected reality (the shocked side). It's a popular template for showcasing "expectation vs. reality" scenarios or the sudden, negative consequences of an action.

skinner-telescope.name: skinner-telescope

text_options.description: This area, associated with Bart, contains the simple, straightforward, or mundane reality of a situation. The text here acts as the punchline, contrasting sharply with the complex idea presented in the top panel and highlighting its absurdity.

This text box, placed in the sky where Skinner is looking, represents a complex, over-analyzed, or conspiratorial theory. It sets up the joke by presenting an elaborate or far-fetched idea that Skinner is supposedly observing.

skinner-telescope.image_description: This meme features Principal Skinner and Bart Simpson from the animated show The Simpsons. Skinner is intensely looking through a telescope at the night sky, while Bart lies on the grass looking bored and writing on a notepad. The format contrasts an overly complex, niche, or far-fetched interpretation of something (represented by Skinner) with a simple, obvious, or straightforward reality (represented by Bart). It's used to poke fun at overthinking or conspiracy theories versus simple explanations.

Afraid-To-Ask-Andy-Closeup.name: Afraid-To-Ask-Andy-Closeup

text_options.description: The bottom text of the meme, which almost always reads, "and at this point, I'm too afraid to ask." This punchline delivers the core concept of the meme, revealing the speaker's reluctance to admit their ignorance.

The top text sets up the context by describing a situation or topic that the user doesn't understand. It often starts with a phrase like "I don't know what [X] is," establishing the premise for the punchline that follows below.

Afraid-To-Ask-Andy-Closeup.image_description: This meme features a still of the character Andy Dwyer, played by Chris Pratt, from the TV show "Parks and Recreation." In the scene, Andy has a confused and slightly worried expression, admitting he doesn't know what's going on. The meme, known as "Afraid to Ask Andy" or "Too Afraid to Ask," is used to express a situation where someone is ignorant about a popular topic or trend but feels too much time has passed to ask for an explanation without looking foolish.

Austin-Powers-Honestly.name: Austin-Powers-Honestly

text_options.description: This bottom text area contains Austin Powers' reaction to the setup in the top text. It's the punchline, usually a blunt refusal like 'How about no?' or a sarcastic agreement to a dangerous idea, such as 'I also like to live dangerously'.
This top text area sets up the scenario. It typically contains a question, a suggestion, or a statement that is absurd, undesirable, or risky, prompting a reaction from Austin Powers.
